<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech terminates Terps
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a seemingly uncanny flair for the dramatic, Joe
Hamilton is making a serious run for the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   And the No. 9-ranked Yellow Jackets needed every bit of
Hamilton's school-record 474 yards and four touchdowns to avoid
disaster and dust off Maryland 49-31 Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tech (3-1, 1-1 ACC) stayed within a Florida State loss of again
sharing the ACC lead, and it should remain in the top 10. But as
the Terrapins capitalized on the Jackets' season-long trend of
shoddy tackling, it appeared that few wins will come easy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Georgia Tech's defense had its moments.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a Marvious Hester interception led to the touchdown
that sealed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The defense started the game by pitching its first
opening-possession three downs-and-out of the season, and Sean
Gregory turned the excellent field position into a 48-yard scoring
dash on Tech's first play from scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   After Maryland converted a long kickoff return and two Tech
turnovers into a 17-14 lead late in the first half, the defense
twice gave the ball back to Hamilton &AMP; Co., who gave the Bobby Dodd
Stadium crowd plenty to shout about.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Uremovich and Nick Rogers threw LaMont Jordan for a 5-yard
loss on third down, and Hamilton put Tech in action at its 30 with
1 minute, 48 seconds left in the half. Twenty-seven seconds later,
Hamilton hit Dez White for a 29-yard score, his second of the half,
and the Jackets regained the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Another three-and-out and an 8-yard Maryland punt later, Tech
was at the Terps' 30. Hamilton then completed his school-record
257-yard passing half with a 30-yard scoring strike to Kerry
Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who broke the 20-year-old record set by Mike Kelley
against Navy, completed 17 of 21 passes before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   With the game televised by ESPN, Hamilton boosted his Heisman
campaign with his second outstanding performance on national
television. In Tech's loss to Florida State on Sept. 11, shown on
ABC, he had five touchdowns, four passing and one rushing, and he
was 22 of 25 for 387 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
