<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ALL THE METS MAY WATCH FROM STANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six weeks ago, there was speculation that Masato
Yoshii would be dropped from the New York Mets' postseason roster.
This was based on the assumption _ credible at the time _ that the
Mets would actually make it to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do if the Mets could not find a spot for
him, Yoshi quipped _ and when was the last time a ballplayer
quipped anything, in English or Japanese or any language? _ ``If
I'm not on the roster, I'll buy a ticket in the stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``I'll have a beer and a hot dog, and I'll shout,
`Put in Yoshii.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nice line. Since then, the former Kintetsu Buffalo and Yakult
Swallow has been the Mets' most effective pitcher. Now it looks as
if Yoshii and all his teammates are going to be spectators when the
postseason begins early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Yoshii tried to keep his team in the race for
the wild card, pitching effectively into the seventh, but the
Braves finally put away the Mets, 4-3, in the 11th inning, putting
the Mets two games behind Cincinnati and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The sky over Shea Stadium was suddenly crisp and clear, and the
public-address system played ``Autumn in New York,'' but there was
nothing promising in this corner of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The once-promising season has turned on so many things that
there is no point harping on any one. Thursday night, there was the
indelible impression of Shawon Dunston, a career shortstop now
professionally willing to help in the outfield, turning the wrong
way on a long fly ball, turning it into a triple in the 11th
inning. The winning run scored, inevitably, a few pitches later.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, there was hope that the pitcher from the other side
of the world might keep the Mets close. Put in Yoshii, indeed.
Since returning to the rotation on Aug. 13, Yoshii had won five and
lost one in eight starts, and his earned run average was 1.63. On a
team with no ace, Yoshii had approximated one.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii's presence in such a vital game was a tribute to Bobby
Valentine, the manager who actually took Yoshii apartment-hunting
when the pitcher arrived in New York in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine added to his own angst last Saturday by volunteering
that if the Mets do not get into the playoffs he should be fired.
That notion has been knocked down by Fred Wilpon, one of the
owners, but Valentine has raised the issue, and it hangs there,
over his head.
</P>
<P>
   The manager does have his strengths, including an inquisitive
mind, that was expanded in his one year with Chiba Lotte of the
Japanese Pacific League. In the last two years, Valentine has shown
faith in Yoshii, 34, who did not come with great hyperbole, like
the Yankee owner calling Hideki Irabu the Nolan Ryan of Japan. But
Yoshii's jock's smile and chesty body language brought him
acceptance quickly last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression of him came from people I trust over there,''
Valentine said. ``I remember them talking about how competitive he
is. He showed some emotion. He was a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   From his year in Japan, Valentine understood that Yoshii could
be expected to accept authority, not necessarily the first thing
that comes to mind about American athletes. When the body count of
starters reached seven in August, Valentine knew he could afford to
send Yoshii to the bullpen without losing the pitcher's heart and
soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of fair or unfair,'' Yoshii said. ``This
might be a Japanese way of thinking, but the manager is chief in
command. Whatever he decides is the law. You have to follow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Having helped win the Japanese World Series in 1997, Yoshii had
done it all in his own country. Now he had hopes of pitching the
Mets deep into the North American version of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Yoshii gave up single runs in the fourth and
fifth innings and the bullpen held until the eighth, when the
Braves went up, 3-2. Then Edgardo Alfonzo made the biggest clutch
hit the Mets have had since their totally fruitless trip to Atlanta
and Philadelphia, a two-out homer that tied the game. Then the
gallant Dunston turned the wrong way, and so did the season.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii can drink beer and eat hot dogs and sit in the stands
during the postseason, but he'll have to go to another ballpark to
do it. The Mets are not going to survive their ill-timed walkabout.
</P>
</TEXT>
