<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT FOR GIULIANI TO PAY TRIBUTE TO THE REAGAN LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on
Thursday night wrapped himself in the legacy of Ronald Reagan in a
speech that glorified the 40th president and seemed an unusual
approach for an unannounced Senate candidate who would need
Democratic votes to win in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   In delivering the annual Reagan Lecture at the Ronald Reagan
Presidential Library here, Giuliani called Reagan one of the two
most important presidents of the 20th century _ the other being
Franklin D. Roosevelt _ and ``a force for good in the world.''
Giuliani praised Reagan's supply-side economics, which Democrats to
this day say caused the huge deficits of the 1980s and favored the
rich. ``Who says that supply-side economics doesn't work?'' said
Giuliani. ``Of course it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani said he was attaching great importance to the
speech, which in its lengthy discourse on foreign policy seemed
more presidential than senatorial in its ambitions. Aides also said
that Giuliani viewed it not so much as a campaign speech as a
tribute to the former president in his twilight years. Giuliani
reveres Reagan, and served in his two administrations as associate
attorney general and U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The annual lecture was created by the Ronald Reagan Presidential
Foundation to honor ``conservative public figures or
policy-makers'' who ``reaffirm and apply the principles that guided
the president and shaped his enduring legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   An official at City Hall acknowledged that there were some
political considerations to the speech, and said that it could help
with those voters upstate and in the suburbs who may distrust the
mayor of New York City but have fond feelings for the president who
gave birth to the term the Reagan Democrat. Giuliani himself
pointed out at a fund-raiser at the Beverly Hills Hotel on
Wednesday that Reagan carried New York state in both the 1980 and
1984 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The speech's Republican orthodoxy also outlined the themes of
the battle that Giuliani is almost certain to fight against Hillary
Rodham Clinton, his likely opponent in next year's Senate race.
Giuliani told the audience of 450 Reagan faithful, who interrupted
his speech several times with applause, about how he had reduced
the welfare rolls in New York City and believed in ``freedom of
choice'' in education. In praising Reagan for returning powers to
state and local governments, Giuliani in part credited the former
president for his own election as mayor, an event that Giuliani
sees as pivotal to the city's resurgence. Without Reagan, Giuliani
said, there might have been ``no innovative governors _ and maybe
there'd be no Republican mayor of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, 88, has Alzheimer's disease and did not attend the
lecture. Nancy Reagan, the former first lady and a trustee of the
Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation, , served as the host. The
day before, she welcomed Sen. tor John McCain, R-Ariz., on a stop
of his presidential campaign. In his speech Giuliani said Mrs.
Reagan was the one person aside from the former president who is
``most responsible for the Reagan legacy that we celebrate
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spent a large part of his speech praising Reagan for
ending the Cold War and building up America's defenses. He also
criticized President Clinton for a foreign policy of ``confusion''
and a weakened military. ``The next president,'' Giuliani said,
``will have to rebuild American foreign policy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In remarks to reporters before the lecture, Giuliani said he had
not yet read Edmund Morris' new authorized biography of Reagan,
``Dutch,'' which paints the president in his second term as an
out-of-touch loner who was often in his pajamas in the White House
family quarters watching television by 6 p.m. ``I only read the
prologue,'' Giuliani said. ``Let me read the book first before I
comment on it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech at the Mission-style library with its distant
view of the Pacific Ocean, Giuliani went with Mrs. Reagan and such
Reagan friends as Betsy Bloomingdale and Charles and Mary Jane Wick
to dinner at the nearby Sherwood Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's speech came at the end of a three-day fund-raising
and political trip to Washington, D.C., Las Vegas and California.
Thursday morning Giuliani played golf on the lush course of palm
trees and oleander at the Stockdale Country Club in Bakersfield,
then spoke at a lunchtime fund-raiser in the clubhouse dining room.
As has happened throughout this trip, one of the guests asked him
about the status of the city's battle with the Brooklyn Museum of
Art over an exhibition that Giuliani has termed ``disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's responses to the question have grown increasingly
descriptive. In Washington he extensively described a sliced pig in
formaldehyde, calling it ``a biology experiment at best.'' In
Stockdale on Thursday, he said the entire exhibit ``belongs in a
psychiatric ward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
