<SLUG> BC-SACTOUR-TOURISM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA CLARITA, CALIF., SEEKS TO PROMOTE TOURISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- William S. Hart Museum and Gallagher's Old Town
Restaurant may not rate a mention in most Southern California
tourist guides, but the Santa Clarita Valley landmarks will soon be
famous if the city of Santa Clarita gets its way.
</P>
<P>
   The museum and restaurant are part of a tourism push beginning
Friday that will take travel agents from Southern California and
Arizona on a tour of the valley's sights. City boosters hope the
inaugural event -- which also includes better-known sites such as
Six Flags California -- will help valley businesses grab a bigger
piece of the region's tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
   They are in for a challenge. This former bedroom community has
never had a large tourist base beyond Six Flags visitors, and the
valley's offerings include few Hollywood-caliber assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been sort of a void for us,'' said Laurie
Lincoln, president of Main Street Tours Inc. of suburban Torrance.
``I think of it more as suburban and Magic Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel coordinator Jason Teng of Los Angeles-based Tour America
Inc. said most of his clientele _ tourists from Southeast Asia and
Hong Kong _ think of Santa Clarita as a one-item destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic Mountain is the only thing I know that's located in the
Santa Clarita Valley,'' said Teng, one of 10 travel professionals
who will take the city's three-day tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city itself is wonderful, and it's enough to draw people
from the Southern California area,'' he said. ``But for tourists
from Asian countries, we still have to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Karp, the newly appointed head of the city's tourism
effort, acknowledged that Santa Clarita lacks the volume of
headliner attractions that its larger southern neighbors enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent addition of an IMAX theater and the expansion
of Six Flags, Karp said much of Santa Clarita's allure lies in its
less-prominent, and less-crowded, assets.
</P>
<P>
   The city's tour highlights many of those attractions, including
the Castaic Lake recreation area and the hilltop museum dedicated
to frontier movie hero William S. Hart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the tourists don't want to be with other tourists,''
Karp said. ``They want to be isolated and away from all the traffic
that L.A. has.''
</P>
<P>
   And the same factors that draw residents to the valley _ low
crime and clean streets _ may also work to the valley's advantage,
Karp said.
</P>
<P>
   The city is also expanding the concept of the Santa Clarita
Valley by including in its listing of attractions several sites in
neighboring Ventura County's Fillmore and Santa Paula, cities in
their own right that aren't even in the same county as Santa
Clarita.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita has not yet compiled statistics on how many people
visit, what they spend or where they go. And Karp said they are
waiting on the results of this weekend's tour to help them shape a
strategy about which tourists to target and how to target them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the infrastructure is already in place, however,
including a toll-free number _ (800) 718-TOUR _ that rings directly
into the Santa Clarita Valley Chamber of Commerce. The chamber ran
the area's tourism bureau until August, when the city took the
campaign under its umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   After this weekend's tour, Karp said the bureau's top priority
will be to obtain state and federal funding that'll help make Santa
Clarita a household name. The bureau is funded with private
contributions and a matching grant from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Karp said the city has not yet decided if it will partner with
tourism efforts in the San Fernando Valley or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But some kind of cooperation is likely, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tourism industry altogether is moving away from
competition,'' she said. ``It's more beneficial for us to partner
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's effort to promote attractions outside its immediate
area drew praise from Kathy Janega-Dykes, executive director of the
Ventura Visitors and Convention Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win situation for us all,'' she said. ``It
absolutely makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
