<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DUBIOUS HEALTH-CARE PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: Subs to add byline-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is finally getting the hang of how he can use
budget-surplus politics to boost his presidential fortunes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bradley proposes a $65-billion-a-year plan to make health care
available to nearly all uninsured Americans. His plan, he says,
wouldn't require new taxes, but could be financed with future
budget surpluses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While those extra revenues are estimated at about $1 trillion
over the next decade, fiscal forecasts are notoriously unreliable.
As recently as the early '90s, for instance, experts were
predicting budget deficits of $400 billion or more by the end of
this decade. Instead, this year's surplus is now being estimated at
$115 billion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recession could put Uncle Sam back into the red, but even if
the surplus forecasts hold up, there are cautionary considerations
to ponder. One is that most, if not all, of the projected surpluses
will be excess revenues from the payroll taxes paid to fund Social
Security. As that money is spent, it will represent nothing more
than borrowing from Peter's Social Security pot to pay for
uninsured Paul's medical-care coverage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, it should be remembered that initial cost estimates
of proposed government programs always turn out to be much lower
than the eventual financial reality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bold new programs offered by candidates, however, aren't much
about details, which are bothersome things that can't be explained
in 30-second sound bites on the evening news. Going beyond the
dubious nature of Bradley's financing plan are the daunting details
of how such a program would improve the lives of those it's
supposed to help. Bradley said, for instance, that his plan would
require health insurance coverage for all uninsured children, but
offered no mechanism to enforce the enrollment of these children in
coverage plans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to trust in the basic goodness of the American
people,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's a touching sentiment, but it's based on a heroic
assumption. Bradley may not appreciate how real life works, but
there are many Americans who may be basically good people but are
nevertheless highly irresponsible. They don't order their lives to
be ready for problems when they happen, but instead choose to wait
for bad things to happen before reacting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another probable consequence of Bradley's plan would be to
increase demand for medical care. Just as there are people who
don't take proper care of themselves and their children, there are
also people who view insurance coverage as justification for
seeking medical care for every real and imagined hurt and
discomfort, no matter how minor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bradley is thinking in terms of fee-for-service or
managed care, the outcome of ratcheting up use of the health-care
system by 45 million users will be the same: More demands on a
system already in a rationing mode. Many Americans may not be aware
of it, but when government trims its Medicare reimbursements to
providers, and companies seek ways to economize on employee
health-care benefits, as has been the case, these are forms of
rationing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Budget-surplus politics, however, aren't about truth or reality,
but about gulling voters into thinking they can have more goodies
from government without having to pay for them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
