<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-PARTY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.   PLANS PARTY FOR ALL AGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Wanted for a millennium New Year's Eve bash:
2,000 line dancers at Van Nuys Airport, 2,000 gospel singers in the
Crenshaw district, 2,000 Mexican folk dancers for Olvera Street,
2,000 marching band members for downtown and 2,000 drummers for San
Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of a plan announced to bring in the 21st Century
with a $4.2 million privately funded celebration around the city
that will end with the New Year's countdown and lighting of the
Hollywood sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has the Statue of Liberty, Paris has the Eiffel
Tower, and we have our own world symbol with the Hollywood sign,''
Mayor Richard Riordan said at the Griffith Park Observatory
overlooking the sign.
</P>
<P>
   With skywriters spelling out ``LA 2000. CU-12/31'' and skydivers
floating down with a giant flag, Riordan and co-chairpersons Andy
Garcia and Paula Abdul outlined a daylong schedule of festivities
Thursday that officials hope will attract up to 100,000 people at
five locations and involve the entire city in some event.
</P>
<P>
   All of the events will be linked by giant screens showing what
is going on in different parts of the city. And, that night, the
screens will also feature excerpts of the concert being staged by
the Eagles at downtown Los Angeles' new Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day on Dec. 31, there will be an air parade of
skywriting, sky divers, hot air balloons and airplane displays,
said Cultural Affairs Director Al Nodal.
</P>
<P>
   The five main events will be held at Van Nuys Airport, Olvera
Street, Baldwin Hills-Crenshaw Plaza, Grand Avenue and the San
Pedro harbor area.
</P>
<P>
   At Van Nuys Airport, the event will begin at noon and will be
called ``The Family Global Millennium,'' featuring the different
cultures in the community. The city will recruit 2,000 line dancers
to entertain the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guinness, get your world book out,'' said Abdul, who is
helping coordinate some of the choreography.
</P>
<P>
   Similar events will be held at different locations, featuring
different entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will be required for the events and will be distributed
free by selected grocery and stores.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said all religious institutions in the city have been
asked to participate with bell ringings at noon, 4 p.m., 9 p.m. and
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Also that night, a private event called Made in Hollywood will
be held at Paramount Studios, with a goal of raising $1 million for
the Los Angeles Public Library literacy program.
</P>
<P>
   The night will be capped with the lighting of the Hollywood
sign.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said the idea for using the sign came from actress Geena
Davis in a conversation he had with her several months ago. ``She
said, Why not use the sign that most symbolizes Los Angeles?''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for limiting public access to the televised event,
which will feature a countdown of the nine letters and then Riordan
flipping a switch to begin a laser light show.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is happy with the plans. Henry Pinczower of the
Hollywoodland Homeowners Association said his group is looking at
different options to try to stop that event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still talking about a few things but won't comment
until we have a final plan,'' Pinczower said. ``We are concerned
that this will be a pretty wild night with the potential for a lot
of inebriated people trying to come up here.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
