<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3000 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-JAPAN-NUKE-2NDLD-WRIT     10-01 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NUKE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE FUEL PLANT SPEWS RADIATION AFTER ACCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Inserts 2 new grafs on risks after 6th graf; inserts new grafs
with Bill Richardson's comments after original 12th graf)  (With sidebars, JAPAN-NUKE-EXPLAIN and JAPAN-NUKE-HEALTH)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In the worst accident in Japan's troubled history with
nuclear power, an out-of-control chain reaction at a fuel
fabrication plant near Tokyo spewed high levels of radiation into
the air beginning Thursday morning. Thirty-five people were
exposed, three of whom were seriously injured, and 300,000 local
residents were ordered to stay indoors. The reaction was brought
under control early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the reaction was set off when workers
accidentally poured 35 pounds of uranium into a purification tank
containing nitric acid, instead of the 5.2 pounds normally used.
</P>
<P>
   This mistake reportedly caused a flash of blue light inside the
plant, owned by Sumitomo Metal Mining Co. Scientists said the flash
may have been the result of a fast chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo Electric Power Co. rushed 880 pounds of sodium borate to
the plant, but the authorities said they had no way of getting
close enough to the processing tank to dump the radiation-absorbing
powder onto it.
</P>
<P>
   When initial efforts to stop the reaction failed, the government
ordered residents of areas near the plant, in the town of
Tokaimura, to stay indoors. A primary school, a kindergarten, a
number of shops and several homes were all located within the
affected area.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day Thursday, the government made little fuss
about the accident, closing off a three-mile perimeter around the
area and warning residents to keep their windows shut. By late
Thursday evening, the East Japan Railway, which serves the area,
suspended train traffic to the immediate region of the accident.
Major highways into the town were also closed, and electronic signs
were posted on small roads warning motorists to avoid the area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions remained in effect Friday and residents of the
immediate area were further cautioned to avoid contact with well
water or rain water. A light rain was falling Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said nothing so far about the possibility of
airborne or waterborne radiation contaminating other areas, nor
have they addressed the long-term impact of the radiation that
escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who was scheduled to name a new
cabinet Friday but was forced by the incident to postpone the
change in government, apologized tacitly for the slow official
reaction. ``We must obtain decisions from scientists, technicians
and experts'' to assess such accidents, the prime minister told
reporters at his residence, according to the Kyodo news agency,
adding ``if they were slow in making decisions, we must make sure
that that never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Japan has compounded other nuclear accidents with
similarly slow, and often misleading, information given to the
public. Commentators here are already predicting a strong backlash
in public opinion against the industry and perhaps too against a
deeply embarrassed government.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The confused emergency response has been matched by a confused
political one, with rival agencies alternately seeking to dismiss
concerns about Japan's vast nuclear energy program, or calling for
a sweeping reevaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, the chief of the government's Natural Resources
and Energy Agency, Hirobumi Kawano, still ruled out the idea that a
``criticality,'' or uncontrolled reaction, could occur at a nuclear
power plant in Japan, and told reporters that he did not intend to
instruct power companies to re-examine their safety measures, Kyodo
reported.
</P>
<P>
   A top official of the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry, however, said the accident was serious enough to lead
Japan to reconsider its nuclear power policy. Japan operates 51
nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Officials requested the assistance of U.S. military forces in
Japan to handle the accident. According to the Japan Self-Defense
Agency, the government was informed that U.S. forces here are not
equipped to deal with nuclear accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In Sarov, Russia, where he is on a study mission, U.S. Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson said that Russia and the United States
were prepared to send nuclear specialists to help Japan if Tokyo
asks for assistance. ``So far, the Japanese have only asked us for
information,'' said Richardson in an interview. ``But I've spoken
to our Russian counterparts, and my department and Russia's
Ministry of Atomic Energy both stand ready to send a joint team
almost immediately to help Japan with this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese television network NHK said early Friday morning
that after repeated failed attempts to drain the tank by remote
control, emergency workers deliberately broke pipes leading to the
purification chamber, allowing it to cool. Workers were attempting
to insert hoses into the contaminated area to drench it with
special chemicals to absorb the radiation.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication that the accident was being brought under
control Friday, Japanese television said that at 6:30 a.m., the
Science and Technology Agency reported that no radiation could be
detected at 14 monitoring sites around the plant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the Japanese Atomic Energy Research Institute,
measurements of radiation levels at the plant were reported to have
been from 10,000 to 20,000 times the normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an intense situation in which there is concern over the
continued effects of radiation,'' Obuchi told an emergency task
force named late Thursday to oversee handling of the accident. ``We
must make certain to prioritize the safety of the residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's chief cabinet secretary, Hiromu Nonaka, said Thursday
night that units of Japan's Self-Defense Forces chemical warfare
unit were being dispatched to the site of the fuel fabrication
plant at Tokaimura, 87 miles northwest of Tokyo, but said that
Japan was ``not capable of dealing with this kind of nuclear
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonaka called the runaway reaction, known as a ``criticality
event'' in the jargon of the nuclear power industry, ``something
that Japan has never experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials were meeting on the matter Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports said that only three workers had been injured at
the site, and had been taken by helicopter to a hospital that
specialized in nuclear-related illnesses in Chiba prefecture to the
east of Tokyo. Later, two of the workers were reported to be in
serious condition, and a doctor involved in their treatment said
that all three of those initially reported injured had been exposed
to ``a quite substantial amount of radiation.'' One is in critical
condition and has not recovered consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   As it became apparent late Thursday that the accident had still
not been brought under control, more and more reports of
radiation-related injuries trickled in. By dawn, authorities said,
at least 35 people had been contaminated, including workers at a
neighboring site, and the paramedics who helped evacuate the three
workers who were initially injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major accident resulting in a radioactive leak has
happened,'' said Koji Kitani, president of JCO Co. ``We apologize
from the bottoms of our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   The town of about 33,000 resident where the accident occurred,
Tokaimura, is home to more than a dozen nuclear-type plants, and
was the site of Japan's worst previous nuclear accident, in 1997.
In that incident, 37 workers were exposed to radiation after a fire
in one of the plants was improperly extinguished and caused a small
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking domestic petroleum resources, Japan heavily pushed the
development of nuclear energy in the 1970s, following the oil
shocks of that decade. The result is that the country is now
dependent upon nuclear power for about one-third of its electricity
needs, among the highest of any country. The fuel made at the plant
where the accident occurred is used in nuclear reactors nearby.
</P>
<P>
   This familiarity with nuclear power has not allowed Japan to
avoid accidents, however, and in recent years, nuclear safety has
increasingly become a major political issue for the public.
</P>
<P>
   In July, radiation estimated to be 11,500 times higher than
normal levels leaked out of faulty pipes in a nuclear reactor in
the town of Tsuruga, about 200 miles west of Tokyo. During that
accident, a reactor owned by Japan Atomic Power Co. was forced to
shut down after losing 51 tons of its radioactive water coolant.
The Tsuruga plant remains closed for repairs. During that accident,
a reactor owned by Japan Atomic Power Co. was forced to shut down
after losing 51 tons of its radioactive water coolant. The Tsuruga
plant remains closed for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's issue of Mainichi Shimbun quoted outraged members of
the government's Nuclear Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Kenji Sumida said, ``I know that this is difficult to believe,
but I think that we have no choice but to recognize this accident
as having been critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Another member, Kazuo Sato, speaking of the reports of employee
error, said, ``If they had done their job as they were supposed to,
there is no way something like this could have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Chihiro Kamisawa, an anti-nuclear activist, told the Associated
Press, ``So much has been made of Japan's sophisticated technology
that supposedly makes nuclear energy safe. The accident proves
that's absolutely not true.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-ARTDEALER-REVIEW-N     10-01 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTDEALER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVING THE BULLETS AND TRYING TO JUDGE A SHOW
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-ARTDEALER-ARRESTED, which moved in ``a'' category) 
(rk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The exhibition of handmade shotguns as sculpture that
resulted in the arrest on Wednesday night of gallery owner Mary
Boone was hardly new for artist Tom Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs, an exemplar of '90s-style artistic machismo, has
displayed his weapons before, and this show, his third in New York,
is actually lighter in the armaments department than his previous
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the police arrested Ms. Boone at her Fifth Avenue
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The show included a vase of real bullets _ for visitors to take
home as souvenirs _ which the police removed on Wednesday and which
led to a charge of unlawful distribution of ammunition against Ms.
Boone. The handmade guns brought a charge of possession of unlawful
weapons, which was later dropped. A charge of resisting arrest was
dropped. And finally she was charged with possession of stolen
property because parts of the guns and their display case were made
of Con Edison barriers that Sachs had collected from city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs, who works with all sorts of found materials, has
exhibited handmade guns since 1996. They are usually crude and
sinister and sometimes work. Still, the notion of anyone actually
pulling their triggers seems as unlikely as the thought of someone
firing a blunderbuss in a history museum.
</P>
<P>
   The show at Boone is in some respects tamer than Sachs' previous
New York shows, which included not only guns in elaborate cases,
but, for example, a weapon-testing chamber built from found
materials. Left alone it might have dulled the bad-boy image that
Sachs seemed to be cultivating.
</P>
<P>
   His first public profile was acquired in 1995 when, after
protests from religious groups, Barney's removed from its window
displays a Sachs' sculpture of a Nativity scene enacted by his
handmade versions of ``Hello Kitty,'' a wildly popular children's
character.
</P>
<P>
   After that, his work alternated between the overly cute and the
potentially violent or misogynist, the connecting link being his
amazing technical skill. The artist, who trained as an architect
and once worked for Frank O. Gehry, seems able to build anything,
and has shown a frequent interest in making things that work.
</P>
<P>
   He has made toilet plungers from orange Hermes boxes; large rats
out of the chic yellow packaging from Balthazar restaurant; chairs
and couches from New York telephone books, and modernist paintings
reminiscent of works by Mondrian and Robert Ryman from gaffer's
tape. Tiffany boxes are also a favorite material.
</P>
<P>
   His 1998 show at the Thomas Healy Gallery in Chelsea, which has
since closed, included a large cabinet containing handmade guns and
blackjacks as well as an encyclopedic array of consumer objects
incorporating the ``Hello Kitty'' image. The centerpiece was a
full-scale model of Fat Boy, the bomb that was dropped on Nagasaki,
Japan, in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually overt display of misogyny, the interior of this
sculpture was outfitted with a bed and stereo set and on Saturdays
was inhabited by a young Asian woman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the vase of bullets and the case of guns, weaponry has
taken the back seat at the Boone Gallery. The show seems a little
all over the place and suggests an artist who is either in
transition or has lost direction.
</P>
<P>
   The least interesting and most plentiful pieces on view consist
of boomboxes and stereo sets that are customized with the addition
of toys, leather and little carts that make them portable.
Excessively busy, most of these works are simply a familiar form of
assemblage art.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the Boone show is a large sculpture of a
working airplane bathroom, which the artist built by hand, mostly
from foam core. It resembles a space capsule, but its main source
of interest is that it is something few people ever see from the
outside, despite their familiarity with its interior. And splayed
across this exterior are its inner workings _ the various tubes,
pipes and tanks that enable it to function _ all made from found
materials.
</P>
<P>
   This large piece may turn out to be a step in the right
direction. It has some of the imposing presence and intricacy of
Sachs' earlier work, but it lacks either the threatening quality of
his guns or the saccharin cuteness of his other pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Macho, however, it still is, and this suggests another irony. In
the 1980s Ms. Boone's gallery, then in SoHo, was considered one of
the white-hot centers of the art boom and seen as slanting heavily
toward an overtly macho form of Neo-Expressionist painting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the decade's most famous photographs shows several of her
male artists posing bare-chested in her gallery. But now she has
run afoul of the law over a different, more real form of machismo.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Roman Catholic leaders and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani are
attacking Chis Ofili for a painting of the Virgin Mary spotted with
elephant dung at an exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, is it
possible that in the confused juncture of art and politics in the
city the National Rifle Association will mount a defense of Sachs?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
