</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT ORIOLES IN NIGHTCAP TO CLINCH DIVISION TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ For just a few hours Thursday night, the New York
Yankees were relieved of the unwavering pressure they created for
themselves. They finished off the Baltimore Orioles Thursday night,
12-5, to clinch the American League East title.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Watson struck out Ryan Minor at 11:01 p.m. for the final
out, and then the Yankees shook hands and hugged on the field.
Derek Jeter shook a fist in celebration toward Yankee fans as he
ran off the field, and manager Joe Torre waved.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who lost the first game of the day-night
doubleheader, 5-0, didn't clinch with a strong finish. They have
played erratically against second-division teams much of this year,
losing three straight games to Tampa Bay as recently as last
weekend. But at 96-63, the Yankees remain in the running for the
best record in the league. They have three games remaining, at
Tampa Bay against the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland is 97-62 and Texas 95-64 in the race for home-field
advantage and playoff placement. Torre indicated before Thursday's
doubleheader that regardless of whether his team wrapped up the
division against Baltimore, he intended to continue playing the
bulk of his regulars in an effort to win as many games as possible.
As it stands now, the Yankees would open the best-of-5 division
series in Yankee Stadium next Tuesday, against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees faced upheaval even before they opened the season.
On the first day of spring training, David Wells, the broadly
curved left-hander who endeared himself to fans with his penchant
for pitching in big games and his taste for beer, was swapped with
two other players for star pitcher Roger Clemens. Torre received a
diagnosis of prostate cancer a couple of weeks later and was
replaced until mid-May by his close friend Don Zimmer, who
unhappily assumed what he considered a burden while struggling to
move on two painful knees.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry, a powerful part of the Yankees' lineup last
season, tried and failed to cope with the effects of chemotherapy
for colon cancer while attempting to win a spot with the team, and
in April was arrested for drug possession and solicitation. A
handful of players, from Paul O'Neill to Scott Brosius, were torn
by illnesses in their family.
</P>
<P>
   And all season the Yankees have played in the shadow of what
they accomplished in 1998, when they set a record by winning 125
games and finished with a four-game sweep of San Diego in the World
Series. Players sometimes griped early in the year that fans and
the news media unfairly compared the 1999 Yankees to that standard,
but by midsummer it became apparent that the Yankees themselves
were trying to live up to their own impossible expectations. Nearly
all the Yankees have been guilty of pressing and pushing themselves
into ruts of anxiety at one time or another, and their performance
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their problems, however, they remain the most potent
club in the league and perhaps in all of baseball. Jeter moved to
the next level of stardom, his average above .350 most of this
season, and Mariano Rivera has not blown a save since July. Their
starting pitching of Clemens, David Cone, Orlando Hernandez, Andy
Pettitte and Hideki Irabu buoyed the team all year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of baseball's other divisions were long since wrapped up,
and there were a few days earlier this month when it appeared the
Red Sox might challenge the Yankees for the AL East title. But the
Yankees won 9 of 10 games, faltered in three straight losses
against Tampa Bay, but recovered enough here to wrap up the
division.
</P>
<P>
   When Hernandez tagged out Baltimore's Calvin Pickering on a
ground ball up the first-base line in the sixth inning, Pickering
threw an elbow in Hernandez's direction; the Yankees' pitcher
glared at him, and Martinez and pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre and
catcher Jorge Posada went to the mound to calm Hernandez. They all
shared a laugh, Martinez closing the meeting by drawing his hands
together and shouting a word, as if to break up a football huddle.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the clubhouse, arrangements had been made for a
celebration: There was champagne, and the lockers were covered. ``I
hope we do celebrate,'' Scott Brosius said earlier in the day.
``Because winning a division, that's an accomplishment that should
be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours, anyway. They will be back to business on
Friday, trying for home-field advantage, before the playoffs and
the pursuit of the organization's 25th championship open next week.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
