<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3009 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BARKLEY-H     10-01 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BARKLEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
and JONATHAN FEIGEN 
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
One day after being described as ``not willing to go the distance''
by teammate Scottie Pippen, the Rockets' Charles Barkley decided to
turn the other cheek.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pippen lashed out at Barkley during an interview Wednesday for
ESPN's SportsCentury series, calling him ``a very selfish guy'' and
saying he ``doesn't show the desire to want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley, speaking by phone Thursday from Phoenix, did not
answer Pippen's shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Pippen (stuff) is an annoying distraction to me,''
Barkley said, ``but I'll take the high road and not respond.
Believe me, it takes some (self-)control, but I have to do it. Why
get into a war of words?''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley did say that what might appear to be a petulant outburst
by Pippen sounded calculated to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's creating all this controversy just to get traded,''
Barkley said. ``He wants to get traded so bad that he'll just say
anything to make it happen. He should have just called me and said
that he didn't want to play here anymore. That's all it would have
taken. He didn't have to fabricate this friction like he did. I'm
very disappointed in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, who played for the minimum salary last season so the
Rockets could accommodate Pippen's five-year, $67 million deal, in
August said he resented Pippen's behind-the-scenes lobbying to get
himself traded to Los Angeles, where he could be reunited with
former Bulls coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, Scottie owes the Rockets' fans an apology,'' Barkley
said at the time. ``They've been terrific to him. Second, he owes
the Rockets an apology. And third, he owes me an apology. Scottie
needs to stand up and be a man. If he does, we can move on.
Everything will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen apparently resented the remarks and ripped into Barkley
during Wednesday's interview with ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't give Charles Barkley an apology at gunpoint,''
Pippen said. ``He can never expect an apology from me. If anything,
he owes me an apology for coming to play with his fat butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen went on to say he was the one who should be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very selfish guy,'' Pippen said of Barkley. ``He
doesn't show the desire to want to win. That's my reason for
wanting to get away from playing with him anymore, because he just
doesn't show the dedication. I probably should've listened to
Michael (Jordan) a year ago when he said that Charles will never
win a championship because he doesn't show any dedication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very shocked to see what type of player he was by
spending half a season with him. I'm a guy that's dedicated to
winning, and I put out a lot of effort on the court. I expect that
from my teammates, especially from a guy of his caliber. You know
he's not willing to go the distance. There's no reason for me to
put my last three or four years at risk of never winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said he had a hard time understanding the personal
nature of Pippen's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was more supportive of Scottie than I was,'' Barkley
said. ``I don't think I offended him in any way. I'm disappointed
more than anything. But what good would it do me to get into a
public war of words with him? How can you win in that situation? It
wouldn't accomplish anything.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another factor to consider, Barkley added. Even though
Pippen has been rumored to be headed to Portland in a deal that
would have the Trail Blazers shipping six players in return, there
is still the possibility Pippen will be a Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, we may have to play together,'' Barkley said. ``I'm
trying to take the high road and not make this a problem right now.
But if they don't trade him (Pippen), we may have some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   If Pippen launched his attack on Barkley intending to hasten his
departure from the Rockets, he might have earned his one-way
ticket. But the aftershocks of Pippen's invective Wednesday might
serve that cause not by inspiring the Rockets to deal him but by
giving them more options.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were well on their way to a deal to ship Pippen to
the Blazers even before he ripped Barkley. But now that teams have
decided Pippen could be drastically marked down in a limited-time
offer, the offers have begun to roll in.
</P>
<P>
   After so many conversations on so many trade possibilities all
summer netted few real offers for Pippen, sources said Thursday
that many teams called to weigh in with their collections of
high-salaried players they would happily ship for him.
</P>
<P>
   But no offer has been deemed more attractive than the six-player
deal in the works with Portland. The trade would send Pippen to the
Trail Blazers for Walt Williams, Stacey Augmon, Kelvin Cato, Ed
Gray, Brian Shaw and Carlos Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, an outstanding shooter who could step into Pippen's
small-forward position, and Cato, a third-year center with
outstanding potential as a defender, are considered the keys to the
deal for the Rockets. Barring other transactions, the Rockets would
have to cut at least four players by the start of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal was not complete Thursday, and the inclusion of
draft picks could be affected, several sources said, by Pippen's
comments. The trade will not be completed until Saturday at the
earliest, according to a source close to the discussions. Training
camp will begin Tuesday in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets officials, citing team policy, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   But if Pippen has made his desire to leave the Rockets clear, at
least two of the players involved have expressed their desire or
willingness to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walt's feelings are basically that he likes it in Portland,
but Walt loves to play,'' said Williams' agent, Mark Bartelstein.
``He likes to play a lot of minutes. We've talked to the Blazers
about their overabundance of threes and fours and that maybe it
would be best for everybody if Walt was moved. We did not demand a
trade, but this could be a terrific situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been talking to (Blazers vice present) Bob Whitsitt all
summer. Walt is a guy that has a lot of pride and loves to play.
It's been difficult for him to get a lot of minutes. They like
Walt, and he's a terrific person. They've been willing to work with
us to make a trade. But they weren't willing to just give him away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is a good franchise. They've certainly got some pieces
there right now, and they play inside-out a lot, and Walt can make
the 3-pointers. They would need a (small forward), and Walt can
handle the ball as well as any (small forward) in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw is a free agent, but his agent, Jerome Stanley, said the
Trail Blazers have discussed the trade with him and that Shaw would
agree to a sign-and-trade deal to the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is anything here that would be a
problem,'' Stanley said. ``It's a part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is an excellent city. Brian would love to play
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
