<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3010 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FOR now, the war of words appears over, or at least in a state of
truce while the U.N. Security Council debates sending in troops.
For now, Charles Barkley has put himself above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Having considered the source, the Chuckster is taking the high
road. His only response to Scottie Pippen's sandbox-caliber chatter
is to express further disappointment in a fellow with whom he was
already disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Barkley is busy. That big ol' bottom of his at which
Snotty Scottie took direct aim? Well, rumor has it Charles stopped
off recently at the fat farm, trying to run off some of his rump
roast prior to the start of training camp next week.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley will return to Houston on Sunday night. Hopefully,
Pippen won't.
</P>
<P>
   The only body part Scottie is known to be exercising is his
mouth. Of course, cardio work for him would be futile, considering
how little evidence he gave us to suggest he has any heart left.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's public bayou bridge-burning should come as a welcome
relief to Rockets fans. By giving the team almost no choice other
than to trade him, a win-win transaction on all counts, they'll try
that much harder to close a deal. They won't be lulled into
complacency, into making the fatal assumption he would return for a
second Rockets season intending to earn his absurd salary.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Tomjanovich might start sleeping better with Pip the Drip
out of his graying hair. He won't have to change his offense any
further to keep the big creep happy. Rudy T can resume coaching
full-time and give up his part-time baby-sitting responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you ever try to find diapers for a kid Pippen's size?
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets will be a better team without the Pippen we know in
Houston, no matter what they get in return for him. I would trade
him to Portland for J.R. Rider's bail bondsman. Getting warm bodies
from the Trail Blazers is cream gravy. Cross your fingers the
Blazers don't come to their senses and deep-six the
six-for-one-half exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Williams by his lonesome for Pippen is enough to make you
shout ``Yippee!'' Williams is a good guy, a low-maintenance,
positive force in the locker room. Also, young Kelvin Cato seems
enough of a defensive presence at center to take a bit of the load
off Hakeem Olajuwon. Alone, they add up to far more of an asset
than a selfish, whiny Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're wondering why the Rockets aren't trying to
revisit the Glen Rice-Robert Horry trade, it's because the Lakers
have taken it off the table. Jerry West sacrificed Eddie Jones to
acquire Rice, and he's not ready to ship him out, certainly not for
a player of Pippen's more-dubious-by-the-day character. Even Phil
Jackson has to be shaking his head about Pippen's juvenile
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Barkley started this fight by roundly criticizing
Pippen's desire to be traded, but the points he made were sound,
and never once did he personally attack Scottie. Fact is, Pippen
has had no greater apologist than the Chuckster.
</P>
<P>
   Let no good deed go unpunished, Charles.
</P>
<P>
   But, remember, the one good thing about the Rockets having
acquired Scottie, as in spotty, is that he cost them only money
(and, OK, Roy Rogers). It was a $14 million experiment that blew up
in their faces, but the residual damage _ except to Pippen's
reputation _ was negligible. They didn't mortgage their future to
obtain his services.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to remain a Rocket, Scottie would become the bane of
their existence in the years to come. The last two seasons of his
five-year contract would cost the Rockets $37 million, crippling
their ability to remake the roster around him. And imagine how
worthless he's likely to be by then.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a mandate to cut one's losses. To date, they have
wasted only a season waiting for him to get his head on straight,
and fortunately it was a short year, one that didn't place undue
strain on the aging legs of Charles and Hakeem. The gamble,
assuming they can dump the chump, hardly paid off, but it was worth
the risk. Who could have guessed he'd prove such a dud? He figured
to be, at the very least, a good complementary player to Olajuwon
and Barkley. Instead, he became a most uncomplimentary one.
</P>
<P>
   What if the Rockets can't move him? Mon dieu. They will make the
'74 Oakland A's look like the '79 Pirates. They'll need to have two
dressing rooms plus a padded cell for Tomjanovich. Jerry Springer
might have to be brought in as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   So light a candle for this trade coming down. May Scottie's
unhappy trail lead him to the Blazers by the weekend. He needs to
be gone quickly, if only for his safety, before Barkley sees him.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's media day might end up looking like a World Wrestling
Federation production. And if push came to shove, it surely would
be the Chuckster vs. the duckster. Pippen hasn't a clue how to meet
a challenge head-on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
