<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GORE-NYT &LR;      10-01 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PLACE TO RUN FROM
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 1:
</P>
<P>
   Even in this restless time, America's politicians need the
appearance of a healthy root system. Successful presidential
candidates in particular seem to require an elaborate connection to
some modest place, a down-home setting for the campaign's
background myth. Thus, Vice President Al Gore, mostly of
Washington, D.C., has returned to Tennessee and not merely to dust
off his old family homestead. Gore needs to establish a
headquarters that will operate more efficiently than the one that
turned him from front-runner into self-described underdog. But the
real goal is to minimize his deep connection to Washington, to
identify him with that supposedly more authentic America out there,
to be, as he said, closer to Kmart than K Street.
</P>
<P>
   The use of an identifying place as a definitional tool is not
new in presidential politics, and the blend of fact and invention
can vary widely. Ronald Reagan, a Midwesterner and a celluloid
wrangler, somehow managed to take on the romantic mantle of the
real West. George Bush the elder seemed most at home at
Kennebunkport, but he used a Houston address to define a ruddier
political persona. Jimmy Carter really was the Man from Plains,
Ga., and always planned to go back after the White House, which is
not what can be expected from the Man from Hope.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, Gov. George W. Bush has enough Texas time on his
bioclock to offset his preppy lineage. Steve Forbes has established
his story line as a rich kid and proud of it. Elizabeth Dole,
despite years as a force in Washington, has a North Carolina
girlhood, complete with an army of college sorority sisters to help
out. Bill Bradley, who played basketball for New York and served as
senator for New Jersey, invoked a Mayberry childhood in Crystal
City, Mo., to launch his presidential campaign. Yet in an earlier
period, as Time magazine noted, Bradley checked out the
possibilities in Missouri before deciding in 1978 that he had a
better chance running for senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gore is discovering that there are no risk-free zones
in presidential campaigns. He faces embarrassment at his new
address if Bush continues to lead him in the Tennessee polls.
Pundits are already seeing the southerly trek as a sign of
desperation. He also faces the possibility that Bradley will stick
to the calm style that has served him so well and refuse to join
the debates that Gore now needs more badly than Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seems receptive, showing that both candidates understand
the public mood. The sudden upheaval in the Democratic contest has
riveted attention and represents an opportunity for a revitalized
national discussion, not just on health care, but on the whole
range of social-policy issues. Even the purported candidacies of
Donald Trump and Warren Beatty are signs of a heightened interest,
even passion, that has gripped this political season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, given the extreme front-loading of the primaries, both
Democratic and Republican voters need to see their candidates in
multiple joint appearances, starting even before the proposed
Democratic town meeting in New Hampshire in four weeks. Gore's
sudden interest in debates may be self-serving or even desperate,
but he has nonetheless offered a worthy idea. Maybe Bradley would
even agree to hold one debate at Ryman Auditorium in Nashville, a
fitting place for the celebration of roots, both real and slightly
imagined.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
