<HEADER>
A3016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-HEALTHCARE-NYT &LR;      10-01 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEALTHCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HEALTH CARE REFORMS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 1:
</P>
<P>
   The enactment of new health care reforms in California shows
that state leaders are well ahead of Congress in addressing the
need for managed care regulation. While many states have moved
forward with consumer protection laws aimed at health maintenance
organizations, the sweep of the California legislation contained in
21 bills, along with similarly broad legislation in Texas, sets an
important standard by which to judge national reform.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial piece of the California package would
allow patients to sue managed care plans for compensatory and
punitive damages if the patient was substantially harmed by a
health plan's action to deny, delay or modify necessary medical
care. The barrier to suing would be high _ lawsuits would be
allowed only when a patient could show that he had suffered
significant harm or significant financial loss. But the law does
not limit the amount of recovery for those losses.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of legal liability has been bitterly fought in
Congress by the insurance lobby, and will be the focus again as the
House begins debate on patients' rights legislation next week. But
in California, Gov. Gray Davis and legislative leaders were able to
craft language that should deter frivolous suits while holding
health plans legally accountable for improper decisions. The
insurance lobby's warning that allowing lawsuits would send health
costs soaring simply has not materialized. An independent study of
one million public employees in California who already have the
right to sue HMOs found that the number of suits filed was very low
and the impact on medical costs minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The California reforms also guarantee patients the right to an
independent review of benefit denials and create a new state agency
called the Department of Managed Care to regulate the industry and
assist consumers with complaints. The package would further tighten
medical privacy laws, as well as require plans to provide coverage
for severe mental illness, prescription contraceptives and cancer
screening. Other states may follow California's lead if they see
that such reforms can improve health care without significantly
increasing costs.
</P>
<P>
   But state initiatives do not replace the need for federal
legislation. For one thing, none of these protections apply to
people in ``self-insured'' plans created by large employers, which
are exclusively federally regulated. More important, current
federal law has long been interpreted to bar patients covered by
private employer-sponsored health plans from suing for damages
caused by improper benefit denials, although the Supreme Court this
week decided to hear a case that will review this issue. The
California legislation tries to get around the legal hurdle by
framing the new state-granted right to sue as based on the right to
obtain quality of care rather the right to particular benefits.
That approach will clearly be challenged in court and may well be
struck down unless Congress closes the loophole in Federal law that
now shields health plans from meaningful liability.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 million Californians will benefit from new managed
care regulations. Americans elsewhere need Congress to enact basic
protections to insure that patients get the care they need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-     10-01 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY ROLLS, WAITS FOR WORD ON FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After the 1979 season, then-Angels general
manager Buzzie Bavasi let Nolan Ryan get away. Soon Bavasi's son,
Bill, could be faced with a similar situation regarding Chuck
Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, a free agent after this season, has surpassed most of
Ryan's pitching records with the Angels and it's him _ not Ryan _
who is considered as ``Mr. Angel'' to his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The current Anaheim Angels GM hopes he doesn't follow in his
father's footsteps, especially since he wouldn't trade Finley to
the Indians for highly regarded prospects before this season's July
31 trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Finley made his final start of 1999 on Thursday night as the
Angels beat the Oakland A's 5-4 before 19,567 at Edison Field. The
question is, was it his last?
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson drove in Troy Glaus with a two-out single in the
eighth inning to snap a 4-4 tie, making a winner out of Angels
reliever Mark Petkovsek (10-4). Lou Pote pitched the ninth and
earned his second career save one night after getting his first.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended with right fielder Tim Salmon playing Rich
Becker's drive off the right-field wall perfectly, then throwing
Becker out at second.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Angel Randy Velarde had four hits for Oakland, and the
Angels' Garret Anderson hit his career-best 21st home run.
</P>
<P>
   But the story of the night was Finley. He gave up four runs and
10 hits in seven innings, striking out nine and walking four. The
nine strikeouts gave him 200 for the season (second best in the AL
behind Pedro Martinez's 312), marking the third time in his career
he's struck out 200 or more. He finished the season 12-11 with an
ERA of 4.43 ERA in 33 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken (since 1981 with Baltimore) and Tony Gwynn (since
1982 with San Diego) are the only active players who have more
service time with one club than Finley, who joined the Angels in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's possible his Angels career is done, Finley never
allowed himself to get sentimental, saying there was no reason for
it. Sure, he might be gone, but so might anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a waste of my time (to worry about it),'' he said.
``I don't even know where the organization's going, so.... There's
probably a lot of us who think we'll be here and might be gone.
There's no use to ponder.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley pitched horribly during the season's middle months. In 11
starts from June 7 through July 31, he was 1-5 with a 7.01 ERA. But
once the trading deadline passed, Finley turned it around.
Including Thursday's game, he is 7-1 with a 2.16 ERA in 11 starts
in August and September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew better days were ahead of me,'' he said. ``I've still
got a lot of life left in my arm ... for whoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley and Bavasi agreed to put off talks until after the
season. But before July 31 the two talked, and Finley reportedly
told teammates he was working on a deal worth $14 million over two
years.
</P>
<P>
   At the time it might have seemed a hefty price to pay for a
soon-to-be 37-year-old pitcher who lost 10 of his first 15
decisions this year. But Finley will finish the season as the team
leader in victories. Including this season, Finley has held or tied
the club lead in wins for seven consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Angels interim manager Joe Maddon has been with the organization
even longer than Finley. Maddon, who played in the Angels'
minor-league system in the 1970s and began coaching in 1981, said
the value of Finley's clubhouse presence is impossible to measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like Fin around because of everything he brings to the
table,'' Maddon said. ``Fin is the guy you identify as being an
Angel.... His record speaks for itself, it's not difficult to
ascertain. He's been a very important part of what we've done the
last 14 years. He's a wonderful person and a great pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley ranks first on the Angels' all-time list in games pitched
(436), victories (165), starts (379) and innings pitched (2,675).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
