<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-VIRUS-MCNAMARA-ART     10-01 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-MCNAMARA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFILE: A PASSIONATE LIFE IN A LAB WITH DEAD ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's always nice when you see a scientist in
playfully patterned scrubs; it suggests that English, rather than
Science, is the language of choice. But Dr. Tracey S. McNamara,
head of the pathology department at the Bronx Zoo (those are
geckos, by the way, on her scrubs) quickly disabuses you of that.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists nationwide are aflutter over the findings that the
encephalitis outbreak that has resulted in at least five deaths in
the New York metropolitan region was caused by a virus never before
seen in the Western Hemisphere, the somewhat exotically named West
Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   Many are crediting the findings to Dr. McNamara's lab work.
</P>
<P>
   Tell us, if you would, Dr. McNamara, of the moment when you
realized you were onto something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ames'' _ sorry, we have to stop immediately to translate:
that's the National Veterinary Services Laboratory in Ames, Iowa,
where Dr. McNamara had been sending tissue samples from dead birds
_ ``was working on the virus,'' Dr. McNamara says, surrounded by
two cans and a bottle of Diet Pepsi, which, one suspects, have been
fueling both her 14-hour work days and her somewhat hyper
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was 40 nanometers in diameter. I was like,
`Eureka! It's a flavi virus, what they are now calling the West
Nile. It's part of the Group B arbo virus, arbo stands for
arthropod-borne virus. The group everyone thought it would be was
the alpha virus, those are 60 to 65 nanometers. We differentiate
virus by their size and characteristics. No previous representative
of that group of virus has been known to ever kill birds. I knew we
had something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Better we tell this story, so the accomplishments of the
compulsive, relentlessly logical research veterinarian her
colleagues occasionally call Dr. Death do not get lost:
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, crows were dying in huge numbers around the
Bronx. The week after Labor Day, a number of birds in the Bronx Zoo
collection were found dead, apparently of encephalitis; around the
same time some human deaths were attributed to the disease. Dr.
McNamara felt the coincidence was ``too striking to ignore.'' She
performed post-mortems on the zoo birds and sent tissue to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and to the National
Veterinary Lab, pursuing her suspicions that ``a novel disease''
might be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Duane J. Gubler, head of the Center for Disease Control's
arbo virus field station in Fort Collins, Colo., has said his
institute could not have made the diagnosis of West Nile virus as
quickly ``without Dr. McNamara's persistent sleuthing.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Dr. McNamara persistently sleuthing or persistently
pestering, she is asked. A deft dodge:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say the secretaries could recognize my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Gotham, people hire publicity agents to get into the
paper. The charm of scientists and zoo keepers of the Wildlife
Conservation Society is that they would like the press to go away.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. McNamara, 45, is of this breed. She regards a reporter with
the same enthusiasm the reporter shows for the dead chameleon
floating in formaldehyde in her lab, which is to say, none.
</P>
<P>
   Is all this press attention exciting? No, she would prefer to
get back to work and ``trim in the cases''; she still does not have
the full histo-pathology on the zoo animals that have died. What
did her parents do? Dr. McNamara's arms cross protectively. She
says she doesn't see any reason to give personal information. It's
``embarrassing.'' There is one unexpectedly frank admission. Asked
if she has a significant other, Dr. McNamara blurts, ``Single _and
available,'' with an urgency that suggests she should take a break
and get out of the lab.
</P>
<P>
   She does say, eventually, that she grew up in Forest Hills,
Queens, one of two children. Her father owned a newsstand, her
mother was a math teacher. Her mother was also a ``brilliant''
investor, which allowed the family to travel frequently. Dr.
McNamara loved animals, travel and languages, and majored in French
at St. Lawrence University in upstate New York. In her junior year,
at the University of Rouen _ in the city ``where Joan of Arc was
burned'' _ she decided to be a veterinarian, and got a degree at
Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. McNamara now lives in a zoo-owned apartment on City Island.
She owns two ``fabulous'' Siamese cats, Coco Puff and Pussy Willow,
despite being allergic to them. She enjoys the mystery books of
Patricia Cornwall, whose heroine is a pathologist. She is a
Buddhist. She does not, it turns out, carve a heck of a turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't eat it, it's too close to the work. I haven't been
able to pick up a chicken wing in years. Or barbecue. If it's
recognizable, I can't pick it up. I'm too aware of disease. I won't
let my friends eat sushi. I read the morbidity and mortality weekly
report. From the CDC.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, even though camera crews are lining up to interview her,
Dr. McNamara cannot get too worked up. Two times before, she has
discovered virus in unexpected places.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big thing, but it's not the first time I've
uncovered something like this, and I suspect it won't be the
last,'' Dr. McNamara says. Uncharacteristically, she flounders for
a moment seeking a reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that quote from Shakespeare? `There are more things in
heaven and earth, Horatio''' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, a language we both speak, we can do this one together:
</P>
<P>
   . . . ```than are dreamt of in your philosophy.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
