<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BRUISED, NOT BEATEN (YET)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the span of about four hours last Saturday
night, USC lost its franchise player and a triple-overtime thriller
to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Could things get any worse for the Trojans? Probably. The morbid
thought following the lost weekend in Eugene was whether the
Trojans' season is already over three games into the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   It's a vicious question, but there's little doubt USC is reeling
after star quarterback Carson Palmer broke his collarbone and the
Trojans dropped their Pacific-10 Conference opener.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Palmer is the single most devastating injury USC
could have suffered, and has produced some numb feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really tough, to tell you the truth,'' wide receiver
R. Jay Soward said. ``Nobody talked about Carson getting hurt.
Nobody talked about that happening before the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, expectations for the Trojans have diminished. No one
was thinking about anything but whether USC could challenge for the
Pac-10 title a couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are questions about everything from quarterback to
tailback to the offensive line to the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're wounded, I know that,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``This is the toughest loss we've had to come back from. And the
loss of Carson. We've been blasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did we mention the schedule is about to hit its supposed
rough patch?
</P>
<P>
   ``The next three weeks are brutal,'' Hackett added.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the entire month of October is going to determine the
Trojans' fate. After Saturday's game with undefeated Oregon State
at the Coliseum, USC travels to Arizona and Notre Dame, returns
home to face conference leader Stanford and then finishes up at
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be looking at 6-6,'' a player said in half-jest this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (2-1) aren't exactly giving up on the season, but
they realize they are a long way from the optimism that flowed
after their 62-7 season-opening victory over Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season. We can't let this take too much of a
toll,'' cornerback Kris Richard said. ``We have to move on. We're
planning on bouncing back. We don't want to develop that losing
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett believes a free fall can be prevented by remembering
last year's team, which followed every regular-season loss with a
victory. That includes coming back from demoralizing losses to Cal,
Oregon and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' energy in practice this week led Hackett to believe
this year's team will also be able to recover quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signs are there. This team has great resilience,'' Hackett
said. ``We're a good football team. We know that.''
</P>
<P>
   They will have to be resilient, considering backup quarterback
Mike Van Raaphorst is likely to play the rest of the season,
barring a miraculous recovery from Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer's injury could effectively undermine the offense's
confidence, but tailback Chad Morton said that as Van Raaphorst
engineered the fourth-quarter comeback against Oregon, he noticed a
different feeling in the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got it solved,'' Morton said. ``I know a lot of
guys were scared with Carson going down. But toward the middle of
the fourth quarter, Mike came back and a lot of guys had faith in
him. He has a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a theory that Van Raaphorst might play better this
season because he no longer has to worry about Palmer waiting in
the wings to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst said he doesn't feel any burden to prevent the
Trojans from regressing offensively, or worry he might become a
scapegoat if USC starts losing games.
</P>
<P>
   He even discounts the proposition that Palmer's presence
affected his performance last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any of that as extra weight. I don't feel extra
pressure,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``I've been up and down too much to
worry about that. A friend told me, `You're like a cat with nine
lives.' He told me, `You're pretty invincible.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates hope so. Some worried privately about his chronic
nausea and vomiting that affected him before or during three games
last season, and wondered if game-day jitters were the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Raaphorst said he discovered last summer while visiting
his family doctor in San Diego that the anti-cramping pills passed
out before games were the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the quarterback position becomes the focal point for
USC's remaining nine games, Hackett places more significance on the
rest of the Trojans' reaction to Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the quarterback,'' he said. ``It's how the team
responds to change at quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the inconsistent offensive line will have to do
a better job, considering Van Raaphorst is less mobile than Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the offensive line's got to keep Mike clean,'' Soward
said.
</P>
<P>
   For every doubter who figures USC will fold under all of this
adversity, there are those who remain unaffected by the recent
misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any doubts. My goal is the same, the Rose Bowl,''
linebacker Zeke Moreno said. ``If anything, all of this has made us
mad to kick some butt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
