<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-01 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS READY FOR MURRAY'S NEW ERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's no truth to the rumor Andy Murray was
plugged into the NHL computer that spits out the team schedules.
</P>
<P>
   You can see where somebody might draw that conclusion, though.
It'd be just like the Los Angeles Kings' fastidious first-year head
coach to start the season against a Nashville team that was
peripherally responsible for the firing of Murray's predecessor,
Larry Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings lost three of four games against the expansion
Predators. Being outworked and outscored by a rag-tag team of
overachievers provided an apt metaphor for the franchise's sorry
1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   What better way to usher in a new era than to open the season
with a resounding victory in Nashville on Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to predict where the Kings will finish in the
wonderful Western Conference _ home to the past four Stanley Cup
champions _ but we can say with absolute certainty they'll own the
first-year Atlanta Thrashers in their two meetings this season.
</P>
<P>
   Murray will make sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits don't give the Kings _ a consensus favorite to bring
up the rear of the Pacific Division _ much of a prayer of making
the playoffs. To pick the Kings to finish out of the Conference's
top eight is to seriously underestimate Murray's powers of
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will grace the postseason in 2000 because they are
more skilled than last year, they can't help but be more healthy
(they lost 335 man games to injuries or illnesses last season, 169
more than the year before) and they will be more efficient than
Molly Maids.
</P>
<P>
   Forget ``Serious Hockey,'' the slogan of this year's Kings might
as well be ``Excellence: It's all in the details.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray is so organized, every practice and every period allows
his players about as much wiggle room as the neutral-zone trap. He
is so meticulous, if David E. Kelly were to make a movie of the
Kings, Murray would be played by Tony Randall. Or David Hyde
Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Such fastidiousness isn't just a compulsion, it's an imperative
for any team having to navigate around Dallas and Detroit and
Colorado, arguably the three best teams in all of professional
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings dropped 18 one-goal games last season. Twelve of those
losses were to conference foes. With so many games decided by one
shot or one shift, diligence matters. Coaches can't afford to leave
their skaters on the ice for even a second too long. Players can't
afford to lose their focus for even a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   As such, Murray has assigned equipment manager Peter Millar to
time each shift of every game this year. Millar will be like a
track coach calling out splits in a race. When he gets to 40
seconds, it'll be time for one shift to pass the baton, as it were,
to another.
</P>
<P>
   Any player who can't concentrate for 40 seconds at a stretch
likely will find himself with all the time in the world to
daydream. On those AHL or IHL bus trips.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, those who perform laudably can expect to see extra
ice time, no matter if they're a star or journeyman. Murray, you
see, is an equal opportunity taskmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Barring injuries, the Kings will have the depth this year to
deliver pointed messages, something Robinson wished to do but
couldn't if the Kings were to remain at all competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The first shots of the new regime were fired during the Kings'
second exhibition game against Colorado. The Kings fell behind 2-1,
at which point Murray called a timeout and called his team out.
They proceeded to rally for an overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings can't say they weren't warned. Murray met with every
player during the summer and outlined exactly what he expected from
each. He followed each meeting up with a letter, re-stating his
points.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that before the start of training camp the Kings had
had more one-on-one contact with their head coach than some NHL
players will experience in a season with their delegating,
detached, dictatorial bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Murray made quite an impression in the dressing room during the
Kings' penalty-marred exhibition game against Anaheim last week. If
his players' sticks hadn't been littered all over the ice the
players would have been tempted to bang them on the ice when Murray
harangued Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg for sending his players at
the Kings' skilled skaters after Aki Berg and the Ducks' Teemu
Selanne collided in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the players got out of it was he's willing to stick up
for us, at any cost,'' said defenseman Rob Blake. ``That's what
guys want.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Kings need is for Blake to stay healthy and for his
defensive partner Mattias Norstrom to get signed and for Jozef
Stumpel to perform more like Mark Grudzielanek than Chan Ho Park in
this, the final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   They need defenseman Jere Karalahti to get his visa and for
center Bryan Smolinski to smolder while he skates and for winger
Ziggy Palffy to be, well, himself.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, what the Kings need is for every player to
buy into Murray's methods. He holds the blueprint for success, so
long as his players follow it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
