<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3039 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN     10-01 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YOU`VE GOT (HATE) E MAIL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If it wasn't bad enough that USC kicker David
Newbury missed three field goals against Oregon, he felt even worse
when he received a nasty e-mail from a fan this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a real shallow person to do that. I don't know why
anyone would take the time to make someone feel bad,'' Newbury
said. ``It said that I cost us the game and a Top 25 ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury said that punter Mike MacGillivray also received an
e-mail ``because he had a punt go out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The junior college transfer said he received comfort from
quarterback Carson Palmer, who said he received angry e-mails last
season.
</P>
<P>
   There was some good news for Newbury. His brother, Keith, who
lives in Texas, noticed a flaw in Newbury's kicking technique while
watching a tape of the Oregon game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking a step toward (holder) John Fox and then came
around like on a golf swing,'' Newbury said. ``I've straightened it
out. I've never looked forward to a game like this Saturday. It
will be a real test of my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury, who spent extra time kicking at the Coliseum on
Thursday, made 11 of 13 field goals from 42 yards in practice this
week and said his kicks are traveling much better than in last
week's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching connection: USC defensive line coach Ed Orgeron is
extremely close to Oregon State head coach Dennis Erickson, who
gave Orgeron his first job as an assistant at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be out there to kick our butt,'' Orgeron said. ``There's
no doubt about that. He's extremely competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron coached the Miami lines that included Cortez Kennedy and
Russell Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson said this week that USC's defensive line is similar to
those Miami lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not there yet, but that's where we're aiming to get,''
Orgeron said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson in control: As reported last week, offensive coordinator
Hue Jackson called the plays last week against Oregon. He is
expected to call the plays again Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer update: Doctors examined quarterback Carson Palmer on
Wednesday night and found that his broken collarbone is healing on
schedule, meaning he will still be out six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting a lot less sore,'' Palmer said. ``And starting to
heal better. Hopefully, I'll be ready for the UCLA game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Palmer is relegated to watching practice from
the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it,'' he said. ``I hate being out here and not
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is forced to sleep on a stack of pillows so that he can
be upright in his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like sleeping in a chair,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   No respect: Oregon State (3-0) earned one vote in the latest
Associated Press poll. The vote was provided by a reporter in
Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Beavers received a vote was two seasons ago,
when a reporter from Arkansas mistakenly put the 2-2 Beavers at No.
25 in his poll, thinking they had a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Tailback Malaefou MacKenzie, bothered by a sore
hamstring, will probably not be at full strength until midseason.
He is doubtful for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive linemen Eric Denmon (knee), Donta Kendrick (ankle) and
cornerback Eric Reese (ankle) are probable. Defensive lineman Aaron
Williams (sore Achilles') and safety DeShaun Hill (foot) are
possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     10-01 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CANDLE IS OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the late-afternoon shadows crept across the
infield of Candlestick Park, a strong wind kicked up and suddenly
things seem a little more like home.
</P>
<P>
   For most of Thursday being here seemed like crashing a cocktail
party for 61,389. When the Los Angeles Dodgers and San Francisco
Giants played the final game the sun was out and the crowd was
well-behaved. Even when Giants reliever Julian Tavarez drilled Mark
Grudzielanek in the back in the ninth inning, everyone kept their
seats.
</P>
<P>
   No fights, no hot dog wrappers caught in the batter's shoe.
</P>
<P>
   There were names and faces that didn't register when 50 or so
old Giants were introduced after the game. Some video clips of guys
in long sideburns and gaudy-looking uniforms that will never have a
place in Cooperstown. Sure the crowd cheered Barry Bonds. Somebody
has to.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Willie Mays and Juan Marichal, it was like looking
through a yearbook that had nobody you knew.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly the guy in the next seat was crying. Couldn't be
because the Dodgers won 9-4 in some meaningless game in the final
week of the season. He was crying because he'll never sit in that
seat again. He was crying because to a Giants fan there is no such
thing as a meaningless Dodger game.
</P>
<P>
   That is the connection that made Thursday's going-away party so
special. If there weren't Giants there wouldn't be Dodgers. They
weren't a bad team, except maybe for the early '80s. But even in
their championship seasons they were the underdog. They hated us,
but we never hated them.
</P>
<P>
   A July night in Dodger Stadium was glorious. A July night in
Candlestick was a trip to the South Pole. But you couldn't have had
one without the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a player's standpoint, this was the worst place you could
ever play,'' said former Giants second baseman Robby Thompson, who
once turned down a chance to sign with the Dodgers as a free agent.
``But I wouldn't have changed a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans in L.A. are pretty smug about their success. They don't
even bother with old-timers' stuff anymore. Here it is different. A
huge cheer went up for '70s reserve catcher Mike Sadek and Giants
fans made him a baseball god, if for just a few moments.
</P>
<P>
   It was a much bigger ovation than anything Brett Butler heard.
The scrappy Butler helped get the Giants to their last World Series
in 1987. More importantly to these fans, he left here to play for
the Dodgers four years later. They booed him Thursday like they did
the day he left.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally it was a day for romantics, even if many think
Candlestick had less charm than Riverfront Stadium. Imperfection
looked kind of sweet in the twilight.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, when the names were called it was clear that there was
life here after the Dodgers. But typically, the memories were more
funky than famous. Game 7 of the 1962 World Series when Willie
McCovey lined out to the Yankees' Bobby Richardson with everything
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   There was the earthquake that halted the 1989 series for more
than a week. The Giants got swept by Oakland in that one and
haven't been close to coming back.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end, the Giants trotted out their greatest jewel.
Mays walked through the open doors in center field wearing his old
baseball spikes and waving in the wind to the fans who never really
appreciated him when he played here. He was a New York guy. Willie
McCovey was theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the cheers you could just hear former Dodgers coach Joey
Amalfitano, a Giants bonus baby in the 1950s, offering to fight
anybody who didn't think Mays was the greatest player who ever
lived.
</P>
<P>
   Mays was the one player for whom the Dodgers never had an
answer.
</P>
<P>
   This time the fans got it right.
</P>
<P>
   When they cranked up Tony Bennett for one last rendition of ``I
Left My Heart in San Francisco,'' there was no better place to be.
They blew out the candles on Candlestick Thursday afternoon. Even
with the wind, it was some party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
