<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3050 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN     10-01 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADDON A LONG SHOT FOR PERMANENT JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels were 15-10 under interim
manager Joe Maddon going into Thursday'sgame, a winning percentage
of .600, but Maddon remains a long shot to shed the ``interim'' tag
and win the manager's job for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner and Don Baylor are the leading candidates, but
Maddon's approach is to not concern himself with anything other
than the immediate task at hand -- which is getting ready for that
particular night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Maddon, though, cannot be completely overlooked. The Angels will
finish with a winning record under Maddon and going into Thursday's
game needed only one more victory to guarantee a winning record in
September for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way the team has played, I like the attitude in the
clubhouse a whole lot, and I like the interaction among players,
things I see as being improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddon was asked if he thinks he's presented himself well to
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I have,'' he said. ``But it's up to somebody
else to make that decision. I've done everything I can for the past
three or four weeks. I would not have done anything differently. If
it doesn't work out and I don't get the opportunity full time, I
can walk away feeling satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddon said he has not yet talked with general manager Bill
Bavasi about scheduling an interview for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper won't forget season: Pitcher Brian Cooper's season is
finished, but he won't soon forget it. The former standout at
Glendora High, Citrus College and USC began the season in Double-A
and finished it in the majors, making five starts with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   With the Angels he went 1-1 (three no-decisions) with a 4.88
ERA, gave up 23 hits in 27 2/3 innings and secured himself an
opportunity to make the starting rotation next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity's been awesome,'' Cooper said. ``I think I've
shown I can pitch at this level. I didn't embarrass myself.
Definitely my control needs to improve (18 walks, four hit batters)
... to come up and walk guys I'm sure did not make them happy. But
I consider myself a control pitcher. It's a matter of trusting
myself and going at guys. That's my main concern for now.''
</P>
<P>
   An opportunity: With closer Troy Percival (inflamed right
shoulder) likely shut down for the rest of the season, Lou Pote
will get an opportunity to finish games. He got his first chance
Wednesday night, retiring the A's in order in the ninth to earn his
first career save. The Angels would like to see Pote, a starter in
the minors, develop into a set-up role.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the kind of stuff he possesses, he gets both left-handed
and right-handed hitters out,'' Maddon said. ``A forkball doesn't
know the difference. And he's got plenty of fastball -- he gets up
to 92 mph. If he could accomplish this (closing), we'll look at him
in a set-up position (next season).''
</P>
<P>
   Big attraction: Ramon Ortiz has pitched all year, starting with
the Fall League, then winter ball, then spring training and a full
season in the minors and majors. He's become a big attraction in
the Winter League, but the Angels have suggested he take a break
this winter and rest his arm some.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said he plans to spend a lot of time this off-season in
Southern California to learn English.
</P>
<P>
   Next: The Angels and Texas Rangers begin a three-game series
tonight at 7:05 at Edison Field. Ortiz (2-3, 6.17 ERA) will start
for Anaheim against Texas' Esteban Loaiza (9-5, 4.61).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
