<HEADER>
A3067 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING-     10-01 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDRAISING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FIGURES SHOW BRADLEY HAS EDGE OVER GORE IN SUMMER
FUND  RAISING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The two presidential candidates generating the most
early excitement toured the Bay Area Thursday as new campaign
fund-raising reports gave them plenty to cheer about.
<P>
   Democrat Bill Bradley raised $6.7 million since July, surpassing
the assumed shoo-in candidate, Vice President Al Gore, in fund
raising for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican front-runner George W. Bush has raked in
$57 million so far _ 10 percent of it in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was in Silicon Valley Thursday, picking up campaign
checks at the Fairmont Hotel in San Jose, where he cashed out with
$400,000. The Democratic former New Jersey senator also held a
health care forum in Oakland as part of a three-day swing through
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who introduced a $65 billion proposal for health care
Tuesday, also picked up $500,000 at a fund-raiser at the Mark
Hopkins Hotel earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley had plenty of competition Thursday. Bush also was
crisscrossing high-tech turf, riding virtual roller coasters with
schoolkids at the Tech Museum of Innovation in San Jose, then
collecting $350,000 in Redwood City at a packed luncheon. Among
those on hand were movie legend and former Ambassador Shirley
Temple Black, C-Net CEO Halsey Minor _ once a chief booster of
President Clinton _ and former Secretary of State George Shultz.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign state chair Gerald Parsky said the Texas governor
had raised nearly $6.5 million in California alone. Bush, who has
$37 million in the bank, was expected to pick up $1 million in his
two days in California this week, his campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also continues to outpace his Republican opponents.
Arizona Sen. John McCain was a distant second in fund raising,
collecting $3 million during the last three months and bringing his
total to $9.3 million. That includes $2 million transferred from
his Senate campaign account. Gary Bauer, Patrick &LR;  Buchanan,
Elizabeth Dole, Steve Forbes and Orrin Hatch each raised more than
$1 million from July through September.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Thursday, Bush addressed the issue of
money _ and campaign finance reform _ and whether his campaign has
been so successful that he faces ``an embarrassment of riches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a corrupt person, you'll be corrupted by money.
Honest people can't be corrupted by money,'' Bush said. ``I'm proud
of the accomplishments I've achieved ... when it comes to raising
money. I've had good success in that, and I'm grateful for that
success. ... It's an indication of a lot of support.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said the also believes campaigns should be held
accountable for fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in instant disclosure. We ought to let the sun shine
in,'' the governor said. ``We ought to raise the limits of what
people can contribute to a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bradley's campaign announced that it raised $6.7
million since July 1, spending about $4.2 million. This gives the
campaign $10 million in the bank, about the same amount as Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the figures, Bradley said he is still the underdog in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The numbers) are only a snapshot at a particular moment,'' he
told reporters Thursday. ``Life is volatile, campaigns are
volatile. We have to get known by more people. Forty or 45 percent
of the people in America don't know who I am. The key is letting
them know who I am, what I believe in, what I care for, &LR;  and what I
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing his underdog status, Bradley said he is up against
an ``entrenched power that is significant and that will be brought
to bear against us. ... It's symbolized by the vice president
arriving in Air Force Two and me arriving in Air Express or a
van.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's success has made state GOP leaders happy _ if only
because some of his magic may rub off. ``We're thrilled,'' said
state GOP Chairman John McGraw, who confirmed that the front-runner
has agreed to a fund-raiser for the California Republican Party in
November.
</P>
<P>
   But technology leaders said it is no surprise that the campaigns
are focusing on fund raising in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about our industry becoming what is a definition for the
economy ... the information technology industry,'' said Ray Lane,
president of Oracle. ``We represent 10 percent of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane said that while Gore has visited Silicon Valley numerous
times, Bush's success shows he's been able to sell ``a much more
balanced viewpoint'' of entrepreneurship in the valley than Clinton
and Gore combined.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Grady, a longtime Bush supporter, noted that both Bradley
and Bush appear to be reaping rewards in the same political turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing very well in the valley, no question,'' Grady said
of Bradley. ``He gets credit for being a thoughtful and ethical
person ... but I wonder if everyone knows what they're buying. ...
There could be some buyer's remorse coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to Silicon Valley, Bradley participated in a
roundtable discussion with health care professionals at Oakland
Children's Hospital and met with about 200 supporters who
registered at his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley repeatedly tried to downplay the momentum that has
others buzzing about his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have momentum,'' Bradley said. ``I think we
have a little traction. We're going to continue to do what we have
been doing _ going out and meeting people and telling them what we
would like to do for the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
