<HEADER>
A3068 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CANNIBALS-NEANDERTHAL     10-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNIBALS-NEANDERTHAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EVIDENCE SHOWS NEANDERTHALS ATE THEIR OWN  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   French and American researchers excavating a cave in
southeastern France have found the first clear evidence that
near-human Neanderthal people practiced cannibalism 100,000 years
ago, the scientists are reporting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fragments of Neanderthal bones, scattered around three hearths
in a fire-scarred cave, reveal striking cut marks that could have
been made only by sharp flints. Other bones obviously were smashed
by stone hammers before they were stripped of their flesh by flint
knives, the scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is conclusive evidence that at least some Neanderthals
practiced cannibalism,'' said paleontologist Tim White, director of
the Laboratory for Human Evolutionary Studies at the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The French scientists, headed by archaeologist Alban Defleur,
have been excavating the cave site known as Moula-Guercy since
1991. It overlooks the Rhone river near the town of Soyons north of
Marseilles. In 1993 Defleur and his team uncovered puzzling bits of
Neanderthal bones at the site that appeared to show cut marks.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the team has dug with meticulous care through deeper
layers in the cave floor. Defleur has enlisted White, an authority
on early humans and their prehistoric kin, to make a detailed
examination of the bone fragments that have been dated at between
80,000 and 120,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The two scientists and three colleagues are reporting their
findings Friday in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a crime scene,'' White said in an interview
describing Defleur's work. ``You rope off the area to keep everyone
out, and then you pick up every tiny piece of evidence, you
assemble everything that fits, and then you analyze it all in the
lab.''
</P>
<P>
   Defleur even used tools of bamboo for his work rather than
metal, because metal could have left marks on the bones that
confused the scientists, White said.
</P>
<P>
   The short, brawny and large-browed Neanderthal people are
believed to have diverged on a dead-end branch of the human
evolutionary tree about 300,000 years ago. They died out about
30,000 years ago, well after Homo sapiens, the true humans, began
flourishing in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Neanderthals were thus distant cousins of today's humans,
but they contributed little or nothing to the human gene pool.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what caused them to vanish. Some scientists argue
they might have been driven to extinction by more advanced humans
occupying their territory and perhaps, at times, mating with them.
Whatever their fate, the Neanderthals are a mysterious people,
known now by little more than their bones, stone tools and caves.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have speculated for nearly a century that the
Neanderthals practiced cannibalism. One cave in Croatia recently
yielded a complete skeleton that had been stripped of all its flesh
_ presumably to eat it before a ritual burial of the bones, some
researchers have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   White himself has excavated remains of the cliff-dwelling
Anasazi people who lived in the American Southwest before A.D.
1000, and vanished around A.D. 1300. He has found suggestive
evidence that some of them may have also practiced cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   The bone fragments in the Moula-Guercy cave, however, are the
first to show ``unequivocal evidence'' that they were smashed to
yield soft tissues and marrow for eating, White and Defleur
concluded in their report.
</P>
<P>
   The 78 bone fragments appear to have come from at least six
individuals, including two Neanderthal adults, two teenagers about
16 or 17 years old and two small children only 6 or 7.
</P>
<P>
   Their skulls were smashed apart to get at the nutritious brain
tissue, Defleur and White report. And one group of fragments,
pieced together, reveals the thigh bone of an adult that shows
where a stone hammer bashed the bone apart to recover its fatty,
nutritious marrow.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered among the fragmented bones of the people were similar
fragments of several animals. They have been identified by
Defleur's associate, Patria Valensi, as coming mostly from a
species of red deer that were butchered in the same way as the
Neanderthals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We interpret these data to indicate that the hominid and deer
carcasses were butchered ... with the objective being the removal
of soft tissues and marrow,'' the scientists say in their report.
</P>
<P>
   Defleur is continuing the excavation at Moula-Guercy, and last
summer five undergraduates from UC Berkeley joined his research
team. Meanwhile, Defleur has joined White's group excavating in
Ethiopia to seek more knowledge of the earliest humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
