 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2579 -- Sept. 30, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. AIDS EPIDEMIC ABOUT TO WIPE OUT THE FEW ACHIEVEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   OF DEVELOPMENT IN AFRICA It is now generally agreed that, given
the rate at which it is progressing in Africa, the Aids epidemic
will soon wipe out the benefits that development has brought that
continent. The disease is no longer just a health disaster for
Africa, where it kills 2 million people a year and infects 4
million others. The pandemic is a threat to Africa's social
cohesion, economic situation and population equilibrium. By
Nathaniel Herzberg. From Le Monde. 1,200 words. (English
translation available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
FRANCE SHOPS FOR ANOTHER PRETTY FACE The statue of Marianne that
graces French town halls is a symbol of the French Republic. Early
statues show a young woman with a helmet on her head and armour
over her breast. Later, actresses Brigitte Bardot and Catherine
Deneuve posed for the statues. As the 21st century dawns, does
France need a new pretty face in a skimpy dress as a national
symbol? And if so, which one? Of the five finalists chosen by the
36,000-member Association of French Mayors in a competition for a
new Marianne statue (to be unveiled in November,) two of the women
are supermodels, one is a game-show host, one a singer and one a
television news anchor. Critics say the choice of a new Marianne
should be more than a beauty pageant. By Suzanne Daley. From The
New York Times. 1,200 words. (Please contact us for availability
your country.)
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
EARTHQUAKES : A MATTER OF LUCK, MOST OF IT BAD Even though the rate
of earthquakes over time seems to be more or less unchanging, the
world's population explosion means that more people are moving into
quake zones, which are often near coasts. The result is the
prospect of continuing trauma as urban areas erupt with what seems
like nearly endless bursts of destruction. By William J. Broad. New
York Times Science Times. 2,000 words + photo + graphic.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW (a) HITLER'S POPE : A DEAFENING
SILENCE
</P>
<P>
   A new study criticizes Pope Pius XII's failure to speak out
against
</P>
<P>
   the Holocaust. 2,000 words. (b) THE BOOK ON THE BOOKSHELF
</P>
<P>
   The birth, evolution, triumphs and failures of the bookshelf.
1,000 words. 5. BULGARIA BLOCKED RUSSIAN PLAN FOR KOSOVO The
deployment of forces into Kosovo came much closer to a military
confrontation with Russia than has been revealed. Bulgarian refusal
to allow Russian overflights stalled the issue long enough for NATO
troops to be on the ground and block the plan for a separate
Russian zone in the northeast, in agreement with Serbia. By Flora
Lewis. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
LEARNING TO LOVE NEANDERTHALS In the spring of 1999, newspapers
worldwide reported the discovery in Portugal of the skeleton of a
4-year-old child, dead for 25,000 years. A ground-breaking and
controversial claim was made : that the skeleton shows traces of
both Neanderthal and modern human ancestry, evidence that modern
humans did not simply extinguish the Neanderthals. The two kinds of
human were so alike that in Portugal, at least, they intermingled
for thousands of years. By Robert Kunzig. From Discover Magazine.
1,300 words + photos.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
WHAT'S DOING IN VANCOUVER In the first five months of 1999, the
number of international travelers to British Columbia increased
dramatically. Sitting in the shadow of snowcapped mountains,
Vancouver has a temperate climate, 187 parks within the city,
trails that lead off urban paths into forests and lots of
opportunities for seaside explorations. By Melissa A. Trainer. From
The New York Times Way To Go! 1,800 words + photos + map.
