<HEADER>
A3163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN02-CO     10-01 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: In praise of chinaberries
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: A photo of Margery P. Dews is available by calling
404-526-5456.)
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. The way we
remember it, life back then was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Margery P. Dews
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   EDISON, Ga. _ To a person who has never spent hours stringing
chinaberries with a strong needle and No. 50 cotton thread, there
is little hope of explaining the pastime of those days when life
was simpler and people were uncomplicated.
</P>
<P>
   Chinaberries are almost a thing of the past even in their
Southern stronghold because most of the old hedgerows and ditches
where they flourished are gone now.
</P>
<P>
   Chinaberry trees, also called the Chinese Umbrella tree, were an
essential feature of all rural yards in our part of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Generous of shade, their growing habits made them perfect
``climbing trees'' with outreaching branches, not-too-frightening
height and enough leafy twigs to conceal anyone wanting to hide
from authority.
</P>
<P>
   Our chinaberry tree grew at the edge of the woodpile. It was a
prize conceit of my playmates and myself that, from a standing
start, we could jump upward to catch hold of the lowest limb, swing
legs around it and, by skillful maneuvering, be peering out above
the top of the tree in less than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   About mid-May the nondescript, sickly sweet-scented purple
blooms had fallen and been replaced by the hard, green,
English-pea-sized berries which would later shrivel, turn a
disgustingly mottled brown and smell to high heaven when crushed.
</P>
<P>
   They were never called just ``berries.'' Berries were something
to eat, and nothing on earth would eat a chinaberry, at least by
choice or preference.
</P>
<P>
   But the warmer weather and longer daylight hours for playing
outdoors gave us time for such a variety of activities that sooner
or later someone would suggest making chinaberry garlands,
necklaces, belts and bracelets.
</P>
<P>
   Any old needle would do, but an embroidery needle was much to be
prized since its big ``eye'' not only made it easier to thread
while perched on the largest branch but also pierced a larger hole
in the chinaberry for security and ease.
</P>
<P>
   The standard necklace was a single strand about 40 inches long,
looking to us like the pearls the ladies of the rotogravure and
magazines wore in those days.
</P>
<P>
   Various other designs sometimes appeared, created by the more
industrious and fanciful among us. Double strands were made for
headbands and, often, triple strands for belts.
</P>
<P>
   An old dress or gathered shirt of Mother's, reaching to ankle
length, a pair of the brightest colored shoes available and a full
assortment of chinaberry jewelry transformed the homeliest little
girl into a gypsy fortune-teller, Spanish dancer or Lady Vere de
Vere arriving for tea, Dutch bob or not.
</P>
<P>
   The grandeur of appearance and sheer aplomb would never again be
equaled although many a young woman dressing for her junior-senior
prom subconsciously hoped for a similar poise.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the self-assurance she had experienced when festooned
with the heavy, opulent-like green stands of chinaberries she had
so painstakingly constructed while sitting cross-legged under the
tree or precariously aloft.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray. Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
