 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, October 2 and Sunday,
October 3, 1999 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Consider today's column a
gift. Certainly it was a gift to me. It came wrapped directly from
cyberspace, from people in various parts of North America who
happened to read the column about my friend who committed a random
act of kindness. (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ If the DAR can welcome
immigrants from around the world into the United States as
full-fledged citizens, then it sure makes all those
Johnny-come-lately Americans look small when they try to slam the
immigration door behind them now that they have their citizenship.
(Rowland Nethaway is the senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HARDBODY-COLUMN _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ For the love of a pickup
truck, all eyes were on Longview last week ... or so it seemed.
Thanks to the ``Hands On A Hardbody'' endurance test and S.R.
Bindler's documentary about the 1995 contest, Longview is garnering
not just national, but international fame as the home of folks who
would do just about anything for the keys to a new pickup truck.
The problem with this newfound attention is that no one knows
whether it will make Longview famous or infamous. (Litterski,
Longview News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The GOP has its long knives out again for the
environment, loading 13 appropriations bills with 58 riders that,
like a street gang on a tear, would vandalize the national
neighborhood. Why does the party keep doing this stuff? Republicans
virtually invented conservation under President Theodore Roosevelt
and threw in with modern environmental protection under President
Richard Nixon. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ The lease on my automobile soon running out,
I am in the market for a car. As I prowl between intensive salesmen
who want my name, address and phone number before they'll allow me
to open the driver's side door of a showroom car, I have come to
the realization that the auto industry _ both foreign and domestic
_ does not meet my needs. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox
News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ As the official photographer
obliged, my wife recalled the bid we'd received from beyond the
confines of the Executive Mansion. ``Mr. President,'' she said, ``I
hope people will be able to tell if it's you or if it's a cardboard
cutout.''
</P>
<P>
   If her jest carried an edge, he missed it. Inclined to quiet
chuckles, this time Ronald Reagan laughed uproariously. ``Yes,'' he
said, ``that's the trouble with this town. It's hard to tell the
difference between a phony fake and a real fake.''
</P>
<P>
   That scene, from more than a decade ago, came in mind while
reading reviews of ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' Edmund
Morris's newly published and widely controversial book. (Andy Glass
is a columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.)
MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
