<HEADER>
A3179 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN02-COX     10-01 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stories from around the country tell of random acts of kindness
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ Consider today's column a gift. Certainly it
was a gift to me.
</P>
<P>
   It came wrapped directly from cyberspace, from people in various
parts of North America who happened to read the column about my
friend who committed a random act of kindness.
</P>
<P>
   My friend found himself blessed then, and still, by spending
$1.72 to pay for the drive in order of food for the person behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the column from across the country was astounding of
people who either did their own random acts of kindness or who were
the recipients. These are their stories, but in the true spirit of
random kindness, I'm only identifying them by one of their names
and hometowns. The best part of a random act is as few people
knowing as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Val from Vancouver was in line at the grocery store and the
woman ahead of her was trying to cut down on her shopping list
because she did not have enough in welfare vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   People behind her were muttering, but what Val noticed was that
the items the woman was having to put back weren't donuts or candy,
they were the essentials such as milk, orange juice and bread.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman had pared down enough to make her purchase, Val
told the cashier to put the items on her bill and bag them for the
lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made me want to cry was when this lady shook my hand and
said that I would be in her thoughts as she fed her children. It
was a big reminder to me that I am very well off in a thousand
different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Val, who must run with a good crowd, also has a friend who
regularly pays for the five cars behind her going through the
highway toll booth.
</P>
<P>
   Judith of Scottsdale, Ariz., says she does, from time to time,
pay for the meal of the person directly behind her in line where
she works, at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little known fact,'' she writes, ``that such random
acts do far more for the `do-er' than the receiver. The Bible tells
us this, too! It's best to do them in secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus her favorite memory is when she paid out a layaway for a
friend who was saving to attend the seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``(She) was shocked when she went to make a payment and found it
was all paid for. To this day she does not know who did it. I have
only told one or two people that story. It is one of my most
treasured memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for passing it along to us, Judith. It made our day, too.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps you'd like to know what it feels like to be the
``victim'' of a random act of kindness? Ask Marilou of Pine, Ariz.
She even remembers the exact day it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Marilou was celebrating her 69th birthday on Aug. 15, 1998 at
the Nifty Fifth Diner.
</P>
<P>
   Another couple, who Marilou did not know, was sitting at the
table next to her group and ate their meal in silence, got up and
left.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, the waitress came over and asked if it was really
her birthday. When she confirmed that it was, the waitress said
that the man at the table, who had already gone, had paid for any
dessert she would like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, that made my day and I will always remember it
with a warm glow.''
</P>
<P>
   The point here is, it doesn't take much to make a lasting
memory.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, my favorite story about a $5 random act of
kindness, again from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Schwartz and his wife of Phoenix happened to be in a used
book store one day when they saw two men in their 20s discussing a
particular volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``One had pulled a small book from the shelf and was showing it
to the other man,'' Mr. Schwartz writes. ``He was leafing through
the book showing the other passages here and there. He spoke with
such zeal and fervor about the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to his friend, `When I scrape enough money together,
I'm going to buy this book.' He put the book back on the shelf and
they walked a short distance away.''
</P>
<P>
   Having heard so many good things about the book, Mr. Schwartz
was curious about it and wanted to know what it was.
</P>
<P>
   The topic was the life of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   He looked inside the cover and saw that the book cost $5. He
stuck a $5 bill inside the book, walked over to the man and said,
``I want you to have this book.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was taken aback and thanked me profusely. We left the
store. My day was made. I was on a high.''
</P>
<P>
   Want to know something else? Indeed, you might have already
guessed. You see, Mr. Schwartz isn't a Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Keep doing random acts and I'll keep telling about them. I hope
I never run out.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
