<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX     10-01 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young people losing touch with America; service is in order
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ My mother's chapter of the Daughters of the
American Revolution hands out the Stars and Stripes to new citizens
of the United States at their swearing-in ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The little flags given to brand-new U.S. citizens are a
``welcome aboard'' gesture by the DAR, an organization whose
members are blood-line descendents of soldiers and partisans who
fought in the war that achieved American independence.
</P>
<P>
   If the DAR can welcome immigrants from around the world into the
United States as full-fledged citizens, then it sure makes all
those Johnny-come-lately Americans look small when they try to slam
the immigration door behind them now that they have their
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The DAR is not concerned about the ethnic or cultural heritage
of the people who accept the U.S. flags. DAR members want the new
citizens to know that they now owe their allegiance to a
democratic, freedom-loving nation that was founded and preserved by
the sacrifices of generations of earlier citizens.
</P>
<P>
   New U.S. citizens are entitled to the same protections, freedoms
and opportunities as the men and women who can prove direct descent
from ancestors who fought to establish this great nation. Besides
being the world's richest, most powerful nation, the United States
also happens to be the planet's oldest representative democracy.
</P>
<P>
   When my mother told me how she looked forward to handing out the
small flags to new citizens, I remembered thinking that America's
newest citizens should understand that the privileges of
citizenship are accompanied by responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, I thought, a national-service requirement of some sort
should be a precondition for immigrants who seek to become U.S.
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Then I realized that America's newest citizens are likely to be
much more aware of their citizenship responsibilities than
born-and-bred Americans who take their citizenship for granted.
</P>
<P>
   To be born an American is effortless good luck. To be a
responsible citizen, however, requires effort and sacrifice that
partly repays the nation for the privileges and protections
extended to all citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Americans who think their citizenship responsibilities ended
with birth endanger America's ability to sustain the blessings of
democracy and liberty to ourselves and our posterity.
</P>
<P>
   America needs a universal service requirement for all citizens,
not just immigrants who apply for citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   One of the casualties of the Vietnam War was the military draft,
which was killed in 1973 by nervous politicians to appease anti-war
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Lost with the death of the military draft was a valuable means
to vest new generations of young Americans in their nation. Due to
the draft, generations of Americans were enlisted in the service of
their country, to the benefit of the draftees as well as their
nation. That tradition of national service has been broken.
</P>
<P>
   More Americans are becoming disconnected with their government _
the government they should be working to improve _ while
complaining louder and demanding more. Many of these citizens have
never lifted a finger in the service of their country.
</P>
<P>
   A universal service requirement would teach new generations of
Americans that citizenship privileges must be paid for with
citizenship responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Draft-age young men and women could work in retirement homes,
hospitals or national forests. They could rebuild America's
crumbling roads and bridges. They could attack urban blight. They
could mentor, teach, register voters or serve in the military.
</P>
<P>
   In return for their service, they would receive education
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam wants you, and you need Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor for the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
