   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Spending a heap of money on
woodworking won't mean a thing unless the tools are good quality.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTVERNON _ Washington never slept in Atlanta, but a lot of
his stuff will be spending some time here this fall. ``Treasures
from Mount Vernon: George Washington revealed,'' a major traveling
exhibition marking the bicentennial of his death, will open at the
Atlanta History Center Oct. 14. We preview the show in Richmond and
consider the marble man no one knows. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE _ The annual design awards from the Georgia chapter
of the American Institute of Architects honors nine buildings, from
an Atlanta home to a Pittsburgh departmenn store. lots of color.
(Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TBS-CHANGES _ The network best known for bringing us Braves
games and Andy Griffith re-runs is re-inventing itself. There will
still be Braves games, but Andy's gone and TBS is moving forward
with male-driven programming like the Chimp Channel, off-network
sitcoms like ``The Cosby Show'', broadcast movie premieres such as
``Batman and Robin'' and original movies like ``The Timeshifters.''
We do a Q&AMP;A with Brad Siegel, the new man in the middle whose now
in charge of TNT, TBS, and the all-new Turner South. (Harris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALFARM _ Review of TNT's ``Animal Farm,'' airing Sunday,
another departure from the westerns and action films of the past.
It's based on the classic book - and features real, live animals,
much like the movie ``Babe,'' and may be almost as good. Grade: B+.
(Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 19.
</P>
<P>
   ART-COLLEGE _ In light of the Woodruff Arts Center's plans to
renovate, we take a closer look at one of its components: the
Atlanta College of Art. Atlantans know it exists, but not much
else. Just what does this institution do? How does it rank
nationally? How successful are its graduates? The school includes a
dorm and studios that are open 24 hours for students to work on
projects. We examine from all angles. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 79. WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Column about the Reagan memoir ``Dutch.''
President Reagan no sooner left office than he lost his mind,
sealing off the world and biographers with it. Edmund Morris spent
15 years in Reagan's periodic company, and the book for which
Morris signed a $3 million contract in 1985 has appeared at last.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 60. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-FASHION _ A. Scott Walton reports from Fashion Week in
Milan. Combo of main runway revue, notes and occasional postcards.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-PANHANDLERS _ You're confronted by a panhandler, asking
for money. What do you do? What's the correct response? It's an
ethical dilemma that almost everyone has experienced. The Bible
offers an answer. Give. But is that possible in a world that
constantly has its hand out? We offer some thoughts from the
clergy, academics and people who face the issue each day. (Blake,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
