<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARDBODY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Big hearts and tough hands in Texas contest
 &HT;    By Pete Litterski
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ For the love of a pickup truck, all eyes were
on Longview last week ... or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the ``Hands On A Hardbody'' endurance test and S.R.
Bindler's documentary about the 1995 contest, Longview is garnering
not just national, but international fame as the home of folks who
would do just about anything for the keys to a new pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   The wave of media coverage focused on last week's contest at Joe
Mallard Nissan was the biggest thing to hit town since Longview
hosted one of several premiers of the movie ``A Time to Kill,''
which starred Matt McConaughey, who like his buddy Bindler, grew up
in Longview.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this newfound attention is that no one knows
whether it will make Longview famous or infamous.
</P>
<P>
   After all, any auto dealer looking for a little publicity can
park a pickup (or, outside of Texas, a car) in the middle of the
parking lot and let a couple dozen contenders see who can keep a
hand in the contest the longest.
</P>
<P>
   But, perhaps only East Texas can come up with the characters who
have apparently won the hearts and the funny bones of movie-goers
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It seems we offer everything from melodrama to humor when folks
gather around a pickup in East Texas. From this year's tear-jerking
story of a mother who needed a better vehicle to transport her
ailing child to Shreveport for doctor's appointments to past
contestants who have seen magnificent visions in their
sleep-deprived delusions, there have always been tangential plot
lines every bit as interesting as the question of who will win the
truck each year.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite tales from this year's contest was of the
contestant who sacrificed his chance at victory by lifting his
hands off the truck and catching a fellow contestant who had
drifted off to sleep and was falling backwards. I'm convinced his
downfall was the result of a good heart and not
</P>
<P>
   a mental lapse, such as that suffered last year by a contestant
who was listening to music and lifted both hands off the truck to
adjust his headphones well into the competition.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, I hope movie-goers, television viewers and newspaper
readers around the world will look upon Longview with a beneficent
eye. Over the years, the people in these contests have been our
neighbors and friends. They're good folks with big hearts and hardy
feet.
</P>
<P>
   I ought to know. The 1995 winner in Bindler's movie showed up
just about a year ago to help my family move a few blocks into our
new house. We had met only a couple of times at Thanksgiving
dinners hosted by the family of my wife's best friend. But when his
niece put out a call for help when we were moving, he showed up.
</P>
<P>
   I guess you could say I was moved by a ``Hardbody.''
</P>
<P>
   (Pete Litterski is the editor of the Longview News-Journal.
E-mail: plitterski(at)coxnews.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
