<HEADER>
A3185 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD02-COX     10-01 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodworkers should spend wisely
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I received an e-mail recently from a gentleman who
asked for the single best tip I would give a beginning woodworker,
which is sort of like presenting me with a pound of Godiva
chocolates and asking me to pick the best piece in the box.
</P>
<P>
   He did rule out a lecture on patience, and that wouldn't have
been my first choice anyway, unless I knew from experience that my
subject was an impatient and impulsive person.
</P>
<P>
   My answer is going to have to be equivocal, because in practice
it would be chosen after a discussion with this hypothetical
beginner, to learn more about the personality and the general
situation.
</P>
<P>
   If the beginner isn't particularly well-to-do financially, I
would warn against buying tools based on price rather than quality.
Fine woodworking is a very expensive proposition, as anyone who's
involved in it can attest. In any class of tools, from chisels to
table saws, you can usually buy great ones, good ones,
conditionally acceptable ones and worthless ones.
</P>
<P>
   Great ones are usually out of reach of anyone but a successful
professional shop or the rich amateur. Good ones are what we
generally want to invest in. Worthless ones are to be avoided.
Conditionally acceptable ones are usually large power tools and
we'll discuss that momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at chisels for an example. The great chisels are made
in Japan. They are works of art in and of themselves, and a single
chisel from the forge of a great maker can cost more than $100. And
even then it might not be terribly useful unless it was intended
for export, because Japanese woodworkers generally use much softer
wood than we do.
</P>
<P>
   The less expensive Japanese chisels, and English chisels,
generally fall under the heading of good ones. Keep them sharp and
they'll do the work for you.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware-store chisels such as Stanley's cheapest line are too
small, won't hold an edge and are generally carelessly made. In
this case, the difference in price between good chisels and poor
ones is so small the decision is easy.
</P>
<P>
   Conditionally acceptable tools are things like table or radial
arm saws which work well enough if kept in good condition, but
resist that condition. They constantly fall out of alignment. If
you don't have a good deal of mechanical and engineering talent and
training, they fall in the unacceptable range. If you have that
talent, and can't afford anything better, take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   So, you say, you can't afford to pay $800 for a contractor's saw
or $1,500 for a big table saw? You want to go with that $300
department store model?
</P>
<P>
   I can certainly understand. I've been there myself. I went with
the $300 table saw. Then I went with the $350 radial arm saw. I am
what you might call a slow learner.
</P>
<P>
   If you go with the cheapest tools, one of two things is going to
happen. The best outcome will be that you learn your lesson, bite
the bullet and buy something you can actually use. The other
possibility, unfortunately, is that you will abandon woodworking
and take up macrame.
</P>
<P>
   What ever happened to macrame, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
