A3191 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     10-01 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Friday, Oct. 1, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence
at 202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUCLEAR (San Francisco) _ The nuclear accident in Japan
would be ``extremely unlikely'' to occur in the United States,
thanks to special regulations and techniques used in this country,
according to federal officials. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-HEALTHCARE (Oakland, Calif.) _ Just a day after
Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley unveiled his $65
billion proposal to offer health insurance to all children in
America, he rolled up his sleeves and clarified his plan. By
MATTHEW YI.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SILICON-VALLEY (Redwood City, Calif.) _ Are there any
Republicans left in Silicon Valley who have not yet sent their
contributions to Texas Gov. George W. Bush? If so, overnight them
in now. Even the hard-charging Bush fund-raising machine may decide
at some point that enough is enough. But not yet. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOG-HEAVEN (Welfare, Texas) _ Grunts of pleasure and clouds of
dust fill the cool morning air as Angharad Rees carries a bucket of
grain toward her impatient four-legged friends, who jostle for a
position at feeding tins. This is life in hog heaven _ better known
as the Safe Harbour Pig Refuge _ where Rees shelters homeless
porkers until they can be adopted. By ZEKE MacCORMACK. (Photo
available on the Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-KINGS (Undated) _ ``Three Kings'' is a
post-colonial, post-war, action-heist-
comedy-satire-farce-screwball circus that's like ``MASH'' being
churned by a sneering, over-amped organ grinder. But instead of
Korea the locale is Iraq. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GUINEVERE (Undated) _ Audrey Wells' debut
directorial feature, ``Guinevere,'' is a love story so implausibly
dainty that when its heroine is sent packing from her older
boyfriend/mentor's loft, you'll want to shed a crocodile tear. By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CRAZY (Undated) _ Adapted by Rob Thomas from Todd
Strasser's novel ``How I Created My Perfect Prom Date,'' this film
has the good sense not to give in to the kids' belief that high
school is cordoned off so that social spheres don't intersect. Set
in Utah suburbia. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MYSTERY (Undated) _ ``Mystery, Alaska'' is
predictable. It's just not as predictable as the rest of its ilk.
It takes you down to the last goal without tipping off which way
the whole thing's going to go. For a movie like this, that's about
all you can ask for. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LOLA (Undated) _ The last woman for whom Max Ophuls
went behind the camera was ``Lola Montes.'' The film feels like the
phantasmagoric final act in an artist's career that demanded that
cinema meet the stage, in the same way that for ambitious dreamers
heaven can sometimes touch the earth. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO-EXHIBIT (San Francisco) _ The attitudes of early modern
artists toward photography was often grudgingly negative. Yet even
as many of them dismissed the medium, they used it, often in ways
that considerably determined the form their art would take. A
fascinating exhibition at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art
through Jan. 2 examines the complex relationships 14
turn-of-the-century artists had with photography. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANIMAL-FARM (Undated) _ The live-action, animatronically
stunning ``Animal Farm,'' debuting Sunday on TNT, is a stark study
of the egalitarian ideals but untenable realities of communism. The
movie is the continuation of a heartening trend of bringing the
classics to television. And after this stirring version, hopefully
more than a few students will want to read the book. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-AUTUMN (Stockbridge, Mass.) _ Fall is young, and
last week the leaf-peepers who flock to western Massachusetts and
other parts of New England have yet to emerge in full force. But,
as the sign at the modest New Ashford Inn reminds us, it won't be
long before the hardwood trees are barren. By DOUG BLACKBURN. (For
release Sunday, Oct. 3.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-YOUTH (Carmel, Calif.) _ Can the nation survive a president
who may have frolicked at pot parties, perhaps sniffed cocaine and
no doubt danced to rock and roll? What kind of leader would a
person like that be? George W. Bush's misspent youth is under
scrutiny. By ALEX A. VARDAMIS.
</P>
</TEXT>
