<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3195 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STROKE-MEDICATION29-C     10-01 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKE-MEDICATION29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drug can prevent stroke-related disability for patients who seek
care quickly
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Without TPA, Michael Miller is sure his legs
wouldn't have been almost fully working three weeks after his Aug.
26 stroke. Libby Ahern doubts if she would be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue plasminogen activator (TPA) has been minimizing stroke
damage by dissolving blood clots since 1996, but it's still not
widely known that people can spare themselves a lifetime disability
by hustling to the hospital when stroke symptoms first appear.
People receiving TPA within three hours of the onset of the most
common type of stroke are 30 percent more likely to have little or
no impairment a year later, the New England Journal of Medicine
reported in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal study didn't look at TPA's immediate impact, but Dr.
Kenneth Pugar has seen it a few times. ``We see a number of people
just literally get better in hours after we give the drug,'' says
the Kettering Medical Center neurologist. ``And we've had a couple
of very dramatic ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern was one of them. ``It really works,'' says the 75-year-old
Kettering woman, whose sister died of a stroke before TPA was
available.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern was in a Meijer checkout lane just after midnight of
Christmas Eve morning in 1997. She was lining her groceries up on
the counter and suddenly her hand froze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill looked at me and said, `What's the matter?' `` Ahern says
of her husband. She tried to answer but couldn't talk. She
remembers someone calling 911 and someone else moving her groceries
to another lane. But after being carried into the ambulance,
everything else from the next 24 hours is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad said it was like somebody sort of popped her with a pin
in the checkout lane,'' says Ahern's daughter, Val Alvey. ``She
just kind of melted.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvey heard from her brother a little after 12:30 a.m., but he
was crying so hard, she couldn't understand a word. ``I thought it
was a prank,'' she says. ``So I hung up.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Alvey reached the hospital at 1:15, her mother was
``totally out of it. She couldn't talk, couldn't move, nothing.''
Ahern's right side was rigid and turned inward, and the only
movement of her left side appeared to be involuntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her right side was totally paralyzed and she couldn't see
anything off to the right,'' Pugar says. ``This was a major, major
stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't any question about Ahern's stroke symptoms, but
sometimes they're easier to ignore. Miller, for example, felt his
feet going numb as he walked into his Versailles home. ``I poured a
cup of coffee and carried it into the other room OK, but then I
went to drink it and it spilled into my lap,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Any sudden numbness, tingling, slurring or loss of speech, or
loss of muscular control on one side of the body is a likely
indicator of a stroke, says the American Stroke Association, a
division of the American Heart Association. Strokes are caused by
either blood clots or hemorrhages that keep blood away from part of
the brain. Deprived of oxygen and other nutrients in the blood, the
brain cells begin dying.
</P>
<P>
   TPA, used for more than 10 years to dissolve cardiac blood
clots, works only for the 85 percent of strokes that are ischemic,
or caused by blood clots. Another group of patients can't use it
because of their other medical conditions or medications. So the
three-hour window when TPA is useful must include enough time for
the examination and CAT scan to make sure TPA won't do more harm
than good.
</P>
<P>
   After Ahern qualified, Pugar told her children it was an option.
He said it could dissolve the blood clot and help her, it could be
ineffective or it could ``dissolve everything and she would bleed
to death,'' Alvey says. Her mother had a good chance of dying even
without the treatment, and status quo survival didn't look very
appealing as she lay motionless and mute.
</P>
<P>
   Following protocol, Pugar gave Ahern 10 percent of the liquid
dose in a minute or so, then hooked the rest up to a vein in her
hand like any IV drip. It all takes about an hour. ``While I was
giving the drug, she started moving her leg for me,'' Pugar says.
</P>
<P>
   As Alvey paced past Ahern's door about half an hour into the
treatment, a nurse signaled thumbs up and beckoned her inside.
``She started moving her right hand,'' Alvey says. ``Next thing I
knew, she was looking around the room and trying to focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern wouldn't be out of danger for 24 hours, doctors said, but
she kept improving. Her speech was slurred, but she was talking.
She was 70 percent or 80 percent improved by the next day, Pugar
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Pugar looked at her on Christmas morning and said, `I want
you to know this is the best Christmas present I ever had,' ``
Alvey says. Ahern was alert enough by then to remember the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what he was talking about,'' she says. ``I
didn't realize he had saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The 730,000 strokes a year in this country are its leading cause
of disability and third-ranked cause of death. The annual rate of
31.9 stroke deaths per 100,000 people in Montgomery County, Ohio,
is 23 percent higher than the national rate, says the Miami Valley
American Heart Association. And about one-third of strokes strike
people younger than 65 such as Miller, a 50-year-old plumber.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's entire left side was numb, but he never lost
consciousness or the ability to speak. Dr. Lawrence Goldstick gave
him the lowdown on TPA risks directly, he says. ``I told him, `You
do whatever you think is best.' What could I say, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   At his worst, Miller lost movement of his left leg and arm and
some of his right leg. Within three weeks, movement in his right
leg had fully returned. He could control and stand on his left leg
and walk with a cane. He could lift his recently limp left arm to
his side and pull it back to his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very encouraging from where I was,'' he says. ``I'm
pretty confident of getting it all back.''
</P>
<P>
   Pugar can't say for sure that TPA stops any particular stroke in
its tracks. ``There are some who have rapid improvement without any
treatment,'' he concedes. But his gut tells him TPA made the
difference in Libby Ahern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' says Ahern, who's back to doing the
cooking and housework and pretty much everything she used to do.
``It's too bad more people don't get there in time to get help.''
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE: The American Heart Association is at
www.americanheart.org. The American Stroke Association has a
toll-free information line at (800) 553-6321.
</P>
<P>
   evin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
