<HEADLINE>
TEXAN OFFERS HOG HEAVEN FOR LOST, UNWANTED PIGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on the Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELFARE, Texas _ Grunts of pleasure and clouds of dust fill the
cool morning air as Angharad Rees carries a bucket of grain toward
her impatient four-legged friends, who jostle for a position at
feeding tins.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go over there without feed, I'm in trouble,'' Rees said
with a joking twinkle.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of their swine kind who wind up as chops, links and
rinds, these lucky porkers are living in hog heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mention of bacon is considered tasteless at the Safe
Harbour Pig Refuge, home to 75 oinkers, including Vietnamese
potbellied pigs, feral hogs and a Russian boar named _ what else? _
Boris Boarloff.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them have names, and they all have a story,'' said
Rees, a 46-year-old nurse whose porcine preoccupation has earned
her the name of ``Pig Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Although always an animal lover, the strapping, red-haired woman
never intended to create a hog resort when she got her first
piglet, a Dukor Yorkshire named Mama Louie, around 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But then her heart wouldn't let her turn away a homeless pig
named Tank, and the course was set in 1995 when she bought four
potbellied pigs for $5 at an auction on the steps of the Bandera
County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid they'd end up barbecued,'' said Rees, whose
Welfare refuge is 50 miles northwest of San Antonio. Rees does not
eat pork but said she does eat beef and other meat.
</P>
<P>
   They just kept coming after that, and the family's 17-acre
homestead is dotted with large pens where pigs weighing up to 400
pounds lounge in the shade while awaiting the next visit of their
dedicated human savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only pig refuge in the state, as far as I know,'' Rees
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take in pigs that have had human contact, and we try to
adopt them out to good, loving homes,'' she said. ``Not all pigs
are suitable for adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   Her clientele has grown to 75 pigs from 14 in the past 18
months, and, she said: ``I get more calls every week, primarily
from people with found pigs, or those who can't keep them as pets
any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The monthly grain bill of $450 is putting a pinch on the
family's pocketbook, so Rees has applied with the Internal Revenue
Service for a tax designation as a nonprofit charity to encourage
donations.
</P>
<P>
   She spends about four hours a day caring for her extended family
that also includes 25 cats, six dogs, five rabbits, one parrot and
``a sundry of fowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The menagerie is remarkably clean and orderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had worse neighbors,'' said Jerry Tilley, who owns the
nearby PoPo Family Restaurant in this Kendall County community.
``We've never sensed an aroma. The biggest problem is an occasional
pig who wants to see what the world's all about, and we help round
them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rees, whose first name means ``safe harbor'' in the Celtic
language, has become a crusader for pig appreciation _ outside of
culinary circles. She uses the hogs to educate elementary students
about animal cruelty and proper pig care. She also has taken
piglets to work at the Vitas Hospice in San Antonio, where
terminally ill patients and their families cuddle and feed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pigs are always the brunt of somebody's joke,'' Rees said.
``What people don't realize is pigs are very loving, social
animals, and they all have personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To visit the Safe Harbour Pig Refuge, call 830-537-4737 to make
an appointment.
</P>
</TEXT>
