<HEADER>
A3224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-ANIMAL-FARM-HNS &LR;      10-01 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANIMAL-FARM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TNT STAGES A COUP IN `ANIMAL FARM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the Emmy Awards last month, ``Politically Incorrect''
host Bill Maher did a skit about the future of television. Too
late: The future is here.
</P>
<P>
   Its name is ``Animal Farm.''
</P>
<P>
   George Orwell wrote this rural allegory about the Soviet Union
in 1945. But it took more than a half-century for television
technology to actually catch up.
</P>
<P>
   The live-action, animatronically stunning ``Animal Farm,''
debuting at 8 p.m. Sunday on TNT, is a stark study of the
egalitarian ideals but untenable realities of communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animal Farm'' the movie is the continuation of a heartening
trend of bringing the classics to television. And after this
stirring version, hopefully more than a few students will want to
read the book, rather than be merely compelled to do so by English
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The plot centers on the battle between the evil two-legged
talkers and righteous four-legged talkers, and how a group of
intelligent animals take control of their farm and, presumably,
their destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animalkind is born to a miserable, laborious and short
existence,'' says the leader pig, Old Major (Peter Ustinov), in a
speech that sounds absolutely Churchillian and paraphrases Thomas
Hobbes. ``Man. Man is our enemy. Remove man, and the root cause of
hunger and overwork is abolished forever. Remove man and overnight
we will become free and equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Major (read: Karl Marx) accidentally dies at the hands of
brutal farmer Jones (Pete Postlethwaite), prompting the revolution
led by Snowball (read: Trotsky, voiced by Kelsey Grammer) and
Napoleon (Josef Stalin, voiced by Patrick Stewart). The revolution
is triumphant, and the dastardly humans are driven from the
property that is renamed Animal Farm.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a dark, dark story of how man, or in this case, pig,
can lay to waste ideals in favor of personal power or comfort.
Power is wrested from rivals and the masses by the pig ruling class
via false vilification, food shortages, nationalistic rantings and
even propaganda films made by Squealer (Ian Holm), who is most akin
to Nazi propaganda chief Joseph Goebbels. We know what happened to
the Soviet Union. We know what happens here.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is the kind that only cable can put together for
television: Grammer, Stewart, Julia Ormond, Postlethwaite, Holm,
Paul Scofield and Ustinov, among others.
</P>
<P>
   But the real stars are the animatronic animals, created by Jim
Henson's Creature Shop technicians in conjunction with Hallmark
Entertainment and enhanced by computer-generated animation. Take
Napoleon: At a gathering of press critics in July, he appeared
onstage opposite alter-ego Stewart and Executive Producer Robert
Halmi Sr. Of course, in W.C. Fields tradition, the pig stole the
show as he explained his life as an actor: ``It's certainly better
than being eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a surreal moment, talking to, and later touching, this
mass of computer chips, servos, silicone, hand-laid hair and
hydraulics. As with watching the movie, you easily suspend
disbelief. This is a talking pig.
</P>
<P>
   There was another attempt at bringing the book to film, a 1954
animated version that reviewers said fell short.
</P>
<P>
   But from Sunday night on, we will remember only one version. Its
name is ``Animal Farm,'' and the telling story from the past in
this movie of today may tell us even more about television's
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
