</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASSACHUSETTS-AUTUMN-$ADV03-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTUMN'S EARLY COLORS TURN THOUGHTS TO WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 3)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. _ Not everyone in the
postcard-picture-perfect Berkshires is thinking autumn, despite the
rapid color changes that are taking place in the Massachusetts
foliage.
</P>
<P>
   Margarite Gigliotti, proprietor of the New Ashford Inn, a modest
motel on Route 7 some 9 miles south of Williamstown, touts a
different season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think snow!'' proclaims the sign at the entrance to the inn,
which Gigliotti and her husband, Francis, built in 1968 and have
operated since.
</P>
<P>
   Fall is young, and last week the leaf-peepers who flock to this
area and other parts of New England had yet to emerge in full
force. But, as the sign at the New Ashford Inn reminded us, it
won't be long before the hardwood trees are barren.
</P>
<P>
   Which means winter is coming, a season that ski operators at
nearby Jiminy Peak and Brodie (not to mention every other downhill
mountain in the Northeast) are praying will be kinder than in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Gigliotti, other motel owners and restaurateurs in western
Massachusetts also would appreciate a full-fledged winter this
year, one in which it snows early and often and one without rain.
As for Gigliotti's sign, she conceded with a warm twinkle that it
is up year-round. It is their calling card, a conversation piece.
</P>
<P>
   Their five children, now all grown and away from home, loved
skiing the region's slopes. The sign is a tribute to them, and a
reminder to their parents. The Gigliotti sons looked forward to
winter more than any other time. It was their favorite season.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who prefer the kaleidoscope of colors autumn
offers, this may be the finest season. 'Tis the harvest, a time for
celebrating. The sun rises later; night descends earlier. Yet the
days, warm and welcoming, are more summer than winter.
</P>
<P>
   On the final Monday in September, a humid, balmy day that began
with a sweater that was shed by mid-morning, I explored the
Berkshires' Route 7 corridor, meandering south from Williamstown to
the Great Barrington border.
</P>
<P>
   Fall foliage information on the Massachusetts' visitors hot
line, 800-227-MASS, had reported that on the day I was visiting the
color was 15 to 25 percent in the western Berkshires. That, in
fact, depended on where you were looking.
</P>
<P>
   Walking the tidy lawns at the Norman Rockwell Museum just
outside Stockbridge, looking beyond the Housatonic River walk to a
panorama of rolling hills, I saw closer to 40 percent color. Yet
some of the maple and locust trees near the museum were as green as
they had been in July.
</P>
<P>
   Fall happens at its own pace, affecting each tree and shrub
differently. Much of the sumac along Route 7 is at peak color now,
a flaming corsage for drivers and their passengers, yet trees
flanking beaver ponds and farmers' fields are two to three weeks
from their final glory days of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkshire communities may not have invented tourism, but
they have mastered it. There are museums big and small sprinkled
throughout the region, from the nationally prominent Massachusetts
Museum of Contemporary Art in North Adams, the Clark Art Institute
in Williamstown and the Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, to
less-well-known treasures, such as the Berkshire Scenic Railway in
Lenox or Herman Melville's Arrowhead in Pittsfield.
</P>
<P>
   Stockbridge and West Stockbridge are my favorite spots to walk
about. Said Rockwell, ``I just love Stockbridge. I mean,
Stockbridge is the best of America, the best of New England.''
</P>
<P>
   His observation is just as true today as it was a half-century
or more ago when he said it.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Lion Inn, at the intersection of Routes 7 and 102, is a
historic draw in the heart of the village. Famous for its food, as
well as its ambience, the inn is a popular spot for couples to
pause and take photographs of one another. Two doors down, to the
east, stands the Yankee Candle Co.
</P>
<P>
   Does this place know how to market itself, or what? Tour buses
roar in and out of Stockbridge all day long, but they seem to be
fewer in fall than during summer. At the Norman Rockwell Museum,
there were as many cars with Florida license plates as either
Massachusetts or New York. Hard to say if these visitors were
simply wise enough to get away during hurricane season or, in the
upstate New York tradition, they were ``snowbirds,'' retired with
winter homes in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   The famous painter's oldest son, Peter Rockwell, was a sculptor.
Some of his impressive works, as varied as a Rodin-like couple
dancing to an Aztec-style creation blasted out of stone, decorate
the landscape at the museum. Because the indoor exhibitions change
regularly, it is a spot to return to time and again.
</P>
<P>
   I could not leave the area without stopping by the Berkshire
Brewery &AMP; Restaurant in the Jenifer House Commons on Route 7, just
north of Great Barrington. John, a good friend for more than 30
years, lives not far away and belongs to a synagogue around the
corner. We made plans to meet for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The lone brew-pub in the region, Berkshire Brewery, makes hearty
food and even better beer. John and I each sipped a pint of a
seasonal Oktoberfest, a heavily hopped, malty brown ale that seemed
a perfect salute to autumn.
</P>
<P>
   We sat under a canopy outdoors, admiring the hop vines growing
up the side of the barn. At the table next to us, two men discussed
Christmas trees, techniques for delivering them and what price they
will fetch this season.
</P>
<P>
   We couldn't have asked for a better reminder that fall may be
the shortest season of all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
