<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Oct. 2. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY: Andy Jackson's portrait on the 20 shows a younger,
thinner fellow that bears little resemblance to possibly the
sickest, crankiest president in our history. And old Ben Franklin,
why he's younger and thinner, too. We can't wait to see what they
do to Abe Lincoln. But what is this youth movement on our currency?
Yet another ripple effect from that tidal wave we know as the
boomers? Rick Montgomery. 30.
</P>
<P>
   WOOD: Ft. Leonard Wood's fortunes have risen and fallen with
world events - Vietnam, the end of the Cold War. Now the base has
escaped from the endangered list by receiving training schools for
chemical weapons specialists and military police, two jobs crucial
to the Army's new role. The new units were officially activated on
Friday. The facility's expansion also is touching the surrounding
community. Oscar Avila. 35. Photos, map.
</P>
<P>
   WITS: Cooperative witnesses are difficult to find in the best of
circumstances, but the recent murders of witness Sophia Szymczak
and would-be snitch James Weber don't make it any easier. The
bottom line, say police and prosecutors, is trust. Potential
witnesses have to believe that authorities will protect them.
Tanyanika Samuels. 25.
</P>
<P>
   COTTON. In southern Kansas, there is a growing reliance on a new
cash crop: cotton; the first farmer to start growing it did so more
than a decade ago, to the jeers of his neighbors; but within a few
years he had lots of company and folks made lots of money, for a
while. John A. Dvorak. 25. photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   CAMPUS _ Sprint officially unveils its new $920 million campus
in Overland Park as a pall of uncertainty hangs over the company's
future. By Ted Sickinger and Mark Couch. Photos, graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Column by David Hayes, Finn Bullars
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Detroit at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   SHEHEE. Rashaan Shehee may be more recognizable around Kansas
City these days since he will make his first NFL start on Sunday in
San Diego. But to some kids in Independence, where Shehee has made
a name for himself by working with troubled youth, he's been The
Man for awhile. Randy Covitz. 25.
</P>
<P>
   POZ. Joe Posnanski column on K-State-Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
