<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY - Best of the Millennium - Oct 1, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE BEST OF THE MILLENNIUM MAGAZINES
</P>
<P>
   Dear Editor,
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium Series, six special issues of The New York Times
Magazine, April 18 through December 5, 1999, celebrates the last
1,000 years of mankind in six themed issues, each on a different,
compelling topic, with contributions by a stellar lineup of
writers.
</P>
<P>
   We have put together a collection of 14 outstanding articles
from the first four issues. Please contact me if you would like
more details on this special package.
</P>
<P>
   Best regards, Karl Horwitz October 1, 1999
</P>
<P>
   April 18: ``The Best of the Millennium''
</P>
<P>
   1. Every Dictator's Nightmare by Wole Soyinka Pulitzer
Prize-winning playwright and Nigerian pro-democracy leader Wole
Soyinka writes, ``every dictator's nightmare'' is the idea that
humans have rights. No matter who preaches it, the universal
principle of the fundamental rights of man is a tyrant's ``province
of terror.'' This concept is poised to totally liberate the lives
of billions of people in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   2. Invention is the Mother of Necessity by Jared Diamond
Pulitzer Prize-winning author and physicist Jared Diamond tells why
he believes that Gutemberg does not deserve sole credit for
inventing the printing press - although it is, no doubt, one of the
greatest inventions in history.
</P>
<P>
   3. When Tristam Met Isolde by Joyce Carol Oates In the ancient
world, romantic love was apparently virtually unknown and rarely
celebrated. Our term ``love'' did not exist and ``eros'' referred
to chaos, even disaster. But to the modern sensibility, love is the
very engine of life and romantic love will survive - at least by
another millennium.
</P>
<P>
   4. How the Bean Saved Civilization by Umberto Eco Forget
electricity, the microchip and the car. Without beans we wouldn't
have made it out of the Dark Ages. If human beings are still here -
Americans and children of European ancestors, descendants of the
Pilgrim Fathers or the Spanish conquistadores - it is thanks to
beans.
</P>
<P>
   May 16 : ``Women : Shadow History of the Millennium''
</P>
<P>
   5. Power Suffering by Jennifer Egan The lives of the mystic
saints offer a cruel lesson in success -- that for many women,
power and suffering, often self-inflicted, are curiously
intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   6. Women in Fiction : First Person Female by Jim Harrison The
author of ``The Road Home'' and ``The Shape of the Journey''
confesses that it isn't easy to be a man writing female characters.
</P>
<P>
   7. Baby in a Box by Natalie Angier Every day, technology offers
women more choices for how and where to bear children - and a
tormenting array of new moral dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
   June 17 : ``The Great Adventures''
</P>
<P>
   8. In the Same Boat by Richard Ford Being in a boat with Stanley
Crouch trying to rediscover Mark Twain's legend, and some personal
truths about modern race relations, became a confessional inward
journey for Richard Ford. An experience in which he was to confront
his own guilt -- and the limits of thinking in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   9. Found in the Woods by Charles Siebert You can still visit a
patch of the forest primeval, in the very urban area of the Bronx,
N.Y. Just don't take a cell phone and watch out for skunks. Charles
Siebert pitches a tent, not far from the zoo, fully equipped with
smoked turkey and Swiss cheese sandwiches, sour pickles, two
bottles of V-8 juice and a pair of binoculars to see any passing
coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   10. On the Road with God's Fool by Gretel Ehrlich The author
retraces the journey St. Francis is believed to have taken in the
13th century, after he stood naked in Assisi's central plaza, lost
his family and possessions and redefined his life as a saint.
</P>
<P>
   11. Journey to the Centre of My Mind by Stephen S. Hall Here is
a different sort of personal journey. This author's adventure takes
place in a medical laboratory on Manhattan's Upper East Side, where
he undergoes an MRI - magnetic resonance imaging - test. The
purpose? To see, in his own brain, the home of memory, the land of
language and the areas that may eventually help to map
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   12. Why We Go by Andrea Barrett Even a modest adventure can
reinvent the world -- and our place in it. Here the author explains
the human impulse to go on adventures -- to ski and climb and sail
and mountain climb and explore the wilds.
</P>
<P>
   September 19 : ``Scenes from the Millennium''
</P>
<P>
   13. The Triumph of Imagery by Luc Sante For most of the
millennium, art was reserved for the rich and the religious. Now,
wherever we look, there is something to see. But is there no
escape?
</P>
<P>
   14. The Crusades, Even Now by Karen Armstrong Europe's first
mass movement has churned Western life ever since. 
--------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------------Please fax this form to Karl Horwitz,
New York Times Syndicate, Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
33.1.47.42.18.81. Or mail to New York Times Syndicate, 3, rue
Scribe, 75009 Paris, France. E-mail : nyt &LR; calva.net
</P>
<P>
   I am interested in story number(s) ________________
</P>
<P>
   from the first four New York Times Millennium Magazines
</P>
<P>
   ('Best of The Millennium Package') : Name: _____________________
Publication: ___________________ Country: ___________________
Telephone: ___________________ Fax: ______________________ e-mail:
______________________
</P>
