<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOLA-HNS &LR;      10-01 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOLA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRIBUTE TO MAX OPHULS ON THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last woman for whom Max Ophuls went behind the camera was
``Lola Montes.'' It was 1955, two years before his death, and she
was his most wretched subject _ washed up, desperate, attempting
everything in her feckless power to matter again, both as a dancer
and a courtesan.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be reaching for a masterpiece as if that
achievement had eluded him throughout the 24 previous films he had
made, as though at 53 he could see a bit of himself in her scandal
and tragedy. But ``Lola'' feels like the phantasmagoric final act
in an artist's career that demanded that cinema meet the stage, in
the same way that for ambitious dreamers heaven can sometimes touch
the earth.
</P>
<P>
   For Ophuls, there was never a sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   For one week, the Castro theater in San Francisco will run 12 of
his films in a program assembled and mounted by the San Francisco
Film Society, which hunted the globe to find spotless prints of
Ophuls' works that provided more than a comprehensive sampler of
his oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   Taken in full or even in parts, the retrospective leaves you not
only with the knowledge that the director died while working at the
height of his ambition but that he was such a consummate sensualist
storyteller that his rapture crept under the skin of everyone's
work from Hitchcock to Nora Ephron.
</P>
<P>
   The series has wisely been arranged out of sequence in
double-feature pairs _ beginning with a masterpiece, ``The Earrings
of Madame De ...,'' Ophuls' penultimate film, and ending with
``Caught'' from 1949 _ demonstrating what an uncommonly focused
filmmaker he was.
</P>
<P>
   The subject matter never strayed far from dilapidated love among
the bourgeoisie. Though his films were made in his native Germany,
in France and in Hollywood, and there's an unwavering assurance in
each.
</P>
<P>
   He came to America and made ``The Exile'' in 1947, an
embarrassing costume-y star vehicle that Douglas Fairbanks Jr.
wrote and produced for himself. It begins to explain why of the
four and half American films he made _ one of three uncredited
directors on 1950's ``Vendetta'' _ for Hollywood, only two hang
nicely in his gallery: ``Reckless Moment'' and ``Letter From an
Unknown Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The former was an uncharacteristically generic piece of noir
pulp, notable for its lightning pacing, its spareness and a silky,
shady James Mason. It demonstrates that if Ophuls wanted to
maintain a career as a magnificent hack, he would've had a
brilliant time communing with Sam Fuller and fellow German Robert
Siodmak.
</P>
<P>
   But it was 1948's ``Unknown Woman'' that would be his finest
hour in Hollywood. It's a 90-minute love story with the opulence of
a saga. Joan Fontaine plays Lisa, the eponymous scribe who sends to
the love of her life, a pianist (Louis Jourdan), a letter so lyric
it seems more conjured than written, particularly the way Fontaine
exhales its contents in the voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the film's beauty lies the type of love that obsessed
Ophuls: the unsuccessful kind. Love wasn't simply complicated, it
was supernaturally awful. As a teen-ager, Lisa is seduced by
Jordan's player then discarded pregnant with his son. He meets her
years later as a grown woman, thinking she's a fresh conquest,
never realizing his romantic faux pas.
</P>
<P>
   The suffering is too much to bear, but the strings of fate
pulling at the film's lovers are the cosmic forces compelling the
sexual pairings in ``La Ronde,'' another master work in which
Ophuls balances reserve with excess. Ophuls' love was festooned
with costumes and wall-to-wall music. He could finds sumptuousness
even in the most decadent of situations (see his suggestive
handling of Guy de Maupassant's short stories in ``Le Plaisir''; or
simply the Spartan presence of Charles Boyer in ``Madame de.''
</P>
<P>
   Ophuls believed above all in rhapsody before he believed in
love, not as an adornment, but as a lifestyle choice, wrapped in a
stole, pulling up to the opera in a horse-drawn carriage, leaving
the box seats to weep. But as someone in ``Madame de'' says, ``it's
only superficially superficial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
