<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOLA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRIBUTE TO MAX OPHULS ON THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last woman for whom Max Ophuls went behind the camera was
``Lola Montes.'' It was 1955, two years before his death, and she
was his most wretched subject _ washed up, desperate, attempting
everything in her feckless power to matter again, both as a dancer
and a courtesan.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be reaching for a masterpiece as if that
achievement had eluded him throughout the 24 previous films he had
made, as though at 53 he could see a bit of himself in her scandal
and tragedy. But ``Lola'' feels like the phantasmagoric final act
