<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-DUMPING-1002-C     10-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-DUMPING-1002-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PEACE, POLLUTION: NEGOTIATORS WORK TO CONTROL DUMPING IN
DISPUTED WEST BANK
 &HT;    475&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UM IT-TUT, West Bank _ An elder community leader, Naifeh Abdul
Kareem clearly did not know what to do with the 230 oozing barrels
of waste illegally dumped in his farming village.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone wants to make some money, he does not care about
anything,'' Abdul Kareem, 63, said looking at the barrels stacked
among the houses of a shallow valley here. ``He is not worried
about the harm that could happen to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The chemicals _ for mixing paints _ were brought by an Israeli
who, it is believed, paid one of Abdul Kareem's neighbors to accept
them. For eight months, they sat seeping in the hot sun until they
were removed last week.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, the West Bank has been used for dumping by both
Palestinians and Israelis taking advantage of the weak legal
controls in the disputed area. Now, with peace talks gaining
momentum, environmental officials are just beginning to bring
modern waste-management practices to the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have . . . the scientific and technical procedures.
We just have what we call crude dumping,'' said Palestinian
Authority Environmental Minister Yousef Abu-Safieh.
</P>
<P>
   He says the new Israeli government elected in May has been more
sensitive about environmental issues that were being neglected in
previous years. They have reason to be concerned. Both Israelis and
Palestinians draw much of their water from an aquifer beneath the
West Bank, which could be affected by exuding wastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely there is an issue, a very grave issue,'' said
Shmuel Brenner, a top official in the Israeli environment ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank and The Gaza Strip were captured by Israel in the
1967 War. The Israeli army has governed the area, including 2.5
million Palestinians and about 180,000 Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1993 Oslo peace accords, Israel has turned over most
of Gaza and about 40 percent of the West Bank to full or partial
Palestinian control. But the environmental problems are just now
being addressed.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a few legal dumps in the West Bank and Gaza and
they are below modern standards. Trash, junked cars, and discarded
barrels can be found along roadsides at hundreds of other sites.
</P>
<P>
   At one of the legal dumps, run by Israel but near the
Palestinian town of Azzun, Palestinian employee Adam Bedwan said
truckers frequently ``beg'' for receipts from him for loads they
have illegally dumped elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian officials say they have not assessed the
damage caused by such dumping.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledge that both sides have contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people in the area are Palestinians and it follows
that they generate most of the waste. But, there are about 145
Jewish settlements in the West Bank and some have factories. Also,
it is easy for Israelis to truck waste to the West Bank, rather
than paying to have it treated in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   That's what officials believe happened here in Um It-Tut, a case
that shows some of the obstacles to cleaning up the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The barrels were brought from a factory in a settlement about a
half-hour's drive away. They should have been taken to a treatment
center about four hours away in southern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian owner of the land where they were dumped says he
intended to use the chemicals to start his own paint factory.
However, he is a laborer with little money and officials believe it
is more likely he was just paid by the Israeli to accept the waste.
</P>
<P>
   Once found, Israeli and Palestinian officials could not agree on
who should pay to have the 230 barrels moved.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis say they will treat such waste if the Palestinians
transport it. Palestinians counter that doing that will encourage
anyone with waste to dump it in their areas and avoid transport
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Though the barrels have been moved from Um It-Tut, officials
have not settled the financial responsibility and are hoping to
have the costs paid by _ and perhaps prosecute _ the factory owner.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials say the waste problem in the West Bank should
be solved by bringing in private firms to manage landfills for
anyone _ Jews in settlements or Arabs in towns.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Safieh, the Palestinian Authority minister, recognizes the
logic to that, but that's where politics enters the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the settlements, which were established by Israel to
stake a claim to occupied land, remains to be settled in the Oslo
process. Abu-Safieh says cooperating on landfills with settlers
would be like recognizing the validity of settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlers are not our neighbors,'' he said. ``They are
occupiers.''
</P>
<P>
   However, with $25 million in foreign aid, the Palestinians are
beginning work on two modern landfills of their own here in the
West Bank. Meanwhile, Palestinian and Israeli environmentalists are
meeting regularly to hash out their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our destinies are together in this place,'' Abu-Safieh
concedes.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
