<HEADLINE>
BAUER-SCANDAL-SPIN 
 WINE-CRIME
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLATE, the premier online magazine of politics and culture, is
now available to your readers from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase these ``separate buy'' articles from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   1. WHEN THE REAL SCANDAL IS THE MEDIA SPIN, by William Saletan
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Gary Bauer denied that he had
violated his marital vows or inappropriately touched anyone, and he
challenged the dozens of reporters on hand to produce evidence or a
specific allegation that he had done so. If reporters had the
evidence, they could have produced it. If not, they could have
closed their notebooks and walked away. Instead, they interrogated
Bauer for half an hour in front of eight TV cameras and wrote
articles suggesting that whether or not he had had an affair, he
was wrong to have left open the possibility that anyone might have
thought he had done anything wrong. The scandal isn't that Bauer
committed adultery. The scandal is that without proving that charge
or even making it, the media have found ways to spin lesser,
derivative, and empty insinuations about him into a national story.
</P>
