<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3266 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-RUSSIA-BALKS-CRITIQUE     10-01 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BALKS-CRITIQUE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT A CONDESCENDING QUESTION! `WHO LOST RUSSIA'? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By PAVEL PALAZCHENKO  
 c.1999 Metro International, Helsinki  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The president and vice president of the United States are being
accused of having ``lost'' Russia _ the assumption being that
Russia was there to be ``lost'' by the West in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russia is being portrayed in the media as perhaps the
most corrupt place in the world. The implicit message is: ``Don't
touch Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago I asked former Secretary of State George Shultz what
he thought had gone wrong in the U.S.-Russian relationship. ``We
should have found a way to show that we respect your country,'' he
replied, ``that we are ready to treat it as a real partner despite
its problems.'' Next to all the current confusion, that sounds good
to me.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, the ``point man'' on
Russia in the Clinton White House, despite his expertise, has been
rather defensive and not very helpful: ``We have been aware from
the beginning that crime and corruption are a huge problem in
Russia and a huge obstacle to reform. Russian reform is not over,
but it's going to take decades and the problem will only get worse
if you isolate Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, for his part, has insisted
that all the negative headlines regarding Moscow going down the
drain are rooted in U.S. electoral politics and aim at
``besmirching Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   But these reactions badly miss the point. There never was a
debate in the West about how to ``engage'' Moscow, and it truly
doesn't sound as if one is about to start now.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the so-called money-laundering, IMF-loan scandal.
It certainly shows no sign of abating. This is purported to involve
money from Russia, perhaps IMF loans, high-ranking Russian
officials and the Bank of New York. The story so far is complex and
convoluted and has fact, fantasy and flawed reasoning mixed in
unknown proportion.
</P>
<P>
   As to facts, it seems clear that large amounts of money, of
murky and possibly criminal origin, went through accounts in the
Bank of New York without triggering any reporting or regulatory
alarms or procedures. How this could happen in banking _ which is
arguably the most regulated area in the U.S. economy _ is anyone's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   One might expect that this would be the first question for the
media and congressional watchdogs to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly charged political atmosphere, the debate has taken a
different turn. ``Hands off Russia!'' ``Russia was never any
good!'' ``No wonder Russia lost the Cold War!'' _ this gloating is
a mere diversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue that troubles me,'' says Condoleezza Rice, a top
adviser to likely Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush,
``is: Were we accepting the rhetoric of reform rather than real
reform in Russia?''
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the right questions to ask. Rice is also right to
use the word ``we,'' because the same mistake was made by President
Bush and President Clinton, by Republicans and Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
   Once the fundamental assumption was made that Russia was a
nation defeated in the Cold War, once the rhetoric of U.S. ``aid''
for Russia replaced the idea of cooperation, subsequent
developments flowed almost automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Troops of American university presidents with little or no
knowledge of the realities of Russia's economy arrived in Moscow to
``advise on economic reform,'' with no regard for the cultural
obstacles they were facing or the need to create a legal framework
for economic change. Sending fly-by-night academics to ``give
advice'' and then looking the other way as ``the new Russia''
degenerated into an orgy of oligarchy and corruption was not the
best way to show respect and willingness for partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, in a recent article in The Washington Post, U.S.
national security adviser Samuel Berger asserts that that was the
only way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Well then, one has to live with the consequences. Mafia-style
economics and a merging of organized crime and bureaucracy become a
very real result when know-nothing advisers put fancy plans into
action that destroy a government's economic control _ and nothing
is put in place instead.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not President Yeltsin and members of his family were
involved in any improprieties is almost irrelevant. What matters is
that Yeltsin is presiding over a system that has made a mockery of
democracy, market economics and the rule of law _ achieving those
goals was among Russia's priorities since the Cold War ended.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, still, the possibilities for cooperative U.S.-Russian
programs are virtually limitless. They exist today, as they have
for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   As two former senators, Gary Hart and Gordon Humphrey, wrote
recently in a letter to The New York Times, ``Why not a U.S.-led
program to create a sound banking system, a mortgage-lending
program, long-term oil purchase contracts to provide revenues for
infrastructure rebuilding and jobs, and a program to establish a
desperately needed pharmaceutical industry?''
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take elections in both countries to cool down
the rhetoric and assess what has been happening and where to go
from here.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, it would not be a bad idea to quit lamenting
the death of Russia and instead take a long, hard look at the
global economy and what has happened to the barriers that once were
in place to prevent the free flow of capital.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps someone might even stand up (when all the noise pipes
down about ``dreadful Russia'') and ask this: Has it not become too
easy for the barons of dirty money to make and hide their mountains
of gold?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pavel Palazchenko is the author of ``My Years With Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze: The Memoir of a Soviet Interpreter'' (1997). His
columns have appeared in Moscow News; Metro International,
Helsinki, and other publications. During the Cold War, he published
commentary under the pen name, ``P. Vorobyev.'' He currently
teaches Russian language and contemporary politics at Colgate
University; he has also taught at Moscow Linguistic University.
From 1980 to 1991 he served in the Russian Foreign Ministry, before
which he was an interpreter with the United Nations in New York. He
is still the chief translator and personal adviser to Mikhail
Gorbachev, the last president of the Soviet Union.) &LR;
</P>
