<HEADER>
A3271 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-MAO-ANNIVERSARY-CHINA     10-01 1966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAO-ANNIVERSARY-CHINA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DO YOU DO ABOUT MAO? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By ERIK ECKHOLM  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    In 1992, a retired book editor named Zhu Zheng read a short
essay a friend of his had written about the Anti-Rightist Campaign
of 1957. That year, more than half a million people were purged
after they responded to Mao Zedong's invitation to criticize the
revolution, only to find themselves branded enemies.
 &HT;    For Zhu, the topic had special resonance. As an idealistic young
journalist in the southern city of Changsha in 1957, he was labeled
``a poisonous weed'' and spent several years breaking rocks in a
labor camp. Upon reading his friend's words, Zhu recalls, he was
consumed by the need to tell the story in detail.
 &HT;    Like many who lived through it, Zhu, now 68, sees the 1957
campaign as a terrible turning point, inaugurating a series of
disastrous upheavals that ended only with Mao's death, in 1976.
 &HT;    So in 1993, in one frantic year, Zhu _ who skipped college out
of revolutionary zeal and describes himself as ``a minor
intellectual'' _ scoured the records and newspapers of the period,
interviewed everyone who would talk and scrawled out a book
manuscript, ``The Summer of 1957.''
 &HT;    Then began the quest to get his book printed. Eventually, the
Henan People's Press expressed interest. But in keeping with the
rules for accounts of Communist Party history, the publisher first
sent the manuscript to the chief guardians of the printed word at
the News and Publishing Office, under the central Department of
Propaganda, in Beijing.
 &HT;    The response came in an April 1996 memo, written by three
scholars at the party's History Research Office, to which the
manuscript had been referred. ``Generally, this book is rich in
sources and supports its account with evidence,'' their memo said,
adding, with patronizing politeness, that ``the author's attitude
is serious and rigorous.''
 &HT;    But noting that it covered ``a rather complex'' subject, the
memo _ its daggers cloaked in typically banal Communist prose _
went on to say that ``particular care must be given to adopt an
analytic attitude of seeking truth from facts.'' Specifically, it
said that the manuscript ``still needs to accurately reflect the
spirit of the 1981 resolution on history that the Anti-Rightist
struggle was a necessary one.'' This was a reference to a key
document that for nearly two decades has set the boundaries for
scholarship on the Mao era.
 &HT;    The censors' memo to Zhu demanded excision of quotes from Mao
that had been circulated at the time but later omitted from his
published works as embarrassing. It noted sections where ``the
reasoning and analysis are not proper.'' It barred the naming of so
many persecutors, ``especially influential and well-known
figures,'' and exhorted Zhu to adopt the spirit of ``uniting as one
to look to the future.''
 &HT;    On Oct. 1, China will mark 50 years since Mao proclaimed the
People's Republic before cheering throngs in Tiananmen Square. In
the best Communist fashion, betraying a mix of pride and
insecurity, China is going all out, giving Beijing a virtual
makeover in preparation.
 &HT;    The big day will feature a minutely orchestrated parade of
140,000 _ everything from Young Pioneers in red bandannas to
China's latest ballistic missiles. The marchers will pass under the
giant painting of Mao that perennially hangs over Tiananmen, facing
toward the mausoleum where the Great Helmsman's embalmed body is
displayed.
 &HT;    The group of men who now rule China will celebrate the triumphs
of the Communist revolution and the inevitable glories ahead. But
they are sure to skate over the past. For an unflinching look at
the half-century of Communist Party rule is the last thing the
leaders want. Confession may be good for the soul, but making a
clean breast of prior calamities can be dangerous for a dictatorial
government.
 &HT;    China's current leaders, including President Jiang Zemin,
watched in horror as the Soviet Communist Party collapsed _ and
they are convinced that Mikhail Gorbachev's decision in 1987 to
allow candid probing of Soviet history helped speed its downfall.
And their harsh crackdown on Falun Gong, the spiritual movement
that staged an illegal protest earlier this year, is further
testimony to their insecurity.
 &HT;    China's problem is epitomized by that giant portrait hovering
over the square in the center of Beijing. Mao is the undisputed
founding father of the revolution and remains a key source of the
party's claims to legitimacy. Yet he was also the source of bizarre
and sometimes murderous campaigns that crippled China's
development.
 &HT;    In addition to the Anti-Rightist Campaign, these included the
economically idiotic Great Leap Forward, in the late 1950s, which
caused the famine deaths of tens of millions, and the Cultural
Revolution, a reign of terror stretching from 1966 to Mao's death,
in 1976.
 &HT;    Deng Xiaoping, who created today's more open and vibrant China,
was the first leader to wrestle with the Mao problem. As he gained
power in the years after Mao's death, Deng was intent on preserving
stability while reviving the economy through market reforms.
 &HT;    But even as he pointed China on the capitalist road, he knew he
could not afford to repudiate a Communist legacy that was, after
all, his own foundation for power. Least of all could he take down
that big portrait in Tiananmen Square. So he presided over an
artful revision of official history.
 &HT;    ``It is better to write in broad outline and not go into too
much detail,'' Deng said in a 1981 speech, as the new guidelines
were being prepared. ``The purpose of summing up the past is to
encourage people to close ranks and look to the future.'' Deng had
a personal reason for stifling the truth as well: He had been a
chief enforcer of the Anti-Rightist Campaign.
 &HT;    To an astonishing degree, Chinese historical scholarship,
journalism and public speech must still adhere to that 1981
document, the ``Resolution on Certain Questions in the History of
Our Party Since the Founding of the People's Republic of China.''
 &HT;    Since he could not afford to jettison the Communist legacy, he
set out to explain the most glaringly disastrous events as
aberrations. The resulting 1981 document is almost surreal in its
efforts to parcel out blame without tarnishing Mao too badly, or
Deng himself.
 &HT;    Mao, it says, was a gross violator of his own thought. The
Cultural Revolution is unambiguously described as wrong, led by Mao
under the mistaken notion that ``capitalist roaders'' had taken
over the party and that ``continuous revolution'' was needed. But
these ``erroneous theses,'' the document says, ``were obviously
inconsistent with the system of Mao Zedong Thought.''
 &HT;    The resolution says that the purges of 1957 were definitely
needed, arguing that some ``rightists'' were out to destroy
socialism, but acknowledges that the purges got out of hand,
harming many innocent people. The Great Leap Forward, with its
forced communal farming and backyard iron smelters, ``overlooked
objective economic laws'' because Mao was ``impatient for quick
results.''
 &HT;    In its overall assessment of Mao, the document describes him as
``a great Marxist and a great proletarian revolutionary, strategist
and theorist.'' In a conclusion that is still parroted by Chinese
officials, it declares, ``If we judge his activities as a whole,
his contributions to the Chinese revolution far outweigh his
mistakes.''
 &HT;    Deng's guidelines have never been updated _ the issues are just
too hot to reopen. So for more recent events, such as the killing
of hundreds in 1989 as the army crushed the student democracy
movement, the government has simply used censorship and arrests.
Everyone instinctively knows the limits.
 &HT;    Today, trying to control history would seem futile. Yes, China's
newspapers and radio and television, virtually without exception,
still stick blandly to the official line. But many Chinese lived
through the disasters and know that the past has been airbrushed.
And now, with the Internet and with so many Chinese studying
abroad, many scholars are also familiar with the devastating
accounts published in the West.
 &HT;    What's more, profit-seeking Chinese publishers are responding to
a clear public yearning with a stream of memoirs, often by retired
party officials, that are loaded with damning facts. These often
wriggle past the censors by avoiding generalizations about national
policy and being careful not to assign blame to particular leaders.
 &HT;    Except in obviously touchy cases, such as Zhu's manuscript on
the 1957 campaign, publishers themselves decide whether a work
needs prior party review. Mostly, writers and editors do their own
tinkering, then publish and pray for enough buzz to stimulate sales
but not attract trouble.
 &HT;    So why do the party leaders still bother? The truth is, that at
this ripe stage in the life cycle of Communist rule, no one really
expects people to believe the canned history or the related, often
vacuous language of political speech.
 &HT;    ``The leaders don't have to believe it themselves,'' Zhu says.
``But they have to make everybody else say they believe it.
Everybody is acting in a play.'' So long as most people agree to
keep acting _ and most do, usually because they see no plausible
alternative for China right now _ the Communist show can go on.
 &HT;    In the end, Zhu had to cut more than 10 percent of the material
in his book, which was finally published in 1998 in a respectable
printing of 30,000 that is mostly sold out.
 &HT;    He went on to write his autobiography, which he called ``A Minor
Scholar in Major Times.'' It is a memoir of betrayed hopes and an
almost comical train of misfortunes through Mao's campaigns, with
homage to the sheer creativity of the persecutors. And because the
manuscript was not a direct analysis of Communist history it was
published this year without prior vetting, by the prestigious
Peking University Press.
 &HT;    Making use of new materials made available in recent years, even
some party scholars have published more revelatory accounts of
events such as the Cultural Revolution. Still, because they cross
that line drawn in 1981, a number of major manuscripts covering the
Mao period languish in office drawers or are passed around,
samizdat-style, among like-minded scholars.
 &HT;    At a formal level, the Communist Party is producing a major new
official history of the revolution. A first fat volume covering the
period from the party's founding in 1921 to its victory in 1949
appeared in the early 1990s.
 &HT;    The second volume, covering the tortured years up to 1978, is
expected by the end of this year. It would be a mistake, however,
to anticipate any major reappraisals of Mao or his destructive
campaigns. A chief editor of Volume 2 just happens to be one of
those three party historians who, back in 1996, so politely
censored Zhu Zheng's manuscript.
 &HT;     c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Erik Eckholm is the co-chief of the Beijing bureau of The New
York Times.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
