<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CRAZY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS PURSUE SWEET REVENGE IN `DRIVE ME CRAZY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To make an impact, you have to go to extremes,'' Nicole, the
popular blond socialite (Melissa Joan Hart, also known as Sabrina
the Teenage Witch), says to Chase, the mop-top politico (Adrian
Grenier, also known as Sebastian Cole).
</P>
<P>
   This means a trip to The Gap, where he can shed those track
pants and Biohazard T-shirt for khakis and an oxford topped with a
leather jacket, his Greg Brady curls turned into a different
hairdon't.
</P>
<P>
   If the 12th-grader were to get any more extreme, he'd have to
start wearing a leather trench coat. But this is ``Drive Me
Crazy,'' an impressively competent ``how will male teen star get
with female teen star at high school dance?'' romance, so this
doesn't get any darker than the eyeliner of its anime-goth girls.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Rob Thomas from Todd Strasser's novel ``How I Created
My Perfect Prom Date,'' the film has the good sense not to give in
to these kids' belief that high school is cordoned off so that
social spheres don't intersect.
</P>
<P>
   They are in this Utah suburbia where a girl still lets the rest
of town know how she feels about ``him'' by cruising down Broadway
listening to Night Ranger, and where the dance is called
``Centennial,'' which looks a lot like the ``She's All That'' prom,
and check out the gay guy, chilling with the beautiful people.
</P>
<P>
   Though, come to think of it, these kids appear to be attending a
magnet school. Still, there's something sweetly retrograde about
Nicole and Chase being dumped days before ``Centennial,'' then
teaming up as a new couple to make their ex'es jealous. Hart and
Grenier have a flirty ``who'da thunk it?'' chemistry that seems
like he's making a play for her TGIF lineup and she's making a stab
at his burgeoning indie-movie fame.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun watching her go nuts at a Donnas concert (the
Ramones-for-girls band plays a group called the Electrocutes) and
seeing him get psyched about watching what may be the worst varsity
basketball game ever put on film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy'' _ directed by John Schultz like that one kid who loves
the cafeteria food so much, he convinces you it might be good _
smudges the lines between the popular and the pariah-ed.
</P>
<P>
   The best scenes involve a couple of Chase's techno-geek buddies
(Kris Park and Mark Webber), who are nothing like his irritating
cafe friends. They want into Chase's new world as much as they
resent him for his sudden access to it. It's easy for a guy like
Chase to be liked schoolwide because he has a crossover appeal that
allows him to break through without selling out, regardless of
where he shops, which is really what this movie's saying: Everybody
invests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
