<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-GUINEVERE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALE LOVE OF `GUINEVERE' INSPIRES CROCODILE TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Audrey Wells' debut directorial feature, ``Guinevere,'' is a
love story so implausibly dainty that when its San Francisco
heroine is sent packing from her older boyfriend/mentor's
Embarcadero loft and back to the slums of Pacific Heights, you'll
want to shed a crocodile tear.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Polley, making the most of a girl underwritten, is Harper
Stone, a 20-year-old loner who scraps her Harvard law plans to take
up with Connie, a creepy Irish photographer (Stephen Rea) of a
certain age.
</P>
<P>
   They meet at her older sister's wedding _ he agrees to cut her
out of the pictures he's snapping _ and she's already in love. The
burgeoning relationship has the requisite queasiness that an affair
between a Bob Dylan-circa-now-looking Rea and any woman a third his
age should.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than go for a quirky _ OK, crazy _ older
guy-waaay-younger woman romance, Wells goes the professor-protege
route, couching the affair in pretentious tutorials about art and
its metaphors for living. All Harper has to do to live with Rea is
something creative, you know, paint, write or dance _ ``You're
mistaking me for someone with potential,'' she warns. ``I don't
make mistakes,'' he warns back _ and not be too freaked out when he
starts calling her Guinevere.
</P>
<P>
   One supposes it's a fair deal: The alcoholic Connie gets some
affection; Harper the girl gets to learn about Alfred Stieglitz and
sit at the Harper's magazine equivalent of the Algonquin
round-table, which, in Gina Gershon (sporting Minnie Driver
pigtails), has its own Edna Ferber.
</P>
<P>
   Gershon plays the sour-grapes painter who's seen Connie's moves
before and tries to warn Harper: She too was once a Guinevere,
which as it turns out is a round-table of sexy Mays to Rea's
rumpled December. But Gershon never comes out and says, ``Eeeww,
get out!'' No one does, not even the gospel-soul singers who
serenade Harper at a surprise birthday party Connie throws for her.
</P>
<P>
   God bless Jean Smart as Harper's bitch-and-brandy mother. She's
the only person in this boho fantasy who seems to know what's going
on. Granted, she has one foot on the ground and the other dangling
from a Town Car, but she prunes the roses it takes an hour for this
movie to wake up and smell.
</P>
<P>
   Mom breezes into Connie's loft and sagely offers the ``you're a
dirty old man'' speech her ``Designing Women'' character was too
dumb to give. Smart is so piercing that you pity Rea, whom Wells,
writer of the far more direct and insightful ``The Truth About Cats
and Dogs,'' uses as a Michael Douglas-Sean Connery stand-in.
</P>
<P>
   Her vehemence gives ``Guinevere'' a purposeful Kodak moment in
Wells' scrapbook of underdeveloped Polaroids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0074 </DOCNO>
