<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY-BOS &LR;      10-01 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY WAR CHEST OVERTAKES THAT OF GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a fresh sign of Bill Bradley's surging strength
in the Democratic presidential race, the former New Jersey senator
reported Thursday that he raised more money in the last quarter
than Vice President Al Gore, leaving both candidates nearly tied in
the financial race with about $10 million each in cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Texas Governor George W. Bush continues
with his remarkable financial strength, having raised $56 million _
more than any presidential candidate in history. Aside from
publisher Steve Forbes, who is self-financing much of his campaign,
Bush's closest competitor is Senator John McCain of Arizona, who
has raised $9.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The devolopment that Bradley has about the same financial
resources as Gore is significant because it shows the two
candidates are neck-and-neck in the all-important ``money
primary,'' which is being waged more furiously than ever because of
next year's compressed voting schedule. It also shows why the vice
president announced Wednesday that he is moving his headquarters to
Nashville and cutting his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who write checks for $1,000 to the campaigns are
among those most interested in shifts in the polls, and they are
beginning to vote with their pocketbook,'' said Larry Makinson,
executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics, which
tracks money and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term significance of the report, meanwhile, is that
Bush _ if he become the GOP nominee _ could be flush with cash for
several months while his Democratic opponent would be nearly broke.
That is because Bush _ unlike the two Democrats _ is not abiding by
a spending cap.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign has been spending heavily even as the candidate
drops in the polls. Gore now is hoping for free media provided by
debates, which might reinvigorate his fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley raised about $6.7 million between July and September,
compared to $6.5 million for Gore, according to reports filed
Thursday with the Federal Election Commission. During the same
time, Bradley spent $4.2 million, while Gore spent around $6
million. Politically during that period, Bradley climbed to a
statistical tie with Gore in New Hampshire polls and benefited from
a flood of publicity, including the cover of this week's Time
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Bradley has raised $18.4 million this year, while Gore
has brought in $24 million, despite the early belief that the vice
president could use his party connections to bring in far more
money than the former New Jersey senator. But with Gore spending so
heavily and Bradley conserving his resources, the two are nearly
even with cash on hand, with Gore reporting $9.5 million to $10
million, and Bradley saying he has $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that in terms of fund-raising, Bradley has clearly
been the candidate who exceeded expectations,'' said Anthony
Corrado, a government professor at Maine's Colby College who
studies campaign finance. ``The expectation was that Bradley was
going to have difficulty being financially competitive with Gore.
It is clear now that is not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairly or not, the amount of money raised by a candidate often
is seen as a crucial test of support, so Thursday's results are
bound to increase Bradley's stock, helping him convince more people
to support his campaign. Gore, meanwhile, is likely to use the
Bradley surge to rally supporters who may have been holding back
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican financial reports again demonstrated Bush's
strength and the weaknesses of most other GOP candidates. Bush has
broken fund-raising records after rejecting federal matching funds,
taking in $19 million in the last quarter alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign treasury was bolstered by five-figure
``bundles'' of money in the last quarter from big companies like
First Energy Corp. of Ohio, and the national accounting firm of
Ernst &AMP; Young. Employees in former Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger
Staubach's commercial real estate firm gave more than $5,000 and
other notable donors included anti-affirmative action activist Ward
Connerly, members of Colorado's Coors beer family and a dozen or
more Washington lawyer-lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, which has been regularly updating its donor
list on the Internet, Thursday released an appendix to its list of
fund-raising ``pioneers'' _ individuals who promised to raise at
least $100,000 for the Texas governor this year. It included
Staubach and, from Massachusetts, Martha Chayet of Manchester,
Chris Jenny of Wayland and former Governor William F. Weld.
</P>
<P>
   The only candidate likely to come close to Bush's financial
strength is Forbes, who is self-financing much of his campaign.
According to Thursday's report, Forbes raised $1.4 million in the
last quarter, bringing his total to $4.2 million. But that does not
include the $9.5 million that Forbes contributed to his effort the
last quarter, or the $6.6 million he gave to his campaign in the
prior two quarters. If Forbes's own contributions are counted, he
has raised $20.3 million, and he says he has the personal resources
to compete with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law allows a candidate to contribute unlimited funds to
his or her own campaign, while other individuals may give no more
than $1,000 per election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans gave the following reports Thursday: McCain
raised $3 million during the quarter, bringing his total to $9.3
million; Gary Bauer raised $2 million during the last quarter,
bringing his total this year to $5.4 million; and Elizabeth Dole
raised $1.5 million, for a year-to-date total of $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin Hatch of Utah, making his first financial report,
has raised $1.2 million, while talk show host Alan Keyes brought in
$500,000 during the quarter for total of $2.4 million. Patrick J.
Buchanan, who is considering dropping out of the GOP and seeking
the Reform Party nomination, has raised $4 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, who dropped out of the race on
Monday due to financial problems, did not release a report
Thursday. An aide acknowledged the campaign is in debt but declined
to be specific, adding that the accounting books will be in balance
after federal matching funds are received.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush's financial strength helps him win the nomination after
an early round of primaries, he could still have tens of millions
of dollars to spend in preparation for the general election. That
is likely to be far more money than is available to the Democratic
nominee, because both Democratic candidates are taking matching
funds and have agreed to spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, while the Democratic nominee might be waiting for
the infusion of federal money provided after the national
convention, Bush could spend millions of dollars during the later
stages of the primary season to establish his campaign and attack
the Democrats. That is similar to the scenario Bob Dole faced in
1996, when he was short on funds after a brutal GOP primary fight
and had no money to respond to attacks from Clinton, who had plenty
of funds because he faced no primary opposition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Aloysius Farrell of the Globe staff contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
