<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV03     10-01 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVER NEEDS TO STEP UP PACE TO WARD OFF EFFECTS OF INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 03, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 37 years old and make a salary of $36,000 a year. I
purchased a condo a year ago, with a $134,000 mortgage requiring a
$1,134 monthly payment. I pay an extra $100 a month and the current
balance is $132,000. (Is this a good idea?) I put the maximum
allowed into my IRA, and have no debt other than the mortgage. An
IRA with T. Rowe Prices Science and Technology fund is now worth
$14,700. Another IRA in Vanguard Index 500 holds $3,300. A Roth
IRA, also with Vanguard, has a $2,000 balance divided between the
Index 500 and Health Care funds. On the taxable side, I have an
additional $8,800 in Prices Science and Technology, and at Vanguard
I have $8,000 in the Prime Money Market fund, $25,200 in Index 500
fund, and $6,400 in Health Care. In addition to my IRA investments,
I add $200 a month to the Index 500 position and $100 a month to
Health Care. I plan to work until I am 50 to 55. How do things look
for my retirement?
</P>
<P>
   M.W., Anaheim Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. To be honest, it looks a little shaky. I'll focus on retiring
at age 55, because the numbers come a little closer at that point.
If you continue saving at your current rate and realized an average
investment return of 10 percent a year, your total savings would
amount to $717,191, which you might calculate could bring you a
$46,617 income stream (presuming a 6.5 percent yield from a
fixed-income portfolio). But there are two problems, both involving
inflation. One is that you are living on $29,208 a year at this
point _ your income minus that amount you are saving. If inflation
averages 3.5 percent, after 19 years you will need $56,152 to buy
the same goods and services that $29,208 buys today. You might
calculate that your mortgage would be paid off at that point, so
you would be about even. But you still would have very little money
available to produce the capital growth that will be needed to
protect you against the inevitable inflation that will come in the
later years of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that unless you can advance the level of your
savings, you would probably be better off targeting retirement at
age 60, by which point you would have accumulated $1,192,073,
following the same assumptions as above. At that point you would be
within a couple of years of eligibility for Social Security, and
your mortgage would probably be paid off, whether or not you
continue to make that $100 prepayment.
</P>
<P>
   As for the question of prepayment, I usually lean in favor of
prepaying the mortgage, following the old-fashioned assumption that
outright ownership of your home is one of cornerstones of financial
stability. But if the mortgage is only a year old, you probably
have a very low interest rate. Further, by prepaying the mortgage,
you are eating away at the amount of the interest deduction you can
take on your tax returns. And since it is reasonable to expect that
in the long haul your investments will earn a higher return than
the interest rate on your mortgage, I think I would suggest that
you divert those $100 monthly prepayments to your investment
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'd be happier if you focused a little more on core
portfolio holdings. I estimate that 45 percent of your investments
at this point are in the health care and science and technology
funds, which I think is too much. I would not debate that in the
long haul these sectors are likely to outpace the market as a
whole, but they also represent a higher degree of risk. I would
rather see these positions represent about 15 percent each, with
the portfolio being rounded out through inclusion of small cap,
mid-cap, and international funds. I wouldn't make any changes in
the current holdings, but I suggest you stop building the sector
positions and divert your ongoing contributions to the new
categories.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have two children, aged nine and six. Currently their
college fund contains $6,500 with $4,800 in Vanguard's Health Care
fund and $1,700 in Dupree North Carolina Tax-Free Income fund. I
will have $10,000 to invest before the end of the year and plan to
contribute $300 a month thereafter. Could you suggest an allocation
within the Vanguard funds for this money, as well as a strategy for
reallocations as they get older?
</P>
<P>
   R.S., Garner, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A. Although I've always been a big fan of Vanguard's Health Care
fund, I'm not sure I would place such heavy reliance upon it as you
are doing. Although the fund has a great track record and it
provides prospects of handsome rewards for long-term holders, I
think at the minimum you should reduce your reliance upon it in
these intermediate-term accounts. I suggest you reduce the position
in that fund to $3,000, mentally earmarking $1,500 of the money for
each child. I would then divide the remaining money into pools of
$6,750, mentally earmarked for each child. For the elder child, you
might put $3,000 of the money in Vanguard Wellington and the rest
in Vanguard GNMA. For the younger child, I'd suggest putting $3,000
in Vanguard Windsor II and the balance in Vanguard Wellington.
</P>
<P>
   Once the elder child gets within your years of college age, I
would swap the Wellington position for Vanguard's Short-Term
Corporate Bond fund, and in each succeeding year I would move one
quarter of the money from the GNMA fund into the Short-Term Bond
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, once college begins, I would move whatever money is to
be used during each year into the Vanguard Prime Money Market fund,
from which you could make the disbursements as the bills come due.
</P>
<P>
   I would follow the a similar procedure with the younger child,
swapping the Windsor II shares for GNMA when the student is age 9,
and then following the same procedure as you did with the older
child.
</P>
<P>
   Since I presume the tax-free bond fund holding was purchased
with a view to your own tax situation, Id suggest no change there.
Moreover, if your tax situation dictates it, you might buy more
shares of that holding instead of the Vanguard fixed-income funds.
</P>
<P>
   As for the money that was in Vanguard Health Care: since that's
the vehicle with the greatest prospect of growth, you'll want to
leave it in that fund for as long as possible to get the maximum
potential benefit. I'd tend to think of that money as funds which
are likely to be drawn upon in each child's final year of school,
and thus leave it invested in the fund until college begins, at
which point it might be moved into the Short-Term Corporate Bond
account.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have noticed that financial planning columns such as yours
routinely and consistently advise shifting from growth to income
investments for retirement and old age. This has always puzzled me
greatly. I am 69 and retired. A fair portion of my retirement nest
egg is in some insurance stock I purchased 42 years ago for $800
and is now worth about $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The dividend is only 1.5 percent. In addition I own mutual funds
that are strictly growth, and a variable annuity that is likewise
in growth stocks. This investment strategy has proved to be nothing
short of fabulous for me, and I intend to maintain it until I die,
a which time my children will likewise benefit handsomely. Not only
has the total return greatly exceeded what any income strategy
would have produced, but the income tax advantages continue to be
enormous also. Am I missing something?
</P>
<P>
   S.C., Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think so. I think that you've been in a bull market for so
long that you've forgotten what happened from time to time back in
the dark ages _ when the stock market went down, moved sideways,
went down again, then went sideways again. (Think back to the 70s
and perhaps you'll remember.)
</P>
<P>
   The high-growth strategy is great for accumulating retirement
funds, but it is too risky for most people once they get into
retirement. You have to be very brave (or foolhardy), or very rich,
to live with such a strategy without worries.
</P>
<P>
   Of course many people get locked into investments such as your
insurance stock, where the gains have been so large that your base
costs represent a token amount, and the tax effect of sales would
seem punitive. Perhaps there's nothing to be done about that, but I
certainly would swap some of the stock funds and the variable
annuity holding for more conservative investments if I were you. I
also bet you won't. Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
