<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX LOSE; GARCIAPARRA SENT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ This was the anti-clinching.
</P>
<P>
   A night after they secured their second straight American League
playoff berth, not only were the Red Sox eliminated from the East
race, but they discovered their buoyant hopes for October may be in
peril.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop/catalyst Nomar Garciaparra, the AL batting leader,
left Comiskey Park just before Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's game, and as a
makeshift lineup of his teammates was falling to the White Sox,
5-2, he was on his way home to Boston to have his ailing right
wrist reevaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was hit by a pitch from the Orioles' Alberto Reyes
Saturday, and X-rays that night revealed no broken bones. In fact,
Garciaparra struck the homer Wednesday that beat the White Sox,
6-2, and guaranteed baseball this month at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Red Sox were consigned to the wild card
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night by the first-place Yankees' 12-5 rout of Baltimore,
manager Jimy Williams said, ``If you'd seen him taking practice
(Wednesday), he hit some balls off the end of the bat and it hurt.
We've talked about his health, what's the correct way to handle
it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the wild card in the bank and chances of catching the
Yankees remote, Williams already had decided to sit out Garciaparra
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night and Friday night in Baltimore. According to trainer
Jim Rowe, Garciaparra complained that the wrist was still bothering
him after he arrived at Comiskey Thursday and requested that more
tests be conducted. Rowe said ``there are a couple of other things
that can be done'' but wouldn't specify what they are. He indicated
that team physician Arthur Pappas probably will have an update
after examining Garciaparra Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was still on the premises an hour before game time,
and team spokesman Kevin Shea announced the All-Star's departure
just before the first pitch. Shea emphasized that the move is
strictly precautionary.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams said, ``We'll have to see what the docs say. It's
just not healing the way he felt it should be. With him not playing
tonight and tomorrow, we decided it was best to send him back
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that there is no fracture, Garciaparra's status for the
Division Series next week would not seem to be in jeopardy.
``Nomar's going to play,'' promised catcher Jason Varitek,
``whether he's hurt or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt that a lingering wrist ailment could be a
major impediment for the player the Red Sox most heavily rely on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good news at this point in the season,'' said
outfielder Darren Lewis, who had similar wrist problems earlier
this year. ``Hopefully, he'll be OK. I know he had X-rays and he
told me it wasn't broken. I know it takes time to go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to heal. I had it and it took two months. His
won't heal until after the season. At this point, I'm sure that if
he can, he'll play through the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's situation turned the night into a complete
throwaway for the Red Sox. The Yankees, who needed only a win over
the Orioles or a Boston loss to retain the East title, were doubly
blessed. Within seconds after New York polished off Baltimore,
pinch hitter Varitek's bid for a go-ahead ninth-inning grand slam
off wobbly Chicago closer Bob Howry died at the center-field fence,
where Brian Simmons made a spectacular catch as he crashed
headfirst into the barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Since a New York pennant was virtually a foregone conclusion,
anyway, the Red Sox deployed a wild-card lineup that wasn't exactly
the junior varsity but never would be on display as a unit in a
high-stakes situation. Not surprisingly, the woeful White Sox took
advantage as Carlos Lee's seventh-inning homer off Brian Rose
snapped a 2-2 tie and Magglio Ordonez's two-run shot off John
Wasdin in the eighth put it away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
