<HEADER>
A3352 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKO-MCHALE-2TAKES-ART     10-01 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-MCHALE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVIN MCHALE DOES FRIENDS, FAMILY PROUD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIBBING, Minn. _ The Beanhead is concerned. He knows his friend
Kevin wants the dock cleaned (there's lots of loon droppings),
taken in, and stored for the brutal, Iron Range winter that is sure
to come. But he also knows Kevin wants the whole house torn down
because the roof leaks, the squirrels are inside, and, well, where
to put the dock if there's no house?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll just bring it in and wait,'' the Beanhead shrugs,
making his way up the staircase from Big Sturgeon Lake to Kevin
McHale's two-story house. Two bald eagles swoop over the property
and a loon bellows from the middle of the lake. With autumn color
visible at every angle, it's a striking snapshot of nature.
</P>
<P>
   In McHale's absence, and sometimes even in his presence, the
Beanhead does most of the grunt work here. But the staircase was
built by another of Kevin's friends, Terry Maciej, who also built
the beautiful oak bar in the basement of the house. But McHale
wants the house knocked down anyway and a log cabin, like
Beanhead's across the lake, built in its place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's happened so far,'' said the Beanhead, also known as
Mark Badovinac, a 40-something heavy equipment worker who doubles
as McHale's Man Everyday on the Range. The Beanhead convinced
McHale to build a heated garage for McHale's seven boats, the
easier to store the assorted craft, which range from jet skis to a
pontoon boat. The Beanhead loves it here, as does McHale.
</P>
<P>
   But the Beanhead also thinks his buddy is a bit crazy to tear
down the house because of bad roof design or a few squirrels in the
television room. There's an expensive deck and oak moldings around
the doors. There are two prized mounted fish, a 64-pound king
salmon and a 10-pound walleye. There are McHale's two Sixth Man
Awards and the framed 1981 Sports Illustrated cover that shows him
``lowering the boom'' on Mo Cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   But it's now October, with winter approaching, and there's been
no decision. McHale says his wife, Lynn, doesn't want the place
razed so it likely will live to see another summer. His brother,
John, laughs when asked about the fate of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin puts very little on his high priority list,'' he says.
``Sometimes trying to get him to make a decision is like trying to
catch the fog.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beanhead knows that as well as anyone. His relationship with
McHale is based on implicit, unconditional trust: they regularly go
on fishing trips to Canada and have shared a tent for five, rainy
days playing cribbage. One other sign of their mutual bond _ they
have a joint checking account.
</P>
<P>
   But the Beanhead is just one of many who know and value the Hall
of Fame inductee, not for what he did in Boston, but what he did
and does on the Range. They knew him when he was simply Kevin, a
tall, gangly kid who, like everyone else, liked to hunt, fish, and
have fun. The relationships are inviolate, regardless of one's net
worth, celebrity status, or address.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's Beanhead. There's Chris Liesmaki, a high school
basketball teammate, and Terry Sachs. There's his brother, John,
and his cousin, Jim, and assorted suckers at Mesaba Country Club,
where McHale inexplicably reigns as club champion. (``The stars and
planets must have been aligned weird this year,'' he says by way of
explanation.)
</P>
<P>
   There are hunting pals. There are fishing pals. There are
golfing pals. If McHale tries to get uppity with any of them, they
can remind him about the time he had to use a shovel to kill a
beaver because he ran out of shells. (There are pictures as well.)
Or the time he mistakenly inserted the pole for his basketball hoop
16 feet into the ground and needed a Jeep and a wench to extract
the digging bit. Anything is fair game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things that any of us could do which still couldn't
make us not be friends,'' McHale says. ``I try to be who I am no
matter where I am. You are who you are. A long time ago I quit
worrying about what people thought. But those guys don't expect you
to be different. It's relaxing.''
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way as Larry Bird found comfort and solitude in
French Lick, Ind., so does McHale when he returns here every summer
and fall. There is much for him here, whether it's visiting his
mother, Josie, who still lives in the same house where Kevin was
raised, hunting with his brother John, or trying to take some money
from Gary Yaeger, the pro at Mesaba.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he comes here,'' Yaeger says. ``He can just be
Kevin and no one gives him a hard time. But on the course, when I
play him, his best weapon is his mouth. That's worth five shots a
round.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale laughs when he hears that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to yack at him when he'd have a 5-footer and he'd
always miss. Now he's gone to a new putter and he beats me all the
time. He says it's McHale-proof.''
</P>
<P>
   This city of 18,000 has produced an inordinate number of
celebrities given its size and location (180 miles north of the
Twin Cities). McHale, newly inducted into the Basketball Hall of
Fame in Springfield, Mass., isn't even the most famous. Bob
Zimmerman lived here from 1948 to 1959, the year he graduated from
Hibbing High School. He then went to the University of Minnesota,
changed his last name to Dylan, and before long his folk music
galvanized a generation. Roger Maris was born here but moved to
Fargo, N.D., at a young age; his family spelled its name M-A-R-A-S
when it lived in the area. Author/attorney Vincent Bugliosi lived
here for 17 years. Two Swedes wanted a way to get mine workers to
work and that begat the Greyhound Bus Line. The founder of Chun
King food products and the president of Pepsico Inc., are from the
area.
</P>
<P>
   But McHale and most of his friends moved in less exotic circles;
their parents either worked in the many Mesabi Range iron ore mines
or had mine-related jobs. Mining is Hibbing's raison d'etre and one
of the city's tourist attractions is the Hull-Rust-Mahoning mine,
the largest open pit mine in the world, 3 1/2 miles long and 1 1/2
miles wide.
</P>
<P>
   The mining company ran the city and Hibbing still is heavily
dependent on the industry. The mining company paid for the
magnificent high school, finished in 1923, which cost an astounding
$3.9 million. The piece de resistance is the auditorium, designed
after the Capitol Theater in New York. Among its highlights are
velvet seats and crystal chandeliers from Belgium, which cost
$15,000 apiece in 1920 and now are insured for $250,000 each. There
are more than 40 backdrops on the stage, each rising 90-plus feet.
There are eight single dressing rooms, modeled after those in
Broadway theaters, and a Barton pipe organ, one of only two in the
country, which pumps out organ music and, thanks to modern
technology, music from every orchestra instrument except the
violin. There's also a $75,000 Steinway grand piano.
</P>
<P>
   McHale's father, Paul, worked in the mines for US Steel for 42
years. One of McHale's high school coaches, Milan Knezovich, lied
about his age and went to work in the mines at the age of 14. It
was the thing to do. Mining and mining-related work made Hibbing a
melting pot of Germans, Finns, Serbs, Croats, Swedes, Italians, and
Irish. It also gave the town and its residents a well-deserved
reputation for hard work, something McHale saw every day at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father didn't expect to go to work and be told that he did
a good job,'' McHale says. ``You didn't expect anyone to pat you on
the back. You just did your job. That's how I approached
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ken Anderson, the former coach at Wisconsin-Eau Claire who
tried to recruit McHale to his then-NAIA school: ``He had a great
work ethic, a typical young man off the range. That's all they
know. That's the way he was brought up and that had to help him
along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
