<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-GRAHAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAME AT HOME IN BRUINS' NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The job is his, for now, sort of, at least until, you
know, maybe there's an official celebration made down at City Hall
Plaza, or better yet, the Guvnah breaks out State House parchment
and declares Official John Grahame Backup Goalie Day in the
Commonwealth of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   By all reads of the tea leaves, Rob Tallas will start in net for
the Bruins Saturday night when they open the 1999-2000 season
against the Carolina Hurricanes. The 24-year-old Grahame, who
backed the Providence Bruins to the AHL Calder Cup championship
last spring, will be at the end of the bench, one giant stretch of
the pads from banking his first minute of NHL action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' said Grahame, now on the eve of finishing his
third Bruins training camp. ``On the same hand, you don't want to
get too excited about it, because you don't know what's to come;
things can change.''
</P>
<P>
   He is in a state of suspended jubilation. Grahame can picture
himself at the FleetCenter, the Providence `P' on his chest
magically converted to a `B', a jubilant hometown crowd embracing a
new season. He can dream about maybe relieving Rob Tallas, or, who
knows, perhaps starting Monday night's game in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   But things can change. He is right here right now, in large
part, because No. 1 netminder Byron Dafoe won't return to work for
$3 million a year. If Dafoe were to sign today, tomorrow, or a
month of Sundays from tomorrow, the food chain above the Boston net
would change dramatically. Grahame would be gobbled up in a second
and returned to Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it kinda tough,'' acknowledged Grahame, who posted
a stellar 37-9-1 record and 2.90 goals-against average last year in
Providence. ``You come in and play well, you do everything that's
asked of you, and if Byron's back, it doesn't matter how well
you've played, you'll get sent down. But, hey, that's the way it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   His dad was a goalie, which means from an early age Grahame
understood netminder pragmatism and the math of the position (one
net equals one goalie equals one job). Ron Grahame was a Bruins
netminder in the '70s, and any Boston fan worth his or her
black-and-gold salt-'n-pepper shakers knows the Bruins swapped the
affable Ron Grahame for the Kings' first pick in the '79 draft.
That pick, No. 8 overall, has had Ray Bourque working the Boston
blue line for 20-plus years.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Grahame is an assistant athletic director at the University
of Denver, and his wife, Charlotte, is the office administrator for
Pierre Lacroix, GM of the Colorado Avalanche. When the Grahames
left Boston following Ron's trade to LA in October '78, John was 3
years old, but he has vivid memories of pulling on his dad's helmet
and gloves, the tools he used in net for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after John Grahame left Lake Superior State to turn pro
with the Bruins in the fall of '97, his mother began working on a
Christmas gift, framing pictures of her husband and son in
near-identical playing poses. Both are wearing Bruins' black and
gold, both are pressed up against the post, father and son joined
in a profession, separated by some 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling how the next few days and weeks will go.
Tallas isn't sure if he's starting, but thinks he is, based on the
vibes head coach Pat Burns has been sending his way. Grahame
assumes Tallas will get the go for Game 1. Most likely, Burns will
go with Tallas, assess the results, factor the future from there.
It could be, Burns said earlier this week, that after 10 games
Tallas and Grahame will have made an equal number of starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big individual, covers a lot of net,'' said Burns, who
sees similarities between the 6-foot-2-inch Grahame and the 6-4
Daren Puppa, dating back to Puppa's more successful days in
Buffalo. ``He seems to be much more calm and cool than when he
first got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that confidence has come from Grahame's work the last
two years with former Boston goalie Ross Brooks, the goalie
consultant in Providence, and Gerry Cheevers, now one of the club's
top scouts and part-time TV color man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that they've worked with my style,'' said
Grahame, ``as they have just with the way I think about the game.
They've given me a lot of pointers, to be thinking about the next
shot and what you might do with it. Both of them have been really
good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A new season is upon the Bruins. Any day now, John Grahame
probably will get to stand in that 4-by-6-foot rectangular cage
and, in his own way, play out his family's circle of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at that sometimes,'' said John, thinking of the framed
pictures that have he and his father in mirror image, ``and it just
gives me a chill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
