<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GOALIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN EVER, STAR GOALIES ARE FRANCHISE SAVIORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great ones have usually had nicknames that connote
impermeability or goose eggs. The China Wall. Tony O. The
Dominator. Mr. Zero.
</P>
<P>
   The goaltender has always been the keystone of his hockey team.
The gardien. The denier, the time-buyer, the last stop before the
red light. ``The goalie has always played the most important
position in hockey,'' says Toronto general manager Ken Dryden, who
backstopped Montreal to six Stanley Cups in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   And in today's parity-swollen National Hockey League, he's more
important than ever _ and he's finally being paid that way. Three
of the NHL's top 11 wage-earners are goalies (Colorado's Patrick
Roy, Buffalo's Dominik Hasek, and Toronto's Curtis Joseph) and all
of them are pulling down more than $6 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goalies are like Pedro,'' says Carolina general manager Jim
Rutherford, whose club rode Arturs Irbe into the playoffs last
season for the first time in seven years. ``That's how important
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   A great goalie can make an expansion team semi-respectable, or
at least hold down the score to single digits. A great goalie can
get a mediocre team a round or two deep into the playoffs. A great
goalie can take a good team to a string of Cups, as Turk Broda did
for Toronto in the '40s, as Jacques Plante did for Montreal in the
'50s, as Johnny Bower did for Toronto in the '60s and as Billy
Smith did for the Islanders and Grant Fuhr did for Edmonton in the
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   And a weak goalie gets hung with a nickname that follows him
into the record books _ Andre `Red Light' Racicot, Howard `Holes'
Lockhart (who played for the Bruins in 1924-25), and Steve `The
Puck Goes Inski' Buzinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goaltender is important by definition, just by the
position he plays,'' says Dryden. ``If you're a forward or a
defenseman, you need to be a star or a player having a star game to
have a big impact on a game. But you can be an average goalie
having an average game and you're going to be important.''
</P>
<P>
   In no other sport does one player have as much control over the
outcome as does the hockey goaltender. The football quarterback
plays only half of the time and needs a decent offensive line to
keep him from being smothered. The baseball pitcher can baffle and
thwart an entire batting order but he only works every fourth day.
</P>
<P>
   The goalie can play 60 minutes a night for 80 nights for 20
years. You can put him between the pipes and build your whole
system around him. ``A great goalie gives you a chance to win every
night,'' says Rutherford, whose Hurricanes pushed the Bruins to six
games in last season's playoffs and meet them in Saturday night's
opener at the FleetCenter. ``Our team knows that with Irbe in there
we can play in a 0-0 game right until the end and still win it with
one shot.''
</P>
<P>
   With the league ballooned to 28 teams (and next year, 30) from
the original six, talent spread widely, and economics keeping
rosters fluid, a top-level goaltender can make up for plenty of
variables.
</P>
<P>
   He can plug a leaky defense like the mythical Dutch boy with his
finger in the dike. He can frustrate star forwards beyond belief.
(Phil Esposito called the rookie Dryden ``a bleeping octopus.'')
And he can allow his forwards to linger in the attacking zone
instead of doubling back to protect him. ``The goalie is that
equalizer,'' says Dryden. ``He allows you wings.''
</P>
<P>
   And if he's having a magical season, a gifted goalie can set his
team soaring to unexpected heights. Olaf Kolzig took Washington
from nowhere to its first Cup final two seasons ago. Irbe, playing
for a San Jose team that had won 11 games the previous year, beat
heavily favored Detroit and pushed Toronto to seven games in 1994.
And Hasek took Buffalo to its first Cup final this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Former Montreal GM) Sam Pollock used to say that the
goaltender is 70 percent of the team,'' says Dryden. ``But even
when you have Hasek as the league's most dominant player and the
MVP, he's still not the highest-paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh wing Jaromir Jagr (at $10.4 million) is. The top six
on the list are all goal scorers _ Anaheim's Paul Kariya,
Colorado's Peter Forsberg, the New York Rangers' Theoren Fleury,
Philadelphia's Eric Lindros, and Florida's Pavel Bure. But goalies
are climbing briskly up the ladder, and they're still paid more on
average than forwards and defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the price for a franchise 'tender who can get you a
champagne-filled Cup has risen steeply in recent years. Roy, who
won two with Montreal and a third with Colorado three years ago,
now commands more than $7 million. ``It's obvious that if you don't
have a premier goaltender, you're not going to make the final,''
says agent Steve Freyer.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven netminders now earn at least $3 million, 19 earn at least
$2 million, and 30 make at least $1 million. And as the prices go
up, the NHL has gone back to the day of the ironman, when one
goaltender got all the work.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the '20s, no team carried more than one. When Lorne
Chabot took a puck in the eye in the 1928 Cup final, the Rangers
had to suit up Lester Patrick, their 44-year-old coach-GM, against
the Montreal Maroons. In 1956-57, when the position was played
without facemasks, three of the league's six goalies played all 70
games. And Glenn ``Mr. Goalie'' Hall played 502 consecutive games
for the Red Wings and Blackhawks between 1955-1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time goalies played every game,'' says Dryden, who
averaged only 50 during his eight years with the Canadiens. ``Then
they worked their way back to two-thirds of the season. Now, it's
probably five-sixths.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, 17 goalies played more than 60 games and four (New
Jersey's Martin Brodeur, Anaheim's Guy Hebert, Boston's Byron
Dafoe, and Toronto's Joseph) logged more than 4,000 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The increased workload has more to do with economics, though,
than it does stamina. ``If you're going to pay your goaltender as
much as you're paying him now, he'd better earn it,'' says
Rutherford. ``He can't just be playing 50 games.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the going rate for a starter these days is at least $2
million, clubs can't afford to have a two-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't afford it to pay two guys that way now with your
salary structure,'' says Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   So most clubs have a predictable ``crease hierarchy'' with a
decided dropoff behind The Man. ``You have a highly-paid top
goalie, a modestly-paid semi-veteran journeyman goalie and you're
developing a younger goalie in the minors,'' says Dryden. ``And you
hope that if your top goalie goes down, your younger goalie isn't
too far from being ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The top netminder usually represents a huge investment, more in
time than in cash. Despite their importance, no goalie has ever
been taken first overall in the NHL draft. That's because few can
have the immediate impact of a Gretzky or an Orr and because
goalies can be maddeningly difficult to identify at the junior
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to evaluate an 18-year-old in anything,''
muses Dryden, ``and it's that much harder with a goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of neophyte 'tenders have made immediate splashes in
the NHL. Roy won the Cup with the Canadiens when he was 20. And Tom
Barrasso went directly from Acton-Boxboro HS to the Sabres in 1983
and is still playing.
</P>
<P>
   But most are in their early 20s before they make their league
debut. ``It took me about three full seasons before I was convinced
I should be in the league,'' says Rutherford, who played 13 seasons
for four clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Tending goal in the NHL requires an extended apprenticeship and
an ability to adapt to who's playing (or isn't playing) in front of
you. There are ``good team'' goalies and ``bad team'' goalies and
they require different skills.
</P>
<P>
   But once they're in the league, whether they're with good teams
or bad, the great ones tend to stick around long enough to get a
gold watch. Sawchuk and Gump Worsley each played for 21 years, Hall
and Plante and Smith for 18. Hasek, Roy, Joseph, and Dallas's Ed
Belfour are all in their 30s and still bedrock players.
</P>
<P>
   Though the NHL has changed dramatically since Georges Vezina
played for Les Habitants in 1917 (and led the league with a 4.0
goals-against average), the essence of the game has not. There is
still a goal at each end of the rink with one man, be he The China
Wall or sieve, who can play 60 minutes for 80 games. The puck still
stops there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
