<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTEBOOK-     10-01 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE FOCUS OF NO. 1 CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when college football seems to be putting its best foot
forward _ with exciting, competitive games between top teams, such
as Georgia Tech-Florida State, Penn State-Miami, and
Florida-Tennessee _ we find ourselves reading about another
academic fraud scandal.
</P>
<P>
   This one involves Tennessee, the defending national champion.
The charges are not new: that tutors either went to class for
football players or took tests and wrote papers for them.
</P>
<P>
   What do you do in such a situation? Shrug and blame the system
of big-time athletics? Roll your eyes and say, ``Who cares? Tell us
about what kind of year Tee Martin and Jamal Lewis are having''? Or
do you get on a soap box and talk about the pond scum that college
athletics has become and argue that it is totally out of control
and should be deemphasized?
</P>
<P>
   There are no simple answers. Depending on your agenda, any of
these reactions may seem approrpiate.
</P>
<P>
   What is disturbing here is the pattern. Miami wins a national
championship in 1991, and the 'Canes soon find themselves on
probation. Alabama wins a national championship in 1992, and the
Tide is hit by probation. Now Tennessee wins the national
championship and the allegations surface, with enough documentation
to make the people in Knoxville nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, some people in Tennessee think this is part of an
ESPN conspiracy _ ESPN.com broke the story _ since many felt ESPN
had led a campaign that kept the Heisman Trophy away from Peyton
Manning two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is nonsense. Reporters follow stories, paper
trails, and tales of misdeed, just as they simply report on Heisman
and national championship races.
</P>
<P>
   The misconception among the public seems to be that the role of
the media is to promote teams and players. Write only positive
stories, and don't look when you see something bad.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. It doesn't work that way. No one in Tennessee complained
about all the positive stuff coverage from Knoxville as the Vols
won a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight works both ways. It shows the good things about a
program and its people, and it illuminates the flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee clearly has made some mistakes. Where this will all
leads is anyone's guess. We could have more dirt dug up, and see
another national champion face the not-so-gentle hammer of an NCAA
investigation and probation.
</P>
<P>
   The one good thing for Tennessee is that the national
championship can't be taken away no matter what happens because the
NCAA doesn't actually award a Division 1-A football championship.
Champions are decided in polls following bowl games, not by an NCAA
championship tournament.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tide of history
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's 35-28 win over Arkansas last week prevented a historic
happening. Had the Hogs won, they would have been only the second
team in history to beat the Tide three straight times in
Tuscaloosa. Only Sewanne, which did it during the period from
1896-1911, had shown such dominance in Alabama . . . Conference USA
is strutting these days. With East Carolina's win over Miami last
week, C-USA had its second upset of a Top 10 team in September. The
other was Cincinnati's upset of Wisconsin two weeks ago . . . East
Carolina is 4-0, its best start since 1976 . . . Penn State is 5-0,
the sixth time the Lions have started that well in the 1990s and
the 14th time they have done it in Joe Paterno's tenure . . . Miami
of Ohio meets Marshall Saturday in a game that features two players
worthy of at least consideration for the Heisman, Miami running
back Travis Prentics and Marshall quarterback Chad Pennington. Not
bad for the Mid-American Conference . . . Alabama, a 17-point
underdog to Florida Saturday, tried to prepare for the noise at
Florida Field by practicing indoors and setting up speakers blaring
crowd noise . . . Division 3 power Mount Union is closing in one of
college football's most enduring records: Oklahoma's 47-game
winning streak from 1953-57. The Purple Raiders have won 45
straight . . . The Atlantic 10 appears to be putting pressure on
Virignia Tech to make its move to the Big East a year sooner than
the Hokies or the Big East expected. Right now, the plans call for
Tech to become a full member of the Big East in July 2001. But the
A-10, which may have its eyes on Delaware, wants to move the
timetable up . . . Movement continues under foot to bring back
Boston Univeristy football, but as long as John Silber is calling
the shots, those possibilities seem slim. It is interesting to
note, however, that the total budget for athlteics at BU is
approximately $2.4 million, while Chancellor Silber, Law School
dean Ronald Cass, and Surgery Department chairman James Becker had
a combined earnings of $1.6 million. Obviously, money is not a
problem at BU with those kind of packages for three people. But the
ongoing problem of Title IX compliance is a concern at BU, which
has a 58 percent-to-42 percent female-to-male enrollment and must
have its sports funded accordingly . . . Lou Holtz is having a
tough first year at South Carolina. Not only are his Gamecocks off
to an 0-4 start, but Holtz's wife, Beth, is dealing with a
recurring case of throat cancer. ``Mrs. Holtz's attitude is better
than mine,'' said Holtz, who took off in the middle of the week to
fly to the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., where doctors are
poondering how to treat the tumors that have appeared in Beth
Holtz's adrenal glands. Major surgery is scheduled, and the burden
on Holtz increases, although the coach said the prognosis for his
wife's recovery is good. On the football side, South Carolina has
lost 14 straight, the longest slide in 1-A football. Added to the
burden was the severe abdominal infection suffered by Holtz's son
Skip, the Gamecocks' offensive coordiantor. It's been a tough fall
in Columbia . . . One of the success stories of the season thus far
is East Carolina. Not only are the Pirates 4-0 after their stunning
27-23 upset of Miami last week, but they are still dealing with the
aftermath of the damage caused by hurricanes Dennis and Floyd,
after which the campus in Greenville, N.C., was closed because of
floods and torrential rains . . . Signs of programs in trouble.
LSU, South Carolina, and Auburn all will play Saturday with
quarterbacks making their first career starts. LSU's Josh Booty
will find the going tough against Georgia on the road, while
Auburn's Jeff Klein will have to deal with Tennessee and South
Carolina's Goodman will face Ole Miss . . . The SEC has six of the
top 20 rushing defenses in college football, led by Ole Miss's No.
6 ranking . . . Syracuse has a QB ``controversy,'' with coach Paul
Pasqualoni playing both Troy Nunes and Madei Williams. When asked
if he was going to ``resolve'' the issue, Pasqualoni said, ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
