<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3357 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ELEVATOR-PITCHES-ART-     10-01 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELEVATOR-PITCHES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTREPRENEURS SHOW OFF `ELEVATOR PITCHES' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Jay Wilkins and Marc Lind each had just 60
seconds _ the time it takes to ride an elevator down a dozen floors
in an office building _ to describe their Internet start-up
companies, the market opportunities for them, and why they will
prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Using a technique dubbed ``elevator pitches'' to win over
potential multimillion-dollar investors, Wilkins scored well with
his quick description of Boatscape.com, an on-line brokerage that
matches buyers and sellers of power boats, sailboats, and other
nautical products.
</P>
<P>
   But Lind got mixed reviews for his pitch for his electronic
commerce firm that caters to a segment of the wholesale auto parts
market, InventoryAuction.com, despite his catchy description of his
venture as ``eBay on steroids.''
</P>
<P>
   Both, however, considered their efforts a success: After they
were finished, each was approached by venture capitalists and other
investors who wanted to learn more.
</P>
<P>
   Their presentations were part of a two-day financial bazaar
called Venture Market East sponsored by Red Herring magazine late
in September. The overflow crowd attracted a range of entrepreneurs
(a few wrote ``seeking $$$'' on their name tags), alongside private
and corporate investors looking for opportunities. Circulating
among them all were accountants, consultants, and lawyers looking
for business.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the pattern at similar show-and-tell sessions where
dreamers on both sides of the balance sheet come together to do
deals, Wilkins, Lind, and 48 other entrepreneurs were picked from
more than 300 Massachusetts- and New York-based start-ups, mostly
Internet and telecommunications companies, by the editors of Red
Herring, a San Francisco-based monthly devoted to high-tech
business trends.
</P>
<P>
   Each company had an opportunity to spend up to 15 minutes
showing and telling their stories in slides and words. But in
addition, Lind and Wilkins were among the seven founders of
fledgling companies who agreed to participate in a separate
presentation forum where each had just 60 seconds to encapsulate
why their company was worth investing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elevator pitches'' represent a generic concept that harkens
back to when struggling sales people had to talk fast and
coherently to sell the boss on an idea or a new product on a ride
to or from an office, and be done before the doors opened. It is
the print version of today's audio sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the leading venture capitalists are receiving
more than a dozen Internet business plans per month, finding the
most promising ones _ the verbal snapshots that convey enough
passion and determination to prompt a later, more formal meeting _
can take more time than many investors are willing to give.
</P>
<P>
   Lind, of InventoryAuction.com, described his company's auto
parts auction service as ``eBay on steroids'' as a way to
demonstrate its role in the business-to-business market niche.
</P>
<P>
   He said 3 to 7 percent of the $100 billion auto parts business
consists of excess, overproduction, or surplus inventories that
often sit on shelves unsold or are later liquidated at a loss.
Using the World Wide Web to match new-car parts manufacturers with
distributors, Lind said InventoryAuction.com was formed in late
1998 to provide free parts listings. It collects fees based on the
completed transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practiced this pitch when I exercised,'' said Lind just
before he gave it as part of his quest for $3 million to $6 million
in funding to further develop his company. While fast-paced, his
spiel still is conversational, nothing like the machine-gun
approach one might imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Diane Hardison, marketing director of the Fairfax
County, Va., Economic Development Authority, Lind's elevator pitch
did not resonate well.
</P>
<P>
   ``After saying his company was the `eBay on steroids,' he just
didn't say why it was unique or why anyone should be head over
heels for this idea,'' she said, adding that Lind's subsequent
15-minute presentation enabled her to better understand the
company.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Lind said his dual approach at the Red Herring
conference won him some investor leads, and he hopes he can launch
the company's Web site early next year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, other investor-listeners considered Wilkins's pitch
for Boatscape.com, which has three competitors, easier to grasp.
``Where boaters click,'' is how he described his auction site for
the recreational boating community, which will charge no more than
$100 to both list and sell a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days before making his elevator pitch on Tuesday,
Wilkins had won a commitment from (at)Ventures, the venture capital
arm of CMGI Inc. of Andover, to provide $5 million in first-round
funding. Still, his 11-person Boston-based company, which Wilkins
has largely financed, needed to reach other investors for
subsequent financing.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, a former Army helicopter pilot and Harvard Business
School graduate who left Boston Consulting Group to launch
Boatscape.com earlier this year, recalled how he practiced his
pitch: ``I walked around the Newton Centre parking lot about a
dozen times with my wife Vanessa timing me and giving me
suggestions about which words to say and not say.''
</P>
<P>
   It must have worked, because several attendees said Wilkins's
determination came across well in his 60-second presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Brenda Chin Hsu, founder and president of
seven-year-old Buyersone.com of Cambridge, received high marks for
quickly explaining how her company serves the small business
community in automating the purchase of office equipment,
technology supplies, and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elevator pitch makes a great way for us to describe our
value proposition in a minute,'' said Hsu. ``For us, having the
investment community enabled us to gain exposure for a second-round
financing and explore some business development opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   evator-pitch sessions were sandwiched among the 15-minute
sessions that often drew standing-room-only crowds to hear about a
panoply of businesses. They range from a Web-based communication
service (MessageBlaster.com) that simultaneously distributes
messages via phone, fax, e-mail, or postal mail, to developers of
sophisticated optical telecommunications equipment companies (Tenor
Networks and Astral Point Communications).
</P>
<P>
   In this year's overheated Internet-oriented investment climate,
it is just a guessing game how many of these companies will be
around in five years. So Red Herring points to its biggest success,
Nexabit Networks Inc. of Marlborough, which participated in last
year's Venture East conference. In late June of this year, Lucent
Technologies Inc. announced it was acquiring Nexabit for $900
million in stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
