<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF AN IRA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are three former chairmen who still keep an
office at BankBoston's downtown headquarters. Now, with Fleet
Financial's takeover of the bank finally a done deal Friday, one is
going. Guess who?
</P>
<P>
   Ira Stepanian hasn't been a gracious loser since he was ousted
in favor of Chad Gifford in 1995. From pointed remarks from the
audience at annual meetings to newspaper opinion columns, Stepanian
has questioned the process that cost him his job and the deal to
sell the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is payback time.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Murray, Fleet's chief executive, and Gifford made the
decision to dump Stepanian. In a letter from the human resources
department, Stepanian was told he would lose his office at 100
Federal St. because the bank has no intention of paying for space
for someone who is not with the program. Two other former chairmen,
Dick Hill and Bill Brown, are staying.
</P>
<P>
   But Stepanian, if he goes, is not going quietly. He suggests
not-so-subtly that if the bank reneges on what he says is an
agreement to provide him an office, ``then all bets are off.'' This
is a man who knows where the bodies are buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't have to meet their obligations, then I don't
have to meet mine,'' Stepanian told me Thursday. He adds: ``I was
at the bank today; I plan to go tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepanian is a guy I like. His is a terrific against-the-odds
story of an Armenian kid from Somerville who rose to run the most
Brahmin of Boston banks. He was a good banker who helped bring
BankBoston back from a close encounter with death in the early '90s
and helped set it on a roll. No one ever questioned his integrity
or that he cared about his bank or his city. He has one incredibly
loyal wife, no small accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   But, simply put, Stepanian has been out of bounds in his
behavior since he was fired. It's not what he's said, but that he's
been waging a campaign against his successor while sitting on the
28th floor of the bank. It's too much to expect the fort commander
to allow you to line up your cannons inside the walls.
</P>
<P>
   This is very, very personal with Stepanian. He was fired, in
part, because he didn't deliver a merger partner to the board. But
he believes Gifford, his second-in-command, was undermining him all
along, arguing against a potential deal with BayBanks and then
going to board members to complain his boss couldn't do a deal. The
board eventually chose Gifford over Stepanian.
</P>
<P>
   How personal is it? Just before Stepanian was fired, the Rev.
Charles Stith, who then ran the Organization for a New Equality,
had decided to honor Stepanian as man of the year. After Stepanian
was fired, everyone decided to go ahead with the tribute. Gifford
was to give the toast at Copley Place. But Stepanian's wife,
Jackie, went to Gifford and told him that if he uttered a word,
she'd walk out. Gifford never got up that night and neither did
Jackie.
</P>
<P>
   Stepanian's severance agreement limits what he can say, but he
has found plenty of ways to make his feelings known. Moving on is
not among his strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Stepanian was nothing short of infuriated by a story I wrote
four years ago that detailed the board decision to fire him. To him
it was an unpardonable ethical lapse by a board member, and he has
never tired of trying to uncover the source. In a highly unusual
move, Stepanian tried to have the board publicly polled to uncover
the leaker at one annual meeting. The bank said no.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the bank sat no better with him. In two Globe
opinion pieces, he questioned the deal's timing and price Gifford
got for shareholders. His nastiest remarks were reserved for
Gifford and his compensation package: ``By accepting a package of
guarantees, which is counter to BankBoston's own philosophy of
being paid for performance, BankBoston's CEO has obtained for
himself what he, in principle, had wanted in earlier talks with
another bank _ a package to retire with.''
</P>
<P>
   Sour grapes or was Stepanian saying what he believed? Or both? I
can't get inside Stepanian's head. Certainly there is nothing wrong
with him saying what he thinks. In fact, it is refreshing,
considering a corporate culture that dictates that a fired
executive should take the money and keep his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   But you do it outside the bank, not inside. A question: Would
Ira have tolerated an Ira firing from within? Would anyone?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
