<HEADLINE>
MFS MANAGER RISES TO THE OCCASION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one thing to replace the manager of a mutual fund that has
gone to the dogs. It's quite another to take the seat of a very
visible manager who has been doing well by his customers.
</P>
<P>
   Maura Shaughnessy found herself in the second category a little
over seven months ago, when she moved beyond the decidedly lower
profile world of utility stock investing to add the management of
MFS Capital Opportunities to her duties. So far, so good and then
some.
</P>
<P>
   MFS Investment Management of Boston had been in a spot in
February, when well-known money managers Chris Felipe and John
Brennan quit to start their own investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   MFS had a roster of strong funds and was pulling in money from
customers at a record pace. Felipe and Brennan were by no means the
entire draw, but they were important players. The challenge: Don't
fall off the track.
</P>
<P>
   The company decided to advance relative unknowns: Shaughnessy to
replace Brennan at MFS Capital Opportunities and Stephen Pesek to
take over the largest of the funds, Felipe's Massachusetts
Investors Growth. Pesek and analyst Irfan Ali took over MFS
Strategic Growth.
</P>
<P>
   Pesek has had his ups and downs, but Massachusetts Investors
Growth has now edged slightly ahead of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index since Feb. 24. MFS Strategic Growth has doubled the S&AMP;P 500,
after a slow start.
</P>
<P>
   But the performance of Shaughnessy's fund is the most
intriguing, nearly tripling the same S&AMP;P 500 index with a return of
9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Her style is a little different, spreading the fund's $2.6
billion among more stocks to dilute a bit of its investment
concentration and avoiding the marketing-timing plays that
sometimes crept into the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Marketwide put options were eliminated. The fund's largest
position, which amounted to about 12 percent of assets, was cut to
half that slice. Another 20 or 30 stocks, ``my bench'' as
Shaughnessy calls them, were added to the roster.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the brokers who sell MFS funds aren't complaining that
they have to sell a new investment story.
</P>
<P>
   ``When and if I start screwing up, we might have that
conversation,'' she said. ``But I don't think they're having a
problem with what we're doing right now, to be a little obnoxious
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   We said she was relatively unknown, not unconfident.
</P>
<P>
   Shaughnessy said her first job out of college, working as a
research assistant at the Federal Reserve in Washington, convinced
her it was a waste of time trying to anticipate when economies and
stock markets would turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a portfolio manager who is supposed to be picking stocks,
why would I spend a second of my day trying tp make some macro
forecast?'' she said. ``I think it's an impossible thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the stocks that have made money for Shaughnessy are
technology names, especially in the telecommunications industry.
She has bought stocks like Motorola Inc., General Instrument Corp.,
Texas Instruments Inc., and Analog Devices Inc. and held on to most
of the wireless communication companies already in the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the industries that don't show up in her fund have
more to do with its strong relative performance. Industries that
have suffered through a terrible 1999 stock market, like health
care and financial services, are largely absent with the exception
of a few insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things you don't own are infinitely more important than
the things you do own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother asking Shaughnessy where she thinks the market is
headed: You'll get a ``who knows'' answer. But she remains upbeat
about the work she actually does, picking stocks and passing on
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about finding relative value in the market and
there's plenty of them right now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Make those lawsuits go away!
</P>
<P>
   How many CEOs have shouted that in frustration? Now Inso Corp.
has actually found someone else to take the heat in a slew of
shareholder suits filed against the Boston software company over
restated financial results. For a price.
</P>
<P>
   Inso said Thursday that an AAA-rated insurance company agreed to
assume all financial responsibility for the defense and ultimate
resolution of the consolidated case.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to take a charge of $14 million to wash its
hands of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   People who sell these polices call them ``loss mitigation
products.'' Everybody else calls it ``burning building insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the name, Boston securities lawyers like Tom Shapiro,
the lead attorney in the Inso case, and Glen DeValerio, a
plaintiffs committee member in the case, say it is a fast-growing
trend among companies that are sued by their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
