<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3364 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      10-01 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS SEE PROGRESS IN KATZENMOYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Andy Katzenmoyer jerseys are selling fast at
the Patriots Pro Shop at Foxboro Stadium. Employees say shirts with
Katzenmoyer's No. 59 are approaching those with Drew Bledsoe's No.
11 in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously there's a vast difference in each players'
accomplishments, but there's something about ``The Big Cat'' that
Patriots fans have grown to like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very flattering,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``It's extremely
flattering. I don't know what to say. It's great when a kid is
wearing your jersey. They sold jerseys at Ohio State, but it was
three numbers and a majority of them were `45' jerseys (the number
Katzenmoyer wore). You'd walk into the stands and see `45' jersies.
It's great to see people get involved. I didn't mind it at all. You
have to be excited and enthusiastic about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer's play has begun to approach the expectations that
came with being a first-round draft pick, though he needs many more
games and much more experience to reach the level he and the
coaching staff expect.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this week's visit to his home state of Ohio, where the
Patriots meet the Cleveland Browns Sunday, will bring out the best
of him. For sure, Katzenmoyer will have friends and family
attending the game, just like the old days at Ohio State in
Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer grew up in Westerville, Ohio, a northern suburb of
Columbus and was a _ sorry Cleveland _ Cincinnati Bengals' fan
because his dad was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no clue why,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``He was always a
Bengal fan so I was. I just remember liking guys like Icky Woods
and James Brooks and Boomer Esiason. I remember the year they went
to the Super Bowl, but I wasn't completely into them like some fans
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer said most football fans in Westerville root for the
Browns. ``It's probably 60-40, maybe now it's 65-35 Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hate the Browns,'' he said. ``I just liked the
Bengals. Nothing against the Browns.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer is pretty excited about seeing the new stadium in
Cleveland and playing in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to see friends and family,'' he said. ``I'm excited that
the people are close by and get to watch me play. I like that. It's
not a thing where it's a big boost for me, but it's just nice for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer wishes he could speed up the learning process. But
he knows that isn't the case. When Tedy Bruschi said a few weeks
ago that Katzenmoyer needed to get up to speed and that he
``couldn't wait for him anymore,'' he did it as a motivational
tool, for Bruschi knows how long it takes to be a top-notch
linebacker in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just Tedy,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``He's always like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer is starting to gain recognition of his work from the
coaching staff. Bo Pelini, a fellow Ohio State grad, has been in
charge of bringing Katzenmoyer along. ``Bo's an all-round good
guy,'' Katzenmoyer said. ``It doesn't matter where he's from. If he
came from Michigan, I'd think he was still the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll speaks of Katzenmoyer as if it's just a matter of
time before his 6-foot-3-inch, 255-pound linebacker will become a
player to be reckoned with. If it's not this year, then some time
some.
</P>
<P>
   ``His last game was his best game,'' said Carroll. ``He was much
more aggressive. He was much more assertive. He had some big hits.
The number of plays he had where he was out of position was very,
very few. I've been waiting for a good basic game, when we weren't
involved in a lot of spread offenses, and this was more of a rock
'em, sock' em game that really suited what we were looking from him
at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had had two games prior to that where he was just fighting
for his life to stay alive and do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer made six tackles against the Giants last Sunday, but
he seemed more active than that. He is not yet the big force in the
middle that Ted Johnson (out for the season) had become, but he
isn't a pushover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really all about the comfort level I feel,'' he said.
``I'm seeing more plays and schemes. The more I see, the better I'm
going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer already recognizes the difference between college
and the pros. ``In college, one week you'll see a team who runs the
option and the next week a team that uses five receivers. Because
there's a limited amount of practice time in college, what you see
is what you're going to get. There's no room to put in new wrinkles
like in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might see a different look at every play in the NFL. It's
making those adjustments on the run all the time that takes getting
used to. Someday, hopefully, it'll all be second nature to me and
I'll be able to recognize formations easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be a lot better,'' Katzenmoyer said. ``I have to keep on
going and keep on improving. I still have a long way to go. It's
going to be a long road all season. I constantly have to work and
work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Katzenmoyer knows he is impatient. ``I want to be there now.
It's going to bother me until I'm there and to be honest, I don't
really think I'll ever be where I expect to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer admits it was difficult to switch from the weak side
linebacker spot he was playing through most of training camp to the
middle spot he had to fill after Johnson tore his right bicep
during an intrasquad game in August.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is familiar with the middle from his college days,
it's entirely different than the weak side spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough transition,'' he said. ``I didn't have time to
think about it, I just had to go out there and learn on the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Katzenmoyer has accepted his role and realizes he might be
playing the weakside spot again next season when Johnson returns to
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm keeping an open mind,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``I'm
aware of what I'm doing wrong and I'm doing the best I can to
adjust. There's always something that you see on film that you can
be better at.''
</P>
<P>
   And no matter how many of his jerseys fans buy, Katzenmoyer
said, ``I won't feel comfortable in this room until I prove more to
myself as a player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
