<HEADLINE>
GOP BREAKS VOW TO PASS SPENDING BUDGET ON TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the federal government rolls into a new budget
year this month, the Republicans who run Congress acknowledge they
have failed to make good on their promise to pass a spending plan
on time.
</P>
<P>
   And that is only one of the problems they are confronting.
</P>
<P>
   The party of tax cuts just watched President Clinton veto its
$792 billion give-back to taxpayers, and it seems to have litle
recourse. The party of less regulation may have to accept new
limits on HMOs, thanks to a revolt by Republican lawmakers. The
party of smaller government is on track to break an earlier promise
to keep federal spending under a predetermined level. It even
appears to be backing away from its traditional opposition to a
higher minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even some friends of the congressional Republicans wonder
why the party in power seems so powerless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally am very disappointed in them, and I know many
other Republicans are also,'' said Diana Furchtgott-Roth, an
economist with the conservative American Enterprise Institute, who
favors lower taxes, lower spending and no minimum wage hike. ``They
call me up and ask me to give money, and I say, `No way.' They are
a deep disappointment to anyone of principle.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, the latest disappointment is the budget process that is
grinding beyond the Oct. 1 start of the new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   One sore point is that Congress appears to be on track to spend
more than it agreed to in the groundbreaking Balanced Budget Act of
1997, which paved the way for the current budget surpluses.
Moreover, House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert had promised that the
budget would be approved on time this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes them look especially farcical and hypocritical,''
said Stephen Moore, a fan of former GOP House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who watches the budget process for the libertarian Cato
Institute. ``The Democrats not getting the budget done on time was
indicative of how corrupt they'd become in power. And now the
Republicans have fallen into the same pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have approved only five of the 13 bills that make up
the federal budget, but Clinton has already vetoed one and
threatened to reject others. The budget battle may continue for
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With the Massachusetts Legislature already three months late in
passing a state budget, the federal showdown broadens the cloud
hanging over programs that rely on government money. Federal
funding for a wide variety of local purposes is still under
negotiation _ money for university research and secondary schools,
to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening salvo in another battle, Senators Edward M.
Kennedy and Thomas Daschle, the Senate majority leader, said they
would introduce a bill to send $9 billion over 10 years to teaching
hospitals. Many of the hospitals claim they are losing money
because of payment cuts that Congress approved two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The money is part of $20 billion that Daschle and Kennedy would
send to a range of health-care providers. Separately, Kennedy said
he is working to give an additional $950 million through 2003 to
the nation's 46 children's hospitals to help cover the cost of
training pediatricians.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years, lawmakers have passed the full budget on
time on only three occasions. Following past practice, Congress has
already passed a stopgap measure to keep the government running for
three weeks while lawmakers continue working. The president signed
that measure Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Republicans suffered a public relations disaster
when Gingrich shut down most government operations rather than
negotiate a budget deal with Clinton. Rather than spark public
anger over another shutdown, many analysts say, the Republicans are
likely to give Clinton much of what he wants. That happened last
year, when Republicans agreed to Clinton's late request for
additional education spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the Republicans will be bested'' by Clinton, said
Alfonse D'Amato, the former Republican senator from New York. ``We
come in with calls to cut education, to cut one popular program
after another. When the economy is booming, people don't want to
hear that you're cutting education. Our doctrinaire rhetoric traps
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, two broad factors are coloring the budget
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   First is the new era of budget surpluses, estimated to reach
$147 billion next year from Social Security payroll taxes and about
$15 billion from other sources. At first blush, the surplus might
seem to make budgeting easier than in the era of budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1997 deal that produced that surplus requires Congress
to keep spending under tight caps. To stick to the caps, Republican
budget-writers have adopted such tactics as reclaiming $3 billion
in welfare money already promised to the states. They have also
designated some expenses for the next census as ``emergency
spending.'' Emergency spending is not counted against the budget
caps.
</P>
<P>
   A second factor dominating the budget talks is a familiar one:
Both sides are angling for a sound-bite to use during the next
campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans not only say they will stick to the budget caps, but
they also make a point of saying that all money raised by Social
Security taxes will be reserved only for the national retirement
program. House Republicans, in fact, have prepared television
commercials protesting a Democratic ``raid'' on the Social Security
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are also positioning themselves as the protectors of
Social Security, arguing that the Republicans' tax cut bill that
Clinton vetoed would have stripped Social Security of required
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really trying to position themselves for the campaign
cycle rather than for substance. Both sides,'' said Patrick Burns,
communications director for the National Council of Senior
Citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
