<HEADLINE>
FILINGS SAY BROKER BILKED CLIENTS OF $6 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the dead of night on Aug. 17, 1998, John Macoul, a
trial lawyer in Salem, N.H., was startled awake by his bedside
phone. Struggling out of a deep sleep, he didn't recognize at first
the voice of his brother-in-law, Donald Martineau, a veteran broker
at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need you,'' the voice whispered tensely. ``Everything's
coming apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Unnerved, Macoul went to his office shortly after dawn the next
morning as his brother-in-law requested. On the stoop outside the
door was a plastic garbage bag filled with financial documents and
a note that read, ``I have made some very serious mistakes, and the
moment of truth is almost here.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, police found Martineau on a deserted New Hampshire
roadside slumped unconscious over the steering wheel of his crashed
Oldsmobile Cutlass. An empty bottle of Jack Daniel's and a loaded
.25-caliber handgun were on the seat next to him, according to
police reports. The broker, roused momentarily by the officers,
mumbled groggily, ``Shoot me. Just shoot me.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than a year later, Merrill Lynch says that the
broker over the course of nearly a decade systematically bilked $6
million from clients who included his closest friends and family.
Many of them are now lining up in court in desperate attempts to
recover their money _ which Martineau claims no longer to have. And
Merrill Lynch, stuck with paying back some of the clients, is left
to explain how one of its own brokers could have evaded detection
for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some clients now question whether the firm ignored
warning signs that something was amiss. Merrill Lynch officials
said the firm did nothing wrong, that Martineau's scam involved
fake investments unrelated to the firm and that he failed to
disclose the investments to the firm, as company policy and federal
rules require. But industry experts say brokerages like Merrill
Lynch should make every effort to know about all investment
activities of their brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the responsibility of the supervisor to know what's going
on with each account,'' said Norman Padgett of Florida-based NL
Padgett Consultants, which advises brokerages. ``A firm has to have
procedures in place that could reasonably be expected to catch that
kind of violation, even when it's going on outside the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Martineau, 56, hasn't been charged with any crimes, but the US
Securities and Exchange Commission and federal prosecutors are
conducting investigations that are ``expected to culminate in a
criminal prosecution,'' according to court documents filed in
connection with a civil lawsuit against the broker.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to live with his wife in their large Colonial home
in an upscale section of Tewksbury, but he has claimed in court
papers that he is otherwise broke. He has filed for personal
bankruptcy protection and applied for Social Security benefits,
according to court filings.
</P>
<P>
   Martineau declined to be interviewed. But the story that emerges
from court filings, former clients, and the broker's own notes is a
tale of greed and desperation in which Martineau, a former history
professor, baldly deceived those around him, apparently to feed a
secret dream of success and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he lived a double life,'' said Macoul, the
brother-in-law, who says Martineau took $245,000 that he invested
through the broker. ``This was the guy I spent holidays with. He's
the godfather of my child. When I found out I was one of the
victims, it was surreal. It was like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Martineau became an investment adviser after starting his career
teaching history at Boston College and the University of Louisville
in Kentucky, family members said. He made a comfortable living but
``always liked nice things,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   He moved back to his home state of Massachusetts and joined
Merrill Lynch in 1979. For eight years, he built a stable of
customers. His investment advice, said former clients, had been
reliable. In terms of the income he generated through commissions,
he performed well but ``certainly wasn't one of our stars,'' said
Bill Halldin, a Merrill Lynch spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, in 1987, ``all this started,'' according to a
handwritten note Martineau addressed to family and friends. The
note contained references to investment losses and a trading
account he maintained in his wife's name at a California investment
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lost a lot of money trying to make money to get me out
of investment losses I couldn't handle,'' the note reads. ``I lost
a lot of money in options and continued like a fool to try and win
it back.'' Options are a risky and complex form of investing,
usually not undertaken by individuals.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Martineau began advising a few of his clients to
invest heavily in a venture he controlled called D &AMP; D Real Estate,
which he claimed made short-term loans to options traders and
guaranteed an annual return of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One such client, Hans G. Viezens of Woburn, invested the bulk of
his life savings after Martineau invited Viezens to his Merrill
Lynch office in downtown Boston, according to a lawsuit Viezens
filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martineau described an `offer' that Martineau said he made
only to `his most trusted clients,' '' the lawsuit says. Viezens
invested $250,000 initially and then made several additional
investments for a total of $800,000. He got some of that money back
when he requested funds from the account. But the rest is gone, he
claims in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   D &AMP; D Real Estate, whose address is a leased post office box in
North Andover, turned out to be ``nothing more than a pyramid
scheme,'' the lawsuit says. A Merrill Lynch manager explained to
Viezens after the losses had been discovered and the firm conducted
its own investigation that D &AMP; D Real Estate never invested any
money. Instead, Martineau used the cash to pay ``personal
obligations,'' the suit claims the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of Martineau's many clients made serious, ongoing
investments in D &AMP; D Real Estate, but those who did poured hundreds
of thousands of dollars into the scheme believing they were getting
high rates of return, Merrill Lynch officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When a particular client's investments came due, Martineau
apparently solicited additional investments from others in order to
come up with the cash, the lawsuits charge. In some cases,
Martineau told investors not to talk to anyone at Merrill Lynch
about the venture, which may have been a way to avoid arousing
suspicions within the firm, Merrill Lynch officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know about it, and there is no way we could have
known about it,'' Halldin said.
</P>
<P>
   That scheme resulted in the bulk of Martineau's client losses,
Merrill Lynch officials said. But as the years went on, his
deceptions became bolder. In a few cases, he told investors he was
putting their money into Merrill Lynch-backed investments when in
fact he was transferring the money to an account he controlled,
according to the records he left with his brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Martineau said in his notes that he forged some clients'
signatures on wire transfer documents. In other cases, he said he
typed up documents that led his clients to believe he was moving
money into safe investments and then transferred the signature to a
document authorizing him to put the money in an account he
controlled. Merrill Lynch officials said those instances were rare.
</P>
<P>
   In Macoul's case, the money was simply gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just stunned,'' Macoul said. ``Here I am, his
brother-in-law. I don't even know what to think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Martineau was often seen making long calls from a pay
phone in the lobby of Merrill Lynch's downtown offices, said Tim
Cagle, a Methuen attorney investigating the incidents for Macoul,
who says he is planning to sue Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The normally mild-mannered Martineau seemed to become especially
animated during those conversations. ``We believe Mr. Martineau was
making very risky personal trades on those pay phones and that he
had a very serious problem with this,'' Cagle said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Martineau appeared to become increasingly obsessed
with trading and that Merrill Lynch turned a blind eye to symptoms
that should have been obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have evidence that suggests there was a serious problem and
that there were enough signs and red flags that they should have
known something was going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill Lynch officials said there is no way for a brokerage
firm to monitor all of a broker's outside activities.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the firm said it had no inkling until Martineau's lawyer
appeared at Merrill Lynch's offices shortly after the broker was
found in his wrecked car. After investigating the ``nightmare'' of
a tale that the lawyer detailed of Martineau's activities, the firm
said, it began its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has returned money to clients who had money stolen
or who believed their money was in a Merrill Lynch-backed
investment, Halldin said, but he declined to disclose a dollar
amount. The firm has declined to settle with clients who invested
in Martineau's D &AMP; D Real Estate venture knowing it was not
sanctioned by Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   In his note to family and friends, Martineau took full
responsibility for the millions of dollars in losses. ``Please
don't hold this against Merrill Lynch,'' he wrote. ``They are good.
I was the problem. Desperate people do desperate things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
