<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-01 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSTOPPABLE MOVES POSITION MCHALE IN THE HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was Lou Gehrig to Larry Bird's Babe Ruth, and as a result
people never fully grasped just how utterly unique and unstoppable
a basketball player Kevin McHale really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best I've ever seen in the pro game with his back to the
basket, for his high rate of efficiency and the fact that he never
gave you the same look due to his diversification of moves,''
declares Hubie Brown, who once had to endure an opening two games
of a playoff series (the 1984 Eastern Conference finals) in which
McHale shot 23 for 28 from the floor against Hubie's Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   There were people who could do a passable defensive job against
Bird. There was, meanwhile, no forward in the world who could
regularly stop McHale, who enters the Basketball Hall of Fame
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rival coaches such as Brown, Chuck Daly, and Pat Riley often
spent more pregame time fretting over McHale than they did Bird,
because there were very few physical beings who had even a remote
chance of matching up with McHale, owner of one of the world's 10
strangest bodies. You could, in theory, put quicker people on Bird
and stronger people on Bird, and their physical superiority might
give them an edge. This was not possible with McHale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just played off what you were trying to take away,''
explains Brown. ``Players today don't have well-rounded games. They
can't do this.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way to stop McHale was to deny him the ball, but few
could do that, for 50 percent of his low-post work was done before
he ever received the ball. He may have looked scrawny, but he did
have a raw-boned strength, and he combined it with an awareness of
how to use body angles, those ludicrously long arms, good hands,
and a dogged determination to get where he wanted to go. And once
he did establish his preferred spot on the low box, the odds were
way above average that the Celtics were going to come away with a
point or 2.
</P>
<P>
   No great player is ever ultimately about the numbers, but in
rare cases a man's numbers are so far above the norm that it does
him an injustice to ignore them. So here a few:
</P>
<P>
   --He is the only man in the history of the NBA to have had a
season in which he shot 60 percent from the floor and 80 percent
from the line (1986-87). Had he made just one more free throw the
following season, he would have done it again.
</P>
<P>
   --He shot over 50 percent from the floor in 12 of his 13
seasons, missing only in his final year, when his most significant
achievement was dragging his battered body onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   --In the four-season period from 1984-85 through 1987-88, he
shot 59 percent from the floor in 365 combined regular-season and
playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   --In his five prime seasons, 1983-84 through 1987-88, he shot
better than 50 percent from the floor (that doesn't even count the
games in which he shot (itals)exactly(unials) 50 percent) in 70
percent of the combined total of 470 regular-season and playoff
games.
</P>
<P>
   Included in these totals were a few dunks and tips, but not too
many. The preponderance of his 8,034 lifetime baskets were jump
hooks, turnarounds, up-and-under moves, and snaking baseline
reverse drives that, in many cases, could not have been scored by
any other player in the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was 7-feet tall with a great angle release and he was
totally unstoppable,'' marvels Brown.
</P>
<P>
   This unique offensive ability alone would have gotten him to the
Hall of Fame. But there was so much more to his game. The people
who coached him and played with him will always appreciate the fact
that he was as important to his team when it didn't have the
basketball as when it did.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few better shot blockers, but none other than
McHale whose calling card was ambidexterity. The average
righthanded player blocks 100 percent of his shots righthanded. The
average lefthanded player blocks 100 percent of his shots
lefthanded. No amount of teaching or coaxing can change this
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   McHale represented his own percentile. On the occasion of his
very first Celtics scrimmage, when Bill Fitch thought he would be
teaching the brash rookie a lesson by making him go directly from a
lengthy plane trip (Milan to Boston) to the Hellenic College floor,
McHale demonstrated that he was different from all other players.
When a righthanded player shot, he stuck up his left hand to flick
it away. If someone tried a lefthanded shot, he knocked it away
with his right. It all seemed perfectly natural.
</P>
<P>
   McHale did something else 99.9 percent of all big men can never
do. Just about every other big guy is incapable of making a play
without bouncing the ball. Throw a pass, and the guy puts it on the
floor (where it can be appropriated by a quick-handed foe) before
shooting. Should he grab an offensive rebound, he goes boom to the
floor and the ball has a great chance of being stolen.
</P>
<P>
   McHale never put the ball on the floor when it wasn't necessary.
N-e-v-e-r. As a result, he converted more tippy-toe putbacks than
the rest of the NBA put together, and we're talking about
(itals)everyone(unitals), since 1946. That may sound like a little
thing, but it represented a surprising number of baskets that could
not have been scored by anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   McHale's defensive value far transcended blocked or altered
shots. He was the only 7-footer alive who could regularly guard the
great small forwards of the day. As such, he was the key to the
Boston frontcourt, because he allowed the much slower Bird to take
the weakest member of the other team's front line and thus free
Larry to be a rover, where he was extraordinarily dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   When McHale was on a roll, you were seriously stunned when he
missed. Consider a four-game run of 38 for 50 in 1984; a three-game
run of 30 of 38 in '86; a two-game run of 23 for 27 in '86; a
four-game run of 48 for 66 in '87; a three-game run of 43 for 56 in
'87; a two-game run of 29 for 36 in '87; and a three-game run of 33
for 47 in '88. These numbers are so laughably absurd that we might
as well go ahead and say we will never see anything like them
again.
</P>
<P>
   But what really matters is that all McHale really wanted to do
was win. ``To me,'' says Brown, ``the greatness of Kevin McHale is
not just his athletic ability but the way he accepted that
sixth-man role early in his career. As we all know, thousands of
guys have come into this game with a selfish attitude, unable to
see the big picture. He knew he was going to get his 32-34 minutes
a game and that he would be out there in prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin could never be Larry, but the converse was equally true.
In his prime, the surest way for any NBA team to score on any given
possession was for a Boston Celtic to throw the ball to Kevin
McHale on the low box. The Hall of Fame goes up a significant notch
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
