<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Oct. 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokaimura) _ Developments: The radiation leak has
been stopped; it has prompted a debate over the future of nuclear
power in Japan. Many Japanese are angry over the way the government
handled the incident. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   With graphc and map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE-MEASURE (Undated) _ A rad is not a rem or a Sievert:
an explanation for readers of the measures of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE (Seoul) _ Interviews with relatives of victims of
the reported massacre of Korean civilians by U.S. troops in the
Korean War. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Russia continues attacks on Chechnya;
the prime minister says the Kremlin no longer recognizes the
legitimacy of Chechnya's president.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade) _ Political developments as
tensions rise between anti-Milosevic demonstrators and the police.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR (Dili, East Timor) _ Peacekeepers take more areas; more
militia-peacekeeper tensions. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran) _ Ayatollah Khameini, the hard-line
supreme leader, calls for unity and an end to conflict between
conservative and reformist factions. He praises the reformist
president, Mohammad Khatami, and judicial authorities for their
handling of a scandal over a satirical student play deemed to have
insulted a holy Shiite figure. The play has outraged Iran's
religious leadership. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MILITARY (Beijing) _ China displays new weapons at its
50th anniversary parade, but the military is feeling even more
backward and worried after seeing U.S. war technology in Kosovo. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ With the government running on
borrowed time, developments on the spending bills. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-VOICES (Washington) _ Following the Census report on
income and poverty, we talk to people who might feel left behind as
a million others rise above the poverty level. And even for the
laoup, are things any better? By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
