<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-OUTLOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS: HOLDING OUT HOPE FOR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Another season is upon us and the Bruins head into the
new year absent their No. 1 goaltender, who was last year's most
valuable player, because of an acrimonious contract dispute.
Independent of that, they have improved on defense, with the young
players having another year of experience and some others having a
bit more seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   At forward, the club has four lines that are capable of
producing offense. In an era of expansion, where depth is not only
a rarity but practically unheard of, Boston seems in decent shape.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a breakdown of what can be expected: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORWARDS _ Centers Jason Allison and Joe Thornton will be the
focal points of the attack. Allison is on the brink of stardom, and
Thornton proved last spring that he can handle a great deal of
responsibility. With wings Steve Heinze, Anson Carter, Sergei
Samsonov, and new addition Dave Andreychuk on the top two lines,
the Bruins will be able to compete with any other team in the NHL.
A third line of Mikko Eloranta and mainstays P.J. Axelsson and Rob
DiMaio will give the team solidity, and fourth-line prospects Shawn
Bates, Landon Wilson, Ken Belanger, and Cameron Mann give coach Pat
Burns options he didn't have last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're really solid,'' said Allison, who led the team
in scoring with 76 points last year. ``If you look down the list,
we have (several) 20-goal scorers. I'm counting Joe because he's
going to get 20 this year; we have (four) who already have and one
who probably should. Not too many teams have that. We're definitely
all capable of getting between 20-40. Forty is a lot, but if
someone gets hot and picks their game up, they're capable.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison, who arrived in Boston after a late-season trade in
March 1997, even said he thought this team is the best Bruins club
he's ever played on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're by far the best we've been in the three years
I've been here,'' he said. ``It depends on how everyone plays. If
everyone plays to the top of their game, we have a lot of
firepower. We have to play defensive, but we also have to play with
confidence and be offensive when we get our opportunities.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE _ The situation behind the blue line is very promising.
Ray Bourque, coming off a year when he was a candidate for the
Norris Trophy as the league's top defenseman, is back for his 21st
season. The other members of the top six are Kyle McLaren, Hal
Gill, Don Sweeney, Darren Van Impe, and Mattias Timander. Others in
the mix are Brandon Smith and young prospects Jonathan Girard and
Nick Boynton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them,'' said McLaren of the assembled blue-liners. ``I
really do. We've got a few guys back from last year, four or five
solid guys who played a lot of minutes. With the young guys coming
up, it's going to really help us. I like our defense tremendously.
I think we have one of the best defenses around. We don't get a lot
of points but we play solid and we play well as a unit, and I think
that's a big (tribute) to (assistant coach Jacques Laperriere).
There's only one superstar out there and that's Raymond. So, all of
us have to bust our butts to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's an area in which the team can improve, it's reducing
the number of shots against even if many of them came from the
periphery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we gave up a lot of shots last year,'' said McLaren.
``I was remembering some of the shots and a lot of them were
outside the blue line and from the red line. If a goaltender can't
stop those, he shouldn't be in the league. Still, we've got to play
stronger as a unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The one question lurking is whether the defensemen will feel
obligated to do anything differently with Rob Tallas between the
pipes instead of Byron Dafoe, who remains unsigned. McLaren said it
isn't really an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out and play the same way in front of anybody who's back
there unless it's a guy brought up from (the East Coast League) or
a junior guy,'' said McLaren. ``He's been here enough; we've played
in front of him. He's played well. There are some games where we're
not having a good night or he's not having a good night. We have to
complement each other. Sure, we can play tighter in front of him
and get the job done better.''
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, McLaren said they're not putting undue
pressure on Tallas to fill Dafoe's substantial skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a talented goaltender but he's not Byron Dafoe,'' he
said. ``People have to realize that. The expectation for him to be
Byron is not going to be there. Just like I'm not going to be
another Ray Bourque. He's going to be Robbie Tallas, and he's an
excellent goaltender. It's going to be a challenge; it's going to
be fun to watch. He's jumping out of his net and moving the puck
well. It helps our confidence a lot and helps his.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOALIES _ Tallas has earned a shot and John Grahame earned his
stripes last year when he led Providence to the Calder Cup
championship. However, it's still a crap shoot. Neither has the
credentials of Dafoe. Whether they can earn them or not remains to
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard because the players are down, reading everything
about Byron and seeing all the frustration and they're thinking,
`Wow, we're not getting Byron back,' when maybe earlier there was a
little bit of hope,'' said Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   As for the coach, Burns said he's taking the high road and is
filled with optimism, cautious as that might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident,'' said Burns, ``but how it's going to go, I
don't know until we play some games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
