<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-OLYMPICS-IOC-1002-COX     10-01 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-IOC-1002-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC PRESIDENT, MEMBERS MAY TESTIFY BEFORE HOUSE PANEL ON BIDDING
PROCESS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece - The International Olympic Committee is weighing
the merits of an appearance by President Juan Antonio Samaranch
before a U.S. congressional committee investigating allegations of
excessive gift giving during Atlanta's campaign for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC executive board, starting weekend meetings in the host
city of the 2004 Games, discussed the matter briefly Friday but had
not reached a conclusion, said Franklin Servan-Schreiber, the
committee's spokesman. The touchy subject is certain to come again
during the meetings here.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting behind closed doors, the executive board officially
received a written report from the IOC's ethics commission
indicating that the panel is evaluating allegations that Atlanta
lobbyists violated bidding rules by showering IOC members with
gifts and favors during the campaign to host the Centennial Games.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics commission review of the Atlanta report is expected
to be completed before the IOC holds a special session in December
to consider sweeping reforms intended to end criticism that the
bidding process is hopelessly corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   The report, written by former U.S. Attorney General Griffin
Bell, was based on documents provided to Congress by Atlanta
Olympics officials. Bell is now with the Atlanta law firm of King &AMP;
Spalding, which provided legal services to Atlanta Olympics
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Upton, the Michigan Republican leading the charge in
the House, has expressed shock at the report's revelations. Upton
has asked Samaranch to appear before his House Commerce Committee's
subcommittee on oversight and investigations later this month.
</P>
<P>
   IOC members close to Samaranch have advised him not to make the
appearance, which almost certainly would cause the 79-year-old
president considerable embarrassment. The former diplomat, who has
been IOC president since 1980, is not used to the kind of rigorous
questioning he can expect in a hostile Congressional hearing.
Samaranch, who is generally treated not unlike a head of state,
declined an invitation to appear before a Senate committee last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   However, IOC officials worry that Upton's committee may issue
subpoenas requiring them to appear before the House panel.
</P>
<P>
   As it wrestles with its problems in Washington, the IOC is
reconsidering plans to come to the United States for February
meetings in Salt Lake City, the host city for the 2002 Winter
Games, and Colorado Springs, Colo., the home of the U.S. Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Servan-Schreiber acknowledged the meetings could be delayed,
postponed or canceled because of schedule conflicts. However, he
said he was unaware of any connection between discussions about the
meetings and the prospect that IOC members, including Samaranch,
could be served subpoenas if they enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks bad,'' he said. ``But there is no link.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has not traveled to the United States since the Salt
Lake City scandal surfaced about a year ago. He and other IOC
members are subject to possible questioning by the FBI in
connection with the federal law-enforcement agency's Salt Lake
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake Tribune reported Friday that a letter faxed to
U.S. Olympic Committee officials this week said the meeting in Salt
Lake City had been canceled because of a scheduling conflict.
Servan-Schreiber denied that and said that, for now, both meetings
are still on.
</P>
<P>
   Upton wants to question Samaranch about how the IOC selects
cities to host the Olympics. Salt Lake City has admitted to using
expensive gifts, cash and offers of scholarships to influence IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
