<HEADER>
A3378 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WOMEN-HANDIWORK-ART-B     10-01 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-HANDIWORK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDEST KNITTING AND NEEDLEWORK RETAILER SUCCUMBS TO CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It used to be a staple of home economics class, the
quintessential sort of ``women's work,'' which is why Mariama
White-Hammond, 20, gets funny looks when she pulls out her
cross-stitch in dorm rooms, airports, and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends say she looks like a grandmother, a label she
doesn't especially mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much is lost,'' she said, ``in not doing the things that our
grandmothers did.''
</P>
<P>
   But even young devotees like White-Hammond _ a tall,
smartlydressed Stanford University student who doesn't exactly fit
the ``grandma'' mold _ concede that needlepoint, cross-stitch, and
knitting aren't the staples they used to be. Most women are too
busy, they say, or too self-conscious about seeming old-fashioned
or domestic. They are more likely to buy a hand-knit sweater than
to make one.
</P>
<P>
   So it's sad, but not shocking, they say, to hear that the
nation's oldest knitting and needlework retailer is closing. The
fiber arts department at the Women's Educational and Industrial
Union folded Friday (Oct. 1), a casualty of the changing retail
market, changing demands, changing lives.
</P>
<P>
   The department dates back to 1877, the year The Shop at the
Union was founded to help women sell their handiwork. For years,
the craft and gift store sold needles, canvases, threads and yarn,
and hired employees skilled enough to coach their customers out of
a stitch gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the last of that merchandise was piled into
clearance bins and pushed into one cramped corner of the store. On
a recent afternoon, a 71-year-old Cape Cod resident looked at the
spread and shook her head. ``Typical,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has been knitting since the age of 12, buying wool at the
Union for 50 years, said the woman, whowould give only her first
name, Evelyn. But she can sense the changing times, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't exactly see us as a culture of knit-by-the-fire.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some knitting and needlework specialists report a
renewed interest in the crafts. The 10,000-member Knitting Guild of
America is growing, and gaining more young, professional women,
founder Carol Wigginton said.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered through the city, the region, and the country are
small groups of women _ and a few men _ who have taken up sewing of
different sorts. Gabrielle Marroig, 32, and Colleen Mulcahy, 26,
said a group of women at their office, most of them pregnant,
recently started a knitting circle. Now, they're hooked and trying
to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister made fun of me until I made her a chenille scarf,''
Mulcahy said. ``And now, she wants me to teach her how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you pick it up only occasionally, a single scarf or
sweater can take months to complete, Marroig and Mulcahy said as
they rifled through the Union's last skeins of yarn. Wigginton,
too, said that knitting takes more money and time than every woman
has.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can spend $500 in yarn for a sweater,'' she said. ``And
then you have to knit the darned thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That time crunch has clearly affected Union sales, said Laurie
Tuttle, the store's communications director. Some customers have
given up their crafts. Others have started to buy supplies from
mail-order catalogs or the Internet. Four years ago, the department
sold $215,000 worth of goods. Last year, sales were down to
$150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders tried to salvage the department with new marketing
techniques, special merchandise, and classes, said Mary Lassen,
executive director of the Union. Still, sales continued to falter,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   And because store proceeds support social programs, from career
centers to homes for battered women, the Union can't afford to
subsidize a department for tradition's sake, Lassen said. Her
organization has survived, she said, by ``being willing to innovate
and be on the cutting edge, and being willing to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, letting go has itself become a Union tradition. In the
1940s, the Union turned over its school lunch program, the first in
the nation, to Boston public schools. In the 1980s, in another
decision driven by economics, the Union closed the cafe where it
used to serve daily tea.
</P>
<P>
   Like the changes that preceded it, this week's closing is
emotional, Union trustee Barbara Mohrman said. She discovered the
union in the mid-1970s, she said, when her roommate dragged her to
a needlepoint class. But she hasn't had time to ply her craft in
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been guilty of that, along with everybody else,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
