<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKO-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     10-01 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVES, PERSPECTIVE   WON'T BE DUPLICATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clues were there, long before he signed his first contract.
If ``The Kevin McHale Story'' were a feature-length film, no one
would be silly enough to label it a mystery. The early evidence was
unmistakable: the kid was a bit unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours after the Celtics drafted him, McHale sat casually
in Red Auerbach's office, as if it were the family den. He talked
of an upcoming fishing trip to Red Sand Lake in Canada. He said his
father was probably at home in the family kitchen, dancing an Irish
jig with the news that the Celtics drafted his son. He even
congratulated Red on making the trade with Golden State that also
brought Robert Parish to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that McHale had wit and perspective at a young age.
Even if you are not a Celtics fan, you should steal one of those
attributes from him on his being inducted into the Hall of Fame in
Springfield, Mass. Steal his perspective. You'll enjoy the ceremony
more that way because you will realize that, barring an NBA
revolution, you'll never see a player like McHale again. Will you
see better players? Yes. But you probably won't see another McHale
``type.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows this is the era of instant judgment and neat
labels, from business to sports. But if you put McHale's career on
a musical staff, it would stun you with its rapid chord
progressions. We like to know immediately if an athlete is an
average player, franchise player, or Hall of Famer. McHale
increased his scoring average in seven consecutive seasons, going
from an average player, to a very good one, to a co-franchise one,
to a Hall of Fame one.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see that again, especially from a player taken with
the third pick in the draft as McHale was. McHale developed. The
theory now is that if you are taken third, you had better give
previews of what your future holds. And do it fast. Ask your
typical pro coach about development and he'll say, ``Send it
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   But a rising scoring average is not the only McHale quirk. You
have heard plenty about his odd body _ 6 feet 10 inches, 225
pounds, exceedingly long vines for arms, and a barrel chest. At
times he looked like a Goth in basketball shorts. The body, alone,
did not make him rare. It was the mentality that went with it.
</P>
<P>
   That is, McHale was not a '90s-type of low-post man. He didn't
want to be a 6-10 guard. His chamber was somewhere between 5 and 10
feet away from the hoop. He gave clinics in there to anyone trying
to guard him. That area was like his own theater. When he was
fouled, he would often go to the baseline where a ballboy would
throw him a towel so he could wipe his hands and face. It was part
of the routine. That strange body allowed him to keep the ball
centimeters out of a frustrated opponent's reach at all times.
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar had the toughest shot to block. McHale was
right after him.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see that again. Because he wasn't the most talented
dribbler, McHale spent most of his time mastering moves around the
basket rather than the perimeter. He was an angles man. If you have
ever wondered how a great pool player would play basketball, you
already know. McHale could work the side pocket. He could work the
corner pocket. He could make the ball skip. Some of his shots were,
simply, ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when a hawkish 6-10 player tells you that he is simply
interested in hanging out in the post, the tendency is to respond,
``You do?'' (Warning to all NBA teams outside of Minnesota: McHale
sharing his low-post craftiness with the talented Kevin Garnett
should frighten all of you.)
</P>
<P>
   The most important reason to be a Prospective Thief tonight?
Think of what could have been. You may do this with your spouse,
girlfriend, or boyfriend. Example: ``Honey, if I had taken that job
in Chicago, do you realize we probably wouldn't have met?'' It's a
similar story with McHale.
</P>
<P>
   Boston had the first and 13th picks in the 1980 draft and
initially talked about drafting center Joe Barry Carroll first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get Carroll and the number 13, to go along with what
we've got, we'll still be a formidable ball club,'' Celtics coach
Bill Fitch said before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Formidable in intelligence maybe (Carroll is a stock market
whiz), but not in terms of ability. Another draft possibility was
Louisville guard Darrell ``Dr. Dunkenstein'' Griffith, who said he
wanted to play with the Celtics. A couple of nights before the
draft, Fitch and assistant coach Jimmie Rodgers met in Fitch's
apartment and continued to debate who was better: McHale or
Carroll. They decided on McHale, traded the No. 1 pick to Golden
State for the third pick and some guy named Robert Parish, and
sweated it out when Utah, picking second, paused dramatically
before calling Griffith's name on draft day.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years after that draft, there will be stories about the
comedic McHale. There will be stories about the way he defended and
the way he never missed from close range. They will be good
stories, ones that will make you laugh and reminisce.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are in Springfield when the tales are being told,
make sure you snap a photo of McHale as you're laughing. And when
you get them developed, request doubles. They will be the only
reasonable McHale duplications you will ever see.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      10-01 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREED LIVES OUT THE EVERYKID DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Creed's music was just called ``Everyguy Rock'' by Rolling
Stone. That suggests the media haven't been able to create any
overweening hype or controversy on the Florida band. And that's
fine with its members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a good thing that the media didn't jump on us
and hype us up,'' says Creed drummer Scott Phillips. ``We had to
crawl our way along and didn't let the hype go to our heads. We
didn't get blown up as being four hunks or four sharp dressers,
that's for sure. Our success was definitely built on the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Creed's debut disc, ``My Own Prison,'' was the No. 1-selling
hard rock album last year and has moved 4 million copies. It also
yielded four hit singles, including the title track and ``What's
This Life For.''
</P>
<P>
   Creed is back with a new album, ``Human Clay,'' and a tour with
Our Lady Peace and Oleander. The new album may not drive away any
of the Pearl Jam sound-alike charges the group has received but
shouldn't slow sales momentum, either. The album rocks, and in
today's poseur climate, that's saying something.
</P>
<P>
   It also finds singer/lyricist Scott Stapp baring his heart
again, though in a different way. ``A lot of tunes on the new album
are less introspective about Scott's personal life than on the
first album. They're more about the world, which Scott has been
looking at since the birth of his son,'' says Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a new song, ``With Arms Wide Open,'' was written from
the perspective of impending fatherhood. No wonder this band has an
``Everyguy'' tag. The group sings about real concerns for real
people.
</P>
<P>
   Creed has sometimes been misconstrued as a Christian band, since
lyricist Stapp grew up with strict Christian parents who wouldn't
let him listen to rock 'n' roll, unless it was by the spiritually
charged (and hence, approved) U2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we're a fairly spiritual band but certainly not a
Christian band,'' says Phillips, adding that some of the group's
songs question doctrinaire beliefs. And how many Christian bands
would have first named themselves Naked Toddler, as Creed did?
</P>
<P>
   Creed was hatched four years ago by four Tallahassee friends
(and Florida State students) from different musical backgrounds.
Phillips loved R &AMP; B. Stapp grew up with gospel. Bassist Brian
Marshall was a lover of the classic-rock of Rush, Led Zeppelin, and
Pink Floyd. Guitarist Mark Tremonti was a huge Metallica fan. Put
these influences together and out pops Creed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got lucky,'' says Phillips. ``We're living every kid's
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Emmylou/Linda transcend trends: There are singers who follow
trends _ and a few singers like Emmylou Harris and Linda Ronstadt
who pay no attention to them. ``We made this album for all the
right reasons that have to do with lyrics and music, not with
looking for a hit single,'' Harris says of her new record with
Ronstadt called ``Western Wall: The Tucson Sessions.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a compelling album in which the two singers record quality
songs by Leonard Cohen, Sinead O'Connor, Patti Scialfa, Bruce
Springsteen, and former Bostonian Patty Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The album has charted on the country charts, but we couldn't
get played on country radio. We're over the age limit,'' Harris
says in a sad but true statement. ``But I'm having a great time. I
feel as creative as I've ever been. And I've been able to do a lot
of projects that are very nourishing and inspiring. There is life
after radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she laughs about how hard it is to categorize the new
album, which was recorded in Tucson, where Ronstadt lives. ``You
walk into a record store and one day it's placed in the folk bin
and the next day in the country bin. But we don't mind. The main
thing is we're doing whatever we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the album special is the close harmonies between
Ronstadt and Harris, whether it's on Cohen's ``Sisters of Mercy''
(sung also with the McGarrigle Sisters, who are old friends of the
artists) or Springsteen's ``Across the Border,'' taken from his
``Tom Joad'' sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda and I have pretty much made our living as being
interpreters in a world that is dictated and ruled by
singer-songwriters,'' says Harris. ``I do some writing, but most of
my artistic work is interpreting.''
</P>
<P>
   She may downplay her writing skills, but there are two gems she
wrote on the new CD: ``Raise the Dead'' (with the haunting verse
``I wrestled the devil, lived to testify . . . But I'll never get
out of your love alive'') and the playful ``Sweet Spot,'' cowritten
by Jill Cunniff of Luscious Jackson, with whom Harris toured on
Lilith Fair last year.
</P>
<P>
   Backing the singers on tour is Bernie Leadon (who used to play
with the Eagles), Buddy Miller, and Paul McCartney's former
keyboardist, Wix. ``It's a small group, but extremely versatile,''
says Harris. ``And, really, if you like Linda Ronstadt, you should
know this may be the last time you'll see her because she may
retire from the road.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Garth pulls it off: If you were waiting for Garth Brooks to fall
flat in his portrayal of fictitious rocker Chris Gaines on an NBC
concert special Wednesday, you'll have to wait some more. Brooks
pulled it off. Some think he's toying with career suicide in the
role of Gaines, but Brooks emerged with integrity intact. He talked
about Gaines (a supposed rocker whose career is ongoing) in the
third person, so as to avoid foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, who loves rock 'n' roll though he's made his livelihood
in country, told the TV audience, ``The closer you look, Garth
Brooks is Chris Gaines.'' His band for the occasion included former
Springsteen bassist Tommy Sims and Billy Joel/Bob Seger
percussionist Crystal Taliefero. They helped make the music
believable, as did Brooks's natural, born-entertainer stage
presence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the act: Out of the ashes of Sublime, whose singer
Brad Nowell overdosed in 1996, comes Long Beach Dub Allstars, a
slinky, skanking septet that made its Boston debut Wednesday at the
sold-out Paradise, with ample aid from reggae aces Barrington Levy
and Half Pint. Sublime's rhythm section, bassist Eric Wilson and
drummer Bud Gaugh, powers the Allstars. The three acts teamed up
for nearly three hours of music; we got there around the halfway
point and witnessed a rock/reggae mix, which brought back memories
of prime-time Clash and Specials. The Allstars are not averse to
punk spurts, but mostly they're into deep, echo-y dub styles and
sinuous rhythmic grooves, with as much emphasis on the spaces
between the notes as the notes themselves. They reworked several
Sublime tunes and featured tracks from their debut disc, ``Right
Back.'' A warm vibe from a band with a future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and Pieces: Susan Tedeschi was just added to VH-1's
``Concert of the Century'' in Washington, D.C. (an undisclosed
location because it's a TV event), Oct. 23. The show also features
Eric Clapton, Aretha Franklin, Garth Brooks, Bono, Sheryl Crow, and
John Mellencamp. Speaking of VH1, Alanis Morissette opens the new
season of VH1's ``Storyteller'' series Sunday at 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporter Jim Sullivan contributed to this column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
