<HEADLINE>
A PREDICTABLE BUT LIKABLE `DRIVE ME CRAZY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
DRIVE ME CRAZY 
Directed by: John Schultz 
Screenplay by: Rob Thomas (based on Todd Strasser's novel, ``How I
Created My Perfect Prom Date'') 
Starring: Adrian Grenier, Melissa Joan Hart, Stephen Collins, Susan
May Pratt, Mark Webber, Kris Park, Ali Larter, Gabriel Carpenter 
Running time: 103 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Drive Me Crazy'' gets by on the watchability of its young
stars, Adrian Grenier and Melissa Joan Hart, as next-door neighbors
who were close as kids, go their different ways in high school, and
in general fool around for 120 pages until they reach a destination
where they will find the audience sitting waiting for them, having
arrived long before. ``Drive Me Crazy'' has several things going
for it, but unpredictability is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Even the differentiation between Hart's Nicole and Grenier's
Chase is more than a bit prefab. She's a bit aggressively
caricatured as a smart senior who has covered all of her scholastic
and extracurricular bases only to find to her surprise that her
game plan develops a hitch when the basketball star she expects to
take her to the prom dates someone else. Grenier's Chase, as the
anti-frat, anti-jock social dropout who fancies himself
disaffected, finds himself dumped by his alternative-lifestyle
girlfriend (an amusingly politicized goth played by Ali Larter).
</P>
<P>
   So they fall back on their old acquaintance for what they tell
themselves is romantic strategy. They agree to date each other in
order to fill their respective exes with jealous regret, not
foreseeing the obvious outcome, or at least pretending not to. What
saves ``Drive Me Crazy'' from becoming the merest exercise in
connecting the dots is Grenier's ability to convince us that
there's something going on behind his eyes, that Chase really is
intelligent enough to reject the airhead conformity that Nicole
finally jettisons as well.
</P>
<P>
   With Nicole, it's a matter of unthinking acceptance of peer
pressure. Hart convinces us that Nicole knows better, but needs to
develop enough self-confidence to step back and go with her inner
prompts. The message of being your own person and rejecting
peer-group tyranny plays well, with appealing sidekick
contributions from Kris Park and Keri Lynn Pratt, even though
there's nothing particularly original or distinctive about ``Drive
Me Crazy'' as a film. At times, it seems little more than
standard-issue connective tissue for the soundtrack, with
performances by Britney Spears and The Backstreet Boys, among
others, and music by Greg Kendall, who earlier collaborated with
director John Schultz on ``Bandwagon.'' If only ``Drive Me Crazy''
had a little real craziness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
