<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANIMAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANIMAL FARM': PEARL AMID THE SWINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANIMAL FARM 
Starring: Pete Postlethwaite, Alan Stanford 
Featuring the voices of: Kelsey Grammer, Ian Holm, Julia
Louis-Dreyfus, Julia Ormond, Paul Scofield, Patrick Stewart, Peter
Ustinov 
Directed by: John Stephenson 
On: TNT, Sunday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pigs who rule ``Animal Farm'' are ugly swine, with drooling
mouths, coarse fur, and snoots that glisten with slime. Despite the
Disneyization of animals in American entertainment, and despite the
``Babe'' cuddly quotient, they are stubbornly, convincingly, and
fascinatingly repugnant. You won't find these anti-worker porkers
stuffed on the shelves of your local toy store.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what makes the new TNT production of George
Orwell's novel such a nice surprise. ``Animal Farm,'' which
premieres Sunday night at 8 on TNT, is a gritty, intelligent TV
movie that doesn't shy away from the dark symbolism of Orwell's
dystopian fable. It hasn't been softened for younger viewers, even
though its creators _ Jim Henson's Creature Shop and executive
producer Robert Halmi Sr. of ``Gulliver's Travels'' _ are generally
identified with family-oriented material. And it hasn't been wholly
dumbed down in the name of mainstream TV, although, like any book
adaptation, it nips and tucks at Orwell's original. ``Animal Farm''
is an adult movie that manages to capture a bleak totalitarian
nightmare, dropping into its new-boss-old-boss pessimism only a
dash of hope at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Postlethwaite, whose angular face recalls a wooden puppet,
plays the negligent, drunken famer Jones. Tired of his abuse, the
animals stage a revolution and run Jones and his wife off the farm.
They set out to build an equal society, with idealistic approaches
to wealth and production and with a neat slogan: ``Four legs good,
two legs bad.'' But greed and power undo the utopia, and the ruling
pigs _ the Stalinesque Napoleon, in particular _ become drunken,
oppressive, murderous dictators who are no better than their human
predecesors. ``Animal Farm'' is famous as an Orwellian critique of
Stalinist Russia, but the movie works as a potent parable even
without its historical associations.
</P>
<P>
   The voice cast is loaded with formidable names like Ian Holm,
Paul Scofield, Peter Ustinov, Kelsey Grammer, and Patrick Stewart,
who is the nefarious Napoleon. But, except for Julia Louis-Dreyfus'
cameo as the vain horse Mollie, their performances don't take
attention away from the unfolding story. Halmi's TV movies
sometimes play as if they were designed as a string of episodic
star turns, but the spell of ``Animal Farm'' is rarely broken. The
only flaw may be Julia Ormond's Jesse, a noble sheepdog whose
kindly voice is slightly out of sync with the story's somber tones.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, the production is absolutely remarkable. It's amazing
how today's technical filmmakers can merge live-action,
animatronics, and digital effects to create a seamless vision of
animal life. After a few minutes at Manor Farm, which the animals
rename Animal Farm, you forget the artificiality of the whole
venture, and you stop noticing how the lips move on the pigs and
horses and dogs. The movie also features haunting pig-made
propaganda films that recall those of the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most imaginatively shot scenes in ``Animal House''
has Jesse spying on Napoleon and his goons as they slurp whiskey in
the farmhouse with a human. Through the glass, all of their faces
look identical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
