<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAINS OF THE DAY HAUNT A BILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Internet billionaire David Wetherell, a funny thing happened
on the way to building his personal high-tech Xanadu. Well, maybe
not so funny from Wetherell's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   All Wetherell, whose net worth has been pegged at $3 billion,
wanted to do was build a garden-variety, 7,400-square-foot palace
on a 10-acre plot of land in Martha's Vineyard. The Squibnocket
site is one of the most beautiful in the Commonwealth, with a
commanding view of such Vineyard landmarks as Nomans Land island,
the estate of the late Jacqueline Onassis, and Gay Head Light.
</P>
<P>
   The trophy home, created by architect Glen Fries of Princeton,
N.J., has what I call a Longest Day design: each of the two wings
resembles a Quonset hut, and they are linked by a circular stone
tower in the middle. Says our Squibnocket stringer: ``The overall
impression one gets, coming over the hill, is that you've stumbled
upon a nicely shingled German bunker overlooking the bluffs of
Omaha Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it has the appropriate Web-mogul accoutrements: a
negative-edge swimming pool like you see in the cigarette ads; a
12-seat basement theater that alas has some soundproofing
``concerns'' (you can hear the furnace when it's on), and a litter
of expensive, German-made digital TVs strewn throughout the rooms.
It's a so-called smart house, ``which means you have to be an
Einstein to turn on the lights,'' according to my source.
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1996, the mansion is still unfinished, although
Wetherell and his family did spend part of this summer in the
mostly complete residential wing. Some of the delays derive from
the usual reasons _ you can appreciate how hard it is to get
kitchen tiles from France, and huge, custom-built arches from
Pennsylvania, for the Great Hall _ but the biggest problem has been
. . . the remains.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's every billionaire's nightmare. In December 1997
archeologists discovered what the Vineyard Gazette said ``may be
one of the most significant archeological finds in New England'' _
a ceremonial Native American burial ground, and surrounding
dwellings. The Vineyard-based Wampanoag tribe and state historical
officials imposed a news blackout concerning the find, and posted a
guard at the site.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999, Wetherell had to pay for a team of
archeologists to live and work on his property while the house was
being built. Their report should be filed soon. I'm told they
identified the remains of two adults and three children,
``post-contact,'' which is archeology-speak for the period
following the European invasion of North America. State
archeologist Brona Simon confirms that the find doesn't live up to
its inital hype: ``It's an interesting site, but not one of the
best discoveries made in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave Wetherell? While on the Vineyard this
summer, he sat down for a major powwow with Wampanoag tribal
chairwoman Beverly Wright. I'm told that he and the Wampanoags
reached a settlement _ not a financial settlement, Simon says _
that will ensure that no construction will take place near the
burial area. (There goes the guest house . . .) According to Simon,
``The majority of the archeological site is to be preserved in
perpetuity.'' Wetherell declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine received an elegant, three-page ``invitation''
to join a new country club called Whisper Hill. It hypes itself as
``a secluded, private club with membership limited to less than
three hundred.'' The club offers complimentary guest suites, free
golf clubs, an exercise facility, spa, ``and gourmet dining
complimented (sic) by your personal wine cellar.'' And it's not
built on top of an Indian burial ground!
</P>
<P>
   Sounds great, but . . . where is it? Nowhere does the mailing
disclose the location of this rare gem. It turns out to be in New
Ipswich, N.H., a few miles north of the Massachusetts border on
Route 124. Why hide the location of the property you're trying to
sell people on?
</P>
<P>
   ``Clever, isn't it?'' says membership director Rob Stroud.
Subsequent mailings have revealed the club's location in the cover
letter, he says. ``The first ones were a little vague in that
area.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
