<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLUE OR NAIL BACK SHINGLE SLIVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 03, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. A sliver of cedar shingle came off my house siding. It is 1
1/2 inches wide and 16 inches long. Can I glue it back?
</P>
<P>
   A.B., Brighton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course. To reglue, use an adhesive caulk of a type that
comes in a caulking cartridge. Or, nail it if you predrill the nail
hole. A sliver like that is a little narrow for safe nailing; you
could split the shingle again. Use a galvanized shingle nail and
nail near the butt of the shingle above. Touch up paint if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had to replace the floor of the second-story porch of an
1890 Victorian, which is covered by a roof. It had a painted canvas
floor that was removed, and now there is new plywood and tarpaper
on top. What can I use?
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL MILBURN, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Yellow Pages reveal nothing about canvas floors. So, use
fir porch flooring. The boards are tongued and grooved, and if
painted, are quite watertight. Apply one coat of semitransparent
stain instead of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Or put down 2 x 4 sleepers, then spaced pressure-treated deck
boards; water will drain between the boards and run down the
tarpaper roof to the edge, out of harm's way. The extra weight of
the sleepers will make very little difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some fine old pine trees, 75 feet high. English ivy is
growing up them, up about eight feet now. Will they hurt the tree,
or twine around it? Should I cut off the ivy or cut it down, or
what should I do?
</P>
<P>
   TONY BASS, Norfolk, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The ivy is competing with the trees for air and sun, but it
is not the twining type that girdles trunks and branches, and will
not choke the trees.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman checked with two know-ledgeable plant people, and
got two answers. One suggested keeping the ivy in control by
cutting it at a certain height, say, six feet, and letting it
continue until it's high enough to cut again. The other suggested
something more drastic: Cut the ivy at the ground and keep it
short.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, you will have your ivy and your pines. In my
opinion, the pines are far more important than the ivy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My central air system has been in place for four years. Now,
every time it comes on it keeps tripping the circuit breaker.
What's wrong, and how can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   GETTING TOO WARM
</P>
<P>
   A. The compressor is pulling more power than it normally does,
tripping the breaker every time. I think the unit needs an overhaul
or at least routine maintenance, perhaps replacement of parts. Call
the installer to do this work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have several swollen doors in my house due to moisture
gain. Some are so tight that they take a lot of effort to close.
Normally I leave all the doors open in summer, but one house guest
needs privacy, which isn't so good because the doors won't shut
without effort. Is there anything I can do to make them close and
open properly without planing the edges? I am reluctant to plane
the edges because in winter, when the doors dry out and contract,
the gaps may be too wide.
</P>
<P>
   E.O., Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The only thing you could do without planing the doors is to
rebuild the frame in the opening, to accommodate the expanded
doors. I don't even want to think of that, because it involves a
lot of unnecessary work. Planing the door edges a bit will make
them fit, and when they dry out and contract, it is unlikely that
the gaps will be intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   You should paint the edges where you planed the wood. This is
good, because when the doors contract in autumn, you can repaint or
revarnish the entire door, including top and bottom edges. This
will seal the doors, keeping out future moisture and the doors
stable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I received several bids to reroof my Colonial house that
needs 22 squares of shingles (22 squares equal 2,200 square feet).
The bids range from $3,200 to $4,000; add $1,800 to $2,000 for
stripping the one layer of shingles already on the house. Is this
fair? The bids include a ridge vent. One roofer suggested putting
Ice &AMP; Water Shield over the old shingles. Is that acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   PAT DELEO, Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Everything is good except the idea of the Ice &AMP; Water Shield
going on top of the old shingles. The Ice &AMP; Water Shield is a
rubberized membrane that goes along the bottom 3 to 6 feet of the
roof at the eaves, and is designed to prevent leaks from ice dams.
The Ice &AMP; Water Shield should go on top of bare sheathing. It will
do its job better if it is done this way.
</P>
<P>
   The bids sound reasonable; in fact, $3,200 to $4,000 for 22
squares of shingles is a good buy. The stripping costs seem high,
too, but I don't think you will do much better. If the job includes
installation of a ridge vent, that is another good deal because a
ridge vent costs $10 per foot. The soffit vents at $400 also sound
fair, depending on the size of the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
