<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3426 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BUSH-SILICON-VALLEY-H     10-01 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SILICON-VALLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILICON VALLEY EXECUTIVES ANTE UP TO BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush took his
money-raising juggernaut to the Silicon Valley, courting votes and
adding more technology-borne wealth to his campaign for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the front-runner for the Republican nomination went
to the valley and vacuumed up another $350,000 at a fund-raiser at
the Hotel Sofitel in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   For the technology-heavy crowd, there was discount pricing: $500
for guests under age 35, $1,000 for those over 35. Never mind that
some of the younger executives and entrepreneurs in the crowd could
well afford the higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's swing through the Silicon Valley, which included a stop
at the Tech Museum in San Jose, came on the same day his campaign
reported that he had raised $19 million in the past three months,
six times as much as his nearest GOP competitor, Sen. John McCain
of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   And the Texas governor reported close to $37 million in the
bank, more than his Democratic and Republican contenders have
combined.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been especially doting in his courtship of Silicon
Valley's technology leaders. Technet, the lobbying group, released
a list of 120 prominent Silicon Valley supporters who have endorsed
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser, Bush once again bashed the Clinton
administration for being slow to support legislation to limit
product liability lawsuits related to Y2K-related computer
breakdowns. He said he would have acted faster than the
administration to ease regulations on the export of encryption
technology and to make the research and development tax credit
permanent _ both big issues with technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always take the side of innovation over litigation, and
private initiative over federal regulation,'' he said. The
suit-and-tie crowd responded with strong applause.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush will have to fight hard for support in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Many top tech leaders backed the Clinton-Gore team in the last
two presidential elections, and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New
Jersey has surprised some recently by raising huge sums of money
from Democrats in the Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are divisions within the tech community,'' said Kathy
Behrens, a leading venture capitalist and Bush supporter. ``There
is good support for Bush, there is good support for Bradley and
there is good support for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one longtime Democratic supporter said Thursday he is
switching his support to Bush. Halsey Minor, the chairman of CNET,
held a $50,000-per-person fund-raiser for the Democratic National
Committee in September 1997. Clinton attended the event at Minor's
Sea Cliff mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Minor said he is drawn to Bush's message of compassionate
conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gore has definitely been good for the (technology)
industry and I'm fairly confident that Bush will be equally good
for the industry. In Internet parlance, he gets it,'' Minor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Minor, who describes himself as fiscally conservative and
socially liberal, said he has ``fiscal concerns with Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're both socially compassionate, but I think Bush
is more fiscally conservative. And I just think we've got a good
thing going right now,'' Minor said. ``We don't need to screw it
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
