A3518 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BRADLEY-HEALTHCARE-HN     10-01 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HEALTHCARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY LISTENS TO CONCERNS ABOUT HEALTH INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATTHEW YI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ A day after Democratic presidential hopeful
Bill Bradley unveiled a $65 billion proposal to make health
coverage available to uninsured Americans, he rolled up his sleeves
and accepted feedback from a group of people.
</P>
<P>
   The former senator from New Jersey used a 45-minute discussion
at Children's Hospital in Oakland to clarify his plan and get
suggestions from doctors and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Americans need to ``keep our focus on health, not just health
care ... to deal with people in the dawn of life, noon and the
evening of life,'' Bradley said at the gathering on Thur{day.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Tom, 51, of Fairfield said she has 13 children, two of her
own and 11 who were adopted. The adopted children each have special
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them was relinquished (by the parents) because this was
the only way for their medical needs to be met, because it
impoverished the family,'' she said. ``The only way for this child
to get medical care was to be adopted. That's a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom said that while insurance covers most medical needs, it
doesn't cover other things such as liquid food, which costs up to
$10 per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``With chronic illnesses, I think the program should be stepped
up ... here any child with chronic, genetic illness would be fully
covered,'' Tom said. ``It should be a basic right in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley told her that his plan would deal with children who need
more than normal care.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the group at Oakland suggested that Bradley's plan
include an increase in mental health coverage and provide universal
coverage for older teen-agers as well as children.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's proposal would provide all Americans access to health
insurance by extending the federal workers' health-care system to
non-employees and providing tax credits to help people pay for
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would mandate coverage for all children. Health care
for children living in households with an income of less than
$32,800 for a family of four would be subsidized by the government.
A partial payment would be offered for families with up to $49,200
for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would use the budget surplus to pay for the program, but
not dip into funds set aside for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Bradley's rival for the Democratic
nomination, has blasted Bradley's plan, calling it too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan offers overblown promises that would endanger
Medicare,'' Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While the question remains whether Bradley's proposal would ever
become reality, some in the health care industry say it's good that
the issue is coming back around as part of a national debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing political leaders talk about universal coverage for
children is terrific,'' said Gregg Haifley, deputy director of the
health division at Children's Defense Fund in Washington, D.C. ``We
have 11 million uninsured kids in America. What we have to face up
to is the fact that if they don't have health insurance, they're
going to have health conditions that are going to go undiagnosed
and untreated. ... It's going to come back to haunt us later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, some 45 million Americans lack health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the industry questioned how parents, especially those
receiving only partial subsidy, would be held accountable for
enrolling their children in a health plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley's proposal is interesting. It's nice to say parents
should buy health insurance for kids, but I don't know how you can
enforce that,'' said Walter Zelman, president and chief executive
of the California Association of Health Plans, which represents
providers of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Zelman was not surprised that the health care debate is quickly
picking up steam just before an election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem hasn't gone away. It's a glaring, glaring
problem,'' said Zelman, who was one of the advisers to President
Clinton's failed effort to provide universal health care in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
