<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA _ MOSCOW _ The Russian government Friday came
under increasing pressure at home and abroad to avoid a full-scale
war in Chechnya, even as warplanes pressed their assault on the
breakaway republic and ground forces made limited incursions across
the border.In a policy address at Harvard, Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott Friday will urge the Kremlin to show
restraint. So, too, are the Russian media. While Russia's 10-day
air campaign against Chechnya has won approval from the majority of
the public, a ground invasion conjures painful memories of Russia's
disastrous war in the republic from 1994 to 1996. An editorial in a
leading Russian daily said Friday: ``With our poverty, we soon
might face the same thing we faced some time ago _ shame and new
coffins. But the problem now is there is no money even for the
coffins.'' (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   TIBET-AID _ WASHINGTON _ House liberals like John Lewis and
Cynthia McKinney of Atlanta have joined Republican conservatives to
introduce a bill punishing the World Bank for its approval of a
loan to underwrite the resettlement of 60,000 Chinese farmers onto
Tibetan farmland. ``This plan will displace a large number of
indigenous people from their land. I tend to identify with the
Tibetan people because they've been peaceful warriors for their
independence for a long time,'' said Lewis. (Nesmith, Cox News
Service).
