A3526 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-01 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IF I CAN HELP SOMEBODY ...'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truly, her living was not in vain.
</P>
<P>
   In life, Oseola McCarty provided resplendent evidence of the
enormous capacity for goodness that exists in the hearts and minds
of human beings and the amazing power of humility and selflessness.
</P>
<P>
   Her great humanitarian gesture calls to mind Alma Bazel
Androzzo's inspirational song, as rendered by the inimitable Mr. B.
_ Billy Eckstine:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can help somebody as I pass along. If I can cheer
somebody with a word or a song.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty, who died on Sunday at age 91, was a Hattiesburg, Miss.,
resident who four years ago donated $150,000 _ almost her entire
life savings _ to the University of Southern Mississippi for
scholarships for needy students.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been a remarkable thing if McCarty had been an
affluent professional or entrepreneur, some economically successful
person who wished to give something back to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can show somebody he is traveling wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCarty had accumulated her entire small fortune from
washing and ironing other people's clothes in her home. And that
circumstance elevated her giving to a higher plane than any
multimillionaire's philanthropic gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then my living will not be in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not seek the honors that came her way. She was a humble
person and did not long for fame. The self-effacing washerwoman who
had outlived all her relatives gave the money to the university,
she said, ``so that the children won't have to work so hard, like I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   But the awards came, more than 300 of them. She shook hands with
the president of the United States and received the Presidential
Citizens Medal. Harvard University bestowed an honorary doctorate
upon her.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty carried the Olympic torch on a short stretch of its
journey through Mississippi. And at the stroke of midnight on Dec.
31, 1996, she flicked the switch that released the giant
illuminated ball that climaxes the New Year's Eve celebration in
New York City's Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   None of that overawed her. She remained the same God-fearing
person, the washerwoman, the servant to her fellow human beings
whose humility and graciousness called to mind Christ washing the
feet of his disciples.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest reward to come to McCarty for her largess
was the imitation that it stimulated. The fund she established at
Southern Mississippi has been more than doubled by the
contributions of 600 additional donors. Her gift is said to have
inspired communications tycoon Ted Turner to contribute $1 billion
to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bill Gates has not made the connection, it is
reasonable to assume that McCarty's philanthropy may have
indirectly influenced his recent decision to establish a $1 billion
scholarship fund for minority students.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't give that money to the school to start something
bigger. She just gave what she could, which is all that can be
reasonably expected of anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can do my duty as a good man ought. If I can bring back
beauty to a world upwrought.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty's gift is a valuable testimonial for millions of
Americans caught up in the chase for material success, the swirl of
changing values, the maelstrom of social and political conflict,
and the anguish of existential uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Her example suggests that in the grand scheme of things, none of
that matters if one derives no real satisfaction from attaining
wealth, power or prestige.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that she had only a short time left to live, McCarty
reaffirmed the ancient wisdom that all you can take with you is the
good that you've done and what you give away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can spread love's message that the Master taught.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty, who lived nearly a century in southern Mississippi,
through the worst days of brutalizing segregation and
discrimination against her people, endured it all and kept her
faith in God and mankind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then my living will not be in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Oseola McCarty was a credit to her race. The human race.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
