<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EDUCATION-SUMMIT-1002     10-01 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-SUMMIT-1002-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNORS, BUSINESS LEADERS, EDUCATORS SHAPE NEW PUSH FOR
EDUCATION REFORM
 &HT;    525&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALISADES, N.Y. _ Nearly half the nation's governors joined
leading employers and educators Friday in endorsing a new
three-point plan for the next stage of reforms in the nation's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   They concluded the third national education summit by calling on
all states to emphasize strategies for ``improving teacher quality,
providing all students a fair opportunity to meet higher standards,
and holding schools accountable for results.''
</P>
<P>
   The 114 leaders at the summit came from governments, companies
and organizations that supply more than 90 percent of the money,
teachers and administrators in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   None of their deliberations or conclusions required federal
action, noted Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson. He and IBM chairman
Louis V. Gerstner Jr. co-chaired the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to me is how we act on this,'' said John Pepper,
chairman of the executive committee of Proctor &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   To put pressure on themselves, the governors agreed that they
will post reports on each state's steps toward meeting the three
goals six months from now on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   This summit was the first to include professional educators. It
built upon the standards-based school reform movement which grew
out of the previous two summits in 1989 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 summit, which consisted only of governors, said the
schools needed higher academic standards. The 1996 summit, which
consisted of governors and business leaders, said states should use
tests to see if students and schools were reaching those standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising standards and developing tests may have been the
easiest part of the journey,'' said the ``action statement''
endorsed at the end of this year's two-day summit here. ``The more
daunting task is ensuring that all students reach these
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sense any teacher-bashing here, and that was
gratifying,'' said Sandra Feldman, president of the American
Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chase, president of the National Education Association, said
he found ``a surprising amount of common ground'' in his
conversation over dinner with Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, whose reforms
have contained some elements opposed by teachers in Chase's union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got good words on paper, and now we have to make them
work,'' said Ohio Gov. Bob Taft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm particularly proud that this summit has focused on the
importance of excellent teaching,'' said North Carolina Gov. Jim
Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Their carefully worded manifesto, consisting of four pages
boiled down from a 67-page first draft, avoided taking sides in two
politically touchy disputes. They didn't take a stand on whether to
use tax-paid vouchers to send some children from failing public
schools to private schools, or on how to offer extra help to
low-achieving students without stoking the resentments of those
parents _ usually the best-educated and most likely to vote _ whose
children do well under current conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed, because this is a consensus document,''
said Bush, who this year convinced the Florida Legislature to start
a voucher experiment in his state. ``The important thing is that
people are united behind the conviction that we must stay the
course on standards and assessments.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add that can stand as a
sidebar, follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the detailed portion of their action statement, governors,
business leaders and educators endorsed policies that would require
major reforms in many states:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To improve teacher quality, they endorsed teacher-college and
certification reforms, professional development courses to
strengthen both ``content knowledge and skills'' of veteran
teachers, and ``competitive salary structures'' with extra pay for
teacher leaders and for teachers whose students show academic
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To help more students reach the higher standards of the 21st
century workplace, they endorsed efforts to require algebra and
geometry before high school, make sure that students are taught the
subjects tested on state exams, transfer fiscal and personnel
decisions from central school systems to individual schools, offer
extra hours and days of schooling for students who need extra help,
and mobilize and train tens of thousands of volunteer tutors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To strengthen accountability for results, they endorsed
financial and other rewards for highly successful schools and
intervention, or shutdowns if necessary, for schools with too many
low-performing students.
</P>
<P>
   They said twice as many companies would start to review high
school transcripts of job applicants, governors will be willing to
report publicly on how their states stack up against other states
and nations in standardized tests of students, and educators will
reduce or phase out the remediation courses used at many colleges
and universities to make up for the failure of high schools to
bring their graduates up to snuff.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
