A3558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NITEOUT-CYNTHIA-NIXON     10-01 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-CYNTHIA-NIXON-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER-HOURS ROLE IN THE SEXY CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 3) 
(jt) 
 By ANTHONY LAPPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a cluttered, unisex dressing room in the dingy
basement of the Greenwich House Theater last Wednesday night,
Cynthia Nixon was still aglow from her opening night performance as
a wry, listless WASP in Douglas Cater Beane's new play, ``The
Country Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon, 33, has become semi-famous playing Miranda, a
high-powered, wryly hard-bitten lawyer on HBO's ``Sex and the
City.'' But she still seems more at home in the low-rent world of
Off Off Broadway, where she got her start. ``Let's hope they feed
us,'' she said of the cast party.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the theater in a 1950s orange cocktail dress and a
diamond and emerald Tiffany necklace given to her by Beane, Ms.
Nixon was hit by a gusher of praise from stagehands and ticket
takers: ``Ms. Nixon, you were great!'' ``Nice dress, Ms. Nixon. You
are on fire.'' Her agent joined in: ``You were wonderful. Have we
discussed a musical?''
</P>
<P>
   The cast party was at Coup, a sleek new restaurant on Sixth
Street, near Avenue A. Missy Yaeger, who was in the play ``This Is
Our Youth,'' was there, and Josh Hamilton, who was in ``Cider House
Rules.'' Ms. Nixon posed for paparazzi with Amy Sedaris, a star of
the Comedy Central series ``Strangers With Candy.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Ms. Nixon's element. She grew up on the Upper West Side
and has been acting since she was 12 in television, on the stage
and in teen-age movies like ``Little Darlings.'' Seven years ago,
she helped found the Drama Department, the company that produced
``The Country Club.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the four sexual adventurers on ``Sex and the City,''
Ms. Nixon is enjoying a newly raised profile. ``People in the
subway come up to me all the time now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the attention, she has little in common with the
bed-hopping characters on the show. ``It's not the New York I
know,'' she said, sipping a Gibson. ``I always had a sense of radar
for men that were trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   After missing several waiters with hors d'oeuvres, she finally
hailed a tray of bean quesadillas, while chatting with Will Arnett,
from ``The Mike O'Malley Show,'' a struggling NBC sitcom. He also
played one of Ms. Nixon's lovers recently in the HBO series. He
said, `` `Sex and the City' is the only show where the guys are the
meat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon then had her fortune told by Karen Thorne, a
dark-haired astrologer and the mother of one of Ms. Nixon's
``Country Club'' co-stars, Callie Thorne. Ms. Thorne told Ms. Nixon
in a spacey tone, ``You have yet to reach your happy glow.'' She
held Ms. Nixon's hand. ``Your destiny is a fireball,'' she said.
``You can't lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still hungry, Ms. Nixon grabbed Patrick Breen, another recent
``Sex and the City'' guest star, and headed for Veselka, the
Ukrainian diner on Second Avenue. As Ms. Nixon devoured pirogis,
Beane arrived with hot-off-the-press reviews of the play under his
arm.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nixon was most pleased by a line that placed her in her
mid-20s. ``Hey, I'm still passing,'' she said. A few more minutes
of banter, and Ms. Nixon was off. She had another party to prepare
for in the morning. Her daughter, Samantha, is turning 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
