   HAITI-AID (Port-au-Prince, Haiti) _ For decades, foreign
governments, aid agencies and lenders like the World Bank have
poured billions of dollars into Haiti. And for decades, those
efforts have come up pitifully short. Rather than push this nation
of 8 million toward prosperity, many aid workers, academics and
ordinary Haitians say, the aid has served merely to soothe foreign
consciences. While softening the social and political impact of
Haiti's destitution, it has converted many people here into charity
cases. By DUDLEY ALTHAUS. (Filed Thursday. Photos available on NYT
database.)
