<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVING WELFARE SUITED FOR WORK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a big week for 64 women in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The women, all current or former welfare recipients, stepped
into a big, yellow semitruck and were fitted for a new
mix-and-match outfit courtesy of Mervyn's California.
</P>
<P>
   Mervyn's began what it dubs its Community Closet program a year
ago to supply women coming off welfare with suitable clothes for
job interviews and work.
</P>
<P>
   Mervyn's, part of the Dayton Hudson Corp., gives away 5 percent
of its profits to the community. When welfare reform came down, the
company thought about how it could help, said Jan O'Laughlin, who
manages the Community Closet program.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer identified three barriers to getting off welfare:
lack of reliable transportation, lack of low-cost child care and
poor self-esteem, which includes not owning suitable working
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Mervyn's decided to focus on women's clothes because 80 percent
of welfare recipients are women, O'Laughlin said. In the past year,
the retailer has outfitted 2,000 women across the county from its
big truck.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-foot rig parked in front of City Hall looked more like an
upscale store than an 18-wheeler. Inside, it is done entirely in
blond wood _ the floor, shelves, walls and doors. There was a rack
of clothes on one wall and dressing rooms at each end. But no cash
register.
</P>
<P>
   All the women got a choice of a blue or black three-piece suit
(skirt, pants, jacket) along with a silk blouse, sweater set,
shoes, belt, pearl necklace and stockings.
</P>
<P>
   A bevy of local store managers, along with a clothing stylist
from Los Angeles, helped the women make their color selections and
gave them tips on how to fix their hair and apply their makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it a blessing,'' said Batina Smith, who chose a
blue suit with a beige blouse. The 35-year-old mother of three has
been working at her retail sales job since March and got off public
assistance in April.
</P>
<P>
   For another excited woman, the new set of clothes meant she
could dress well like everyone else at her office. She just got off
welfare and couldn't afford to lay out the $350 it would have cost
to buy the clothes off the rack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLOTHES MEAN A LOT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clothes mean so much for the women, who have traditionally
received their first working outfit from a thrift store, O'Laughlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   And that largess means a lot to Mervyn's customers. Mervyn's has
done surveys, and consumers decide where to shop based on how a
store contributes to its community, O'Laughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, when affordable child care was the hot-button
issue, Dayton Hudson spent $10 million on improving teacher
training and boosting pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mervyn's program is unique among retailers, other
companies also are reaching out to give welfare recipients a hand.
</P>
<P>
   Katy Mills mall is courting welfare workers to fill its 3,000 to
5,000 jobs when the mall opens Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great way to find workers in a tight labor market,
company officials said last month when they unveiled the plan. And
the shopping mall developer wanted to do something to help welfare
recipients find jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The mall is addressing the child care and transportation issues
head-on. The mall is building an on-site child care center and
shuttle buses will pick up employees and their children.
</P>
<P>
   So far, between 150 and 200 welfare recipients are in the
process of either getting hired or being trained at Houston
Community College, said Kevin Kudlo, vice president and development
director for the mall in Katy, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COMMITMENT FROM EMPLOYERS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easier for welfare recipients to find jobs when employers
seek them out, said Jeff Crain, area manager for Houston Works in
Houston. And with all the attention welfare reform has had, there
is more commitment among employers to hire welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare used to be an entitlement program _ anyone who qualified
received benefits. That changed two years ago when Congress limited
the number of years a person could receive welfare. Limits are
based on previous job history and educational level.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the maximum time anyone can receive benefits is 36
months, said Crain, whose organization put 1,777 welfare recipients
into jobs between May 1998 and July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Several local organizations, including Houston Works, have
contracts with the Houston-Galveston Area Council to find jobs for
welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
