<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Oct. 3, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-SCHOOLS (New York) _ Parents used to view private
schools as a gateway to good colleges and a rewarding career;
increasingly on the Upper East Side of Manhattan, having a
private-school child is a means of social advancement (italics)for
parents.(end italics) By Monique P. Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   JIMENEZ-FASHION (New York) _ Part performance artist, part
designer, Ms. Elisa Jimenez, 34, likes to sew her clothes directly
onto the body and douse them in ginger, eucalyptus and other
spices. Hunger World, the name of her label and quasi-spiritual
fashion sect, embraces sexuality, ancient mythology and magic. Her
one-of-a-kind separates, with prices from about $150 for a G-string
to $800 for an evening dress, have become favorites among
celebrities known for their naughty she-power personas like
Courtney Love and Cher. By Julia Chaplin. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GLAMOUR-NAILS (New York) _ With the advent of Korean-owned nail
salons here in the last decade or so, manicures and extensions,
called tips, have become affordable to all women, not just the
traditional privilege of the old money set (clear polish, short
tips) or the new money set (a flair for the extravagant, if not the
tasteful). By Alex Witchel. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-CYNTHIA-NIXON (New York) _ In a cluttered, unisex
dressing room in the dingy basement of the Greenwich House Theater
last Wednesday night, Cynthia Nixon was still aglow from her
opening night performance as a wry, listless WASP in Douglas Cater
Beane's new play, ``The Country Club.'' Ms. Nixon, 33, has become
semi-famous playing Miranda, a high-powered, wryly hard-bitten
lawyer on HBO's ``Sex and the City.'' By Anthony Lappe. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (New York) _ The cultivar Actaea dates to the
1920s. It was a product of what aficionados call the golden age of
daffodils, when breeders stopped obsessing about tulips and started
exploring the possibilities of other bulbs. Of the 7,000 or so
daffodil varieties created during that golden age, Actaea is among
the few still available today. By Cass Peterson. Photo.
</P>
