<HEADER>
A3585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GLAMOUR-NAILS-ART-$AD     10-01 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAMOUR-NAILS-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS `NAIL ART' BECOMES THE FASHION, WHO'S TO SCRUB THE BROILER
PAN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 3) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I can't say I've ever paid much attention to my
fingernails. I don't bite them. I don't polish them. I don't even
cut them. If they get long enough, I peel them.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know. But it's just one of those girl things that
never interested me _ like flower arranging. I stare at the
two-inch acrylic nails on the hands of cashiers at Zabar's and
Fairway _ the look that David Sedaris described as ``resembling
lacquered corn chips'' in a recent Allure essay _ and marvel that
they can even pick up a pen. And in my house, if I'm not the one
who takes on the glamour jobs of scrubbing the broiler pan or
picking pills out of their foil seals, they don't get done. Which
is fair enough. Hobble skirts and bound feet disappeared for a
reason. And I've certainly never yearned for hobble hands.
</P>
<P>
   I seem to be alone. With the advent of Korean-owned nail salons
in the last decade or so, manicures and extensions, called tips,
have become affordable to all women, not just the traditional
privilege of the old money set (clear polish, short tips) or the
new money set (a flair for the extravagant, if not the tasteful).
Sheril Bailey, the manicurist who is the author of ``The Sheril
Bailey Complete Manicure and Nail Care Handbook'' (Andrews McMeel),
said recently: ``It used to be that only wealthy women could afford
manicures, which they would have while getting their hair done.
Working women couldn't. When the small neighborhood salons started
in the '80s, suddenly a manicure became affordable for the working
class.''
</P>
<P>
   That working class included a new black clientele, Ms. Bailey
said, who embraced manicures ``as a way to say, `We know about
fashion.''' They took over, doing nails brighter and longer, she
continued, and the trend of nail art took off with hip-hop artists
like Mary J. Blige and Foxy Brown, who sported flamboyant acrylic
talons airbrushed with all manner of design, from stripes to palm
trees.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion world is now co-opting that flashy look: Gucci ads
this season show a hand with long black nails, the pinky pierced
with silver hoops; Marc Jacobs and Alexander McQueen both made
black, sparkly nail statements in their recent runway shows, and
the Gen Art fashion show featured 14-karat-gold nails. Some fashion
stylists are having their pinky nails airbrushed and calling it a
``Chloe nail,'' after airbrushed T-shirts Stella McCartney designed
for Chloe.
</P>
<P>
   One practitioner of the new nail art is Ji Baek (pronounced gee
beck), who owns Rescue Aromatherapy Nail Spa with her husband, Alex
Sobolevsky. Ms. Baek, 29, is a former viola prodigy who was forced
to abandon her studies at Juilliard when she developed tendinitis
in her shoulder. ``The first thing I did was get a manicure,'' she
said recently at her shop, at 21 Cleveland Place (Spring Street) in
lower Manhattan. Ms. Baek quickly recognized the need for ``a
middle ground'' between the neighborhood salons offering $5
manicures and the fancier places where they went for $80. ``People
my age don't want cheap stuff, but they don't have money,'' she
said. (A manicure at Rescue is $15).
</P>
<P>
   Besides shunning the use of thick acrylic tips in favor of the
thinner, more expensive silk extensions, Ms. Baek saw a need for a
tasteful, conservative translation of nail art from fashion and
hip-hop for women who ``want to be naughty but don't want to
experiment with their hair or get plastic surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nail design is recent for the upper middle class,'' she said.
``They want something, too, but they don't want to look like
that.'' She pointed to a magazine featuring blue fingernails
adorned with white feathers.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue's trademark is delicate hand-painted designs _ flowers,
animals, even tiny rhinestones set against a navy background,
though Ms. Baek acknowledges that most of her clients prefer to
keep those on their toenails. ``Your hands reflect your
personality, and nails make a statement about your individualism,''
she said. ``And yes, people get jaded. We're planning on doing
ladybugs for the fall and winter, when everyone is really bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Though I've never looked toward my hands as a potential source
of entertainment, I agreed to let Kathy Sanchez of Rescue give me a
full set of silk extensions, complete with a French manicure and
one tiny hand-painted flower on my left ring finger. The procedure
took 2 hours 15 minutes and cost $93.60, not including a $20 tip,
entirely fair for such painstaking work. Would I pay it again? No.
Not to mention that maintaining the job requires weekly follow-ups.
As for having to schlep back to lower Manhattan, the good news is
that Rescue will open a branch at Bergdorf Goodman in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   I must say I left Rescue floating, and couldn't wait to show off
my hands to everyone I knew. It was a job beautifully done, making
my fingers look longer and my rings look better. I even got some
admiring glances from women on the subway who had nail statements
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The downside, I quickly discovered, was that I had no feeling in
the tips of the nails, an odd disconnect I couldn't quite get used
to. I was also not used to opening a box of Cascade with a knife
because I couldn't pull the spout with my fingernail, and once I
sat at my computer, I quickly realized that typing had become a
contact sport. I did love the sound, though. Whether my nails hit
Formica, wood or tile surfaces, it was my every tap-dancing fantasy
come true.
</P>
<P>
   My husband, who had shown no enthusiasm at all for this project,
was nonplused by the results. ``It's not he proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like the flower?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He squinted. ``Is that what that is?''
</P>
<P>
   I kept my promise to give him what I imagined would be a deluxe
back-scratch. But my nail tips felt strange on the skin, like
plastic, as if they were attached to a doll's hand. Back-Scratch
Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, no, I was missing the fun, I was counseled by Linda
Wells, editor in chief of Allure, who is an expert on all girl
things, including nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of nail art now is that it's done with a wink,'' she
said. ``Even if it's not American flags, women are definitely going
with wilder effects. Remember the Nicole Miller tie in the '80s? It
said, `I'm racy _ I'm wearing a kooky tie.' Nails are not next to
the face and don't affect the essence of how you look. If you
change your hair, you're stuck with it. You can be playful with
your nails, because it's temporary and then you move on.
</P>
<P>
   Nadia Yaron, a manicurist at the Antonio Prieto Salon, agreed.
``Nails have always been like a fashion accessory, and the kind you
have are a matter of taste,'' she said. ``But most women feel more
sophisticated with their nails. They feel sexy. It becomes an
obsession. Women come in even when they have no nails left, just
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The only obsession I have at this point is the packing tape I've
been trying to strip off the new roll for a week now. It's too
humiliating to ask my husband or even the doorman for help. Though
I've come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you feel more feminine?'' Ms. Baek had asked as I left
her spa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' I said wiggling my new tips. But a week later, the
jig's up. Yes, I enjoyed being a girl. It's just that I enjoy
opening a Diet Coke even more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
