<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN     10-01 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER COLUMN: MAVIS BEACON _ STILL TYPING AFTER ALL THOSE
YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know how old Mavis Beacon was when she first popped on
my computer monitor with her typing lessons some 12 years ago. So I
can't tell you now if she was 33 years old then and pushing 45 now,
or if she was 47 now and nearing 60.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the age, she doesn't look like she's nearing retirement
soon. The picture on the promotional materials for Mavis Beacon
Teaches Typing Version 10 is of a woman less than half retirement
age.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis doesn't exist. She's a Betty Crocker _ someone to give a
typing program a face and a personality. And like her counterpart
on the cake-mix boxes, she's done exactly what she was supposed to
do. Sales of the typing program have averaged 500,000 copies a
year; awards have been numerous.
</P>
<P>
   Her popularity is further proved on the shelves: Stores still
carry copies of previous versions _ priced lower than the estimated
street price of $50 for the new program _ because they still sell
well.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a reason to upgrade or buy the new version instead of
previous ones? Only if you can't do without some of the features
added to Version 10. One of the better ones: Users can now select
an age group and skill level when they go into the classroom to
sign up. Mavis will then select lessons appropriate for that group
while looking at the typist's strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   The program carries a guarantee to produce measurable typing
results for all students through 15 minutes of practice a day. It
offers frequent progress reports and sets benchmarks for speed and
accuracy for the student to beat in subsequent drills.
</P>
<P>
   The program is divided into three categories: classroom,
practice area and games. New this version is ``Far-Off Adventure,''
where students can practice typing rhythm. A smooth rhythm keeps a
hot-air balloon at the right speed and altitude. Other games
involve road races, undersea chase, space flights and grocery
checkout (for building skills on the computer keyboard's 10-key
pad).
</P>
<P>
   There's a new section of typing ergonomics that provides a check
list so students will know when they're typing correctly. To
further promote that, the program comes packaged with an ergonomic
mousepad (it has a rolled bottom edge to support the wrist) and a
stress ball to squeeze to exercise the fingers.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   LavaPort-Plus PCI is a plug-in card for computers with PCI
slots. The name of the card gives a hint of what it does: lava, the
melted rock flowing down from a volcano. The flow in the computer's
case is information sent to other devices.
</P>
<P>
   LavaPort provides two ultra high-speed serial ports capable of
handling data speeds of 460K bps and one enhanced parallel port to
which an external drive (like a ZIP) can be connected. The port
speed will be three times faster than the parallel port on the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``LavaPort-Plus (PCI) breaks the speed and interrupts
bottlenecks that limit expandability and performance in today's
personal computers,'' a company spokeswoman said. ``Combining both
serial and parallel port acceleration on one PCI bus card, the
LavaPort-Plus provides PC users with a single board _ and shared
IRQ _ solution for all of their I/O connectivity needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The new card builds on Lava's two popular products: a line of
COM port accelerators for modes and a parallel-port PCI accelerator
for Zip drives and parallel-port scanners. The new LavaPort-Plus
PCI provides both those capabilities in a single PCI-card.
</P>
<P>
   The company points out that users can now connect their external
modem to one of the card's serial ports, and use the additional
port to run their PalmPC or digital camera without using an
additional system interrupt.
</P>
<P>
   For information: Tollfree, 1-800-241-LAVA; Internet,
www.lavalink.com.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
