<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-JAPAN-NUCLEAR-HNS &LR;      10-01 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-NUCLEAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN-TYPE ACCIDENT NOT LIKELY HERE, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The nuclear accident similar to the one that
occurred in Japan on Thursday would not likely happen in the United
States because of special regulations and techniques used in this
country, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory are
tracking the path of a radioactive plume from the accident in the
village of Tokaimura 70 miles northeast of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that such an accident struck a uranium fuel plant
in the United States was July 24, 1964, in Wood River Junction,
R.I.
</P>
<P>
   In that accident, a nuclear worker received an extreme dose of
radiation _ about 40 times as much as a dose that would prove
lethal 50 percent of the time. He died 49 hours after the accident,
said Victor Dricks, spokesman for the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Dricks said the safeguards that are in place ``make it
extremely unlikely that we could have an inadvertent criticality
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his comments implied the Japanese nuclear program's
procedures are less strict, Dricks replied, ``I can't answer that.
We're not commenting on the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he didn't know if the Japanese accident would
trigger a federal review of safety procedures at U.S. nuclear fuel
manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
   Uranium nuclear fuel for commercial atomic reactors is
manufactured at seven plants in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Japanese and U.S. procedures for manufacturing
uranium fuel for nuclear reactors appear similar.
</P>
<P>
   Both involve so-called wet processes, involving liquid solutions
of chemicals _ resembling a dark sludge _ such as uranium
hexafluoride.
</P>
<P>
   A common type of nuclear reactor known as a light water reactor
works by burning uranium nuclear fuel in the form of uranium
pellets stacked inside long, thin tubes made of zirconium.
</P>
<P>
   Bundles of these zirconium tubes sit in a pool of water. The
liquid slows high-speed subatomic particles called neutrons so that
they can engage in nuclear reactions with the uranium.
</P>
<P>
   While the nuclear reactor is on, neutrons split Uranium-235
atoms, causing them to unleash more neutrons plus energy. The newly
unleashed neutrons then split other U-235 atoms, causing them to
spill even more neutrons and more pure energy. This generates
enough heat to drive a turbine that, in turn, generates electricity
for a commercial power grid.
</P>
<P>
   Because uranium atoms naturally decay over time, releasing
neutrons, it is essential to avoid putting too much uranium in one
place at a time, otherwise the steady rain of neutrons could
trigger a chain reaction and a very small explosion.
</P>
<P>
   In a nuclear bomb, chemical explosives confine the chain
reaction into a small space long enough to unleash an extraordinary
amount of atomic energy.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a normal criticality accident isn't nearly so
awful. If uranium-containing chemicals get too close together,
they'll generate just enough heat to blow themselves apart. That
separates them enough to shut off the nuclear reaction.
</P>
<P>
   During an accident like the one in Japan, victims see a blue
glow coming from the liquid solution in which they're mixing
uranium-containing chemicals. At that moment, a flood of neutrons
is ripping through their bodies, splitting DNA coils that control
heredity and upsetting the body's metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the victims feel nauseated and suffer diarrhea. In many
cases, excruciating suffering follows _ then death.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent such accidents in U.S. plants, officials maintain
tight limits on the amount of uranium hexafluoride that can be
placed into a tank at any one time, Dricks said.
</P>
<P>
   A different process, called a dry process, is used for handling
plutonium, at the Lawrence Livermore Laboratory, said lab spokesman
David Schwoegler. The lab has a plutonium research center used to
study the physics of plutonium deployed in nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Livermore's dry system _ involving poather than liquids _
is used because it is much easier to control than liquids,
Schwoegler said.
</P>
<P>
   In U.S. nuclear fuel manufacturing plants, some criticality
accidents have been caused by what experts call unfavorable
geometry _ that is, the chemicals getting into a shape that favors
a sudden critical reaction. The ideal shape for a disaster is a
sphere.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, in U.S. plants, workers pour uranium hexafluoride
into tanks that ``tend to be elongated, to minimize the likelihood
of a spherical arrangement'' of chemicals forming, Dricks said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a leading critic of the U.S. nuclear complex said processes
at manufacturing plants have improved since the early days of the
nuclear age.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States up through the mid-'60s, there were a
couple of dozen critical events throughout the weapons and civil
programs'' dealing with nuclear energy, but today ``it only happens
rarely,'' said Tom Cochran, a physicist who works for the Natural
Resources Defense Council in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the Japanese accident, Cochran said, ``It's going to
take months of investigation to determine why this happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
