<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO CONTACT PAUL TIBBETTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ I am doing school research on the dropping of the
atomic bomb on Hiroshima, Japan. How can I contact crew members of
the Enola Gay? _ T.B., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ You can contact the pilot, retired Gen. Paul Tibbets,
in care of Mid Coast Marketing, 1620 E. Broad St., Columbus, OH
43203. He also has an official World Wide Web site at
www.theenolagay.com.
</P>
<P>
   Tibbets piloted the Boeing B-29 Superfortress Enola Gay, which
dropped the atomic bomb on Hiroshima on Aug. 6, 1945, causing an
estimated 66,000 to 240,000 deaths. He named the plane after his
mother, Enola Gay Tibbets.
</P>
<P>
   Autographed copies of Tibbets' book, ``Return of the Enola
Gay,'' are available from his Web site. Book signings are scheduled
for Oct. 1-4 at the Confederate Air Force Air Show in Midland,
Texas, and Dec. 4-5 at the Flying Tigers Warbird Restoration Museum
in Kissimmee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ If you look at Texas license plates at an angle, you
can see circles with a series of numbers and letters. What is their
purpose? _ R.W., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ ``Those are lot numbers used for inventory and quality
control purposes,'' said Mike Viesca of the Texas Department of
Transportation. ``They are about the size of a quarter. Sometimes
they are in the middle, and sometimes on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers and letters are on the 3M-manufactured sheeting
material that covers each license plate and makes it more
reflective, Viesca said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a safety feature,'' he said. ``It has a lifespan of about
eight years; that's why license plates are changed every eight
years.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past fiscal year, Texas prisoners manufactured 7.56
million license plates.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Our church quit collecting canceled stamps. I don't
know what they were used for. Is there a charity that wants them? _
C.J., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Stamps for the Wounded, a not-for-profit group founded
in 1942, seeks donations of canceled stamps and other postal items
for redistribution to hospitalized veterans and outpatients.
</P>
<P>
   Donations should be in good condition, and if you are requesting
a receipt for tax purposes, include an inventory that estimates the
value of what you're sending.
</P>
<P>
   Send items to Stamps for the Wounded/LI, Box 1125, Falls Church,
VA 22041. To promote interest in stamp collecting and encourage
patients to be active, the group sends stamps and other supplies to
more than 11,000 veterans and stamp clubs at hospitals and
convalescent centers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
