<SLUG> BC-STATES-TRADE-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PENNSYLVANIA'S EUROPEAN TRADE TIES PROSPER, STUDY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 31, -- Europe might be a long way from
Pennsylvania but this year there were 167,300 jobs in the Keystone
state supported by European businesses, according to a Fall 1999
study by the European-American Business Council.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Pennsylvania was fourth in the top ten states supported
by European-generated jobs, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania's scene is part of the European investment
nationally, which reached $470 billion and about 6.5 million jobs,
according to the study. California, New York and Washington are the
top three exporters to Europe. Those states also have the most jobs
supported by European businesses. The study said strong
transatlantic economic ties continue to boost the U.S. economy, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
   Pennyslvania's top export is industrial machinery, and computer
equipment, which adds up to $768 million. Electronic and electric
equipment generated $569 million, with chemical products making up
$533 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
