<HEADLINE>
RUNNING AMOK WITH AOL? TRY THIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I guess anyone who has been online for more
than a month or so has an America Online horror story. I won't bore
you much. They knocked me off for several weeks and continued to
charge me. Disgruntled users should do what I did. Fire AOL. Don't
even try to call their help desk. Call your bank. Dispute any
current charges, and don't accept any new ones. You'll get
attention real fast. _ Righteously Indignant
</P>
<P>
   Dear Righteously: Half of America must be ticked off at AOL,
judging by the ton of e-mail clogging up my mailbox after I told
some guy to just tough it out until he got through to a rep so he
could actually quit. I've got no beef with AOL, but I haven't tried
to unsubscribe lately, either. Plus, I'm so full of Saint Johnswort
right now, I'm starting to think this old world of ours is a pretty
wonderful place where all we have to do is love one another. Tell
you what: I'll let you guys do the ranting for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: If you want to cancel AOL or another ISP, just
call your credit card company and tell them to refuse future
billing _ it's amazing how fast you will be canceled when you stop
paying. _ Chop 'Em Off
</P>
<P>
   Dear Chop: I wonder if that would work for my utility bills. I
don't think I really used all the electricity they said I did.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Several years ago, I was having the same
problem with Compuserve. I hastened the solution by ``cutting them
off at the credit card.'' That got their attention. There were a
few threatening letters and e-mails, but they finally stopped. No
matter how tough and insensitive some of these leatherheads are,
they have a tender spot somewhere. Keep probing until you find it.
_ Free at Last
</P>
<P>
   Dear Free: Aren't any of you guys worried about this stuff
showing up on your permanent records? I almost got turned down by
the mortgage company because I had disputed a J.C. Penney bill for
some jockey shorts. Anyone who knows me knows it's boxers or
nothing. Lord knows what the AOL goons would have put in my
financial folder.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I have found a phone number that AOL does not
give out freely that will help your reader cancel his service
without any problems: (888) 265-8008. _ Number's Up
</P>
<P>
   Dear Num: I actually tried this number on a Sunday afternoon and
got through to a real human being within 30 seconds. I was too
awe-struck to do anything but hang up, though. I should have at
least asked if his refrigerator was running. Better call it fast,
though, now that it's not a big secret anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: A suggestion: Write the attorney general of
Virginia. That is the state where AOL's headquarters is. The
address is: Office of the Attorney General, Anti-Trust and Consumer
Litigation Division, 900 E. Main, Richmond, VA 23219. _ Litigious
</P>
<P>
   Dear Litigious: Can't we all just be friends? I guess not. I
talked to a couple of suits at the AG's office last week while I
was making some other personal long-distance calls at work. Even
though AOL is in Virginia, they suggest writing your own state's
attorney general, then sending a copy of that to Virginia. Call 'em
at (804) 786-6551 if you have more questions. Use the phone at the
office.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay loves America Online, especially the live
chats with washed-up actors and other has-beens. Reach him at
drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com or via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax: 390-7257. In
real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
