`God's Little Acre' an earthy tale of the Deep South 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before TV sets were mass-marketed for American homes, reading
was a popular indoor pastime, certainly for adolescent boys. Books
were passed around, mostly paperbacks, and the most coveted items
were those with high quotients of sexual commotion.
</P>
<P>
   Was I a hypocrite? I professed not to like ``dirty'' books, and
some I did scorn, unread. But I certainly read Erskine Caldwell's
``God's Little Acre;'' and as soon as I finished it, I read it
again. Over a period of half a century plus, I've read ``God's
Little Acre'' I don't know how many times.
</P>
<P>
   If sexual curiosity was the initial lure, it soon ceased to be.
The lascivious goings-on in and around Ty Ty Hardin's rugged spread
in rural Georgia explain the novel's phenomenal sales _ more than
20 million copies in the Signet paperback edition alone _ but do
not define its greatness. ``God's Little Acre,'' Caldwell's fourth
novel, was published in 1933, one year after ``Tobacco Road'' made
him notorious. The two works have much in common: almost identical
Deep South rustic atmosphere, human characters reduced to
animality, and believably gamy dialogue sheathed in a rapid-fire
prose style.
</P>
<P>
   Only slightly tamer are some later, lesser-known Caldwell
studies of unlettered Georgia folk: ``Trouble in July, Journeyman,
A House in the Uplands, Tragic Ground, The Sure Hand of God.'' Each
may be worthy, but the author is vulnerable to a charge of writing
the same book many times.
</P>
<P>
   So why does ``God's Little Acre'' transcend the others? Not
because it's dirtier, if it is in fact so. Its strength is the
validity of characters with romantic and tragic substance quite
apart from their bawdiness. There's more sympathy here, or at least
there's greater compassion. ``God's Little Acre'' is a novel of
obsessions: Ty Ty Hardin is obsessed by the search for gold on his
rotted land. His son-in-law, Will Thompson, is obsessed by a need
to break into the closed-down mill and turn on the power. And
there's Pluto, the obese layabout, whose obsession is Darling Jill,
the youngest of Ty Ty's three voluptuous daughters. Where Jeeter
Lester of ``Tobacco Road'' is shiftless and apparently bereft of
ambition, Ty Ty is a committed dreamer, prodded by a primitive
religious faith. He is Dickens' Mr. Micawber transplanted in a
desolate, unforgiving earth.
</P>
<P>
   Bygone discovery of a few nuggets has fostered a local legend of
gold in this Georgia scrubland. Ty Ty is sure that his land will
yield gold, so he and his sons have pockmarked the spread with
holes from their incessant digging. Ty Ty continually redesignates
1 acre as belonging entirely to God. The widowed Ty Ty has little
to show for his life except three sons (one of whom has disowned
the family and gained wealth as a stockbroker in a nearby city) and
those three oversexed daughters (one of whom married Will Thompson
before the mill closed). Poverty is rampant, tragedy is inevitable,
yet the narrative is buoyed by a richness of folk humor.
</P>
<P>
   The story is funny and sad, not by turns but simultaneously.
``God's Little Acre'' and other Caldwell works were ineligible for
the Pulitzer Prize in fiction _ which, according to Joseph
Pulitzer's will, must impart a ``favorable impression of American
life.'' The lowest stratum of American life is Caldwell's own
preserve, and he was adamant that his novels did not exaggerate.
</P>
<P>
   Did people really live like this, and were they confined to a
specific region? Carolyn Chute's ``The Beans of Egypt, Maine''
would suggest that such primitivism prevails to this day, in the
Down East country as well. Two-thirds of a century have passed
since ``God's Little Acre'' apprised its first readers of our
nation's lower depths. It was a shocker then, but times and reading
have changed, and it doesn't shock now.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3632 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC--TEX     10-01 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
