<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-EXHIBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT FOCUSES ON THE PHOTOS OF GREAT ARTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``From today, painting is dead,'' French
academic painter Paul Delaroche proclaimed when he was first shown
a photograph in 1839, the year the process was made public.
</P>
<P>
   And in England, when he first saw the products of the machine
that recorded realistic impressions of the world by means of light,
J.M.W. Turner, whose atmospheric, proto-Impressionist canvases owed
little to a ``photographic'' vision, exclaimed, ``This is the end
of Art. I am glad I have had my day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the response to the camera eventually moderated.
Delaroche swiftly came around to seeing the virtue of using
photographs as a visual aid, urging fellow artists to compile
photographic archives of images they might find useful in their
work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the attitudes of early modern artists toward photography
was often grudgingly negative. Yet even as many of them dismissed
the medium _ Edvard Munch said, ``The camera cannot compete with
painting so long as it cannot be used in heaven and hell'' _ they
used it, often in ways that considerably determined the form their
art would take.
</P>
<P>
   The fascinating exhibition, ``The Artist and the Camera: Degas
to Picasso,'' at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art through
Jan. 2, examines the complex relationships 14 turn-of-the-century
artists had with photography. Organized by the Dallas Museum of
Art, it is accompanied by a dense catalog (Yale University Press;
$49.95, hardbound) that abounds in fresh scholarship. Those who
think they already know modern art might find that this show will
overthrow some of their preconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the surprises are some of the artists featured. We don't
expect to see Fernand Khnopff, Gustave Moreau, Alphonse Mucha or
Franz von Stuck at the museum. But modernism is far more complex
(and interesting) than the view that dates it only from 1900, as
the museum does. The museum might not collect art from before that
date, but it can certainly benefit from showing it from time to
time as its regular visitors can benefit from seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this is essentially a photography exhibition, an
important addition to the historical archaeology the medium has
undergone in recent years, the knock-out works are mostly paintings
and sculptures. Masterpieces by Edgar Degas (two pastels of ballet
dancers), Pierre Bonnard, Medardo Rosso, Constantin Brancusi and
Pablo Picasso (his ineffable rose period ``Boy With a Pipe'') are
of a quality not seen in local museum collections. And paintings by
some lesser lights, Khnopff, von Stuck and Felix Vallotton, for
instance, offer unexpected pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a thesis show, and it's not about ``great'' works,
even though it can boast of more than a few. And the idea addressed
_ how turn-of-the-century artists came to terms with the new medium
that utterly transformed image-making _ proves to be absorbing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The focus on photography's influence on painters and sculptors
who worked between 1885 and 1915 obscures the fact that the
exhibition is also a survey of Symbolism and its influences, the
primary interest, I suspect, of exhibition curator Dorothy
Kosinski.
</P>
<P>
   The thesis of the exhibition is made visually clear in the many
pairings of photographs with paintings, sculptures and works on
paper that relate to them, some of which are uncanny. The way
Munch, for instance, took two visually uninteresting studio
photographs of two female musicians and combined them to create a
lithograph, ``The Violin Concert,'' that is resonant with
unfulfilled longing goes to the heart of artistic creation _ the
ability to turn dross into gold.
</P>
<P>
   An even more dramatic example of artistic transformation is
evident in how Bonnard used a tiny 1 1/2-by-2 inch photograph he
made himself of a female nude reclining unalluringly on a bed in a
visually cluttered room to create one of his most erotic paintings,
``L'Indolente,'' an image of an open-legged nude sprawled upon a
large, sun-streaked, white-sheeted bed in solitary sensual abandon.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition makes it clear that there was no single pattern
followed by the artists investigated. Each of the 14 offers a
different model of how an inquiring artist can make use of a new
technological development.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the artists, like Degas, von Stuck, Khnopff and the
Nabis, Bonnard, Vallotton and Edouard Vuillard, took their own
photographs for their own purposes. Some, like Paul Gauguin and
Picasso, kept an archive of photographic reproductions of great art
masterpieces of different cultures for inspiration or to
appropriate when needed. Some, like Vallotton and Picasso, used
commercially available ``academies'' _ nude studies.
</P>
<P>
   Both Rosso and Brancusi took photographs of their sculptures
after they were completed, and Rodin, who never took a photograph
himself, commissioned photographers to document his work as it was
being made and after it was completed. In a unique instance, Degas
used Eadweard Muybridge's famous photographic time studies to make
physiologically accurate sculptures of galloping horses.
</P>
<P>
   None of these artists, however, took photographs that they
considered equal to their major work, however interesting we might
find them today.
</P>
</TEXT>
