<HEADLINE>
A SURVIVOR FROM THE GOLDEN AGE OF THE DAFFODIL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the fascinations of buying an old house with an
``established yard,'' as real estate ads call it, is discovering
the gardening tastes of its previous owners. Some former owner of
my old farmhouse planted a hedge of lilac, spirea and forsythia
closer to the house than I would have preferred, and I sometimes
wish for the cedar tree by the driveway to be magically transformed
into an oak.
</P>
<P>
   But the place is well supplied with old-fashioned perennials,
including a tall cultivar of heliopsis that I've yet to identify,
and irises and peonies of varieties that were popular in the 1930s
and '40s. And I was charmed the first spring to find a large clump
of Actaea daffodils growing at the edge of the kitchen garden in
the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   My daffodil expertise is limited, and it took me some time to
identify the variety. The daffodils bloomed so late in the season
that I could mix them in vases with lilacs, and were so fragrant
that the vases had to be placed near open windows to avoid
overpowering the room with the combined scent of lilac and
daffodil.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers are on the small side, with white, rounded petals
and a tiny yellow cup, gently fluted and rimmed with red. The stems
are slender and willowy, in contrast to the stout stalks that hold
up King Alfred's robust blossoms. In bloom, the clump looks like a
drift of large dogwood blossoms come to earth, or fairy faces
bobbing in a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, I understood the comments of the garden
writer Henry Mitchell that there is a difference between ``a superb
daffodil and a good old boy of a flower.''
</P>
<P>
   The name of the genus, Narcissus, is commonly thought to have
come from the Greek lad who was so taken with his own good looks
that he pined away over his reflection in a pool and was turned
into a narcissus flower. But it's more likely that it comes from
the Greek word ``narkao,'' which means ``to benumb'' and refers to
the narcotic properties of daffodil bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   The common name, daffodil, is a corruption of Asphodel, a lily
relative that hails from the same Mediterranean region as
daffodils.
</P>
<P>
   Daffodil bulbs, and to a much lesser extent their blooms, have
enough toxic alkaloids to be poisonous to people and animals. The
leaves and roots also contain needlelike crystals of calcium
oxalate, which make them indigestible and therefore unattractive to
deer and rodents.
</P>
<P>
   All this I learned in the process of identifying my pretty
clump, the inhabitants of which belong to the species N. poeticus,
or poet's narcissus. The cultivar Actaea dates to the 1920s. It was
a product of what aficionados call the golden age of daffodils,
when breeders stopped obsessing about tulips and started exploring
the possibilities of other bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 7,000 or so daffodil varieties created during that golden
age, Actaea is among the few still available today. Suppliers that
have it include White Flower Farm (P.O. Box 50, Litchfield, Conn.
06759-0050; 800-255-2852; www.800allbulb.com) and Old House Gardens
(536-W Third Street, Ann Arbor, Mich. 48103-4957; 734-995-1486;
www.oldhousegardens.com; catalog $2).
</P>
<P>
   I have it, too, and I'd like to have still more of it. As with
many perennial bulbs, it is possible to increase your stock of
daffodils by dividing them, and it's a good idea to do that
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Until I got acquainted with Actaea, I had assumed that daffodils
were perennial almost to the point of perpetual, and would thrive
with practically no attention from the gardener other than avoiding
cutting off the foliage until it had withered.
</P>
<P>
   If the bulbs have been naturalized with plenty of space between
them, they may not become crowded for more than a decade. But if
planted in clumps in flower beds, daffodils should be divided every
few years. My Actaea clump bloomed less freely than usual this
spring, a sign that it's overdue for dividing.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been best to do this in early summer, when the
foliage had withered but not disappeared. I always seem to miss
that ideal period, and I never have a bed prepared for the
daffodils in the summertime. My plan was to divide the Actaea in
the fall, as I did several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't be my first choice,'' Scott Kunst of Old House
Gardens said. The reason, he added, is that daffodil bulbs, unlike
many perennial bulbs, always have fibrous roots present, and those
roots begin growing actively again in the fall. If the tips are
damaged or dry out, root growth will be limited.
</P>
<P>
   N. poeticus cultivars, he said, are best moved in that brief
period after their foliage has withered, and then replanted
immediately. ``Poet's narcissus are notorious for never really
being dormant,'' Kunst said. ``But then I always say that gardeners
can do anything they want whenever they want, and the best time to
move the daffodils is when you think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That perfectly matches my general philosophy about garden tasks.
And since the Actaea transplanted several autumns ago seem to be
doing well, I believe I'll risk it again. To minimize trauma to the
daffodil's roots, I'll do it on a cool and dampish day when the
soil is moist and pliant.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were as easy to move that shrubbery a few yards
farther away from the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
