<SLUG> BC-BEAUTIFULGAME-SOCCER-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR IN THE LIFE OF A GIRLS' SOCCER TEAM OR, `HOW TO GROW UP A
WINNER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE BLACKMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Beautiful Game: Sixteen Girls and the Soccer Season That
Changed Everything''
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Littman
</P>
<P>
   Sports
</P>
<P>
   Avon, $23
</P>
<P>
   Reading Jonathan Littman's engaging account of one year in the
life of a teen-age girls' soccer team elicits more than a few
memories about proud-as-punch parents, painful losses and, more
times than your heart and patience can endure, wasted Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays like the steamy spring one a few years ago on Fort
Worth's west side Lions complex. That's when a bubbly, bow-headed
young mother, bedecked in chic sweats and matching tennies,
suddenly appeared on the sideline at half time, cooler in hand. One
look, and you just knew her Suburban was idling in the parking lot,
ready to whisk her to brunch at the club after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls,'' gushed the mother as she passed out petite water
bottles to her daughter's teammates _ who were all more interested
in comparing fingernails and friendship bracelets _ ``this is not
just ordinary water.'' She paused, as if to let the drama build.
``Girls, this is ``sparkling water!'''' All the little bowheads
squealed.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that's how many nonsoccer folk think of the sport
_ a game for the elite, for the white-dominated, monied suburban
crowd who have nothing better to do with their Saturdays but to
foist chilled juice and Rice Krispy treats upon their pampered
darlings.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately Littman's book, ``The Beautiful Game,'' is about the
grittier face of youth soccer. The girls of the Santa Rosa Thunder,
a Northern California team, come mostly from the more economically
challenged side of soccer tracks. These 13- and 14-year-olds aren't
chauffeured to practice in $40,000 SUVs, and don't gargle Perrier
at half time.
</P>
<P>
   Thunder is a new team, comprising remnants of a year-round Class
I team, the Eclipse, and a recreational-type Class III team, the
Fury, long mocked by Eclipse players. At best, the new Class I
Thunder, with its take-no-prisoners young coach, is an uneasy
alliance. But Thunder's goal is ambitious nonetheless: to win the
California State Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   You most definitely don't have to be a soccer parent to
appreciate ``The Beautiful Game,'' but it helps, for Littman
records in abundant detail all the familiar nuances and scenarios:
</P>
<P>
   Parents wondering why some kid is getting so much more playing
time than theirs ... Wondering why, if the coach is so darn smart,
she can't communicate without screaming ... Enduring the
foul-mouthed, abusive coach on the opposite sideline ... Worrying
about who's jumping ship to another team ... Trying to remember
what life was like, especially weekends, before soccer. And,
``we're paying good money for this?''
</P>
<P>
   One might be tempted to dismiss ``The Beautiful Game'' _ the
title comes from soccer legend Pele's nickname for the sport _ as
just another juvenile sports book. You yawn and your eyes begin to
glaze. Well, this is no ``Bad News Bears Make the World Cup.'' This
is a sports story about a team with a heady goal, so to speak,
driven by Emiria Salzmann, a coach gifted in her game (college
All-America) but painfully flawed as a leader of young girls. As
the story unfolds, half the time you want to slap Salzmann's silly
teeth down her 22-year-old throat; yet other times, you wish your
child could play for her.
</P>
<P>
   The Thunder's tribulations are many. It is the 1997-98 soccer
year, and all the obstacles of rampant egos and insecurities,
jealousies and conflicts, race to the fore. Even El Nino proves an
indomitable foe. Because of record rains that winter, the Thunder
girls often have to practice on swampy fields or tennis courts.
They practice several days a week, for 21/2hours, in the rain,
cold, hail and lightning. One has to admire their determination, if
not their good sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beautiful Game'' is sometimes uncomfortable reading,
because Littman, a former college soccer player, sugarcoats little
with his impressive behind-the-scenes reporting. But, then, that's
the same quality that makes the book compelling _ the intimate,
driving details of so many of the players, their coaches and
parents: Will bone-crunching Arlene, the team's enforcer, ever
learn to go easy on her teammates? Will the hugely talented
sweeper, Catherine, the team's quarterback, put school sports and
hanging out at the mall behind her and focus on Thunder? Will shy
Jenny, a reserve, and 95-pound Heather ever amount to a hill of
beans? How could the parent/assistant coach do what he did, and
will the young head coach who challenges coaching convention ever
prove herself right? Or grow up herself?
</P>
<P>
   So rich is the book's detail, especially about the 16 players,
that keeping characters straight in the early chapters can prove
challenging. But this is a minor hurdle. ``The Beautiful Game'' is
a story of a journey, an eventful and difficult journey for a team
and the players who comprise it, as well as for the girls' coaches
and parents. One father calls the excursion a love story; he may be
right. At the very least, it is the story of a talented, headstrong
and savvy group of girls who, in spite of circumstance and
themselves, forge a remarkable bond of mutual respect and uncommon
commitment, surprising themselves in the process.
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely why ``The Beautiful Game'' is about so much
more than soccer.
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Blackman is a former ``Star-Telegram'' editor and a
devoted soccer dad. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
