<HEADER>
A3652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-JIMENEZ-FASHION-ART-2     10-01 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIMENEZ-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAMING SHE-POWER AT A FASHION SPECTACLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fashion designer Elisa Jimenez first trained her
eyes on me last spring at a trendy downtown clothing store where
she was giving one of her bizarrely ritualistic custom fittings.
</P>
<P>
   One of her customer-acolytes was sprawled on the shop floor on
top of a piece of shimmery tea-stained fabric redolent of exotic
oils, while Ms. Jimenez expertly snipped around her and fastened
the material with transparent monofilament fishing wire. She bit
the line in half, burnt a few holes in the hem for a lace effect
and turned and smiled at me.
</P>
<P>
   She then grabbed my shoulders and looked straight into my eyes.
``You're a beamer!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A beamer?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You beam a very special energy. Would you like to model in one
of my shows?''
</P>
<P>
   I considered this an odd compliment. The only people who ever
tell me I should be a model are cab drivers and men lurking in
train stations. Perhaps Ms. Jimenez had spotted that hidden
something in me. ``Think about it,'' she whispered, slipping me her
number.
</P>
<P>
   I asked around and found out that I was just one of the hundreds
of women that the charismatic Ms. Jimenez had recruited at stores,
parties and on the streets of New York and Los Angeles over the
last few years for the Hunger World, the name of her label and
quasi-spiritual fashion sect that embraces sexuality, ancient
mythology and magic.
</P>
<P>
   Part performance artist, part designer, Ms. Jimenez, 34, likes
to sew her clothes directly onto the body and douse them in ginger,
eucalyptus and other spices. Her one-of-a-kind separates, with
prices from about $150 for a G-string to $800 for an evening dress,
have become favorites among celebrities known for their naughty
she-power personas like Courtney Love and Cher.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than show her clothes on a conventional runway, Ms.
Jimenez frequently stages orgiastic fashion happenings at old
churches, galleries and warehouses. She is one the few designers
represented by an art gallery; Holly Solomon Gallery added Ms.
Jimenez to their roster three years ago. They do not exhibit her
work on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they arrange private fittings for clients and
occasionally house her 20-minute-long, mythically titled
spectacles. In ``Claiming the Sacred Harlot'' and ``In the Woods
... Well-Come-Bliss-Dawn,'' Ms. Jimenez is joined by dozens of
women wearing her sexy wood-nymph outfits undulating to a live
opera singer or drums. Somehow, the clothes always manage to slip
below the bust or waistline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elisa's clothes have a way of bringing out your more daring
side,'' said Miranda Brooks, an editor at Vogue, who recalled a
posh fashion event in which a long red dress Ms. Jimenez had made
for her drifted well below her spine.
</P>
<P>
   To perform in these spectacles, Ms. Jimenez maintains an
ever-fluctuating group of artists, musicians, stylists and
actresses, ranging in age from 16 to 40, who dance and model free
of charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I select my models out of intuition,'' Ms. Jimenez said. ``I
don't care if they're 5 feet 2 or 6 foot 3 and pregnant, but they
have to be open-minded, and they have to trust that the situations
I put them in will be safe.''
</P>
<P>
   In return for their modeling services, Ms. Jimenez, who has a
tattoo of a red flower between her breasts that appears to bloom
when she opens her arms, dotes over these women and hosts sewing
circles. At the marathon gatherings, which can last all night, the
Hunger World models sip honey wine, tell stories and learn how to
make their own clothes, so they don't have to ``spend all their
money at Prada and Gucci,'' Ms. Jimenez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elisa makes you feel like a princess,'' said Sarah Tregor, 22,
a graphic designer, at a recent performance that was being filmed
for the Hunger World Web site.
</P>
<P>
   No one had ever called me a ``beamer'' before, and so, after
resolving that I had lived in New York too long to be seduced into
a cult, I decided to take my chances and join the Hunger World just
in time for Fashion Week.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jimenez said she needed me in a show that was part of a
group exhibition called ``Fantastic Planet'' at an old shipping
warehouse in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. The name of her performance
was ``Her Wild Horse Heart Matrix,'' and I had my choice of being
either a ``horse,'' which Ms. Jimenez said would require running
around with hooves on my hands, neighing and tossing my head
``rapaciously,'' or a ``heart,'' which would mean standing around
and ``exuding love.'' It wasn't a hard decision to make. I would be
a heart.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived for the 1 p.m. call time. (Our show was scheduled for
7:30 that night.) There were 20 or so other models, many of whom
were regulars and some ``newbies'' like me, sitting in a lot out
back, combing each other's hair and giggling.
</P>
<P>
   Among heaps of clothes, I noticed a jar of McCormick cinnamon,
which Ms. Jimenez explained would be sprinkled on the horse dresses
in the shape of a love sign to evoke prosperity and sexuality.
There were oils, a guitar and a copy of Jack Kerouac's ``On The
Road'' that belonged to one of the models. Over in the distance, a
young woman with a Walkman on was sleeping on a huge rock.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Jimenez looked like a female warrior, racing
around in tight brown tea-stained pants with sewing needles stuck
handily in the fabric. When it was time for my fitting, she led me
into a moldy bathroom with a clogged toilet.
</P>
<P>
   My heart dress was purple and white and extremely slinky,
low-cut down the back and high cut up the back of my legs. It
smelled ripe. ``I marinated the fabric in red wine, whiskey and
sugar,'' Ms. Jimenez said. ``So you'll be intoxicating.''
</P>
<P>
   For my hair, a volunteer in a blue camouflage T-shirt emptied
half a can of Edge shaving gel onto my scalp. ``It keeps the hair
looking wet,'' he told me. Ever heard of Paul Mitchell? I wondered.
I also wondered if anyone here even knew what the Hunger World was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all pretty vague,'' said the only male model, a thin
18-year-old ballet dancer named Misha Braun who had on brown
motorcycle boots underneath his horse outfit. ``But I feel like I'm
on the cutting edge of fashion. That band Hole wears her stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   I headed over to the other side of the parking lot. There, a
robust blonde named Silvie Jensen, 22, the in-house opera singer
for the Hunger World, was making patterns in the dirt. ``Elisa
wants me to sing the words `Do you know what you see when you see
what you know.''' Ms. Jensen confided. ``But I'm not going to do
it. It's too banal. I'm just going to sing vowel sounds like in
Mozart!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jensen would be modeling two clumps of clay that she would
smear over each breast. Ms. Jimenez planned to sell the clay tops
as part of her Spring 2000 collection.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 p.m., we had the runway set up. Ms. Jimenez's laid down
white masking tape on the pavement in a giant spiral. (It's
supposed to symbolize a labyrinth.) Around the outside, we placed
several large pieces of brown paper and fabric held down by rocks
to serve as seating for the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jimenez instructed me to drip ylang-ylang oil over
everything to induce feelings of love and openness. I decided to
smear a bunch on myself to enhance my mood.
</P>
<P>
   Show time. We all huddled in a little room, and Ms. Jimenez gave
us a pep talk. ``Don't be intimidated by the crowd, be confident,''
she said. ``You're all beautiful!'' No one seemed to know what was
going on. I looked around at our small group.
</P>
<P>
   One woman was almost twice as tall as everyone else, another was
pregnant, some had rolls of fat hanging out and some had armpit
hair. The thinnest ones were wearing loin cloths and tall black
boots.
</P>
<P>
   When it was my turn to go out, I waved my arms in the air like a
beating heart. Ms. Jensen was singing, ``Do you know what you see
when you see what you know.'' I could see my boyfriend through the
whirl of horse girls cantering around me, his mouth hanging open in
shock.
</P>
<P>
   I started to recognize people in the crowd. I closed my eyes and
tried to exude love. By the time I looked again, almost everyone
had gyrated off stage. Ms. Jimenez was standing on the side
``beaming'' like a proud parent.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunger World seemed like a nice place to visit, but I felt
it was time to go home. As I was leaving, Ms. Jimenez invited me to
an ``evening of reciprocity,'' as the post-show sewing circles are
called. It was held at one of the model's apartments at Union
Square. About 12 of the women showed up, and each had brought some
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzy Star, a folk rock group, played softly in the background,
and honey wine was served in paper Dixie cups. We talked about the
availability of Nike Air Rifts, the sneakers that separate the big
toe from the rest of the foot, and the film ``American Beauty,''
while Ms. Jimenez helped each woman make an article of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   She showed me how to sew a black halter dress. She cut a
pattern, and I stitched it up with transparent fishing wire. Five
minutes later, I pulled it over my head. All the women crowded
around my flirty cocktail number in awe. ``It's beautiful!'' they
cooed. I looked in the mirror. It was true. The same dress would
cost at least $700 at Barneys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
