<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-01 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO NEW EXAMPLES OF MOUSE EVOLUTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The computer mouse has come a long way, baby, since Douglas
Englebart's very first model, invented in 1963 as a simple wooden
shell on wheels. When it was finally patented in 1970, it was given
the catchy name of ``X-Y Position Indicator for a Display System.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, mice are the primary way folks interact with their PCs,
thanks to graphical interfaces and Web browsers. They're bristling
with new features, and you certainly won't suffer any wood
splinters from the smooth plastics and ergonomic shapes currently
used.
</P>
<P>
   And the mouse continues to evolve. A stroll down the
pointing-devices aisle at your local computer store will turn up
dozens of different styles and designs.
</P>
<P>
   I've been playing with two of the more advanced models from the
biggest players in the mouse category _ Microsoft and Logitech.
Both are excellent mice, but I sure wish either company would
combine the best attributes of both into one. It'd be a killer.
</P>
<P>
   _ IntelliPoint Explorer, $75, Microsoft: Anyone who has used a
computer for any length of time knows what eventually happens to
its mouse. No matter how clean you keep your workspace, dust, hair
and bits of grit are picked up by the mouse's ball and deposited
inside its housing.
</P>
<P>
   This junk gets onto the rollers that sense which way the ball is
moving _ and those rollers ultimately transmit location information
to the PC, which controls your cursor. If the rollers can't roll
smoothly, you get sluggish performance, or your mouse appears to
hit ``dead spots'' where the cursor won't even move.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's slick new IntelliPoint Explorer mouse fixes this
problem by doing away with the ball and replacing it with a bright
light and a tiny camera. The light points at the work surface, and
the camera snaps 1,500 ``pictures'' a second, reporting the changes
as movement back to the PC. That's a much faster report rate than
you get with a traditional mouse, resulting in smoother onscreen
movement. It also plugs into either a PS/2 or a Universal Serial
Bus port _ use the latter, if you can, for the best responsiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Because there's no ball, you don't need a mouse pad. You can use
this mouse on almost any surface, from the top of a desk to the top
of your thigh.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, this is not the first use of optical technology in
mice. Sun Microsystems for years made an optical mouse, but it
required a mirror-like mouse pad.
</P>
<P>
   The IntelliPoint Explorer, despite its klunky name, has a cool
design. It's a silvery gray on top and a translucent red on the
bottom. A bit of this translucent plastic curves up at the back of
the mouse, showing a red glow when the computer's on.
</P>
<P>
   It has two buttons in the usual place and a scrolling wheel
centered between them that, when pushed, serves as a third button.
There are two more buttons on the left side, where your thumb would
be, which are preset as forward and back browser-page controls. You
can, of course, reprogram all five buttons.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoyed using this mouse, particularly when playing
fast-action games, because it moved so smoothly, both on the
desktop _ where I'd removed my mouse pad _ and onscreen. My only
complaint about the design is that the thumb buttons are placed too
high on the side _ they should be lower, where the thumb naturally
falls when holding the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   This model is a bit pricey, but Microsoft also has a $55 version
that puts the light-and-camera feature _ which it calls IntelliEye
_ into its standard mouse body. Now, if only it was cordless ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Cordless MouseMan Wheel, $60, Logitech: Once you've used a
cordless mouse, it's hard to go back, and Logitech has long made
the best cordless mice around. Even after playing with Microsoft's
impressive new product, I'm probably going to return to this one.
</P>
<P>
   The Cordless MouseMan Wheel has the same rounded, satisfying
feel as the curvy Logitech MouseMan Wheel. Like the Microsoft
mouse, it's a silvery gray. It's got some heft to it, and will easy
fill a large hand. People with small hands might not find it as
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   It's got rubberized sides for a solid grip, and a thumb button
properly placed near the bottom of the mouse's left side. The wheel
centered between the right and left mouse buttons also can be
programmed as a button. It doesn't quite roll as smoothly as the
Microsoft wheel, however.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this mouse is best known for what it lacks _ a cord.
It uses radio waves to send its position signals to a small base
station _ about the size of a cigarette pack _ that plugs into a
computer's PS/2 port.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse uses a pair of triple-A batteries, which last about 4
to 6 months before they need to be replaced. You can tell when the
batteries are low _ the mouse occasionally loses contact with the
base station, which is easily fixed by pressing a button labeled
Connect on the base.
</P>
<P>
   Not having to keep a cord out of the way is a joy, particularly
in fast-action gaming. But, because of the limitations of the radio
frequencies used, the reporting rate to the computer is slower.
It's not something you notice in day-to-day Windows usage, but it
becomes quickly apparent in a hectic Quake III Arena firefight.
</P>
<P>
   Both mice come with useful software for configuring the various
buttons and other features. I prefer the Logitech MouseWare
program, which is easier to use and has more options.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this mouse doesn't use the USB port, but again,
the speed-up you'd get with that option is likely to be negated by
the radio connection. It would be nice to see some technology that
inexpensively speeds this up. Then, if Logitech just converted to
an optical system to replace the ball in its cordless mouse, I'd be
in pointing-device heaven.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
