A3670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MARRIAGE-REVIEW-NY     10-01 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARRIAGE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A RATHER ENGLISH MARRIAGE': A REMARKABLE DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review. Time,
channel are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(th) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reggie Conyngham-Jervis is not an effusive mourner. In the
person of Albert Finney, seated in a London hospital waiting room,
he turns to a man who has just told him that his wife, like
Reggie's, died the night before and says, barely looking up from
his newspaper, ``Well, look at the bright side, what?''
</P>
<P>
   That man also turns up at Reggie's wife's funeral and murmurs
sympathetically, ``One day at a time, eh?'' To which Reggie replies
brusquely, ``Whatever you say, old chap.'' This is one repressed
Englishman.
</P>
<P>
   So it's all the more devastating to see Reggie arrive home that
night and, without thinking, stop at the staircase and call,
``Mary!'' In that second, as he realizes with blow-to-the-gut force
what has happened, signs are good that in ``A Rather English
Marriage,'' the ``Mobil Masterpiece Theater'' series has come up
with a remarkable drama.
</P>
<P>
   The other fellow, Roy Southgate, is played by Tom Courtenay,
Finney's co-star in both the stage and film versions of ``The
Dresser.'' Again, Finney ends up giving orders; again, Courtenay
serves; again the two men come to recognize a meaningful bond;
again both actors are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, ``A Rather English Marriage'' turns into sentimental
odd-coupleness at times. But the film is compelling from the
beginning, and in the course of two hours there are enough flashes
of brilliance to make it very worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie is a gruff old guy who, more than 50 years after the war,
still encourages people (nurses, prostitutes, his pals at the pub)
to call him Squadron Leader. Roy is a gentle soul, a retired
milkman who tells the social services worker who visits him that
he'll be fine cooking and cleaning for himself, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie, visited by the same worker, flirts with her and asks her
to dinner. She suggests that Roy move into Reggie's house (Reggie's
wife had money, most of which she has left to her nieces) to help
with household chores and for companionship. He does, but he's soon
addressed as Southgate and treated like a servant.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are dealing with their grief mostly silently (through
beautifully photographed flashbacks of their younger selves with
their young wives). Roy has the added weight of visits to his son,
Alan (Sean Murray), in prison. Then a romance complicates things.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie meets Liz Franks (Joanna Lumley, as convincing in drama
as she is in comedy as the happily hedonistic Patsy Stone of
``Absolutely Fabulous''), an attractive, middle-aged dress shop
owner, at the pub and they go out a few times. That she seems most
interested in him when she has financial problems is not a good
sign. Through it all, 1940s big-band numbers like ``Pennsylvania
6-5000'' and ``Moonlight Serenade'' play, setting a mood of fond
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Rather English Marriage'' was written by Andrew Davies, who
has done television adaptations of ``Moll Flanders,'' ``Pride and
Prejudice'' and, a while back, ``To Serve Them All My Days.''
</P>
<P>
   The director, Paul Seed, has worked with Davies before, as
director of the BBC mini-series ``House of Cards'' and ``To Play
the King.'' Even when ``A Rather English Marriage'' gushes a
little, it's good to be in the hands of masters.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MASTERPIECE THEATER
</P>
<P>
   `A Rather English Marriage'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Sunday night at 9 (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written by Andrew Davies; directed by Paul Seed; Jo Willett,
producer; Alex Graham, executive producer for Wall to Wall
Television; David Thompson, executive producer for the BBC, and
Rebecca Eaton, executive producer for WGBH/Boston. A Carlton
International production.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Albert Finney (Reggie), Tom Courtenay (Roy), Sean Murray
(Alan), Joanna Lumley (Liz), John Light (young Reggie), Joanna
Scanlan (Sister), Priyanga Elan (Dr. Swann), Ursula Howells (Mary),
Katie Carr (young Mary), Aileen O'Gorman (Grace), Iain Jones (Young
Roy), Caroline Carver (young Grace), Rebecca Clarke (Nurse), Laura
Heath (Felicity) and Rosamund Pike (Celia).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
