<HEADER>
A3677 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      10-01 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Oct. 3, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   FERTILITY-BIOTECH-REVIEW (Undated) _ There is perhaps no more
unsettling noise in medicine than the sound of infertility
specialists tinkering with the biological clock. Witness the uproar
over their latest technological triumph, the apparent reversal of
menopause in a 30-year-old ballerina whose ovaries had developed
cysts. But the most remarkable thing about the supposed end of the
biological clock may be just how unrevolutionary the reproductive
revolution has been. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-RACE-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ Five years after the death
of apartheid, some South Africans are still struggling to redefine
themselves and their roles here. And some are finding that old
classifications fade slowly from the hearts and minds, the politics
and economics of the new South Africa. By Rachel L. Swarns. (`i'
category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   VISITATION-RIGHTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The idea that grandparents
have a right to see their grandchildren has much sentimental
appeal. But the legal issue of what third parties should have
visitation rights, even against a parent's will, is complex. In
Washington state, visitation rights were awarded under a law giving
such privileges not just to grandparents, but also to unspecified
third parties, if continued contact is in the child's best
interest. The U.S. Supreme Court will consider the
constitutionality of that law, in a case closely watched by
family-law experts By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FATHER&AMP;SON-REVIEW (Washington) _ As George W. Bush stakes
his own claim to the White House, he and his father still seem to
be resolving _ or, just as often, failing to resolve _ how to play
this whole filial-parental thing. And they continue to discover
that the elder Bush's history and the younger Bush's destiny
intersect in odd and unexpected ways. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-CHOKING-REVIEW (Undated) _ The psychology, and history,
of choking. Clutch and choke, as sporting terms, came from auto
racing and spread to other sports. Hemingway, writing about Joe
DiMaggio, defined `clutch` performance for all time: `Grace under
pressure.' `Choke` has never needed a Hemingway to define it. By
Allen Barra.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUDGET-REVIEW (Washington) _ The GOP, custodians of fiscal
responsibility, in the hot seat. It has been the deliberate
strategy of House Republicans to promise the American people that
they would not finance the operations of the government by spending
money out of the Social Security trust fund. To try to keep this
promise, the Republicans thus far have used every accounting device
in the book, and some previously unrecorded, to try to make the
numbers add up the way they want. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-LAUNDER-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at why it's so hard to
nail the bad guys in money-laundering cases. Much of the money
flowing around the world these days flits across borders
electronically in the blink of an eye. And that can be much harder
for banks to monitor than paper checks. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   REAGAN-BIO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Critics have chided Edmund Morris
for writing Forrest Gump-or-Zelig-meets-the-Gipper instead of a
conventional biography of Ronald Reagan. But such comparisons are
inexact. Forrest Gump and Zelig were comic creations, while Morris
is a serious biographer with a serious mission. He is trying to
make myths in the only way they can be made in these ironic times:
by pretending someone else is narrating.
</P>
<P>
   TWAIN-HANGING-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Back when hangings were a
gruesome public spectacle, people turned out to see the show _ Mark
Twain included. His eyewitness account of a celebrated 1868 hanging
in Virginia City, Nev., was recently rediscovered. Some excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week, leading
with Warren Beatty as a possible presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-REVIEW (Washington) _ Half a century of fearing
China: if you ask the `Old China Hands' _ men like like John Paton
Davies and his younger counterparts who traveled the countryside as
Mao battled the Nationalists _ the problem of striking a balanced
view of China in Washington has never been easy. In fact, the
popular imagery has almost always been out of sync with the
reality. By Alan Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE-REVIEW (Paris) _ The report that U.S. soldiers
massacred civilians in the Korean War raises a larger question: at
the end of the 20th century, the century of total war, can the
protection of civilians ever be more than a thin pretension, even
when protecting civilians is the declared war aim? Recent
experience in the Balkans is not encouraging. By Craig Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RIGHTS-REVIEW (London) _ Britain prepares for a
constitutional revolution that will profoundly alter its citizens'
relationship to the state and the rule of law. A year from now,
when Britain incorporates the European Convention on Human Rights
into domestic law, ordinary Britons will for the first time have a
set of fundamental human rights that can be enforced in British
courts, similar to those guaranteed by the Bill of Rights in the
U.S. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Photo-Graphics editor is Deborah Marchand
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 603-1036
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: marchand(at)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECHNICAL PROBLEMS: &LR;  Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com. &QL;
