<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANATOMY-ARCHITECTURE-     10-01 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANATOMY-ARCHITECTURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEPRINTS IN GENES: ARCHITECT'S BODY OF WORK MAY BE MORE THAN JUST
METAPHOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time. And space. Sooner or later,
someone was bound to suggest that architecture is a biological
function. Since classical times, buildings have been likened to
bodies. Now the metaphor has grown up: buildings are not just like
bodies; they are deeply biological.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars are now saying the kinds of buildings that people
design and the choices they make about where to put them are, to
some degree, inherited. Architecture is part of what Richard
Dawkins has called ``the extended phenotype,'' genes' ``effects on
the world at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Biology and architecture have been through a lot together. The
Roman architect Vitruvius codified the idea that the proportions of
buildings should be based on the ideal human form. In the
Renaissance, the metaphor was revived. Descartes compared muscles
to pneumatic devices. And Claude Perrault, designer of the east
front of the Louvre, explained the action of an arm _ its extension
and flexion _ by the mechanical analogy of a mast held by two
ropes.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, biological metaphors for building started
to get out of hand. Dr. Adrian Forty, a historian of architecture
at University College, London, wrote in ``The Architecture of
Science'' (MIT Press, 1999) that Viollet-le-Duc first used the word
``circulation'' to describe humans moving around a building in
1872, some 250 years after Sir William Harvey used ``circulation''
to describe blood moving around a body. It was not the best of
metaphors. As Forty points out, people do not generally move round
and round in a building, hitting every room. But the metaphor was
still wildly successful, reaching its peak in Le Corbusier's
proposition ``Architecture is circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Why so popular? Forty believes it's because it made architecture
seem scientific. ``Each one of the countless scientific metaphors
in 20th-century architecture is a little experiment, an attempt to
find a relationship between architecture and one or another branch
of science,'' he writes, ``but they all rely on our belief that
really, at the bottom, architectural practice is not scientific,''
that ``architecture cannot reach where science may.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century pushed the parallels between building and
biology to the breaking point. In 1928 Hannes Meyer, the second
director of the Bauhaus, declared, ``Building is a biological
event.'' What he meant was that buildings are not designed so much
as determined by their function and the constraints of construction
and materials. Buildings are not works of art. They are
technological organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Dreary as Meyer's formulation was, it did parallel some of the
lessons of D'Arcy Thompson's 1917 book ``On Growth and Form.'' If
Thompson showed how ``the forms of living things'' and their parts
_ skeletons, eggs, eyes, webs, shells _ ``can be explained by
physical considerations,'' Meyer did his best to enforce nature's
sternest laws.
</P>
<P>
   Now the building metaphors have gone genetic. In ``The
Monumental Impulse: Architecture's Biological Roots'' (MIT Press,
1999) Dr. George Hersey, an emeritus professor of art history at
Yale University, enumerates the similarities between nautilus
shells and spiral staircases, termite mounds and obelisks,
honeycombs and dome interiors, and concludes that the desire to
build is ``in our genes.'' Human beings appear to have inherited
some sort of architectural impulse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are genetic homologies between us and the other species
that build, no matter how distant from us they seem,'' Hersey
writes. ``Science writers are always calling the genome a
blueprint; now I will call a blueprint a genome.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally there are problems with this idea. One of the biggest
stumbling blocks is that even though bees and termites are
wonderful architects, ``our own closest cousins, the other
primates, hardly build at all,'' Hersey writes. ``An African
termitary might remind us of Wright, or a Gaudi spire, or of a
skyscraper by Hermann Obrist. But no such thought comes to mind
when we look at the rudimentary retreats of chimps and gorillas.''
</P>
<P>
   Apes are terrible architects. ``Thus any genetic homology that
brackets us with the other builder-species will have to be very
ancient and, also, will have to have bypassed our immediate
ancestors and cousins,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds pretty unlikely, doesn't it? But Dr. E.O. Wilson, a
biologist at Harvard University, says there may be a kernel of
truth in it. Although the kinds of rules that determine the way
that nautiluses grow shells and the way termites build their
platforms and arches are far, far simpler than the kinds of rules
that determine the way human architects build, it is possible that
humans have inherited a monumental impulse, perhaps even an impulse
to build certain kinds of structures.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says that when it comes to certain esthetic judgments _
the way human beings see and talk about color, decide how much
complexity they like in a painting or think about where they would
want to live _ there are ``genetically determined regularities,''
inherited tendencies they share with the rest of the species.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Wilson was not ready to say anything about what kinds
of buildings human beings are wired to build and to like, he gladly
offered a description of the kind of real estate they are wired to
prefer. In much the same way that the Russian artists Vitaly Komar
and Alexander Melamid surveyed people around the world to find out
what they like in a painting (they love lots of blue), so Dr.
Gordon Orians, a zoologist at the University of Washington, has
surveyed people about their taste in landscape. (What they like are
places that alleviate their most primitive anxieties about
survival.)
</P>
<P>
   In a recent lecture to the American Society of Landscape
Architects at Harvard's Graduate School of Design, Wilson expanded
on Orians' findings about human landscape preferences. Given
complete freedom, Wilson says, people will gravitate to
environments with the following features: ``They want to live, to
have their habitation on a height, looking down. They prefer open
savannalike terrain, parkland with scattered trees and copses. And
they want to be near a body of water, such as a river or lake,''
even if the water has no function.
</P>
<P>
   They also want a retreat with good prospects for foraging. They
want to see ``trees that have low, nearly horizontal branches,
preferably with compound, finely divided leaves,'' he said. And
they want to see large animals, like deer and sheep, scattered off
in the distance. That may be why people decorate their lawns with
animal statuary, Wilson observed in a telephone interview. (Lawn
jockeys are still a mystery.)
</P>
<P>
   Wilson even speculated about why humans have inherited these
tastes: ``People want to be in the environments in which our
species evolved over millions of years: that is, hidden in a copse,
against a rock wall, looking out over savanna and transitional
woodlands at acacias and other similar dominant trees of the
African environment. And why not?'' Animals have a tendency, ``an
inborn guide,'' he said, to go toward the micro-environments that
they need to survive, and so do humans.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the properties of human behavior, he said, are so
natural that people don't even realize they are there. But one day,
he suspects, humans will not only recognize them but understand
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the threshold of a new theory of art,'' a theory
that will explain human esthetic judgment, he said. In the meantime
it's probably good to remember that one of the things humans like,
one of the things that separates people from termite builders _
other than lawn animals _ is ``that humans metaphorize'' about
their buildings, Wilson said. Termites don't.
</P>
</TEXT>
