<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL REPORT FOR SATURDAY, OCTOBER 2, 1999 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SATURDAY'S KEY GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Purdue 4-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 at Michigan 4-0
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Michigan contained one Heisman Trophy candidate
in Ron Dayne, the Wisconsin fullback. Now it faces another in Drew
Brees, the Purdue quarterback, whose offense is averaging 477 yards
a game. Purdue has won 10 consecutive games, but Michigan has the
defense to end that.
</P>
<P>
   No. 21 Alabama 3-1
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 Florida 4-0
</P>
<P>
   Alabama upset Arkansas last week despite six turnovers. Florida
is something else. The Gators are averaging 43.5 points and 518
yards a game, and their defense held pass-happy Kentucky to 10
points.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8 Virginia Tech 3-0
</P>
<P>
   No. 24 Virginia 3-1
</P>
<P>
   A good test for Virginia Tech, the best team in the Big East.
Its defense (164.7 yards a game) ranks first in the nation.
Virginia can run, as witness Thomas Jones' 210 yards against
Brigham Young.
