<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOSE JOB IS IT TO PROTECT ME AND MINE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within hours after the shootings at the Wedgwood Baptist Church,
a letter arrived at the ``Star-Telegram'' expressing the wish that
I had been inside the church on that deadly Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I had, too, but for a different reason than the writer's
desire for me to witness the carnage left by two handguns wielded
by a raging paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   At least the seven victims would have had a fighting chance.
</P>
<P>
   Every time this argument is raised by proponents of
concealed-carry permits for private citizens, gun-control advocates
counter that they don't want public venues turned into some
modern-day version of the OK Corral. Firearms should be left to the
professionals, they say _ law enforcement officers trained in their
use.
</P>
<P>
   The first concern has been proved as statistical nonsense. Since
1987, 24 states including Texas have permitted the concealed
carrying of handguns by law-abiding citizens. The country has yet
to experience such an occurrence. Despite macabre hopes to the
contrary, concealed-carry does not lead to bloody rampages. Folks
will have to look elsewhere for the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   The second argument _ leave the guns to the police _ reflects a
naivete that could turn you or your loved ones into victims. As
well-intentioned as every man and woman who wears a badge might be
to protect and serve, it is not now and has never been their job to
protect your individual hide _ or your child's. A slew of court
cases confirm that law enforcement is necessary to help keep peace
throughout society, not to protect individual citizens.
</P>
<P>
   As far as training goes, state certification standards for peace
officers require that they qualify with their firearms once a year.
No other proficiency training is mandated for the average patrol
officer in Texas _ the type of officer who initially will be
dispatched to your house in your time of need _ to take his or her
gun from the holster.
</P>
<P>
   Qualification takes 20 minutes. And it's done while the officer
stands still and shoots at a fixed target in broad daylight. No
night shoots. No moving targets.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, many police departments go beyond what the Texas
Commission on Law Enforcement Officer Standards and Education
requires for officers to keep their licenses, but any police
department training officer speaking honestly will admit that the
rank and file spend precious little time at the gun range.
</P>
<P>
   When the bad guy is crawling through your child's window, do you
want to trust that the police, with an average response time in the
Metroplex of about seven minutes for Priority 1 calls, will be
there in time to help? A lot of damage can be done in that time.
Look what Larry Gene Ashbrook did in less than 10 minutes, with a
police officer at home across the street from the church when the
shooting started.
</P>
<P>
   The argument always turns to a ban on handguns. If no one but
the law had them, then America wouldn't be agonizing over the
sporadic but nightmarish situations that occur when they are
misused. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose that Congress does vote to ban private ownership
of handguns. From henceforth, the manufacture, sale and importation
of handguns are forbidden by federal law. Why, that's a strategy
that has worked wonders for illegal narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   As keen as the desire might be among some people for this to be
reality, the experiences of such bans in other nations show the
deficiencies. Take Australia, which recently instituted a
nationwide ban on private ownership of many types of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ban, 84 percent of the homicides Down Under were
committed with something other than a gun, and the homicide rate
had been level for 80 years. One high-profile case involving a
gunman at a resort was enough to push policy-makers to change the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's homicide rate has risen more than 3 percent since
the surrendering of more than 600,000 guns by law-abiding citizens;
assaults have increased by more than 8 percent; and armed robberies
_ bad guys don't turn in their guns _ have increased 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In England, which is often cited by gun-control activists as a
model for strict gun ownership, people are 40 percent more likely
to be mugged or assaulted than in America, according to a study
done three years ago by the U.S. Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Does the United States have a problem with the misuse of
firearms by a minuscule percentage of the population? Yes. Are
there reasonable steps that can be taken to curtail the potential
for future problems, even though violent crime is statistically
down in this country? Probably.
</P>
<P>
   But telling me and mine that we must rely on law enforcement to
ensure individual safety is a leap of faith I'm not willing to
gamble on.
</P>
<P>
   I'm married to a police officer. I have my own security detail
living under the same roof. Guess who's the one in the family to
insist that we spend time at the shooting range?
</P>
<P>
   He knows better than anyone that the only person who can give me
a fighting chance to survive an attack is me.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe &LR; star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
