<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HANDICAP-SKIER-ART-NY     10-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDICAP-SKIER-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  
 WHIDDON CAN'T WALK, BUT HE'S A WORLD CHAMPION WATER SKIER  (mk) 
 By DICK SCANLON   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLK CITY, Fla. _ At one time, Clay Whiddon was a natural as a
water skier. That is no longer the case, although he is a world
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Whiddon grew up near Lake Arianna in Auburndale and learned to
love the water early in life. By the time he reached the age of 21,
he could do just about anything behind a boat with a rope in his
hands _ with or without skis.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed abruptly in a single-car accident 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a tree. The steering wheel went through my chest and
killed my spinal cord,'' Whiddon said. ``I'm very fortunate. They
told me I'd never walk again.''
</P>
<P>
   For about nine months, Whiddon was completely paralyzed in a
wheelchair. Getting up on skis wasn't something he cared to think
about, even after he was informed it was being done by disabled
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of had a little ego problem then,'' he said. ``If I
couldn't ski like I used to ski, I didn't want to ski at all.''
</P>
<P>
   So for more than a decade, he didn't. He raced Go-Karts for a
while, studied computer systems at the University of South Florida
and gradually regained the use of most of his body. Whiddon learned
that a lot of people are far worse off physically than he is and
that some of them are serious water skiers.
</P>
<P>
   That was his first step toward winning the overall gold medal in
the MP3 division at the World Disabled Water Ski Championships last
month. He competed on a sit-ski, a water ski adapted so it can be
maneuvered from a seated position.
</P>
<P>
   Whiddon went to Heron Lake in Wraysbury, Middlesex, Great
Britain, as a complete unknown and came home with five medals. One
of the gold medals was for being a member of the champion American
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there as an alternate,'' said Whiddon, who had to
qualify for the team last year. ``Then somebody got hurt at the
nationals, and I went in and it was just kind of my week. Plus, I
had gotten better. In '98, when I qualified for World, I was new at
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament's official program includes no mention of the
35-year-old Whiddon, who set a world MP3 record in trick skiing
(1,010 points), won a silver medal in slalom and finished fifth in
jumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty much a newcomer,'' he said. ``Most of the people at
that level have been doing it for a number of years. But being from
around here and having skied before was a great advantage, and now
I think I can continue to compete at this level for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that will require a lot of traveling and, at some point, a
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3 Class is for paraplegics who are the least disabled.
There are tests and strict guidelines placing skiers in their
respective classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very grateful to be able to do the things I can,'' said
Whiddon, who lives in Polk City and trains five days a week nearby
at the Lake Hamilton Water Sports ski school. ``I'm on the upper
end of disability.
</P>
<P>
   He said when he first heard about sit-skiing, he didn't think
many people would be interested. ``But when I got back into it, I
found it was very competitive,'' he said. ``It's been a great
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
