<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BEATTY-2000-HNS &LR;      10-01 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATTY-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPASSIONED BEATTY ADDS TWIST TO POLITICAL SEASON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Warren Beatty's last movie role was a naive
politician. What would be so strange then about his moving to a
real-life campaign for president?
</P>
<P>
   A White House bid by the 62-year-old Hollywood legend would be a
piquant turn for an actor long given to liberal causes and just one
more twist in a political season that may be far more interesting
than seemed possible a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not many associates _ in the movie business or Washington _
believe Beatty will ultimately take the plunge, but he has not
ruled it out.
</P>
<P>
   A phalanx of journalists from around the world gathered
Wednesday night at a Beverly Hills hotel to await word as Beatty
received an award from the Southern California chapter of the
liberal Americans for Democratic Action.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders predicted yet another tease. And they were right.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of an impassioned defense of his liberal agenda,
including a call for recognition of Fidel Castro's Cuba, Beatty
coyly addressed a mythical drum majorette who might be considering
a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no harm in thinking about this, however unlikely it
may be,'' Beatty told a ballroom full of fellow left-wingers who
had whooped it up throughout his remarks. ``But whatever you do, go
ahead and speak up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speak up for the people nobody speaks for. Maybe you'll
influence some people. Maybe you'll influence the party. Maybe
you'll influence the candidates who are running.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his remarks Beatty expressed dissatisfaction with the
two candidates for the Democratic nomination, Vice President Al
Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, and only modest
hope they might find their way to a more liberal path.
</P>
<P>
   In closing, Beatty urged his audience: ``Keep talking. Keep the
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   That apparently is what Beatty plans to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll assess it and decide whether he's serious or not,'' said
one of Beatty's political friends as the crowd filed out of the
Beverly Hilton, some disappointed they had not gotten a clearer
sign from a famously enigmatic figure.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, say political operatives with Hollywood connections,
Beatty is most interested _ as he has made clear _ in affecting the
debate, especially in the Democratic Party, which he believes has
become too comfortable and too inattentive to its historic
constituency among the less well off.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem anomalous for a wealthy actor, director, writer,
producer _ and former playboy _ who lives with his actress-wife,
Annette Bening (who has already played the president's girlfriend,
but opposite Michael Douglas), and a growing young family in the
Hollywood Hills.
</P>
<P>
   But not, perhaps, for a movie man whose last film was
``Bulworth,'' in which he starred as a Democratic senator from
California who has a nervous breakdown in the midst of the
intellect-dulling nature of high-dollar politics and begins to
speak oracular truths _ in rhyming rap as he woos a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   And not strange given the tightening of the race for the
Democratic nomination between Gore and Bradley. Beatty apparently
figures there's no reason he should take himself out of
speculation. A situation might crop up in which a long-shot
outsider with a distinctive message might have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beatty could be a very strong candidate, could be a very fine
president,'' said former Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who sought
his party's presidential nomination in 1984. ``He's been working in
politics and campaigns for 35 years. He knows the issues upside
down and backwards. He's never going to be caught making some
blunder because he doesn't understand some issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by his speech Wednesday, Beatty would be the most
unabashedly liberal candidate in a major party since the Rev. Jesse
Jackson sought the Democratic nomination in 1984 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his remarks, Beatty described himself as ``an old time,
unrepentant, unreconstructed, tax and spend, bleeding heart, tax
and spend Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the value of social programs,'' he said. ``I
believe in the safety net. I believe in regulation. And I believe
in active government.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty was most pointed in criticizing what he sees as the
self-satisfaction of the Clinton-Gore administration with the
economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we gloat about prosperity when the poverty level
hasn't changed at all?'' Beatty demanded.
</P>
<P>
   After ticking off some bad economic indicators, Beatty asked:
``Do we have a party that quietly shoves this stuff under the rug
and says, 'Most things are going right for America...?' What would
Hubert Humphrey say today?''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty blasted what he sees as Democratic complicity in
sacrificing labor and environmental interests to the increasingly
international economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need a third party. We need a second party,'' Beatty
declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we come to the point where the Democratic Party needs to
have a Republican president before it finds its voice again?''
Beatty asked. ``A rising tide is not lifting all boats.''
</P>
<P>
   But Beatty sought to draw a bright line between his views on
global economics and the protectionist proposals of Pat Buchanan,
who may quit his race for the Republican presidential nomination
and seek to be the Reform Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Buchanan is wrong,'' Beatty said. ``We can't build a wall
or turn our backs. We have to work with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beatty boomlet began last month when speculation about his
prospective candidacy appeared in a column by Arianna Huffington, a
generally conservative gadfly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if he doesn't run, he will have shaken up the ossified
system,'' Huffington said as she arrived for the dinner, clearly
thrilled with having stirred the political pot.
</P>
<P>
   Her championing of a Beatty candidacy has drawn barbs. Fellow
columnist Mark Shields, a center-left Democrat, said it was as if
Anthony Lewis, the liberal New York Times columnist had promoted a
presidential candidacy by actor Charlton Heston, the conservative
activist and gun-rights spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty seemed to rule out a campaign in an op-ed piece that ran
newspapers in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 35 years of liberal activism as a Democrat, I am being
urged by some people to spend 40 years of fame on a presidential
campaign,'' Beatty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no wish to diminish the capable, cautious centrists Al
Gore and Bill Bradley, who have unselfishly devoted much of their
lives to public service when they could so easily have enriched
themselves in the private sector, as I have.''
</P>
<P>
   But after an indictment of the party's current stance on issues
foreign and domestic and a call for public financing of all federal
campaigns, Beatty tantalizingly signed off with: ``Stay tuned.
We'll be back after this message.''
</P>
<P>
   The dinner crowd of about 1,000 included a glittering
cross-section of the Hollywood Left: Hustler publisher Larry Flynt,
Courtney Love, Dustin Hoffman, Faye Dunaway (who played Bonnie to
Beatty's Clyde), Morgan Fairchild, Mike Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   A taped presentation praising Beatty started rolling with Barbra
Streisand and ended with historian Arthur Schlesinger Jr. urging
the actor to ``Keep up the debate, Warren, and let us save our
party.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, were cameos that included: Rob Reiner, former Texas
Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower, Penny Marshall, Goldie
Hawn, Paul Newman and Sean Penn. The heavily reconstructed Roseanne
asked Beatty to include free plastic surgery in his health plan,
and comedian Gary Shandling, in true Hollywood fashion, urged the
actor to seek billing ``above the country,'' as in ``Warren Beatty
in the United States of America.`` Beatty was introduced by
producer Norman Lear, founder of the liberal advocacy group People
for the American Way, who encouraged him to ``kick some tires.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was the Beatty dinner over than Hollywood was
tantalized by the news that Arnold Schwarzenegger might run for
governor of California as a Republican in 2002. He'd have to stop
there, however, as the federal Constitution requires presidents be
native-born _ and he's a naturalized citizen, having been born in
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
