<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALIBI-BOOK-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME LACED WITH ROMANCE MAKES FOR A DEFENSIBLE `ALIBI'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHY HARRIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Alibi''
</P>
<P>
   By Sandra Brown
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Warner, $25.95
</P>
<P>
   ``The Alibi,'' Sandra Brown's latest novel, isn't completely
ironclad, but it is well worth investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Straight-arrow Charleston assistant district attorney Hammond
Cross (an assistant county solicitor in Southern-speak) stops by a
county fair to blow off some steam and ends up in a very sticky
situation (no, not cotton candy). Within hours of meeting a mystery
woman at the fair, he ends up tangled in a web of sex, lies and
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Alibi'' gets off to a promising, steamy start, it
suffers a mild case of predictability. You know Cross will resort
to ``redial'' to get a lead on the mystery woman at least a page
before he actually does it. And the ending, in particular, holds no
surprises. There's also a problem with continuity. At the end of
one chapter, a character leaps to her feet to defend herself. At
the beginning of the next chapter, her attorney tells her to stand
up, they're leaving. But this is a minor flaw that should have been
caught by a sharp-eyed editor.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Brown throws a few curveballs I didn't see coming.
She kept me guessing until the very end about the identity of the
killer, and she tosses in some surprises that interconnect
characters, much like an episode of the dearly departed ``Melrose
Place.'' She's also adept at jumping from one location to another
to build suspense, a tactic that can backfire and leave some
readers confused in the hands of lesser writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Alibi'' is sure to be a movie of the week _ a casting
agent's dream. The characters are engaging, and Brown does a nice
job of adding them to the story unexpectedly, making the reader
wonder what's around the corner, and how can this person possibly
be involved? But the story bogs down when it gets to Cross and the
mystery woman, who suffer from too much thinking out loud in the
form of questions. For example, Hammond Cross ponders: ``How could
one, anyone describe the instant when it all comes together? How to
describe that burst of clarity when one knows that his life has
only just now begun, that everything that's happened before was rot
compared to this, and that nothing will ever be the same again?''
It's nice to know what's on the characters' minds, but not in the
form of 20 flowery questions.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the characters aren't so besotted, and a couple are
refreshingly funny. One comment made me laugh out loud. (Sorry, I
can't repeat it in a family newspaper.)
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Brown fans won't be disappointed by ``The Alibi;'' but
hard-core mystery fans may judge it good but not great. Melding
romance and mystery is tricky, and jaded mystery aficionados are
difficult to shock. ``The Alibi'' shows that Sandra Brown has what
it takes to churn out a good mystery. She just needs to use less
talk and more action to make one first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   (Kathy Harris is features copy desk chief at the Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-MASTERPIECE-BOS &LR;      10-01 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MASTERPIECE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINNEY DOMINATES `ENGLISH MARRIAGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
A RATHER ENGLISH MARRIAGE 
Starring: Albert Finney, Tom Courtenay, Joanna Lumley, 
Directed by: Paul Seed 
On: PBS, Sunday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his booming voice, Albert Finney is a thunderstorm of an
actor, and never more so than in ``A Rather English Marriage,'' the
first ``Masterpiece Theatre'' of the series's 29th season. Finney
plays a gruff, hard-drinking old coot named Reggie who likes to be
addressed as ``Squadron Leader'' by ordinary people, including the
hookers he visits. When his long-suffering wife dies, he mutters
``Look on the bright side'' and heads to the local bar to pickle
his vague sorrows. The phrase ``self-absorbed'' understates
Reggie's state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Courtenay, too, is a force of nature, although the quiet
persistence of his style is more like a slowly accumulating
snowfall. In ``A Rather English Marriage,'' he plays the low-key
Roy, a retired milkman and mother hen who is happiest when serving
others. After his domineering wife dies, he loyally addresses her
photograph, lonely without any whims to cater to. And he visits his
son in prison every week, despite the bitter young man's verbal
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, this odd couple of widowers make beautiful music
together. ``A Rather English Marriage'' is a rather unusual
second-time-around story that adds more shadings to its male-couple
theme than you might expect. Reuniting the two actors from ``The
Dresser,'' this British production is for Finney and Courtenay what
the ``Grumpy Old Men'' movies were for Jack Lemmon and Walter
Matthau _ a new vehicle to revive old chemistry. But unlike the
``Grumpy Old Men'' movies, ``A Rather English Marriage'' relies on
cool, engaging melodrama and not on sentimentality and shtick.
</P>
<P>
   The two men meet in the hospital while visiting their dying
spouses. Once the wives pass on the same day, Roy pursues Reggie's
friendship, and soon he moves in with Reggie as his manservant and
buddy. They have a perfectly interlocking psychological dynamic,
one that happens to mirror each of their long marriages. They
realize this instinctively, and they never discuss their
friendship, or question it. All they know is that Roy is content
preparing meals for Reggie, and Reggie is content to sit back and
sing the praises of Roy's cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Rather English Marriage,'' which won a British Academy of
Film and Television Arts Award for best single drama, features two
scenes in which Roy and Reggie dance together in the living room.
It's the rare movie that can pull off such moments without
resorting to humor, or alluding to the torment of latent gay
desires. And Finney and Courtenay are remarkable as they
consistently avoid defining the friendship with easy cliches. Both
characters have had bad luck in the child department, but neither
actor resorts to sympathy-mongering or bathos as their secrets
unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Lumley also adds luster to ``A Rather English Marriage''
as the boutique owner who appears to fall for Reggie. Lumley, Patsy
from ``Absolutely Fabulous,'' is oddly touching as a woman whose
questionable motives are softened by her acute self-knowledge. She
thinks Reggie is rich, unaware that his wife has left her fortune
to her nieces. In a powerful scene that doesn't become evasive
simply because the characters are older, she and Reggie make love.
Like the rest of ``A Rather English Marriage,'' it grants the
characters dignity, illusion, and loneliness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
