<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Oct. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A generally dry pattern will prevail across the eastern half of
the nation as westerly winds above the ground hinder the northward
advance of moisture from the Gulf of Mexico. However, a low
pressure system over Ontario will glean moisture from the Great
Lakes, setting the stage for spotty showers, mainly across
Michigan. The forecast for the Michigan-Purdue football game at Ann
Arbor will be mostly cloudy and cool with a chance for showers.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of the system, a shield of high clouds will stream into
western New York and west-central New England, gradually dimming
the sun. On the western flank of the low, rain mixed with snow will
fall across Michigan's Upper Peninsula as cold air streaming across
Lake Superior is moistened in transit and lifted overland.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will dive southward across the Great Plains, reaching
the panhandles of Texas and Oklahoma, as a broad ridge of high
pressure builds south from Canada. Snow will develop from the Black
Hills of South Dakota to the Big Horn Mountains of Wyoming as moist
winds from the southeast associated with the high glide up the
sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated showers and thunderstorms, a few of which could produce
moderately heavy rain, will develop later Saturday near the east
coast of Florida in concert with the sea breeze moving inland.
Isolated thunderstorms are also possible in extreme south Texas in
response to a sea breeze. Meanwhile, an area of clouds with very
spotty light rain will arrive over the middle Mississippi Valley
later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Computer Fire
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, an electrical fire knocked the fastest computer at
the National Centers for Environment Prediction in Washington,
D.C., out of commission. This division provides computer guidance
to weather forecasters across the nation. With the loss of the fast
computer, guidance distributed to forecasters has been diminished
and less timely. Fortunately, the weather pattern across the nation
has quieted down, reducing the need for a high volume of timely
computer forecasts. For example, without the threat of an Atlantic
tropical storm, there has been no need for hurricane computer
guidance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
