<HEADLINE>
ANNUAL SOCIAL SECURITY STATEMENTS MAY HELP BOOMERS PLAN  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL BENFELL   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ It used to be that one of the first signs
of advancing age came at 50, with an invitation in the mail to join
the American Association of Retired Persons. But soon all of us
will be getting annual reminders of our mortality in the form of
retirement statements from the federal Social Security
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Friday, Social Security will mail individual
estimates of future benefits to wage-earners over 25, a change from
times past when a worker had to write to the agency and request a
statement in order to do financial planning.
</P>
<P>
   Some 125 million wage-earners will receive the annual statement,
which will arrive about three months before each person's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Congress mandated the $70-million annual mailing after a poll
showed those who received statements had a better understanding of
how Social Security works.
</P>
<P>
   The annual mailing comes at a time when baby boomers are edging
toward retirement age and the number of people on Social Security
is expected to increase. People also are living longer and are
drawing more benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The statements are expected to be particularly relevant to the
boomers, who, more than their parents, find they need to do their
own financial planning for retirement. As traditional pensions
disappear, the boomers will need to juggle Social Security, 401(k)
plans and other investments to provide for their futures.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security earlier tried to make the information available
over the Internet. Wage-earners could type in their Social Security
numbers and get statements of earnings and benefits on the spot.
But privacy concerns and fears the information would be
appropriated for criminal use led the agency to close the site
temporarily. It has since reopened, at www.ssa.gov, but a statement
is available only by mail.
</P>
<P>
   The four-page statement being mailed out annually will contain
several kinds of information. One section lists the agency's
records of past earnings, year by year. It's important to make sure
the list is accurate, because eventual retirement benefits will be
based on it.
</P>
<P>
   Another section of the statement projects the amount individuals
will receive at retirement, using the examples of age 62, the
earliest you can receive Social Security; your ``retirement age,''
which is between 65 and 67, depending on your birthday; and age 70.
You can retire and receive benefits any time after you reach 62,
but you are penalized for retiring early and given a premium for
working longer.
</P>
<P>
   The statement is also a reminder that you can draw benefits if
you are disabled before retirement and that your children and your
spouse also may be entitled to benefits if you are disabled and
when you die. It also estimates what those benefits might be.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing about survivors' benefits is important, because the
burden is on family members to apply for benefits. Social Security
doesn't take responsibility for notifying them that they may be
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The first rule of Social Security is that you don't get Social
Security benefits if you don't pay Social Security taxes.
Consequently, many public school teachers, local and state
government workers and others on civil service won't be receiving
statements. Federal government workers will get statements,
however, because they began paying into Social Security in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   If you do pay Social Security taxes, you need a minimum of 10
years of work to receive benefits. The amount you receive is
generally based on your lifetime earnings. However, if your annual
income exceeds the Social Security maximum, which is currently
$72,600, your benefits will be based on the maximum, which changes
from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   To figure your benefit, the agency adjusts your earnings for
inflation and then picks your 35 highest earning years. A
complicated formula is used to determine the exact amount of your
monthly benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security currently is providing about 40 percent of a
retiree's income, according to agency figures. Some 27.5 million
retired wage-earners currently receive Social Security, with an
average benefit of $780 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Another formula is used for those who want to retire earlier or
later than their Social Security retirement age. It used to be that
a person received full retirement benefits at 65, but recent
changes in the law extended the age so that currently, for workers
born after 1937, retirement age ranges from 65 1/2 to 67.
</P>
<P>
   If you retire before your Social Security retirement age, your
monthly benefit will be 0.56 percent less for each month you retire
early. If you retire after your retirement age, your monthly
benefit will include a bonus of up to 0.67 percent for each month
you delay. For example, a worker born in 1960, with earnings of
$68,400 a year, would receive about $1,105 a month at age 62, about
$1,580 a month at retirement age of 67 in this case and about
$1,905 a month at age 70.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is usually thought of as a retirement tool, but
about one out of every three Social Security recipients is a
disabled worker or a family member of a deceased or disabled
worker. Their benefits stem from their relationship to the
wage-earner and are based on his or her earnings.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
