<HEADER>
A3712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SENIOR-POLICY-NYTR &LR;      10-01 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-POLICY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE HMO SHAKE-UP TAKING HEAVIEST TOLL IN SMALLER COMMUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Idaho, Iowa, Kan., Ken., Miss., Neb.,   N.D., S.C.,
S.D., Utah, Vt., Wyo., Ala., Fla.) (Eds: Senior Policy and Politics is a monthly column from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.) 
(js) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The turmoil in Medicare's managed care initiative
has sent older Americans in some cities scrambling to find new
coverage after their health maintenance organizations
unceremoniously pulled out. But at least those seniors had
alternatives available to them.
</P>
<P>
   In smaller communities, the HMO options under the troubled
Medicare Plus Choice program are drying up entirely if they ever
existed in the first place. Recent reports from the White House and
an interest group found that HMOs are scarce in rural America and
becoming rarer, forsaking the very communities that need them most.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the report by the group Families USA disclosed,
almost 75 percent of the more than 9 million Medicare beneficiaries
living in rural counties are not served by any HMO. Just one in 10
resides in a county that has two or more managed care plans from
which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 states _ Alaska, Idaho, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky,
Mississippi, Nebraska, North Dakota, South Carolina, South Dakota,
Utah, Vermont and Wyoming _ rural residents have no HMO option. In
another 12, the choices are greatly restricted. In Alabama, for
instance, only one rural county out of 46 has a Medicare HMO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The managed care industry has virtually ignored Medicare
beneficiaries in rural communities,'' declared Ron Pollack,
executive director of the liberal watchdog organization.
</P>
<P>
   The White House report, which focused on the decline in drug
coverage provided by Medicare HMOs, found that only one-fifth of
rural beneficiaries had access to a health plan that provided
prescription benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of this lack of health care choice in
small-town America are significant for the residents, who are
older, less healthy and less affluent than their urban counterparts
and are thus more dependent on Medicare. The scarcity of HMOs means
beneficiaries have no opportunity to obtain the drug coverage,
wellness protection and other extra benefits offered by managed
care plans to attract customers.
</P>
<P>
   Both studies confirmed the suspicions of many lawmakers and
senior advocates that Medicare beneficiaries in rural communities
are at a serious disadvantage when it comes to managed care.
</P>
<P>
   These critics say a flawed funding formula based in part on past
Medicare spending has driven up federal managed care reimbursement
rates in urban areas, where health care usage is high, while
penalizing rural areas for conservative medical practice. Take the
case in Florida, where HMOs in Miami's Dade County are paid $778
per month per HMO enrollee compared to the $452 HMOS would be
entitled to if they served largely rural Hamilton County in North
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, HMOs have clustered in large population centers
while moving more slowly into areas beyond the suburbs. And as
managed care companies pull out of areas due to their ongoing
struggles with Medicare, rural counties are often the first to be
jettisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, in business you go where there is
the best return and the heck with everybody else,'' said Rep. Karen
Thurman, D-Fla., who has pushed for Medicare HMO reforms intended
to draw more plans into rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the managed care industry has lobbied for higher
reimbursement rates, saying companies can only provide services in
areas where they are adequately compensated.
</P>
<P>
   The Families USA report said factors other than reimbursement
rates are at work in keeping HMOs out of rural areas. Besides the
general problems of a limited number of enrollees and fewer health
care providers and facilities, the report said HMO companies find
it difficult to wring savings out of rural health care systems
since health care spending is already low.
</P>
<P>
   ``HMOs _ at least as they are currently structured _ may be an
inherently unsuitable system of health delivery for rural areas,''
said the Families USA report, entitled ``Rural Neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the White House and the interest group offered their
findings in support of President Clinton's reform plan and said any
alternative that relies on competition among HMOs _ as several
circulating on Capitol Hill do _ will further harm rural Americans.
The group says reform must be done in a way that guarantees that
Medicare benefits remain affordable and available to all
beneficiaries equally.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear how or if Congress will make any substantive
changes to Medicare yet this session. But it is clear that the
effort to expand the availability of HMOs is not now reaching rural
America.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
