<HEADER>
A3715 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ANIMALFARM02-COX     10-01 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALFARM02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Farm' presents beastly specter of Stalinism
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TNT's ``Animal Farm'' is an epic near-miss. It's the kind of TV
movie you wish TV attempted more often. Airing at 8 p.m. Sunday,
``Animal Farm'' is startling and ambitious and harrowing and bold _
all virtues that should add up to something triumphant and not
merely noble. Yet the fact that it makes you wish for more than
mere nobility is a kind of triumph in itself. ``Animal Farm'' is TV
as moral victory.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour, $23 million film is an adaptation of George
Orwell's classic political fable, a 1945 novel famous to many high
school students, one critic has put it, as ``the Shortest Serious
Novel It's OK to Write a Book Report About'' (it edges out
Hemingway's ``The Old Man and the Sea'' by three pages). The book
endures for many reasons, not the least being the affecting,
brazenly simple way it morphs the atrocities of Soviet Communism
under Joseph Stalin into a believable barnyard society.
</P>
<P>
   This is a world where the animals of Manor Farm overthrow their
oppressive human masters and set up a one-for-all, all-for-one
utopia. Anybody recall the Bolshevik revolution? Doesn't matter.
Manor Farm is quickly redubbed Animal Farm, a place where ``four
legs are good, two legs are bad,'' where animals are animals and
not tools for others' gain.
</P>
<P>
   Things go along like this until power corrupts the pigs, who
concoct a corrupt dictatorship of their own. They employ propaganda
films, a secret security force and paranoia. Anybody recall Stalin?
Doesn't matter. Things turn worse than before.
</P>
<P>
   Only today, in the age of ``Babe,'' could the book be plausibly
adapted as a live-action film. (A 1955 feature was animated. In
fact, this production, from executive producer Robert Halmi Sr.
(``Merlin,'' ``Alice in Wonderland''), is crafted by much of the
same crew that created that heralded 1995 film: Jim Henson's
Creature Shop built 14 farm animals, and John Stephenson directs.
</P>
<P>
   Their work here is as realistic as it gets, though there's
always something self-consciously curious, if still thrilling,
about watching a dog or a horse or a pig move its lips properly to
speak the queen's English.
</P>
<P>
   But the film's staggering atmospherics extend beyond special
effects. Filmed in Ireland, there's a lush bleakness bled into
every scene that perfectly frames this tale's theme of ideals gone
awfully wrong. Even when characters are portrayed with a kind of
cartoonish heavy-handedness, the film never loses its weight.
Animals might talk, but this ``Animal Farm'' isn't for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when you're more amazed by what you're seeing than
engrossed in what you're watching, something fundamental is amiss.
That's often the case here.
</P>
<P>
   The real defect is hidden in the movie's strength: the animals
so wonderously created by the Creature Shop. They have life, but
little depth. An oppressed horse is pretty much the same as an
oppressed goose or mule or sheep _ no matter which celebrity voices
it (Kelsey Grammer, Ian Holm, Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Patrick Stewart,
Julia Ormand, Peter Ustinov). The animals are more sympathetic than
the humans, but also flatter. We root for them in the simple way we
root for the good guy in a wrestling match.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Postlethwaite (``In the Name of the Father''), brilliant as
the pathetically heinous Jones, the drunk farmer against whom the
animals originally revolt, is seen as both the oppressor and the
oppressed. He's crude and complex, and ultimately more gratifying
to despise than the animals are to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   By the time you reach its contrived, un-Orwellian end, ``Animal
Farm'' isn't the memorable TV movie it could have been. But it is a
memorable attempt.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Animal Farm''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0175 </DOCNO>
