r l BC-ARCHITECTURE03-COX     10-01 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1999 Georgia American Institute of Architects Design Awards
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The construction of a new department store in an old
downtown is an event in itself, and architects at the Atlanta firm
Cooper Carry Inc. celebrate the occasion with an urbane design that
tips its hat to tradition without losing its modernity.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazarus Department Store in Pittsburgh, the first
free-standing store to be built there in 25 years, is a grand
building in the spirit of Marshall Field's in Chicago or Macy's in
Atlanta. Its highly articulated facades, which give the building
scale and character, were inspired by the sturdiness, texture and
vertical rhythms of the early 20th-century structures nearby, such
as H.H. Richardson's Allegheny County Courthouse. Vertical bands of
windows sliced with mullions break up the facade further and call
attention to the entrances below them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike our mall department stores, we placed the entrances on
the corners,'' Jerry Cooper says. ``They line up with the
crosswalks at the intersections, the way pedestrians approach the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury for the 1999 Georgia American Institute of Architects
Design Awards, which gave the store one of three top awards this
year, was particularly appreciative of the old-style monumentality
and copious use of natural light. Beyond the qualities of the
building itself, Lazarus is, says jury chairman Stephen Muse, ``a
great piece of urban design.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The best work among the 80-some entries went beyond the
building itself to play a larger role in the environment,'' says
Muse, a Washington architect.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Heery International's additions to Darrell K.
Royal-Texas Stadium at the University of Texas in Austin created
more than seats and skyboxes, Muse says. The project, whose
monumentality and decorative flourishes bring to mind Atlanta's
Turner Field, which Heery also designed, enhances the campus,
giving it a front facade.
</P>
<P>
   Muse describes the third honor award winner, the Lee B. Philmon
Branch Library in Riverdale, as ``a great piece of highway
architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   The attention to detail alone distinguishes this small but
elegant library, which uses triangular windows and skylights to
welcome light inside. Scogin Elam and Bray Architects designed the
casework and tables to complete the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The library plays other roles in the community. As Carol
Stewart, director of library services for Clayton County, explains,
``Riverdale is so chaotic; Merrill (Elam) wanted to create a quiet
refuge.'' Stewart and the firm have teamed up on two other
libraries to earn a reputation for adventurous architecture, which
serves to announce that the library is a special, exciting place to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   The following merit awards _ like the honor awards, all going to
Atlanta firms _ will be presented Saturday in Atlanta during the
Georgia AIA chapter's annual convention. Here's a rundown:
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN CATEGORY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Interactive Planet, Atlanta. The curved and angled wall of the
interior creates an energetic environment appropriate for a
high-tech firm. The combination of wood, steel and plastic sheeting
add to the effect. Stanley Beaman &AMP; Sears.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  64 Wakefield. An unusual house in Brookwood Hills that
rethinks traditions of living space and domestic materials. The
master bedroom aerie looks out to the treetops and second-story lap
pool. Scogin Elam and Bray.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A corporate headquarters in Roswell (Ga.). The handsome facade
of stacked stone and copper-colored aluminum projections and
charcoal metal canopy create the rustic, lodgelike appearance the
client wanted. Designed by Leo A Daly.
</P>
<P>
   SUSTAINABLE MERIT AWARDS
</P>
<P>
   For adaptive reuse and environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Piedmont Park Multi-Use Complex. Old sheds become office and
community buildings in a sensitive renovation. Smith Dalia
Architects.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Farm Preservation/Conservation Community. This plan turns 400
acres of farmland outside Athens into an ecologically sensitive
residential community. The compact housing and village center saves
most of the property as open land for farming and recreational
uses. Preston &AMP; Associates and Village Habitat Design.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  15 Simpson St., offices of Richard + Wittschiebe Architects. A
defunct nightclub in a small masonry building at the north edge of
downtown is transformed from an eyesore to an attractive,
street-oriented office. Richard + Wittschiebe, Architects.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURAL TOURS
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Chapter of the American Institute of Architects
holds its annual conference Thursday through Oct. 10 in Atlanta.
Several architectural tours are open to the public:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Friday: 9 a.m., UPS headquarters; 12:30 p.m., Oakland
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday: 9:30 a.m., the Lofts at Muse's; 12:30 p.m.,
Coca-Cola headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Call 404-222-0099, Ext. 0, for reservations. $20; $10 children.
Buses leave from the Sheraton Atlanta Hotel at International
Boulevard and Courtland Street.
</P>
<P>
   The AIA is also hosting exhibitions of drawings by its members
at the Studioplex, 659 Auburn Ave. N.E., which will be open for
guided tours Oct. 17, 24 and 31. Call 404-222-0099, Ext. 0, for
times and reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
