<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3717 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ART-COLLEGE1STTAKE03-     10-01 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-COLLEGE1STTAKE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta College of Art builds a reputation amid tight quarters,
creative classes and culture clashes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Antonio Garcia started taking classes at the Art
Institute of Chicago while in elementary school. Then an awful
thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   His parents moved to Peachtree City (GA.). ``All I wanted to do
was get back to Chicago,'' says the 20-year-old, remembering his
junior year in high school. ``That was the plan. I just wanted to
finish school and go back home.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, he enrolled at the Atlanta College of Art, moving
into its residence hall behind the High Museum of Art. The dorm,
where baggy jeans, pink hair, tribal dance music and pot-smoking
are part of the status quo, is the last refuge of Bohemianism in
the button-down world of the Woodruff Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, things were looking up for Garcia. Then he met his
roommate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when he was eating a bowl of cereal on Friday
and I said goodbye to him and went home,'' says the advertising
design major, now a resident assistant at the 35 Lombardy Way dorm.
He stretches out on his unmade bed, stares at a ``Taxi Driver''
poster showing a young Robert De Niro with a gun and a Mohawk, and
continues: ``I came back Monday morning and the bowl of cereal was
still out in the living room and the whole place smelled like a cow
died in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Living in tight quarters has never been easy.
</P>
<P>
   So even as Garcia settles into his junior year _ with several
scholarships, a 3.9 grade point average and a roommate that he
likes _ the 71-year-old liberal arts college is undergoing its own
growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   As Italian architect Renzo Piano sketches a new master plan for
the Woodruff, including an addition to the High Museum of Art that
is expected to displace the college dorm and sculpture studio, the
school is enjoying unprecedented enrollment growth and an excellent
academic reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Ellen Meyer, the college president, met with the Piano
workshop to discuss construction, which she expects to be completed
within three years. More tangibly, since February, the college has
raised $3.4 million of a $4 million campaign that will give its
technological programs a major boost.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one catch: Behind the all-consuming sprawl of the
Woodruff, the ACA seems almost invisible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I tell somebody where I go to school,'' says Janet
Lankford, a senior photography major from Birmingham, ``they are
like, `Oh, the Art Institute,' and I am like, `No, the Atlanta
College of Art! The Woodruff Arts Center!' It's like it's just
hidden. Nobody knows that we are here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody outside of the academic world, that is.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the school _ which founder Benjamin Shute described in
1928 as ``a bunch of girls standing around in fur coats waiting to
go to the Piedmont Driving Club'' _ is one of the South's most
prestigious art colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school has really come into its own in the past few years
and is exercising a leadership position, partly in the Southeast,
but it is also positioning itself gradually with respect to the
national scene,'' says Charles Olton, former dean of New York's
Parsons School of Design and former chairman of the Association of
Independent Colleges of Art and Design. Olton credits Meyer _ who
has focused on technology and internationalism and put in place a
rigorous multidisciplinary world studies curriculum _ with the
school's ascent.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a quick turnaround for a college that was almost
closed in the mid-'80s, after running up a $300,000 deficit. When
Ofelia Garcia, Meyer's predecessor, came on board in 1986, she was
given a mandate: Stop the red ink or the college will be closed.
When she left in 1991, she had more than doubled the enrollment and
stabilized the coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, all debt has been paid off, and enrollment is at a record
430. The demographic is impressive: 19 percent African-American and
7 percent from foreign countries. Meyer is particularly proud of
the recruitment program that takes her to Seoul, South Korea, to
enlist students every year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its credentials, the school suffers the distinction of
being the least sexy, and least noticed, of the Woodruff siblings:
the High, the Alliance Theatre and the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra.
With a $9.8 million budget, it's the smallest of the four
divisions. Yet from tuition, it generates 62 percent of its
operating budget. By comparison, the ASO, the largest division,
earns back only 47 percent of its $23 million budget, and gets the
rest from contributions. The Woodruff gives about $1 million a year
to the college, its most intensive space occupant, and $4.2 million
to the symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a big light saying, `Eat, eat, eat,'' says
Marcia Cohen, who has been a professor of painting and drawing at
the college for nearly 25 years. ``But it's been a very consistent,
a very strong energy. Maybe no one knows we are here, and yet I
think they do know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you actually go in the college or the gallery,'' says
ACA board Chairwoman Sallie Adams Daniel, ``you don't realize how
exciting it is. It's not as exciting as going to a symphony
performance or the Alliance Theatre with Elton John or the High
Museum's impressionism or Picasso exhibit.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it: The college is the only institution in
America that is part of a vibrant arts complex that includes a
theater, a symphony and a museum. This remains one of its most
compelling selling points. But as it prospers, some observers
question whether its relationship with the Woodruff is an asset or
a liability.
</P>
<P>
   Does the concept of living together still work?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Woodruff Arts Center should have busted up years
ago,'' says Larry Jens Anderson, who has taught drawing at the ACA
since 1982. ``It's a small town concept to put all the arts on a
city block.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel is more circumspect: ``We are all kind of busting out of
the seams,'' says the Bank of America vice president, who is also
chairman of the Fulton County Arts Council. ``If we can tackle the
space issue, if we can fix that part of it, I still think it's a
great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Campus life
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Garcia is sitting in his room when Lankford drops by to
show off her new haircut. ``You look so fine, Janet,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia is a slightly stocky kid who wants to go to film school
after graduation. On this day, he's wearing big, baggy bluejeans,
athletic shoes and a baggy gray sweatshirt. There's the beginning
of a goatee on his chin. Over his bed is a ``Trainspotting''
poster, and on another wall there's a Puerto Rican flag. He proudly
tells a visitor that his family is from Puerto Rico, how he likes
to get back to Peachtree City on weekends to load up on his mom's
cooking. But his trips have gotten less frequent as he's adjusted
to dorm life.
</P>
<P>
   Lankford is a svelte 21-year-old who has spent the last few
years making documentary photographs of her grandmother, who has
Alzheimer's. On one wall of her dorm room, there's a
heartbreakingly beautiful portrait of her grandmother, sitting up
in bed. The image is not maudlin or poignant; instead, it captures
the woman in a state of vulnerability and grace. It was shot by a
young photographer who already knows something about mortality and
fading beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Lankford is disturbed over the sale of condoms in the dorm
vending machines. ``I've been fighting that one,'' she says. ``I
just don't agree with it. I just feel like it promotes it.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she became a Christian while still in high school, and
she shows a visitor one of her favorite images. Ripped from Rolling
Stone magazine, and stuck up on the wall by the door, it's a
photograph of Jay Bakker, the youth minister and son of Jim and
Tammy Faye, flexing his muscles and showing off his tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   During the 30 seconds she is in Garcia's room, he taunts her for
being a Miss Goody Two Shoes. She says she's going out to dinner.
He says: ``I never thought you went out. You are such a dorm
body.''
</P>
<P>
   She shoots back: ``I am not!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out for Bible study and then go back to your room.''
He's joking but she seems uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   When Lankford leaves, Garcia says he used to have a ``beef ''
with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sophomore year she was my R.A., and it's like anything that
went wrong she blamed it on us. ... She wrote us up for a pipe bomb
that blew up, and we weren't even aware of it. That was the first
time I ever felt discriminated against. But now that we are R.A.'s
together, we've put it all behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   On another visit to the dorm, Lankford tells a visitor about the
time last year when a man got shot on the street next to the dorm.
``It was the students who administered first aid on this guy who
had been shot five times in the head,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw it out their dorm window. He survived. He came back
last year to thank the people who had helped him. They never caught
the guy who did it. Security got a lot better after that. Anybody
could have walked in this building. It almost took somebody getting
killed and then they paid attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia says the most difficult thing he has to do is get tough
with the residents who smoke pot. ``If I smell it, I'm going to
deal with it. I'm not going to let you off because you are my
friend. ... I almost take it as a personal offense, especially if
it's a friend of mine, because they know my situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Both students save about $4,000 a year by working as resident
assistants. Still, the tuition is expensive, $13,180 a year. ``I've
thought a lot about if I could have gotten the same education at
another school for a lot less money,'' Lankford says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
