<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-MILITARY-500&AMP;AD     10-01 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MILITARY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH POMP AND PRECISION, CHINA'S MILITARY MARKS 50 YEARS OF
COMMUNISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ With a Soviet-style procession of goose-stepping
troops, tanks, missiles and fighter jets setting the tone for the
parade marking 50 years of communism, China showed off a formidable
armory Friday, even if few of the weapons could match the latest
Western models.
</P>
<P>
   There were no technological surprises to cause gasps in Taiwan
or in Washington. Still, military officials from foreign embassies
here eagerly studied the display through binoculars, viewing some
of China's best anti-aircraft missiles and other systems for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet potential foreign adversaries were not the main intended
audience, Chinese and Western experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military parade is intended to show confidence and
strength, especially domestically,'' said Zhang Yunding, director
of Asia-Pacific Studies at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
``It's to give the people a sense that we have a new China, to let
people feel proud of that rather than to focus only on our current
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Any intimidation of Taiwan is an added benefit, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Pollack, a China specialist at the Rand Corporation in
California, said: ``The leadership wants to signal that it's not
standing still and that it can display this prowess _ at least as
much to its own citizens as to the world at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's parade, the first of its kind in 15 years, also served
the political ambitions of Jiang Zemin. In a stiff drive-by review
of the forces from an open-roofed limousine, Jiang aped the late
Deng Xiaoping's performance in 1984 and also showcased his own
position as chairman of the Central Military Commission, as well as
president and general secretary of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   All this year, preparations for the exacting procession absorbed
a huge share of the military's attention.
</P>
<P>
   If the tanks and jets on display were a generation or so behind
the world's best, the Chinese also displayed mobile short- and
medium-range ballistic missiles that are nearly impossible to
counter effectively.
</P>
<P>
   China still lacks the ability for sustained air and naval
operations that would be necessary to invade well-defended Taiwan,
100 miles off shore and the main focus of Chinese military
planning. And should the United States be drawn into combat, China
would almost certainly be outfought by American ships and planes,
which can strike precisely from hundreds of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   But the mobile missiles on display Friday, which are being
deployed in growing numbers adjacent to Taiwan, could serve in a
sense as equalizers, able to inflict terrible damage on the island
as well as on more distant American bases.
</P>
<P>
   The parade also featured the recently tested DF-31
intercontinental ballistic missile, able to reach parts of the
United States. Unlike China's existing, vulnerable nuclear forces,
this one can be moved about, lending it far greater protection from
surprise attack.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The military chest-thumping comes at a time when the
long-outmoded and underfunded military has gained status in top
political circles and, almost certainly, a new boost in funds for
weapons development and purchases, Chinese and Western military
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Many of China's best weapons, including some fighter jets and
surface-to-air missiles seen Friday as well as naval destroyers and
submarines, have been purchased from Russia. But even with recent
budgetary increases, military spending here remains only a fraction
of that in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The generals' political stock is up these days, experts say,
because the modernization of Chinese forces now seems all the more
urgent.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' dazzling display of precision bombing in the 1991
Persian Gulf War caused consternation in China's backward military
and led to a major overhaul that is still going on. This spring,
the long-distance prowess showed by the United States in its
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia was, in the words of an army
newspaper here, ``a new wake-up call'' to the Chinese military.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big surprise to the military people,'' Zhang said.
``There's really pressure now to develop high-tech weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer's war of words with Taiwan, too, heightened the
sense of urgency. In the months since Taiwanese President Lee
Teng-hui declared that relations between Taiwan and China should be
conducted on a ``state-to-state'' basis, a statement Beijing took
to be another step toward formal independence, the Chinese press
has been filled with bluster about China's new capacity to easily
vanquish Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But thus summer's crisis forced China's military and political
leaders to confront how limited their military options actually
are, especially with the specter of American involvement in
Taiwan's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from backward technology, the Chinese military is in the
throes of multiple transitions and its leaders appear especially
anxious to avoid any conflicts in the next few years, outside
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Burdened with a surplus of troops, a legacy of the old doctrine
of ``people's war,'' the three-million-strong army is trying to
reduce its numbers by another 500,000, after already pruning one
million people in recent years. But the dearth of jobs for
cashiered soldiers is slowing the process.
</P>
<P>
   The military is also supposed to be ending its involvement in
the myriad businesses that helped pay its bills in the past. It is
revamping the organization of forces and is in the midst of a
fundamental rewriting of military doctrine and strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all these traumas, the military put on an impressively
precise show Friday, even if it seemed from another era.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 50th anniversary was a special occasion,'' Zhang said. ``I
think this is probably the last parade of this type.''
</P>
</TEXT>
