<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3719 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MOUNTVERNON03-COX     10-01 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNTVERNON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Washington relics hit the road
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND _ If you ever wondered why George Washington looks
irritated on the dollar bill, you'll understand when you see one of
the oddest artifacts in all Americana. It's the star attraction of
``Treasures From Mount Vernon,'' an exhibition about the first
president that opens Saturday, Oct. 16, at the Atlanta History
Center.
</P>
<P>
   As schoolchildren kept asking during the show's previous run at
the Virginia Historical Society, ``Where are the teeth?''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the presidential dentures. Of all the precious relics
assembled for the traveling exhibition, none seems as personal as
the disembodied set of choppers. They're a mouthful. Carved from
ivory, cow's teeth and perhaps a nut (or is it a peach pit?), the
teeth are rooted in a heavy lead base that was held in Washington's
mouth not by adhesive, but with metal springs. The contraption
looks as uncomfortable as a Clydesdale's bit.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Washington appears almost ready to blow his lunch
in the dollar bill cameo. The likeness is based on the famous
portrait by Gilbert Stuart, who earned Martha Washington's
disapproval by faithfully reproducing the facial distortions caused
by ill-fitting false teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha hated that portrait,'' says King Laughlin, special
projects director at Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Vernon Ladies' Association, the preservation society
that runs Washington's home and tends his flame, organized the
exhibition to mark the 200th anniversary of his death in December.
It's part of a public relations campaign to increase interest in a
man whose monumental reputation has made him seem remote and
unknowable. ``Washington eludes us,'' the writer Gary Wills once
put it, ``even in the city named for him.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mount Vernon wants you to meet the real George, a tall,
well-muscled, hot-tempered Virginian who liked to gamble, dance,
ride fast horses and toss back a few at the Masonic hall. ``In many
ways,'' Laughlin says, ``he was a normal guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that he wasn't, at least not in the important ways
Americans remember and revere. Washington realized his symbolic
position as the first head of a new republic, and he carried
himself with an appropriate reserve and dignity. No one actually
called him George (at least until JFK Jr.). Even around the house
they addressed him as ``the General,'' or if Martha was in a frisky
mood, she might call him her ``old man.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition fleshes out Washington through 170 artifacts _
paintings, letters, clothing, personal effects _ more than half of
which have never been shown publicly. They illustrate different
sides of a remarkable life:
</P>
<P>
   Soldier. Washington first made his reputation as a military man
fighting with the British during the French and Indian War. We see
the bloody silk sash he was given by his mentor, Gen. Edward
Braddock, as Braddock lay dying after a battle. Washington survived
with four bullet holes in his coat. ``There is something charming
in the sound'' of musket fire, he admitted in a letter.
</P>
<P>
   Man of peace. Washington came to see gunfire less romantically
during the Revolutionary War. After the British were defeated, he
commissioned a copper dove weather vane with an olive branch in its
mouth to crown his mansion overlooking the Potomac River. It was
removed for restoration a few years ago and will be returned to
Mount Vernon after the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Husband. Washington fell hard for a neighbor as a young man, but
she married his best friend. He ended up with the widowed Martha
Custis, whose tiny wedding slippers and blue checked linen bathing
gown are seen. It has weights in the bottom to prevent anyone from
glimpsing her bare legs. Martha might have feared other
indiscretions; she burned all but two of her husband's love letters
to her. The survivors are displayed in rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Icon of freedom. Europeans were fascinated by a man who won a
war and then had to be coaxed from his farm to head the victorious
government. During the French Revolution, Washington's old
lieutenant Lafayette sent him a big iron key to the Bastille, the
Paris prison that became a symbol of the repressive monarchy. The
French also gave Washington a model of the jail carved from one of
its stones. Notice the chipped places; Martha's grandchildren
apparently liked to play with it.
</P>
<P>
   Slaveholder. Washington was the only Founding Father who
actually freed his slaves. Though he and his wife owned more than
300, he grew so disenchanted with the institution of slavery that
he wrote Lafayette, ``I do not like to even think, much less talk
of it.'' In a neatly scripted ledger, Washington accounts for which
slaves are his and which belong to the Custis family. He could free
only the ones he owned, which he did in his will.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was only 67 when he died on Dec. 14, 1799,
suffocating from an acute case of tonsillitis. We see the
blood-stained dressing gown he is thought to have worn during his
final hours, as doctors bled him, bathed his throat in ammonium
carbonate, forced him to vomit, gave him an enema and applied a
poultice of wheat bran to his feet and legs.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of other artifacts: his pistol, his dress
sword, his camp bed from Valley Forge, a deerskin bag of his hair
powder. But none of them humanizes the Father of His Country quite
like his dentures.
</P>
<P>
   Washington started losing his teeth in his 30s, probably, he
told John Adams, because of all the walnuts he cracked in his
youth. He had trouble finding good-fitting false teeth; the
exhibition includes a letter he wrote to a dentist complaining of
dentures that ``bulge my lips out in such a manner as to make them
appear considerably swelled.''
</P>
<P>
   He never owned a set of wooden teeth, as is commonly thought.
They just looked wooden, having yellowed to the tone of varnished
hickory. ``It took us five or six hours to clean them,'' Laughlin
says.
</P>
<P>
   And these are Washington's show teeth _ the ones he used for
greeting guests. He used another set for chewing food.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was a proper man who guarded his privacy, so one can
only imagine what he would think of airing his dirty teeth. But
from Mount Vernon's point of view, the anniversary attention has
proved a tonic. After declining for several years, attendance at
the estate has rebounded in 1999 and is expected to pass 1 million
before Thanksgiving. That's more visitors than Elvis Presley's
Graceland or Thomas Jefferson's Monticello draw.
</P>
<P>
   Dabney Barber of Mineral, Va., was so impressed with Mount
Vernon this summer that she took her two teenage children to the
``Treasures'' exhibition in Richmond to complete their tour of all
things George.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed to admit this,'' she said, ``but I talked to
his tomb. I stood there and told him, `We could use a man of your
integrity and character right now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Caleb, her 14-year-old son, didn't go that far, but he agreed
with his mother. ``He was a good guy,'' he said. ``And his teeth
are pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   THE STUFF
</P>
<P>
   Washington's famous dentures were made of ivory and animal
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Custis' silk slippers from her wedding to Washington in
1759.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Washington
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Stuart painted this oil on canvas portrait about 1798.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Stuart's famous portrait, which Martha Washington
``hated.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Washington's brown silk satin gown from the 1790s.
</P>
<P>
   Leather holsters held this flintlock pistol, made by London
craftsmen.
</P>
<P>
   French sculptor Devile is credited with casting this plaster
mask.
</P>
<P>
   A tackle box holds fishing lines, floats and loose hooks.
</P>
<P>
   This key to the Bastille in Paris was sent as a gift by
Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Treasures From Mount Vernon: George Washington Revealed''
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16 through Jan. 6. Atlanta History Center, 130 W. Paces
Ferry Road N.W. 404-814-
</P>
<P>
   4000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
