<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3720 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ART-COLLEGE2NDTAKE03-     10-01 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-COLLEGE2NDTAKE03-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: for a lot less money,'' Lankford says.
</P>
<P>
   A generation gap?
</P>
<P>
   The politics of living together is infinitely complex, whether
you are a college freshman living with a strange roommate for the
first time _ or a couple in a state of marital bliss. But the
culture clash among the Woodruff administration, patrons and art
students has always particularly obvious, and often comical. That
the tuxedo-and-gown crowd brushes against the tattooed-and-pierced
set is what gives the college so much vitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they have an event, they post guards at all the
doors around the whole building and redirect you to the slave
entrance like we are not fit to be seen by the patrons that are
basically supporting the arts center and the school anyway,''
Garcia says. ``We have to be rerouted so no one can see us and then
take the little elevator up. I know it has to do with not
disturbing whatever it is that they are doing and keeping traffic
down, but it feels kind of crummy.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Lankford: ``Our feeling of how they feel about us is that
we are a nuisance. And the beauty of it is that we are constantly
hanging out the windows or yelling or doing something that just is
not for the arts center. `It's just not proper!''' At this last
remark, her voice changes register, as if she is mocking a
schoolmarm scolding her charges.
</P>
<P>
   She continues: ``You feel tension between the High and here.
It's funny because you realize we are what fuels them and they
totally don't appreciate our creativity. No matter how intrusive it
is on their pristine white walls, we are the next generation that's
going to fuel their business. You would think they would be more
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the board chairman senses conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel like the rest of the Woodruff Arts Center looks
at us like we are the art students who might be a little more
avant-garde than the patrons,'' says board chairman Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   In a college history published by the Atlanta History Center,
the writer describes the atmosphere in the '50s: ``Adding to its
problems, (the college) made an increasingly odd mix with the
society ladies who ran the museum. They did not like finding
evidence that some down-on-his-
</P>
<P>
   luck student had camped there overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Meyer: ``Sometimes I see it, and it's all so human. All it
takes is one engagement as simple as, `Oh, are you a student here?'
And usually both sides relax and talk.''
</P>
<P>
   When the college does build a new dorm, Meyer and the board are
adamant about keeping it close to the college's teaching space.
Security is a prime concern.
</P>
<P>
   The college teaching space occupies the fourth floor of the
Woodruff building; its administrative offices are on the third
floor, as are the Woodruff's executive offices.
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty members say it might make sense if the Woodruff
moved its offices across the street and let the college use that
space. ``We wouldn't have the secretaries walking down the halls
getting offended,'' says Anderson, the drawing professor.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one problem: How do you move the Woodruff out of
its building?
</P>
<P>
   Paging Mr. Piano.
</P>
<P>
   The serious side of art
</P>
<P>
   But this was supposed to be a story about educating the art
student, and it is. In this temple of learning, there are at least
430 stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
   On a fine fall day, Anderson is telling a senior drawing class
about aspects of beauty, why we are drawn to symmetrical faces.
Marcia Cohen's drawing class is on the floor using sticks to
scratch images of her collection of pods and pine cones and dried
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the college gallery, senior painting major Scott Foxx is
writing a review of the faculty art show. He's angry that there's
not more new work, that some of it is so blatantly commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, Anderson is counseling a student whose grandfather has
committed suicide. Back down in the gallery, Foxx is talking about
Anderson's installation in the faculty show. It's a series of
shovels that conjures up images of AIDS, religion and the grave
diggers in ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry says, `There are only three subjects in art: sex, death
and mom,''' says Foxx, with obvious admiration for his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Anderson if there is a schism between the computer art
disciplines and the fine arts, and he has a quick reply: ``Imagine
if Leonardo had had a computer. He probably wouldn't have
painted.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody has a story, it seems. Meyer likes to talk about the
time the entire college went to see the Picasso show at the High.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 8 o'clock in the morning,'' she says. ``They haven't
opened the elevator to the upper floors and it's incredibly noisy.
One student breaks free and tries to run up the ramp. You know, `To
the art! Get me to the art!' So then there was this amazing thing.
The elevators open, and everybody goes upstairs. Silence. It's like
being in a church. And you are taken aback because they are so
taken aback.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who is a design major, says he's only been in the museum
once _ on assignment. Then he remembers a lovely story about the
day he learned an important lesson about art. Everybody was
supposed to bring a pepper to professor Tony Greco's drawing class,
but no one remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really stupid because I didn't bring it in either. That
was like the very beginning of my freshmen year when I wasn't quite
adjusted and stuff. He was going down the roll, and he was asking
you if you had a green pepper, and for some reason I was just a
smart ass that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Greco asked Garcia if he had his pepper. ``And I was like: `No.'
Like: `Of course not.''' The professor flipped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just gave us the most motivational speech I've heard since
I've been here about him being passionate about art. `Sure, it's
just peppers, but it boils down to you being interested in what you
are doing and paying so much money and then not coming equipped.'
He like broke down and his voice cracked, and he got teary-eyed.
And that made me realize with his pepper lecture that this was
serious and that was time to take art seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The professor dismissed the class and told them to return in an
hour _ with peppers.
</P>
<P>
   This being an urban college, the students just ran across the
street and got some from the pizza place at Colony Square.
</P>
<P>
   THE ATLANTA COLLEGE OF ART FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  History: Founded in 1928. Has always been affiliated with the
High Museum of Art. Has undergone several name changes: High Museum
School, Atlanta Art Institute, Atlanta College of Art.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accreditation: One of only three arts schools in the South to
be accredited by both the Commission on Colleges of the Southern
Association of Colleges and Schools and the National Association of
Schools of Art and Design. The others: Ringling School of Art &AMP;
Design in Sarasota, Fla., and Memphis College of Art. The Savannah
College of Art and Design and the Art Institute of Atlanta are SACS
accredited.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Student body: 430 students; with 120 living in the dorm. By
gender: 51 percent male, 49 percent female. By race, 64 percent
white, 19 percent African-American, 2 percent Hispanic-American, 6
percent Asian-American, 7 percent nonresident alien or
international. By comparison, the Art Institute of Atlanta has
about 1,900 students.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Breakdown by major: Design majors, 32 percent. Electronic arts
majors, including video and digital art, 32 percent. Fine arts
majors (printmaking, sculpture, painting, drawing and photography),
36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.s
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
