<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3721 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-PANHANDLERS0     10-01 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-PANHANDLERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To give or not to give: That is the question _ and moral dilemma
_ people face daily when confronted by panhandlers begging for
change
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Don't forget to show hospitality to strangers, for some who
have done this have entertained angels without realizing it!'' (The
apostle Paul in Hebrews 13:2.)
</P>
<P>
   ALTANTA _ In a busy street corner in downtown Atlanta, a man is
about to become invisible.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Russell Tinsley, a scarecrow-thin man with a Don
King Afro. Tinsley, a 68-year-old panhandler with dirty fingernails
so long they're shaped like claws, wobbles to his sidewalk perch.
Twenty-one pennies rest in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be all right,'' he announces to no one in
particular as he holds out a plastic cup. ``I'm a child of David.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley's disappearance isn't caused by magic.
</P>
<P>
   He simply ceases to exist as the lunchtime traffic swirls by him
on Marietta Street. Most people who walk past speed up as they
approach; a few glance over with concern, but do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   This grim street drama is played out hundreds of times each day,
part of urban life in the late 20th century. With every fleeting
encounter, a choice must be made _ to give or not to give?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard question,'' says Alan Harris, an activist for the
homeless for the past 16 years. ``I still don't have a simple
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Few do. There are an estimated 11,000 homeless people in Atlanta
on any given day. Some are in need. Some are on drugs or mentally
ill. And some are scamming. Each extended cup thrusts a moral
dilemma onto the panhandler's target.
</P>
<P>
   The right response seems simple at first. The Bible, Torah,
Koran and other holy books are filled with exhortations to help
strangers in need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theologically, you should think of people on the streets as
people created in God's image,'' says Andrew Walker, 40, a Georgia
Municipal Association employee who was so vexed by encounters with
beggars that he attended a recent seminar given by Columbia
Theological Seminary on the issue. ``You should be welcoming to
people you don't know because you could be entertaining angels.''
</P>
<P>
   But a seminar can only offer advice. The answers have to be
found on the streets, in that instant when both sides meet.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schiele is caught in such a moment.
</P>
<P>
   He is part of the crowd that streams by Tinsley on this sunny
afternoon in early fall. He doesn't break stride, doesn't even look
at Tinsley when the man extends his cup.
</P>
<P>
   Schiele is startled when asked why he didn't give. He says he
never gives to panhandlers. He prefers charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're going to do with the money, and what
they're going to spend it on,'' says Schiele, a 29-year-old
employee at the Federal Reserve Bank. ``I don't know if they got a
house and a job and come down here on their day off to panhandle.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people simply improvise. They bounce between compassion and
cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the day, the moon and whether I have change in
my pocket,'' says Jessie Bitetti-Griffin, Schiele's co-worker and
lunchtime companion.
</P>
<P>
   Bitetti-Griffin, 29, says she was once approached by a desperate
woman who said she needed bus fare to visit her sick daughter. She
gave the fare to the woman. Later that day, she saw the same woman
approach a passer-by with the same story.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, Tinsley insists his needs are legitimate. He pulls a
wrinkled paper from a plastic bag, containing seven prescriptions
from Grady Memorial Hospital for assorted illnesses, including
emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could work, do you think I'd stay out here and become
subservient for three or four dollars?'' he asks in a raspy voice.
``I got too much pride as a black man to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley says he nets about $17 a day from begging. He says he
can't work because he's too ill, and he has no family or friends.
He says he sleeps on a bed of cardboard in abandoned houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get a job again, maybe telemarketing,'' Tinsley
says, adding that he once did that kind of work. ``But first I
gotta get cleaned up. I gotta get shaved, trim my hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris Jolley says he's already found his job. A wheelchair
user, the 36-year-old man is holding a McDonald's cup outside of
Macy's department store on Peachtree Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodness!'' Jolley shouts to a statuesque woman, swiveling his
wheelchair to get a better view.
</P>
<P>
   Jolley has been panhandling in Atlanta for 11 years. But he
doesn't call it that _ he says he's a tour guide. He flags down
tourists and gives them directions to city landmarks. ``If I help
them,'' Jolley says, ``then I expect a donation.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes up to $100 on a good day, he says, from assorted
donations. ``I live better than some of the folks who work down
here,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   James Hall, 33, approaches Jolley, frowns briefly and walks by
his rattling cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen him for years,'' Hall says. ``This guy might be in a
wheelchair and limited in mobility, but he has the ability to do
telemarketing, work with his hands or get trained to work on a
computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolley says he'll lose his medical benefits if he works full
time. He earns enough from his panhandling to rent a $550-a-month
two-bedroom apartment, complete with a television, microwave, CD
player and VCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no shame at all,'' he says of his panhandling. ``It
pays my light bill, my gas bill. I get to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Morningstar of the Columbia Theological Seminary thinks
there are several practical ways to handle panhandlers.
</P>
<P>
   Associate director for its Lay Institute of Faith and Life, she
taught a seminar on the subject that included a couple of options.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of money, Morningstar suggests giving panhandlers
coupons to fast-food restaurants, keeping nonperishable food items
in your car for panhandlers on freeway exits, or giving them a 211
card _ a free service operated by United Way that refers people to
agencies for food, clothing, shelter and day care.
</P>
<P>
   But she also gives money _ even though she knows it might be
used to buy drugs or alcohol. It's not her place, she thinks, to
judge others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one of us is created by God and loved by God,'' says
Morningstar, 49. ``When you pretend that a person is not there and
do not acknowledge their humanity, it's a slam in the face of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Russell Tinsley, the invisible man.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, he's not having much luck. In two hours, only five
people _ mostly blue-collar types _ have stopped by to give him
change.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch hour crowd is thinning. Tinsley wraps a dirty
imitation-leather jacket closer around his thin body. A young man
in jeans and shades steps out of a pizza shop, looking like a young
Tom Cruise. He pauses and drops 50 cents into Tinsley's cup.
</P>
<P>
   A faint smile spreads across the panhandler's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone like him is obviously down on his luck,'' says Patrick
Venturella, 30, a tourist from New York. ``It's not something I do
all the time. You can be cold and callous but you gotta look at it
from their perspective. I've gone through periods where I've been
broke. You live on five bucks a day in these little minimum wage
jobs. You remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Venturella shrugs and glances at Tinsley once more. Then he
vanishes into the sidewalk traffic, leaving the panhandler alone at
his sidewalk stoop. The chattering pedestrian traffic surges past
Tinsley's outstretched hand. He fades into the urban landscape,
just another bedraggled beggar, once again invisible.
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
