<HEADER>
A3727 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      10-01 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Oct. 2 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-COALITION (Washington) _ In a striking testament to
the potency of his presidential quest, Gov. George W. Bush glosses
over many issues vital to the Christian Coalition but still draws a
rousing ovation at the group's annual conference here. Unlike his
rivals for the Republican nomination _ and past front-runners who
have addressed the organization of religious conservatives _ Bush
essentially delivers his standard stump speech to the more than
3,000 delegates. His only nod to the group was an appended passage
where he mentioned his championing of a measure in Texas on
parental notification on abortion. By Richard Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-COMPANIES (Undated) _ Gun manufacturers react to the growing
pressure from lawsuits by cities across the nation. By Fox
Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran, Iran) _ Iran's supreme religious leader
moves decisively to head off a fresh confrontation with the
country's reformist president, instructing hardline Muslim clerics
and their loyalists in the country's police not to ``take matters
into their own hands'' in a new and potentially explosive dispute
involving Tehran university students. By John F. Burns. 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokaimura, Japan) _ Developments: The radiation leak
has been stopped; it has prompted a debate over the future of
nuclear power in Japan. Many Japanese are angry over the way the
government handled the incident. By Howard W. French. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-GANDHIS (Rampur, India) _ The political and personal soap
opera of Sonia Gandhi and ``the other'' daughter-in-law, Maneka
Gandhi. By Barry Bearak. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-NEWYEAR-VACANCIES (New York) _ Despite all the hype, the
puff, the ``reserve now or you'll be ringing out the twentieth
century in Scranton'' threats, bookings for the New Year's holiday
have been slow. And there is at least the possibility that for
hoteliers, restaurateurs and impresarios, the party to end this or
any other century may turn out to be a bit of a bust. Not a total
bomb, of course. Reservations at hotels and restaurants are still
ahead of where they would be in a normal year, and travel and
tourism honchos express confidence that everything will be entirely
booked by the big day. But New Year's Eve has not, so far, been the
blow-out many expected. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
