<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-DOLLAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BUSINESS CONFIDENCE GROWS, EURO STAGES A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ After a nearly nonstop slide against the
dollar for the first six months of its life, the euro is coming
back into vogue.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, the common currency adopted in January by 11 European
nations, jumped 3.6 percent this week. On Friday it reached $1.0767
in European foreign-exchange trading, its highest level in eight
weeks, before settling in New York at $1.0728.
</P>
<P>
   That level is still well below the euro's opening value of
nearly $1.18 at its introduction on Jan. 4, but it represents a big
shift since the currency plunged to just a bit more than a penny
above the dollar in July.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts now believe the euro will continue to climb in the
weeks ahead, even if does not recoup its original value.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate reason for the rise is a growing suspicion that
the European Central Bank, which oversees the euro, might raise
interest rates soon to help cool inflationary pressure. Rising
rates tend to make a currency worth more.
</P>
<P>
   But the broader reason behind the euro's advance is an
unmistakable acceleration of European economic growth and a big
improvement in business confidence over the last month or so.
</P>
<P>
   Growth nearly came to a halt last fall, after the Asian and
Russian financial crises. European exports and industrial
production are now once again climbing.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Europe's biggest and most beleaguered economy,
business confidence has soared in the last month, in part because
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has veered sharply to the right and is
pushing through big cuts in taxes and spending.
</P>
<P>
   European central bankers have turned much more hawkish in the
last few days, warning that inflationary pressure might be rising
again and that it might well be necessary to cool things down with
an increase in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Noyer, the bank's vice president, warned last Monday
that price pressures had increased and that the bank might have to
react to the inflation risk sooner rather than later. Friday, two
of the bank's top officials issued broad hints in the same
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Wim Duisenberg, the central bank's president, said Europe's
outlook for growth had improved and dangers to price stability
should not be overlooked. Otmar Issing, the bank's chief economist,
warned that price pressures were on the ``upside'' and should not
be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their message has changed over the last four weeks,'' said
Joachim Fels, an economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in London.
``I wouldn't overrule an increase in interest rates at the next
meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank's board of governors is scheduled to meet next
Thursday, and the mere possibility of a rate increase has led
traders to buy up more euros and sell more dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Economists at Deutsche Bank Research, reflecting the view of
many experts, still predict that the bank will probably not raise
rates until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, analysts say there are other reasons for the euro's
second wind.
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth appears to be picking up in both Europe and
Japan, a development that is tending to pull capital out of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rest of the world looking better, it is now more
difficult to finance it,'' Fels said. ``Capital is looking for
other places to go.''
</P>
<P>
   As growth prospects here and in Japan improve, investors are
also focusing more anxiously on the huge U.S. trade deficit. A
widening U.S. deficit means that a larger supply of dollars is
leaving the country to pay for its imports, which can have a
weakening effect on the currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more surprising areas of economic expansion in Europe
is France, where the growth rate could reach 3 percent this year
and where the unemployment rate has fallen from more than 12
percent to about 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller euro-zone countries like Finland, Spain, Portugal and
Ireland are all growing rapidly. And though Germany remains
Europe's debilitated economic giant, business confidence has
climbed sharply there in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Back in April, central bankers were so worried about declining
confidence and even the possibility of a recession that they
reduced the European Central Bank's key interest rate from 3.0
percent to 2.5 percent. But the climate has changed considerably
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main rationale for the rate cut back in April was that
confidence was very low,'' said Sonja Helleman, a currency analyst
at Banque Paribas in London. ``But that is not the case now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
