<HEADLINE>
NASA SAYS LAUNCH OF CREW MODULE TO BE DELAYED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The already tardy launching of a Russian-built crew module for
the international space station will be delayed from early November
to no sooner than Dec. 26, NASA said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Space agency officials from the two countries agreed to the
change during a series of technical sessions this week in Moscow
and are expected to set a firm date by early November.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-foot-long Zvezda crew module will furnish the living
space and life support equipment for the three-member crews of
astronauts and cosmonauts that are scheduled to take up residence
next spring. Without it, future assembly of the new orbiting
laboratory would be stalled.
</P>
<P>
   The previous target of Nov. 12 for the module's launching from
the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan was already 17 months later
than originally planned. Chronic financial problems in Russia are
to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The latest postponement can be traced to issues in the United
States and Russia, including the electrical wiring problems found
aboard NASA's space shuttles, said Kyle Herring, a spokesman for
the agency's station program.
</P>
<P>
   The latter date will produce favorable lighting conditions in
orbit for the automated docking between the new module and the
unstaffed components of the new station that were launched and
joined in orbit late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The linkup is to take place over Asia, where there is radio
contact between Russian ground stations and all of the orbiting
components.
</P>
<P>
   The area will be too dark between November and early December
for the live television views of the rendezvous and docking
activities from cameras on the new module that are to be beamed to
Earth, Herring said.
</P>
<P>
   During the operation, the new module is to act as a passive
target for the Russian propulsion and U.S. docking modules that
were linked previously.
</P>
<P>
   The delay will also permit Russian engineers to extend the
module's pre-flight software tests that have been under way at
Baikonur for months, Herring said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the readiness of the shuttle Atlantis, which
had been slated to follow Zvezda into orbit in early December to
deliver tons of supplies for future station crews.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle flights, however, were suspended following the late July
launching of the shuttle Columbia. An electrical short that
jeopardized the Columbia launching prompted a lengthy round of
inspections and repairs of the wiring on Discovery, Endeavour and
Atlantis before launchings resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery should be ready to launch before Thanksgiving on a
high-priority mission to replace failing gyroscopes on the Hubble
Space Telescope. Endeavour could be ready for launching in December
with a large radar apparatus to map the Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Wiring work on Atlantis did not begin until late this week, and
it is unlikely to be ready for launching on its station supply
mission until February.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the latest delay of the Russian crew module and the
shuttle wiring problems, station planners had scheduled eight U.S.
and two Russian construction missions for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The accumulation of delays will have a ripple effect, forcing a
succession of delays in those missions to furnish the American
laboratory module, electrical power generators and an airlock,
Herring said.
</P>
<P>
   The station's first resident crew, though, could be launched as
soon as March.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
