<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GOP-CHRISTIANS-HNS &LR;      10-01 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHRISTIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HOPEFULS COURT CONSERVATIVE RELIGIOUS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Christian Coalition exercised its clout within
the Republican Party Friday as it flailed Congress, chastised
maverick Pat Buchanan and embraced Texas Gov. George W. Bush and
other candidates seeking the party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want leaders who are motivated by love of country, not fear
of the next opinion poll,'' Christian Coalition founder Pat
Robertson told 3,500 cheering conservative activists attending the
``Road to Victory'' rally.
</P>
<P>
   All but two of the Republicans seeking their party's
presidential nod were scheduled to appear before the group in the
cavernous Washington Hilton and Towers during the two-day event.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has crafted a centrist message, got loud applause when
he sounded anti-abortion principles that remain at the core of the
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child, born and unborn, must be protected by law and
welcomed to life,'' Bush said in a 25-minute speech that touched on
personal responsibility, a stronger national defense, family themes
and the need for local control of education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also called for a tax cuts and a tax plan that helps those
emerging from poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, he accused the Republican-led Congress of
trying to ``balance their budget on the backs of the poor'' by
deferring tax-credit payments to people with low incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gary Bauer, the former president of the Family
Research Council and a favorite of religious conservatives,
received a standing ovation when he told the crowd: ``I will not
sacrifice one baby for political gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer also vowed an administration that would work to overturn
abortion rights, repeal trade pacts with China and block gay rights
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage is between a man and a woman, not a man and a man,''
Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before his speech, Bauer's wife, Carol, took the lectern
and tearfully insisted that rumors that her husband had had an
affair with an female aide were unfounded and untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's campaign accused aides with billionaire publisher Steve
Forbes of spreading the lies and innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign adamantly denied being the source of the
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, the former Red Cross president, invoked the
image and deeds of former President Ronald Reagan to bolster her
conservative credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to lead with your heart, not with the latest polling
data,'' said Dole, using one of several applause lines that got
only a tepid response here.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican presidential candidates did not appear before the
rally _ Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Buchanan, who has strongly
hinted he will bolt the GOP and seek the Reform Party presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson issued a warning to Buchanan that conservatives would
not follow him to a party that was founded by billionaire H. Ross
Perot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see him taking many Christian conservatives with him,
not to the Reform Party,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused Republicans in Congress of doing little to
further the causes of the religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We helped you to be elected. Now we ask for your principled
leadership. We ask for courage,'' Robertson said, adding that ``it
is better to lose fighting a noble cause than to live in peace as a
coward.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson saved his most blistering rhetoric for President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we prepare for a new millennium, I want to start with
cleansing the highest offices of the land from the sleaze and the
equivocation and the moral rot, which has embarrassed us all,''
Robertson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
