<HEADER>
A3740 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SUPREME-COURT-$ADV03-     10-01 1566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-COURT-$ADV03-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WEIGHS AID TO RELIGION, FREE SPEECH AND CONGRESS' POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 3)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Should states be allowed to give computers bought
with taxpayers' money to parochial schools? Does a limit on
campaign donations to candidates for state offices
unconstitutionally restrict freedom of expression. Has Congress
gone too far in protecting personal privacy and the rights of
women?
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court takes up these and other hot-button issues
this fall as it wrestles with a wide variety of cases in its
1999-2000 term that starts Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the court may have to deal with some cases without
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, who underwent surgery for colon cancer
on Sept. 17 and is recuperating at home.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg did some work during her hospitalization, taking part
by phone or with written comments in the court's review of hundreds
of appeals that had come in over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Although she may miss some oral arguments, court observers
expect her to vote on all the cases before the court. But if she
were to excuse herself from any case, these experts say her absence
would likely have little impact on the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Berger, a Columbia University law professor, noting that
Ginsburg is one of the most liberal justices and rarely casts a
swing vote, says that her absence would mean ``that on a close
vote, the court would go 5-3 instead of 5-4.''
</P>
<P>
   The parochial school issue is a recurring problem for the high
court given the First Amendment rule that ``Congress shall make no
law respecting an establishment of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the justices have agreed to decide whether the state of
Louisiana can continue to use taxpayers' money from a federal bloc
grant to provide computers, software and library books to religious
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the court further relaxed the
separation-of-church-and-state doctrine by allowing public school
teachers to go into religious schools to provide remedial tutoring
for low-income students under a federal aid program. In that case,
the court said there was no violation of church-state separation
because the public school teachers were instructing the poor
students in secular subjects.
</P>
<P>
   In the Louisiana case, the Clinton administration wants the
court to apply that rule to computers and other electronic
equipment. ``We need to be sure all school children learn to use
computers and are connected to the Internet,'' U.S. Solicitor
General Seth Waxman said in a written argument to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of school vouchers, which President Clinton has
opposed, are backing his position in this case because they see it
as a chance for the court to open the door for the use of taxpayer
money for private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voucher issue is cropping up all over the country, and
this case gives the court an opportunity to give some guidance as
to where the boundary between church and states lies in regard to
schools,'' said Steven Shapiro, legal director of the American
Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   The first big case on the court's docket involves a dispute over
whether a Missouri law capping contributions from individuals to
candidates for statewide office at $1,075 interferes with the
donors' right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the case will give the court a chance to reconsider
its 1976 ruling that upheld limits on contributions to federal
campaigns. In that decision, the court said that although political
contributions were protected under the First Amendment's right to
free speech, the government could limit their amount to avoid the
``appearance of corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the system is screwed up in that it favors
incumbents and candidates with a ton of money,'' says Professor
Joel Gora, a campaign finance expert at Brooklyn Law School. He
adds: ``The court could take this opportunity to really change the
laws and make the system a little more fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In another First Amendment case the court will decide whether a
public university can use mandatory student fees to fund
organizations that support political or religious views that some
students believe are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the U.S. 7th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the
University of Wisconsin had violated the free speech rights of
students who objected to their fees being used to fund a campus
women's center that supported abortion rights and an environmental
group that lobbied against mining and supported a presidential bid
by Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the number of publicly supported groups that hold
strong political or religious views, this case could have a major
impact on how public money is spent,'' says Stephen J. Wermiel, a
law professor at American University in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Another free-speech case involves a Colorado law that places
restrictions on abortion protests. The state law makes it a crime
for a demonstrator near an abortion clinic to approach another
person within eight feet in order to distribute leaflets, display
signs or engage in conversation unless invited to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy and women's rights issues are intertwined with a
question that keeps popping up before the high court: Where does
the power of Congress end and the power of states begin.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chief Justice William Rehnquist, the court has tended to
favor the states. Beginning in 1992, when the justices said
Congress had no constitutional power to make states accept nuclear
waste, they have repeatedly rejected the idea that Congress can
give the federal government authority over states on issues such as
gun-free school zones and gambling on Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Now the court has agreed to decide, in a South Carolina case,
whether Congress exceeded its power when it barred state motor
vehicle agencies from revealing personal information about drivers
who did not consent to the disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from an appeal by the Clinton administration of a
ruling last year that declared the Driver's Privacy Protection Act
passed by Congress in 1994 was unconstitutional. The law was
enacted after a stalker in 1989 used data from the California motor
vehicle bureau to track down and murder TV sitcom star Rebecca
Schaeffer.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina, which was considering selling drivers' license
information to businesses that wanted it for commercial use,
challenged the law, and last year the U.S. 4th Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled it unconstitutional. The appeals court said the law
had offended ``our system of dual sovereignty'' by telling the
states what they could and could not do with their drivers'
records.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Supreme Court took a case that it could use to
decide whether Congress overstepped its power when it allowed women
to sue rapists, stalkers and other attackers under the 1994
Violence Against Women Act. The case involves a student at Virginia
Polytechnic Institute in Blacksburg, Va., who went to federal court
rather than a state court to sue two football players who she
claimed had raped her.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the 4th circuit appeals court rejected the
federal violence statute, saying it ``cannot be reconciled with the
principles of limited federal government upon which this nation is
founded.''
</P>
<P>
   Other federalism cases before the court will decide whether
states can impose additional safety regulations on ships and cars
that go beyond federal regulations and whether states can be sued
in federal court under a federal age discrimination law.
</P>
<P>
   The age bias case was brought by public university professors
from Florida and Alabama and could affect millions of employees in
all states, including those who are not teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The court also has agreed to decide whether the Food and Drug
Administration has the power to regulate tobacco products. The case
tests the government's effort to control cigarette makers and
prevent young people from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the FDA asserted broad authority over tobacco products
and enacted extensive regulations that restricted cigarette sales
and advertising. But the 4th circuit appeals court ruled last year
that the agency had gone too far by asserting power that belongs to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Other important cases before the court this fall include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether states can give grandparents visitation rights. A
Washington state couple, after their son committed suicide, were
denied the right to see their granddaughters by the girls' mother.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether health maintenance organizations and their physicians
can be sued under federal law for policies that give doctors
incentives to keep costs down and potentially influence medical
care;
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether police on patrol in a high-crime neighborhood may stop
a person because he fled when he saw them approaching;
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether the city of Erie, Pa., was within its rights when it
banned nude dancing, which is protected as a form of free speech,
to prevent crime associated with strip clubs, such as prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Congress had the right in 1996 to require cable
companies to completely scramble the signals from their adult
channels so children could not see them or to offer adult programs
only between 10 p.m. and 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV04-     10-01 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE GOOD SHOW THAT'S, LIKE, REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Oct. 4)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As easy as it is to bash TV, I think you need a certain amount
of it in your life. You come home. You're too tired to read. You
don't want to talk to one more person but you want some noise. So
you look for a good dependable story, something to make you laugh
or cry and whose characters you feel you know even if you never
worked in a hospital or a law office or lived in a town with moose.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally you hit upon a new favorite that moves right into
your personal agenda. You start to speak of it in terms of ``my
show.'' It's why you need to get home on a certain day by a certain
hour, and if anyone dares to put football on in its place you are
aggrieved.
</P>
<P>
   The remote jockeys, those casual TV watchers who can walk in,
sit down, click around until any old thing catches their eye may
not understand this need to connect with one show. They're kind of
promiscuous about their viewing.
</P>
<P>
   But we monogamous types are true to our show and once hooked
will likely stick around as long as it does. When it's finally
canceled, as all shows must be, we mourn and years later will
wonder what ever happened to Murphy and Frank? Cybill's friend
Maryanne? What about the woman who ran the store in ``Northern
Exposure''?
</P>
<P>
   There's always the chance it will happen again, and so, when the
new fall lineup is announced, we start to cruise in a casual but
mildly interested way.
</P>
<P>
   This year's slate didn't look too promising. It looked at first
like the same sad extremes of the human spectrum _ leering
lunkheads who tell barf jokes and serial killers. In between, all
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Even the reviewers were talking in cliches. Here's a
``hard-boiled cop show.'' Here's a show with a woman detective who
gets emotionally involved in her cases.
</P>
<P>
   How about a show with a woman lawyer who says, ``I hate men and
I play dirty''?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a befuddled man trying to survive in a houseful of women
with a mother described as ``catty,'' and a mother-in-law who's
``nettlesome.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a year when TV could show its sensibilities are in the
right place, seeing as how it's been under heavy attack for having
shows with too much violence, too much sex and all white faces.
</P>
<P>
   But there were few repentant signs. Here's a new series that
focuses on sex crimes. They could call it the Dismemberment Hour.
And look, it's on at 9 p.m., that golden hour between homework and
bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   TV is like the weather. We take it very personally and talk
about it as if we should have some say over it. But it just
delivers what it feels like. We say we want less blood and gore and
we get psychopath of the week. We say we want diversity and the
characters get another bleach job.
</P>
<P>
   There's a newspaper cartoon with a white Hollywood mogul sitting
by a pool surrounded by white people, and he says, ``I'd put more
blacks in my shows but look around. There just aren't that many in
real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Real life, at least outside Hollywood, is not full of lunkheads,
vicious killers and stereotypes. Real fathers are not buffoons.
Women do not hate men. Mothers-in-law are not nettlesome.
</P>
<P>
   And, by the way, male detectives get pretty emotional about
their cases, too. Fans of ``NYPD Blue'' say that Dennis Franz's
Andy Sipowicz gets so overwrought they fear each week he'll have a
heart attack. And his connection with his late partner, they
contend, was the most convincing love story on TV last year.
</P>
<P>
   There is something new this season, however, that just might
grab on and become a lot of people's ``my show.'' It's intelligent,
romantic and, like, real, and it might make Tuesday at 10 p.m. a
regular date.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``Once and Again,'' and not only does it have two
guilt-ridden divorced people who are both over 40, which is so real
it hurts, but they have children and ex-spouses who are downright
typical, not overdrawn ogres.
</P>
<P>
   It's sexy in a mature-couple-with-kids-watching way. So far it
has a divorced father character who can talk about being afraid of
being alone, a divorced mother character who likes flirting again
but isn't sure she should take time out from her kids, and a
teen-age daughter character who's conflicted about her looks and
going to a make-out party.
</P>
<P>
   That there was that much worth commenting on after one show,
along with the fact that some of us were wondering where Sela Ward,
the mother character, got her lipstick, is a strong sign of early
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
