<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECNYA-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SEVERS TIES TO THE REPUBLIC OF CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
(th) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a move that could intensify the conflict in the
northern Caucasus, Prime Minister Vladimir V. Putin cut Moscow's
last links with the elected government of the breakaway republic of
Chechnya on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For eight days, Russian planes have been bombing what it says
are strongholds held by Islamic militants in Chechnya who have
launched armed attacks against Russian territory. Moscow also says
the militants have set off bombs that have killed almost 300 people
in Moscow and other Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
   Putin declared that the only legitimate authority in Chechnya, a
region that eight years ago voted for independence from Russia, was
a parliament that took office on the eve of the defeat of Russian
forces in 1996 in their first, disastrous two-year war against
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Regional experts say the parliamentary leaders, who met Putin on
Friday in Moscow, had not been heard from since 1996 and had no
authority among the Chechnya population. The population, now
totaling less than one million, regard the parliamentary leaders as
puppets of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not say so directly, Putin effectively withdrew
Moscow's longstanding recognition of President Aslan Maskhadov, who
has repeatedly asked to reopen negotiations with Russian leaders.
As Russia carried out its aerial bombardment, Putin said he would
negotiate with Maskhadov only on the condition that he denounce the
Islamic militants who have set up base camps in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the discredited Chechen Parliament, Amin Osmayev,
told reporters Friday that the reinstituted parliament would be
based for now in Moscow and move later to Grozny, the Chechen
capital. ``The timing of our return depends on the situation in the
republic,'' Osmayev said.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya's official representative here, Mayerbek Vachagayev,
took Putin's action, however, as a declaration of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means war,'' Vachagayev said. ``Until now, we thought there
would be some way to agree with Moscow. But now it is clear there
is none.''
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov had called for talks and asked regional leaders to
mediate. Putin rejected every offer, Vachagayev said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leadership now intends to set up a puppet government
that it would try to install in the north of Chechnya and use to
rubber stamp a military offensive, just as they tried to do in
1994, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other regional leaders were also stunned by Putin's
announcement, saying it can only make a bad situation worse. ``The
legitimate authority in Chechnya is President Maskhadov, whether
anyone likes it or not,'' President Ruslan Aushev of Ingushetia
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ingushetia borders Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maskhadov is being left no chance,'' Aushev said. ``He is
being driven into a corner. I can't understand what kind of
advisers Mr. Putin has if they advise to take this road.''
</P>
<P>
   Aushev mocked the parliamentary leaders, who he said were
``perfectly aware that they will have no influence, no prestige in
Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin made his announcement as Western governments stepped up
warnings to Moscow not to intensify the Chechnya conflict and to
move swiftly toward a political settlement. Until now, the
international community has cautiously supported the campaign
against the militants.
</P>
<P>
   But as bombing continues, the conflict has spread across
borders. More than 80,000 civilians have spilled into neighboring
Ingushetia, creating what a Russian official belatedly conceded
Friday was a serious humanitarian crisis. Federal and U.N. agencies
are scrambling to provide food and shelter for the refugees, mostly
women and children.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Refugees interviewed on Russian television said the bombing had
killed numerous civilians. Chechen authorities have put the
casualties at several hundred. But with Chechnya cut off by a wave
of kidnappings by gangs led by wayward warlords, there has been
scant independent confirmation of the damage or casualty numbers.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50,000 federal troops are massed along the Chechnya
border. On Thursday, some reports said, columns of troops advanced
several miles into Chechen territory, although the Russian military
has denied that.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya's representative here, Mayerbek Vachagayev, said the
troops had moved into the areas around Naursky and Shelkovskoy
along the eastern and western borders.
</P>
<P>
   Russian newspapers have reported this week that preparations are
under way for a ground invasion. Some reports said it might start
in days and move across the Chechnya lowlands up to the Terek
River, effectively redrawing the border between Chechnya and the
rest of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters Friday, Defense Minister Igor D. Sergeyev
did not deny that Russian troops would move into Chechnya. But
Sergeyev said the goal would be to establish a ``security zone''
along the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
