<HEADER>
A3761 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     10-01 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Father in Heaven''
</P>
<P>
   By John W. Cooper
</P>
<P>
   Baker, $19.99
</P>
<P>
   Using full-bore inclusive language for the God of the Bible is
like using a pocketknife to open a paint can: Not only is it the
wrong tool for the job, but it's all too possible to wind up with a
serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Cooper doesn't use that figure of speech in ``Our Father
in Heaven,'' but it's a fair summation of his case.
</P>
<P>
   Should we _ can we _ call God ``Mother''? Is the deity beyond
gender? Are the Bible and the Christian tradition sexist? Cooper, a
supporter of women's ordination and a professor at Calvin
Theological Seminary, painstakingly dissects the pros and cons of
inclusive language and argues that although the Bible does use
feminine imagery for God (and therefore believers can also do so in
certain ways), the church cannot adopt the inclusivist agenda and
remain true to Scripture _ which he sees as the central issue in
the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's study is rather technical and certainly not a light
read. But ``Our Father in Heaven'' approaches this difficult and
touchy topic with great care and considerable subtlety, and it
deserves the attention that it demands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountain High ... Valley Low''
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Adams
</P>
<P>
   Elektra Records
</P>
<P>
   This is Yolanda Adams' moment, and she's not letting it go to
waste.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who has become the top contemporary female gospel singer,
took an at least slightly controversial route by recently signing
to a secular label, Elektra (home of the sometimes decidedly carnal
Doors, for instance) after releasing four CDs in 10 years for
smaller labels Tribute and Zomba.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't happen that often, and it wasn't as if Adams needed
Elektra to maintain her career: She long ago became a huge favorite
in the gospel community and frequently shared the stage with gospel
superstar Kirk Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   But Adams clearly wants to build on her success _ and no doubt
would also like the crossover pop/contemporary Christian/R&AMP;B
success that Franklin has enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Mountain High ... Valley Low'' is any indication, she will
have it. A richly varied contemporary gospel CD, ``Mountain'' finds
Adams co-writing five of the CD's 11 tracks, and often working in
tandem with veteran superstar producers Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis,
who have produced numerous multimillion-selling CDs for Janet
Jackson and other mainstream R&AMP;B stars.
</P>
<P>
   Like Franklin, Fred Hammond and several others, Adams is
striving to give gospel a clean, contemporary R&AMP;B feel. And like
them, she is largely successful. There are definite touches to the
opening ``Time to Change'' (a terrifically catchy number about
personal responsibility) and definite nods to Whitney Houston's
big, sweeping ballad style throughout.
</P>
<P>
   But Adams is not ``going secular.'' These songs are clearly
rooted in religious messages, from following God's will on
``Wherever You Are'' and ``Open My Heart'' to reaching out to help
other people on the moving ``The Things We Do.'' As with previous
Adams CDs, there is a slight overreliance on big ballads, but in
general this is a very good contemporary gospel release.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
