<HEADER>
A3762 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TORONTO-FILMFESTIVAL-     10-01 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-FILMFESTIVAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR CRITIC'S NORTHERN EXPOSURE LEAVES HIM GROGGY FROM FILM
OVERLOAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Toronto International Film Festival is not the oldest in
North America; that would be the San Francisco International
Festival. Nor is it considered the most prestigious _ that title is
a toss-up between the Sundance and New York festivals. But the
Toronto festival is easily the most comfortable, and it has the
most interesting mix of mainstream and international fare. It has
more than 300 films to choose from, so one would hope that would be
the case. (And you can tell which people are in Toronto to check
out the festival; they stumble through the downtown streets in a
daze, happy but more sleep-deprived than most new parents.)
</P>
<P>
   If you decided during last month's festival that you were
interested in studio pictures with an imminent release, there were
films such as ``Boys Don't Cry,'' the achingly tragic true-life
memoir of Teena Brandon, the young woman who impersonated a boy, or
``Black &AMP; White,'' director James Toback's heated and funny quest
to deal with the race issue in pop culture. And those movies
generated as much conversation as any movies playing at the
festival's 24th installment, proving that even the films that most
might consider mainstream because of their associations with major
studios deserved a look.
</P>
<P>
   Or if you were looking for less-than-mainstream fare, there was
also ``The War Room,'' the troubling directorial debut of actor Tim
Roth, a film that may have provoked the incensed audience response
during a question-and-answer segment held at the end of the movie.
That's saying something, because Canadian audiences tend to wait
politely in movie lines that are so long they bring back memories
of seeing queues in the Soviet Union for bread and toilet tissue.
One of the endearing aspects of Toronto's festival is that the city
takes part in it; the pictures are well attended by residents.
(Keep in mind that Toronto, New York and Los Angeles have the
highest movie-theater attendance in North America.) The lines are
also filled with excited conversation about the movies, with
attendees gleefully trading information. It's stimulating to be
part of a festival whose mandate isn't to serve the rarefied
movie-business crowd. It should be said, though, that the show-biz
component gets bigger and bigger every year.
</P>
<P>
   It's been noted that this year's festival featured films that
deal with sexuality more than any other year in recent memory. But
given the stigma facing adult sexuality in the cinema, the movies
focusing on this subject in Toronto gave the collection of films a
buzz of sophistication lacking in other festivals. Some films, such
as ``Lies,'' which was quickly tagged the Korean ``Last Tango in
Paris'' (part of it even takes place in Paris), featured a graphic
look at the power plays between an older man and a younger woman.
(The subject matter got ``Lies'' banned in its home country, where
it has yet to play.) Even the studio pictures premiering here, such
as ``American Beauty,'' struggled to bring a discussion of sexual
politics to the proceedings. And ``Beauty'' wasn't the only movie
to touch briefly on the baby boomer-chasing-teen-age girl story:
besides ``Lies,'' there was ``Gregory's Two Girls,'' a
disappointing sequel to the fluky 1980 comedy by Scottish director
Bill Forsyth, whose better days seem long behind him. (There is
also an aspect of the theme in Roth's ``War Room,'' although it's
part of the predatory, incestuous relationship in which a father
forces himself on his young daughter.)
</P>
<P>
   Equally potent on the subject was the French film ``Une liaison
pornographique,'' which showed the power of language. The movie is
a series of funny, corrosive interviews with a couple describing
their highly charged affair. Provocative subject matter wasn't
simply limited to films about sex. Kevin Smith's ``Dogma,'' a
revisiting of the Christ story, was the talk of the festival, too.
Harmony Korine's follow-up to ``Gummo'' _ ``Julien Donkey Boy'' _
sent people out scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the films that got good buzz _ such as the crowd-pleaser
``But I'm a Cheerleader'' and the likable
white-guys-sitting-around-chatting movie ``The Big Kahuna'' with
Kevin Spacey and Danny De Vito _ were picked up for U.S.
distribution. But there wasn't the kind of distributor feeding
frenzy that most people expected. The haunting and beautiful
``Ratcatcher,'' a touching Scottish film with waves of magic
realism about a boy growing up in a squalid housing project, was
not bought. It deserves better.
</P>
<P>
   The international thrust of the festival has to be noted, too.
After all, this is the festival where ``Diva'' had its North
American premiere, and where ``Run, Lola, Run'' and Bernardo
Bertolucci's ``Besieged'' were first seen last year. ``Lola'' and
``Besieged'' caused such a stir that this year's festival was said
to be a letdown in comparison. But that kind of talk _ the
you-shoulda-been-here-last-year contingent _ can always be found at
a film festival. (Remember, too, that U.S. films are seen as
international in Toronto.) And anyone who saw the Michael Apted
documentary ``Me &AMP; Isaac Newton,'' a wonderfully entertaining look
at how scientists were inspired to pursue their various
specialties, had to be excited; each person had a beatific
expression as they spoke in vivid terms about their particular, and
peculiar, love of science. (A NASA scientist said seeing ``Flash
Gordon'' serials gave him the bug; he really wanted to be the
scientist who sent men into space.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite its size, Toronto is a festival that acknowledges its
roots. Hometown boy Norman Jewison, the director whose long and
intriguing career includes films as varied as ``In the Heat of the
Night, A Soldier's Story'' and ``Moonstruck,'' received a warm
response to the work-in-progress he chose to show here: ``The
Hurricane,'' his version of the story of boxer Rubin ``Hurricane''
Carter (Denzel Washington), a man railroaded into prison in the
1960s, and of the Canadians who mounted an investigation to get him
released. It was worth attending the festival to watch Carter speak
and move the crowd with his roiling, powerful reminiscences before
the film on his life played. (When some of the show-biz types in
the theater began to grumble during Carter's remarks, Washington
quelled the impatience with quiet authority: ``Take your time,
Rubin.'') There were enough moments like this to make me start
sleeping in to prepare for next year. .MDNM/ (Elvis Mitchell is a
film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
