r l BC-PIANIST-TURNAROUND-TE     10-01 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANIST-TURNAROUND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANO PERFORMANCE HELPED AMATEUR FINE-TUNE HIS LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fort Worth changed Greg Fisher's life.
</P>
<P>
   He's inspired. He's in demand. He's even engaged.
</P>
<P>
   When the Oklahoma pianist came to town to participate in the
International Piano Competition for Outstanding Amateurs in June,
he was only two years removed from a prison stint and four years
removed from the crack cocaine habit that put him there. He worked
part time, installing auto glass at his parents' shop. He saw a
parole officer once a month.
</P>
<P>
   But when Fisher put his fingers to the Steinway keyboard at
11:28 a.m. on June 11, Ed Landreth Auditorium became his oyster.
The audience shouted their enthusiasm for Fisher's 10-minute
performance, and that night, he socialized with the other 89
pianists at Van Cliburn's Fort Worth home.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the evening, Fisher was announced as one of 18
semifinalists.
</P>
<P>
   The semifinals is as far as he got, but it was far enough,
Fisher says. His performance of Liszt's ``Sposalizio'' was ``the
most fulfilling single performance of the competition'' wrote
Boston Globe classical music critic Richard Dyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great experience,'' Fisher says. ``I wouldn't trade
it for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Fort Worth almost immediately after the
competition to take master classes and to compete for the chance to
play with the Fort Worth Chamber Orchestra. He won, and debuted
with the orchestra June 22. Back at the University of Central
Oklahoma in Edmond, where Fisher is pursuing a graduate degree in
piano, he was offered four dates with the school orchestra (the
first was Sept. 28).
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Marlene, says that audience members from the Fort
Worth competition still keep in touch with him. Some have said they
plan to travel to suburban Oklahoma City to hear him play.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher now has a graduate assistantship at UCO, where the
competition ``kind of put me on the map,'' he says. He'll receive
his degree in May and hopes to pursue a doctorate at the University
of Miami, or with his former teacher, Richard Cass, at the
University of Missouri-Kansas City Conservatory. Then again, he'd
love to study for an artist's diploma in Italy under Benedetto
Lupo, the 1989 Cliburn bronze medalist.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fisher is back working at the glass shop part time
(but doing bookkeeping, not installing glass). His parole officer
released him from his last three years of parole.
</P>
<P>
   If all that weren't enough, Greg Fisher is engaged to be married
_ to another amateur competition contender, no less. Fisher met
Miho Yamada during the master classes that followed the
competition. Yamada, a pediatric cardiologist from Japan, was a
research fellow at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston until
mid-August, when her work visa expired. In November, Fisher will
travel to Japan to ask Yamada's parents for their permission to
marry their daughter. The wedding is scheduled for this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher says he has come away from the experience in Texas with
``lots and lots of pride.'' He attributes much of that to the
response his playing received from the Cliburn's hometown audience.
</P>
<P>
   Says Fisher: ``I can't imagine any pianist not falling in love
with the people of Fort Worth.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
