   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-ARREST _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A 41-year-old white man was
arrested on federal charges in two recent bombings at predominantly
black Florida A&AMP;M University, the FBI said today. The man was
identified as Lawrence Michael Lombardi. He is an unemployed father
of two from Tallahassee. He was arrested about 4:30 a.m. and
charged with a single count of manufacturing a bomb, according to
FBI agent Tom Kneir. (Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ PAINT LICK, Ky. _ Baked by a summer-long drought, some
Kentucky tobacco fields will produce half their typical yield. But
the real heat, the farmers say, comes from a $206 billion health
settlement by Big Tobacco. Experts predict cigarette prices will
keep climbing and escalating excise taxes will further diminish
domestic demand. That means Kentucky farmers will need to grow less
tobacco. Their toil has made Kentucky the state most economically
reliant on tobacco and helped generate the country's highest
smoking rate. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   YOGURT-MURDERS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Follow on the police
investigation into four suspects in the 1991 slaying of four
teen-age girls in a North Austin yogurt shop. Police release few
details today. We take a look at the shop today; the high school
the girls attended; the church that played a central role in the
days after the murders stunned the city. (Quin, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CARTER-BDAY _ AMERICUS, Ga. _ Former President Jimmy Carter
celebrates his 75th birthday Friday evening with a gala in Americus
(with entertainers and speakers ranging from Sam Donaldson to Pat
Boone to the Indigo Girls). Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, will
speak to reporters shortly before the event begins, and we'll quote
locals about what Carter's continued ties to the place he grew up
mean to them. (Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-SUMMIT _ PALISADES, N.Y. _ Nearly half the nation's
governors joined leaders of business and education Friday in
endorsing a new three-point plan for the next stage of reforms in
the nation's schools. They concluded the third national education
summit by calling on all states to emphasize strategies for
``improving teacher quality, providing all students a fair
opportunity to meet higher standards, and holding schools
accountable for results.'' The more than 100 leaders at the summit
came from governments, companies and organizations that supply more
than 90 percent of the money, teachers and administrators in public
schools. (Mollison, Cox Service).
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-PRISONS _ Ten months after taking their first convicts,
two of Georgia's three private prisons are failing to meet the
state's minimum standards in inmate health care, staffing and
security. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
