<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3793 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CHILD-CARE-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      10-01 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-CARE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD CARE SCARCE IN TEXAS, SURVEY INDICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Quality child care is both scarce and expensive
in Texas, where only 5 percent of working poor families who need
government subsidized care actually receive it, a new survey shows.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Workforce Commission Chairwoman Dianne Rath underscored
the depth of the problem Friday as she released the 1999 Texas
Child Care Portfolio, billed as the first comprehensive survey of
child care data in Texas. The study covers child care conditions in
all 254 of the state's counties.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows that the average weekly price of child care in
Texas is $83 for infant and toddler care, $73 for preschool care
and $48 for school-age care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a single mom working full-time in a minimum wage
job will have to pay on average in Texas 40 percent of her income
for care at a licensed child care center for one child under the
age of 2,'' Rath said.
</P>
<P>
   Such information is critically important to recognize and
understand as the state moves more families from welfare to work,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be sure that we have child care available, but we
also need to be sure there is quality child care available,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just over half, more than 2 million children in Texas aged 13
and under, are in need of some type of child care, the survey
shows. Yet there are slots available for only 772,000 of them in
regulated day care centers and homes, said Nancy L. Hard, a child
care consultant who served as director of the project.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are especially worried about the potentially
unsafe and unreliable ``patchwork solutions'' of those in
unregulated care, she said, noting some of the children might have
no supervision at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where quality comes in. They're in substandard quality,
they're in very fragile relationships _ maybe two days with a
grandmother, a day with an aunt, a day with a neighbor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where if it falls part _ if somebody gets sick or a car
breaks down or somebody has a doctor's appointment _ we really do
see the effect on the employer's bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also identified important emerging trends, such as
growth in service sector and industrial jobs with non-traditional
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``More of the growth in the Texas economy is expected to occur
in industry that will be utilizing swing shifts and receiving
increasing numbers of seven-days-a-week, 24-hour-a-day jobs
available,'' Rath said.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that in Dallas County fewer than 16 out of every
100 child care providers offered child care before 6 a.m. or after
6:30 p.m., yet that was better than in other large metropolitan
areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Harris County, which includes most of Houston, only 69
child-care facilities, less than 2 percent of the total, offered
services during non-traditional hours. Weekend care was available
at 238 or 6.5 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   The study also draws attention to the problem of rewarding and
retaining child care workers, who are often lured to other entry
level jobs where wages are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not able to keep those people in child care,'' Rath
said. ``We're seeing 30 to 40 percent turnovers in the child care
staff, which is very unstable for children in care and also
difficult just from a management perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
