<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     10-01 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP GIMMICKRY 
 GORE COUNTS ON DIXIE  
 WATCHING OUT FOR RURAL AMERICA  
 EMBATTLED REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 Washington Bureau   
 New York Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the political upheavals of the Gingrich era
and the impeachment saga, Republicans promised a new era in the
House. There might not be as many bold initiatives, they said, but
the trains would run on time.
</P>
<P>
   Better check that watch. Despite months of warnings, Congress
confronted a derailment of sorts as the new fiscal year kicked off
Friday with most of the annual spending bills still unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the way I would want government to work,'' sighed
Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala., who sits on the Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are having a hard time crafting the 13 spending
bills because they have seemingly contradictory goals. They propose
tax cuts, but they also want increased defense spending. They
proclaim that the Social Security surplus is off limits, but budget
analysts say they are in danger of breaking their promise. They
talk of spending cuts, but fear being labeled as callous.
</P>
<P>
   Gimmicks are coming in handy. Republicans classified some
routine spending as an ``emergency,'' a designation that allows
them to ignore their own self-imposed budget caps.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, for some programs, congressional leaders have
created what amounts to a 13th month, pushing spending beyond the
12-month fiscal year so they don't have to fully count it.
Democrats have mockingly dubbed this new month ``Spendtember.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world we wouldn't do that,'' conceded Rep. Dan
Miller, R-Fla., an Appropriations Committee member, about some of
the creative accounting techniques. He described the process as
``frustrating,'' but said competing interests within Congress and
with the Democratic White House forced lawmakers to look for
less-than-perfect solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Strategy
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is attracting all the buzz for the aggressive
insurgent campaign he has mounted against Vice President Al Gore,
but Gore may have a secret weapon _ the South.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's been very active on what he considers his home turf and
he bolstered that emphasis this week with the move of his campaign
to Nashville, Tenn. Bradley, on the other hand, is concentrating
his efforts in California, Iowa and the Northeast while paying
scant attention to Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen it,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La., when asked
if he had noticed evidence of Bradley working the South. ``Bradley
has positioned himself to the left of Gore and I think that is
going to be a problem in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign is calculating that strong early showings up
North will quickly translate into organization and support in later
Southern primaries, when about one-third of the delegates to the
party convention will be chosen. But Gore's staff is confident that
his Southern strength will hold, particularly among black voters
who have been among the Clinton administration's strongest
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Country Caucus
</P>
<P>
   A new congressional caucus that will look out for the interests
of rural America is being organized.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., who is working with Rep. Jo Ann
Emerson, R-Mo., envisions the aptly named Congressional Rural
Caucus as a way to ``promote economic and social policies'' that
may not always be in sync with the priorities of big cities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the area of health-care reform, many lawmakers
from rural areas say the problem of access to medical care is just
as important as the more popular talk about patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   A rural caucus existed in the 1970s and 1980s, but the group
disbanded in 1994 because of new congressional rules and little
money.
</P>
<P>
   Endangered Species?
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Southern Republicans was instrumental to the GOP's
winning control of the House of Representatives and the region is
usually viewed as increasingly safe territory for congressional
Republicans. It is the Democrats who are supposed to be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   But a political handicapping sheet in Washington paints a
different picture. Eight of 14 embattled GOP incumbents listed in a
recent edition of the Rothenberg Political Report hail from the
South while just one of 11 Democrats does.
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation: GOP gains in the region have resulted
in Republicans' moving into seats serving areas with enough
Democrats to keep the districts competitive. Surviving Democrats,
on the other hand, represent districts with solid Democratic
majorities, making them difficult to knock off.
</P>
<P>
   Among Southern Republicans on the endangered list are Reps. Clay
Shaw of Florida, Richard Baker of Louisiana and Robin Hayes of
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
