A3797 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV04     10-01 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV04-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE FOR MONDAY OCT. 4 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 GETTING THOSE PAPER CLIPS ALL LINED UP 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is Get Organized Week, proclaimed by the National
Association of Professional Organizers. And here's a handy idea,
from NAPO's list of ``Home Organizing Tips'': ``Group similar
objects together.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Donna Karan &LR;  hired feng shui maven  &UR; David Raney &LR;  to
examine her new flagship store on Madison Avenuein New York. Raney
made several adjustments of the ``energy flow'' and lighting, he
told New York magazine, particularly at the front of the store,
where ``the energy coming from the sidewalk to the building's
entrance created a less than harmonious feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you feel liberated,'' he said. ``Liberated to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME SWEET HOME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Observer sent  &UR; Philip Weiss &LR;  to Chappaqua, the
Westchester County town where the Clintons have just bought a house
that ``screams `rich doctor,' '' he writes. The house is on a
``cul-de-sac with a perfect yellow gravel driveway and specimen
plantings, as they say in Chappaqua, whatever specimen plantings
are. And no blacks. This is probably the first place  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 
will live without black people around.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Weiss, ``People move here for the schools, and
there's a stern family feeling about the place. ... The real estate
agents hand out sheets listing where all the '99 high school
graduates are going to college.''
</P>
<P>
   The property's tax bill is $26,000 a year. ``Everyone in
Chappaqua is wealthy. ... They don't want any blue-collar people
around _ tax them out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The autograph collection of well-known San Franciscan
 &UR; Proctor Jones &LR; , who was a regular in  &UR; Herb Caen &LR; 's column and died
earlier this year, will be auctioned at the Swann Galleries in New
York on October 14. The collection includes documents or letters
bearing the signatures of  &UR; Napoleon &LR; ,  &UR; Robespierre &LR; ,  &UR; George &LR; 
 &UR; Washington &LR; ,  &UR; Thomas Jefferson &LR; ,  &UR; John Hancock &LR; , &UR; Buffalo Bill &LR; ,
 &UR; Annie Oakley &LR; ,  &UR; Mark Twain &LR; ,  &UR; Alexander Dumas &LR; ,  &UR; Sigmund Freud &LR; ,
 &UR; Claude Monet &LR; ,  &UR; Frederick the Great &LR; ,  &UR; Charlie Chaplin &LR;  and others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART ATTACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite protests of New York Mayor  &UR; Rudy Giuliani  &LR; about
``Holy Virgin Mary,'' a work in which British artist  &UR; Chris Ofili &LR; 
employed elephant dung, the ``Sensation'' show opened at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  asked some of the art-lovers whether the work had
any particular scent: Said novelist  &UR; Tama Janowitz &LR; , ``The elephant
dung has an animal smell to it, like a ferret I once owned.'' &UR; Hugh
Grant  &LR; said he was ``quite disappointed'' to have been unable to
smell anything.  &UR; Anthony Haden-Guest  &LR; said, ``When you are surround
by artists like now at the opening reception, all you can really
smell is the sweaty artists and it is impossible to smell anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   And sculptor  &UR; John Ahearn &LR;  said that he smelled marijuana, which
seemed to be wafting from another part of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new show at the Whitney Museum of Art in New York features a
 &UR; Jackson Pollock  &LR; painting, No. 27, 1950, hung vertically, although
the artist's signature is horizontal. Next to the work are photos
of its first exhibit, at a New York gallery, when it was vertical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had only ever seen it hung horizontally,'' the current
show's curator, &UR; Lisa Phillips &LR; , told the New York Times. When she
first saw it vertical, she said, ``It was a revelation. We wouldn't
have done this if Pollock hadn't approved.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kirk Varnedoe  &LR; of New York's MOMA, who curated a previous
Pollock show, said it didn't matter too much to the artist, who
worked moving around his paintings. ``There's no telling if he had
any particular orientation in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``My first day of filming, he rigged a pail full of water over
my trailer door so that when I came out to do my first lines, I got
soaked. Then in a scene where I put on a pair of shoes, he had
filled them with toothpaste. In another scene when I reached for
the doorknob, he had taped wet Tampaxes around it. We had a cake
eating scene and Freddie slipped meat into the cake and I bit into
it, and it really grossed me out because I am a vegan.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Actress Julia Stiles, at a premiere party in New York for the
Japanese movie ``Princess Mononoke,` describing working with
Freddie Prinze Jr. on the forthcoming ``Down to You.''
</P>
</TEXT>
