<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3800 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$A     10-01 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Ticket to Ride, But Seats Aren't There
</P>
<P>
   When you bought your ticket, the airline said there was space on
the flight. But at the airport check-in counter, the agent tells
you and other ticket holders that the flight is overbooked _ and
somebody is not getting a seat. You and the other wannabes start
eyeing one another like members of the Donner Party on their way
into the pass. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., says this surprise should never happen.
In response to his earlier calls for legislation, airlines adopted
voluntary customer service plans. Not satisfied, he introduced an
amendment to a Transportation Department bill, eventually passed by
the House of Representatives; it comes before the Senate this week.
It would guarantee another change: at the time of ticket
reservation, an airline must inform customers who ask if it is
selling seats on a flight that is already overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of passengers are denied boarding every
year, but a report published quarterly by the Transportation
Department says that nearly all of these are ``voluntary,'' meaning
that they have accepted the promise of a seat on a later flight
plus vouchers for additional free travel, or even cash.
</P>
<P>
   The report lists the number of people denied boarding, and
calculates how many were involuntary, per 10,000 passengers
boarded. For the most recent report, covering January through
March, Continental had the lowest rate, at 0.31 involuntary bumpees
per 10,000, and Delta the highest, at 3.33.
</P>
<P>
   The average of 10 major airlines was 1.44, up from 0.95 for the
corresponding quarter last year. Other airlines with a rate above 1
were United, Southwest, America West and TWA. The report is
available at www.dot.gov/airconsumer/991qovs.htm.
</P>
<P>
   _Matthew L. Wald
</P>
<P>
   Charity Flows in Floyd's Wake
</P>
<P>
   From big tobacco companies to private foundations to a
Pennsylvania youngster who taped four quarters together and mailed
them in, Americans have moved quickly to help victims of Hurricane
Floyd in eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   An emergency relief fund set up by Gov. Jim Hunt raised nearly
$5 million in the first week of the fund-raising effort from
individuals and corporations, with thousands of contributions still
not tallied.
</P>
<P>
   And North Carolina foundations acted quickly in approving $2.15
million in allocations. They are expected to contribute at least $4
million. ``In my 20 years of doing this, I've never witnessed the
foundation community come together as they did on this,'' said
David Winslow, a consultant in Winston-Salem who was enlisted as a
volunteer by the governor's office to aid in fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate pledges included $1 million each from Food Lion and
Blue Cross and Blue Shield of North Carolina; $250,000 from R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco; $100,000 from Cisco Systems, and $50,000 from
Philip Morris, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Cohen
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
