<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-SCHOOLS-800(2TAKES)-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING, WRITING AND SOCIAL CLIMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 3) 
(jt) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edes Gilbert saw it all. For 15 years as the
headmistress of the Spence School, she saw the parents who lobbied
for their 7-year-olds to be assigned to classes with children who
weren't their friends but whose parents were rich and prominent _
in the hopes that the students would become friends and so would
the parents.
</P>
<P>
   She saw the jockeying to volunteer on the ``right'' parent
committees. ``Mothers would be upset because they weren't put on a
committee with someone who would give them that social leg up,''
said Mrs. Gilbert, who retired in 1998 from Spence, the prestigious
Upper East Side girls' school. ``Mothers would throw a hissy fit.''
</P>
<P>
   And she saw how back-to-school night, when parents flood the
school to meet teachers and rub elbows with other parents, often
had the aura of a competitive Park Avenue cocktail party, with some
adults networking furiously to set up play dates for their
daughters with the offspring of prominent parents like Sigourney
Weaver, Michael Bloomberg, Katie Couric and Ronald O. Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   In her decade and a half as headmistress, Mrs. Gilbert saw these
rituals become increasingly common as some parents came to view
Spence and other elite Manhattan private schools as akin to country
clubs and charity committees _ arenas in which to advance
themselves socially. ``You have to say to yourself, `What's wrong
with this picture?''' Mrs. Gilbert said. ``Where does it say that
school is supposed to take care of the social aspirations of the
parents?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is not a country club, but parents are treating it
that way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For the large and mostly affluent pool of New York's
private-school parents, the motivation has long been to secure for
their children certain perceived advantages over public schools:
smaller classes, rigorous academic programs, a haven from the chaos
of the larger society. Private education, at $16,000 a year for top
schools, has been seen as a gateway to good colleges and successful
careers. It still is. But increasingly, having a child in a
Manhattan private school, especially a score or so of schools on
the Upper East Side, is also a means of meeting the right people
and having a focus to one's social life _ for the parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old story was that you had to make it into those schools
in order to insure an Ivy League school for your child,'' said Dr.
Pamela Sicher, a child psychiatrist whose patients live mostly on
the Upper East Side. ``The reasons now seem to have more to do with
parents' feeling accepted on the social hierarchy and less to do
with progression toward academic success on the part of the
child.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gilbert, in her year since retiring, completed a study on
reforming the arduous kindergarten admissions process, commissioned
by a group of Manhattan private schools. The schools' kindergarten
applications have risen some 25 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   She said the pressures on very young children could be enormous.
``The children are carrying their parents' social hopes and
dreams,'' she said. ``Getting into the `right' school, so called in
the parents' eyes, means a lot to the parents. The 4-year-old gives
them a social leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   She stressed that this was not true for all parents at Spence,
not even the majority. But for an increasing number who may be new
to the city or to affluence, and who do not have strong ties to
churches, neighborhoods or other institutions, the school becomes
the social focus. ``What they think is that if they are associated
with the right institution, they will meet the right people,'' she
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One private-school mother who lives on Fifth Avenue and spends
weekends in Millbrook, N.Y., amid a colony of fox-hunting types,
said she was the target of parents who, she suspects, seek social
advantage. At school-related parties, ``certain people make a
beeline right for you,'' she said, adding: ``It's very obvious. One
lady who we know wanted to get to know the Millbrook crowd kept
asking me for play dates with my daughter, and my daughter is not
friends with her daughter. I know why she was asking. It's
obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Hausman, an author of ``The Manhattan Family Guide to
Private Schools'' (Soho Press, 1999), said: ``That's typical.
Social climbing through your children _ there's a lot of it. It's
high-class schmoozing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her co-author, Victoria Goldman, pointed out that the presence
of a famous or prominent person's child often swells the number of
applicants at a school. ``After Caroline Kennedy sent her kids to
nursery school at All Souls, it became the No. 1,'' she said.
``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   In their guide, the only one of its kind, Ms. Goldman and Ms.
Hausman generalize about the parental dress style, professions and
school-related activities like cocktail parties at many schools,
details meant to evoke the parental social life typical of each
school. Some schools have more of a social component, they note,
while others have little. Of the Chapin School on East End Avenue,
one of the city's seven private girls' schools, they write:
``Chapin is also social in the traditional sense. `You would never
dress informally for a school event,' we were told, although we
noted that khakis and hair clips have replaced suits and headbands
at drop-off and pickup.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Spence, on East 92d Street, they said one parent told them,
``Ascension through the ranks of Spence's Parent Association
requires a certain amount of social skill and savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Calhoun School on West 74th Street: ``Socially, Calhoun
is low-key. The primary focus is always on the child, not the
parent or social scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at many schools acknowledge that social climbing takes
place among parents but say they try to discourage it. Elizabeth
Manley Murray, the director of admissions at the Brearley School on
East 83d Street, one of the city's most sought-after, said
prospective parents regularly try to learn the names of the other
children in the grades their daughters are applying to. ``Parents
don't come out and ask me who else will be in their daughter's
class, but they ask other people, and I find out,'' she said. ``We
discourage it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Bosworth, the headmaster of St. Ann's School in Brooklyn
Heights, where there are 10 applicants for each place, said: ``Do I
have a repellent magnet that repels the social climbers? No. What I
do is make it somewhat awkward to be in this community because I do
not allow them to participate in the school as they do with many
private schools.'' There are very few parent-run fairs, he said,
and very few fund-raising auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Bass, the editor and publisher of Private School Insider,
an independent newsletter, said: ``There are tremendous social
expectations of parents. It's no longer who has the second house
but who has the third house and how many cars you have and what
fabulous vacation you're taking. These are the children you should
be hobnobbing with and also the parents. There are many parents who
think it's good for their businesses. There is a group who want to
social-climb through their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``The schools don't necessarily want that,'' but
``the parent body'' does.
</P>
<P>
   Still, are there ways that schools foster social maneuvering
among parents, and an aura that connections count in life? One is
suggested by the surprisingly widespread conviction among parents
that getting a child into some schools is like joining a club.
Maeve Heath, a marketing consultant, decided to put her daughters
into the Marymount School, where 65 percent of the students are
Roman Catholic and religion is part of the curriculum, after
visiting other girls' schools she deemed too social. ``I picked
Marymount because when I went to Nightingale-Bamford, I sat on the
bench with the other mothers who were applying with their
daughters, and it was a bunch of people who just all knew each
other, either from East Hampton or private schools,'' she said.
``They said, `Muffy,' `Buffy.' `It's just like old home week.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any connections, and I knew we wouldn't get
in,'' she added. ``I knew you had to know someone to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Her assertion was denied by Carole J. Everett, the director of
admissions for the Nightingale-Bamford School, on East 92d Street,
where according to ``The Manhattan Family Guide to Private
Schools,'' ``the parent body is diverse and varies from class to
class.'' Twenty-two percent of students are members of minority
groups. Ms. Everett, in an interview in her office, pointed to a
couch and said, ``People sit there and say, `I know so-and-so,' and
`We are good friends with the parents of so-and-so.' And that is
supposed to make them a good fit for our school?'' It has no
bearing, she said. Still, many parents, making inferences from the
notoriously opaque process in which their 4-year-olds are tested,
interviewed and observed at play when applying to kindergarten,
insist that it does matter whom they know. ``You hear about this
kindergarten thing, and you never really believe it until you go
through it,'' said one father, a magazine editor, whose son is now
a first-grader at an all-boys school. ``You hear that it is all
about connections. Then you apply, you write essays, you go in,
they look at you. Then you bring your son, and they look at him.
Then you go in again. And then you all go in. And you know what? At
the end, it's all about who you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether parents' social circles have anything to do with
who is admitted to kindergarten, Ms. Gilbert, the retired
headmistress, said: ``Without a question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the subtle ways we limit who applies,'' she
continued, adding that her report is aimed at making kindergarten
admissions more fair and open.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Buckley School on East 73d Street the other day, a
lawyer in a navy blazer stopped to chat after picking up an
application for next year's kindergarten class. Buckley, the
all-boys school where students address male teachers as ``sir,'' is
one of the city's most traditional. ``My partners' sons all went
here,'' said the man who would not to give his name or the name of
his firm. ``So will my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Walsh, Buckley's headmaster, said: ``Admissions are not
dependent on social aspirations or social contacts. We do not even
ask for letters of reference.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators and other experts say that children pay a price when
parents make them, even unwittingly, into agents of their social
aspirations. The impact can be general, manifested as anxiety
brought on by parental pressure. Or it can be quite specific, as
when children reflect their parents' hyper-awareness of status
symbols.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are absorbing an enormous amount of anxiety with
parents who are concerned if they don't get a certain place,'' said
Dr. Sicher, the psychotherapist.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gilbert said: ``The girls are given power they shouldn't
have. They are supposed to get good grades so they can go to
Princeton _ and then you are responsible for your parents' social
life? It's too much power for the child.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Sarasohn, whose daughter graduated from Spence in May,
marveled at how young her daughter's classmates were when many
began parroting parental notions about the ``right'' addresses and
vacation spots. ``They all know the good buildings,'' said Ms.
Sarasohn, a real estate broker. ``It went from kindergarten, where
they might think an apartment was great because there were a lot of
stuffed animals, to seventh grade, when they would describe who
lived in what building _ East Side, West Side.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Jamie Beilin, recalled how the mother of a
classmate who lived on the West Side used the Spence directory,
with its listing of student addresses, to select her daughter's
playmates from across Central Park. ``It started with the play
dates in the very first months of school,'' said Ms. Beilin, now a
freshman at Cornell. ``Then the birthday parties.'' Only girls from
Park Avenue and Fifth Avenue were invited.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude was once unusual at Spence, Ms. Sarasohn said, but
is now more common. ``There was always one parent who might be
orchestrating play dates for the wrong reasons, but that was the
exception,'' she said. Today, ``there's a mentality of who you
know, who you should get to know,'' she continued, adding: ``The
parents will comment on who else is in the child's class, who's
famous and social. The kids learn directly from the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sarasohn's daughter seems to be no exception. From her dorm
room last week, she expounded on one topic her 13 years of private
school on the Upper East Side had taught her: the difference
between a Range Rover and its cheaper-by-half cousin, the Land
Rover Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Land Rover looks like you want to have a Range Rover but
can't afford it, and it hurts you,'' she said. ``It looks like
you're trying, and the whole point is to look like you're not
trying, but you know. That's the style of the school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
