<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3816 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FAMILYHONOR-BOOK-REVI     10-01 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILYHONOR-BOOK-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELEN HUNT INSPIRED ROBERT B. PARKER'S FIRST FEMALE PRIVATE EYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After devoting years to his revered Spenser series, Robert B.
Parker has landed a book with his first female protagonist on the
bestseller lists. And he has Helen Hunt to thank for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weird, huh?'' the 67-year-old Parker says, chuckling, during a
phone interview. ``But, what the hell. It's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Los Angeles to attend the 1998 Oscars ceremony, Parker
says, he was told that the Academy Award-winning actress wanted to
meet with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turned out she was a fan of the Spenser books,'' Parker says,
``She asked me to write a book with a female character she could
play in the movie version. We talked at length. The deal we made
was, her (production) company would buy the novel even if, after I
wrote it, they didn't like it. I said to her, `This is my novel;
I'm interested in your views, but I might not pay attention to your
suggestions.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months later, ``Family Honor'' is a bestseller, and
Hunt loves the book. It's all about Boston-based private eye Sunny
Randall, who has split up with a Mafia-connected husband and is hot
on the trail of the missing teen-age daughter of a slimy
banker/politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw in some Helen Hunt things,'' Parker says. ``For
instance, I learned she loves to paint, so Sunny Randall likes to
paint, too. I like this new character, though Spenser will stay my
main focus. We'll see about Sunny. If `Family Honor' keeps selling
well, she may be back.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Family Honor'' is still fresh on bookstore shelves,
Parker is already working on Spenser's next adventure. He says it
takes ``four to five months for me to write a book, and that means
seven to eight months a year to do something else if I want, except
I don't. I like to write. I have no desire to travel to far places,
sit on the beach and look at sunsets. I don't fish or hunt. I just
go to the gym and lift weights, and then I come home and write _
five pages a day, five days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating his first female heroine was an interesting challenge
for Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I don't entirely understand a woman's point of
view,'' he admits. ``But I've been married to a very smart woman
for 43 years, and she was very helpful with her input. The hard
part for me wasn't how a woman puts on makeup, but, say, what does
a woman think when she's looking at a guy, their sexual take on the
world, all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   With his continued high ranking among modern crime novelists
assured, Parker doesn't mind admitting that he trusts his own
judgment as a reader as well as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just write books I want to read,'' Parker says. ``I don't
think about anything else when I'm doing a book, really. Not is
this a hot market topic, not is this politically correct. I'm not
one of those authors who thinks, `Hey, I'm the character I'm
writing about.' Spenser is fiction. And I'm not a writer who thinks
I'm on a higher mission than entertaining people with my books. I'm
not a crime fighter using a pen.''
</P>
<P>
   So whether it's Sunny Parker or Spenser, Parker's protagonists
will continue to be quick with quips and fists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been writing these books now for 25 years,'' he
concludes. ``I hope I'm getting better as a writer, and I'm
inclined to think most of the later books are better than the
earlier ones. But I'm going to keep writing a day at a time, a book
at a time, and if Helen Hunt asks for another one, I'm probably
going to give it to her.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
