<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-REEBOK-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS REEBOK STILL REELING OR POISED TO REBOUND?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of Reebok vs. Nike stocks is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE LEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the great sneaker face-off, Nike Inc. has cleaned the floor
with the competition. It had 34 percent of the $13.8 billion United
States athletic shoe market last year, nearly three times that of
its long-suffering rival, Reebok International, with 13 percent.
And Nike's market capitalization, at $16.25 billion, is about 28
times Reebok's.
</P>
<P>
   So why are some investors still betting on Reebok these days?
It's an interesting question.
</P>
<P>
   The past few years have been miserable for Reebok, largely
because the company was ill-prepared to cope with a consumer shift
from sneakers toward hiking shoes. Managers came and went. Adding
to the company's woes _ and not helping Nike, either _ was negative
publicity about use of child labor in the apparel industry.
Reebok's stock fell 31 percent in 1997 and 48 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the past four months have been particularly rough. The
stock, which had shown signs of bouncing back earlier this year as
investors warmed to a restructuring plan, has lost more than half
of its value since hitting a high of $22.75 on May 24. Last Friday,
Reebok hit a 52-week low of $10.25.
</P>
<P>
   The main cause of the recent decline was a disappointing second
quarter. Analysts had forecast that Reebok would report earnings of
12 cents a share. Instead, it posted earnings of 8 cents a share on
sales of $697.4 million, down from 11 cents a share on sales of
$760.6 million in the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some value investors say there is reason for Reebok to
rebound. In that camp is Robert Rodriguez, chief investment officer
for First Pacific Advisors in Los Angeles, which owns about 6
percent of Reebok's shares.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rodriguez calls the stock ``one of my most unsuccessful
investments,'' he says Reebok's stable of brand names, including
Rockport and Ralph Lauren footwear, still resonate with shoppers.
The Ralph Lauren line _ though small _ was a bright spot in the
second quarter, with sales up 42 percent, to $23.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Maramarco, manager of the Babson Value fund, which also
owns Reebok shares, likewise says the company has potential at its
current price. ``Sooner or later, people are going to come along
and pick this stock out of the gutter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maramarco and Rodriguez say they are bullish on some of the
changes being made by Carl J. Yankowski, a former Sony executive
who was hired last September as chief executive of Reebok
Unlimited, the sneaker division. Yankowski has put more focus on
women's and children's lines _ two areas in which Reebok has
traditionally done well.
</P>
<P>
   New senior managers have been hired and _ in contrast to Nike _
the company decided to place less emphasis on sports celebrities in
marketing. Debt and expenses were reduced, and last month, Reebok
announced plans to cut its payroll by 600 people after laying off
500 in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts say the changes have not exactly been
sweeping. ``It's hard for me to say that there's anything dramatic
going on,'' said Leslie McCall, an analyst at Brown Brothers
Harriman, where she has a neutral rating on Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCall has short- and long-term buy ratings on Nike and says
the stock, which closed at $57.5625 on Friday, will hit $70 within
12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rodriguez says Nike is the better company. But he says
Reebok, with a 1999 price-to-earnings ratio of 10.7 and a
price-to-sales ratio of just 0.2, versus 27.9 and 1.83,
respectively, for Nike, remains the better value. ``At the current
share price, it discounts a lot of Reebok's problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks Reebok's enterprise value _ what it would be worth to
an acquirer buying the entire company _ at $900 million to $950
million. The current stock price puts the company's value at $575.1
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
