A3833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CONGRESSIONAL-AWARD-H     10-01 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESSIONAL-AWARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS STUDENT TO RECEIVE NATION'S HIGHEST HONOR FOR YOUTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ No doubt about it, the challenge facing high school
student David DeFilippo was daunting.
</P>
<P>
   First he dedicated hundreds of hours to community service, then,
dictionary in hand, he haltingly navigated the pages of two
Spanish-language novels. Somewhere along the way, he scaled a
12,000-foot mountain.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, all of his effort will pay off. DeFilippo, 18, a
senior at Strake Jesuit College Preparatory, will become the 22nd
Texan in 20 years to receive the prestigious Congressional Award.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, will present the Silver Award during
ceremonies at Houston Community College's Central Campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to mention that David did not win this
award,'' Archer said. ``He earned it. Congressional Award
recipients represent the best America has to offer, and this young
man is a shining example.
</P>
<P>
   ``... We hear so much about what young people are doing wrong.
But we know that there are also so many young people who are doing
good things.''
</P>
<P>
   The award _ the nation's highest honor for youth _ is open to
contenders ages 14-23. To earn the gold, silver or bronze awards,
they must set and meet goals in four areas: volunteer public
service, personal development, physical fitness and
expedition/exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Seven thousand people have received the award since it was
created in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, the expedition was what really interested me,''
DeFilippo said Friday. ``But as I set my goals and began getting
involved, I recognized that the whole thing attracted me. It was a
way to get myself going in the right direction, a way to get
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFilippo began working toward the goals two years ago after his
mother, Marilyn DeFilippo, a reading teacher at Northbrook Middle
School, stumbled onto an article about the program in a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``She actually got the whole thing going,'' he said. ``She
showed it to me and said it might be neat.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet community service requirements, DeFilippo spent 200
hours, first as a volunteer at a Houston hospital then, during the
past two summers, as a counselor at a camp for young muscular
dystrophy patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was assigned to one kid with MD, Dwayne Campbell from
Houston, and I'd help him do whatever he couldn't do,'' DeFilippo
said, referring to multiple dystrophy. ``We'd do horseback riding
and canoeing. Mainly, we'd hang out. He was pretty fun to talk
to.''
</P>
<P>
   For the award's physical fitness section, DeFilippo, who had
played basketball and soccer in high school, devised a strenuous
regimen of daily workouts. For the expedition, he accompanied his
older brother Anthony DeFilippo, 21, and a friend on a three-day
outing near Ruidoso, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   In three grueling sunrise-to-sunset treks, the trio hiked about
25 miles. On the second day, they scaled Sierra Blanca. ``It was
pretty rugged,'' DeFilippo said. ``There were a lot of loose rocks
and the wind was going extremely fast. I have pictures of my
brother and I just leaning over into the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   For the academic section, DeFilippo twice made Jesuit's honor
roll, and, though a struggling Spanish student, he read Spanish
translations of two novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd read maybe 15 minutes a night,'' he said. ``I don't speak
Spanish at all. I struggled. I have a hard time with Spanish. When
I first started reading, any word I didn't know I'd look up in a
Spanish-English dictionary. I'd make notes. Then I bought English
versions of the books and read a chapter in each, comparing, trying
to get the feel.''
</P>
<P>
   For his reading, he chose Jean Craighead George's ``My Side of
the Mountain'' and C.S. Lewis' ``Lion, the Witch and the
Wardrobe.'' ``I picked those because I like them,'' he said. ``The
weren't Odyssey; they weren't complicated reading.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFilippo said he hopes to be admitted to the Air Force Academy
or, alternately, to pursue environmental studies at an as yet
unselected university.
</P>
<P>
   DeFilippo's mother _ his father is John DeFilippo, a computer
account manager at CISCO Systems _ described her son as a selfless
teen who ``really likes people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prejudiced,'' she said, ``but he really is very caring. He
puts other people before his own interests.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFilippo's brother, Anthony, is an engineering student at
Columbia University. His sister, Christina DeFilippo, 20, is a
sophomore at the University of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a really good kid from a really good family,'' said
Becky Sheetz, Congressional Awards Foundation spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
