<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3836 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS     10-01 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGE-MARKETS-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW WATCHERS' ALERT: HERE COMES OCTOBER DREAD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   September, historically the worst month for the Dow Jones
industrial average, has been worse than normal. Now, here is
October, which is the second-worst month of the year for the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, Federal Reserve policy makers will meet to
decide whether to raise their short-term interest-rate target for
the third time since June.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow dropped 4.5 percent last month, its worst September
since 1990. Since 1915, the Dow has declined 0.68 percent, on
average, in September. For October, the Dow's average performance
is a decline of 0.05 percent. All other months are up.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of 6.33 percent in October 1997 was the worst recent
performance for the Dow. Though investors may have unhappy memories
of the summer and fall of 1998, September and October that year
turned out to be good and spectacular, in that order. The Dow rose
4.03 percent in September and 9.56 percent in October, the best
one-month performance since January 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Roger G. Ibbotson, a professor at the Yale School of Management
and chairman of Ibbotson Associates in Chicago, a market research
firm, doesn't think the threat of history, however, should make
investors flee the market. ``I just get a little bit more worried
in October,'' he said. ``But I don't tell people to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he seems hopeful about the outlook for stocks, taking a
long-term view that peers well beyond what the Fed will or will not
do this week. In the recent rage for predictions about how far the
Dow can go, he has set his marker at 120,040.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dow 36,000,'' a three-to-five year forecast and title of the
book by James K. Glassman and Kevin A. Hassett, already seems
pretty far-fetched. So what about 120,000?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Ibbotson doesn't get there until the end of 2025. He
doesn't get to Dow 36,000 until 2013, which shows how much the
magic of compounding plays into his prediction.
</P>
<P>
   His forecasting method is simple. Using the yield on the
Treasury's 30-year bond as a base, he adds the historical premium
that stocks earn over bonds, known as the equity risk premium,
because stocks are riskier. He subtracts the 1998 dividend yield
for the Dow of 1.6 percent, giving him an annual growth rate of 9.7
percent, starting in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 120,000 sounds big. But Ibbotson is relatively conservative
given the current stock mania. His annual growth rate for the Dow
is lower than the performance so far this year _ 11.9 percent _ and
well below the 14.9 percent average annual rate of growth from 1990
through last year. If he used that rate, the Dow would hit 120,000
in 2017, the year it would just reach 56,000 in his forecast.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also assuming a risk premium for stocks of 5.7
percent, much higher than the 2.5 percent to 3 percent that many
bullish Wall Street strategists are using. He acknowledges that
others believe the risk of holding stocks is lower.
</P>
<P>
   And he says that his Dow forecast would be much lower using a
more modest equity risk premium. But he wants to stick, he says,
with the historical risk premium, based on data since 1926.
</P>
<P>
   Choose your historical period. The average annual growth for the
Dow since 1915 is 8.54 percent, according to Birinyi Associates in
Greenwich, Conn. That growth rate brings you to 120,000 in 2030. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE GOLD WATCH The rally in gold last week, in which the price
jumped 15 percent, to $308.10 an ounce, before settling at $305.30
on Friday, makes one wonder how closely European central bankers
watch the precious-metals market. With more than 16,200 tons of
gold in their vaults, the nearly 40 percent fall in the price since
1996 should have received their attention.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems that they realized only recently that the fear of a
flood of central bank gold sales had taken control of market
sentiment. Sales had been coming at a pace of 315 tons a year. So
when 15 European central banks announced that they would limit
their total sales to 400 tons a year for five years _ poof! _ gold
took off.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Trichet, governor of the Banque de France, explained
it this way: ``When the Banque de France, the Bundesbank and the
Banca d'Italia, amongst others, were saying that they would not
sell gold, markets did not seem to understand this and did not seem
to be fully informed on this.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that central bankers took too long to understand how
easily they could fully inform the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
