<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN MOVES TOWARD RUSSIAN-CONTROLLED RULE IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In yet another sign that Russia is preparing for a
full-scale war with Chechnya, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin said
Friday that the Kremlin no longer recognizes the breakaway
republic's democratically elected president and took the first
steps toward setting up a pro-Moscow puppet government-in-exile.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's announcement came as Russian warplanes
pounded Chechnya for the ninth straight day and officials claimed
that government troops had seized strategic heights several miles
inside the separatist republic's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Russian news media have speculated that Russia, which rejects
Chechnya's claims to independence, may seize part of the territory
and install a rival government loyal to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Putin gave credence to that speculation Friday when he said that
an obscure pro-Moscow parliament, elected in 1996 when Russia's
military still occupied about half of Chechnya, was the only legal
authority in the rebel region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This parliament is the sole legitimate authority in Chechnya
and we give it full support,'' said Putin at a news conference.
``The legitimacy of all other bodies in Chechnya is, to put it
mildly, conditional, since they were not elected according to
Russian law.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement indicated the Kremlin was withdrawing
recognition from Chechnya's President Aslan Maskhadov, with whom
President Boris N. Yeltsin signed a peace accord in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Moscow parliament was elected in June 1996 during
Russia's bloody and unsuccessful attempt to stop Chechnya from
gaining independence. At the time of the vote, Chechnya was a war
zone and Russian troops occupied about half the republic, including
the capital Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Amin Osmayev, speaker of the rump parliament, appeared with
Putin Friday and said that ``Mashkadov is not (Chechnya's)
legitimate president.''
</P>
<P>
   The parliament and a puppet government the Kremlin had installed
were disbanded and fled Chechnya after Russian troops withdrew late
in 1996. Since then Chechnya has run its own affairs, although no
country has recognized its independence.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997 Chechnya held its own parliamentary and
presidential elections, which were monitored by international
observers. Maskhadov won the presidency in a landslide, taking 65
percent of the vote. The Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe, which monitored the vote, called Maskhadov's election
``democratic and free.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's announcement was criticized as folly by several analysts
and politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what kind of advisers Vladimir Putin has if
they advised him to take this road,'' said Ruslan Aushev, president
of Ingushetia, a republic in southern Russia which borders
Chechnya. ``The legitimate leader of Chechnya today is President
Maskhadov whether anybody likes it or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3850 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-BOS     10-01 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FLEEING CHECHENS, AN ALL-TOO-FAMILIAR SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTERN CHECHNYA, Russia _ The Arsagireyev family was preparing
for bed when they heard a loud explosion and the roar of a jet over
their home in a residential neighorhood in Chechnya's capital,
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Startled and unsure what it meant, they turned on the TV and
watched as a Russian general explained that federal warplanes had
begun conducting ``pinpoint airstrikes'' against Islamic terrorists
suspected of hiding in the separatist Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   For eight days of terror, the Arsagireyevs huddled in their
basement as the rockets flew and their neighbors fled.
</P>
<P>
   The lights went out and the gas stopped working. The train
station blew up and the TV tower went down. The phones shut down
and the water stopped running. A family of refugees was hit as they
were crossing a bridge and six children were incinerated when a
rocket exploded where they were standing in the street.
</P>
<P>
   On the ninth day, Friday, the radio said all civilians had left
Grozny and there was nothing left in the city but bandits. The
implication was clear _ now everything was a target.
</P>
<P>
   The Arsagireyevs knew what that meant. They had twice fled heavy
fighting in Grozny during the 1994-1996 war between Russian forces
and separatist militants that killed tens of thousands of
civilians. Fearing a repeat of that nightmare, Berlan Arsagireyev,
59, gathered what belongings she could _ as well as eight of her
nine daughters and two small grandsons _ and joined the exodus. Her
husband and eldest daughter stayed behind to look after the family
homestead, under the rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the family members who escaped pondered their fate as
they sat on the side of a road clogged with cars and trucks heading
out of Chechnya to the west, toward the tiny southern Russian
region of Ingushetia, where some refugees have found places to stay
with friends or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   For the Arsagireyevs, sweating in 80-degree temperatures, there
was no place to go and no money for food. The nearby tent city that
Russian relief workers have thrown up was full, with a five-day
wait for space in a tent.
</P>
<P>
   So the Arsagireyevs got ready to spend the night in the open,
and repeated the bitter refrain so often heard from Chechens, whose
claim to independence is not recognized by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the bandits?'' said Mariam Arsagireyev, 19, the
youngest daughter, a sophomore ecology major at a Grozny
University. ``There is no reason why the Russians should want to
destroy us.''
</P>
<P>
   Their fate is shared by many of the 88,000 Chechens who Russian
officials say have fled the violence. Russia's sudden air campaign
against Chechnya took everyone by surprise, including Russian
relief agencies. Unable to accommodate all the refugees, Russia has
appealed to the United Nations for help. Four trucks carrying
tents, mattresses, food and other supplies arrived in Ingushetia
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But at a makeshift refugee camp on an unnamed field on the
Chechen-Ingush border, there was no sign of new supplies. Here,
some 3,000 refugees huddle in torn and crowded tents, sleeping on
straw. Food is whatever they brought from home, plus the bread
sporadically brought in by relief workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is what you see,'' said Major Tugran Chepanov, a
Russian relief official. ``We have received no help yet.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of pregnant women and mothers with small children
gathered around a tent where Tamara Akhmedova, a doctor at nearby
hospital who fled Grozny during the 1995 fighting, conducts
perfunctory checkups. She has no antibiotics and little besides a
stool and a table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the children have colds from sleeping on the floor,''
she said. ``There's also diarrhea; these are not sanitary
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   But people continued to stream into the camp Friday as Russian
warplanes again pounded Chechnya. As cars and trucks stuffed with
belongings crept towards Ingushetia, a large armored column of
Russian troops moved in the opposite direction toward Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The military situation around the separatist region's volatile
borders remained unclear. Russian political leaders said Thursday
that government troops had moved several miles inside Chechnya, but
the military declined to confirm or deny that a ground offensive
had begun.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has made it clear it will punish Chechen targets until
the region stops aiding and abetting the Islamic militants, whom
they blame for bringing crime and violence to the region. But
Russia denies its planes are targeting civilians.
</P>
<P>
   That is news to Audin Magomedov, who Friday left Grozny with his
wife and family after daily bombing had caused her to suffer a
nervous breakdown. As they left the city a rocket hit two families
of refugees, killing several people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us are just normal people who want to live normal
lives,'' Magomedov said. ``I wonder if the people ordering these
air strikes realize that. It is disgusting what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the people in the camps expressed sympathy for the
rebels Russia says it is fighting, the militants led by Chechen
renegade commander Shamil Basayev and his Saudi-born sidekick,
Khattab. Their forces twice invaded the southern Russian region of
Dagestan in August and September, and Russia blames them for the
wave of deadly apartment blasts that killed nearly 300 people in
Moscow and other cities last month.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the refugees see Basayev and Khattab, who say they are
fighting to end Russian rule in the Caucasus and unite Chechnya and
Dagestan in an Islamic republic, as their enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't stop (the Islamic rebels), then a new war is
unavoidable, not just for us but for the whole North Caucacus,''
said a slight young man who gave his name, Hadzhi, and the nickname
he picked up as a prisoner of war during the 1994-1996 conflict,
``The Executioner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Executioner'' and two comrades were taking their wives,
children, blankets, and a potted pepper plant out of Chechnya. Then
they were heading back home, they said, where they and some 400 of
their followers were planning a military operation to ``punish
those responsible'' for the new outbreak of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Executioner'' did not elaborate on his plan. He only
predicted new upheavals and fighting in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation is destroyed every 50 years,'' he said. ``Every
generation has been through a war. We are used to it, but it's a
bad habit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
