<SLUG> BC-MORRIS-BIOGRAPHY-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: BIOGRAPHY AS A MIRROR REFLECTING BIOGRAPHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1985, when President Ronald Reagan selected Edmund
Morris as his official biographer, the writer vowed he would
produce ``a substantial, scholarly book.'' Fourteen years later,
after years of worrying he didn't ``understand the first thing''
about his subject, Morris has produced a book that is anything but
scholarly or substantial. He has produced a bizarre, irresponsible
and monstrously self-absorbed book _ a Ragtime-esque ``memoir''
featuring a self-annotating narrator out of a Philip Roth novel and
childlike hero out of ``Being There.'' Even worse, this loony
hodgepodge of fact and fiction is being sold not as a novel but as
``the only biography ever authorized by a sitting president.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Morris' new book ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald
Reagan'' recapitulate the very blurring of reality and
stage-managed illusion that that president was often accused of
perpetrating, but it also underscores disturbing trends percolating
through biography writing and the culture at large today. Instead
of using his extraordinary access to a sitting president and his
personal papers to grapple with important matters like Iran-contra
or the end of the Cold War, Morris simply ratifies the familiar
mythology of Reagan as a charismatic actor blessed with a resonant
vision of America. And instead of working hard to evaluate Reagan
and his administration, Morris gives us pages and pages of
self-indulgent maundering about himself _ or rather, about a
fictional alter ego who knew Ronald Reagan as a teen-ager and who
pops up, Zelig-like, in later episodes of Reagan's life. We are
coyly told that Reagan rescued America ``in a time of poisonous
despair'' ... and also saved the fictional Morris from drowning as
a youth.
</P>
<P>
   This narrator is 28 years older than the real Morris, and has a
fictional son named Gavin, who is a political radical, and a
fictional friend named Paul Rae, who works as a gossip columnist.
The ersatz Morris blathers on at length about his romances, his
fictional family and his private regrets (``budding opportunities
unblown, breasts not cupped in my hands, scripts unfilmed and books
unfinished''). He resembles one of those academic
deconstructionists continually nattering on about how things exist
only in the beholder's eye. Or the narcissistic Ted Baxter on the
old ``Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' always making everything about
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares, the reader wonders, whether Morris' ``fish-white
body'' earned him the nickname ``Moon-Tan''? Who cares whether
``happiness suffused'' Morris' heart when President Reagan
mentioned reading his biography of Theodore Roosevelt?
</P>
<P>
   Although Morris has repeatedly argued that he did not
fictionalize Reagan, his virtual narrator's ubiquity, not to
mention his youthful hero worship of the future president,
undermines all credibility. This narrator appears in the footnotes
to the book alongside real-life sources, and he makes the reader
think: if Morris won't tell the truth about himself, why should we
believe what he has to say about the president or anyone else?
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Morris has described his use of this narrator as
``an advance in biographical honesty,'' a signal to the reader
concerning the subjective element involved in all writing. It is an
argument that recalls the disingenuous reasoning of Janet Malcolm,
who suggested in ``The Silent Woman,'' her highly partisan 1994
portrait of Ted Hughes and Sylvia Plath, that all biographers share
her own disdain for fairness and objectivity. It is also an
argument that recalls the reasoning of current academic writers,
who preface scholarly papers with lengthy disquisitions on their
own ``positioning,'' their ethnic background, sexual identity and
personal experiences that might just possibly skew their arguments
or outlook.
</P>
<P>
   This approach _ what the scholar Daphne Patai aptly calls ``the
nouveau solipsism'' _ does not hold, as the old scholarship did,
that truth, however fragmentary and provisional, is an end worth
trying to pursue. Instead, it assumes that writers are
intrinsically biased by their own demographics, that, in Ms.
Patai's words, ``men cannot speak for women, one group of women
cannot speak for another.'' Hence, perhaps, the decision of Morris,
who was born in Kenya in 1940, to turn himself, in ``Dutch,'' into
a Reagan contemporary _ an American born in 1912 who migrates from
the Middle West to Hollywood and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, this sort of ``moi criticism'' _ as the writer
Leslie Heywood dubbed her use of personal anecdotes about anorexia
in a 1996 study of literary modernism _ simply gives an author
license to substitute personal talk show-style testimony for the
careful weighing of available evidence, to substitute polemic and
lazy speculation for hard-won argument and research.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
