<HEADLINE>
EX-ENVOY URGES RUSSIA TO AVOID CHECHEN WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who stood
close to Moscow during its 1994-96 war in Chechnya, edged away
Friday, emphatically urging the Kremlin to steer clear from another
full-fledged conflict there.
</P>
<P>
   As Russian warplanes bombed Chechnya and refugees streamed from
the southern region, Talbott declared that Russia must embrace
peaceful solutions in the volatile area or risk deep and violent
dissent for years. Hours after Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
snubbed Chechnya's moderate leader by endorsing a puppet group of
pro-Moscow legislators as the region's leaders, Talbott was urging
Russia to work with the moderates instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``For there to be any chance of success, Russia must show
restraint and wisdom in the coming weeks. This means taking action
against real terrorists, but not using indiscriminate force that
endangers innocents or resuming the disastrous 1994-96 war in
Chechnya,'' Talbott told a crowd at Harvard University's John F.
Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   In comments there, and to a group of editors at the Globe,
Talbott, the State Department's senior Russian expert, also
lambasted Moscow's wholesale roundups and deportations of an
estimated 10,000 people of darker complexions _ often associated
with the southern Caucacus region that includes Chechyna.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, too, is not just an ugly and atavistic development but
an ominous one _ and, I believe, profoundly contrary to Russia's
own interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is taking a careful line on who is responsible for a
terrorist bombing campaign that prompted both the crackdown in
Moscow and the intensifying military attack on Chechnya. Moscow has
blamed Islamic separatists based in Chechnya for the attacks, but
Washington has not entirely accepted that explanation _ nor has it
supported speculation that another group carried out the series of
apartment bombings.
</P>
<P>
   A concern amid the attacks on Chechnya is that a new Chechen
conflict will spill over or destabilize other formerly Soviet areas
such as Georgia or Azerbaijan. Unlike Russia's conflict with
Chechnya in 1994-96, when Washington stuck with Boris N. Yeltsin in
fear of a Communist rollback in Moscow, the United States is less
firmly aligned now with the Russian leadership, which Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright has criticized for widespread corruption
and Central Bank money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott's Harvard speech sought to emphasize that Russia,
despite its myriad troubles this decade, may still become a modern
state. He pointed to the excitement over upcoming parliamentary and
presidential elections as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more firmly established that mechnanism becomes, the
longer it continues to function, the greater the chance of having a
government _ and a state _ more responsive to the needs of the
citizenry,'' Talbott said. ``This would be something new under the
Russian sun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MORRIS-BIOGRAPHY-ART-     10-01 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRIS-BIOGRAPHY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and research.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the case of ``Dutch,'' Morris tends to play down anything
that transpired in the Reagan administration that he did not happen
to witness himself, eschewing the sort of reportorial legwork and
archival research that might have enabled him to more fully assess
the president's character and his foreign and domestic policies.
Earlier events in Reagan's life, of course, are filtered through
his virtual narrator's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Morris reports the rumor that Reagan tried to become a Communist
during his early years in Hollywood (and was discouraged by a local
party leader), but never really determines its accuracy: ``So
what,'' he shrugs, ``if Dutch, young and ardent in 1938, thrilled
to the message of Marx for a few experimental months?''
</P>
<P>
   As for the funneling of Iranian funds to Contra operations in
Central America, Morris reports his ``suspicion'' that ``Dutch did
authorize the transfer, not having the smallest comprehension of
the laws he was subverting,'' but leaves serious reporting to
others, arguing he is simply ``writing Dutch's personal story, and
not correlating the millions of impressions of the hundreds of
witnesses whose testimony fills more than 50,000 pages of
documents.'' Analysis of such testimony, after all, might interrupt
the user-friendly flow of Morris' narrative, a narrative weighted,
like so much writing in our post-Monica, post-Matt Drudge era,
toward the sensational and the private.
</P>
<P>
   This is Morris, ``the Official Biographer,'' on the future
president of the United States: ``Even his pectorals are flat and
square: he has no bulges in him, of brawn or brain.'' This is
Morris on the future first lady: ``Her figure _ 5 feet 4 inches of
pile-driver purpose _ was more suited to table-hopping than couch
football. She was not averse to sex, as Dutch would discover.''
</P>
<P>
   While the chatty, you-are-there style of ``Dutch'' is a kind of
extrapolation of methods used in Bob Woodward's political books
(which blithely tell us what various people thought or felt on a
given occasion, even when they were not directly interviewed by the
author) and Joe McGinniss' egregious ``Last Brother'' (which
employed wholesale speculation to try to convey ``what it might
have been like to be Teddy Kennedy''), the book as a whole also
points up the contamination of biography writing that has
accelerated during the last decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   Those years saw the publication of many exemplary works of
biography _ from A.N. Wilson's vivid life of Tolstoy to Joseph
Ellis' sympathetic portrait of John Adams to the riveting first
volume of Peter Guralnick's biography of Elvis Presley _ but they
also bore witness to the proliferation of ``pathographies,'' those
lurid, voyeuristic works that relentlessly focus on a subject's
foibles and failings (Jeffrey Meyers' ``Scott Fitzgerald,'' Ronald
Hayman's ``Tennessee Williams,'' Joan Peyser's ``Bernstein,'' to
name just a few).
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, we have become all too familiar with the
phenomenon of biography as spin job (Andrew Morton's ``Diana: Her
True Story,'' Jonathan Dimbleby's ``The Prince of Wales''),
biography as feminist tract (Francine du Plessix Gray's ``Rage and
Fire: A Life of Louise Colet''), biography as deconstructionist
exercise (S. Paige Baty's ``American Monroe: The Making of a Body
Politic''), and biography as philosophical manifesto (Norman
Mailer's ``Portrait of Picasso as a Young Man''). Mailer and Ms.
Baty at least make it clear that they are writing interpretative
studies; in many cases, editorializing is simply woven into what
purports to be a standard life.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this has to do with the tenor of the times: the erasure
of the lines between opinion and fact, the tabloidization of the
cultural zeitgeist and the relativistic approach to truth fostered
by identity politics. It also has something to do with the growing
desire on the part of biography writers like Morris to be
``creative,'' to think of themselves, in Justin Kaplan's words,
``not as post-mortem amanuenses but as writers, even participants,
agonistic heroes and joint tenants in ongoing posthumous lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make literature out of Ronald Reagan,'' said Morris,
who in this book lays out his impressions of the president in a
cringe-making mixture of screenplay scenarios, phony letters, poems
and bad novelistic prose. ``Dutch,'' a Random House publicity
release reads, ``is a unique literary achievement,'' enlivened ``by
a poetic sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   There are precedents, of sorts, for Morris' strange approach. In
his 1991 biography of Dickens, Peter Ackroyd imagined encounters
between the novelist, his characters, other famous writers and
himself. In her 1995 book about the duchess of Windsor, Caroline
Blackwood turned her own frustrating efforts to come to terms with
her elusive subject into the volume's central story line. And in
her 1989 biography of Josephine Baker, Phyllis Rose wrote of
identifying so strongly with the dancer that she perhaps imposed on
her ``some of my own sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am getting too interested in myself, which is the mark of
the burned-out biographer,'' Ms. Rose wrote in an essay several
years later. ``The burned-out biographer is no longer willing to
suppress herself in the service of another. She no longer wants to
express indirectly in terms of the narrative of another's life the
burning issues of her own. That interrogation by the self of
another, which animates a good biography, no longer works. The self
wants center stage, the whole enchilada.''
</P>
<P>
   That, apparently, is what happened to Edmund Morris. By turning
his biography into the work of a novelist manque, he could show
readers he could write _ not just the sort of sedate prose that won
him the Pulitzer Prize in 1980 for his biography of Teddy
Roosevelt, but also something more purple and poetic. (``All his
life, Ronald Reagan has ridden a long road dissolving, at the limit
of sight, into something scintillant yet ethereal.'') By tricking
up his narrative with the distracting pyrotechniques of fiction, he
could try to conceal his own inability to understand his subject _
never mind the fact that earlier biographers like Lou Cannon and
Garry Wills, and dozens of reporters with considerably less access,
managed to make sense of Reagan in the past. And by turning himself
into a central character in the former president's story, he could
absolve himself of the responsibility of trying to rise above his
personal feelings and turn his simultaneous adoration and contempt
for the man into a post-modern narrative device.
</P>
<P>
   There may, of course, be something fitting about America's first
actor-turned-president (whose carefully scripted White House was
predicated on perception, whose view of the past, in Wills' words,
was ``largely shaped by the movies he saw or made'') getting a
biographer who freely glosses history with fantasy, who values
style over substance. There may also be something fitting about a
man renowned for his contradictions (a ``hemophilic liberal'' who
became a conservative poster boy, a big-government hater who
created a huge national debt) getting a biographer who argues that
Reagan was ``a great president'' and ``an apparent airhead''
endowed with an ``encyclopedic ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that a rare opportunity to chronicle a sitting
president in office has been squandered, while readers have been
cheated: under the guise of an authorized biography of Reagan we
get a cloying, egocentric novel; instead of a revealing portrait of
a president, we get a phony self-portrait of the president's
would-be Boswell, another self-absorbed Ted Baxter doggedly hogging
the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan once wrote an autobiography called ``Where's the Rest of
Me?'' The rest of him is decidedly not to be found in ``Dutch,'' a
book that might well have been titled ``The Rest of Edmund
Morris.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
