<SLUG> BC-Y2K-AIRLINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES SHOULD BE UNFAZED BY Y2K `BUG,' GROUP SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's major airlines and airports should function
smoothly on New Year's Day, but they are hammering out contingency
plans in case computers are fouled by the date change, officials
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be as safe to fly on Jan. 1 as it is today,'' vowed
Tom Browne, executive director of the Aviation Millennium Project,
the Year 2000 program for the Air Transport Association in
Washington, the trade association group which represents virutally
all of the nation's major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Because so much of the aviation system is interconnected, the
Aviation Millennium Project has compiled information for 102 North
American airlines to use, as well as some 500 airports, pertaining
to 9,000 computer-dependent systems ranging from baggage systems to
airport runway lights.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, which is responsible for
the computer-dependent air traffic control system, has been working
to make sure the system functions on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we have been looking at tells us we are ready,''
said Robert Bartanowicz, the New England regional administrator of
the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said about ``99.9 percent'' of airline systems in the
United States have been tested and validated to be year 2000
compliant. Avionics equipment on board airplanes has been tested by
Boeing, Airbus and the equipment manufacturers. Three systems were
found to have problems, and they have been replaced or corrected.
The airplane manufacturers have flight tested every plane, Browne
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coffee maker might not work, but there are no
safety-of-flight issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   US and Canadian airlines have spent about $750 million on
solving the so-called Y2K problem, and the two-year budget for the
Aviation Millennium Project is $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   There is some concern that if there are significant failures in
the system, planes will be delayed and travelers stranded as the
air traffic control system is slowed down and planes spaced further
apart to ensure that safety is maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Some carriers, including American Airlines, have announced
reduced service on Dec. 31 and Jan. 1, but Browne said those flight
cancellations were because of low advance bookings, not concern
about Year 2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest party night of the last millennium, and
people are not going to want to be on a plane when the partying
starts or ends,'' he said. ``If airlines were really concerned
about Y2K, the reduction of schedules would not be for 12 hours; it
would be much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tara Werho, general manager of the Year 2000 Program at Delta
Air Lines said the airline has spent about $90 million on fixes,
and everything is ``100 percent complete.'' She said work on about
230 systems was completed in June. That work now is being validated
by independent consultants, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Anglin, director of information services at the
Massachusetts Port Authority, which owns and operates Logan
International Airport, said the agency has spent about $5.5 million
on making certain everything functions smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 111 Massport computer systems tested, 27 percent ``had
problems,'' including some important ones controlling airfield
lighting, security control, and fuel distribution. Those systems
have been fixed and are being tested, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Anglin added, ``We do have a contingency plan to keep the
airport operational if something happens with power or
telephones.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Massport officials will be in contact with airport
managers in Australia and England on Dec. 31 to see how those
airfields, where the New Year arrives earlier, manage at the stroke
of midnight and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Anglin said, Massport will be in touch with West
Coast airports when it is midnight here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
