<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACID-RAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACID RAIN DEADLINES UNMET, ENVIRONMENTALISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen months after New England governors and eastern Canadian
premiers vowed to crack down on acid rain and mercury pollution,
they are already falling behind on their self-imposed deadlines,
environmentalists charged Friday. If anything, pollution from the
region's power plants is rising, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, contained in a letter signed by representatives
of 45 environmental groups, went to the state and provincial
leaders as they prepare for a three-day meeting beginning Monday in
Rockland, Maine, where air pollution will be on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a disconnect between our public officials and
what the public thinks and how deeply these sentiments run,'' said
Cindy Luppi of the environmental group Clean Water Action in
Boston. ``New England is one of the most hard hit regions in the
country by both acid rain and mercury.''
</P>
<P>
   Acid rain and mercury deposition do major environmental damage
in the Northeast, from Vermont forests killed by high acidity to
scores of lakes and streams where the fish are unsafe to eat due to
high mercury levels. New England is especially vulnerable because
its pollution comes from both local sources and windblown emissions
from Midwestern coal-burning plants.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the New England Governors' Conference conceded that
the activists were technically correct that regional leaders missed
a May deadline to come up with ways to cut releases of toxic
mercury. However, they said the protest letter overlooks major
progress in other areas, such as reducing mercury emissions from
trash incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the first year of a multi-year plan and we've done a
lot already,'' said John Shea, spokesman for the governors
conference. ``A plan like this is beyond anything anybody else is
doing so it becomes kind of a target . . . Sometimes it gets a
little frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The sparring comes little more than a year after the political
leaders and environmentalists jointly celebrated the governors' and
premiers' landmark agreement to tackle both acid rain and mercury
pollution, promising to make coal-burning power plants install
state-of-the-art mercury pollution controls and to cut emissions of
sulfur, the main ingredient in acid rain, in half by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Northeast's resolution has no effect on pollution
drifting in from other regions, the political leaders said it would
give them moral authority in demanding that Midwestern states clean
up their old power plants whose super-tall smokestacks send air
pollution here.
</P>
<P>
   But, almost as soon as the crackdown was approved, states and
provinces ran into objections from the industries likely to bear
the brunt of it, coal-burning power plants and trash incinerators.
Last month, the incinerator industry sued Massachusetts to overturn
new limits on mercury emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, environmentalists fear that the governors and premiers are
squandering their moral authority just when it's needed most. US
Representative Tom Allen of Maine, backed by the Massachusetts
delegation, plans to announce a bill Saturday to require pollution
reductions at the dirtiest power plants nationwide, and the state
of New York recently sued several Midwestern governments to
accomplish a similar goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that unless our officials in New England come up with
good strong precedents, it is very unlikely that there will be any
progress nationally,'' said Luppi.
</P>
<P>
   But Shea of the New England Governors Conference said the US and
Canadian leaders are making far more progress than
environmentalists give them credit for. He said new initiatives to
reduce mercury releases from hospitals, municipal facilities and
incinerators will cut overall mercury emissions in the region by 40
percent, assuming the Massachusetts incinerator rules survive their
legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that the governors and premiers haven't come up with
ways to limit mercury from coal burning plants yet, but he said
that is partly because controlling mercury from coal-burning is
costly _ anywhere from five to 300 times the cost of controlling
mercury releases from trash incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of concern within the utility sector of the
costs and the technical feasibility of some of these options,''
said Shea. ``That's why we are taking our time trying to develop a
set of options . . . that will be feasible and not rush out with
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, say environmentalists, the result is that many
Northeastern power plants, spurred by the hot regional economy, are
increasing releases of sulfur and mercury. Sulfur releases from the
five most polluting power plants in Massachusett rose by 50 percent
from 1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed that there does not seem to be the
followthrough on the commitment they unveiled with great fanfare,''
said Rob Sargent of the Massachusetts Public Interest Research
Group. ``There has to be clear action now to show that they are
serious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
