<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOYS-R-US(TRIMS)-ART-     10-01 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-R-US(TRIMS)-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYS `R' US WORKS TO PREVENT MISHAPS THAT HURT IT LAST HOLIDAY
SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, Toys ``R'' Us shoppers, armed with holiday wish
lists, often left the chain's cavernous stores frustrated and
empty-handed. It was not just the hot sellers like Furby that were
in short supply. The stores even ran out of stocking-stuffers like
Crayola Crayons. And the company felt the pain acutely in its
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   But what of this year? As the company heads into the
all-important Christmas season, with Walmart and Etoys continuing
to snatch a big share of its business, Toys ``R'' Us is trying
mightily to do things differently.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it is hoping to avoid a repeat of last year by
placing bigger bets on top-selling toys like Furby and Pokemon as
well as must-have items like Potato Head. But even if it succeeds _
and that is very much an open question _ it would take several
quarters of solid results for the company to get back in investors'
good graces, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate fate of Toys ``R'' Us, which throughout the 1980s
bestrode the nation's toy industry like a giant Jesse Ventura doll,
depends in large part on how successful it is in mending its
bruised relationship with its suppliers _ the ones it must rely on
to get toys on its shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Toy makers became frustrated last year with management's
haphazard handling of its inventory and failure to communicate with
key customers. But since its previous chief executive resigned in
August, Michael Goldstein, the chairman and now acting chief
executive, has been busily calling industry chums to try to ease
the tension.
</P>
<P>
   In but one case of communications breakdown, Mattel Inc. sales
representatives warned Toys ``R'' Us buyers early last year that
the chain risked running out of some popular Fisher-Price items
during the holidays and should probably order more. But Toys ``R''
Us, trying to shave costs largely by unloading warehouses full of
slow-moving merchandise, did not listen. When December came, many
of its 700 stores ran out of Fisher-Price's Magnadoodles and Little
People play houses. Not only did this hurt Toys ``R'' Us, but it
caused Mattel to stumble, cutting into its revenue last year by
about $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``They were ordering only when necessary as opposed to taking
some direction on what we felt they needed to order to stay in
stock,'' said Fisher-Price president Neil Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vendor relationship is very important. They have to be
able to trust us and we have to be able to trust them. That is
something that has never been a problem with Toys `R' Us prior to
that year.'' But on a more optimistic note, he added, ``I think all
of those issues are past.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us' troubles are far from over. Its profits are still
tumbling, and its stock price is off 40 percent from the year's
high, closing Friday at $14.8125. Walmart, after all, earlier this
year stole the title of top toy seller, while Etoys has become the
Toys ``R'' Us of online toy selling. And the chain still has work
to do to win back customers who had grown weary of its
warehouse-like stores and dismal customer service _ a problem it is
also trying to address with an extensive program to retrain all
workers and managers.
</P>
<P>
   But heading into the year's final quarter, when toy makers and
retailers typically earn more than half their annual profits, Toys
``R'' Us _ according to suppliers and industry experts _ has a
better merchandising mix and will have enough of the stuff people
want. In short, it is no longer operating like a closeout chain
offering bargains on toy-chest rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Even Toys ``R'' Us management admits that its obsession with
winnowing inventory got out of control last year, and that top
executives had to step in to smooth over wrinkles in relations with
companies like Mattel, which last year described the reduced orders
from Toys ``R'' Us as ``very painful and disappointing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who is filling in until a replacement is named for
Robert Nakasone, the chief executive who resigned abruptly under
board pressure, said, ``If you talk to vendors about what the
issues were, it gets back to the point that the partnership was too
adversarial.'' Goldstein has personally called on large
manufacturers that Toys ``R'' Us executives had not visited in
years, as well as small but important ones that had also been
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   He has assured those toy makers that the company is now open to
more suggestions about what will sell, invited them to visit the
chain's spruced-up stores and sent a message that unresolved issues
will be handled by top management.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They are just bringing everybody back into the family in a
sense,'' said Stephen Berman, co-founder and president of Jakks
Pacific Inc., maker of World Wrestling Federation action figures,
who said his company has not had a problem with Toys ``R'' Us but
has, nonetheless, noticed a new era of openness at the company.
</P>
<P>
   The schmoozing helps, but Toys ``R'' Us has also finally begun
to show some competitive spunk. Two weeks ago it introduced Pokemon
leagues in stores, prompting thousands of youngsters to sign up to
compete in six-week competitions involving the trading cards'
imaginary creatures.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, after an embarrassingly unsuccessful dabble in
cyber selling, Toys ``R'' Us is reviving its website
(www.toyrus.com) in October month to go toe-to-toe with Etoys,
Amazon and the growing list of online toy sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect Toys ``R'' Us to finally do what critics say it
should have done in the first place _ promote the new site heavily
on television and in national print adds, play up customers'
ability to return goods bought on line to its hundreds of stores
and offer exclusive deals to lure shoppers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In September, Toys ``R'' Us smartly found a way to one-up the
discount chains, which have lured the retailer's once-loyal
shoppers by cutting prices. Walmart, Etoys and other retailers were
selling the Sega Dreamcast system for $199, and Toys ``R'' Us
matched that price, but offered an added incentive.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for bringing in old video game systems when they
purchased Dreamcasts, the company offered shoppers $100 worth of
``Geoffry Dollars,'' toy money named for the chain's giraffe mascot
that could be used to purchase any item in its stores. As a result,
many consumers traded up to the new game system and spent the play
money on accessories to go with it, which enabled Toys ``R'' Us to
sell more Dreamcasts than its competitors, luring new customers in
the process, said Jim Silver, publisher of Toy Book, a trade
publication, and co-publisher of a new toy-buying guide, Toy
Wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``By heavily couponing, they can compete because they offer
deals like Sega Dreamcast that bring people in stores,'' Silver
said.
</P>
<P>
   But change will not come overnight. ``A lot of things, the
redesigned stores, the push and pull here and there, it sounds in
theory good, but I think it may take a while before customers
really notice an improvement,'' said Maureen Carini, an analyst
with Standard &AMP; Poors Equity Group. ``I'm not looking really for
any short-term big changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has good reason for its wait-and-see attitude. The
company turned in its seventh quarterly earnings decline in August,
reporting a 25 percent drop, to $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   And any changes that followed Nakasone's departure, even though
it came before most shoppers were thinking about the holiday
splurge ahead, will have little impact soon, because toy retailers
lock in their merchandise orders and promotional budgets and
strategies months ahead of the season. Nakasone could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Since his departure, Toys ``R'' Us may have gotten back in the
good graces of its suppliers, but it will take far longer to win
over customers and investors. For just that reason, the most
important change for Toys ``R'' Us may well be not the number of
Millennium Barbies sitting on its shelves on Dec. 24, but whom it
brings in to lead the company into the next century _ and how well
that person executes the strategy Goldstein and team have begun. As
of now, there is no clue who that person will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the most important hire Michael Goldstein
makes,'' said Silver, the trade magazine publisher. ``A lot of
people have been brought in through the years, but this will be
watched more closely and have more impact than any in the past.
With all the problems, this one has to be right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
