<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUCHANAN(TRIMS)-ART-2     10-01 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN(TRIMS)-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN IS ENERGIZED BY PROSPECT OF THIRD-PARTY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   McLEAN, Va. _ This vernal, affluent suburb of Washington is
known for the discreet coexistence of the CIA and Patrick Buchanan,
the maverick presidential candidate who lately takes pre-dawn jogs
around his CIA neighbor's perimeter, all the better to plot his
next intrigue against the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exhilarating, waking up at three in the morning, running,
planning things,'' says Buchanan, describing a Napoleonic edge to
his aerobics in his current threat to spurn the GOP and make a run
for the Reform Party nomination. ``You think of what you're going
to say, how they'll come at you in sound bites, how much time
you'll have to make your proper point. Very exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, far from flinching from a two-week bout of controversy
over his isolationist views on America's involvement in World War
II, seems exultant. He believes he has mastered, not merely
weathered, a ``firestorm'' that one of his mentors, President
Richard M. Nixon, taught him can only add strength to a quixotic
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Galvanized by being targeted, Buchanan avidly discussed one
theoretical battle plan in an interview at his home in McLean. He
estimated that he could likely wrest the Reform nomination from his
opponents in that party, collect the resultant $12.6 million in
federal campaign subsidy to get off the ground, and maintain enough
of an insurgent free-media blitz next year to register 15 percent
approval in presidential campaign polls. This would earn him a
place in the critical televised debates, where Buchanan envisions
his best haymaker shot at undoing the big-money candidacies of the
other two nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go, we would have a fighting chance,'' he said, claiming
polls show him defeating other possible Reform rivals, including
his most serious opponent in that party, Minnesota Gov. Jesse
Ventura, who has thus far said he will not seek the nomination
himself but has also expressed opposition to Buchanan getting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ross Perot would be a benign neutral, I think, and Ventura
would not,'' Buchanan said of the former professional wrestler. ``I
think he has in mind body-slamming me,'' he added with a sudden
grin of delight in the virtual warfare that he likes to make of
politics.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``You're up there on that high diving board, my friend,''
Buchanan said, offering the image of himself poised in presumed
uncertainty about the party switch. He smiled, relaxing in his
handsome library stocked with biographies of political and military
leaders. ``It seems a thousand feet down to the water. It's go or
no-go. If I come down that ladder, you know what people will say,''
he continued, looking pleased enough at the sheer political anxiety
he is teasing out with his threat.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As the forces of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP
front-runner, plead with Buchanan not to attempt to create a
three-way race, some fellow conservatives have begun denouncing him
as an ego-tripper and hypocrite driven to flirting with fringe
politicians of the Marxist left and madcap right. In reply,
Buchanan mainly beams at all the attention that he knows attends
political controversy. No one laughs harder than he at some of the
anomalies of his courting the more exotic Reform politicians, like
Lenora Fulani, the New York figure associated with such
controversial firebrands as Louis Farrakhan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only going to say this just once: I did not have sex with
that woman,'' Buchanan sternly declared, then guffawed in mocking
the disapproving talk of his recent lunch meeting with Ms. Fulani.
``I did not convert to Marxism,'' Buchanan continued, and described
a luncheon discussion of mainline social and political ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Beijing in 1972 when Richard Nixon toasted the
greatest mass murderer of all time, Mao Tse-tung,'' Buchanan
continued. ``If we can do that, why is it wrong for me to have a
Caesar salad with Lenora Fulani? This is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   His barking laughter rang through the stately home that the
60-year-old conservative politician earned across decades of work
in Republican politics and cable television as a celebrity
polemicist turned chronic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As he mused upon the opportunities and risks of a Reform run,
Buchanan seemed more excited than nonplussed. ``I think I can hear
the distant sound of bugles,'' he lightly allowed, as if the
``pitchfork brigade'' supporters of his earlier presidential runs
had somehow found their way to the curved driveway of his home.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As he contemplates switching to the Reform Party, Buchanan is
drawing fire from some conservative stalwarts, including radio
talk-show host Rush Limbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Respected as a canny wordsmith, Buchanan was asked about one
criticism, by conservative columnist Charles Krauthammer, that he
softens his candidate image on television and mutes his
sharpest-edged views. Buchanan wrote last year, for example, that
``non-Jewish whites'' ``get the shaft'' at Harvard where, he
contended, admission favors Jews and Asians.
</P>
<P>
   Dogged for years by accusations of anti-Semitism, Buchanan
contended in a recent TV interview that the Harvard comment was
intended ``tongue in cheek.'' But Krauthammer quickly wrote that
there was not a hint of irony in the complaint's angry wording on
behalf of ``white Christians.'' He accused the supposedly candid
Buchanan of going ``impish and squishy'' in his TV persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you do everything perfectly?'' Buchanan responded when
asked about this at home in McLean. ``Of course not. But look, I
believe this is by and large rooted in hostility and malice towards
me because it only bursts out when I'm doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Current controversy centers on his new book about foreign
policy, but he feels this was unfairly seized upon once his
political enemies realized he might seek a third-party outlet.
``They thought I was dead,'' he observed. ``Then they saw the
casket lid open and the arm come out and they said, `Oh my Lord,
it's him again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan insisted he has not made a final decision about party
switching, even though he conceded that it would seem ludicrous if
not cowardly to come down that ladder now as the alternative to
taking a ``swan-dive of humiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be parturition,'' he said of the pain of his
possible _ many politicians guess all-but-certain _ decision to
quit the Republican Party, where his standing in pre-primary polls
has been merely single digit. ``Whatever you do, there's no doubt
you're going to wound yourself forever with people who have been
your friends and supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go, this is going to be the darnedest coalition you've
ever seen,'' he enthused. ``All kinds of disenchanted people. Can
you put together a left-right-center coalition for a single brief
campaign?''
</P>
<P>
   As an avid history buff, Buchanan had to concede third-party
politics historically yields a spoiler's role at best, not outright
triumph. ``It may be possible and it may not,'' he said. ``But the
whole challenge of something like that is very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan claimed a political realignment of the two parties is
already under way with an internationalist approach by one major
faction and what he called a ``Buchananite'' outlook in the other
opposed to global free trade, military intervention and large-scale
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may end up hurting, at least for a period of time, the
causes in which I believe deeply,'' he said of the contemplated
Reform run. ``And that weighs upon me and it weighs upon my
conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, however, Buchanan seems ebullient as he jogs and
strategizes after a revivifying, controversy-crammed stint of 50
radio shows and 20 TV shows in the past two weeks. He rates himself
overexposed right now and wants to go off and think in time to make
his decision by the end of October. ``The thing to do now is go
down under the water, then surface at the other end of the pool,
fresh and new,'' he said with no further mention of that high
diving board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
