<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TIBET-AID-1002-COX     10-01 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIBET-AID-1002-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIPARTISAN HOUSE BILL WOULD PUNISH WORLD BANK FOR CONTROVERSIAL
TIBET LOAN
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill introduced by an unusual coalition of
liberals and conservatives would restrict U.S. support for the
World Bank because of a controversial loan to help open
traditionally Tibetan lands to impoverished Chinese farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, for which the bank has tentatively approved a $40
million loan to the People's Republic of China, would re-settle
nearly 60,000 farmers from the heavily populated and eroded Qinghai
region onto a sparsely populated plateau in autonomous Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals such as Democratic Reps. John Lewis and Cynthia
McKinney of Georgia joined conservative Republicans in introducing
the bill this week to withhold U.S. funds from bank projects found
to result in harm to the environment or the rights of indigenous
peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the United States and 10 other countries on
the bank's board of executive directors had opposed the loan, which
was approved in June, pending a review by an independent bank
inspection panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan will displace a large number of indigenous people
from their lands,'' said Lewis. ``I tend to identify with the
Tibetan people because they've been peaceful warriors for their
independence for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and McKinney joined such conservative Republicans as
Christopher Cox and Dana Rohrabacher, both of California, in
introducing the bill _ entitled the ``Ecosystems and Indigenous
Peoples Protection Act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This project would harm the cultural and social life of the
area,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``liberals, conservatives and moderates'' had signed the
bill, which was introduced as representatives to the World Bank
gathered in Washington for the bank's annual meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a message for the international financial officials
who are in Washington for these meetings,'' said Cox, a primary
sponsor of the bill. ``The World Bank must make human rights and
the environment top concerns when it is deciding to allocate its
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspection panel, which operates within the bank but
independently, was to arrive in China over the weekend to begin its
review.
</P>
<P>
   Bank management was under intense and conflicting pressure when
the loan was approved. China had said it would ``re-evaluate'' its
relationship with the bank if the loan were not approved.
</P>
<P>
   The land that is to be turned over to Qinghai farmers is now
occupied primarily by Tibetan and Mongolian nomads, a bank
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, led by the International Campaign for Tibet, say these
people would be forced to give up their traditional lifestyles and
become sedentary farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Qinghai is hilly and heavily eroded and the (Chinese) people
there are unable to feed themselves. They are very eager to move,''
said Peter Stephens, a bank spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Chinese plan contains provisions that would
``protect the ethnic health'' of the Tibetan region.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the project violates the bank's own policies on
environmental impact and protection of indigenous peoples.
</P>
<P>
   The bill in Congress would require the United States to withhold
World Bank contributions equal to the amount loaned for any project
the Environmental Protection Agency or the Agency for International
Development determines violates the bank's own environmental or
social policies.
</P>
<P>
   Other authors of the bill include Reps. Dennis Kucinich and
Sherrod Brown, both Ohio Democrats; Ben Gilman, R-N.Y; John Porter,
R-Ill.; California Democrats Barbara Lee, Nancy Pelosi, Pete Stark
and Tom Lantos; Democrats Jesse Jackson Jr., Lane Evans and Luis
Guiterrez of Illinois; James McGovern, D-Mass., and Mark Udall,
D-Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
