<HEADER>
A3903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-710&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-     10-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-710&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPERS MOVE TO SECURE WESTERN REGIONS OF EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ International forces opened what they called
a decisive phase in the campaign to secure East Timor Friday,
sending troops for the first time into the western region of the
territory, where militias that oppose them have a strong presence.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, commander of the peacekeeping forces,
said the mission was intended to protect East Timor from threatened
attacks by armed groups that have retreated across the border into
the Indonesian region of West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a grouping of militia who have threatened to come
into the province with the intent to cause harm,'' the general
said. ``Our notion in going into the western regencies is to
demonstrate that the mandate is clear that we must offer protection
to all East Timorese.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the peacekeeping forces, which began arriving here 12
days ago, had spent considerable time securing the capital, Dili,
from violence by militias. Now, he said, ``we also have to take
seriously the threat that they will attempt to deny the western
regencies to all those other East Timorese who live there but do
not agree with them politically.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation, involving 1,000 soldiers along with armored
vehicles, naval landing craft and Blackhawk helicopters, met no
initial resistance, said Brig. Gen. Mark Kelly, chief spokesman for
the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant event within the expansion of our
operations,'' he said. Until now, the multinational force, heavily
dominated by Australians, has operated in the eastern part of the
country, where resistance has been light.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said the force, which is to grow to about 7,500 troops
from a dozen countries, numbers just over 5,000. He said the
western operation, which is intended to secure the area for food
distribution to refugees, could continue for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cosgrove said that although the international force is mandated
to operate only within East Timor, there were circumstances under
which it could pursue aggressors or fire into West Timor if its own
security was threatened.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The militias, set up by the Indonesian military to oppose
independence for East Timor, have not so far confronted the
peacekeepers, but they continue to issue threats from their
sanctuary in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the militias' campaign of terror, the people of East
Timor voted on Aug. 30 to break free of Indonesia, which has
administered the territory since invading it in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   After the result of the vote was announced on Sept. 4, the
militias began a program of destruction in which most of the
territory's towns and villages have been wrecked and more than half
of its population of 800,000 people have been driven from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said that the peacekeepers fired the first warning shots
of their mission here on Thursday, in an incident that involved
British Gurkhas escorting an aid convoy in the town of Com in the
east.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The shots were fired when the Gurkhas encountered 10 to 12
members of a militia group holding more than 2,000 people hostage,
said Lt. Col. David Richards, commander of the Gurkha unit here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scattered and took to the hills,'' he said of the militia
members. ``In pursuit, troops fired warning shots.'' Three militia
members were detained while the rest escaped, he said. The hostages
were released and returned home.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout East Timor, militia groups have moved large numbers
of people like these from their homes and out of the territory. As
many as 200,000 people have settled _ both willingly and
unwillingly _ in West Timorese camps controlled by the militias.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of this huge forced migration remains unclear, but
the camps do offer a potential base for possible cross-border raids
by the militias and by renegade Indonesian troops who support them.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The continuing threat of attacks, both in the west and
elsewhere, has slowed the start of a huge international relief
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers said Friday that they planned their first major
distribution of food and water here in Dili at the start of next
week. They estimated that as many as 100,000 people could come down
from their mountain refuges for supplies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At six distribution points around the city, each family is to
receive one 110-pound sack of rice per month, said Rachel Stabb, a
representative of the British aid group Oxfam.
</P>
<P>
   As tens of thousands of refugees return to the capital from
their hideouts, the focus here has shifted from destruction and
threat to the immediate need for food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The first downpour of the rainy season Friday afternoon
heightened the urgency of finding shelter for huge numbers of
people.
</P>
<P>
   And the desperate need for food aid was underscored when
hundreds of people, lined up near the central stadium for small
handouts of rice, paid no attention to a large fire that had been
set just two blocks away at the central police station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
