u i BC-JAPAN-RADIATION-BOS &LR;      10-01 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-RADIATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE PUBLIC, TOLD RADIATION DANGER IS OVER, REMAIN SKEPTICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A day after a major radioactivity release from a uranium
processing plant, Japanese officials moved Friday to reassure the
public that the danger was over. But many Japanese remained
skeptical, amid accusations that the government was slow to respond
to the country's worst nuclear disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The government officially admitted Friday that an uncontrolled
nuclear reaction in Tokaimura, 70 miles northeast of Tokyo, had
spewed radioactivity for 20 hours before it was extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   The company that runs the Tokaimura plant, JCO Co., blamed the
accident on human error but came under fire for having lax safety
measures. Forty-nine people, most of them plant workers, were
poisoned, three of them critically.
</P>
<P>
   Chief government spokesman Hiromu Nonaka called the accident a
``simple, primitive mistake'' that should not affect the country's
nuclear policy. But some here wondered if Japan, the only country
ever attacked with nuclear weapons, should rethink its heavy
dependence on nuclear power. Fifty-one reactors provide a third of
Japan's electricity,
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Nuclear Safety Commission said Friday that
radiation levels were back to normal. The 300,000 people living
within a six-mile radius of the plant, who had been instructed to
stay indoors since Thursday night, were told it was safe to go
outside in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people who had been evacuated from homes close
to the site, though, were told not to return yet.
</P>
<P>
   Many wondered whether the government was being completely
candid. They found it hard to believe that the radioactivity _
which had been 10,000 times above normal in the plant's immediate
vicinity _ had suddenly evaporated a day later. ``The government is
saying the problem has finished. But we think the radioactivity may
be continuing,'' said Mika Ohbayashi of the Citizens Nuclear
Information Center in Tokyo. ``People don't trust the government,
because they have a tendency to hide information on nuclear
incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   The center received a deluge of calls from frightened Japanese _
some living as much as a hundred miles from Tokaimura _ worried
whether it was safe to go outside.
</P>
<P>
   One scientific observer in the United States said he, too,
feared that Japanese authorities were prematurely reassuring people
that the danger had passed, when they haven't done enough study to
be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Hisham Zerriffi, project scientist at the Institute for Energy
and Environmental Research in Maryland, said he was skeptical that
radiation levels were back to normal outside the plant, since the
radiation released probably included isotopes that take much longer
than a day to disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Japanese government, in particular, should err on
the side of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``With certain segments of the public, they don't have the
benefit of the doubt. We already know they have in the past tried
to cover up accidents so they wouldn't look bad,'' said Zerriffi,
whose organization provides scientific analysis for environmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, officials conceded the government did not move quickly
enough to contain the damage and safeguard the public. The
government did not hold its first emergency meeting on the accident
until ten hours after it began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we must frankly admit that we were slow in
responding,'' chief government spokesman Nonaka. ``We must frankly
admit that we were too optimistic in assessing the seriousness of
the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people in the Tokaimura area, in Ibaraki
prefecture, flocked to community centers and hospitals to have
themselves tested for radiatioactive contamination. They were urged
to bring clothing they were wearing at the time of the accident for
testing as well.
</P>
<P>
   Keiko Haginoya came with her nine-year-old daughter to be tested
and was relieved they were found to be free of contamination. But
she was still worried. ``We really don't know what it means in the
long run,'' she told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The government at first played down the severity of the accident
and did not evacuate families living within 350 yards of the site
until nearly five hours later. Instructions that thousands more
should say indoors didn't come for 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials at JCO Co., the accident started when
workers improperly mixed uranium oxide with nitric acid, part of
the process to turn uranium into nuclear fuel. They used nearly 35
pounds of uranium, seven times more than the limit designed to
avoid criticality, the point at which a nuclear fission reaction
can occur.
</P>
<P>
   The workers bypassed certain other procedures, said Makoto
Morita, spokesman for JCO. Several company executives and staff
were questioned by police on suspicion of negligence.
</P>
<P>
   The company is being sharply criticized for its lack of safety
controls. Japanese media reports said the plant did not have proper
measures to protect workers from radiation, such as glove boxes, or
automated or remote-controlled safety systems.
</P>
<P>
   When JCO Co. president Koji Kitani appeared at an evacuation
location in Tokaimura to apologize to residents, he was jeered and
called ``liar.''
</P>
<P>
   The fuel made at the Tokaimura plant is designed for Japan's
first experimental fast-breeder reactor and uses a higher
concentration of uranium than that used in conventional nuclear
power plants. Under those circumstances, analysts said, the plant
should have had especially tight controls in place.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there was little government oversight over the plant.
Ibaraki prefecture governor Masaru Hashimoto said the site had a
single bare-bones inspection in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 hours in which it was termed too dangerous for anyone
to approach the site, 16 JCO workers began efforts to bring the
nuclear reaction under control. Early Friday they removed the
coolant around the uranium, since water helps sustain nuclear
fission, and then began to inject about eight gallons of
boron-containing chemicals into the facility to shut down the chain
reaction. The boron absorbs neutrons released by uranium molecules,
which split other molecules and keep the reaction going.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese are increasingly skeptical of their country's reliance
on nuclear power. The country has had six serious mishaps at
nuclear facilities since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent was in July, when 51 tons of coolant water
leaked from the Tssuruga power station. A government poll taken
several months before that incident showed that 68 percent of
Japanese were concerned about the nation's use of nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   The worst accident occurred in March 1997 when a fire broke out
at another reprocessing plant in Tokaimura, exposing 37 workers to
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Public mistrust grew after that incident. Officials later
admitted that a report on the fire was altered. It also was later
disclosed that a radioactive waste storage facility had been
leaking for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, officials at a nuclear agency tried to conceal
videotape of massive coolant leak.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's nuclear safety culture is poor, says Shaun Burnie, who
as East Asia research director of Greenpeace International, spends
most of his time in Japan. ``That's because they retain an
arrogance that their nuclear technology is superior and won't go
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Also the government's desire to keep nuclear power affordable
pushes it to keep costs down with fewer inspections and safety
systems, said Burnie. ``The government is conspiring with the
nuclear industry to keep it operating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scott Allen of The Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
