<HEADLINE>
NEW HEWLETT-PACKARD CHIEF CRITICAL OF COMPANY'S MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After warning that sales growth would not be
quite as robust as Wall Street had hoped, Hewlett-Packard Co.'s new
chief executive on Friday criticized the company's ``inadequate
performance management'' and announced that employees would be
dismissed in a lagging division.
</P>
<P>
   In her first analysts' briefing since joining the company in
July as president and chief executive, Carly Fiorina said revenue
growth, previously estimated at 10 to 13 percent for the quarter
compared with a year earlier, would be closer to the low end of
that range.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard shares dropped 3 3/8, or 3.72 percent, to close
at $87 3/8 on the New York Stock Exchange. But the trading day also
concluded with drops in several other leading technology stocks,
including Microsoft Corp., Apple Computer Inc. and
Hewlett-Packard's archrival, Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Fiorina laid some blame for the anticipated slowdown
in revenue growth to a slowdown in chip production after the
earthquake in Taiwan, she also singled out Hewlett-Packard's Unix
servers division as an area in need of her attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite an absolute winning Unix server product line, our
North American sales organization continues to underperform,'' she
said. ``This is not news. It is a longstanding problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many a new chief executive, Ms. Fiorina laid the blame at
the feet of her predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, we have operated over several years with
inadequate performance management, and we're correcting that right
now,'' Ms. Fiorina said. She announced that sales people with poor
track records were being dismissed and that the company's
compensation program was being restructured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sales force issue is fully in our control,'' Ms. Fiorina
said. ``The earthquake in Taiwan, on the other hand, was not. And
while the situation is still somewhat fluid, we are sure of some
disruption and delay in some elements of our PC supply chain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hewlett-Packard is the first major U.S. technology
company to formally warn of financial repercussions from the 7.6
magnitude earthquake last week in Taiwan, analysts said the
earthquake was also likely to disrupt other major PC companies,
including Apple and Dell Computer Corp. Chip makers, including
Intel Corp. and Advanced Micro Devices Inc., may also suffer, since
56 percent of motherboards, the circuit boards that house most PC
chips, are produced in Taiwan, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard is particularly vulnerable, however, because of
the degree to which it has shifted PC production to contract
manufacturers, many in Taiwan. Mitac International Corp., one of
Taiwan's biggest PC makers, said this week that factory shutdowns
would shave about $13 million off September sales, and
Hewlett-Packard is among its biggest customers. The use of contract
manufacturers has, however, helped Hewlett-Packard reduce costs and
improve profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   John Jones, an analyst with , described the Taiwan situation as
``not news and short-term in nature,'' and said he still expected
Hewlett-Packard to meet his earnings estimate of 81 cents per share
in the quarter. ``HP can still meet earnings expectations for a
series of reasons,'' he said. ``The PC pricing environment is
better than planned, and HP is getting better PC margins. HP is
increasing its inkjet market share, up two points in August, and
sales of very high-margin consumables are booming.''
</P>
<P>
   The weak performance in Unix servers has, by contrast, been a
problem spot for some time as Hewlett-Packard has steadily lost
market share to Sun. Although Hewlett-Packard now has a competitive
product line, and the new compensation system should help, analysts
said the company still lacked the focus Sun brings to the market.
Sun's message is that Unix is the most robust operating system and
that Sun's version of Unix, Solaris, is the most advanced.
Hewlett-Packard, on the other hand, sells both Unix servers and
machines running Microsoft's Windows NT, thus diluting its efforts,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Fiorina said the problems were in Hewlett-Packard's
business processes. ``We have had compensation systems that failed
to drive superior performance,'' she said. ``We are instituting
significant changes to improve performance in this quarter, and we
are implementing an entirely new incentive-based compensation
system, starting Nov. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Hewlett-Packard will have some special charges in
the quarter because of the spinoff of its test and measurement
business, now known as Agilent Inc. ``We also will have other
special charges to reflect some of the actions we are taking to be
more competitive as we enter the year 2000,'' Ms. Fiorina said. ``I
am not able to provide any specific numbers on that at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fiorina also said that two of Hewlett-Packard's business
unit presidents would assume new responsibilities. Ann Livermore,
who has been president of enterprise computing, will now have
primary responsibility for the company's 100 largest customers
across all business units as well as for e-services,
Hewlett-Packard's central Internet strategy. Antonio Perez, who has
been president of the hard copy business unit, will head up
Hewlett-Packard's efforts in digital imaging for both commercial
and consumer accounts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
