A3929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      10-01 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZE GIVEN MAJOR DEFENSE ROLE BY BURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Steve Heinze has bounced back and forth from left wing
to right, from a boat load of ice time to a few shifts here and
there, depending on whether he's riding a hot streak or a cold one.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bruins set to open the regular season Saturday night
against Carolina at the FleetCenter, coach Pat Burns told Heinze,
who turns 30 in January, he is one of the forwards the team is
relying on to provide a steady stream of offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good discussion about it,'' said Burns. ``It's a big
year for him, he's not getting any younger. He's got to be a strong
skater. When he's down on his knees or on his belly, he's not a
strong skater. He can fire the puck with a lot of speed and if he
does that, he'll do well. (He can't) get down on himself when
things are going bad; that's been his problem the last eight or
nine years, and he has to find a way to get out of it. I think he
knows me now. He knows I'm not going to wait forever. I have to win
hockey games and that's the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Heinze had 22 goals and 40 points in 73 games, down
from a career-high 26 goals and 46 points in 1997-98 in just 61
contests. He will start the season with Joe Thornton at center and
Sergei Samsonov at left wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``Those guys have a ton of offensive
skill. I think with Sammy, you've got to play a little bit
different than when Joe has the puck. When Joe has the puck, you go
straight ahead and get to the net quick. When Sammy has it, you
have to kind of time yourself and lay back a bit because he's going
to dangle and beat three guys. If I go flying to the net, I'm just
going to have some 6-foot-5-inch guy beating me up for 30 seconds
before the puck gets there. Sammy pulls guys to him so if I come in
late, I'll be going to the net with no one around me.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze, a righthanded shot, said part of the reason he has
switched to the right side is because of opportunity. There weren't
any open left-wing spots, and he said that's fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I think about it is when I'm out there, if I
have a center who's a lefty and a left wing who's a righty and just
remember who you're passing to and which side of the stick it's
going to be on,'' he said. ``It helps out on the power play if
you've got a left and a right on defense and at least one lefty or
righty to mix with others but if you don't have that, you've just
got to make do.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said part of the reason he wants Heinze to step it up is
to help absorb some of the offensive void created by Dmitri
Khristich's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows this is a contract year for me and I'm a couple of
years away from free agency,'' said Heinze, who was married this
summer. ``I kind of slowed down in the scoring department last
year, not extensively but a touch slower than the year before. He
was saying he needs a lot from me and I have to expect a lot from
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has adjusted his forward lines in an attempt to strike a
balance, but he said it's been difficult because of the
preponderance of righthanded shots at forward (only Thornton, P.J.
Axelsson, Mikko Eloranta and Ken Belanger are left shots), and
left-shooting defensemen. Among the top nine blue-liners, only
injured Nick Boynton and rookie Jonathan Girard are right shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most odd team I've ever had,'' said Burns.
``(Nearly) all our forwards are righthanded shots and all our
defense are lefthand shots, which makes for a power-play nightmare.
We can't have everybody playing on the left side. We already have a
right shot who's playing the left side (Dave Andreychuk). We have
Samsonov who's a right shot and plays the left side. I think
Heinzey can handle the right. All he has to do is go up and down
his wing and wait until Samsonov comes out of the corner and feeds
it to him. He has to shoot the puck and skate. If he does that,
he'll do well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
