<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, Oct. 2. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   GUN-COMPANIES (Undated) _ Leading gun manufacturers react to the
growing pressure from lawsuits by cities across the nation. At
issue is gun safety and reducing the flow of guns to criminals. By
Fox Butterfield. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-COALITION (Washington) _ In a striking departure from
other presidential candidates _ past and present _ Gov. George W.
Bush glosses over or does not mention abortion, school prayer, gay
rights and other matters vital to the Christian Coalition in an
address to the group. Even so, he draws a rousing ovation and an
unusually warm outpouring from the coalition's founder, Pat
Robertson. By Richard Berke. (Scheduled to move by 8:45 p.m. ET in
``p'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to GORE-CAMPAIGN; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead: 4-column photo reefer to CHINA-MILITARY.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran, Iran) _ Iran's supreme religious leader
moves decisively to head off a fresh confrontation with the
country's reformist president, instructing hardline Muslim clerics
and their loyalists in the country's police not to ``take matters
into their own hands'' in a new and potentially explosive dispute
involving Tehran university students. By John F. Burns. (The story
has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokaimura, Japan) _ The scene: Residents of
Tokaimura interviewed by phone while barricaded in their homes, or
caught on the street in the first minutes after the ban on going
outside was lifted, express their anger and disbelief that safety
precautions could have been so lax and that the government could
have minimized the accident in the crucial first hours. By Howard
W. French. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-GANDHIS (Rampur, India) _ The political and personal soap
opera of Sonia Gandhi and Maneka Gandhi: Sonia is the aloof woman
who now wants to run the country. Maneka is the ``other
daughter-in-law,'' and oh, how the irony grates on her. She has
been in politics for 20 years, Sonia for two. She is the widow of
Sanjay, who was his mother's right-hand man. Sonia's husband was
Rajiv, an airline pilot disinclined to governance. Sonia is the
leader of the venerable Congress Party; Maneka, the cabinet
minister for welfare. From 1974 to 1982, the two daughters-in-law
lived under the same roof. ``They hated each other's guts from the
word go,'' said the writer Khushwant Singh. By Barry Bearak.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-NEWYEAR-VACANCIES (New York) _ Despite everything you may
have heard about millennium madness, out-of-towners have not booked
every overpriced hotel room in the city for New Year's Eve. They
have not snapped up every $3,000 seat in the Rainbow Room,
purchased every $1,000 ticket to every ``gala'' event, hired every
limousine _ or even every baby sitter. By Leslie Eaton. (Scheduled
to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,700 words.
</P>
