<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WITH-BRYNE-ART     10-01 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-BRYNE-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH SUSAN M. BYRNE: GABELLI WESTWOOD EQUITY FUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Okla.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of Gabelli Westwood Equity fund is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Wall Street, there is money to be made running with the herd
_ or against it. Susan M. Byrne, portfolio manager of the $194.1
million Gabelli Westwood Equity fund, takes the second approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for stocks where I see that improvements in a company's
growth prospects are going unrecognized by Wall Street, either in
consensus earnings or forward growth rates,'' she said from her
office in downtown Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the crowd has paid off. The fund returned 19.8 percent
for the 12 months ended Sept. 30, compared with 15.7 percent for
its peers in the large value category, according to Morningstar
Inc., the Chicago financial publisher, and 21.4 percent for the
Standard &AMP; Poor's Barra Value Index of large-capitalization value
stocks, with dividends reinvested monthly.
</P>
<P>
   It returned 18.1 percent a year, on average, for the three years
through Sept. 30, versus 15.4 percent for its peers, according to
Morningstar, and 19 percent for the S&AMP;P Barra Value Index.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing stocks, Ms. Byrne, 53, makes use of what she calls
``a proxy for professional skepticism'': She starts with the
percentage by which a company beats analysts' consensus earnings
estimates for a quarter and compares that number with the
percentage increase in earnings that analysts forecast for that
year. A ratio higher than 1 suggests that analysts may not be
giving enough credence to the company's improving fundamentals. (In
the fourth quarter, she will look at the next year's earnings
forecast.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When analysts don't revise earnings upward after a company
beats its estimate,'' she said, ``it means that they don't believe
that the company can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   That situation, she added, creates opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Byrne looks at a company's price-to-sales ratio, but pays
relatively scant attention to its price-to-earnings multiple when
buying. ``When you have a large company that is in a period of
turning around its business, its income statement could mean
anything,'' she said. ``The balance sheet is the real story.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Ms. Byrne likes to see companies with debt-to-total
capitalization ratios of less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   She steers clear of companies with price-to-sales ratios
exceeding the average of roughly 4 for the S&AMP;P 500. That eliminates
most Internet, software and early-stage growth companies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she also demands an improving return on shareholder
equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I combine that with a showing of stable to lower debt,'' she
said, ``which tells me that the improvement is coming from company
operations, not financial leverage.'' (A rising return on equity,
of course, can be a result of increasing debt.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Byrne, who works with three analysts on the fund, said she
tends to sell stocks when their price-to-earnings multiples rise
above their corresponding earnings growth rates _ when the P/E
climbs to 31, for example, and the earnings growth rate is 30
percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Byrne likes the Devon Energy Corp., an Oklahoma City-based
oil and gas company. In August, Devon bought Pennzenergy, formerly
Pennzoil, based in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural-gas companies are coming through with tremendous
positive earnings surprises and no earnings revisions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices have been strong this year and oil prices have risen
sharply, she noted. ``We did our work on Devon,'' she said, ``and
kept getting multiples and cash flow estimates that were
significantly higher than other people's.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund began buying shares in January at an average cost of
$30. Ms. Byrne forecasts earnings growth of 30 percent a year, on
average, over three years, and has a 12-month price target of $60 a
share. The stock closed on Friday at $41.625.
</P>
<P>
   She bought shares in the Walt Disney Co. in late summer at an
average cost of $27, after the company announced that it would sell
its Fairchild magazine division and its two hockey teams. The
company posted a positive earnings surprise in the second quarter,
beating analysts' estimates of 19 cents a share by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts, worried about deteriorating attendance at Disney's
Florida operations and lackluster video sales, revised their annual
earnings estimates downward by 5 cents a share, to 67 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we'll see an improvement in Disney's focus,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She forecasts an annual three-year growth rate in earnings
before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization of 18 percent
to 20 percent, and has a 12-month price target in the mid-$40s. The
stock closed on Friday at $25.325.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Ms. Byrne bought shares in Federated Department Stores
at an average cost of $46. Federated, which owns chains like
Macy's, Bloomingdale's and Lazarus, acquired Fingerhut, a catalogue
retailer of lower-priced novelties, in late March, she said,
because of its expertise in order fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that a year from now, when people look back at the
Internet, they will realize that it's a lot easier to create a Web
page than it is to get an order out to a consumer at the right time
and get paid,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Federated posted earnings of 61 cents a
share, beating analysts' consensus estimate of 50 cents. But
analysts did not revise their annual earnings estimates upward, she
said, because ``they're concerned that consumers will stop buying
because of the rise in interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   She estimated that Federated's earnings would grow 20 percent a
year, on average, over three years. Her 12-month price target for
the stock is $85; it closed on Friday at $44.8125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
