<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATON GLAD TO HAVE WOHLABAUGH ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There's a good chance Dave Wohlabaugh wasn't
shaking in his boots in Cleveland this week, but he probably got a
good laugh from the series of phone messages from Chad Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a friendly battle of interior linemen Sunday between
Eaton, Wohlabaugh, the Browns' center. The two battled on the
practice field for two years before Wohlabaugh jumped ship and
signed a lucrative seven-year, $26.5 million deal with Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be fun,'' said Eaton. ``Dave's a friend, but it was fun
just trying to get him going. I was going to leave him phone
messages every so often just to get him going. I just wanted him to
know that I'm going to be in front of him all day. I want him to
know I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   One time Wohlabaugh called back and left a message saying, ``Why
are you stalking me? Leave me alone. No, just kidding, call you
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time Eaton left a song he heard on the radio on the
message machine. Eaton said he would probably leave another message
or two by the end of business Friday, but then he would leave
Wohlabaugh alone.
</P>
<P>
   Other Patriots, including Max Lane, also have been in touch with
Wohlabaugh this week.
</P>
<P>
   Concidentally, Eaton left Cleveland to come to New England. He
often tells the story of being in the Browns' locker room when
owner Art Modell told the team it was moving to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlabaugh has been the steady hand on the Browns' offensive
line this season, working with No. 1 pick Tim Couch, just as he had
to work with Drew Bledsoe, though Bledsoe was in his third year
when Wohlabaugh was drafted in '95 out of Syracuse. He was a very
effective player for the Patriots and he wanted to remain with the
team, but a contract offer never came. When the Patriots finally
got into it, their offer couldn't touch the Browns' deal, which
made Wohlabaugh the highest-paid center in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots then opted for Boston College's Damien Woody with
their first round pick.
</P>
<P>
   And Eaton had a new center to torment.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton will certainly be motivated by two factors Sunday: his
matchup against Wohlabaugh and returning to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered what it would be like to play against Dave
in a game,'' said Eaton. ``He was a great guy to battle with in
practice, because the centers I'd face in the games couldn't match
up against Dave. We all hated to see him go because he meant a lot
to this team, but now he's on the enemy side and we have to battle
him and make sure he doesn't get the best of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Pete Carroll has gotten into the ``matchup'' saying earlier
this week, ``We'd like to see Chad whip him, but I know Dave's
going to do everything he can to keep that from happening. We'll
keep close watch on the film and see if Chad gets him.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   Eaton will have to swallow a few of his words.
</P>
<P>
   But this kind of friendly matchup has been missing in the NFL
for many years now. It seems that teams are afraid to exchange
barbs for fear of ``locker room material'' that might incite the
other team.
</P>
<P>
   Some players fear that, but Eaton feels confident enough in his
ability to have some fun in pure WWF style, while understanding the
matchup is vital to the success of the Patriots, who must not only
get to Couch and pressure him, but also stop the Browns' running
game.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton is also very serious about the Cleveland game, echoing
Carroll's words that this could very well be a ``trap'' game _ in
which the Patriots get overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the games that you need to worry about,'' said
Eaton. ``They have some good players and we have to play against
those good players. It's not an easy game and I'm not going to go
into it that way. I know more than anyone the guy I'm facing is a
good player. I know because I've faced him a lot. It'll be
interesting to see what I can exploit against Dave and what he can
exploit against me.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Patriots don't want to do is get into a close game and
have the ``Dawg Pound'' involved. Eaton recalls the home-field
advantage those fans used to give the Browns. The stadium may be
new and the team different, but dawgs will be dawgs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
