<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3948 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-THREEKINGS-FILM-TEX     10-01 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREEKINGS-FILM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE KINGS' DAZZLES WITH A SURREAL BREW OF HUMOR AND HORRORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Three Kings'' _ an action/comedy/melodrama set during the last
days of Operation Desert Storm in 1991 _ is the movie Oliver Stone
has been trying to make his entire career. It's a pi$ata of a
picture, filled with ideas, exhilarating filmmaking technique and a
robust (even off-putting) bleak humor. ``Kings'' mostly uses
contradictions to set a questioning, roughhouse tone, both in its
storytelling and in its use of popular culture _ the movie careens
from one irony to another like a master player's pinball, scoring
at will.
</P>
<P>
   The story follows four American soldiers who happen upon a map
that leads to Iraqi gold, treasure that the men plan on liberating
for themselves. As they make the trek, they discover that the heist
will end up being as complicated as the war itself. Nothing is
simple.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing except the film's action sequences, which come together
with ruthless clarity. Writer/director David O. Russell employs
moviemaking skills and fervor that, based on his modestly staged
but thoughtful screwball comedies, ``Spanking the Monkey'' and
``Flirting With Disaster,'' he seemed incapable of. The story is
told with a variety of camera tricks and hand-held moves that give
the film a journalistic immediacy. Russell also uses the bravura
mechanics of action moviemaking to impart an element of swiftness.
He never lingers on anything for too long. It's a pulse-pounding
style that makes ``Three Kings'' feel like Jean-Luc Godard's ``Les
Carabiniers'' _ a legendary anti-war film about a pair of kids who
go off to war to loot and arouse themselves from boredom _ but as
handled by the Bomb Squad, the sonic masterminds who produced the
dizzying assault of rappers Public Enemy. (One of their songs,
``Can't Do Nuttin' for Ya, Man,'' which includes the line that
could sum up the characters' plight _ ``You jumped out of the jelly
into a jam'' _ is used on the ``Three Kings'' soundtrack.)
</P>
<P>
   The men out to recover the gold are Archie (George Clooney), a
Special Forces veteran whose brow is twisted into a permanent
furrow, and the Army reservists Troy (Mark Wahlberg), who tries to
do what's decent whenever he can, his buddy Vig (Spike Jonze), an
eager but brainless redneck who'd rather shoot or fight, and the
resourceful Chief (Ice Cube). It's Troy who sets into motion the
moral questioning when, in the first scene in the picture, he asks
``Are we still shooting people?'' and blasts a man who may have
been trying to surrender ... or trying to kill him, we're never
sure. Wahlberg's light, raspy voice _ how was this guy ever pop
star Marky Mark? _ gives him a querulous quality. He seems to
always be wondering how people are feeling, which doesn't mesh with
the ``collateral damage'' of the Persian Gulf War, where the
killing techniques far surpassed any of the soldiers' abilities to
figure out what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   When this quartet proceeds with their free-enterprise mission,
they get to see, up close, the calamities they've only caught on
TV. Despite the apparent U.S. victory, and the cease-fire, Saddam
Hussein's army is still beating and torturing Kuwaitis. It doesn't
make any sense to the young reservists, who are itching for a
fight. (''We didn't see any action,'' they tell Archie, which leads
to a hilarious scene involving a cluster bomb and a wandering cow.)
When Archie decides to take an active stance, ``Three Kings''
hurtles into a faster mode.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney is used for his commonsense star quality. He's a brooder
with a Heathcliff aspect and a patient, deliberate way of speaking
that masks an undercurrent of anger; until he explodes, he seems to
be the sanest and most beleaguered of men. This may not be his best
performance, but he shows why he's a star; he steps up and takes
command. He's also a generous actor, and an ambitious one who makes
interesting choices. Neither ``Three Kings'' _ which he is said to
have campaigned for _ nor Clooney's previous film, ``Out of
Sight,'' are the picks of a complacent actor. Clooney doesn't
overshadow any of his co-stars. And Spike Jonze, the talented young
music-video director who lives to perpetrate pop-culture scams,
shines as Vig, the comic relief who always says the wrong thing.
Nora Dunn is a Christiane Amanpour-ish reporter who's angry over
the Army's stonewalling of the media. It points the press toward
only the news it wants broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Kings'' shows an unblinking willingness to exhibit the
real results of action-picture violence. A flash-cut to a body's
interior _ Wahlberg's _ shows the damage a bullet can do. ``Three
Kings'' treads a dangerous line between wanting to have its cake
and eat it, too. You can't help but be excited by the bravado and
precision of the action the movie is trying to comment on, tinged
with its drab khaki and olive palette. When a woman is executed,
we're almost catapulted out of the movie, even as ``Three Kings''
tries to depict the casual cruelty of war.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the movie seems so hungry to express ideas that it
feels pitiless. After Troy has been captured _ following a funny
digression by his captor on race oppression and Michael Jackson _
he has an eye-opening political discussion in which he strains to
convince the Iraqis (who have been pressed into service, like Troy,
for the extra money, and don't really believe in Saddam) why the
United States is involved. Here, a point is made too crudely about
the real basis for the gulf war. Troy's captors shove oil down his
throat to teach him what the West is really fighting for.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ironies in ``Three Kings'' come more quickly and
smoothly. When Ice Cube bursts into a bunker filled with Iraqis,
and their Western booty _ computers, VCRs and TVs _ the camera
whips around to show Rodney King being beaten by police officers to
raise the question, What is this black man fighting for? On an even
subtler front _ and in maybe one of the funniest scenes of the
decade: Cube and Jonze, once two of the most subversive figures in
popular culture, argue over which music is more suitable for
listening, Chicago or Judas Priest. And this before they're about
to drive a fleet of luxury cars across the desert to save their
captured buddy. When the contrasts pile up this fast, you know
you're seeing something unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Kings'' is so smart and nimble, making references
ranging from ``Star Wars'' to ``The Stunt Man'' to the media
establishment, that it comes off as a little cold, not affecting
when it could be. But that's meant as a compliment _ there's
nothing else out there remotely like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Kings'' is rated R for profanity, violence, gore and
brief sexuality. .MDNM/ (lvis Mitchell is a film critic for the
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
