<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JOINT-VENTURES-450&AMP;AD     10-01 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOINT-VENTURES-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ISSUES SOME GUIDELINES ON FORMING JOINT VENTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department and the Federal Trade
Commission published proposed guidelines Friday for joint ventures
among businesses, indicating the sorts of agreements that do not
violate federal antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Joint ventures or collaborations in purchasing, marketing,
patent licensing or research are growing more common, but the legal
standards showing when cooperation is permissible, and when it
might violate antitrust laws, are murky and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   The two agencies, in a summary accompanying the guidelines,
said, ``Competitive forces of globalization and technology are
driving firms toward complex collaborations to achieve goals such
as expanding into foreign markets, funding expensive innovation
efforts and lowering production and other costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the Trade Commission, said: ``What
we have strived for is a uniform standard. It's the first effort in
this country to have guidelines that cut across all joint ventures
_ research and development, marketing, patent, cross-licensing,
production.''
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines are merely proposals. They are now subject to
comment for 90 days, after which time the agencies will decide
whether to modify or approve them.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-page guide sets out the tests the two agencies will apply
in determining whether to investigate or challenge a proposed joint
venture. They do not definitively establish which ventures are
legal and which are not, noting that each case has unique
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   But, in general, they do say that ``agreements among
competitors'' to ``share or divide markets by allocating customers,
suppliers, territories or lines of commerce'' are automatically
considered illegal and will be challenged. An alleged proposed
agreement of that sort is at the center of the Justice Department's
antitrust suit against Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But when two companies in an otherwise competitive industry
choose to cooperate in a way that does not significantly alter the
competitive landscape, the likelihood is that the joint venture
would be permitted, the guidelines say. One indication that a
problem might exist is if the two companies, combined, hold more
than 20 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said the genesis of the guidelines came from hearings
the agency held on high-tech competition two years ago. At the end,
the commissioners asked the witnesses ``what area of law we should
turn to to assist global and high-tech competition by clarifying
the law, and we were blown away by the unanimity of responses,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses said they wanted more clarity on joint ventures
and antitrust because ``American joint venture law is unclear,
murky, uncertain,'' Pitofsky said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Often, the trade commission will approve a cooperative agreement
in part but make certain stipulations, just as is true in many
merger cases. For example, the commission approved a significant
joint venture between Shell and Texaco last year after the venture
agreed to sell a refinery and divest itself of some retailing
operations in Hawaii and California, eliminating areas where the
commission believed the two companies, together, would hold too
much market power.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, the commission tries to block cooperation when
one company's arrangement with another causes what the
commissioners see as anti-competitive harm.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, seven months ago the commission charged Mylan
Laboratories, one of the world's largest makers of generic drugs,
with violating antitrust law by entering into illegal agreements
with one of its suppliers to eliminate competition in the market
for two generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked on these guidelines to give certainty to the
parties,'' Pitofsky said. ``There are no absolute bright lines. But
at least if you know the progression, we'll all be on the same
page.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
