u w BC-STATES-watch-NAT     10-01 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  New York Times Votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224. PLEASE
NOTE: THERE IS NO ATTENDANCE CHART WASHINGTON, Oct. 1 -- The
following chart shows how senators and representatives voted on key
bills and amendments within the last week. A ``Y'' means the member
voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the member voted against the
measure; a ``?'' means the member did not vote; and a ``P'' means
the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: ENERGY-S
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved, 96 to 3, a $21.3 billion
spending bill for the Department of Energy. The bill left out $35
million requested by the department for computer security.
Supporters of the bill said the department needs to reform its
management before getting more money. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson said he objected to the final bill's failure to
adequately address the cyber security needs. A ``yes'' vote favors
the spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved, 98 to 1, a temporary spending
measure that will keep the federal government open until Oct. 21.
The bill gives lawmakers time to resolve several problems
surrounding the annual spending bills, some of which President
Clinton has threatened to veto. Clinton has signed the resolution
into law. A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: LAWSUITS
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Sept. 23, the House approved, 222 to 207, a bill to
move some class action lawsuits into federal courts. The bill would
give federal courts juridisction in cases where the party filing
the suit is a citizen of a different state than the defendent.
Supporters said the measure would prevent lawyers from filing cases
in states where they know they will get a ruling in their favor.
Opponents, including the White House, said the bill would make it
harder for individuals to sue companies for wrongdoing. A ``yes''
vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: ENERGY-H
</P>
<P>
   The House on Monday approved, 327 to 87, a $21.3 billion
spending bill for the Department of Energy. The bill left out $35
million requested by the department for computer security.
Supporters of the bill said the department needs to reform its
management before getting more money. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson said he objected to the final bill's failure to
adequately address cyber security needs. A ``yes'' vote favors the
spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: PREGNANT
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 201-224, a substitute measure
that would have increased penalties for crimes committed against
pregnant women. The bill would have replaced a measure, that later
passed, that makes it a separate federal crime to harm a fetus.
Supporters said the measure addresses the need to protect pregnant
women without compromising a woman's right to have an abortion.
Opponents said the measure failed to address the need to protect
unborn children. A ``yes'' vote favors the substitute measure.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: UNBORN
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 254 to 172, a bill that makes it
a federal crime to harm a fetus. The measure says anyone who
injures or kills a fetus in the act of another federal crime can be
punished for a separate offense on behalf of the ``unborn victim''.
Supporters said the bill properly addresses crimes against fetuses
without affecting abortion rights. But opponents said that by
recognizing a fetus as a separate entity, the bill is just the
first step in an attempt to eliminate a woman's right to have an
abortion. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The attendance record is not part of the
current vote chart because the company that supplied us with the
information is no longer in service. We are looking for a new
source.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
