<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3968 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     10-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TURN OF EVENTS HAS LIMITS FOR GOLD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time was, ``Worth its weight in gold'' meant something. Trouble
is, for the past two decades, gold has been on a diet.
</P>
<P>
   For two days in early January 1980, a time of double-digit
interest rates and stagflation, gold fetched more than $800 an
ounce. But then the ride that had taken the metal up to that level
ended, and prices have been falling pretty much steadily ever
since. Earlier this year, they hit a 20-year low, at $252 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past week, gold has perked up.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen European central banks said on Sept. 26 that they would
limit their sales of gold to 400 tons a year for the next five
years. With the fear removed that monetary authorities would swamp
the market and push the price lower, gold jumped more than $42 an
ounce in two days. On Friday it closed at $TKT.TK.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Eveillard, portfolio manager of the Sogen Gold fund,
took some time last week to discuss what the gain does _ and does
not _ mean for investors. Here are excerpts from the conversation: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has the rise in gold prices been due solely to the central
banks' announcement? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There may be some worry about Y2K and perhaps some worries
about the inflationary implications of a weaker dollar. But on
Sept. 26 there was a major turn of events that was unexpected,
particularly by me. As a result, I think things look good for gold
for the next few months. But to carry the price much higher than
the current $300 an ounce will take something else, like an
increase in investment demand. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you think motivated the European central banks to
take this step? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. On one level, they said that gold remains an important
monetary asset, a position Alan Greenspan shares. When he has been
asked about gold in the past, he has called it the ultimate form of
payment.
</P>
<P>
   But my own suspicion, which I cannot prove, is that the central
bankers may have been worried that too many hedge funds were
playing a gold ``carry trade'' with a lot of leverage. Until
recently, you could borrow gold at a rate of about 1 percent, turn
it into cash and buy two-year Treasury bills and pocket the
difference when you bought back the gold and returned it with the
interest. If you leveraged the purchase, you could make even more
money, because the price of gold was coming down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the central banks were not lending gold to the hedge funds,
but to bullion banks, which in turn lend to hedge funds. By shaking
things up now, perhaps the central banks thought that by creating a
little bit of trouble now they might avoid a lot of trouble in six
months to a year. The memories of Long Term Capital are still
pretty fresh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You started the fund in 1993, when gold had been in decline
for years. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. When Warren Buffett bought silver last year, he said he had
observed that demand exceeded supply and concluded the imbalance
could only be resolved by a higher price for the commodity.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of gold, demand, mostly for jewelry, has exceeded
supply for the last 10 years. The gap has been somewhere between
500 and 1,000 tons a year. But it has been more than filled by
central bank selling, producers selling gold forward and commodity
funds shorting gold. That was my mistake.
</P>
<P>
   I started the gold fund not because inflation was coming back or
that monetary disaster was impending, but that the demand-supply
gap would take care of itself through an increase in price. It was
a big mistake on my part. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You said gold will need something extra to push it much
higher. Can you elaborate? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Anything more would be triggered by inflation, poor
performance by financial markets or a financial market crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the price can go to $350 an ounce, but no higher without
something like that.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, that is because there is price resistance on
jewelry, particularly in Asia. If the price of gold goes up more
than that, it will drive people out of the market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Should investors consider gold, even if the upside in prices
is somewhat limited? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think gold can play a modest role in one's investment
portfolio. By modest, I mean a position that does not exceed 5
percent of assets.
</P>
<P>
   If one comes to that conclusion, the decision then is between
buying bullion, which is the least risky way, or gold mining and
related securities. The problem with securities is that you are
introducing considerable leverage. Whenever gold prices go up 10
percent or down 10 percent, securities fluctuate 30 percent in
either direction.
</P>
<P>
   In order to reduce risk, one is probably better off with
established producers like Newmont Mining and Homestake Mining, or
Placer Dome in Canada. And there are a few South African gold
stocks like Gold Fields Ltd. and Harmony Gold, which trade ADRs in
this country. The advantage they have is that they are a lot
cheaper than the Canadian and American stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
