<SLUG> BC-COALITION02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian Coalition founder says Bush is worthy of group's
support
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson had kind
words for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas on Friday at the group's
political convention, but called on congressional Republicans to
show more courage.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded Republicans in Congress that they achieved a
majority with the help of Christian conservatives and warned them
about compromising their conservative beliefs. ``It's better to
lose fighting a noble cause than to live in peace as a coward,''
Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed to have no such qualms about Bush, even though
some coalition members suspect the governor is not conservative
enough on a range of social issues.
</P>
<P>
   While Robertson did not endorse Bush, he is openly in search of
a Republican candidate who can win in 2000, preferably with the
coalition's help. Bush appears to be the strongest Republican
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far George Bush has said things that cause me to believe
he'd be worthy of the support of Christian Coalition members,''
Robertson told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson praised Bush shortly before the candidate delivered
his standard stump speech to a few thousand delegates. Remarks
about his opposition to abortion was the only nod Bush made to the
socially conservative crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child born and unborn must be protected by law and
welcomed to life,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that he signed a parental notification law on
abortion in Texas, saying ``Parents should be the first to help,
not the last to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush received a warm ovation from the audience, which filled a
hotel ballroom with many empty seats for other speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, a Bush adviser and former coalition executive
director, said he believes the Texas governor has strong support
among coalition members. ``Given his standing in the polls, it's
demographically impossible for him not to have a plurality among
Christian conservatives,'' Reed said. ``He otherwise could not get
to those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was also little doubt that Bush's centrist campaign
makes some coalition members uneasy. ``I like him, but people here
just seem nervous about him,'' said David Shepard of Arlington,
Va., a convention attendee who is not affiliated with any campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks contrasted with those of conservative activist
Gary Bauer, who thundered his intent to appoint only dedicated
anti-abortion judges. ``I will not sacrifice one baby for political
gain,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of oratory drew rousing applause from delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire, who left the GOP this year and
is considering running as a third-party candidate for president,
said that if the Senate rejected a pro-life judicial nominee of
his, ``I'd send them another one and another one and another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole spoke about her
commitment ``to strive to lean on the Lord with my whole heart,
reading His Word daily and earnestly seeking His will in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, Bauer and other speakers were harshly critical of
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, who told an interviewer in Playboy
magazine that organized religion is a ``sham'' and a crutch for the
weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse is off his rocker,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer suggested that instead of ``The Body'' or ``The Mind,''
Ventura's nickname should be ``The Bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) said Ventura had ``spoken like a true
pro wrestler.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson also had a warning for commentator Pat Buchanan, who
is thinking about moving his GOP presidential campaign to Ventura's
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the Reform Party is ``180 degrees'' different from
Buchanan on social issues, Robertson predicted Buchanan would lose
the support of coalition members if he jumped.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan had been scheduled to address the convention, but his
staff said an unspecified conflict forced him to cancel his
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
