<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MICHIGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE IS ON A ROLL WITH NO SIGN OF LETTING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ How long has it been since ``Purdue
Boilermakers'' and ``football power'' have shared the same
sentence?
</P>
<P>
   Study the musty benchmarks. A victory against Michigan on
Saturday means Purdue would match the 11-game winning streak set
from 1928 to 1930. It means the Boilermakers would be 5-0 for the
first time since 1945. It means the 11th-ranked Boilermakers would
crack the top 10 Associated Press poll for the first time since
finishing No. 10 at the end of the 1979 season.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, it means the modern age offense of Coach Joe
Tiller and the Heisman Trophy-caliber arm of Drew Brees puts Purdue
in the Big Ten title hunt _ at least for a week.
</P>
<P>
   If Purdue survives the No. 4 Wolverines at Michigan, No. 12 Ohio
State awaits in Columbus next week, followed by consecutive home
dates against No. 14 Michigan State and No. 2 Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unbelievable stretch,'' Tiller said. ``It will be a
real test for us, but I think we've got to lighten up and enjoy the
moment, the opportunity to play this level or caliber of
competition. That's a difficult draw for anybody. But that's the
way the schedule has been set, so we plan on being there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers will not be unarmed as they embark on what they
hope is a brawl to the Rose Bowl. They have Brees and a
multiple-set spread offense that Tiller brought from Wyoming in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   In only 24 games, 17 of them as a starter, Brees has thrown 49
touchdown passes and has amassed 5,530 yards. He is so comfortable
at the controls of the nation's ninth best team in scoring and
total offense _ 41 points, 447 yards a game _ that he believes a
perfect game is in reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think I should complete every pass, unless I'm trying
to throw the ball away to avoid a sack,'' said Brees, a junior.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wolverines (4-0) will counter with the nation's 18th
stingiest defense, one that gives up only 271 yards a game, and one
that pretty much derailed the Heisman aspirations of Wisconsin
running back Ron Dayne when it held him to 88 yards _ zero in the
second half _ last week in a 21-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's defenders say they relish having an impact on the
outcome of the nation's most coveted college award. The defense is
already responsible for keeping the Wolverines' national title
drive alive while the offense has struggled with its transformation
from a running team (117 yards a game) to a passing team (223.8
yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to change gears at any time and learn things quick,''
Michigan safety DeWayne Patman said. ``If you want to be a great
defense you have to learn a lot of different coverages. It's a big
challenge going against another Heisman Trophy candidate. And we
accept this challenge. We wouldn't have it any other way: to have a
great running back come in and then have a great quarterback come
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Coach Lloyd Carr does not expect his defense to do to
Brees and Purdue what it did to Dayne and the Badgers' running
game. The one statistic Carr marvels at is one the Wolverine
defense must shatter if it hopes to contain Brees: the pass-happy
quarterback has only been sacked once.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have to play a perfect game to stop it, and even
then I don't know if you could stop it because there is too much
space between the defenders,'' Carr said of Purdue's offense. ``You
are spread out and they have enough speed to throw the ball deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr said to keep Brees off balance you have to mix up the
coverages and the pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most impressive thing about Purdue, in spite of all the
statistics passing, is the fact that Brees has only been sacked
once,'' Carr said. ``That speaks of his athleticism, his getting
the ball off quickly and the job the offensive line is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that will be the key to whether Purdue updates its record
books and continues on the road to the Rose Bowl. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3990 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BRAIN-SEMINARS-$A     10-01 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRAIN-SEMINARS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN `NEUROBICS' DO FOR THE BRAIN WHAT AEROBICS DO FOR LUNGS?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Calif., Fla., Mich.)  (af) 
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago, in chatting with a guest at the Holiday Inn she
manages in Binghamton, N.Y., Candace Jones found herself confiding
in him about her problems renovating the hotel and managing her
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The guest, Anthony Dottino, president of the Dottino Consulting
Group in Old Tappan, N.J., suggested that she let him take a crack
at solving the problems. Ms. Jones agreed, joining a list of
clients _ including IBM, Consolidated Edison, British Airways and
Johnson &AMP; Johnson _ that have sought Dottino's help with business
applications of brain research.
</P>
<P>
   Contending that managers need to make use of ``intellectual
capital,'' Dottino has created what he calls a comprehensive mental
literacy program to help employees unleash their creative energies.
``The human being has unlimited creativity if focused and nurtured
properly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he is far from alone. Although some neuroscientists dismiss
the trend, business people are increasingly using pop neurology or
``neurobics'' _ brain teasers, puzzles and cognitive exercises _ in
the belief that mental workouts enhance job performance, just as
aerobic workouts build fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baloney,'' said Dr. Michael Gruber, director of neuro-oncology
at New York University Medical Center, adding there was no
scientific evidence to support neurobics.
</P>
<P>
   His colleague, Dr. Carol Maxfield, a neuropsychologist in the
center's psychiatry department, conceded, however, that the new
brain programs might have a placebo effect on users. ``On a
psychological level, if someone does a group of exercises that they
really believe will help them concentrate, they just might,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Elizabeth Gould, a neurobiologist in Princeton
University's psychology department, said that while mental
exercises were likely to enhance brain functioning, ``reading,
playing the piano or doing any number of different hobbies that
don't involve passive participation are probably enough.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, William M. Jenkins, a former professor of
neuroscience at the University of California at San Francisco,
School of Medicine, has embraced the field, becoming vice president
for development at Scientific Learning, a company in Berkeley,
Calif., that uses brain research and technology to develop products
intended to enhance human learning and performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists have found that the brain is capable of altering
its connections,'' Jenkins said. ``The brain learns best through
associations, by linking new information to existing information in
synergistic fashion. You have the ability to change the synaptic
connections within the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Holiday Inn, Dottino met with the staff and encouraged
them to speak freely about their boss, while teaching them to draw
mind maps _ visual tools that resemble family trees but link words,
colors and pictures to express thoughts and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a map of thinking that one has on a particular topic,''
said Dottino, co-author of ``The Brain Smart Leader'' (Gower,
1999). ``It maps one's neural patterns, or thoughts, in an
associative and connected fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Ms. Jones' employees expressed feelings that her
managing style was too didactic and controlling and that she
treated them like children. Dottino invited her into the meeting,
and they then told her how they felt. ``It wasn't easy listening,
but it was a positive step because it forced me to come to grips
with things I needed to improve on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dottino came to neurobics after a career in financial and
executive management at IBM, and while he is not a neuroscientist,
he is a convincing and passionate speaker, whose clients point with
satisfaction to the results he has achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising sales through Oct. 1 at WMXJ, a Miami radio station,
for example, were 10 percent ahead of a year earlier, after the
station's employees worked on mind maps with Richard Israel, a
colleague of Dottino's, according to Dennis Collins, senior vice
president for the station.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bannon, former director of corporate accounting services
at IBM in Endicott, N.Y., recalled that the company was
restructuring and undergoing major layoffs when Dottino was doing
consulting work for IBM in 1992. ``Because of all the tension,
people were in a major state of paralysis,'' Bannon said.
</P>
<P>
   So he brought in Dottino, who had employees map their issues.
``The first time my boss saw me doing a mind map, he told me to
stop doodling,'' Bannon recalled. Nevertheless, he said, using
Dottino's methods, he was able to increase productivity in his
department enough to avoid more than two dozen planned job cuts in
the 18 months the consultant was there.
</P>
<P>
   Business people who want to test the idea of a mental workout
can do so easily without calling in a consultant. Numerous Web
sites offering memory- and attention-improving products have popped
up, including a mind map software program call Mind Manager
(www.mindmanager.com).
</P>
<P>
   Among the others are supermemo.com; brain.com; neurobics.com,
and enchantedmind.com, which presents a new set of puzzles weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia University School of Business has expressed
interest in Brain.com's services, especially Thinkfast, a series of
brain teasers and IQ tests.
</P>
<P>
   Al Thorrez, co-owner of Al Thorrez Industries, a maker of
automotive, tractor and office furniture parts in Jackson, Mich.,
was so impressed with Brain.com's products _ ``They increased my
decision-making and ability to think clearly,'' he said _ that he
invested in the company. He also said he had found its 12-minute IQ
test an effective way to screen job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Bannon, now controller at Maxtor, a disk drive maker in San
Jose, Calif., said, ``We've been taught that as we get older, we
lose our memory.'' But that need not be so, he contended. ``The
older you get, the more connections and associations your brain
should be making,'' he said, ``Therefore you should have more
information stored in your brain. You just need to tap into it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hill, a systems specialist at Con Edison, has similar
feelings. In the past, new employees at the company's nuclear power
plant in Buchanan, N.Y., were given thick notebooks; now they learn
with mind maps _ a great way to convey ``dry, boring material,''
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mind-mapping, mental skills and intellectual capital are the
things that will make the difference in the next 100 years,'' Hill
said. ``It's the wave of the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
