<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
EDS: Accompanied by SUBURBAN-GLANCE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The all-new 2000 Suburban, which made its worldwide public debut
at the State Fair of Texas, goes into production this month,
completely redesigned and much better.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles will begin arriving at Texas dealerships in
December, but the rest of the nation won't see them until January,
General Motors officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There might be some confusion among shoppers at GMC dealers,
however, because the new GMC version of the venerable Suburban has
a new name: Yukon XL.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban fans can rest assured that it's the same vehicle as the
one called Suburban at Chevy dealers. But GMC officials said they
felt it was time to call their vehicle something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be foolish on our part to continue spending
advertising dollars on a Chevrolet name, especially since they
already outsell us two to one,'' Yukon Brand Manager Denny
O'Donnell said during a recent media ride-and-drive program for the
new Yukons. ``That's sort of like McDonald's and Burger King both
selling the Whopper.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. Chevrolet and GMC are entities of the same
company. But I have often wondered why they would call the Suburban
the same thing under both the GMC and Chevrolet banners.
</P>
<P>
   What's important, though, is that the two vehicles are the same,
and they're bigger, more powerful and much more refined than
before. Considering that they were already very popular, especially
in Texas and California, which account for about half of their
sales, the big sport-utilities could be poised to take an even
larger share of the SUV market.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is only one competitor as big as the
Suburban/Yukon XL _ the all-new Ford Excursion (which is 7 inches
longer and about 2,000 pounds heavier than the Suburban) _ the
Suburban has been going head to head against the Ford Expedition
and its clone, the Lincoln Navigator, since the Expedition was
introduced in 1996. Expedition accounts for 35 percent of the sales
in the full-size SUV class in which Suburban is lumped.
</P>
<P>
   The new Suburban and Yukon XL are just slightly longer versions
of the Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon full-size SUVs. Until now, the
biggest difference was that only the Suburban came with a third
seat, but even that has changed for 2000. To help meet the
challenge from Expedition, which has always offered a third seat,
the extra seat now is available in the Tahoe and standard-length
Yukon.
</P>
<P>
   With that third seat in place, there is very little cargo space
in the shorter vehicles. To maintain ample cargo room with a third
seat, you have to go with the longer Suburban or Yukon XL.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior appearance of the big new SUVs is no surprise to
those who have seen the redesigned Chevy Silverado and GMC Sierra
full-size pickups introduced last year. From the back of the front
seat forward, the Suburban, Tahoe, Yukon and Yukon XL look
identical to their pickup counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   The new Suburban/Yukon XL is wider and taller than before, but
it's a fraction of an inch shorter, and it has a shorter turning
radius. That radius is nearly five feet less than that of the
Excursion. And, GM officials like to point out, the Suburban/Yukon
XL still fit nicely in a standard residential garage and a downtown
parking space.
</P>
<P>
   Those are definite advantages in the marketplace for the
Suburban, said Bruce Aiello, GM's assistant vehicle line manager
for full-size SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   ``During our marketing studies, no one asked us to make the
Suburban seven inches longer and 2,000 pounds heavier,'' he said.
``People did ask for us to make it roomier, and we have
delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Suburban and Yukon XL offer a choice of a full swing-up tailgate
or full-height double doors that open to the sides, just like the
previous models. There is no price differential.
</P>
<P>
   Two new Vortec V-8 engines are offered in the Suburban and Yukon
XL, and they are more powerful and more durable than ever, GM
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The base engine, standard on the half-ton Suburban and Yukon XL,
is a 5.3-liter V-8 rated at 285 horsepower and 325 foot-pounds of
torque. That's 30 more horsepower than the 5.7- liter V-8 that it
replaces.
</P>
<P>
   Standard on the heavier 3/4-ton models is a 6.0-liter V-8 with
300 horsepower and 355 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   These engines give the new Suburban and Yukon XL higher tow
ratings and allow for higher gross weight capacities. Despite the
Excursion's bigger size and engines, the Suburban and Yukon XL
still outrank it in towing capacity. Maximum trailer weight with
the 5.3-liter engine is 9,000 pounds; with the 6.0-liter engine,
that climbs to 10,500 pounds (500 more than Excursion).
</P>
<P>
   Four-speed automatic transmissions are standard, and they have
been improved to provide more durability, GM said.
</P>
<P>
   Ride and handling are better, steering response is improved, the
body and frame are stiffer than last year's, and there are choices
of suspensions offered. The ride is much smoother and more carlike
than that of the Excursion, which is built on the chassis of Ford's
Super Duty pickup line.
</P>
<P>
   An option is the new Autoride suspension, which automatically
varies the amount of shock-absorber action to provide the same
level of control and stability whether the vehicle is empty or
loaded, or pulling a trailer. Half-ton models with this suspension
have an automatic rear leveling system that uses compressed air.
</P>
<P>
   The interior has improved dramatically. For the first time,
automatic climate control is offered, and the air-conditioning
vents are easy adjusted for direction. The front bucket seats are
very comfortable, and rear passengers get more leg and head room.
</P>
<P>
   Power windows and door locks are standard, and the door locks
can be programmed four ways to allow for automatic or manual
locking and unlocking.
</P>
<P>
   Shoulder belts on the front and third-row seats are attached to
the back of the seat rather than the side walls so they don't ride
up on the neck, a major point of irritation for occupants in many
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Among the safety features are four-wheel antilock brakes, front
and side air bags for the front seats, telescoping front frame
rails designed to absorb energy in a frontal collision, and
energy-absorbing foam inside the interior trim to help protect the
driver and passengers' heads during a collision.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban's three trim levels are the base model, the midlevel LS
and the top-of-the-line LT. The LT comes with leather interior and
automatic climate control, among other amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Yukon XL comes in two trim levels: the base model is the SLE,
and the high-end one is the SLT, which includes leather interior.
You have to choose a ``luxury convenience package'' to add the
automatic climate control.
</P>
<P>
   Both vehicles are offered in two- or four-wheel-drive in all
configurations. GM says about 65 percent of all sales are expected
to be four-wheel drive models. But in Texas, probably only about 20
percent of buyers will choose four-wheel drive, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-inch wheels are standard, and available designs include
chromed steel and polished, brushed or painted aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings were not provided, but you should
expect a range of 12-16 miles per gallon based on previous
performance of these vehicles. The tank holds 26 gallons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
