<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EX-MILITANT-RELEASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATHERINE ANN POWER FINISHES JAIL TERM IN 1970 KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Katherine Ann Power haunted Clare Schroeder for years.
She would stare at Power's face on the FBI's Most Wanted List,
puzzled at the face staring back.
</P>
<P>
   The wispy bangs and thick eyeglasses, the chunky-toothed smile,
belied Power's militant, rebellious side. For 23 years, Schroeder
prayed police would find Power, who vanished after her involvement
in the 1970 shooting death of Schroeder's father, a Boston police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when Power gave herself up, Schroeder finally got what
she wanted: to see Power in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   But today, as Power is released from prison in Framingham,
Schroeder says she is no closer to forgiving Power than she was the
day she fled Boston. But she hopes that Power is sincere when she
says she was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what forgiveness is in this circumstance,''
Schroeder said. ``I'm not going to extract any vengeance. I don't
wish her ill will. Other than that, she has no significance for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The day Walter Schroeder died, Sept. 24, 1970, the lives of both
women _ the victim's eldest daughter and the fugitive _
dramatically changed.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the two women have been entwined in the minds of
anyone who looks at the bank robbery shooting as a reflection of a
tumultuous time, when youthful activism blurred into the realm of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since Power turned herself in, Clare Schroeder, 46,
has struggled to understand Power's actions as a renegade driver of
the getaway car, the woman who spirited away the man who shot her
father in the back, before getting away with $26,000 in cash. And
Power has had to come to grips with her past, with living 23 years
as a lie. She surrendered, Power later said, because her conscience
was eating away at her.
</P>
<P>
   Only in prison, after years of therapy did Power come to terms
with her guilt, Power told a parole board in March 1998, after
withdrawing her request for release.
</P>
<P>
   ``My work in prison has been to peel off the layers of that
defensiveness, to get to the point where I could look squarely into
the pained, accusing faces of the victims of my crime and say, `I
was wrong. I was wrong all along. Before God I am sorry. I will
always be so sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, she issued a similar statement: ``Today marks the
payment of my legal debt for my role in the murder of Walter
Schroeder. But I will always carry my human responsibility for the
sorrow my actions have caused. As I noted in my parole statement of
March, 1998, I do not intend to cultivate media attention to my
feelings, to my problems, or to what the media see as my `drama.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time to acknowledge that a human life, once lost, is
lost forever: that the death of a father, husband, and brother is a
terrible event, and one for which I will always be deeply sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clare Schroeder tightened her grip on the phone, agitated at the
stranger babbling about wanting to save her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I go to the hospital to donate blood? Do you think it
will save your father?'' the man repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, a senior at Mount St. Joseph Academy, remembers his
words swarming like mosquitoes; she couldn't process them.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, her mother walked into the house, with such a hollow
sadness in her eyes, that, with just one glance, Schroeder knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to worry about donating blood,'' she bluntly
spoke into the receiver. ``My father is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   From that day forward, Schroeder was no longer just big sis to
her eight brothers and sisters. She took on more and more
responsibilities, helping her mother cope with the cooking, the
cleaning, the disciplining.
</P>
<P>
   Her family moved to a quiet street in Waltham, away from the
Brighton neighborhood where there were too many reminders. But they
couldn't get away from the memories, or the reporters who always
asked the same question: ``Where is Katherine Power?''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's mother, Marie, a very private woman, would not talk
to the media, so it fell on her. She became the family
spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke when Power became the longest woman to remain on the
FBI's Ten Most Wanted List. When the FBI took her off the list,
media crews flocked to her doorstep. Every time rumors surfaced
about Power being found, every time media did the `Whatever
happened to Katherine Ann Power?' story, Schroeder spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   She kept tabs on the investigation, especially after she became
a cop herself. Following in her father's footsteps, she joined the
Waltham police force after graduating from Regis College.
</P>
<P>
   The day of Power's sentencing, Schroeder met with Boston Police
Lieutenant Timothy Murray of the Cold Case Squad. He showed her his
files, the places throughout the country he thought Power might be.
Just a few months before Power surrendered, Schroeder said Murray
had compiled a list of 300 names _ all possible aliases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice Metzinger was on that list,'' said Schroeder. ``I'm
convinced he would've tracked her down. He's a phenomenal
investigator.''
</P>
<P>
   As a detective, Schroeder made a living trying to understand
criminal minds. But understanding Power seemed to be as elusive as
finding her.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she came to this conclusion: That Power arrogantly
believed her cause justified her illegal, immoral behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a group of young idealists whose goal was peace
and harmony,'' Schroeder told the parole board two years ago.
``These people were experienced career criminals whose only goal
was to reap profit for themselves regardless of the consequences to
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people protested the war in Vietnam. They would
perform acts of civil disobedience, they burned draft cards, and
did a lot of things, but they didn't steal guns and rob banks,''
she said. ``To me, it's hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder doesn't want to relive the past, and says that she
never let anger consume her. She looks at Power's release as the
end of a chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied in that she's fulfilled what the state requires
of her,'' Schroeder said. ``The length of time served is
irrelevant. It doesn't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Ann Power stood in her Beacon Street studio hours
after the bank robbery, surrounded by a stash of rifles, shotguns,
and grenades.
</P>
<P>
   She kept the radio on, and heard the news: ``Boston Police
Officer Walter Schroeder has been shot...''
</P>
<P>
   Her group's plan _ to rob $26,000 from the State Street Bank in
Brighton to fund their antiwar campaign _ crossed the line of
militant activism to terrorism. A day later Schroeder died and now
murder hung over their heads. Power and the four others went
underground.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, police caught her accomplices: Robert Valeri within
hours, William ``Lefty'' Gilday and Stanley Bond within days. Five
years later, the FBI nabbed Susan Saxe. But Katherine Ann Power
continued to elude police, year after year.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen, Power semed a model citizen in the making. She was
valedictorian of her Denver high school, the product of Catholic
schools, the daughter of Winfield Power, a banker, and Marjorie
Power, a nurse. As a teen, she won a Betty Crocker Homemaker Award
for her sewing and cooking skills. But later, on the campus of
Brandeis University, she became a fervent crusader against US
involvement in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, though, she found herself at its violent fringes. She
hooked up with Stanley Bond, an ex-con with a seventh-grade
education who charmed his way into Brandeis through a government
program for parolees. Together with Bond, a violent thief who spent
time in Walpole State Prison, they became a 60s version of Bonnie
and Clyde, robbing several banks, and even breaking into a National
Guard Armory in Newburyport, to steal a cachet of weapons to use in
their antiwar campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, after careful planning, Bond, Saxe, Gilday,
and Valeri stormed the State Street Bank, armed with high-powered
guns. Power _ who later said she was not considered dependable
enough to join the others inside the bank _ waited in a humming
Ford stationwagon six blocks away. Her accomplices rode by in the
getaway car, a blue Chevy, and hopped into the ``switch'' car.
Gilday remained behind, where, unbeknownst to the others, he shot
Officer Schroeder in the back, piercing his aorta. He bled to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Power was on the run, changing identities several times
before settling in rural Oregon as Alice Metzinger, wife,
restaurateur, mother.
</P>
<P>
   After serving six years of an 8- to 12-year prison term at MCI
Framingham, less time for good behavior, Power walks out of prison
and can finally be herself again. No more fake identities. No more
lies.
</P>
<P>
   But everywhere she goes, she knows a spotlight will be on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she leaves she hopes to leave the legal system behind,''
said her attorney, James M. Doyle. ``She does not want to be a
celebrity. It's that kind of human interest in her that detracts
from the enormity of the crime she committed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
