<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POKEMON CRAZE JUST KEEPS GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Kate Speck is a Pok-e-chick.
</P>
<P>
   She collects Pokemon game cards, saving her modest allowance _ a
buck a week _ to splurge.
</P>
<P>
   She watches Pokemon on TV. She has Pokemon stuffed animals.
Pokemon books. Even a Pokemon keychain. And Kate will croon a giddy
tune based on, well, you know, the P-word.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and there was the time Kate's buddy Mia had a birthday
party and Kate gave a gift of Pokemon cards and Mia opened the deck
and _ oh brother! _ inside was this sparkly Pokemon card Kate
wanted really, really BAAAD!!!
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I didn't ask her for it,'' Kate says, the sound of
gentle longing in her voice. ``I mean, it was her birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough.
</P>
<P>
   Kate's mom is a cardiologist and her dad's a writer, but not
even their combined brain power can figure out why Kate _ a
self-described ``average'' fanatic at 8 _ goes bonkers over a tiny
yellow Pokemon creature with a name that sounds like a sneeze:
Pikachu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep telling them what I like about it,'' the Seattle girl
giggles. ``They just don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Duh.
</P>
<P>
   But plenty of young people do get it _ and they are eating up
the Pokemon cultural feast of video games, trading cards, a
television show, comic books, T-shirts, soundtracks and notebooks.
The menu keeps growing.
</P>
<P>
   There are Pokemon leagues. Pokemon tournaments. Pokemon
contests. Pokemon Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, a full-length Pokemon movie hits the big screen; toy
experts say Pokemon will be THE THING for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo _ which is to be lauded or blamed for hatching Pokemon
_ even serves up training tours, aimed at teaching kids how to
develop skills and ``train how to battle'' for Pokemon tournaments
using Game Boys, Nintendo's hand-held video-game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   They also feature a card-trading area and a chance for players
to become (drumroll, please) Pokemon master trainers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, when the 19-city training tour rolled to
the Mall of America in Minneapolis, it was a big hit _ 44,000
people showed up. (Music's 'N Sync and Shania Twain only drew
20,000 each in concerts!)
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon _ short for ``pocket monsters'' _ began in the mid-1990s
in Japan as a video game from Nintendo. In the game, a player
captures, nurtures or improves 150 different kinds of Pokemon
creatures that have Harry Potter-ish sounding names (Pikachu or
Paras, anyone?).
</P>
<P>
   The Pokemon are divided into different types _ including
``fire,'' ``water'' or ``ground.'' Depending on their type, some
Pokemon creatures are more suited to kick the Poke-butt of another.
</P>
<P>
   In both the video and trading-card versions of the game, players
seek to get as many Pokemon as they can _ thus the motto ``gotta
catch 'em all.''
</P>
<P>
   But because some video cartridges _ as well as card sets _ have
a specified number of premium characters, some Pokemon are harder
to get. So players must interact with other players, igniting
feverish swapping.
</P>
<P>
   When Pokemon came to the United States, it arrived first as a
cartoon show in 1998. Then it moved into card games, video games
and other areas _ fanned by companies with licensing agreements to
issue Pokemon products.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy marketing has worked like a dream: The TV show introduced
characters, which piqued interest in the video game, which in turn
set the tables for the trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   This year alone, Pokemon products are projected to generate $700
million in U.S. retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest licensing companies is Wizards of the Coast
Inc., a Renton, Wash.-based company that publishes trading/game
cards. The company has sold more than 2 millon of the two-player
starter sets since their release in January 1999, and has been
pressed by high demands.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks Pokemon is grand. Reports have
crisscrossed the country of school kids getting Pokemon cards
stolen; trading cards instead of doing homework; pressing parents
for Pokemon purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Kate said at her school, University Child Development School,
teachers issued a no-card rule after kids who had them made kids
who did not feel left out on the playground.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people still talk about the cards,'' Kate says.
</P>
<P>
   Kate _ who is a big Beanie Baby collector and has taken part in
a girl youth ski group called Chicks on Stix ( the``X'' represents
crossed skis) _ likes Pikachu because he is cute and packs a punch
_ a tiny shock that stuns other Pokemon characters. She cracks up
just talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawyers have serious problems with Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   In federal court in San Diego last month, attorneys filed a suit
on behalf of four parents who allege Pokemon trading cards promote
a form of illegal gambling. That's because only through chance can
players get the premium cards randomly inserted in packs, the
lawyers contend.
</P>
<P>
   The suit said wrapping on the card packs put the odds of getting
a premium card at 1 in 33; the premium cards have a resale value of
more than $70 each, compared to $3 to $10 for an unopened pack of
11 cards, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo attorneys said similar suits have been filed against
sports trading-card makers, without success.
</P>
<P>
   Kids, however, aren't sweating it. And Pokemon popularity is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Zyduck started watching Pokemon on TV after he heard a
news story about flashing lights in a Pokemon cartoon had sent
schoolchildren in Japan to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``So naturally, this piqued my curiosity,'' he wrote on the
Internet. ``But it's been strangely addicting. I started watching
it before I had to go to school. ... Now I'm hooked. And strangely
enough, I found someone at school who watches that show, too. And
we're in high school, man. High school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
