<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leadership Training With a Stellar Professor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brand names are well known to business school professors, but
only one professor is a brand name herself. Call her Professor
Oprah. Oprah Winfrey began her pedagogical career at the highest
levels on Tuesday, teaching a course in ``Dynamics of Leadership''
to second-year MBA students at Northwestern University's Kellogg
Graduate School of Management in Evanston, Ill. Actually, she is
the co-teacher, with her beau, the marketing consultant Stedman
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Oprah Winfrey Show'' itself has turned from
celebrities to spiritualism, with ``gratitude journals'' and ways
to ``remember your spirit,'' the 110 students in course G26 got
down to cases in the first session _ starting with Katharine Graham
and the Washington Post Co.
</P>
<P>
   The host of the ``change your life'' television talk show is her
own case study in entrepreneurial dynamism: Actress. Book promoter.
Movie producer. Charity organizer. And publisher of a new, as yet
unnamed Hearst Magazines title.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight. The university urged students not to divulge
even the course syllabus, though it is available for purchase at
the student bookstore. It promises that students will ``increase
their capacity to enhance their performance potential,'' ``improve
self-awareness'' and ``develop a detailed plan to turn vision into
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it very seriously,'' the professor said on her way into
class with Graham, ``because both of us care very much about
leadership in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere Mrs. Duncan, my fourth grade teacher, is very happy
today,'' she added. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Bill Dedman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Woman Takes the Helm? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Partners at Baker &AMP; McKenzie, which with 2,400 lawyers is
America's largest law firm, will vote this week to elect a new
chairman. Only one lawyer, Christine Lagarde, has been nominated
for the job of managing the firm, based in Chicago but with offices
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Lagarde is elected, she will become the first woman to
lead any of the 20 largest law firms in the nation. Insiders say
her election is virtually a done deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Melody Petersen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Criticism on a Different Runway &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Ralph Lauren learned that his sense of fashion
doesn't please quite everyone. He had entered one of his cars, a
black 1938 Bugatti 57SC Atlantic, in the Louis Vuitton Classic, an
annual concours d'elegance, or beauty pageant for antique cars, at
Rockefeller Center. One of only four of its type ever made, this
Bugatti has a magnesium alloy body so difficult to weld that it is
held together by a prominent riveted spine. It's the Batmobile's
sinister older brother.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren was there on Saturday to show off his car _ call it the
Polomobile _ which, like others in his collection, has served as a
prop in his advertisements. He was absent on Sunday, attending a
sister's birthday party, when the Bugatti was proclaimed best of
show. Poised to roll down a street converted to a carpeted runway
to receive a trophy, however, it wouldn't start.
</P>
<P>
   Once it did get rumbling, the jury chairman, Murray Livingstone
Smith, a partner in Bozell Worldwide, responded like an automotive
fashion critic. Noting that the car was not black before Lauren
bought it, he loudly appealed for a return to the original color,
saying ``Please. Paint it blue.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to Smith's appeal, a Lauren spokeswoman laughed,
saying: ``You're serious? And it still won best of show?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staying in Toyland &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When your own house is on fire, it's no time to be lingering
down the block at the neighbors'. And so Jill E. Barad, chief
executive of Mattel, said last week that she would not seek
re-election to the Microsoft board, which she joined in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when corporate boards strive for diversity, her
departure would leave the Microsoft board without a woman. The
board, relatively small with just six members left, has no plans to
add others.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's stock slid on Friday, reaching its lowest level since
1995. The stock has slumped as children have set aside their Barbie
dolls and other Mattel toys in favor of computers and electronic
games.
</P>
</TEXT>
