<SLUG> BC-WTO-BARSHEFSKY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION OFFICIALS WILL MEET WTO CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House will invite critics of the World
Trade Organization to meet with high-ranking Clinton administration
officials this month, and President Clinton is hoping to make a
major speech defending his trade policy before this fall's meeting
of the World Trade Organization in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings and the speech were promised in a letter from U.S.
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky to Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which Murray released to the news media Friday, was
dated Thursday, and followed news reports about a previously
unanswered Aug. 5 letter from Murray to Clinton in which the
senator suggested that the president needs to do more to reach out
to labor and environmentalists concerned about the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefksy, who said she was asked by Clinton to respond, wrote,
``I want to assure you that the White House and USTR (the U.S.
Trade Representative's office) are actively working with labor,
environmental, consumer and other non-governmental organizations
that have concerns regarding the WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said that during the past six months, her office has
``consulted extensively'' with such organizations about the U.S.
agenda for the ministerial meeting in Seattle, which is scheduled
to run from Nov. 30 through Dec. 3. And, she said, ``these
consultations will continue during October as many of these groups
will be invited to the White House to meet with senior-level
Administration officials for comment on our Seattle proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky said the meeting in Seattle will be more open than
any previous WTO meeting. She cited the WTO's decision to agree to
a U.S. request for a symposium in Seattle Nov. 29 at which groups
with concerns about the WTO will be invited to address the world's
trade ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who has been concerned by reports of potentially
disruptive protests planned by critics of the WTO, had urged
Clinton to make a speech to the nation defending global trade. In
response to that request, Barshefsky wrote ``the White House is
looking for an appropriate opportunity for him to deliver such a
speech.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barshefsky also pointed to several comments Clinton has
already made this summer pledging to support trade agreements that
``enhance labor standards and environmental protection all across
the world,'' as he said in a speech in Chicago in June.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said she was pleased by the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and the ministerial, we will see a concerted
effort by the administration to promote U.S. and Washington state
trade interests,'' she said. ``The administration is also stepping
up its efforts to work with the labor and environmental
communities. This is very encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor and environmental groups, long critical of the World Trade
Organization for paying too little attention to global working and
environmental conditions, have become increasingly critical of the
Clinton administration for not pushing more aggressively to make
sure that trade agreements don't harm workers or the environment.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference this week, five major environmental groups
said that the Administration's trade agenda has not matched
Clinton's rhetoric, and called on the Administration to alter its
agenda for the Seattle meeting to give a higher priority to
evaluating how trade agreements affect the environment. Labor
leaders want the administration to push for greater enforcement of
agreements by WTO members to allow workers around the world to
unionize and to prohibit child labor.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents of WTO said they were still not satisfied when
told of the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access is not the same thing as influence,'' said Daniel
Seligman, responsible trade program director at the Sierra Club.
``While the U.S. Trade Representative has been talking to the
environmental community, there's precious little indication that
their approach to the summit has changed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky's office did not return a call to discuss the letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
