A4053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-U.S.-NUKE-440&AMP;ADD-NYT     10-01 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-NUKE-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME U.S. PLANTS VULNERABLE TO NUCLEAR MISHAP LIKE JAPAN'S
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., R.I., N.M., Idaho, Wash., Tenn.)   (See also JAPAN-NUKE) 
(bl) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Friday told the Energy and
Defense departments to review the safety of civilian nuclear fuel
processing, but experts inside and outside government said that the
Energy Department itself owns the plants that are most vulnerable
to an accidental chain reaction like the one in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The only commercial plant in the United States to ever
experience such a reaction was in Charlestown, R.I., in 1964. But
the Energy Department and its predecessor agency, the Atomic Energy
Commission, suffered six such reactions from 1958 to 1978,
including three at the Idaho Chemical Processing Plant, near Idaho
Springs, Idaho, one at the Y-12 plant, near Oak Ridge, Tenn., one
at Hanford, near Richland, Wash., and one at Los Alamos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Five people died in those incidents, in which uranium or
plutonium was accidentally assembled into a critical mass, starting
a chain reaction that created a shower of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Energy Department, there have been a total of
21 inadvertent ``criticalities'' in the United States, the Soviet
Union and Britain, of which 20 involved nuclear materials in liquid
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a statement, said, ``We've been providing
information to Japan on our experiences in dealing with similar
incidents in the United States, and making available our experts in
atmospheric monitoring and any other areas that might be useful.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the seven commercial plants licensed by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission process uranium that is 3 percent to 5
percent U-235, the type that sustains a chain reaction. The
accident in Japan involved a mixture enriched to 19 percent U-235,
meaning a smaller volume would suffice for a chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   One commercial plant, in Lynchburg, Va., owned by Framatome
Cogema Fuels, handles uranium that is more than 90 percent U-235,
for naval propulsion reactors.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the uranium solutions used in the United States
are a different chemistry from the mixture in Japan, but a critical
mass can occur with any of a variety of different chemical
mixtures. But in the United States the commercial plants have an
advantage because they perform the same activities over and over,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Energy Department, Dr. David Michaels, the assistant
secretary of energy for environment, safety and health, said the
weapons program once had that benefit, when it was in steady
production. ``We recognize this overall vulnerability, going from
doing the same thing every day in the production operation, to
cleanup, which is a more dynamic activity,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Now the department is trying to clean out tanks that have been
sitting for months or years, with materials whose volume, content
or concentration must be carefully measured and calculated.
</P>
<P>
   Liquids are the most prone to flow into containers where they
will assume a shape and volume that can support a chain reaction,
as happened in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials acknowledge that over time, their ability
to deal with the problem has declined. A government panel of
independent experts chartered by Congress to advise on the safety
of the Energy Department's weapons production process, the Defense
Nuclear Facilities Safety Board, said in a recommendation in May
1997, that at many Energy Department plants, ``The typical
criticality safety staff consists mainly of individuals who have no
prior first-hand experience in criticality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They lack background in neutron physics on a fundamental
level, and are not familiar with work on assembles near a critical
state, activities that would foster intuitive approaches to
criticality control,'' said the report, which was written as the
department was considering closing its last criticality safety
training laboratory, as a cost-saving measure. The department kept
it open, but board members are still concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Herbert J.C. Kouts, a member of the board and former senior
scientist at Brookhaven National Laboratory, in Upton, N.Y., said
in a speech in August that two of the accidents, one at Los Alamos
National Laboratory and the other in Rhode Island, ``occurred
during cleanup of waste containing fissile material, an activity
that is now taking place at a number of the facilities for the
Department of Energy.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the public once accepted occasional nuclear mishaps,
Kouts said, ``in the most general way, a criticality accident is
now a complete no-no.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Kouts said, making the rules stricter to avoid criticality
problems is not itself the answer, because workers may happen to
break rules without causing an accident, and then ``develop a
contempt for the limits.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a special problem with ``orphan material,'' which is
nuclear material left over from experiments or projects from years
ago, said Robert Alvarez, a former senior advisor to the energy
secretary. Much of the department's clean-up work is driven by
agreements with state governments, he said, and if the orphan
material is not covered in such an agreement, it is often
neglected.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ``criticality safety is rapidly atrophying
for lack of priority attention, because the front office doesn't
understand that this is one of the things that makes up the heart
and soul of nuclear safety.''
</P>
<P>
   But department officials said that they have intermittently shut
down plants for months at a time when they have found criticality
problems, and they recently discovered that they have ordered a
cumulative total of seven and a half years of shutdowns since 1994.
Partly for that reason, they organized the workshop at which Kouts
spoke in August.
</P>
<P>
   At the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, which licenses the seven
commercial nuclear fuel processing plants, spokeswoman Sue Gagner
said, ``Right now, we have not instituted any changes.'' The NRC
inspects each plant twice yearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We require that they have at least two safety measures to
prevent criticality,'' she said. These could include such
precautions as regulating the size or shape of containers to
configurations that could not support criticality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
