<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANS JOIN JEWS IN FESTIVAL OF SUCCOTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With parades and prayer services, some 5,000
evangelical Christian pilgrims descended on the Holy City this week
to take part in the Jewish harvest festival of Succoth.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian visitors _ mostly from America and Europe _ are
part of a growing fringe evangelical movement that embraces a
militant belief in Zionism and sees a biblical connection between
the emergence of a strong Israeli state and the Second Coming of
Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian believers were easy to pick out among the usual
tourists and throngs of Jewish worshipers gathering for prayers at
the Western Wall. They were the ones wearing pendants with a
Christian cross in the center of a Star of David. One group had
T-shirts that read ``Oklahoma is for Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The group began gathering in the desert a week ago at Ein Gedi,
80 miles southeast of Jerusalem, under the full moon that marked
the beginning of Succoth, or the Feast of Tabernacles. On Tuesday,
Christian representatives from more than 100 nations joined
thousands of Israelis in a ``Unity of Jerusalem'' march in an
annual parade to affirm Jews' ancient claim to the city.
</P>
<P>
   To the bemusement of many Israelis, the Christian marchers
passed along the ancient Herodian walls of the Old City in various
forms of traditional dress _ from Native Americans in fringed
buckskin and leather shields emblazoned with the Star of David to
natives of Tahiti in grass skirts.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian evangelicals' presence at the march is nothing
new. This is the 20th year that the International Christian Embassy
of Jerusalem has organized the pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that God gave this land to the Jews, and that their
ingathering here will bring about the return of our Lord, and that
that time is at hand,'' said Geraldine Kendall, 69, of Tampa, Fla.,
as she prepared for the final prayer vigil lastnight to mark the
end of the feast.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20 years it has been operating in Israel, the Christian
Embassy has flourished into a political force, with some 70
employees, foreign offices, and an $8 million annual budget, about
half from contributions by American evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   The group's Washington office has become known as a political
lobbying group for Israel's rightist Likud Party and has worked
tirelessly in support of Israeli settlements in the West Bank and
Gaza and on the campaign to move the American Embassy from Tel Aviv
to Jerusalem. The Christian Embassy has also been a fierce critic
of the underlying premise of the Mideast peace process, under which
Israel would cede land captured in 1967 to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Olmert, Jerusalem's mayor and a leader of Likud, praised
the visitors as ``the most wonderful guests that this city has.''
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the group was fawned over by former Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Likud, who delivered thundering
speeches at its gatherings. But this year, newly elected Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of the more liberal Labor Party declined an
invitation to speak, which the organizers saw as a deliberate snub.
</P>
<P>
   The group's assiduous support of Israel grows out of a
fundamentalist belief that the ``ingathering'' of Jews in Israel
will prepare the way for the the Second Coming and Judgment Day.
Their rhetoric is often apocalyptic, and many speakers at a series
of seminars in Jerusalem demonized the Arab population.
</P>
<P>
   One, Gary Cooperberg, an Israeli who led a tour of his militant
settlement of Kiryat Arba, went so far as to tell the audience that
if Palestinians threw stones at his car he would shoot to kill
them.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of this largely Western group of Christian
evangelicals and their zealous support of Jewish settlements in the
West Bank and of extreme rightist views in Israel is not welcomed
by the indigenous Palestinian Christian population. The Palestinian
Christians deeply resent the evangelicals claiming to represent
``the Christian community'' in support of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Naim Ateek, a Palestinian Christian leader and theologian
who was uprooted from his home in the 1948 Israeli-Arab war, said
he was annoyed that the group did not seek out the views of local
Palestinians or bother to hear how Palestinian Christian
communities, which he said date back 2,000 years, have ``suffered
under Israeli occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it seems as if they are reading a different Bible,
twisting scripture to fit their own jigsaw puzzle,'' he said.
``They are not for the peace process, which seems unbelievable to
me, since the central focus of the Christian faith is to work for
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   David Parsons, the organizer of the event and a spokesman for
the International Christian Embassy of Jerusalem, said the
Christian presence for the feast had a ``special prophetic
significance.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited Old Testament passages from prophet Zechariah in which
God promises to ``gather all nations against Jerusalem'' and to
usher in the messiah and a final day of judgment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
