<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4060 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ART-CONTROVERSY-TEX     10-01 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-CONTROVERSY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACON EXHIBIT SIZZLES WITH CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone once intoned that the first casualty of war is truth.
Rejiggering that sentiment, one might now warn that the primary
loss in an arts controversy is the art.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fort Worth school district, responding to parental
complaints, canceled elementary and middle school field trips to
the Modern Art Museum's Francis Bacon exhibit in September, there
was breathless talk of the show's homosexual references, its
displays of frontal nudity and its being ``emotionally charged''
and not ``age-appropriate.'' There were reports of students seeing
the exhibit and suffering sleepness nights, their heads filled with
nagging questions.
</P>
<P>
   Those accounts only make clear that the Bacon exhibition did its
job of stimulating emotion and provoking debate. What the
field-trip cancellations achieved was to link the exhibit to such
perennial hot-button issues as policing of museums (a distant
cousin of censorship), the effects of art on fragile young psyches,
and how discriminating schools should be when exposing students to
art that isn't predictably classical.
</P>
<P>
   For the Modern Art Museum, this little dust-up is too
reminiscent of a previous flap. A year ago, some schools nixed
student tours of the museum exhibit ``Self-Taught Artists of the
20th Century: An American Anthology,'' outraged over its depictions
of copulation and hermaphroditic imagery. Currently, a moralistic
crusade against scrofulous art is under way in that bastion of
cultural openness, New York. Gotham Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has
threatened to shut the spigot on $7 million in city contributions
to the Brooklyn Museum of Art unless it cancels the opening of the
Saatchi collection of young British artists. That exhibition
features a shark suspended in formaldehyde and a portrait of the
Virgin Mary adorned with elephant feces.
</P>
<P>
   Now whether the marriage of elephant excrement to religious
subjects is art at all must be open for debate. Such heated
discourse should mark any society encouraging freedom of
expression. But financial blackmail of a museum, or the
</P>
<P>
   barring of fifth-grade schoolchildren from viewing an art
exhibit during a school-sponsored event _ especially when many
parents didn't agree with the decision _ inflicts a black eye on
any open-minded society.
</P>
<P>
   But what has been lost amid all the high-dudgeon indignation
over what children should see is exactly what it is they actually
experience at an art exhibit. The Francis Bacon show offers a
selection of his surreal and, yes, nihilistic, excursions into
various worlds. But what an eclectic world tour he leads, careening
from an imperious pope to an inscrutable Sphinx in Egypt, to the
wind-whipped fields of southern France or an elephant lolling in a
South African marsh. These are cultural postcards that any
land-locked 12-year-old could benefit from.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bacon's color choices, many of the exhibition's
detractors chose to fixate on his use of the blood-red often used
to paint, well, blood. But this is a cheap shot because it ignores
the enormous palette Bacon worked in, employing everything from
burnt umber to the lavender of a Vatican robe. There is sun-kissed
orange for Bacon's loving study of van Gogh or lemon-zest for his
cubist take on painter Lucian Freud.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Bacon did relish the more saturnine shades of pewter
gray and cobalt blue when doing his self-portraits, but those tints
are not more sinister than the somber clothes favored by any number
of youngsters and goth-inspired Bohemians. In fact, Bacon's color
and thematic choices owe much to Halloween and Grimm's Fairy Tales
by way of Salvador Dali, Andy Warhol, Diego Velazquez and Jean
Auguste Dominique Ingres. Last time anyone checked, no one was
prohibiting children from experiencing those great masters.
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't legislated anywhere that children should avert
their eyes from Bacon's favored territory: painterly expressions of
angst and melancholy, the baleful moments in a non-Disneyfied life.
No parent should fear their children departing on momentary trips
into somber artistic country and returning to decipher them
afterward. Kids are making these mind-expanding journeys every day
by watching television and surfing the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Certain parents objected most vociferously to their children
viewing some of Francis Bacon's nudes. True, in an exhibition
spanning more than 50 works, approximately 5 or 10 percent involve
nudity. But those are not photo-realistic portraits, but amorphous,
Henry Moore-like forms, bulbous relatives to Picasso's cubist
renditions. Bacon's nudes are either blurry (''Study for a Nude'')
or sketchy outlines (''Reclining Figure,'' where splayed legs
reveal a smudge of color suggesting either genitalia or a fig
leaf.)
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, some fifth-graders confessed that several of
Bacon's nudes made them feel as if their bodies were ugly. That
echoes how most adolescent girls feel looking at the anorexic
supermodels in ``Vogue.'' Again, no school has barred kids from
those fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The Bacon exhibit also repelled some parents with its wall-text
descriptions of the homosexual relationship between Bacon and
George Dyer. How ironic that the paintings of Dyer are models of
prissy decorum. ``Portrait of George Dyer Talking'' and ``Study of
George Dyer'' aren't smutty body worship but show a man with primly
crossed legs. Within the catalog of homoerotic art, with
Michelangelo's ``David'' as its paradigm icon, Bacon's work is
extremely tame.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a shame if the balanced and invigorating Bacon
exhibit should be bruised by the Fort Worth school boycott. To
cordon off youngsters from an exhibit of one of the acknowledged
masters of 20th-century surrealism is, at best, a misguided attempt
to circumscribe the cultural intake of preteens. And that can only
hamper their ability to absorb, comprehend, and, yes, savor the
unsettling nature of good art.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
