<HEADLINE>
NICOL BEGINS REVOLUTION RESCUE MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Before this season, Walter Zenga had been
the symbol of Revolution success. But lately Zenga has been
associated with the team's failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution almost completely collapsed in the second half of
the MLS season, and Zenga could not save them either as player or
coach. Now, the job has been given to Scotsman Steve Nicol, who
will guide the Revolution against the MetroStars in the final home
game of the regular season Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nicol, a former star with Liverpool in England, has been in
Boston since April, when he arrived to be a player-assistant coach
for the Bulldogs in the A League. Nicol played for the Bulldogs in
a 2-1 exhibition loss to the Revolution in Framingham May 5 and has
been observing the Revs most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is that they haven't played as a team,''
Nicol said after conducting his first practice Friday.
``Individually, the players can play with any team in the league,
but they've fallen down when it comes to team play. We need to
harness that individual talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coach has to come up with new ways, new ideas, give pointers
to show a team that's the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Nicol has high-level credentials as a player and has
performed for extremely prominent teams in Europe, he has kept a
low profile. Nicol's speech is economic and he has remained in the
background since arriving in the United States. Nicol succeeded
John Kerr as player-coach of the Bulldogs for the final two games
of the season, both losses.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Zenga was always the center of attention, leading
the Revolution to their only playoff berth as a goalkeeper in 1997
and regularly in conflicts with fans, the press, and referees as a
player-coach this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to be working with the players the Revolution have,''
Nicol said. ``I hope I can pass something on to them for the last
two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I will be here next year. I can't look that
far ahead, but if this team makes the playoffs anything can happen.
I came here in April and I've enjoyed it, and hopefully I will be
here longer than a year. Obviously, I was surprised by this. I
wasn't expecting it. It's a nice surprise, but unfortunate that
this situation has arisen.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Brian O'Donovan said no decisions have been made
for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an audition, that would be unfair,'' O'Donovan
said. ``Steve is here to help us out. He was effectively the coach
of our second team. We will discuss next year at the end of this
season. But right now that is absolutely the furthest thing from
our minds. We need to get through these next two games and try to
get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga's dismissal was precipitated by a request from his agent,
Eric Manasse, to renew his contract for next season. O'Donovan said
he would wait until the end of the regular season to make a
decision and denied having negotiated with Nicol before Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Some Revolution players joined Nicol with the Bulldogs during
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bulldogs were a very organized group and that's what we
need,'' midfielder Paulo Dos Santos said. ``He was able to motivate
players with the Bulldogs, and that is a key for us. There could be
just a little change that makes a big difference. Hopefully, we can
turn things around, but that's up to the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Said John Harkes, who played against Nicol in England: ``He was
a quality player and a nice person. We can only find out how good a
coach he is in time. We can't change what happened and we can only
live in the present. The best thing for us is to stay together as a
team and lift our spirits because the MetroStars are going to come
in pumped up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
