<HEADLINE>
TWO DECENT TEAMS ATTEMPT TO ESCAPE MIDDLE AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oxford, Ohio, home of Miami Univeristy, is known as being the
``cradle of coaches.'' Today, it's the center of the mid-major
football universe. The buzz is loud, the traffic will be snarled _
and not just because it's Parents' Weekend and John Cougar
Mellencamp is in concert.
</P>
<P>
   The Mid-American Conference has a showcase game in No. 17
Marshall (4-0) and Miami (3-1). The Thundering Herd attack is keyed
by senior quarterback Chad Pennington. The RedHawks' upset hopes
are carried by senior running back Travis Prentice. Both are
long-shot Heisman Trophy candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real excitement and energy surrounding this game,''
said MAC commissioner Rick Chryst, a former assistant commissioner
in the Atlantic Coast and Southwest conferences. ``There are some
pretty high stakes on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's a melancholy aspect. Both Marshall and
Miami are in the MAC's East Division. The winner can shoot for
playing in the conference championship game for a place in the
Motor City Bowl, the MAC's only guaranteed bowl. The loser can
probably forget about the postseason. Last season, Miami finished
10-1 _ it's only loss coming to Marshall _ and did not gain a bowl
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   In basketball terms, today's game is similar to a conference
tournament championship game where the winner gets a spot in the
NCAA Tournament and the loser can start washing and packing
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really not concerned about the top-25 rankings,'' said
Pennington, the nation's sixth-rated passer. ``We understand about
the only way to get to a bowl game is to win our conference. That
is what we're focused on. By no means are we taking this game
lightly. We understand what it is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marshall, what it's all about is continuing a season that
could become magical _ and futile. Marshall could become this
season's Tulane, an undefeated team that winds up playing in an
also-ran bowl instead of for the national title. The Thundering
Herd cracked the top 25 on Sept. 20. At No. 17, they're about a
month ahead of Tulane's pace; the Green Wave was tied for No. 15
the first week of November last season.
</P>
<P>
   The MAC, like the Western Athletic, Mountain West and Conference
USA, are not part of the Bowl Championship Series. To even be
considered for a BCS at-large bowl, Marshall would need to finish
ranked 12th or higher in the final BCS rankings. Because of the
BCS' strength of schedule and computer rankings factors, not even a
miracle could push Marshall high enough in the BCS rankings _ No. 1
or No. 2 _ to play for a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still perceive our conference as being inferior, but we
know that's not the case,'' Prentice said. ``We can go out and play
football and beat anybody. I mean football is football. It doesn't
matter what conference you come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the innocence of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington and Prentice are each having solid senior seasons to
cap off excellent careers. Pennington, at 6-foot-4, 220-pound, has
passed for 8,155 yards in his career and thrown 74 touchdown
passes. Prentice, a 6-1, 228-pounder, has rushed for 4,445 yards
and scored 67 touchdowns. He needs nine rushing touchdowns to break
the career touchdown record held by Texas' Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   A record crowd is expected at 30,000-seat Yager Stadium. ``USA
Today'', ``Sports Illustrated'' and ``ESPN Magazine'' will have
reporters and photographers on hand. There will be
loud-blazer-wearing representatives from the Motor City, Mobile and
Micron PC bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it makes it more exciting to get all this press,''
said Prentice, who two years ago rushed for 203 yards and four
touchdowns in the RedHawks' 45-21 upset of Marshall, which then had
wide receiver Randy Moss. ``Everybody has their eyes on you. You
know people are paying attention. So you have to go out and have
your best ballgame. So, I like it. It's good for me, it's good for
my team and it's good for the conference, especially nationally.
It's good for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get caught up in all the hype. Because when you get
down to it, it's still football. You can't worry about the hype.
You have to win this game, first. It's about football, first.''
spotlight
Safeguarding football's top trophy
Jared Newland has one of those dream jobs. He travels around the
country to the nation's top campuses and gets to watch each year's
best college football games, usually from the sidelines. Newland's
traveling companion on these trips is the 35-pound Sears Trophy
that is awarded to the No. 1 team as voted by the coaches' poll.
Think of him like the guys who escort the NHL's Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Sears Trophy has been traveling around the country since
1993 and has been present for 45 games. Corporate Marketing
Associates, Newland's employer, targets nearly 10 games a year for
road trips. Thus far, Newland and the trophy have been at the
following games: Arizona-Penn State, Ohio State-Miami, Notre
Dame-Michigan, Georgia Tech-Florida State and Penn State-Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to pick out the games where there are
national-championship caliber teams,'' said Newland, who attended
Wyoming and worked in sports information there, at Tulsa, UT-San
Antonio and Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   For each trip, Newland ships the trophy _ which, with padded
carrying case, weighs in at 123 pounds _ via UPS. He shows up a few
days early in each town to display the trophy, squire it around to
television stations, etc. The football-shaped trophy is a frequent
set decoration on ESPN's ``GameDay''.
</P>
<P>
   There was some unexpected drama before the trophy's last road
trip. Newland shipped it from Tallahassee to Miami, but Hurricane
Floyd shut down UPS deliveries. When Newland arrived in Miami, he
couldn't locate the trophy in Miami at his hotel. He eventually
tracked it down after two hours of telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The Sears Trophy, insured for more than $30,000, is a Waterford
crystal football that weighs 7] pounds and sits on a pedestal much
like a football tee. During games, it's displayed on the sidelines.
Newland keeps an eye on the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the players or the ball starts heading our way, I grab the
ball and head the other way,'' he said. ``Sometimes, the players
come over and look at it, touch it. Before the Arizona-Penn State
game, an Arizona lineman came over and touched it and then kissed
his fingers. Obviously, that didn't do his team much good.''
Stomping some grapes Last season, Wisconsin had 54 penalties for
423 yards. This season, the Badgers have 26 penalties for 241 yards
during a 2-2 start. Wisconsin coach Barry Alvarez called Big Ten
Conference supervisor of officials David Parry this week to discuss
his concerns about officiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason why we've led the league in least amount of
penalties for four years,'' Alvarez said. ``Then, all of a sudden,
we get a \Rlot of\S little touchy-feely penalties. Why, I don't
know. There are some that are obvious. But there are some that are
very questionable, too.''
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like sour grapes and tastes like sour grapes, it's
sour grapes.
In quotes North Carolina quarterback Ronald Curry on the criticism
being leveled at coach Carl Torbush for the Tar Heels' 1-2 start:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking a lot of heat he shouldn't have to be taking. It's
not his fault. You can see who's out on the field making the plays.
It's not him; it's the players. We can talk all we want about
`we're going to do this; we can do that.' But a time comes when you
have to quit talking, put on your pants and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado senior cornerback Damen Wheeler on the Buffaloes'
second-half effort against Washington:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half they went straight at the belly of the
defense and were eating at us. I had to question our pride,
especially the second half. People were out there, but nobody was
making plays ... People stopped running to the ball _ just giving
up, I guess. No, I don't want to say giving up. But there's just no
excuse for how we played, no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Purdue linebacker Mike Rose on today's game at No. 4 Michigan, a
team the Boilermakers haven't played in two years:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to finally say we can look forward to this Michigan
game ... To not play \RMichigan and Ohio State\S for two years,
everyone's kind of looked down on us and said, `Oh, yeah, you won
nine games, but you didn't play the big boys.' We're really looking
forward to showing everybody that we're for real.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA freshman quarterback Cory Paus on the sternum jacket he
doesn't want to wear to protect his bruised ribs:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bulletproof vest. And it looks funny. If you don't
feel like you look good, you don't play good.''
By the numbers 1: Number of offensive touchdowns Southern
Mississippi allowed in consecutive losses to Big 12 teams Nebraska
and Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   4: Number of Texas teams ranked 100th or lower in scoring (out
of 114 Division I-A teams). Those teams are Baylor (101), Rice
(109), North Texas (110) and SMU (111). No other state has more
than one team ranked 100 to 114 in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   5: Misses by California on field goals in six attempts. All five
misses have hit one of the uprights.
</P>
<P>
   7: Number of pass plays by 5-0 Penn State that have covered at
least 47 yards. Last season, the Nittany Lions had just four pass
plays of that distance or greater.
</P>
<P>
   32-4: Florida State's record in games played when it was ranked
No. 1. The top-ranked Seminoles play 0-3 Duke today in
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   25: Oregon State's losing streak against Southern California,
its opponent today. The Beavers' last victory over the Trojans came
in 1967, a 3-0 decision against the Trojans and junior running back
O.J. Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   34: Number of defensive touchdowns scored by Virginia Tech in
141 games under coach Frank Beamer.
</P>
<P>
   4 hours, 40 minutes The game time for the Southern
California-Oregon game Saturday. The Ducks won in triple overtime.
</P>
<P>
   0-5: Tommy Tuberville's record in the Mississippi-Auburn series.
While at Ole Miss, Tuberville was 0-4 against Auburn. He chalked up
another loss last week when his Tigers lost to the Rebels in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   88-0: The aggregate score of New Mexico opponents in the third
quarter of the Lobos' past eight games.
Around the country Memphis can make the argument that it's the
nation's best 1-3 team. The Tigers' losses have been by a combined
seven points. And those three losses game to teams with a combined
record of 10-2 _ Mississippi State (4-0), Tennessee (3-1) and
Mississippi (3-1).
</P>
<P>
   East Carolina, displaced for a week because of flooding in North
Carolina, spent most of the $250,000 the school earned for its game
at South Carolina to cover its expenses for the unexpected extended
road trip. The school also had to pay North Carolina State about
$6,000 for damage caused by East Carolina fans to Carter-Finley
Stadium as they celebrated the Pirates' 27-23 upset of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   State College, Pa., home to Penn State, is acknowledged as one
of college football's toughest logistical road trips. Indiana's
trip last Saturday was one of the worst. After a 45-24 loss to the
Nittany Lions, the Hoosiers were stranded because their charter
plane had mechanical problems. There were no hotel vacancies, and
Indiana had checked out of its rooms. So, their hotel put up the
traveling party _ coaches, players, cheerleaders _ in two large
ballrooms.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina has the nation's longest losing streak at 14.
That's because Kent, Holtz's alma mater, won Saturday, ending its
16-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their lucrative contracts, coaches are often paid for
their time doing weekly television and radio shows. Sometimes, it
hardly seems worth the extra cash. On his call-in radio show this
week, LSU coach Gerry DiNardo heard from a disgruntled Tigers
``fan'' who asked if the coach needed help moving out of Baton
Rouge.
Short shots Short: Kansas State president Jon Wefald responded
(why?) to comments written by Will Leitch (who?) on ``The Sporting
News Online'' (what?) by ripping (in a letter posted on Kansas
State's Web site) the University of Texas and the state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Shot: Another example of why not all adults should have access
to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Short: Tennessee is investigating possible academic fraud in its
football program involving other people doing work for players.
</P>
<P>
   Shot: Considering the school's graduation rates for football
players _ 57 percent, 11 percent, 25 percent _ in the past three
NCAA reports, the academic substitutes weren't exactly Rhodes
Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Short: Colorado coach Gary Barnett's catch phrase to turn around
the Buffaloes was Return to Dominance (RTD).
</P>
<P>
   Shot: With the Buffs a disappointing 2-2, it turns out that RTD
might stand for Return to Durango. Barnett's first college coaching
job was at Fort Lewis College in Durango, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Short: Temple coach Bobby Wallace says, ``Offensively, we're
struggling about as bad as you can struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Shot: Wallace could be the coach at South Carolina. The
Gamecocks are last in the nation, averaging three points per game.
Wallace's Owls are next to last, averaging 3.8 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Short: Duke agreed to move today's ``home'' game with Florida
State to Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Shot: To be fair, Florida State should agree to move this
season's ACC basketball home game with Duke to Charlotte.
