r l BC-PANAMACANAL-CULTURE-1     10-01 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMACANAL-CULTURE-1600(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES HAVE DEEP ROOTS IN PANAMA CANAL ZONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED:at Gorgas Hospital. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``They didn't have any work in Jamaica,'' Williams said. ``They
were very, very faithful to the old canal and the Americans, I
guess, because they got a job and living conditions were better.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Williams' father worked in the Canal Zone as a
paymaster. But Williams, who attended Panamanian schools and grew
up outside the zone, said he got a different perspective of canal
history and a sense of Panamanian nationalism that makes him
optimistic about the canal transition.
</P>
<P>
   The Canal Zone was like a country within Panama, with its own
jail, military and stores, Williams said. His grandparents were
loyal to the U.S. system in place, Williams said, but he questioned
the discrimination he noticed. For years, the neighborhoods were
segregated.
</P>
<P>
   In the early construction days, white Americans were paid in
gold and everyone else was paid in silver, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the difficult things to understand,'' said
Baquero, the canal museum director.
</P>
<P>
   Seabert Haynes, 80, lives in the Pedro Miguel neighborhood in
Panama, near the canal locks. He said his parents left Barbados
during the end of the construction period. In 1914, the family
resettled in the Canal Zone, where they were recruited to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are descendants of the West Indians who came to build the
canal,'' said Haynes, who is president of the National Association
of Retired Federal Employees of the United States. ``To me, it is
something that I don't think words can tell you. I feel we have
contributed so much to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard McConaughey, a Florida resident whose grandfather
traveled to Panama in 1906 to work on the passageway, also has deep
family roots at the canal. Four generations of McConaugheys have
labored for the canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a McConaughey working the canal from the
beginning until the end. It's quite a feat,'' said McConaughey, 81,
who has a son who is a lockmaster for the canal.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey was born in 1917 in Panama at Ancon Hospital, which
was later renamed after Col. William Gorgas, an American who helped
fight yellow fever and other diseases during construction of the
canal.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey, a retired canal locomotive operator, said strong
friendships formed among workers who waited to pull ships through
the canal, and they got an unusual glimpse of the outside world.
McConaughey said he remembers goats, pigs and cattle en route to
Greece, and Egyptian workers drinking tea aboard English ships.
</P>
<P>
   The canal proved to be an important piece of the Muller family's
heritage, one that Walter Muller wanted to protect before he died
in June 1997. The former U.S. Navy officer wrote down many of his
memories while living in Southlake, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pride about being a little piece in helping make
that possible,'' Pam Muller said. ``We always got the sense that it
was very important to the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Muller inherited a love for the canal from his parents,
Jack and Margaret, who lived in the Canal Zone during the
construction period and started a family there. Jack Muller, a
carpenter, helped build U.S. Army barracks, two high schools and a
Canal Zone junior college.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, when the U.S. government debated whether to give
the canal to Panama, Walter Muller argued against the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very concerned about the Panama treaties,'' he wrote in
1978 to members of Congress. A loss of hemispheric peace, defense
of the canal and degradation of morale in the U.S. military were
among his chief worries.
</P>
<P>
   The treaties won approval. But the family's connection to the
canal remains.
</P>
<P>
   When Jack Muller left New York in 1912, the 22-year-old was
searching for work and adventure, family members said. His voyage
on the SS Advance marked the beginning of a love that beckoned him
to Panama, even in death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandparents' ashes were spread in the canal. That's how
attached they were to the area,'' Pam Muller said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
