r l BC-PANAMACANAL-CULTURE-1     10-01 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMACANAL-CULTURE-1600(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES HAVE DEEP ROOTS IN PANAMA CANAL ZONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a child in the 1920s, Walter Muller played baseball, followed
railroad tracks to his grade school and enjoyed watching U.S.
infantry practice military maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of growing up on apple pie or selling newspapers on
New York streets, the plucky youngster ate plantains and sold
parakeets and fish to sailors traveling through the steamy,
tropical Isthmus of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the life of children whose parents migrated to Central
America during construction of a historic interoceanic passage, the
Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   The passageway, completed in 1914, didn't just connect the
Pacific Ocean and the Caribbean Sea (and thus, the Atlantic Ocean).
It was a strategic military point that solidified the United
States' role as a world power, and an engineering achievement from
which many Americans and Panamanians drew pride. Canal workers
built history and helped to establish Panama's rich mosaic of
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canal is not just the ditch, the waterway. The canal is
all those who participated in its construction and in its present
day,'' said Angeles Ramos Baquero, director of the Interoceanic
Canal Museum of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   That legacy is alive in the family albums and the memoirs of
those who descended from Panama Canal workers. It ties the Mullers
to other families _ the Williamses, the McConaugheys, the Hayneses
_ who are living miles apart in North Texas cities such as
Southlake and Plano, or across the United States or in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five years after the canal was built, the Panamanian
government is preparing to assume control of it from the United
States on Dec. 31. As that day draws closer, families reflect on
their ties to the canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad,'' said Pam Muller, a Southlake resident who
kept her father's memoirs. ``It makes me miss my dad. I wish he
were here to talk about how he feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Many descendants try to keep up with events leading to the
transition through e-mail, reunions and news stories about the
canal as its latest chapter unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The personal stories they tell aren't in history books but are
among the canal milestones that began with U.S. workers leaving
states such as California and New Jersey to find work in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   After a French attempt to build the canal was plagued by
mismanagement and yellow fever, Americans took up the ambitious and
dangerous project during the leadership of President Theodore
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Laborers came from all over the world to help build the canal.
Workers from Jamaica, Barbados and the Virgin Islands labored
alongside Panamanians, Greeks, Europeans and Asians. U.S.
carpenters, boilermakers and railroad crane operators were among
those lured by the promise of good wages and opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The canal was completed in 10 years for about $387 million,
according to the Panama Canal Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing. It was a miracle,'' said Cedric Williams, a
Plano resident who is a descendent of a Jamaican immigrant who
found work in Panama in the early 1900s. ``I think that's the
biggest construction of this century. They had to do it through
sickness and while speaking different languages.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Hummer Jr., executive vice president of the Panama
Canal Society Foundation in Florida, said his grandfather and a
great-uncle went to Panama in 1904 after seeing an advertisement
stating, ``Jobs in Canal Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me it seemed like a challenging thing to do,'' Hummer
said of his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Louis, the great-uncle, died while digging the canal when
dynamite left behind during the French effort detonated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fact of life that people got injured or died in this
business,'' Hummer said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said financial opportunity brought his grandparents to
the isthmus. The 57-year-old member of the Panamanian Association
of Dallas-Fort Worth said his grandfather found work as a cook for
the hospital where malaria, yellow fever and other diseases were
treated. He retired after working at Gorgas Hospital. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
