100 GREATEST: THE 100 MOST MEMORABLE MOMENTS IN THE CENTURY OF
SPORTS NO. 91: SAYERS' 6-TD GAME WAS ONE FOR THE AGES (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEPHEN SCHROATS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is safe to assume that Steve Sabol has seen more professional
football than anyone. As president of NFL Films, where he's worked
for 38 years, Sabol's job has been to review, edit and catalogue
the filmed history of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be possible to single out, among those miles of film, a
singular person or play as the most memorable? For Sabol, the task
wasn't difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 25,000 cans of film going back to 1894,'' Sabol said.
``The most thrilling five minutes of footage you'll ever find is
Gale Sayers in the open field. Gale Sayers is the most exciting,
thrilling player in the history of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   With the third and fourth picks of the 1965 NFL draft, Bears
coach and owner George Halas chose Dick Butkus, a middle linebacker
from Illinois, and Sayers, a halfback from Kansas. At the time,
Halas was certain that Butkus would excel, but about Sayers openly
wondered if, ``some of his \Rcollegiate\S performance was just
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   That was answered in Sayers' first exhibition game with the
Bears. He returned a punt 77 yards for a touchdown, took a kickoff
93 yards for a score, and completed a 25-yard option pass for a
touchdown . That was the precursor to Sayers' record 22-touchdown
rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Sayers' legend was validated Dec. 12, 1965, on a soggy, sloppy
Wrigley Field. His six-touchdown performance that day was one of
the most extraordinary feats in the 80 years of the NFL, as Chicago
defeated San Francisco, 61-20.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Sayers took a screen pass from Rudy Bukich
and churned 80 yards through the mud for a score. By the end of the
third quarter, Sayers had added touchdown runs of 21, 7, 50 and 1
yard. His crowning achievement came on a fourth-quarter punt
return.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding the ball at his 15, Sayers started right, shed a
tackler, and sped upfield. At midfield, he crossed to the left
sideline, unimpeded by mud or tacklers, and finished his misty
flight in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been proud that I had enough left in the fourth
quarter to run that one in,'' Sayers later said.
</P>
<P>
   His six touchdowns equaled the NFL record set in 1929 by Chicago
Cardinals halfback Ernie Nevers and matched in 1951 by Cleveland
Browns running back Dub Jones.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the game in the fourth quarter, Sayers had touched
the ball only 16 times, yet amassed 336 yards: 113 on nine rushes,
89 on two catches, and 134 on five punt returns _ this in just his
11th NFL start.
</P>
<P>
   Sabol relayed a memorable line from Papa Bear that put the
halfback's career in perspective: ``Halas said, `If one is certain
of anything in football, it is that we shall not look upon his like
again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sayers suffered a devastating injury to his right knee in 1968.
He returned in 1969 to lead the NFL in rushing, gaining 1,032
yards, despite no run longer than 24 yards. All on a surgically
repaired knee and for a Bears team that won only one of 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   An injury to his left knee in 1970 spelled the end of Sayers'
brief but magical career. He retired in 1971 after playing only 67
games. In 1977 at 34, Sayers became the youngest player ever
inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   His legacy lives on in snippets of celluloid that recall flashes
of fluid motion, grace and speed that might never be equaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great athlete never reminds you of someone else. Others are
compared to them,'' Sabol said. ``Gale Sayers had the capacity to
create a moment of pure wonder. What he did on a football field was
unimaginable and undefinable.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
