PURDUE'S DIFFICULT MONTH BEGINS AT MICHIGAN (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michigan's 4-0 start and climb to the No. 4 ranking has been
fueled by a defense that ranks 18th nationally, allowing 271 yards
per game. The folks in Ann Arbor believe this Wolverines defensive
unit ranks favorably with the 1997 group that helped Michigan win a
share of the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, Michigan's defense has to switch from analog to
digital. In their first four games, the Wolverines faced
run-oriented teams _ Notre Dame, Rice, Syracuse and Wisconsin. No.
11 Purdue visits Ann Arbor today with junior quarterback Drew Brees
and the nation's sixth-best passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know a lot more about our secondary after this game,''
Michigan coach Lloyd Carr said. ``I asked the team last week to
describe the secondary, and guys talked about it being hard-hitting
and all of that. I asked them if they wanted me to tell them what I
thought. I said it was a suspect secondary because that's what the
paper up in Syracuse said. I just call them the `suspects.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carr would like his defense to get some help from his offense,
which is averaging just 118.7 yards per game on the ground, 80th
nationally. Purdue enters the game with the nation's longest
winning streak, 10 games. For the Boilermakers, today's game marks
the start of the toughest four-game stretch any team could face
this season. Next Saturday, Purdue plays at Ohio State, then has
home games with Michigan State and Penn State. All are ranked
teams.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
