<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Versace bedazzling but no trailblazer
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN _ Versace: By the end of Italy's Fashion Week, we had seen
bold colorations, intense beading, slit skirts, scarved necklines
and floral fabrications. At the standing-room-only Versace show,
which closed out the week of spring/summer 2000 previews, we were
hoping to see something original.
</P>
<P>
   But original this wasn't. It was more like a retrospective of
all the grand trails Gianni Versace had begun to blaze earlier this
decade before he was killed. All that seemed missing was the model
Naomi Campbell strutting in Versace as only she can, and ardent
customer Elton John in his usual front-row seat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one does color and embellishment and vivid patterns
and just plain sexy like the house of Versace. And Donatella
Versace, who took over the design reins after her brother's death,
proved that the house is still in order.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were either skintight or slashed at the breast,
thigh and backside to show a sinful amount of skin. Models came
down a Plexiglas runway over a narrow pond of waterlilies wearing
an eye-popping array of outfits, in shades of aquamarine, fuchsia,
orange, yellow, shimmering indigo, brilliant black and iridescent
white. Versace showed two distinct floral prints: one decadent and
blossoming, the other innocent and budding.
</P>
<P>
   There were compact jackets beaded with the trademark Medusa
logo, and breeze-blown coats bearing sequined buddhas in the lotus
position. Suede, silk and jersey knit shirtdresses had silver snaps
up the front. Gowns wrapped in the front and scarf-tied around the
neck. Super-sheer blouses were jewel-encrusted at the neck, waist
and wrists.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't much to signal where the label might go in the next
millennium. And though this show didn't break new ground, it was
quite a spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miuccia Prada created classic clothes with a spoiled rich kid
edge to them for her more youthful and (relatively) affordable Miu
Miu line shown Friday. Given Prada's considerable influence over
the fashion industry, these were looks that will likely be copied
by other, even lower-priced, labels in some way, shape or form.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared as if Prada had deconstructed the wardrobes of prep
schoolers and debutantes down to their essential elements, and then
reconstructed them in styles to suit the postgraduate jet set.
</P>
<P>
   Dresses and unitards were cut from the same jib as button-down
oxford shirts. Necklines and pants hems were banded in the same
manner as varsity lettermen's jackets. A great many of the
ensembles featured T-shirt-thin turtlenecks. The line looked
sporty, relaxed and somewhat dressy all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Prada takes great pains to distinguish herself from other
designers. So while the trend is to infuse spring/summer styles
with vivid colors, she kept hers muted (pale blue, tan, burgundy
and olive). She didn't use as much leather as others have either,
but she did send out sheer looks in the form of pleated mesh
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marni: If any Milanese label has burgeoning cult status, it's
this one. And dozens of women turned out for the preview at a
remote loading dock dressed in Marni's hot-selling arts-and-crafts
silk skirts. But Marni followers shook their heads in dismay after
viewing this latest, idea-starved collection. The clothes were
feminine, colorful and pretty, but the concept of putting dots on
nearly everything _ polka dots, painted dots, plastic dots,
sequined dots _ didn't seem especially inspired. The clothes looked
demure and delicate; skirts rarely rose above the knee, the fabrics
were thin but not too sheer, and the ruffled trims looked as if
they were unraveling. The collection had skilled craftsmanship in
its favor, but its one-trick nature left something to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
