<HEADER>
A4073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-A     10-01 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-ART-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IS WARMLY RECEIVED BY CHRISTIAN COALITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Ariz.)  (See also: GORE-CAMPAIGN, BUCHANAN, BUSH-CONGRESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT12 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a striking departure from other presidential
candidates _ past and present _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
delivered a speech to the Christian Coalition on Friday that barely
mentioned abortion, school prayer, gay rights or other matters
vital to religious conservatives. Even so, he drew a rousing
ovation and an unusually warm outpouring from the coalition's
founder, Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's reception was a testament to the potency of his
presidential quest and underscored a new pragmatism among religious
conservatives. Many said they were comfortable with the governor
and, most important, believe he can win.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his advisers said he enjoys such a commanding lead in
the polls that he can behave more like a general election candidate
_ and avoid saying things that could haunt him if he wins the
nomination. That also explains why for the first time on Thursday
he surprised Republican leaders in the House by assailing their
spending proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bush seemed to win over many at the Christian
Coalition, his strategy was not as successful on Capitol Hill:
Several House Republicans said they were angry, even felt betrayed,
by his criticism and that they had alerted the governor's aides of
their proposals in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Christian Coalition has waned in power in the past
year or so, it remains the nation's most powerful group of
religious conservatives. And its convention here attracted most of
the Republican presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   And while other candidates spoke more directly and passionately
about conservative issues, Bush was clearly favored by Robertson,
the group's president, who offered high praise for him and
dismissed the prospects of other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely comfortable with him _ he is sound on the
issues and running a simply marvelous campaign,'' Robertson said in
an interview Friday. ``He's acting very presidential already. I
wouldn't say, `Well, come to the Christian Coalition and pander to
them _ and go to the labor unions and pander to them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush felt no need to tailor his message to the group.
Unlike his rivals, Bush essentially delivered his standard stump
speech to the 3,500 delegates. His only nod to the group was an
appended passage in which he mentioned having signed a bill
requiring that parents be notified whenever their unmarried, minor
daughters seek abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laws like this both respect families and protect life, and
these are some of the highest and most compassionate goals of
government.'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush opposes abortion and holds conservative views on many
issues, other candidates have questioned his commitment,
criticizing him particularly over his comment that there would be
``no litmus test'' for judicial nominees for their stands on
abortion and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   In their own addresses, other candidates put forth far more
direct and vigorous appeals, emphasizing abortion, homosexual
rights and prayer in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole asserted that silent school prayer should be
permitted, and that the Ten Commandments should be displayed in
public schools. ``My commitment is to lean on the Lord with my
whole heart,'' she said, ``reading his word daily and earnestly
seeking his will in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, who is basing his campaign on backing from religious
conservatives, touched heavily on abortion, school prayer and
homosexuality. Unlike Bush, he said, he would make a judge's
opposition to abortion rights a prerequisite for appointment to any
federal bench. He added forcefully, ``My judges are going to
understand that marriage is between a man and a woman _ not two
men.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, reminded the group that he has
fought abortion for years. ``For 23 years,'' he declared, ``we have
fought together for the right to life.'' He vowed to be ``a
conservative president with guts.''
</P>
<P>
   The event at a hotel here came at a crucial time for religious
conservatives. Since former Vice President Dan Quayle dropped out
of the race this week and with Pat Buchanan expected to bolt the
party to seek the Reform Party nomination, Steve Forbes, Alan
Keyes, Mrs. Dole and Bauer are making particularly aggressive plays
for religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about other candidates who made more forceful appeals to
the coalition, Robertson offered a pragmatic analysis that they had
little chance of winning.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He was most critical of Bauer, saying, ``He's not going to win.
You don't win with 1 or 2 percent. And most people are not terribly
keen on a lost cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of the remark, Bauer replied, ``The voters decide who wins
_ not the heads of private organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he admired Mrs. Dole, but explained: ``Elizabeth
is a very charming lady. She subscribed to virtually all of the
ideological points of the Christian Coalition. But I don't think
she will take first. Maybe she's playing for a role as vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson was even more critical of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
the only Republican contender who turned down an invitation to
speak. He said McCain's support of campaign finance reform would
make him a terrible president. ``It would absolutely gut
organizations like the Christian Coalition,'' he said. ``He will
not talk to our lawyers. He will not listen to reason. He is just
bullheaded on this.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the biggest threat to Bush is Forbes, because he is
organizing in pivotal states and pouring his own fortune into the
race.
</P>
<P>
   And while he was critical of Buchanan in his own speech for
Buchanan's comments on World War II _ and for threatening to bolt
the party for the Reform Party nomination _ Robertson defended Bush
for not mentioning Buchanan Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would seem self-serving if Bush goes after Buchanan,''
Robertson said. ``Then it would focus attention on Buchanan. And
that isn't necessarily a smart thing to do.'' Robertson said
Buchanan had canceled a scheduled appearance at the conference on
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
