<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH02-COX     10-01 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth considers merge with Sprint
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. is pondering a blockbuster merger with
Sprint, a combination of equals that could be worth nearly $90
billion.
</P>
<P>
   To complete such a deal, potentially the largest in
telecommunications history, BellSouth would have to outbid _ or
out-bluff _ MCI WorldCom, the aggressive, Mississippi-based giant
already reportedly closing in on an agreement to purchase Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is also considering a range of other options,
including acquisition of several attractive pieces of Sprint, which
is based in Westwood, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of a deal between Sprint and MCI WorldCom could
come as soon as Monday. No competing bid from BellSouth is likely
until later in the week _ if it comes at all. Certainly BellSouth,
which has stubbornly held back from the telcom merger frenzy, could
again turn back from the brink.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of BellSouth are worth about $88 billion, roughly equal
to Sprint's value. By comparison, SBC Communications' pending
purchase of Ameritech is valued at just over $70 billion and AT&AMP;T
has offered to pay about $60 billion for MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Marc Bacurin of JC Bradford, an investment company, said
a Sprint marriage to BellSouth stands a better chance of regulatory
blessing than a Sprint deal with MCI WorldCom. He said BellSouth
has ample reason to stop playing hard-to-get.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth could find itself too small to be a ``supercarrier''
and too big to be a niche player _ while its only potential
partners are either too anemic to help or too muscular to be an
equal mate. ``They have been so nonaggressive, but maybe they see
this as their last opportunity,'' Bacurin said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has grown smoothly and profitably for years, but the
company seems increasingly hemmed in by events in an industry
roiled by mega-mergers. BellSouth has, in three years, gone from
the largest of seven regional Bells to the second-smallest of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to say that the industry is passing them by, but
relative to the others, they are getting smaller and smaller,''
said analyst David Burks of Hilliard Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   Should BellSouth desire just a portion of Sprint, analysts say
the most attractive is Sprint's Internet network, which might be
worth about $4 billion. MCI WorldCom would almost surely have to
shed that unit, since regulators won't allow one company to control
too much of the Net's ``backbone.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth might also be persuaded to take Sprint's local phone
service business, much of which is in the Carolinas and Florida,
both within BellSouth's nine-state territory. Analyst Anthony
Ferrugia, of A.G. Edwards, put the value of that business at nearly
$18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For MCI WorldCom, Sprint offers the national wireless network
that a complete telecom company needs, Burks said. ``There are four
growth components in telecom: data, Internet, wireless and
international. MCI WorldCom has a strong presence in three of the
four.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth offers three of the four, but has mostly a regional
presence.
</P>
<P>
   That is drawback enough, but in those nine Southeast states,
BellSouth faces ominous trends that undermine its core business of
providing dial-tones for local service.
</P>
<P>
   Internet phone service and competition are likely to drive down
rates, and BellSouth already looks to calling features like voice
mail as the source of profits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rates that other companies pay for connections to
BellSouth's network have been dropping.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has looked to wireless service and international
investments to provide much of future growth. But the company has
been stymied in efforts to add long-distance service to its
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other Bells created by the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T,
BellSouth was long forbidden to offer long-distance in its region.
The Telecommunications Act of 1996 lifted the ban, but required the
Bells to open their network to rivals _ something federal
regulators say no Bell has yet done.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth hopes for permission to offer long-distance for its
first state _ Georgia _ early next year at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   When long-distance carrier Qwest Communications _ in which
BellSouth owns a 10 percent stake _ bought US West, it agreed to
surrender long-distance on US West turf. BellSouth might arrange
something similar with Sprint. Analysts said if the company waits
for regulators, it will pass up a strategic necessity.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Chief Executive F. Duane Ackerman last year began
publicly touting data transmission as the future of the company's
business. Both Sprint and Qwest have national networks for carrying
data. In April, Ackerman announced the $3.5 billion investment in
Qwest Communications, the Denver-based company completing a
16,000-mile network of high-speed lines.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth's satisfaction with owning 10 percent of Qwest
proved temporary. Company stock has stagnated, while Qwest made a
high-stakes agreement to buy US West, the smallest of the Bells, a
merger that dilutes BellSouth's influence.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, analysts say, Qwest's network may not be
extensive enough. Sprint has a 30,000-mile high-speed network with
far greater reach.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's high-stakes decision ultimately depends on its
directors. And the board members depend on the recommendations
brought by Ackerman, who, in turn, relies on a core of executives
who have spent their working careers in the company and _ before
the breakup _ at AT&AMP;T. The elite group includes Jere Drummond, who
heads BellSouth Communications, Charles Coe, who runs the phone
units, Earle Mauldin, president of BellSouth Enterprises, and Chief
Financial Officer Ron Dykes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the wild card in the BellSouth inner circle is Gary
Forsee, who was recently named to replace the retiring Sidney Boren
as the executive responsible for strategy. Forsee has been
unavailable for interviews since arriving about six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He is a veteran telecom executive with some intriguing
connections. His previous job was as chief executive of Global One
Communications, a $1.1 billion-a-year venture that provides data
communications in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It is part-owned by Sprint. Before that, Forsee ran Sprint's
long-distance division.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
