<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORFOLK-HISTORY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking into Norfolk Southern's history
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Norfolk Southern Corp. is the product of hundreds of
rail company mergers dating to the mid-1800s. In 1982, Southern
Railway and Norfolk Western Railway merged to form the current
company.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Railway, which was formed by the mergers of about 150
rail lines, traces its origin to the South Carolina Canal &AMP; Rail
Road Co., which ran the nation's first regularly scheduled
passenger train on Christmas Day 1830 in Charleston, S.C. When it
was renamed the Southern Railway in 1894, it operated 4,400 miles
of rail line in the East and South.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk and Western Railway Co. was formed by more than 200
mergers over the years and began operating under that name in 1881.
Mergers during the 1960s positioned N&AMP;W as one of the nation's
dominant rail lines, with links from the Atlantic Ocean to the
Mississippi River and Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
