<SLUG> BC-NORFOLK02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norfolk Southern to sell Atlanta property
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Norfolk Southern Corp., whose large land holdings have
at times been eyed for office towers and sports facilities, has put
all those properties up for sale just as demand soars for sites in
the vicinity of Centennial Olympic Park and the new Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Norfolk, Va.-based railroad, which has 2,700 employees in
metro Atlanta, owns 37 acres containing 404,020 square feet in four
aging office buildings along Spring Street. About 1,500 employees
are based in the buildings that are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Friday it won't decide whether to relocate any
of its employees until it strikes a deal for the properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't figure that out unless and until we have a deal for
these,'' said Norfolk Southern spokesman Frank Brown. ``We've got
to see what offers we get.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Holmes, a broker with Insignia/ESG Inc., which is handling
the sale of the property, said there has been ``some strategic
marketing'' to prospects such as large Atlanta companies who might
need the existing office buildings and to developers converting
downtown commercial buildings to loft residences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not really started the process with the land,'' Holmes
said. The largest tract, 20 acres on Spring Street next to the new
Philips Arena and CNN Center, is zoned for very high density
development, Holmes said. It was once considered a tower site for
the railroad or another company.
</P>
<P>
   Another eight acres adjoins the Castelberry area, where lofts
have recently flourished, Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the opening of the arena, that whole area is hot,'' said
Kris Cooper, a Cushman &AMP; Wakefield broker who has handled deals in
the area. ``Interim uses could be parking,'' Cooper said, ``There
is a dire need for parking, and I don't know that the raw land is
ready (for development) yet. It may be a few years away.''
</P>
<P>
   No prices have yet been set for the properties, Holmes said.
While ``the timing is fortuitous'' with demand for downtown
property so strong, Holmes said the railroad's decision was driven
more by the timing in the business cycle for review of its
properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always been in the habit of looking at our assets all
around the system to determine the highest and best use for them,''
Brown said. ``It's been known for a fairly good while those
buildings are not ideal for us anymore. They are getting some age
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent a lot of time looking for relocation sites here
and elsewhere _ there are significant opportunities intown and out
of town,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
