A4079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEATHERCHANNEL02-COX     10-01 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHERCHANNEL02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weather Channel transmitting via Internet
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Weather Channel has begun transmitting TV
programming via the Internet to a Memphis, Tenn., cable system, an
industry first and a step toward what the company hopes will become
a significant new business.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based programmer is sending local weather
information. The recipient is a Time Warner system, which serves
231,000 subscribers in metropolitan Memphis. The system will air
local weather information, commercial-free, on a separate, new,
24-hour channel.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Weather Channel and Time Warner say Memphis is the
first site _ in both companies' opinion _ to receive localized
24-hour television programming via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If this service, called Weatherscan Local, proves popular in
Memphis, the Weather Channel plans to offer it to cable operators
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delivery via the Internet opens the way for the Weather
Channel to extend a great number of options to cable companies for
tailoring weather services to each unique market,'' says Decker
Anstrom, the Weather Channel's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Although scheduled officially to launch on Monday, Time Warner
began airing the new channel Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Channel is based in Atlanta but is owned by
privately-held Landmark Communications, a diversified media
conglomerate. It is one of the most successful cable TV channels.
Its namesake channel is in more than 70 million households
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Weather Channel has become a mature
business, and the company is looking for new areas for growth.
Executives say they believe the Internet offers the best
opportunity. It has built up a huge Web presence, becoming the
leading provider of weather content on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is moving that Internet weather content to
television with Weatherscan. Developed digitally for the Internet,
Weatherscan content can be endlessly customized and quickly
updated. This is not true for traditional television shows,
produced in a studio and transmitted via satellite to cable
systems.
</P>
<P>
   In Memphis, for example, Weatherscan will offer complete local
forecasts every two minutes. Not so on the Weather Channel, which
also offers national and international forecasts, specials and TV
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The cable system receiving Weatherscan Local recently upgraded
its plant to digital, a format that makes it easy to transmit data,
voice and video between televisions and cable wires.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Williams, a spokesman for the Time Warner Memphis system,
says his city is a good test site for Weatherscan. ``There is an
intense interest in the weather here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the city is the No. 1 air cargo airport in the country.
It's the headquarters of Federal Express, and UPS also maintains a
large operation. In addition, the city is surrounded by
agriculture. ``Farmers are also interested in the weather,''
Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
