<HEADLINE>
WTO CHIEF DEFENDS ORGANIZATION IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Michael Moore, the New Zealand politician who now
heads the World Trade Organization, had a taste of Seattle Friday _
from breakfast and dinner with dignitaries to encounters with
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who elected you?'' shouted protesters as Moore showed up for a
breakfast meeting on the Seattle waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was selected by a consensus of the WTO's 134 member
governments, some of which are democratic and some not. ``I would
have liked to have been called `the New Zealand candidate,''' he
said. In the eyes of the Asian and European press, ``I was always,
`the American candidate.'''
</P>
<P>
   He disputed the opponents' image of the WTO as a shadow
government in Geneva overruling national laws. ``We are an
organization of sovereign governments,'' he said. The rules are
what they agree upon, and in the case of the United States, require
ratification by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In trade negotiations, Moore said, ``Any country has veto power.
The United States puts its hand up, and things stop. Japan puts its
hand up, and things stop. The little guys put their hands up, and
things stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the breakfast, Moore got into a dialog with Jim Puckett of
the Asia Pacific Environmental Exchange. Puckett said the wealthy
countries can use the WTO to force poor countries to accept
shipments of toxic waste, which they thought they had banned under
the Basel Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your legal advice is wrong,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Puckett insisted that he was correct, and was finally cut off
from speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Rockwell, WTO's spokesman, said later there has never been
a toxic-waste case before the WTO, and that if there were, a
country wishing to protect itself would win it. ``The WTO
specifically says that products that are dangerous to humans,
plants and animals can be kept out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office Sept. 1, Moore has been making the proposal
that the rich countries agree at Seattle to let in the goods and
services of the poorest countries with zero tariffs. ``For the
United States, these amount to 0.7 percent of imports,'' he said,
arguing that the United States could easily afford such a gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Moore bristled at opponents' questions that suggested that world
trade was against the poor countries. ``How dare they speak for the
poor countries,'' he said. ``These countries want investment.
They're desperate for it. They're all leading missions to
Washington, D.C., to get it. This,'' (he motioned as if the
protesters were still there) ``is very '60s stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is a former minister in New Zealand's Labor government of
1984-1990, which deregulated the economy. ``Everywhere I worked,''
he said, ``we ended up sacking 50 percent of the workers.'' As a
result, he said, it takes a day and a half to unload a ship in New
Zealand, as opposed to four and a half days.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's opponents blame him for championing ``the most radical
set of economic reforms inflicted'' on any rich country. They call
him ``Mad Mike;'' he recently called them, they say, ``grumpy,
geriatric communists'' and ``a mutant strain on the left.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Ambassador Koji Watanabe was also in Seattle yesterday,
urging a greater effort be taken to communicate with trade
opponents who plan to disrupt the WTO meetings in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who believe in world trade should be talking to those
people who have misgivings about trade itself or WTO,'' Watanabe
said after addressing a Japan-America Society luncheon at the
Sheraton Seattle Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be some areas of meeting of minds. Trade has been
the most important engine of growth of the world's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some arguments opponents are asserting ``may have some
justifiable grounds, and those are questions that must be
discussed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture and labor are valid areas for discussion, ``but WTO
is a positive organization for addressing issues of health and
environment,'' said Watanabe, whose first foreign service
assignment was as Japan's vice consul in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor costs differ among countries and expansion of trade
creates opportunities for countries to overcome handicaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Watanabe told the Japan-America Society audience that
Japan is emerging from economic problems that forced it into
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Weak banks have closed and others have merged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese companies, once bloated by workers assured of lifetime
employment have been reducing their workforce and becoming more
efficient, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a renewed confidence in the economy,'' and it is
resulting in imports from the United States and other countries,
Watanabe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
