<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE PRESENCE AGAIN THWARTS ANTI-MILOSEVIC PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The demonstrations against President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia appeared to flounder Friday night,
with opposition leaders unsure how to respond to Milosevic's
willingness to use the police and an arbitrary legal system to
defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   A scheduled ``driving'' protest in cars and buses to Dedinje,
the suburb where Milosevic lives, failed when the police
predictably sealed off entry roads with armored vehicles and water
cannon.
</P>
<P>
   And a rally in downtown Belgrade attracted only some 7,000
people, who finally marched 200 yards to the political headquarters
of the opposition to protect a young Democratic Party official,
Cedomir Jovanovic, from being arrested by policemen who had
surrounded the building for nearly 20 hours.
</P>
<P>
   As Jovanovic was finally allowed to leave the building and went
into hiding, state television announced Friday that Belgrade
prosecutors had asked the police to investigate the ``perpetrators
and ringleaders'' of the violence at Wednesday night's rally that
left five policemen injured. Opposition leaders said they feared
that all of them might face arrest, even though the police
initiated the violence on both Wednesday and Thursday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday evening, opposition leaders argued among themselves
about the risks and responsibilities of taking a more
confrontational line toward the police, one of them said. They have
not attracted the hundreds of thousands of demonstrators they say
are needed to force Milosevic to resign, yet they are unwilling to
call for an uprising. They decry Milosevic's willingness to draw
blood, but they seem unwilling to ask their followers to shed it.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's rally, the Democratic Party leader, Zoran Djindjic,
said that on Saturday demonstrators would march to a hospital
center to visit those wounded earlier in the week. But the center
is on the same street where police blocked a march to Dedinje
Wednesday night. If the police block them again, Djindjic
suggested, ``we will stop this for a few days and then meet each
other in front of the federal Parliament and stay there until they
go.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments suggested that the leadership is considering a halt
to the nightly marches, with their risk of confrontation, and
instead will try to bring in more protesters from other Serbian
towns. The idea would be to produce a rally large enough to try to
show Milosevic that most Serbs want him gone.
</P>
<P>
   But other leaders suggest that they should turn their efforts to
forcing early elections from Milosevic, much as Djindjic's rival,
Vuk Draskovic, leader of the Serbian Renewal Movement, has urged.
Draskovic has refused to join these rallies and called them ``a
waste of time,'' saying that Milosevic can only be brought down by
elections, not by force. ``Milosevic is not a man you can force to
resign by singing, by dancing and by walking,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jovanovic's troubles, and the connected shutdown of the Glas
Javnosti newspaper and printing press for two weeks by the
financial police, are a good example of how Milosevic uses the
legal system to harass and undermine political challenges, said
Biljana Kovacevic-Vuco of the Lawyer's Committee for Human Rights.
``This country is expert at making a political case into a legal
case,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they were investigating irregularities at Glas
Javnosti. But the real issue is a contract by the press to publish
the daily bulletin, Promene, or Changes, issued for free by the
Alliance for Change, and allegedly published without a license.
</P>
<P>
   The signer of the contract, and hence the publisher of the
bulletin, is Jovanovic, a 28-year-old aide to Djindjic, whom police
sought to arrest. He took refuge late Thursday in the offices of
the Alliance for Change, while plainclothes policemen surrounded
the building.
</P>
<P>
   They negotiated with Alliance lawyers for Jovanovic's surrender,
but he refused police offers of protection, and police did not
storm the building. Friday night, demonstrators set him ``free,''
and the police did not intervene. But he is likely to have to go
into hiding or face arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The police have also been blocking protest marches outside the
city center, where protests are authorized, on the grounds that
demonstrators are interfering with public order and blocking
traffic.
</P>
</TEXT>
