<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDRESSING LABOR UNION GATHERING, GORE AND BRADLEY CRITICIZE EACH
OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The debates that Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley are promising began in a virtual way Friday as
each candidate pleaded with an important labor union for support
and directly criticized his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In his strongest words to date, Gore cast Bradley's brief
flirtation with an independent presidential candidacy in 1996 as
disloyalty to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been tempted to leave the Democratic Party,'' Gore
said, speaking by satellite from Washington to members of Local 250
of the Health Care Workers Union, who were meeting in Oakland,
Calif. ``I've never been tempted to turn my back on the Democratic
Party. I've never been tempted to run as an independent and divide
the progressive coalition, and I have always, always been for
working families and for organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   In an videotaped appearance before the union, which played for
members earlier Friday, Bradley portrayed Gore as a life-long
Washington insider with little real-life experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has a life that is primarily based in
Washington, and I think that gives us a different idea of who the
American people are and what we can do,'' Bradley said. ``I think
it also flows into a different style of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments marked the first time that the two have criticized
each other directly to the same audience and signaled a distinct
escalation of Gore's determination to fight for his party's
nomination. When the two made separate appearances last weekend
before the Democratic National Committee they did not aim their
fire at each other.
</P>
<P>
   The comments also showed just how hard both candidates are
courting the labor vote. Local 250, a part of the Service Employees
International Union, is the second-largest health-care local in the
country after Local 1199 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It is a critical part of the AFL-CIO, which is scheduled to meet
Oct. 12 in Los Angeles and consider whether to endorse a candidate
for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore once expected that endorsement, but Bradley's fund-raising
prowess and strong showing in opinion polls has given him enough
clout to at least forestall an automatic AFL-CIO nod to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism of Bradley was just one sign Friday that Gore was
trying to make good on his pledge to revitalize his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He also replaced his top pollster, Mark Penn, with Harrison
Hickman, a move that the Gore camp described as a way to focus more
closely on polling in the early-voting states of Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters have very particular views in those states,'' said a
campaign aide, describing Hickman as an expert in polling specific
issues and voters rather than broad national sentiment. ``You need
research that is very, very targeted,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gore was more overt in his criticism of Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, the Republican front-runner. For the first time
Friday, he mentioned Bush by name, indicating that he believes that
while he must beat back the Bradley challenge, he must also carry
the party standard against the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At a hospital here, Gore touted his support for a patient's bill
of rights and criticized Bush for not supporting one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that Gov. Bush will break with the Republican majority
in the Congress and start supporting the patient's bill of
rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said that Bush, who on Thursday said congressional
Republicans should not ``balance their budget on the backs of the
poor,'' could not simultaneously oppose the Republican spending
plan and still support their proposed tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   And the vice president said that if Bush really wanted to
``demonstrate compassion for working families,'' he would break
with the Republicans and support an increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was in Washington to address the Christian Coalition,
seemed surprised that Gore had mentioned him. ``Really?'' he asked
a reporter excitedly when informed of Gore's comments. ``What did
he say?''
</P>
<P>
   After a description of Gore's comments, Bush said, ``Well, I
think that Vice President Gore needs to debate Bill Bradley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
