<HEADER>
A4101 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-NUGENT-AR     10-01 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-NUGENT-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BATTLE-SCARRED BURGER WARRIOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Like some other chief executives, Robert J. Nugent
shares the limelight with the founder of his company. In this case,
however, the ``founder'' is a clown with an oversize Ping-Pong ball
for a head.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday both Nugent and the clown, named Jack, will ring the
closing bell at the New York Stock Exchange to celebrate the
changing of the company's name from Foodmaker Inc. to Jack in the
Box Inc., after the quick-service restaurant chain that is its only
business.
</P>
<P>
   That Nugent, 58, can clown around at all is startling. In 1993,
Foodmaker was plunged into crisis after four children died and
hundreds more were sickened from Jack in the Box hamburgers
contaminated with deadly bacteria. The company was sued by victims
and franchisees and suffered heavy losses as customers abandoned
its restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent himself, Foodmaker's No. 2 executive at the time, was
criticized after he apparently tried to deflect the blame.
</P>
<P>
   But Nugent and Jack in the Box have recovered in a major way.
The company has had record earnings in the last two years and
expects another record in the fiscal year that ends Sunday. Sales
in stores open at least a year were up 9.8 percent in the last
quarter, far exceeding those of most other burger chains.
</P>
<P>
   And Jack in the Box, which operates in the West, is expanding
into the Southeast this month as part of Nugent's long-term plan to
create a nationwide chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are running better than anyone else in the sector right
now,'' said David Rose, an analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. in Los
Angeles. ``Bob is the force behind all the change.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent, who bought a golden retriever during the crisis for
added comfort when he went home, said the incident had made the
company stronger. ``As a result of having gone through it, we as an
organization have a sense of self-confidence that is second to
none,'' he said in an interview at the headquarters in San Diego.
``We just believe that there's nothing we can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent, a 20-year company veteran who became president and chief
executive in 1996, has received help in the recovery effort from
Jack, the star of a popular advertising campaign that is not afraid
to tweak the competition.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, for instance, a Spanish-speaking Chihuahua tells
Jack he wants Taco Bell. Jack stares down condescendingly and says:
``So? You're a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   The company parking lot has a space reserved for Jack. The
annual report last year was a comic book featuring Jack. And new
business cards portray Jack's yellow hat on a red background.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent is more of a buttoned-down executive than a comedian. The
key to success, he said, is listening to customers through
extensive market research and providing good food and service.
``It's not rocket science,'' he said. ``It's really kind of a basic
business we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack in the Box, whose real founder in the 1950s was Robert O.
Peterson, has a more varied menu than many competitors and aims at
young adults, rather than children. Nugent is proud of a new
policy, now also being tried by some other chains, of making all
sandwiches to order.
</P>
<P>
   With 1,500 restaurants, all in the United States, Jack in the
Box is the nation's fifth-largest burger chain, but is tiny
compared with McDonald's, which has more than 12,000 outlets in the
United States alone. With more than 75 percent of his stores
company-owned rather than franchised, Nugent says he can exercise
closer control over food and service.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent, who is from Dayton, Ohio, received a business degree
from the University of Cincinnati and went into banking. One day
about 30 years ago, he let his office be used to close the sale of
a mansion in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer, Dan Lasiter, then 26, a founder of the Ponderosa
steakhouse chain, awed Nugent by paying in cash. Nugent soon shed
his banker's suit for a cowboy outfit to join Ponderosa as a
management trainee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute I went into the steakhouse it was love at first
sight,'' he said, explaining that one can change the look, service
or food at a restaurant and get instant feedback from customers.
``You can't do that in a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent worked at Ponderosa for 10 years _ the first two without
a day off. He joined Jack in the Box in 1979 as a division vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   When the first death from tainted burgers was reported in the
Northwest in January 1993, Nugent angered victims by blaming the
company's meat supplier and Washington state regulators. But Jack
in the Box got credit for offering to pay the medical expenses of
victims and for hiring an expert, David M. Theno, to create a new
safety system that set the industry standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I would say it was a good healthy case of
denial,'' said Roni Rudolph of San Diego, whose 6-year-old
daughter, Lauren, died. Although her hard feelings linger, Ms.
Rudolph said Jack in the Box ``became a model or a template for
cleaning up a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent eats at Jack in the Box about twice a week. He also loves
fine wines and is part of a group starting a new vineyard in Napa
Valley. He was president of San Diego's Museum of Contemporary Art
for two years. He and his wife, Anne, have two daughters, one of
whom has followed him into the restaurant business as an executive
at Starbucks. Nugent now has four dogs.
</P>
<P>
   His goal, besides expanding nationwide, is to get Jack in the
Box onto Fortune magazine's list of most-admired companies. In
this, he's not clowning around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
