<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The (plus) word should be replaced with the symbol)  
(ART ADV: Graphic of non-profitable, non-Internet IPOs is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IPO WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For New Issues, A Contagion of Red Ink &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is a truism that Internet companies that go public are
unprofitable, but that often doesn't stop their stocks from
soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from that playbook, more unprofitable non-Internet
companies are deciding to go public, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet standards for lack of profitability are beginning
to affect the rest of the new-issue market,'' said Linda Killian,
manager of IPO(plus) Aftermarket, a $16 million fund that invests
in new issues.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has accelerated in recent months. According to Thomson
Financial Securities Data, a research firm in Newark, the
percentage of non-Internet new issues, excluding closed-end funds
and real estate investment trusts, that were running losses at
their offering rose from 25 percent in the first quarter of 1997 to
34 percent in the first quarter of this year, and to 55 percent
last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public investors are behaving like venture capitalists,''
said Ms. Killian, adding that some such offerings hold promise:
``In many ways, they have business plans that are better thought
out and achievable than the Net companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Cohen, research director of Wit Capital, praises the
willingness of investors to look beyond the price-to-earnings
multiple. ``The growth of the Internet industry may have
conditioned the public to look at net present value measures other
than P/E's,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Lackluster Quarter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were a few bright spots for mutual fund investors last
quarter: Japan funds and gold funds surged 23 percent and 18.5
percent, respectively, according to preliminary data from Lipper
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, these are also two of the least popular fund
categories, with total assets between them of $8.2 billion. That's
the size of the 65th-largest mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter also showed that investors can lose money
during the summer without a global economic crisis and a hedge-fund
bailout, which clobbered equity markets last year, or an impending
war. (Stocks slumped badly in the third quarter of 1990, after Iraq
invaded Kuwait.) Every other year this decade, investors prospered
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the S&AMP;P 500 Index lost 6.3 percent and the Dow
industrials dropped 5.4 percent, while the NASDAQ managed a 2.3
percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Among the largest stock funds, those run by Janus stood out
again _ this time just by breaking even. The largest, the $32
billion Janus Fund, lost 1.6 percent for the quarter, while the $26
billion Janus 20 gained 1.2 percent and the $21 billion Janus
Worldwide was up 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12 months ended on Thursday, Janus 20 and the Janus Fund
ranked No. 1 and No. 2 in performance among the 25 largest funds,
with returns of 54.6 percent and 51 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Value funds skidded, with Washington Mutual Investors falling
9.4 percent, Vanguard Windsor down 10.4 percent and Vanguard
Windsor II off 13.6 percent. Over all in the quarter, small beat
large, and growth beat value.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of gold funds, ``the big winner in the domestic sector
is technology,'' said A. Michael Lipper, the Lipper chairman. ``The
loser is financial services.'' The average technology fund rose 7
percent, while financial services funds fell 12.7 percent, on
average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
