<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-REVLON-PERELMAN-ART-4     10-01 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVLON-PERELMAN-ART-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED PERELMAN SHIFTS COURSE ON REVLON SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN and DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having failed to find a buyer willing to pay the
price he wanted, Ronald Perelman said Friday that he was taking
Revlon Inc. off the market and would instead try to sell two units
of the ailing cosmetics giant to raise much-needed cash.
</P>
<P>
   The news was a defeat for the billionaire financier, who
publicly put the company up for sale in April.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon said it expected the sale of the two units, Latin
American brands and salon-style hair care products, to generate at
least $500 million and to be completed by March 31. Talks were
being held with prospective buyers, Revlon said, but it declined to
name them. Revlon's chief executive, George Fellows, said the
proceeds would mostly be used to help reduce $1.6 billion in debt.
The rest of Revlon _ whose brands include the Almay, Ultima II and
Revlon lines of blush, lipstick and eye shadow _ will stay in the
Perelman stable.
</P>
<P>
   Because of troubles abroad and a glut of inventory, Revlon also
announced that it expected to post a large loss in the third
quarter instead of the small profit that stock analysts had
projected. That will lead to a large operating loss for the year,
and earnings next year are also expected to suffer. Investors
pummeled Revlon's stock Friday, sending it down 34 percent, or
$6.25, to $12, its 52-week low. Perelman was said to want up to $40
a share from an outsider investor.
</P>
<P>
   Although many companies had expressed interest in buying Revlon
_ Coty Inc., a German perfume mass marketer, and Unilever NV, a
Dutch consumer products company, were said to be among the suitors
_ they apparently could not countenance that top-dollar price. And
Perelman is known to hold the line on price _ whether in a
corporate deal or a divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts conjecture that Perelman's intransigence on
Revlon's price stems from not really wanting to part with the
glamorous crown jewel of his portfolio anyway. Revlon gives the
thrice-divorced Manhattan bachelor access to the A-list parties
attended by supermodels and other beautiful women.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest that Perelman could not take the loss of face.
``This is the first time in Perelman's career where he is put in
the position of other people dictating to him,'' said Allan Mottus,
a consultant to the beauty industry and the publisher of the
Informationist, a trade publication. ``When you bring a property to
other people that is reported to have some problems, I think in the
bargaining process what happens is people try to knock the price
down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A 1980s-style corporate raider, Perelman has earned a dubious
reputation for bailing out of ventures just before they collapse.
Public shareholders have taken big baths at Marvel Entertainment,
Coleman, Consolidated Cigar and Sunbeam, in which he is still a
large shareholder. For many years after Perelman bought Revlon, in
a leveraged buyout in 1985, the company appeared to be an
exception.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last year, deep fissures have emerged in what
appeared to be a smooth skin. Competitors like Procter &AMP; Gamble
with its Oil of Olay line and Johnson &AMP; Johnson with its Neutrogena
line have been chipping away at Revlon's market share. A backlog of
inventory at the drugstore chains combined with weakening in key
international markets like Russia and Latin America also hurt the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon now projects a 1999 operating loss, before charges, of
$70 million to $80 million. It said the loss stemmed from an effort
to reduce its bloated inventory, something that would position it
for better performance in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging investor displeasure, Revlon said it would
postpone product introductions and spend more on advertising to win
back customers. ``I don't want to diminish the effect of what we
announced today,'' Fellows said, ``but if you look past the short
term, getting the albatross of the inventory behind us really sets
the stage for a very solid and powerful year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   William Steele, a managing director of Banc of America
Securities, voiced support for Revlon's decision to take the
inventory down in one big bite. ``They have been trying to work
down quarter by quarter, and it wasn't working, so they are saying,
`Let's get it done now.' Obviously it's a very dramatic
announcement, but I think from a long-term perspective we are going
to start to see the company generate working capital efficiencies
and stronger cash flow.''
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts who examine corporate debt were not so
sanguine about Revlon's future. Indeed, the company's low-rated
bonds fell by as much as 36 percent Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed sale of the two units would make a meaningful dent
in Revlon's debt, said Al Alaimo, an analyst with Banc of America
Securities. ``But it is very difficult to say whether the company's
actual credit statistics will improve.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report on Revlon's creditworthiness, Merrill Lynch worried
that with operating losses so high, Revlon might exhaust its
current credit line before raising cash from the proposed sales and
be forced to borrow from lenders at high rates. The company said
that the expected loss would put it in violation of certain
conditions of its credit agreement and that it was confident it
could negotiate the necessary changes with its bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the company does get a better grip on its debt, which
management has insisted that investors are making far too much of,
Perelman must contend with a big payment in another year.
Zero-coupon bonds he issued in 1998 through Revlon Worldwide, the
cosmetics company's privately held parent, come due on March 15,
2001, and are secured by 20 million of his shares.
</P>
<P>
   When the bonds mature, holders will be owed $770 million. ``In
order for the collateral underlying security on the bonds to
provide enough value to pay for the bonds,'' Alaimo said, ``he
needs a stock price of around $36 a share,'' or triple its current
level.
</P>
<P>
   Absent a surge in the stock, Perelman can roll over the bonds,
but to do so he must begin to clean up Revlon to attract new
investors. Or he could raise cash, which would require selling more
assets than announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
