<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4115 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BOMB-ARREST02-COX     10-01 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-ARREST02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspected Florida A&AMP;M bomber arrested
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A former potato chip deliveryman who used an
old identification card to get inside Florida
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M University has been charged in two recent bombings at the
state's historically black school, according to the U.S. attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Michael Lombardi, 41, an unemployed white man, was
arrested by authorities early Friday at his home in a new
Tallahassee subdivision, a few miles from the 12,000-student
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Married and the father of two children, 9 and 16, Lombardi was
charged on two counts of illegally manufacturing a homemade bomb.
He could face up to 20 years if convicted. Other possible charges
include using a destructive device and also a civil rights
violation, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Patterson. Lombardi
is being held in the Federal Detention Center in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI had been investigating the bombings, on Aug. 31 and
Sept. 22, as hate crimes. Both occurred in unoccupied restrooms. No
one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   An Ohio native who used to live in Orlando, Lombardi was
arrested a day after police officials publicized in the news media
an audiotape containing racial slurs and a surveillance camera
photo of Lombardi taken at a local Lowe's home supply store.
</P>
<P>
   The release of both led to more than a dozen tips from the
public. ``There was a consistency in the message in those calls,''
said Florida Department of Law Enforcement Commissioner Tim Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Lombardi had threatened a third bombing this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing leg chains and the jeans and plaid red-and-black shirt
he wore when a SWAT team of three dozen officers descended on his
house after midnight Friday, Lombardi said nothing during his
90-minute arraignment in the afternoon. His lawyer, Timothy Jansen,
entered Lombardi's plea of not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   He nodded to some of U.S. Magistrate William Sherrill's
questions, and occasionally conferred with Jansen. Not once did he
look at his wife, Cathy, as she sat in the courtroom behind a pair
of dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Jansen called the government's case weak, pointing out that
prosecutors haven't charged Lombardi with planting any bombs,
merely possessing one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't prove that he made the device, and they can't prove
that he was at FAMU,'' Jansen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly circumstantial.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Lombardi admitted it was his voice
on the audiotape, which recorded his Sept. 22 call to a Tallahassee
television station moments after the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi also admitted that it was him in the Lowe's photo, the
complaint said. That photo, taken the day before the first
explosion, shows him buying a plastic pipe _ fragments of which
were found at the Aug. 31 bombing. Lombardi told an FBI agent he
intended to use the pipe ``in a home irrigation system.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill ordered Lombardi held without bail, saying the evidence
of his making the incriminating phone calls as well as the bits of
plastic found on drill bits and a hand saw at his home were more
than enough probable cause to believe he is the FAMU bomber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe I would be able to assure the safety of the
community with electronic monitoring,'' Sherrill said. He did grant
Jansen's request that Lombardi be kept apart from other inmates
while awaiting trial, because of the racially charged nature of the
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Until about a month ago, Lombardi worked for Toms Foods, a
potato chip manufacturer with a plant about an hour from
Tallahassee. An employee there who helped FBI agents identify
Lombardi said that Lombardi's route included FAMU and that he kept
his ID card when he stopped working. The employee also described
Lombardi as ``an individual who did not like blacks,'' the
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Before his delivery route, Lombardi worked at Culley's
Meadowwood Funeral Homes, near his house, said a woman who answered
the phone there. He has a 1980 degree from the Cincinnati College
of Mortuary Science, and is a licensed embalmer in Florida. That
license was suspended from 1991 to 1994 because he failed to
complete an AIDS education course.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi served in the U.S. Marines for about three years in the
early 1980s, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors at his old apartment complex were surprised. ``You can
tell he was kind of different,'' said Vatrus Parmer, a Tallahassee
city police officer who lived near him. ``He gave my boyfriend
beers, my boyfriend gave him beers, and my boyfriend is black.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lovely wife and children,'' said Ralph Antonucci, a
realtor who sold Lombardi his new $115,000 home in December. ``He
was always friendly and always worried about whether he was doing
the right thing, with buying the house. He was just a man who
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the arrest spread slowly across the usually tranquil
campus Friday, which was the first day of the school's annual
parents' day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary at times, but you can't run,'' said Taunya Bryant
of Martin County, who was visiting her son, Zachary, a freshman at
FAMU.
</P>
<P>
   ``You, FAMU students, are the real heroes in this crisis. It
took courage to stay on this campus,'' University President
Frederick Humphries told hundreds of students and parents as he
stood in front of the administration building.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the explosions, the Rev. Jesse Jackson had
visited Tallahassee Sunday and encouraged students in a special
prayer vigil to keep attending classes.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Gov. Jeb Bush said, ``Despite these
horrible attacks, the mission of the university has continued on
during these difficult times.''
</P>
<P>
   Heightened security throughout the campus will remain in place
over the next few days. Additionally, several permanent
surveillance cameras will be installed by next week, Humphries
said.
</P>
<P>
   And though the campus police checkpoints that were established
last week will gradually disappear, a new school policy will
require students and faculty to carry photo identification, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how relieved I feel,'' Humphries said. But he
reminded students and faculty to keep their eyes open. ``Students,
keep your doors locked in the student dormitories, and remain
vigilant to make sure there are no strange packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Shirish Date and Mary Ellen Klas contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
