<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GIULIANI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI ENDORSES BUSH FOR PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Flush with Republican pride after a visit to the
Reagan Presidential Library in California, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
endorsed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for president on Friday,
saying he could restore the ``sense of unified purpose'' that
Americans had during the Republican administrations of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made the announcement at an early-morning news
conference at City Hall, where he spoke with Bush by telephone,
their conversation broadcast for reporters over a loudspeaker.
Officials said the endorsement was timed to drum up attention for a
visit by Bush to New York state, which will begin Monday night in
Buffalo and end Wednesday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here this morning, just having returned from the Reagan
Library on the red-eye, so I think this is a very appropriate time
to do this,'' Giuliani said in the Blue Room at City Hall, where he
was joined by a fellow Republican, Borough President Guy Molinari
of Staten Island. ``I believe that Governor Bush is the best
candidate, Republican, Democrat, Independent or anything else, to
be our next president.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual step of making the endorsement in a telephone call
rather than at a more traditional joint appearance also seemed
intended to insure that all of the formalities were out of the way,
and that Giuliani had joined the crowded bandwagon of Republicans
already supporting Bush, before the Texas governor arrived on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani confirmed that. ``We thought it was best,'' he said,
``to make it clear that I support him and endorse him and therefore
everybody can have that question out of the way when we do
fund-raising and campaigning and everything else that we are going
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's endorsement was not a surprise. The mayor, who is
expected to run for the U.S. Senate next year, had quietly
committed himself to supporting Bush some time ago, and advisers
said he had been waiting for instructions from Bush campaign
headquarters in Austin. Gov. George Pataki formally endorsed Bush
in May.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening of their brief telephone conversation Thursday,
Bush quickly made it clear that the endorsement was mutual. ``Hey,
senator,'' Bush declared with his gentle Texas twang. ``I mean
mayor _ how are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Giuliani talked about teaming up on the campaign trail
next year. ``We're a winning ticket in your great state,'' Bush
told Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were hints of a rivalry, although not a political
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that you're a winner _ like the Yankees,'' Giuliani
told Bush, needling him that the mayor's beloved team may well face
the Texas Rangers in the playoffs this year. Bush, a former owner
of the Rangers, quickly shot back, ``Wait a minute, Mr. Mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rivalry that has been of biggest concern to Republican
politicians regarding New York state is that between Giuliani and
Pataki, both of whom harbor ambitions for higher office.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Giuliani had only nice things to say about the governor.
Asked if Pataki would make a good vice presidential nominee, the
mayor said: ``Yes, I do. I think that it's premature and
presumptuous to support anybody for vice president at this stage,
but I think Governor Pataki has the kind of record of leadership,
the kind of philosophy, the kind of approach to government so he
would be an excellent choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also professed to have no interest in serving as
attorney general in a Bush administration. ``That is not one of my
preferences,'' he said. ``I haven't talked to anyone about being
attorney general. The thing that I am focusing on and the question
that I am resolving is about running for the Senate, solely that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani said he would welcome a return to the political
philosophies of the days when he served at the Justice Department
during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a good deal of the day yesterday at the Reagan Library
and Museum and it focused me on just how much this country is in
need of the kind of leadership that we had during the Reagan-Bush
administration,'' he said, ``the kind of focus in our foreign
policy, the kind of support of our military that we had then, the
kind of sense of unified purpose that Americans had.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
