u s BC-BKN-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT &LR;      10-01 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCHALE AND THOMPSON LEAD LATEST HALL CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mass. _ In one corner of the hotel ballroom, a
smiling Kevin McHale doled out a healthy supply of one-liners,
including, ``I used to have pictures of Bill Walton on my wall as a
kid, he's so old.'' Across the room, an introspective John Thompson
said he would probably be remembered for ``things that have kept me
out of the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale, whose repertory of post moves helped bring the Boston
Celtics three championships in the 1980s, and Thompson, who for 27
years was a domineering sideline presence at Georgetown University,
took divergent paths to the Springfield Civic Center on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Carefree or controversial, their contributions to the game
earned them enshrinement in the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall
of Fame, along with Wayne Embry, Billie Moore and the late Fred
Zollner.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who resigned from coaching at Georgetown on Jan. 8
with a record of 596-239, won one national title and turned
Georgetown into a perennial power by relying almost exclusively on
black players.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond coaching eight first-round draft choices, 75 of 77
players who remained at Georgetown for four years under Thompson
received their degrees. His legacy also includes a hard-line stance
on the unfairness of standardized tests by the National Collegiate
Athletic Association, an issue the NCAA recently gave credence to,
and a disappointing bronze medal as the coach of the 1988 U.S.
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   McHale, the gangly kid from Hibbing, Minn., who gave up hockey
when he sprouted to 6 feet 11 inches, played in the NBA for 13
seasons. He made the All-Star team seven times and played on what
is generally regarded as the best front line of all time with Larry
Bird and Robert Parish _ a threesome that won three NBA titles,
nine Atlantic Division championships and six Eastern Conference
titles.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Embry _ who were backups for Bill Russell during
their playing days _ and McHale became the 26th, 27th and 28th
Celtics to be enshrined. They all dusted off Red Auerbach stories,
including Thompson, who made the mistake of not putting a contract
in writing with his new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember telling Warren Brown I didn't care how much he paid
me, I just wanted to make the team first,'' Thompson said to the
former Celtics owner after he was drafted. ``I said: `Mr. Brown, if
you cut me, no matter what I tell you, I'm not going to get a dime
out of it. Let me make the team, and I'll come back and tell you
what I think I should have.' Well, when I came back, Mr. Brown had
passed away and I was in a smoke-filled room with a man eating
Chinese food, looking at me. I said, `Oh, no.' Red was sitting in
the room, waiting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Embry, the five-time All-Star and NBA executive, was honored
Friday night as a contributor; Moore was a women's coaching pioneer
who won national championships at Cal-State Fullerton and UCLA, and
Zollner was the Pistons' patriarch and longest-tenured owner of an
original NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   Embry seemed the most affected by the induction, calling the
occasion ``the happiest day of my life.'' The 62-year-old president
of the Cleveland Cavaliers, who last season handed over the general
manager duties to Jim Paxson, was the first African-American to
hold a general manager post in any sport when he was hired by the
Milwaukee Bucks in 1972, a year after his 11-year playing career
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond winning two national titles, Moore coached the first U.S.
Olympic women's team to a silver medal in Montreal in 1976. The
eighth coach in women's basketball history to reach 400 victories,
her players included the Hall of Famers Ann Meyers and Denise
Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Zollner died in 1982 at the age of 81, but his contributions
were remembered Friday night by Carl Bennett, the general manager
and coach of the Fort Wayne Zollner Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Zollner helped the NBA weather financial crises its first few
seasons, contributing money, transportation and personnel to insure
the fledgling league's survival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
