<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4125 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-BUCHANAN-CANCELED-TEX     10-01 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-CANCELED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GROUP CANCELS BUCHANAN APPEARANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A Texas oil industry group canceled two
speeches by GOP presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan because of low
interest, officials of the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, whose high-profile interest in the Reform Party has
irritated some Republicans, was invited to speak to the North Texas
Oil and Gas Association next week at gatherings in Dallas and
Wichita Falls. But no one registered for the Dallas event, and only
eight people signed up in Wichita Falls, said Alex Mills, the
association's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the group's members concur with Buchanan's
protectionist views on oil and gas trade, his anticipated bolt from
the GOP to the Reform Party and his recent comments on Hitler were
not well-received, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he'd be a great draw. He is a national figure, and
he is thought-provoking,'' Mills said. ``He is making people think,
and we like to have thought-provoking figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Association members also were concerned that a Buchanan
third-party candidacy would siphon off votes from the Republican
Party, just as Ross Perot's independent candidacy did in 1992,
Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a sour taste in our members' mouths about Ross
Perot's run as a third-party candidate that got Bill Clinton
elected,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign spokeswoman would not comment on the canceled
speeches. She said Buchanan will attend a private reception in
Dallas on Tuesday night and on Wednesday will autograph his book _
``A Republic, Not an Empire'' _ at a Borders bookstore in north
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has said his critics are unfairly attacking his book,
one he has described as a ``boring, scholarly work on foreign
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Buchanan says that Hitler's Third Reich was no
threat to the United States after 1940 and that Allied guarantees
to Poland brought war to the Continent and gave the Soviet Union's
communist government two extra years to prepare for Germany's
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who is the GOP front-runner, and Republican
presidential contenders such as Ariz. Sen. John McCain, Elizabeth
Dole and Steve Forbes have criticized Buchanan for the writings.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Republicans should welcome Buchanan's anticipated
switch from the GOP to the Reform Party. Bush has said he hopes
Buchanan will remain a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he hopes to make a decision this month after
talking to Reform Party founder Perot and to Minnesota Gov. Jesse
Ventura, the party's highest-ranking elected official.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2116EDT &QL; 
