u f BC-FLEET-BOARD-BOS &LR;      10-01 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BOARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TO DOMINATE BOARD OF MERGED BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Having absorbed its former rival, BankBoston Corp.,
Fleet Financial Group Inc. has established a new corporate board
that reflects its chief executive's strong hand in shaping the new
company, sources familiar with the matter said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's new 22-seat board is composed of 12 members of Fleet's
old 22-seat board and 10 members of BankBoston's 17-seat board.
</P>
<P>
   Gone in the new order are several strategic allies of Charles K.
Gifford, head of the old BankBoston and now the number two
executive under Terrence Murray, Fleet's leader.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Gifford allies not on the new Fleet board include
Wayne A. Budd, the president of Bell Atlantic-New England, and
William C. Van Faasen, president and chief executive of Blue
Cross-Blue Shield of Massachusetts, according to the sources. Both
men were widely regarded as strong supporters of Gifford, who is on
the new board.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of a board might seem esoteric to casual
observers, but the choices reflect a business's heart, soul, and
character _ especially when the company is at the center of New
England's clubby banking world. Corporate boards represent the
interests of shareholders and oversee management. Members sit on
committees that set strategic agendas and policies, and must
approve all mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fleet expects to announce its new board next week, and a
complete list of appointees was not available Friday. Fleet
spokesman James Mahoney declined to comment, while two BankBoston
officials did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Banking analysts could not be reached for immediate comment. But
one seasoned East Coast business executive said the choices
reflected moves by Murray to strengthen his hold over the nation's
eighth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry is consolidating his power,'' said the source, who is
familiar with the matter. BankBoston, a 215-year-old institution
that was America's oldest bank, ceased to exist Friday as an
independent entity.
</P>
<P>
   One BankBoston board member who has a place on the the new Fleet
board is William F. Connell, chief executive of Connell Limited
Partnership in Boston. Connell, a friend of both Gifford and
Murray, is widely credited with having played a major role in
bringing the two companies together in March, when they announced
their $16 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said two other prominent BankBoston board members _
Alfred M. Zeien, the retired chief executive of The Gillette Co.,
and Thomas B. Wheeler, the chairman of Massachusetts Mutual Life
Insurance Co. _ would not sit on the new Fleet board. But
BankBoston board member Gary L. Countryman, chairman of Liberty
Mutual Insurance Co., will.
</P>
<P>
   Old Fleet board members not on the new board include Samuel O.
Thier president and chief executive of Partners HealthCare System
Inc.; Kim Clark, dean of Harvard Business School; and John R.
Riedman, chairman of Riedman Corp., a Rochester-based insurance
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Old Fleet board members who will stay include two longtime
Murray allies _ Paul J. Choquette Jr., chief executive of Gilbane
Building Co., a Providence-based construction firm, and James F.
Hardymon, retired chairman and chief executive of Textron Inc., a
corporate conglomerate also based in Providence, where Fleet was
headquartered before moving to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Current Fleet members Marian L. Heard, head of the United Way of
Massachusetts, and Joel B. Alvord, who owns a venture-capital
buyout firm, are also on the new board. Alvord was head of Shawmut
National Corp., the Boston bank that Murray acquired in 1995 in a
deal that moved Fleet's headquarters to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When he struck his merger deal with Gifford, Murray amended
Fleet's charter to require an 80 percent vote by the board, or 17.6
members, to remove Gifford from the new company. Gifford is
scheduled to take the reins of the new Fleet at the end of 2001,
when Murray will retire.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet filed a document Friday with the Securities &AMP; Exchange
Commission that referred to the new company as Fleet Boston Corp.
Murray is considering using that name for the holding company, but
has insisted on calling the bank proper Fleet Financial Group Inc.
A Fleet spokesman said the name is a temporary one until a final
decision is reached next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
