<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO INDUSTRY'S SALES FOR '99 MODEL YEAR BROKE '86 RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Customers lured by hefty rebates bought more than 16
million new cars, sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickup
trucks in the 1999 model year, breaking the sales record set in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good times,'' said Roy Roberts, group vice president
of sales, service and marketing for General Motors Corp., which had
its best model-year results in a decade. ``The combination of
affordable vehicles, high employment and buying momentum continues
to propel us to record levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Most automakers reported strong September sales Friday, closing
out the 1999 model year on a strong note.
</P>
<P>
   Sales reported for the model year, which traditionally runs
through the end of September, so far total about 16.3 million
vehicles, already surpassing the 1986 sales record of 15.8 million,
said James Bush, publisher of Ward's Automotive Reports. That tally
doesn't include September sales for Ford Motor Co., the
second-largest automaker, which is scheduled to announce its
results Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is strong, and increasingly the auto companies are
buying the sales with aggressive incentive programs, and they can
afford to do that because of their continued success in containing
costs,'' Bush said. The incentives, offered by many automakers,
come in the form of rebates, discounted financing and cheap monthly
payments on leases.
</P>
<P>
   GM said its sales for the 1999 model year totaled 5,006,076 cars
and trucks, a 9 percent increase over 1998. However, the company
Friday turned in mixed results for September. Its overall sales for
the month rose 8.9 percent compared to the same period a year ago,
with its sales of sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickup
trucks jumping 30.2 percent because of strong sales of full-sized
pickups and sport utility vehicles. But its car sales dropped 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler Corp. said sales for its Dodge, Chrysler,
Plymouth and Jeep brands hit a record 2,651,090 for the 1999 model
year, up 8 percent from 1998. For the month of September, sales for
those brands rose 7.3 percent. Car sales rose 4.9 percent and truck
sales rose 8.4 percent. Small cars, small pickups and minivans
turned in weak showings, but larger sedans and sport utility
vehicles sold briskly.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Mercedes-Benz unit saw its sales rise 9.6 percent,
largely because of the continued popularity of its M-class sport
utility vehicle and its E320 sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect Ford, which has been selling fewer discounted
cars to rental fleets this year than last year, to report Monday
that its sales fell between 2 percent and 4 percent in September.
George Pipas, Ford's manager of sales analysis, said that for the
industry as a whole, 1999 was ``easily the best model year in
history.'' The auto industry is also expected to sell more cars
this calendar year than in any previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota sold 1,465,399 cars and trucks in the 1999 model year, up
13.2 percent from the year before. The company said its September
sales rose 10.4 percent, with strong sales of its bread-and-butter
Camry sedan, its Tundra pickup truck and its Sienna minivan. Car
sales rose 4.2 percent, while truck sales rose 20.6 percent. ``Nine
months of sustained industry growth has surprised everyone,'' said
Jim Press, executive vice president of Toyota's American unit.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts earlier this week scrambled to revise their
estimates for industry sales upward. On Wednesday, John Casesa of
Merrill Lynch raised his estimate for the year's sales from 16.2
million to 16.6 million. David B. Healy of Burnham Securities
raised his estimate from 16.6 million to 16.8 million, well above
last year's 15.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Honda sold a record 1,067,468 cars and trucks in the 1999 model
year, up 7.4 percent from the year before. Honda's September sales
rose 9.7 percent from the same period a year ago. The increase was
due to strong sales of Honda's Odyssey minivan and its Accord and
Acura TL sedans. Honda's car sales rose 3.8 percent, while its
truck sales jumped 42.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan sold 653,771 cars and trucks in the 1999 model year, up
4.6 percent from the year before. The company said its September
sales rose 19.8 percent this year, with car sales up 12.7 percent
and truck sales up 29.3 percent. The increase came from strong
sales of its Xterra sport utility vehicle, Quest minivan and Maxima
and Altima sedans, and from sales of its Infiniti luxury division.
</P>
<P>
   Other automakers also reported strong September sales Friday.
Volkswagen sales rose 52.3 percent in September compared to the
same month in 1998, and the company said it had already sold more
cars this year than it did in all of 1998. Subaru said its sales
rose 17 percent for the month compared to the previous year, while
Isuzu's sales went up 55.7 percent, Mitsubishi's increased by 36
percent and Land Rover's rose 60.8 percent for the period.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai said its sales rose 82.5 percent in September. Audi said
it sales rose 60.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      10-01 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN MUSEUM EXPANDS CHARGES AGAINST GIULIANI IN LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn Museum of Art on Friday refined its
lawsuit against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, contending for the first
time that the mayor should be held personally liable for his
campaign to cut off public financing and evict the museum on the
basis of his displeasure with an exhibition of British art.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, ``Sensation,'' is to open to the public
Saturday, and several protests were planned by groups angered at
various pieces in the collection, which includes dead cows sliced
and suspended in formaldehyde and a portrait of the Virgin Mary
with a breast fashioned from elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has called the portrait ``sick stuff,'' but the museum
asserted in a federal lawsuit this week that Giuliani had violated
the First Amendment when he withheld public funds from the museum
and then began eviction proceedings because the museum refused to
withdraw the disputed works.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the museum amended its complaint. In addition to the
First Amendment claims, the museum now contends that the mayor, by
singling out the museum for punishment, has violated the
Constitution's guarantee of equal protection under the law. In a
third allegation, the museum has accused Giuliani of violating the
state constitution and the City Charter by refusing to release
money already appropriated to the museum by the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the museum's initial lawsuit was against Giuliani ``in
his official capacity,'' the amended lawsuit is directed against
Giuliani ``individually and in his official capacity.'' It also
seeks punitive damages, not simply lawyers' fees, in addition to a
judicial declaration forbidding the mayor from punishing the museum
in any way for staging the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   City officials did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of protesters gathered in front of the museum Friday
night to denounce the mayor. ``Lust for higher office and cultural
terrorism _ that offends my religion,'' read one protest placard.
Speaker after speaker warned of a chilling effect on all local arts
institutions should the mayor prevail. The demonstration, organized
by the New York Civil Liberties Union and People for the American
Way, seemed a sign of things to come Saturday, with counter
protests scheduled by animal-rights and religious groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
