<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-01 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYROLL NO INDICATOR OF PLAYOFF HOPES IN BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How would you like to be Peter Angelos, owner of the Baltimore
Orioles, and have the second highest payroll in major league
baseball ($86.4 million) but your team doesn't make the playoffs.
This has been a strange year in baseball. In recent years, the top
eight teams in payroll generally make the playoffs. Not so in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Player salaries:
</P>
<P>
   1.. NY Yankees $89.5 million
</P>
<P>
   2. Orioles $86.4m
</P>
<P>
   3. Dodgers $85.7m
</P>
<P>
   4. Mets $79.6m
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles and Dodgers are already out. And the Mets are on the
way out. Cincinnati is the only team in the majors with a payroll
under $50 million to make the postseason, if they hang on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtics coach Rick Pitino on second-year man Paul Pierce: ``He
is on his way to being one of the best players in the league. I
have never seen anyone work as hard as Paul has this offseason.
Every day he has been working out for five hours. Five hours. His
work ethic is fabulous. He wants to be a great player, and because
of the way he works at the game, he will be a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino says the Lakers and San Antonio are the two best teams in
the league, but feels the Eastern Conference is ``wide open'' and
that his team will make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first year we overachieved. The second year we were a bad
team. This year we will be better and more competitive. People say
we pressed too much last season. In reality, we pressed about 10
percent of the time. We weren't in good enough shape as a team to
press more than that. And this year, we will press, maybe 30
percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The thing that impressed the Giants' players and staff most
about Drew Bledsoe last Sunday night was the way he was unfazed in
the pocket even with defenders flying all around him. ``He never
moved once,'' said a top Giant executive. ``His feet stayed still,
and he got the ball out of his hand in a hurry. There's no one in
the league throwing the ball the way he is. No one.'' Says Chris
Palmer, head coach of the Browns who are next up on the Bledsoe
menu: ``The three games he has played this year are MVP season kind
of games. He is in total command of what he is doing.'' . . . Not
all things are rosy for the Red Sox. They have yet to be paid by
JCS, one of the two television networks broadcasting their games.
JCS got into the picture late, just before the start of the season,
and reportedly owes the Sox $10 million in rights fees. According
to some in the organization, the team has not been paid in full,
and wonders if the money is coming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seems like Friday, I was sitting in the Celtic coaches'
locker room, listening to Bill Fitch relay a message from a mutual
friend. ``He said the big kid from Minnesota is the best player on
the team and if we have a chance to get him, he's the kid we should
go after.'' Fitch was telling Red Auerbach of a conversation he had
the night before with Indiana coach Bob Knight. Knight had coached
the United States in the Pan-Am games that summer, which had all of
the top US college players. At that point, Kevin McHale was not one
of the bigger names. Knight, who has a close friendship with
Auerbach, passed it on, and the Celtics followed up . . . Speaking
of Auerbach, who was 82 a couple of weeks back, he told a group at
the annual Red Auerbach Youth Foundation Golf Tourney this week,
``I've been down to see my statue (in Quincy Market Place) four or
five times. Every time I see it, I get scared. Only dead guys have
statues. But I got news for you. I'm not ready go yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any sports fan with a brain knows by now the ESPN top 100
athletes of the century was picked by a bunch of clowns. How else
could you describe a group that picked Bill Russell at 18. Here's
Russell's unmatched career of championships: Thirteen NBA seasons,
11 championships. His final two collegiate seasons at San
Francisco, two national championships and a 56-game winning streak.
Also, one gold medal in the Olympics. So in 15 years of top-level
competition, he walked away with 14 championship medals. No one
else can match that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There has never been a bigger bunch of whiners and sore losers
as the European team that jetted home after the Ryder Cup with
tears on their blazers. Crybabies all. Did we hear griping about
the crowd or the conduct of the US team after Friday's play, when
Europe was ahead, 6-2? Nope. Did we hear any bellyaching after
Saturday when they went up, 10 to 6, and everyone conceded them the
Cup. Nope. Only when they lost were the fans unruly slugs, and the
US players a bunch of unsophisticated bums. The truth: it hurts
when you are supposed to have a walkover, and suddenly the putts
stop falling. Unsportsmanlike conduct had nothing to do with the
way the US team came back to win Sunday. The US team played better
when it counted most. I've spoken to more than 25 people this week
who were at Brookline Sunday and asked them the same question: Did
you hear anyone verbally insult the Europoean players? Every answer
was the same. No. In fact, many thought the crowd as overly
supportive of the European players. It is a shame that a vast
majority of what was reported in the aftermath was the beefing by
the losers, instead of praising the marvelous job the members of
The Country Club did putting this show on. There has never been
anything like it in sports in the history of this city. The members
are to be congratulated. Many of them gave up a good part of their
lives the last three or four years to pull it together. The
membership gave up their golf course for long periods to be primed
for the event. All of their work allowed the businesses in Boston
to gain more than $150 million in revenue. ``We have heard nothing
but the best of comments,'' says John Cornish, who chaired the
Ryder Cup committee. ``It couldn't have worked out any better for
us. And then we wound up with the greatest Ryder Cup in history on
top of it.'' I asked Cornish his most cherished memory: ``I have
not seen this reported anywhere, but I think it was the most moving
thing I experienced the entire week,'' he said. ``I was the marshal
with the first group, (Tom) Lehman and (Lee) Westwood. On the first
tee, Sunday morning, just as (Lehman) was to hit the first ball,
the fans around the tee started singing the national anthem. Tom
backed away, then went over and led the gorup in singing the
anthem. It was really moving, and it turned out to be a perfect way
to start the day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I pointed out that Pedro Martinez will be the first man to
average 13 strikeouts per game in major league history, and a
couple of fans wrote to point out that he'll have perhaps the best
strikeout-to-walk ratio ever, giving up just 37 walks and striking
out 312, one walk in every 8.43 strikeouts. Jim Pringle of Vineyard
Haven pointed out that pitching in the American League, Pedro had
to pitch against designated hitters, not pitchers . . . And last,
but not least, Rich Kreswick, who runs the FleetCenter, has just
been hired by the Bruins as their executive vice president. ``He
will still run the building like he has been doing,'' says Sinden.
``But now he will also work for the Bruins, running the business
side of the operation. He will head up marketing, ticketing, and
business side. He won't be involved in the hockey. I think it's a
great addition to our team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
