<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FORFEIT02-COX     10-01 1607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORFEIT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forfeiture law funds police targeting drug dealers
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In south Florida, when police
investigate a crime, they are thinking about more than just who
should be arrested and what the charges should be.
</P>
<P>
   They're also wondering if there's any property involved that the
police department can keep for itself.
</P>
<P>
   They do it all the time: grabbing a car used to drive to a drug
deal; snapping up tools used to strip a stolen car; taking money
used to buy and sell drugs; or keeping a computer used to download
child pornography. They can take any property used in a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Police see the forfeiture law as one of their most powerful
weapons against crime. But a Palm Beach Post examination of how the
law is used locally shows:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes innocent people lose their property. For example, if
you lend your car to someone to buy groceries and they get caught
buying crack instead, the police can take your car and you may not
get it back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly half the people whose property is seized _ and a third
of those who eventually lose it in court _ are not convicted of a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Poor defendants are hurt by the law more than the big-time
drug dealers and criminals who can afford to hire lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Even some police and their lawyers admit that police make
decisions on seized property based on money, not justice.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing property has become standard police practice, one that's
also extraordinarily profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Florida collected $124 million this way from April
1996 to March 1999 _ including $7.4 million seized in Palm Beach
County, the third-highest total for any county. Millions more was
collected by federal authorities and shared with local police.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office hauled in $4.3 million,
making it the most aggressive agency in the county. St. Lucie
County authorities seized just over $1 million in that time, and
police in Martin County collected $501,000.
</P>
<P>
   With this money, the police can bankroll long investigations,
buy high-tech equipment, meet state and federal grant goals, and
assist crime prevention programs. Last year, for example, the Palm
Beach County Sheriff's Office used $453,000 in seized assets to
buy, among other things, six video cameras for patrol cars, 10
bullet-proof vests, 25 bicycles, and 27 ``less lethal'' weapons
that fire beanbags and polyurethane bullets. The sheriff's office
also donated $328,000 to various youth groups and anti-drug
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Police are supposed to look at forfeitures not as a way to make
money, but as a way to prevent crime by stripping criminals of
their tainted wealth. But in practice, as the police and property
owners duel over the stakes, nearly every move and counter-move is
made with money in mind: The police want to collect as much money
as possible while spending little, and property owners try to get
back as much as they can without placing themselves at risk in
criminal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like its own little ball park,'' said Catherine Kozol,
legal adviser to the Delray Beach Police Department. ``It's kind of
a game. I hate to say it that way, but it is. It's who can outsmart
who.''
</P>
<P>
   The peculiar nature of forfeiture law has spawned a court system
unto itself _ one that blends criminal issues with the rules of a
civil lawsuit. Defense lawyers say this system is harder on the
poor than on high-powered drug traffickers. For every major seizure
that can be linked to a large drug organization, police seize
dozens of cars from people in possession of small amounts of drugs,
or those accused of a comparably minor crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute had some good intentions to punish the big-time
trafficker,'' said Stephen Melnick, a lawyer who once prosecuted
forfeiture cases for the Boca Raton Police Department. ``But the
only one getting punished is the small-time user.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They (police) use forfeiture law to raise money,'' said Jim
Eisenberg, a West Palm Beach defense lawyer who handles dozens of
seizures every year. ``It's the most regressive tax that's ever
been established. It's the poor that get hit the hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a seizure has been made, the owner is thrust into a
complicated legal process separate from any criminal charges he may
face.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the police can seize property without even arresting
anyone. Forfeiture law is based on the premise that the property
itself is at fault, regardless of who owns it. The standard of
proof needed for the police to keep property is lower than the
standard necessary to make an arrest. Property owners must fight
the police at their own expense, and even those who are cleared of
criminal charges can lose their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   A Palm Beach Post analysis of 678 seizures in Palm Beach County
from 1996 to 1998 shows that property owners who have their
belongings taken by the police are found guilty in about 50 percent
of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Post analysis shows that this system can put the
poor at a disadvantage. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Defendants represented by the public defender in criminal
court are more likely to lose their property entirely, because the
public defender is barred from handling forfeiture cases. Private
lawyers hired to fight the criminal charges typically negotiate a
settlement with the police in return for the property.
</P>
<P>
   _ Because they didn't have a lawyer, some defendants have lost
their property for as little as a $5 crack rock, even though
seizures over such a small amount of drugs could be considered an
excessive fine under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   _ So-called ``innocent owners,'' those whose cars were used in a
crime without their knowledge, sometimes must pay an
``administrative fee'' to get their cars back _ usually about $250.
</P>
<P>
   _ Often the police will choose not to use the forfeiture law
after taking small amounts of cash _ but in many cases they still
get to keep the money. The Delray Beach police have kept as little
as $32 belonging to a defendant, calling the cash abandoned
property after the criminal case has concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, police in Palm Beach County have seized all
sorts of items: guns, cameras, computers, boats, engines, cellular
phones, Jet Skis, jewelry, even an airplane (which crashed with 777
pounds of cocaine on board) and a golf cart (the getaway car in a
Boca Raton burglary). But cash and cars are the most common.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Lucie County, the Sheriff's Office files just two or
three forfeiture cases a month. But because it often costs more to
file the cases than it's worth, the Sheriff's Office usually just
levies fees _ usually between $250 and $750 _ that suspects have to
pay to get vehicles back.
</P>
<P>
   Most forfeitures stem from drug cases. Several times, state
troopers have found bundles of cash concealed in cars traveling on
the highway _ sometimes drug money is kept in a secret compartment,
or it's wrapped in sheets of fabric softener to throw off
drug-sniffing dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 678 cases reviewed, the police found $10,000 or more in
cash 62 times. Twenty-four of those came aboard Greyhounds or other
interstate buses, which are routinely searched by sheriff's
deputies looking for couriers moving drugs or cash for drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Over that same time, 432 cars and trucks were taken by police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is applied against whoever is caught with
contraband,'' said Jim Hicks, a lawyer who prosecutes forfeitures
for the Lake Worth police. ``It's disingenuous to say we are
punishing the little guy when the little guy has $100,000 in his
car that he can't explain.''
</P>
<P>
   LARGE DEPARTMENTS THE MOST AGGRESSIVE
</P>
<P>
   The most aggressive police departments are typically the largest
_ those with full-time attorneys. The sheriff's office and police
in West Palm Beach, Delray Beach and Boca Raton account for 86
percent of the assets seized in the county, according to state
records.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, police use the seizure law in tandem with an
arrest; it's the exception when officers simply take property
because they believe it's part of a crime. Of the 678 seizures
reviewed, an arrest was made 86 percent of the time; in 75 percent
of the cases, it was the owner who was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   But there were 94 cases where property was taken even though no
one was arrested. And in 72 other instances, the owner had to pay
the police or lose his or her belongings even though the criminal
charges were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Jorge Ignacio Alvarez, 27, of South Bay.
On the night of July 1, 1997, Alvarez was driving home with a
girlfriend in his 1993 Mustang when he was pulled over because his
license tag light was out. The deputy asked to search the car, and
found more than a half-pound of marijuana in a shopping bag under
the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez and his girlfriend, Jennifer Baker, were charged with
felony marijuana possession. The charges against Alvarez were
dropped after Baker was placed in a pretrial intervention program.
But that didn't help Alvarez get his Mustang back. After paying a
lawyer to fight his criminal case, he had nothing left with which
to bargain with the sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ran out of money,'' said Alvarez, who earns $11 an hour
at a sugar mill. ``I thought that once they dropped the charges I
would get the car back ... I had just finished paying for it when
it was taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez now drives a 14-year-old Oldsmobile his grandfather
bought for him for $800. His Mustang was later used by a sheriff's
deputy as an undercover car.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
