<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA'S WRIST BRUISED, NOT BROKEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra received the
expected good news Friday _ that his right wrist was bruised and
not broken _ but Boston manager Jimy Williams saw extra value in
his shortstop's trip back to Boston for the definitive opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It alleviates the concern that (Garciaparra) had,'' said
Williams after being notified of the medical results. Williams
added that Garciaparra had suggested that he return to Boston for
the examination, ``and it was a good suggestion by Nomar, to go
back to Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Team physician Arthur Pappas examined Garciaparra Friday at the
University of Massachusetts Medical Center in Worcester.
Garciaparra was hit by a pitch during last Saturday's game at
Fenway Park against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bone looks fine,'' said Pappas. ``But there is a tendon
that travels under the bone that is bruised and that tendon is
swollen. Extra stress on the tendon can be painful such as a
checked swing, but it doesn't bother Nomar when he makes good
contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas said he expects Garciaparra to take several days off but
should be fine for the American League playoffs, which begin
Wednesday. Garciaparra is expected to be back with the Red Sox
Sunday in Baltimore and will definitely sit out Saturday night's
game. Whether he plays in the season finale, said Williams, won't
be determined until he has a chance to talk with his shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he is not concerned even if Garciaparra, who leads
the AL in hitting, sits out this entire series in Baltimore. ``We
still have that workout day Tuesday (in Cleveland or Texas), which
will allow him to evaluate himself,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra left the team before Thursday's night game in
Chicago. On Wednesday, when the Red Sox clinched their wild-card
berth, Garciaprra led the team to victory with a key two-run home
run and sealed the victory with an unassisted double play to end
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't even close to 100 percent for that game,'' said
Williams, ``but, damn . . . that'd be a career game for me. That's
pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But the soreness in his wrist concerned Garciaparra and he
wanted to clear his mind of any worry, said Williams. Now,
``mentally he feels a lot better and physically, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams again would not disclose the Red Sox' third and fourth
starting pitchers in the division series, but left little doubt
that it would be Ramon Martinez and Kent Mercker. ``You guys are
smart guys,'' said Williams, ``you see what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez will start Saturday for the Red Sox against
Baltimore and Williams would like to see him throw approximately
90-100 pitches. The third playoff game is scheduled for Oct. 9,
meaning Martinez will have a full week's rest. Mercker will be
Boston's starter Sunday. Pedro Martinez will pitch the opener of
the playoff series, with Bret Saberhagen pitching the second game.
</P>
<P>
   What has impressed Williams in Ramon Martinez's comeback from
reconstructive arm surgery is that his stamina has been strong. A
pitcher's legs weaken before his arm, said the manager, ``and I
thought his legs have been good. He looks strong to me out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also will apparently wait until the final moments
Tuesday or Wednesday before setting his playoff roster. If the Red
Sox choose to go with 11 pitchers, as Williams seems to be leaning,
it may be that rookie third baseman Wilton Veras or DH-first
baseman Reggie Jefferson won't make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Williams intends to bring as many as 28 or 29
players to the playoff site and hopefully have them dress and be in
the dugout. The American League, and the opposing team, would have
to approve inactive players being in uniform, said Williams, but he
would prefer the inactive players be with the team as a gesture of
their contributions to the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 for the Sox (either in Cleveland or Texas) is scheduled
for Fox at 8:07 p.m., and Game 2 will be the following afternoon at
4:09 on ESPN . . . Williams gave third baseman John Valentin the
night off Friday, but said the veteran would be back in the lineup
Saturday as a final prep for the playoffs. ``I'm ready to go,''
said Valentin, whose achy left knee left him on the disabled list
three weeks ago. ``I'm pretty excited about being in the playoffs
and I hope everybody feels the same way I do.'' Valentin said he is
trying to recover his timing at the plate (``Sometimes it's there,
sometimes not; it depends on the pitcher'') but said he is both
physically and mentally ready for the playoffs . . . Pedro Martinez
was named the American League pitcher of the month for September,
the fourth time Martinez has won the award this season. It marked
the first time any major league pitcher has won the award four
times (out of six months) in one season. Martinez is expected to
pitch an inning Saturday after his brother Ramon exits. The two
brothers pitched in the same game six years ago when they were with
Los Angeles . . . Mike Port, the Red Sox' vice president for
baseball operations, is one of several candidates for the vacant
general manager's position with the Seattle Mariners. ``Mike's a
versatile baseball executive,'' said Red Sox GM Dan Duquette, ``and
has done a very nice job for the Red Sox.'' Port, the former
California Angels GM, has been with the Red Sox since 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
