<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS END THREAT TO BLOCK COURT NOMINEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Calif., N.Y., Mo.)  (js) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An impasse over confirming federal judges ended
Friday as Senate Democrats gave up their efforts to block a vote on
a judicial candidate favored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, the Utah
Republican who is chairman of the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In order to press a point, Democrats had threatened a filibuster
against all the judicial nominees of President Clinton, a fellow
Democrat. The Senate Democrats had complained that the Republicans
were pushing through Ted Stewart, a Republican from Utah, who had
only been nominated in July, while other Clinton nominees had been
waiting years to be considered by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton nominated Stewart as a courtesy to Hatch and with the
hope that the gesture would speed up confirmation of several other
Democratic nominees to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Under Friday's agreement, Stewart, along with two other
nominees, will be voted on by the full Senate on Tuesday. In
dropping their opposition, the Democrats ended the logjam, but may
have received little in return beyond a vague promise to consider
the candidates who have been held up the longest.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the Democrats will probably not get votes on
Marsha Berzon and Richard A. Paez, two nominees to the U.S. Court
of Appeals for the 9th Circuit, which covers California and several
western states.
</P>
<P>
   Paez has waited nearly four years for a floor vote and Ms.
Berzon almost two years. Democrats said that the Republicans are
trying to defeat Paez by denying him a vote because it would be
politically risky to vote against him on the floor in full public
view.
</P>
<P>
   Nan Aron, the executive director of the Alliance for Justice, a
liberal group that monitors judicial selections and supports the
Paez and Berzon nominations, said of Friday's agreement, ``We're
deeply disappointed that Senate leaders once again failed to
schedule votes on two superb nominees to the federal bench.''
</P>
<P>
   But in breaking the logjam, the Senate on Friday quickly
confirmed two people to the bench. They were Victor Marrero, a New
York lawyer, to be a federal trial judge in Manhattan, and M. James
Lorenz, to a district court seat in California.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over Stewart's nomination threatened to produce a
situation in which no judges would be confirmed until after the
next presidential election. There are 40 vacancies in the U.S.
district courts and 15 on the nation's appeals courts, the level
just below the Supreme Court, a vacancy rate of nearly 8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
