<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PRIVATE-PRISONS02-COX     10-01 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-PRISONS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audit blasts private prison management
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After 10 months in operation, two southeast Georgia
private prisons failed to meet the state's minimum standards in
inmate health care, staffing and security, according to a quarterly
audit.
</P>
<P>
   Critical security posts were not staffed for entire eight-hour
shifts, and inmates had easy access to medications and tools that
could be used as weapons, and more than one-third of the nursing
positions at one prison were vacant, the state Department of
Corrections audit said.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Corp. of America showed ``borderline deliberate
indifference'' in running Wheeler Correctional Facility at Alamo
and the Coffee Correctional Facility in Nicholls, DOC regional
director Johnny Sikes, part of the review team, said in the audit
report.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the problems in the report were not as bad as
they were made to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the facilities are operated in a safe, secure,
humane matter,'' said Jimmy Turner Jr., CCA's director of
operations. ``The taxpayers are saving money by our management.''
</P>
<P>
   CCA receives $90,000 a day to incarcerate almost 2,000 inmates
in the two institutions, which opened in December.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the deficiencies have been raised in other
routine, quarterly audits. Some of the problems are only now being
fixed, DOC spokesman Mike Light said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a large prison corporation and these relatively minor
problems should have been fixed by now,'' said Light. ``These
issues are basic security issues (and) personnel issues.''
</P>
<P>
   There are almost 1,000 medium-security inmates in the Coffee
County prison. The state stopped sending inmates to Wheeler because
of the concerns; its population is 960.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this comes to light because we have close oversight
over the private prisons,'' Light said. ``And we're not putting
(more) inmates in there until we get things right.''
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that both prisons did not have enough guards
and some ``priority'' security posts were not staffed as they
should be. ``No overtime was paid and there was no indication that
an effort was made to fill these positions or cover them in any
way,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates had easy access to tools that could be used as weapons,
like scissors. Turner said there was only one such incident, yet
the report made a single mistake by one employee seem like
continuing, prisonwide problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have certain ways of doing things, within our policies and
procedures, that is different from the people, who are being
subjective, are used to,'' Turner said. ``We are attempting to make
it more clear to those individuals that we are meeting the
requirements by changing some titles. ''
</P>
<P>
   The report said there was no discipline and that ``inmates are
loud and unstructured throughout the facility. ... Inmates act
disrespectfully toward line staff, talking back, ignoring
directives, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner disagreed. ``I just didn't see any disrespect,'' Turner
said. ``I saw more respect at the Coffee facility and the Wheeler
facility than I have at any prison.''
</P>
<P>
   DOC officials said they are most worried about the health care
CCA provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, health care services had deteriorated since the
time of the medical audit on July 22, 1999,'' the report said. ``At
that time, serious concerns were noted, which had not been
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Light said many of the medical problems have been resolved since
the most recent report was written, but ``we still feel there are
some problems with the overall management of the medical area.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said inmates waited more than a week to see a nurse
because of staffing shortages. Dr. Christopher Fletcher, CCA
managing director of health services, said it was more like ``2.7
days from the time the inmate filled out the request.''
</P>
<P>
   The auditors also said narcotics were left on the pharmacy
counter; it took four days to refill medications; nurses sometimes
wrote prescriptions without a doctor's authorization; and the daily
distribution of medications was chaotic and took too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staffing pattern is not deficient,'' Fletcher said. ``We
have added staff beyond what is required. ... The scheduling is
improving gradually. (And) pill call could be shortened.''
</P>
<P>
   Light said the problems at the CCA prison began after the inmate
populations passed 750, moving toward 1,000 prisoners at each. DOC
plans to ask the Georgia Legislature next year for funding to fill
all 1,500 beds at each of the prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, DOC found some problems at a third private prison
in South Georgia, a prison Cornell Corrections Inc. built in
Folkston. Light said that facility now is operating properly.
</P>
<P>
   CCA has plans for 1,500-bed prisons in Jenkins, Wheeler and
Telfair counties. DOC says it has no agreement with CCA for those
facilities; the company has said it will try to lease the cells to
Georgia first before asking other states if they want to send
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
