<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT &LR;      10-01 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: CANDID PIAZZA FAILS TO GRASP THE BIG PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Piazza has been as candid as any player while
the Mets have allowed their once-special season to disintegrate
into praying for a miraculous weekend. Piazza has never been the
type to berate teammates or make bold declarations, but he has been
honest and available, conspicuous traits in the midst of a
phenomenal collapse.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets lost three straight games to the Braves last week,
Piazza admitted they had been walloped and looked nervous. When the
streak continued with three more depressing losses in Philadelphia,
Piazza's rambling answers and contorted facial expressions
indicated how bewildered he was about the Mets' spiral into
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   So it was rather surprising that when Piazza offered his opinion
on the state of the Mets Thursday night, he expressed satisfaction
with a season that has disappeared faster than a slice of pizza at
a fraternity house. Piazza's voice was a curious mixture of
exasperation and pride, unwilling to let this season be remembered
as a total disaster. No, Piazza claimed, he would repeat this again
and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, with these guys here, if we're in the
same position next year, I'll take it,'' Piazza said. ``If we're in
the same position the year after that, I'll take it. I hope we're
always in a position to get to the postseason. I hope this doesn't
sound like we're folding the tent, because we're not. As I said,
our timing is tough. That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is wrong. Simply being in position to make the postseason
is not good enough for the Mets. It is not even close, not after
the way they crumbled last year and not after the way they have
collapsed even more dramatically this year. The Mets are a strong
team, a team that should have made the postseason after investing
$164 million during the off season. Just challenging for a spot is
unacceptable, no matter how many games the Mets wind up winning.
</P>
<P>
   This season is likely to be remembered as torturous, for the
Mets and the fans, especially the last 12 days. Piazza reiterated
his comments outside manager Bobby Valentine's office Friday and
explained that he would take 93 victories over the first 159 games
any time. It sounded like something a leader would say, but it is
hollow. The number of victories in a season is not relevant.
Playing games in October is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're playing for the last weekend to get in, I'd take it
again,'' Piazza said. ``I know, sooner or later, it's inevitable,
these guys are going to come through. When we do, it's going to be
that much sweeter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets probably have botched a journey to the postseason by
losing 8 of 9 games before facing the Pirates Friday night. Blame
Valentine, blame a lack of clutch hitting, blame an erratic bullpen
and blame Chipper Jones. When a team loses this often in pressure
situations, the blame spreads throughout the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   If Piazza were in Cincinnati, where the Reds have a $33 million
payroll and were not expected to reach the playoffs, his comments
would be correct. The Reds should be thrilled to simply challenge
for the postseason, and if they had ever stumbled out of the chase,
it would still have been a memorable season. Because the Mets have
a payroll of around $71 million, have not reached the postseason
since 1988 and occupy the same city as the defending World Series
champions, the scrutiny and the expectations are much different
here.
</P>
<P>
   When Piazza was reminded that another year without a postseason
berth was probably not going to be considered acceptable in New
York, he took umbrage with a realistic comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what?'' he said. ``Acceptable to who? I don't feel
that we have to validate ourselves. I think it's obviously an
unfortunate situation we put ourselves in, but by no means is this
a tragedy. Tragedies are little kids getting cancer. I think you
have to have perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Perspective is reality, and reality tells Piazza that the Mets
will make changes after two straight destructions. Valentine could
go, and though he is the same manager who guided the Mets to the
finest record in the major leagues for a three-month stretch, he
probably has to be fired. A fresh start would be necessary to
distance the Mets from the stench of the last two Septembers, but a
true No. 1 starter and a corner outfielder who can play defense and
go deep would be more vital than a new manager scribbling out a
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   As Piazza spoke about what has gone awry with the Mets, he
remembered to mention that they were not mathematically eliminated
before Friday night's games. Someone told Piazza that the Mets
could make those who have already buried them look silly by somehow
wriggling into the playoffs. Piazza smiled, considered the
possibility and expressed more honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the planets are lined up the right way,'' he said, ``I
guess that could happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
