<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4156 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-POLICE     10-01 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-POLICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHBROOK TALKED TO POLICE CHIEF OVER THE YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB MAHLBURG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Larry Gene Ashbrook, the jobless loner who
killed seven people and fatally shot himself at a Baptist church,
rarely talked to his neighbors or even his family. But he spoke
regularly with someone else: Police Chief Thomas Windham.
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook called Windham off and on for years and once visited
Windham's office for rambling conversations about unemployment, his
years in the Navy and concerns that police might be following him,
Windham said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Windham said he talked with Ashbrook at least four or five
times, the last occasion just a few months before the shootings.
Windham said Ashbrook sounded lonely and paranoid, but never
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make anything out of it other than, here's a guy who
lost his job,'' Windham said. ``He always seemed like a nice enough
guy to me. It's an understatement now to say that's a misperception
of him, but nothing in those conversations would ever signal he was
a violent individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook walked into Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth with
two handguns, denounced the Baptist faith and opened fire at youth
meeting Sept. 15. In addition to the people he killed, he wounded
seven more.
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings, Windham said, he told police officials and
the city manager about the conversations. He said he didn't reveal
them publicly until a reporter asked Friday because he feared that
it would disrupt the city's emotional healing.
</P>
<P>
   Windham said he began talking to Ashbrook about 1990, when
Ashbrook called to say he believed that he had lost a job because
police had gone to his workplace and that police were following
him. Windham said he assured Ashbrook that neither allegation was
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a number of conversations with him after that,'' Windham
said. ``He would call me on occasion. It was very interesting,
because he would never tell me who he was. He would just start a
conversation. Eventually, I picked up on things he said, and I'd
say, `Larry, you rascal, how you doing?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Windham said he hadn't heard from Ashbrook in several years when
Ashbrook called him a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `How are you doing?' He said: `Not too good. My father
died.' I said, `I'm very sorry to hear that.' He said: `All he left
me was debts. I don't have a job. I haven't worked for years, and I
guess I'm going to lose my house because it's not paid for, and I
don't have any way to pay for it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't angry, and he really wasn't distraught. It was just
a voice of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook never mentioned guns, religion, family or friends,
Windham said.
</P>
<P>
   In one previous talk, the chief said, Ashbrook claimed that he
was being followed by police and was mistaken for a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed a little concern that people would think he's a
serial killer. I said, `Larry, no one would think you're a serial
killer. An officer may have thought you fit a description.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ashbrook expressed similar fears in calls and letters to the
Star-Telegram and FWWeekly, an alternative newspaper. But Windham
said Ashbrook seemed ``just a guy who needed someone to talk
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Windham said it is not unusual for him to spend time reassuring
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls at the office from people who are distraught about
personal issues, financial issues, and I talk to them,'' he said.
``That may be a surprise to people, but that's the way I operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Windham, who has been praised for being accessible to the
public, said he regularly talks with ``probably half a dozen''
people like Ashbrook.
</P>
<P>
   Windham said he didn't consider urging Ashbrook to seek
professional help. ``Obviously, hindsight would suggest that, but
it never struck me I should,'' he said. ``The only advice I ever
gave him was, just because he lost one job doesn't mean he couldn't
get another.''
</P>
<P>
   Windham said he invited Ashbrook to his office after their first
chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came into the office and he was very well-presented: He was
very clean, very starched, well-groomed. He looked to me like a
typical middle-class worker,'' Windham said. ``I don't think
anyone's incapable of violence, but he struck me as someone
unlikely to do violence.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
