<SLUG> BC-MODEL-LAWSUIT(EXCLUSIVE)-ART-2TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE MAY HAVE THE LAST LAUGH AND A FORTUNE  
 (EMBARGO: 6 P.M. EDT, SUNDAY, OCT. 3.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas, Kan.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3)  
 (af)  
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ When last we left her, Anna Nicole Smith, the
Playboy centerfold and former Guess jeans model, was at war over
how to hold a proper funeral for her husband, J. Howard Marshall
II, the Texas oilman who was one of the richest people in America
when he died at age 90.
</P>
<P>
   That 1995 feud, with one of Marshall's sons, was never really
settled. They wound up holding two services and dividing the dead
man's ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ms. Smith has battled drug addiction; suffered as
snide journalists published photographs of her weighing more than
200 pounds; filed for bankruptcy protection, and gave up both the
Cypress, Texas, ranchette and the Los Angeles house that her
husband had given her.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she lives with her young son by a previous marriage in a
modest apartment in this decidedly unglamorous Los Angeles suburb,
trying to stage a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   But her luck may be about to change. Ms. Smith, the
5-foot-11-inch Marilyn Monroe wannabe, is back down to her vamping
weight of 155. She is also on the edge of what could be a major
legal victory in her struggle to win a huge chunk of the Marshall
estate from E. Pierce Marshall, the stepson who fought her over her
husband's remains.
</P>
<P>
   If she wins, Ms. Smith, now 31, could become one of the richest
women in America. The estate is estimated to be worth more than $1
billion, and she hopes to get as much as half. The bulk of it is in
stock in Koch Industries, the nation's second-largest private
company, so Ms. Smith, a ninth-grade dropout from tiny Mexia,
Texas, could conceivably wind up with a seat on Koch's board and a
say in the Koch family's own long-running and much-litigated feud.
The Marshall clan controls 8 percent of Koch's voting stock and 16
percent of the nonvoting stock.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the Koch family of Wichita, Kan., has been drawn
into the Marshall estate battle. A disinherited Marshall son, J.
Howard Marshall III, 63, has sued the Koch company, its chairman
and other Koch associates, accusing them of conspiring with his
brother, Pierce, to influence his father and cheat him of his
inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Cordes, a lawyer for Koch Industries and himself a
defendant in Howard Marshall's suit, called such claims
``completely meritless.'' Referring to Howard's dead father, Cordes
said, ``I don't know how any individual could have influenced J.
Howard Marshall to do anything that he didn't want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Marshall, meanwhile, remains the heir, and he seems
unlikely to settle with Ms. Smith, the stepmother he detested, or
with his estranged brother. His lawyers maintain that, if anything,
Ms. Smith owes money to the estate, given her lavish life style and
the way it drained millions of her husband's fortune during his
last months.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 1 percent of American estates wind up in litigation,
according to Stanley Johanson, a professor at the University of
Texas School of Law. But this one has all the ingredients of a
spectacular fight: An enormous amount at stake, a disinherited
child, a new wife who is not the mother of the children. ``That's
the kind of case where you could say, `Anticipate a will
contest,''' Johanson said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Ms. Smith seemed more intent on pouting
for a photographer than discussing her prospects in the trial in
U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Los Angeles, scheduled to begin on Oct.
25. (The estate battle became an issue in bankruptcy court after
Ms. Smith listed her claim to part of the fortune as an asset in
her personal bankruptcy filing in 1996.)
</P>
<P>
   She pleaded ignorance of the legal details _ or unwillingness to
discuss them _ while leaning forward obligingly in a low-cut black
knit dress for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   But one look at a May ruling by Judge Samuel L. Bufford of the
Los Angeles Bankruptcy Court makes it clear that Ms. Smith, who was
married to Marshall for 14 months, approaches the trial date with a
huge advantage. In a slap at Pierce Marshall for refusing to
cooperate in pretrial discovery, Bufford ruled that Ms. Smith
should share equally in proceeds from the estate.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling stands, it will give Ms. Smith, a one-time Playboy
video star, more than enough to bankroll her dream of opening her
own film studio, one where innocent, less sexually explicit movies
like those from the 1950s could be produced. ``That's kind of weird
coming from me,'' she acknowledged. But referring to sexual content
on TV and in films, she said, ``It's just gotten out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said she would be happy to both direct and star in,
and perhaps even write, movies with scripts like those of the old
Marilyn Monroe films. She, of course, would play the Marilyn parts.
</P>
<P>
   Through his lawyers, Pierce Marshall, 60, who lives quietly in
Dallas managing the family investments, refused requests for an
interview to discuss how he would feel if half of his Yale-educated
father's estate were to go to such an enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   But Rusty Hardin, a lawyer for Marshall Petroleum, a holding
company containing most of the Marshall fortune, had more to say.
``This is ludicrous,'' he said. ``This woman is not entitled to a
dime. And nobody who rationally looks at this case would give it to
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a very brief relationship with a man who was pleased
by her appearance,'' Hardin added, dismissively. ``And that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   In his quest for the Marshall millions, J. Howard Marshall III,
the older son and the founder of an electronic instruments company,
is suing in Houston probate court to overturn his father's will and
a family trust that benefits his brother Pierce and Pierce's
family. In this effort, Howard is also suing Koch Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Marshall and Ms. Smith make similar arguments in their
suits. Each says the elder Howard Marshall orally promised to
remember them in his will, but that Pierce Marshall interfered. Ms.
Smith goes further, saying that signatures on 1994 documents
amending the Marshall trust and gave Pierce Marshall his father's
power of attorney were not really those of her late husband, or
were obtained through fraud or duress.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Marshall's lawyers brushed aside the contentions of oral
promises. ``Pierce's position is that J. Howard Marshall II's will
should be followed,'' said Don Jackson, one of Pierce's lawyers.
Referring to Ms. Smith by her real name, he said, ``He did not
leave anything to Vickie Marshall, or to his older son, J. Howard
Marshall.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 amendment to the Marshall trust, dated just two weeks
after Ms. Smith's marriage to Marshall, specifically excludes his
older son from the benefits of the trust. It makes no mention of
his young wife.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Marshall's distaste for his flamboyant stepmother became
clear even before his father's death in August 1995. According to
Ms. Smith, Pierce, as co-trustee of the family trust, failed to
cover a $956,000 check that his father had written to a Beverly
Hills jeweler to buy jewelry for her. The jeweler then sued Ms.
Smith and the elder Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband's deteriorating health left him bedridden, Ms.
Smith appeared on the ``Howard Stern'' show to complain that her
stepson was restricting her to 30-minute visits once a day with her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   During a court battle for guardianship of the dying man, she
contended that Pierce Marshall had so starved the couple for cash
that ``one of the wealthiest men in America and his wife have had
the water turned off in residences for nonpayment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith's remarks on Stern's show were among those Pierce
cited in a 1995 slander and libel suit against her and two of her
lawyers. The claim against her was discharged last month by the
bankruptcy court; the two lawyers settled.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith now says she forgives him. ``I have no harsh feelings
for anybody, not even Pierce,'' she said. ``It's a peaceful
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
