<HEADLINE>
HEARING LOSS DOESN'T SLOW DEFENSIVE END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC ZARATE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Defensive end Casey Wines expects to see the
largest crowd of the season Friday when his Arlington (Texas) Colts
take on the Arlington Lamar Vikings at Cravens Field.
</P>
<P>
   His senses can also expect the pungent odor of freshly trod
grass chunks, the glint of stadium lights on band instruments and,
perhaps, the end-over-end flight of the football during a field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds of the game, however, are missing for this Arlington
High senior. Wines is profoundly deaf _ 90-percent hearing loss _
in both ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like (playing football), and it's fun,'' said Wines, who
reads lips when you look directly at him. ``This doesn't hold me
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not.
</P>
<P>
   Wines is a two-year starter for the Colts, and his coaches and
teammates regard him as one of the most tenacious players on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great one to have in your program,'' Arlington High
coach Mickey Finley said. ``I think he kind of motivates us all
sometimes and is a great inspiration. Besides that, he's a great
football player and helps our football team. He's one of the best
football players we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Wines' 34 tackles tie him for second-best on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's aggressive as anything,'' linebacker Lath Staats said.
``He's always going 110 percent. He just goes. He's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Wines lost his hearing between the ages of 3 and 4, said his
mother, Leigh Anne Drake.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speech was developed, so that helped him read lips,''
Drake said, ``but he says he does not remember hearing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the classroom, where Wines wears hearing aids and has been in
the mainstream curriculum most of his life, he is almost painfully
shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey's withdrawn in unfamiliar surroundings,'' Drake said.
``I try to make him do things on his own. He registered for school
on his own this year. I was pretty proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wines played linebacker last year, but works closest with
defensive ends coach Jason Blevins this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been times when I'm coaching him and he gets
frustrated,'' Blevins said. ``I think he'll agree just so I'll go
on. He never gives any excuses and he's real hard on himself. He
bounces back and tries even harder on the next play, and the
players see this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hand signals from the sideline tell Wines what to do on each
play. Wines also looks back a second time in case Blevins wants to
add a stunt or warn his end about something else.
</P>
<P>
   A touch of the shoe by Blevins alerts Wines to a possible
bootleg. When the coach moves his arms like a pair of windshield
wipers, Wines looks for the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been real effective,'' Blevins said.
</P>
<P>
   Wines has played football since the fifth grade, and would like
to play at the college level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to make tackles and I love taking on the blocks,''
Wines said. ``No, I don't really get discouraged. If I miss the
play, I'll still go hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The sights and movement of football are enough for Wines, while
his mother also enjoys the sounds of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me proud when he makes a tackle and the crowd
cheers,'' Drake said. ``He can't hear it, but I sure can.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4163 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MODEL-LAWSUIT(EXCLUSI     10-01 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODEL-LAWSUIT(EXCLUSIVE)-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BURBANK, Calif.: peaceful feeling.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much Pierce Marshall values Ms. Smith's forgiveness is
uncertain. What is clear is that the bankruptcy judge presiding
over her case takes a less beneficent view of him.
</P>
<P>
   Bufford slammed Pierce Marshall after finding that he had
destroyed some documents and refused to produce others showing what
happened to his father's assets after 1990, and that he had refused
to appear for depositions. As punishment, the judge upheld Ms.
Smith's contention that her husband had directed Pierce to equally
share proceeds from the Marshall estate with her. He said Pierce
had lost his chance to argue the point.
</P>
<P>
   Such a dramatic action, known among lawyers as a ``death
penalty'' sanction, is within the court's power but ``a bit
unusual,'' especially given that the California bankruptcy ruling
would make moot part of an active Texas probate case, said Dan
Bussel, a professor of law at the University of California at Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, neither Ms. Smith's nor Howard Marshall's claim
for a share of the estate seems strong. Texas law does not honor
oral contracts to make a will. Ms. Smith's filings alternately
argue that under the Texas community property law, she should at
least get half the income generated by the Marshall fortune during
her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Marshall acknowledges that his father threatened to
disinherit him in 1980, after the younger man joined with dissident
sons in the Koch family to take control of Koch Industries, where
his father had been on the board for years.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Marshall and his father apparently remained on hostile
terms afterward. In a June 1999 filing, Howard Marshall said his
father had a habit of ``entering into oral contracts and breaching
such contracts if he felt like doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Howard Marshall says his father agreed to treat him
equally as part of a bargain struck in return for his Koch stock,
which he sold back to his father rather than pooling it with the
Koch family dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the Koch family responded to requests for comment on
the Marshall lawsuits or their impact on Koch Industries, including
the prospect of Ms. Smith becoming a major shareholder and board
member. However, Cordes, the Koch Industries lawyer, said it was
unlikely that Ms. Smith would be given a board seat even if she
managed to win her case.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, much of the Marshall estate's Koch stock will
probably be sold to settle claims against the estate, with Koch
Industries having a right of first refusal. ``She has a long way to
go before she gets Koch stock,'' Cordes said. ``Nobody's staying up
late at night and worrying about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Smith said her husband not only promised her
half his estate, but was also planning to adopt her son, Daniel. In
proposing marriage, she said in a filing, her husband told her she
needed to be married to him so that he could provide for her and
``protect her from Pierce.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the marriage, she contended, her husband directed
his advisers to change his estate plan in keeping with his pledge.
Instead, she said, they ``began planning a series of false and
fraudulent transactions'' to permit Pierce to seize control of his
father's assets.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 documents giving Pierce control of the trust bear an
illegible scrawl of a signature, made, she said, at a time when her
husband's eyesight was so poor that he could not have read what was
put before him.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith described her late husband, whom she called Paw-Paw,
as her ``security blanket.'' Referring to her days as a topless
dancer in Houston, trying to support her son, she said: ``He had
taken me out of this bad place. I loved him deeply for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People can think what they want. I really don't care,'' she
said. ``He's the only person who ever cared for me in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   After her husband's death, with lawsuits mounting and Pierce
Marshall cutting off her support, ``I just lost it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking over 100 pills a day,'' she added. ``I got fat. I
was having seizures. I was having panic attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   During this period, the media were sometimes vicious. A
photograph of her at her heaviest, bulging out of a red evening
gown, turned up repeatedly in magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Her emotional condition may help explain the disappearance of
more than $3 million worth of jewelry given to her by Marshall
before he died. A court-appointed examiner in 1996 found Ms. Smith
so addled by prescription drugs and alcohol that it would have been
easy for people around her to steal the jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Business associates described Ms. Smith as ``naive'' and
``childlike,'' said the examiner, who added that she was surrounded
by people motivated by their own self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Marshall offered a different explanation for the missing
jewels. ``The debtor may have simply manufactured the disappearance
to prevent the jewelry from becoming estate property upon her
bankruptcy filing,'' he argued in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   After fours years of court battles, a settlement that could put
an end to the protracted fight seems as distant as ever. With case
files already swelling in two states, ``It has become a
full-employment act for lawyers in Texas and California,'' said
Hardin, the Marshall Petroleum lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith says she hopes something good comes of the Oct. 25
trial. ``I'm praying to the good Lord,'' she said. ``I just want
this to be over with.''
</P>
<P>
   But her career seems foremost in her mind. ``I'm reading
scripts,'' she said. ``I'm thinking about a perfume line. And I'd
love to do another jeans contract.''
</P>
<P>
   And, like virtually everyone else in America, she is setting up
a Web site. One of the items to be auctioned on the site, she said,
is the infamous red gown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
