<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE, BRUINS MAY YET LET ARBITRATOR SETTLE IMPASSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH AND NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's possible a solution to the Byron Dafoe contract
stalemate could be right around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden says he is willing
to give Dafoe a second crack at arbitration if the league, the
Players Association, and Dafoe agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a chance to go to arbitration and didn't do it,'' said
Sinden Friday, two days after his No. 1 netminder asked to be
traded when the team and player clearly couldn't come to terms.
``That's why we have arbitration in our collective bargaining
agreement. It's there for the player who doesn't think he is going
to get a fair shake. Now, here's what I'll do. I'll gladly go to an
arbitrator as soon as possible if Byron is willing, and take
whatever the award is and live with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's no problem with the league or the Players
Association, and I don't think there would be, let's get an
arbitrator, submit our offers from both sides, and see what he
decides. Byron said if he knew this (impasse) was going to happen,
he would have taken arbitration. I'm giving him a second shot at
it. And since he said he wanted to be traded, we haven't had a
single call from anybody because there isn't a single team out
there willing to pay him what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, it's a win-win situation for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   From a public relations perspective, it would be positive for
management because people would credit the Bruins with finding a
solution to the impasse. It is also, in Sinden's eyes, a calculated
risk. Sinden has maintained that he thought Dafoe would get far
less in arbitration (between $2.2 million and $2.6 million) than
the Bruins were offering ($3 million). Sinden said he thought Dafoe
knew that, and that's the real reason he didn't seek arbitration
when he was eligible to file prior to July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said he elected to pass on having a third party decide his
fate because he thought he and his agent, Ron Salcer, could sway
the Bruins after the club made such a positive initial offer in
late June. As it turned out, the Bruins didn't move off their
offer, and Dafoe continues to sit as the season is set to begin at
the FleetCenter Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was pleased with Sinden's idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie and I were actually talking about going to him with
that approach,'' said Dafoe. ``I'd definitely be open to that
because we honestly thought they wouldn't take it. That's exactly
what we were thinking about doing. That definitely could be an
alternative. There aren't really too many other options out there
the way it's going. I'm glad he said that. At least we both agree
to that, if anything, so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said he didn't think it would be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If both parties agree, it's like settling out of court, why
couldn't you?'' he said. ``I shouldn't say settling out of court,
but it's two parties going to an arbitrator because you and the
parties tried to work it out a different way but it didn't work.
That's definitely an alternative that could work. The bottom line
is if you go to an arbitrator and no matter what the award is,
whether it's good or bad for either party, you accept it because
supposedly it's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   A stumbling block, however, could be that this proposal flies in
the face of the collective bargaining agreement. The deadline for
arbitration has passed. It would take a special exception to do
this, and commissioner Gary Bettman might not want to open that can
of worms.
</P>
<P>
   If the league didn't allow it, it's possible the Bruins and
Dafoe could hire a private arbitrator to end the dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
