<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAS POPE PIUS XII A SAINT, OR HITLER'S PAWN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some Roman Catholic leaders are pushing to have Pope
Pius XII declared a saint. By contrast, John Cornwell, in the title
of his new book, calls Pius ``Hitler's Pope.''
</P>
<P>
   Are those the alternatives? There is a lot of room between being
a saint and being Hitler's pope. Which is where one can find most
of the knowledgeable historians.
</P>
<P>
   Chatting in his room at the Regency Hotel in Manhattan last
Monday, his tie loosened and his feet up on the bed, Cornwell made
it clear he was not a historian. He is a British journalist, whose
interests have run from the history and philosophy of science to
grisly murders and tales of demonic possession.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, he published ``A Thief in the Night'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster), an investigation into the sudden death of Pope John Paul
I, which occurred scarcely a month (33 days) after his election in
August 1978. Cornwell's account sometimes made the Vatican look
like an HMO from hell, but the book was a model of common-sense
reporting compared with the conspiratorial fancies that other
writers concocted about John Paul I's unexpected demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler's Pope'' (Viking, 1999) is quite another matter. The
author plunges through territory that has been raked over by
painstaking historians as well as Pius XII's many critics and
defenders. Cornwell's distinctive contribution, he said on Monday,
was simply to paint ``the first full portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   The book also shifts the story's center of gravity from the
familiar debate about Pius' ``silence,'' his refusal to voice a
loud and unambiguous condemnation of Nazi deeds during the war and
Holocaust, to the less familiar debate about the church's fateful
dealings with Hitler during the months when the Nazi regime was
consolidating its dictatorial powers.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1933, the German Catholic Center Party voted for the
Enabling Act affirming those powers, and, four months later, voted
itself out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   Also in March, the German Catholic bishops lifted their previous
censures of Nazism. Immediately afterward, Hitler and the Vatican
moved to sign a concordat, an agreement regulating church-state
affairs that removed the German church from politics in exchange
for pledges of Nazi non-interference in church matters, which
Hitler, of course, violated.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestrating it all, according to ``Hitler's Pope,'' was
Eugenio Pacelli, the Vatican secretary of state who would be
elected Pope Pius XII in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   He may have hated Nazism, Cornwell acknowledges, he may even
have risked the most serious reprisals by later abetting a plot to
depose Hitler in 1939, but ultimately he spent his life in the grip
of a ``papal ideology'' that subordinated everything, including
resistance to Hitler, to the extension of papal control over the
rest of the Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   This may come as a surprise to Catholics and non-Catholics alike
who assume that papal claims to govern the church were centuries
old. In principle, yes; but in practice, those claims were hedged
by concessions to Europe's monarchies and local officials, both
religious and secular.
</P>
<P>
   Following the traumas of the French Revolution and its
aftermath, when two popes were taken captive and humiliated by
Napoleon and when anti-clerical politicians frequently replaced the
old dynasties, the papacy became militant about asserting its
claims against state restrictions and local prerogatives.
</P>
<P>
   All his life, Pius XII surely held this exalted view of papal
power and a corresponding distrust of independent Catholic
movements. He was austere, solitary, a problematic figure
undoubtedly more at home with authoritarian leaders than democrats.
But was that all there was to him?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to lean heavily on reputable scholars,'' Cornwell
said on Monday. And to get through the thicket of German historical
debates, he has leaned most heavily on Klaus Scholder, whose two
volumes on ``The Churches and the Third Reich'' (Fortress Press)
have been available in English since 1988, three years after his
death.
</P>
<P>
   Footnote after crucial footnote refers to Scholder, who is
certainly a reputable scholar, but not the only one in the fray.
Others insist that protecting Catholic schools was always the
uppermost consideration for both the Vatican and the German bishops
in the pursuit of a German concordat, not nominating bishops or
imposing canon law. Or they argue that the Center Party, Catholic
trade unions and other political church groups were already
buckling under the Nazi mix of emergency powers and street-level
terror. The Vatican was simply salvaging what it could.
</P>
<P>
   Did other groups, not burdened by a code of canon law,
concordats or Vatican diplomacy, do better in resisting Hitler? The
German Protestant churches? The Catholic church in France? The
other German political parties?
</P>
<P>
   ``A fair criticism up to a point,'' Cornwell said of his book's
lack of comparisons, which results almost inevitably from the
author's skill in keeping Pacelli always in the foreground. If Pius
XII was ``Hitler's pawn,'' as Cornwell writes, then everyone else
was Pacelli's pawn. No one seems to act from motives or principles,
virtues or vices, independent of his _ not the German bishops, the
Center Party leaders or even Pius' predecessor, Pius XI. One
chapter describes the young Pacelli's hand in the negotiation of a
June 1914 concordat with Serbia, and the reader ends up wondering
whether this man did not also start World War I!
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Longley, a veteran English religion writer, in an
article in the London Daily Telegraph, calls ``Hitler's Pope'' a
book about the present, not the past, a book whose ``real target is
Pope John Paul II.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfair, said Cornwell, although his book closes with a chapter
titled ``Pius XII Redivivus,'' attacking John Paul for reaffirming
``the ideology of papal power.''
</P>
<P>
   The real issue of course is not the disagreements among
Catholics over the current pope's leadership, but whether fighting
them out over Pius' dead body does an injustice both to him and to
the memory of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pacelli was no monster,'' Cornwell says in his book, and he
repeated that on Monday. But the author misses no opportunity to
portray a man obsessed by papal power, harboring a secret antipathy
to Jews, insensible to pity, narcissistic and self-exonerating.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic church used to assign a church official to
relentlessly pursue any possible unworthiness of a person proposed
for sainthood. That position was called the ``devil's advocate.''
John Cornwell, by his own admission, is not a historian. But he
certainly makes a superb devil's advocate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
