<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After 2 years in making, Thrashers ready to go
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The South's first major-league experiment with this
sport from the northern provinces concluded with an ugly exit.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Flames lost their final game at the Omni, ousted
from the playoffs by a 5-2 New York Rangers victory April 12, 1980.
The owner, Tom Cousins, needed cash to support his sagging
real-estate interests and jumped on a $16 million offer.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the team was shoved into a moving van bound for Calgary,
and the NHL's existence in Atlanta was over after eight seasons and
not nearly that many playoff victories.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, all memories of the city's NHL cameo can, like the
Omni, be imploded.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers make their regular-season debut at Philips Arena
against the New Jersey Devils, a matchup of teams expected to have
opposite seasons. The Devils led the Eastern Conference in
victories last season. The Thrashers led the league in scouting
backup goaltenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that this has been building for a long time,''
said Thrashers coach Curt Fraser, a second-year player in Vancouver
at the time of the Flames' departure. ``But as a team we don't want
to get hung up in all that too much. We just want to go out and
play a game. Training camp was great, but it's training camp. This
is the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL took Time Warner's $80 million expansion fee and
returned no favors. The Thrashers open with a three-game homestand
against three teams expected to contend for the Stanley Cup _ New
Jersey, which won it in 1995 and has averaged 47 victories the past
three seasons; Detroit, which won Cups in 1997 and '98; and
Buffalo, a finalist last year with the world's best goaltender,
Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser's team is expected to rely on goaltending and defense.
And perhaps he could find solace in the Thrashers' 6-1 exhibition
victory over the Devils two weeks ago. But New Jersey did not play
a number of its front-line players, most notably goalie Martin
Brodeur. Fraser even suggested the Devils might have sleep-skated
on purpose, to set up a sneak attack tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey knew they were going to play us in the first game,
so they weren't going to show us anything,'' Fraser said. ``I know
what they're all about. I'm sure they wanted us feeling pretty good
about ourself. But they don't need to do that. They're a great
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers defenseman Kevin Dean, plucked from New Jersey during
the expansion draft, doesn't quite subscribe to Fraser's conspiracy
theory. ``I think we'd be the last team that could be lured into a
false sense of security,'' Dean said. ``That would be pretty
foolish of them, if that was their plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils will be missing two players, center Brendan Morrison
and left winger Patrik Elias, both of whom are restricted free
agents and playing for a club team in the Czech Republic. But the
Devils have an attack deep enough to pressure goalie Damian Rhodes
and play more of a wide-open style under coach Robbie Ftorek than
they did under Jacques Lemaire.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, the Thrashers' aggressive forechecking system
will be given its first severe test. The forwards will be trying to
create more scoring attempts against Brodeur than they did against
Carolina and Nashville in the last two exhibitions, both shutout
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have to go all out every game,'' said left winger
Denny Lambert, a member of expansion Nashville last season. ``We're
not like Colorado or New York or Detroit. They can take a night off
and still win 3-2. If we take a night off, it's going to be 6-1 the
other way. We want to set the tone right off the bat. We want to be
physical and be in their face. We want other teams thinking, `These
guys don't give up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Gord Murphy agreed. ``We want to make it tough for
teams to come into our building,'' Murphy said. ``We want to make
it so that if teams come in and beat us, they're going to be pretty
fatigued and sore when it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
