<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whitesell's debut works for Gordon
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Brian Whitesell was the center of attention
for his sensational debut at Martinsville Speedway on Friday, but
he wasn't driving.
</P>
<P>
   Whitesell, 35, replaced Ray Evernham this week as the No. 24
team's crew chief. With the new guy on the headsets, Jeff Gordon
earned a prime starting position in Sunday's NAPA AutoCare 500 by
qualifying fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today went real well,'' Gordon said with a smile. ``Obviously,
the results are there. We were fifth, (which) is the best we've
qualified here in a little while.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly a lot of pressure on (Whitesell) and,
really, the whole team. So it was a big relief to have a good
qualifying run. We had no problems, and everything was smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was the first challenge _ it went real well _ and the
next is calling the race on Sunday. I don't expect anything to be
different Sunday than it was today.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitesell was heavily watched from the moment he entered the
track gate at 6 a.m. Friday. Despite stepping into the most
prolific crew chief job in Cup racing, Whitesell gave the
appearance of being calm and unassuming, yet confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The promotion) has not sunk in yet and there is too much work
to be done to get nervous,'' Whitesell said. ``I'm not really
worried about this weekend, but I want to make sure to do
everything right. Ray taught us very well, and we're going to do
the best we can and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after qualifying did Whitesell admit he felt like he was in
an awkward situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing interviews is the biggest thing,'' Whitesell said. ``I'm
over here with reporters, and the car is over there. I want to be
working on the car, but I've got great people who can do it, and I
can rely on them. That is the way that it has got to be from now
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Landing the job was the culmination of Whitesell's rapid rise
through Hendrick Motorsports. He arrived at the organization with
Gordon and Evernham in 1992, working as transporter driver, timer,
scorer and chassis technician during the first season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
