A4174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS02-COX     10-01 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Case of good timing
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baltimore Ravens quarterback Stoney Case owes the
Indianapolis Colts a long thank-you note.
</P>
<P>
   Case opened training camp in July as a backup in Indianapolis
after signing a two-year contract with the Colts. But he was
stunned when the team waived him after the preseason opener, in
which he completed five of six passes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a blessing in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, Case wasn't going to get much playing time
behind starter Peyton Manning, the only NFL quarterback to take
every snap last season. When he signed with Baltimore, Case had a
legitimate chance of starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous opportunity,'' said Case, who kept a
$500,000 signing bonus from Indianapolis. ``I guess I owe the Colts
a favor. It sounds strange saying that now.''
</P>
<P>
   New Ravens coach Brian Billick traded for Scott Mitchell and
Tony Banks, who last season lost their starting jobs in Detroit and
St. Louis, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   After leading the Ravens to last-minute victories in the final
two preseason games, it took Case only two regular-season games to
leap-frog Banks and win Mitchell's starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of surprised, because I missed the first three
weeks of training camp (with Baltimore),'' Case said. ``I was in
Indianapolis. I got a late start in learning the offense. Those
guys had the whole offseason, all summer and the first couple of
weeks of training camp to learn the offense. I had a lot of
catching up to do. When I got released from Indy, I was coming here
to get a job and make the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Billick's decision is one of the few breaks Case has received in
his five-year NFL career. A third-round pick of the Arizona
Cardinals in 1995 from New Mexico, Case expected to study under
veteran Dave Krieg and then take over the offense in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardinals coach Buddy Ryan was fired during Case's rookie
season, and the new coaching staff had little regard for Case.
Under coach Vince Tobin, Case spent the next year and a half behind
Boomer Esiason and Kent Graham.
</P>
<P>
   When Arizona drafted Jake Plummer in 1997, it became clear that
Case's future wasn't in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   It might be in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Harbaugh, who started in Baltimore last season, signed with
San Diego in the offseason, and backup Eric Zeier was traded to
Tampa Bay. Billick gave up four future draft picks for Mitchell and
Banks, but both struggled in learning his sophisticated offense.
</P>
<P>
   After Mitchell threw four interceptions and was sacked six times
in the first two games, Billick turned over his offense to Case.
</P>
<P>
   In his first start against Cleveland last week, Case was shaky.
He completed 12 of 25 passes with three interceptions, but he
rushed for 57 yards and two touchdowns. Case was sacked four times
and amassed a passer rating of 30.0 against the Browns, who gave up
69 points in their first two games.
</P>
<P>
   But he directed Baltimore to a 17-10 victory, something Mitchell
couldn't do in the first two games. Billick said that result is
reason enough to stick with Case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make the change to Stoney as a temporary situation,''
Billick said. ``He has everything a quarterback needs to succeed:
size, speed, vision, arm strength, confidence and intelligence.
We're giving him this opportunity. If he hits his stride and uses
all of his abilities, we could have a heck of a quarterback here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
