<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-DAY202-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 tied for lead at Buick
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Those Ryder Cup players are news hogs. One
falls out of the picture at the Buick Challenge and another grabs a
headline.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was Jeff Maggert's turn at Callaway Gardens. Hal Sutton's
partner at Brookline, Maggert is flourishing back on his own. The
Houston resident shot a 9-under par 63 to move to within two shots
of leaders David Toms, Stuart Appleby and Harrison Frazar.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder Cup teammate Justin Leonard, after a 67 Thursday, shot a
72 in his second round and is at 5-under 139. First-round leader
Bob Friend shot a 73 and fell to four shots off the lead at 6-under
138.
</P>
<P>
   The cut came at 2-under 142, pushing 70 players to the weekend.
Among those missing were John Daly, Curtis Strange, Nick Faldo,
Atlanta's Billy Andrade and defending champion Steve Elkington.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert was surprised he could manage a 10-birdie performance
Friday, but not that he would regroup from last week's emotional
drain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any more relaxing than this tournament,'' he
said. ``You've got a cabin in the woods, a little baseball on TV at
night ... it doesn't get any better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the players to catch at 10-under-par 134, Frazar is the only
one without a tournament win. Frazar, who has a pair of 67s, has
been friends with Leonard since they were children in Texas. The
two have not had an opportunity to discuss what happened in
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Frazar and Toms are not in the physical condition you might
expect from co-leaders entering weekend play. Frazar has a thick
bandage on his left wrist from a possible stress fracture and needs
to keep the ball out of the rough to minimize pounding. Toms, who
shot a 66 Friday, had to withdraw from the Wednesday pro-am because
of severe pain in his neck and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying not to swing too hard,'' said Toms, who won
the Sprint International in August.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby, who shot a 64 Friday, is showing the fatigue of a long
season. He won the Shell Houston Open in May, his first since the
death of his wife, Renay, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just very tiring this time of the year,'' said the
Australian. ``But you've got to do the last few laps.'' Tom Kite,
with a 65, and Trinidad's Stephen Ames join Maggert at 8-under, a
stroke better than Columbus resident Larry Mize (69). Sea Island's
Davis Love III continued his strong play following the Ryder Cup
with a 68 that placed him at 138. Teammate Steve Pate (73) is at
3-under 141, along with Duluth's Stewart Cink (68).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
