<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY TAKE AIM AT EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for complete writethru to reorganize and make additions
throughout. No pickup.)  (th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The debates that Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley are promising began in a virtual way Friday as
each candidate pleaded with an important labor union for support
and directly criticized his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In his strongest words to date about Bradley, Gore cast the
former senator's brief flirtation with an independent presidential
candidacy in 1996 as disloyalty to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been tempted to leave the Democratic Party,'' Gore
said, speaking by satellite from Washington to members of Local 250
of the Health Care Workers Union, who were meeting in Oakland,
Calif. ``I've never been tempted to turn my back on the Democratic
Party. I've never been tempted to run as an independent and divide
the progressive coalition, and I have always, always been for
working families and for organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped appearance before the union, which played for
members earlier Friday, Bradley suggested that Gore could not get
elected because independents and Republicans would not support him
in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective of nominating somebody is to win in the fall,''
Bradley said. ``Since January, people have come up to me, in hotels
and restaurants, and said, `I'm an independent or a Republican and
I would vote for you and I would never vote for him,''' Bradley
said, citing a recent poll that showed Bradley beating Bush in New
York while the Republican would beat Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The comments marked the first time the two have criticized each
other directly to the same audience and signaled an escalation of
Gore's determination to fight for his party's nomination. When the
two made separate appearances last weekend before the Democratic
National Committee they did not aim their fire at each other.
</P>
<P>
   The comments also showed just how hard both candidates are
courting the labor vote. The union, a part of the Service Employees
International Union, is the second-largest health-care workers
local in the country after Local 1199 in New York. It is a critical
part of the AFL-CIO, which is scheduled to meet Oct. 12 in Los
Angeles. At that meeting, the AFL-CIO will consider whether to
endorse a candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore once expected the endorsement, but Bradley's fund-raising
prowess and strong showing in opinion polls has given him enough
clout to at least forestall an automatic nod to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism of Bradley was just one sign Friday that Gore was
trying to make good on his pledge to revitalize his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He also replaced his top pollster, Mark Penn, with Harrison
Hickman, a move that the Gore camp described as a way to focus more
closely on polling in the early-voting states of Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters have very particular views in those states,'' a
campaign aide said, describing Hickman as an expert in polling
specific issues and voters rather than broad national sentiment.
``You need research that is very, very targeted,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was also more overt in his criticism of Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the Republican front-runner. For the first time Friday,
he mentioned Bush by name, indicating that Gore believes that
although he must beat back the Bradley challenge, he must also
carry the party standard against the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At a hospital here, Gore touted his support for a patient's bill
of rights and chided Bush for not supporting one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that Governor Bush will break with the Republican
majority in the Congress and start supporting the patient's bill of
rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said that Bush, who on Thursday said congressional
Republicans should not ``balance their budget on the backs of the
poor,'' could not simultaneously oppose the Republican spending
plan and still support their proposed tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   And the vice president said that if Bush really wanted to
``demonstrate compassion for working families,'' he would break
with the Republicans and support an increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was in Washington to address the Christian Coalition,
seemed surprised that Gore had mentioned him. ``Really?'' he asked
a reporter when informed of Gore's comments. ``What did he say?''
When told, Bush said, ``Well, I think that Vice President Gore
needs to debate Bill Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore thinks so too. He has called for debates every two weeks.
On Friday, the Bradley campaign sent a letter thanking the Gore
camp for its ``sudden interest'' in joint appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In their comments to the health-care workers, Gore and Bradley
gave a taste of how they planned to engage each other and present
their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley portrayed Gore as a life-long Washington insider with
little real-life experience. ``The vice president has a life that
is primarily based in Washington, and I think that gives us a
different idea of who the American people are, and what we can
do,'' Bradley said. ``I think it also flows into a different style
of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's comments about Bradley's loyalty to the party stem from
statements he made four years ago. After he announced in 1995 that
he would not run for a fourth term for the Senate, Bradley declared
the political system ``broken.'' The comment reflected his feeling
then that Congress had become too partisan and controlled by
big-money and special interests.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1995, he delivered a keynote address at a Liberal
Party dinner in New York and said he had ``not ruled out'' an
independent candidacy, especially after a series of discussions
with other independents, like Lowell Weicker, a former senator from
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bradley insisted at the time that his discussions were
``not groundwork for a formal third-party challenge to the
two-party system,'' and in the last month he has said that he never
seriously considered a third-party candidacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
