<SLUG> BC-TXU-SALES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TXU TO SELL SIX TEXAS GENERATING PLANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TXU Electric has hung a ``For Sale'' sign on
the generating plant that has stood guard over the north side of
downtown Fort Worth for 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-acre North Main plant is one of six TXU generating plants
offered in Texas. Other plants on the block are Mountain Creek and
Parkdale in Dallas, Lake Creek and Tradinghouse near Waco and
Rivercrest outside Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Mountain Creek units, built in 1945 and 1949, are older
than North Main in the TXU system.
</P>
<P>
   Even before TXU announced the sale Friday, North Main had ceased
to be a daily part of the utility's generating capacity. Three of
the four steam-driven turbines have been closed. The fourth, with
capacity of 80 megawatts, is used only during peak demand periods,
usually during the hottest days of a Texas summer.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the work of providing electricity to Fort Worth-Dallas
was assumed a decade ago by the Comanche Peak nuclear plant when it
opened in Somervell County near Glen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   North Main, like other generators, feeds directly into the
national electrical grid. Its output could potentially be sold
throughout Texas, although TXU spokeswoman Carol Peters said that
``economics always dictates that electricity be used as close to
its generation as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The plant has no permanently assigned employees. Peters said
that on occasions when North Main is restarted, TXU shifts workers
from other generators nearby.
</P>
<P>
   North Main and the other five plants are natural gas-fired,
steam-driven units. TXU (formerly Texas Electric Service Co.) says
it is selling the plants in anticipation of the deregulation of
electric service in Texas in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is recognized as a very attractive market in which to
operate when competition begins, and many entities are expressing
interest in owning generating facilities in the state,'' TXU said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Potential buyers are likely to be other utilities or energy
companies seeking a piece of Texas' lucrative and growing
electricity market.
</P>
<P>
   After the plants are sold, TXU said, the utility will buy
electricity from other providers rather than relying solely on its
own generation.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation will open up Texas' electricity market, including
TXU's 2.5 million residential customers in North and Central Texas,
to any and all electric providers. Monopolistic utilities such as
TXU, which already possess exclusive residential customer bases,
are expected to rely more on purchased rather than generated
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Outside corporations such as Calpine Corp. of San Jose, Calif.,
and Duke Energy of Charlotte, N.C., have announced plans to build
generating plants in Texas to sell power to utilities.
</P>
<P>
   TXU spokeswoman Peters said that TXU expects the North Main
plant to continue as a generator under its next ownership, and that
TXU could conceivably buy electricity from the generator it once
owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generating plants don't just go away,'' she said. ``It is
conceivable that we would buy power from the next owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Although three of the four turbines are inactive, Peters said,
they could be re-equipped and started up again. The other three
turbines can each generate 80 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   One megawatt can provide peak electricity power to 250 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The market for used electrical generators is considered strong.
Robert Rubin, an analyst at Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. in New York, told
Bloomberg News that ``this is a phenomenal time to sell. There's at
least 20 different companies that will be looking at the assets TXU
is offering for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors viewed the potential sale favorably. While the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 63.90 Friday, TXU stock rose 3.2
percent to close up $1.19 at $38.50 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The strong potential market is the reason TXU expects to get
more than $1 billion for the six generators, although it carries
the plants on its balance sheet at $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will leave TXU still with 18 generators. Another
generator, near downtown Dallas, is being taken out of service and
converted to a distribution center as part of the development of
the new Dallas sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the buildings, structures and wiring, North
Main's assets include land, water rights, emissions permits and
fuel transportation contracts. A levee on the Trinity River
protects the site from flooding, Peters said.
</P>
<P>
   TXU said it will sell the plants as a package, singly or in
smaller groups.
</P>
<P>
   The utility has hired Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. to conduct the sale.
No real estate brokers are involved.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
