<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      10-01 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JAPAN'S NUCLEAR LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Oct. 2:
</P>
<P>
   It was nowhere near as bad as the 1986 accident at the Chernobyl
nuclear reactor in Ukraine, which spewed radiation over a vast
territory. It was not even as scary as the 1979 accident at the
Three Mile Island nuclear plant in Pennsylvania, which had the
entire nation on edge wondering if the reactor core would break
through its confinement and reach the outer world. (It didn't.) But
the nuclear accident this week at a fuel processing plant at
Tokaimura was certainly the worst in Japan's history _ and a vivid
reminder that nuclear energy is a demanding technology that
severely punishes human error and inadequate technical designs.
</P>
<P>
   Just what went wrong will not be known until investigations are
complete and the Japanese make full disclosure. But from the
fragmentary and conflicting accounts now available, the accident
appears largely due to human error. Workers at a privately operated
plant who were preparing nuclear fuel poured far too much liquid
uranium into a small vessel, more than its design could safely
handle, with the result that a chain reaction started that released
lethal neutrons and fission products.
</P>
<P>
   There was apparently no real danger of a major explosion or
massive release of radiation that would contaminate large areas of
the countryside and threaten public health. The amount of uranium
present was too small for that, only some 35 pounds as compared
with the 50 to 100 tons in a power reactor. High doses of radiation
did escape outside the building into the immediate surroundings,
some 150 people nearby had to be evacuated, and more than 300,000
people living within six miles were told to stay in their homes.
But the chief danger was to workers inside the facility. At least
two received such high doses of radiation that they are likely to
die, barring a medical miracle.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of a comparable accident in this country is hard
to assess. ``Criticality'' accidents were once common in the United
States, occurring in plants other than reactors about once a year
on average in the two decades from 1945 to 1964. But there have
been none since 1978, an indication perhaps that nuclear engineers
have employed safer designs and nuclear technicians have learned to
be more careful. Still, an accident is hardly impossible here. As
recently as 1991, conditions conducive to criticality occurred at a
plant in North Carolina. The Japanese accident may have involved
fuel for a research reactor, which is susceptible to inadvertent
chain reactions in smaller quantities than power reactor fuel, but
it is not yet known whether the process that went awry is similar
to processes used to make such fuel in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government, which has been accused of cover-up
tendencies after previous nuclear accidents, will need to make full
and prompt disclosure of what happened at Tokaimura if it is to
maintain credibility and salvage its troubled nuclear industry. For
the United States, the main lesson may lie less in the particular
flaws and errors uncovered at Tokaimura than in the reminder that
it is alarmingly easy to get into trouble in the nuclear business
the minute one's guard is lowered. As the U.S. nuclear industry
continues to press for easier regulation and less stringent
standards, Tokaimura is a warning that too much relaxation can be
dangerous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-SALVADOR-NYT &LR;      10-01 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SALVADOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAL SALVADOR, 73, TEACHER, BE-BOP GUITARIST AND KENTON PROTEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The guitarist Sal Salvador, a warm-toned be-bop improviser who
performed with Stan Kenton, Bill Evans, Phil Woods and other
canonical jazz figures, died at a medical rehabilitation center in
Stamford, Conn., on Sept. 22. He was 73 and lived in Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   He died of cancer, said his daughter, Lorinda.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador, who was also an instructor and the author of many jazz
instruction books, was born in Monson, Mass. At the age of 18,
Salvador, whose name was originally Silvio Smiraglia, heard Charlie
Christian on a record and taught himself to play the guitar. With
his friends the saxophonist Phil Woods and the drummer Joe Morello,
he performed in Springfield, Mass., and was eventually hired by the
vibraphonist Terry Gibbs and the guitarist Mundell Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950 he became a staff musician at the Columbia label and two
years later went to work with Stan Kenton in his breakthrough job.
He left the band 18 months later but Kenton enabled Salvador to
make an LP for Capitol records under his own name, ``Kenton
Presents Sal Salvador,'' in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Kenton spotlighted him in the work ``Invention for Guitar and
Trumpet'' on the ``New Concepts of Artistry in Rhythm'' album, and
the piece was later included in the 1955 film ``Blackboard
Jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960 Salvador started his own big band, the Colors in Sound
Orchestra, which toured and recorded for five years. Later he
served as an accompanist to singers like Johnny Mathis and Paul
Anka.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 until recently Salvador taught jazz at the University
of Bridgeport and Western Connecticut State University; he also
taught privately in New York City. In the 1990s he began recording
again with a small group for the Stash and Jazzmania, and he
performed in several recent JVC Jazz Festival concerts, usually in
duets with his longtime colleague Mundell Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter, who lives in Stamford, he is
survived by his wife, Catherine D. Smiraglia; his sons, Daniel B.
Smiraglia of Stamford and Barry S. Smiraglia of Pepperill, Mass.,
and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2208EDT &QL; 
