<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-DYKES-T     10-01 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-DYKES-TEX </SLUG>
 
DYKES' TASK AT HAND ISN'T SAVING JOB (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Life was good in Coahoma for Sharon and Spike
Dykes that fall of 1964.
</P>
<P>
   They owned a ``new'' Volkswagen beetle with 150,000 miles, but
they generally got where they wanted to go. They lived in a
$10-a-month oil-field house (''They charged you $5 a bedroom, and
we had two bedrooms,'' Dykes recalled), but it was comfortably
appointed with castoffs from Sharon's father's furniture store in
Ballinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they'd throw something away, we'd pick it up,''
Dykes recalled. ``We had a bunch of junk, I'm telling you.''
</P>
<P>
   Spike had just completed his first season as a head football
coach. He had taken over a team that was winless the year before
and guided it to 10 consecutive victories and a district
championship, though the Bulldogs lost the bi-district tussle to
Seagraves, 32-28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bulletproof and invisible,'' Dykes said.
</P>
<P>
   That is until that November afternoon when Sharon came through
the door of their home visibly upset. After several minutes of
urging, she finally blurted out the reason she had come home close
to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spike,'' she said, ``they're after you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What? Who's after me?'' said Spike, stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon said she overheard a conversation between two crusty old
ranchers while she was at the post office picking up the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something about that coach,'' one of them had
said. ``If he'd played that other quarterback the other night, we'd
still be in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykes still laughs at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of those welcome-to-the-head-coaching-business
deals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The story recently has taken on added significance. Just a week
after Dykes became Texas Tech's winningest head coach with a
victory over Louisiana-Lafayette, Red Raiders fans were in an
uproar after a loss to North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old saying that things are never quite as good or as bad
as they seem is probably true,'' Dykes said. ``Everybody has an
answer for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Dykes' future rages anew each day on Lubbock
radio and in the letters-to-the-editor section of the local paper,
unabated after an open date following the 21-14 loss to UNT on the
heels of the historic victory over Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the antis are going to call more than the pros in any
circumstance,'' said longtime Lubbock radio announcer Jack Dale,
who does three daily sports-talk segments. ``But there are a ton of
anti-Spike Dykes people who want him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech president Donald Haragan last week said that Dykes, who is
in the next-to-last year of a contract, will remain through the end
of the season. Then, Haragan said, Dykes' status will be fully
evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are even more upset about that,'' Dale noted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dykes goes about business as usual, getting his team
ready for what is perhaps the Red Raiders' biggest game of the
season today against fifth-ranked Texas A&AMP;M, one of college
football's winningest teams of the '90s. Tech has beaten the Aggies
in consecutive visits and four of the past six times A&AMP;M has played
in Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Dykes has maintained the wit that both endears
and alienates, depending on one's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   At Tech's weekly news conference Monday, sports information
director Kent Partridge announced that he was out of this week's
passes for ``shooters,'' meaning sideline photographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooters, huh?'' Dykes observed. ``That's encouraging to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his lived-in office suite, Dykes addressed the
firestorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider the sources,'' he said. ``Now if \Rformer boss\S
Darrell Royal calls me and tells me I'm doing a \Rbad\S job _ and
he might _ that would worry me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're going to get this team ready to play, and I'm not
going to worry about what people are saying because I don't care. I
really don't. A lot of things are important to me _ things I hold
dear _ but \Rkeeping\S this job is way down the list. These kids
are a lot more important than this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Rob Peters, who has also taken his share of blame
for Tech's 1-2 start, said the players regrouped during the
off-week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, we found out a lot about ourselves,'' Peters said.
``We had a good team meeting. Some admitted they weren't playing
like they should. Others challenged some people. I believe we're
headed in the right direction. We realize we've got to have each
other. It's us against the world _ maybe even Lubbock.''
</P>
<P>
   Extenuating circumstances abound, though Tech fans are not
interested in debating them after what they consider to be the
inexcusable loss to the Mean Green. The most pertinent is the loss
of four of the Raiders' best offensive players _ tailback Ricky
Williams, fullback Sammy Morris and two offensive linemen _ in the
first half of the first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they got off to a pretty good start in the Arizona
State game, and then they lose their guys and have to play without
them for a few weeks,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said. ``That makes a
huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't realize what kind of an impact that had,''
Tech linebacker Kyle Shipley said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams re-injured the strained ligaments in his right knee in
practice Tuesday and is out for the season. But he is aware the
personnel losses have taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me and Sammy, you're looking at two captains who bring a
lot of motivation and leadership to the team,'' he pointed out.
``But I think this team got it back last week \Rand is\S mentally
ready to play Texas A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he also was surprised by fan reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how so many people can doubt \RDykes\S like they
are,'' he said. ``We've only lost two games. We can still win the
Big 12. We do that and a lot of people are going to look pretty
silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Dykes won't speak about it publicly, sources close to him
confirm that he would have retired two years ago if not for wanting
to see Tech through a four-year NCAA probation that has forced his
program to operate under an 80-scholarship limit and lose 18
initial grants through the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into all that,'' Dykes said with a wave
of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed \R13 years as Tech's head coach\S. I love this
school. I love these kids. I'm going to have fun today. I'm going
to enjoy next week. I'm going to have a lot of fun until the last
day _ whenever that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to lay awake at night and worry about this
deal. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Sharon and Spike get their mail at home now. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
