<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS CONTINUE TO SLIDE ON STRONG ECONOMIC NEWS
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index on Friday was flat, rising
a mere 0.10 point, to 1,282.81. The index is up 4.36 this year and
had been down 10.6 percent this week from its July 16 high, putting
it into what Wall Street defines as a correction _ a selloff of 10
percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Other market gauges resumed their slide after reports showed
that the economy's surging growth has not slowed in recent months.
The data renewed concerns that the Federal Reserve might raise
interest rates next week. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
63.95 points, to 10,273, and the NASDAQ composite index fell 9.31
points, to 2,736.85.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.13 percent from
6.04 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY'S MILLENNIUM BOOKINGS ARE SLOW
</P>
<P>
   Bookings for the New Year's holiday have been slow in New York,
and there is at least the possibility that for hoteliers,
restaurateurs and impresarios, the party to end this or any other
century may turn out to be a bit of a bust. A new survey by the
agency that oversees the city's tourism efforts, NYC &AMP; Co., finds
that three-quarters of the 40 hotels that responded are not yet
fully booked.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA NAMES LIAISON TO DOCTORS
</P>
<P>
   Health insurer Aetna named a division president, John Kelly,
director of the company's new office of physician relations to help
bolster its ties with doctors. The creation of the unit comes after
the American Medical Association, among others, objected to Aetna's
$1 billion purchase of the Prudential Insurance Company of
America's health-insurance unit in August, saying it would hurt
competition in the managed health care market.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING GREW IN SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing sector grew in September much more strongly
than expected, while prices of raw materials soared to the highest
level in more than four years. The report by the National
Association of Purchasing Management confirms that industry is
recovering from the Asian financial crisis and provides further
evidence that the economy rebounded from a sluggish second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   EURO ENDS WEEK UP 3.6 PERCENT AT $1.07
</P>
<P>
   The euro, the common currency adopted in January by 11 European
nations, jumped 3.6 percent this week. It reached $1.0767 in
European foreign-exchange trading, its highest level in eight
weeks, before settling in New York at $1.0728. European central
bankers have turned hawkish in the last few days, warning that
inflationary pressure might be rising again and that it might well
be necessary to cool things down with an increase in interest
rates. Wim Duisenberg, the central bank's president, said Europe's
outlook for growth had improved and dangers to price stability
should not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   JOINT VENTURE GUIDELINES PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission
published proposed guidelines for joint ventures among businesses,
indicating the sorts of agreements that do not violate Federal
antitrust laws. The guidelines are subject to comment for 90 days,
after which time the agencies will decide whether to modify or
approve them.
</P>
<P>
   KELLOGG TO BUY VEGETARIAN SPECIALIST
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg plans to buy vegetarian food maker Worthington Foods for
$307 million. Worthington's shares shot up 60 percent, gaining
$8.6875, to $23.0625, in Nasdaq trading. Worthington Foods
specializes in manufacturing and marketing products like vegetarian
burgers and meatless sausage, chicken and hot dog products.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOREAN REPAYMENT IS SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Creditors have voted to demand the full repayment of $1.4
billion in outstanding Ecuadorean discount bonds. The vote comes
after Ecuador defaulted on a $44.5 million interest payment on the
bonds Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
