<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-FRESNOSTATE-TEX </SLUG>
 
FROGS WON'T BE WELCOME IN `DOG HOUSE' (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione will introduce the Horned Frogs to
one of his old haunts tonight ... a charming arena in California's
San Joaquin Valley known affectionately as ``The Dog House.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulldog Stadium is the home of the Fresno State Bulldogs (2-2),
who _ along with the Frogs (1-2) _ are the favorites in the Western
Athletic Conference title race.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the engagement is therefore somewhat awkward,
since it is the conference opener for both teams. Properly
distressed by this development, Franchione's response is the
equivalent of, ``So what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little bit early to be worrying about `title
showdowns,''' he said. ``There's a lot of football left, and the
way this league is, I don't think anyone is going to come through
without at least one loss, maybe two.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team, and this is an important game for us. But
as I told the team, it doesn't count more than any other game.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione has adroitly sidestepped the suggestion that a
``rivalry'' is growing between the two schools, based on their
status as favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rivalry?'' he said. ``No, I don't sense any rivalry here. It
takes more than one game \Ra 21-10 TCU win last year\S to develop a
rivalry. Most of our kids have probably never even been to
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the chunk of California occupied by 41,000-seat
Bulldog Stadium, Franchione has been there, memorably.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went in there my first year at New Mexico \R1992\S,'' he
said, ``and I'll never forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had beaten New Mexico, 49-17, the year before, and I
guess they figured on an easy game. When we went in with a lead at
the half, it was like their fans became enraged. They were very
abusive, throwing things and screaming at us. I'm not even sure
they realized I was the head coach, but they knew I was from New
Mexico and it was one time when I was very grateful for the police
escort. We ended up losing by three points.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State coach Pat Hill has vowed to recreate the Bulldogs'
glory period of the 1980s, when they achieved success under coach
Jim Sweeney with quarterbacks like Kevin Sweeney (the coach's son)
and Trent Dilfer and were known as ``Wide Receiver U.''
</P>
<P>
   He also regards this as a rivalry, regardless of what the Frogs
think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for this game for a year,'' he said. ``They
beat us down there last year and outplayed us, and they're an
exceptionally good program.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his evaluation of TCU's two-headed quarterback
monster, Hill replied, ``We're preparing for their starter, Patrick
Batteaux.''
</P>
<P>
   This despite the fact Batteaux didn't play last week due to a
hand injury and freshman Casey Printers is expected to start. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
