<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     10-01 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA, ASU ARE DESPERATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Both coaches have three daughters. Both worked
for John Robinson at USC, and both used to play the sax. But the
similarities don't end there for UCLA coach Bob Toledo and Arizona
State boss Bruce Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   Their teams, which meet today in Sun Devil Stadium, are united
in injury, they are united in defeat, and they are united in
desperation. When dusk falls and the desert shadows disappear, one
of them can make millennium plans. The Rose Bowl won't be an
option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pivotal game,'' Toledo said. ``The winner still has an
outside shot at the Rose Bowl. The loser, in my opinion, is out of
the Rose Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The loser will have two conference losses _ first-place Stanford
has none _ and while that doesn't guarantee elimination, it comes
pretty close. In the last 40 years, there have been just four
two-loss champions. The most recent was UCLA in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Stanford wins the head-to-head tiebreaker with UCLA
(2-2, 0-1) based on its victory last week. If the Bruins lose
today, they'll need Stanford to lose three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened when we lost to Stanford was we lost our margin
for error,'' Bruins safety Joey Strycula said. ``We still have a
legitimate shot at the Rose Bowl, but we have to win out. If we
lose (today), it's the Aloha Bowl or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Same for Arizona State (1-2, 0-1), which suffered the biggest
upset in Pac-10 history two weeks ago. A 25-point favorite, the Sun
Devils lost to New Mexico State by 28 points. Last week, they
wasted a fourth-quarter lead and lost to Cal 24-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we took a huge step in getting rid of (the New Mexico
State) loss,'' Snyder said. ``Maybe we still have little remnants.
But we have a chance to not carry it for the season. If we do,
it'll be like an anchor.''
</P>
<P>
   Predicaments aside, the Bruins and Sun Devils have plenty in
common:
</P>
<P>
   _Both have injured tailbacks. Arizona State's J.R. Redmond,
perhaps the best player in the Pac-10, has a slight shoulder
separation and practiced sparingly this week. Despite his official
status (questionable), Redmond told reporters he expects to play.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA tailback DeShaun Foster did not participate in contact
drills this week because of a sprained ankle suffered in the first
quarter at Stanford. Chances are, he'll play. But how long _ and
how effective he'll be _ is unknown. (Senior Keith Brown will start
at tailback for UCLA.)
</P>
<P>
   _Both have quarterbacks with bruised ribs, which means both are
one tackle from the training table. UCLA's Cory Paus has had two
weeks to recover and looked sharp in practice Thursday. ASU's Ryan
Kealy, who was injured at Cal, missed several practices early in
the week.
</P>
<P>
   _Both teams have inconsistent offenses _ partly the result of
injured quarterbacks _ and porous defenses. New Mexico State rushed
for 363 yards on Arizona State, while Stanford passed for 465
yards, a record for UCLA opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game will show a lot about the character of our team,''
Toledo said. ``And I hope it's good character.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, the Bruins will be home on New Year's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
