<HEADER>
A4191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BADILLO-HISPANICS-ART     10-01 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BADILLO-HISPANICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUNY LEADER GETS SUPPORT AFTER UPROAR ON COMMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a lengthening lineup of Hispanic political
leaders calling for the removal of Herman Badillo as chairman of
the City University of New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Gov.
George Pataki said Friday that they would stand by him, though they
described as inappropriate his remarks about Dominican and Mexican
students that ignited the uproar.
</P>
<P>
   A number of prominent Hispanic officials _ including Fernando
Ferrer, the Bronx borough president, Guillermo Linares, a Manhattan
councilman, Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez of the Bronx _ have
demanded Badillo's removal, saying remarks he made last week
demonstrate that he is racially insensitive and bigoted and not fit
to be CUNY's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Many who are calling for Badillo's dismissal have strongly
opposed the policies he has introduced at CUNY, including the
exclusion of remedial students from CUNY's bachelor's degree
programs, and his remarks last week gave them one more ground for
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo's comments came in response to a question about how
immigrant children with little formal education should be taught,
and he explained that the city's middle schools face an influx of
students from the hills of the Dominican Republic and Mexico who
arrive with little formal education. He referred to the immigrants
as ``pure Indians _ Incas and Mayans who are about, you know, five
feet tall with straight hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that in Mexico and Central America, there has
never been a tradition of education,'' he told the audience at a
lunch sponsored by the Center for Educational Innovation on Sept.
22.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo, who was born in Puerto Rico, two days later issued a
statement that stressed his role as ``passionate defender of
immigrant rights.'' He added: ``I know my words were wrong and I
apologize. My intent was to suggest assistance to the groups
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But the apology did not quiet the criticism or calls for his
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani acknowledged that Badillo had used ``wrong and
insensitive'' words in talking about immigrants but called the
attacks on Badillo politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole political agenda in trying to remove,''
Giuliani said. ``They are not trying to remove him because of the
remarks that he made, they are trying to remove him because they
don't like the policy and direction of CUNY, and this is a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Deister, a spokesman for Pataki, said the governor
continued to back Badillo. ``Obviously his remarks were
inappropriate and he's acknowledged that,'' the spokesman said,
``but that by no means overshadows his accomplishments or his
commitment to provide CUNY students with a better education.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor appoints 10 of CUNY's 17 trustees as well as the
chairman and vice chairman of the board. He named Badillo chairman
in late May.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo, who declined to be interviewed Friday, has been in a
battle with many leading Hispanic politicians for years. Once a
liberal Democrat who served as Bronx borough president and a
congressman in the late 1960's and early 70s, Badillo is seen as
having become more conservative in his views and he recently joined
the Republican Party and has expressed interest in running for
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Some Hispanic leaders defended Badillo.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ruben Diaz, president of the New York Hispanic Clergy
Organization, with more than 150 Hispanic ministers, said the
political leaders attacking Badillo were widening the splits in the
Hispanic community when they should be healing them. He argued that
while Badillo had used some inappropriate words, he had done more
for Hispanic people in the United States than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herman Badillo is not racist,'' Diaz said. ``He has helped
Dominicans. He has helped Puerto Ricans. They are using Herman
Badillo to advance their own political agenda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
