<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4192 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SUV-BUYERS-TEST(EXCLU     10-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-BUYERS-TEST(EXCLUSIVE)-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EMBARGO: 6 P.M. EDT)  
 A TALE HANGS IN THE TEST NUMBERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Big cars and minivans produce sterling performances in
federal crash tests. Large sport utility vehicles, which tend to be
modified pickup trucks with very stiff bodies that absorb little
energy in a crash, often fare worse.
</P>
<P>
   When regulators crashed a new Chevrolet Impala sedan into a
concrete and steel barrier at 35 miles an hour recently, the dummy
in the driver's seat escaped largely unscathed. Measured on a point
scale in which 500 reflects a 1-in-25 chance of a life-threatening
injury and 1,000 indicates a greater than 1-in-6 chance, the dummy
in the Impala test suffered only 322 points' worth of harm.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when a big Dodge Durango sport utility vehicle with
four-wheel drive took the same test last December, the dummy in the
driver's seat suffered head injuries scored at 1,008, as well as
severe chest injuries. It was the worst score for driver's head
injury of any recently tested vehicle and was particularly
dismaying to regulators because it was the second time they had
tested the Durango; DaimlerChrysler had made adjustments to the
vehicle after it scored equally poorly in the first test a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I look at the truck, it's beautiful, but my gosh, it does
let tremendous forces go into the dummy,'' said Richard Morgan, the
group leader of the government's New Car Assessment Program, which
runs the tests.
</P>
<P>
   The government conducts a separate test at 30 miles an hour
before letting any vehicle be sold in the United States. If the
Durango had recorded the same head- or chest-injury scores on the
slower test, it would have flunked and been ineligible for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But the slower test was never performed on the Durango; instead,
the government accepted DaimlerChrysler's assurances that the
Durango was virtually identical to the Dodge Dakota pickup truck,
which was tested and passed with good scores.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Gruber McLean, a DaimlerChrysler spokeswoman, said the
company had done many of its own safety tests on the Durango,
including the basic safety test at 30 miles an hour, and the
vehicle had always passed. ``We're confident this vehicle offers
adequate protection for its occupants and meets all the standards
it needs to meet, or exceeds them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLean contended that federal crash tests at 35 miles an
hour are meant ``to reflect a Durango hitting a Durango, which is a
very rare crash.'' But regulators and the insurance industry
disagree, saying the tests also simulate what happens when a
vehicle hits a fixed object or another vehicle of similar size and
weight.
</P>
<P>
   The Durango was also rated ``acceptable'' in a somewhat
different test for the insurance industry, in which a vehicle hits
a barrier with its front, driver's-side corner, rather than with
its whole front as in the government test.
</P>
<P>
   Other sport utility vehicles have somewhat better crash test
scores than the Durango does for head and chest injuries, but do
worse on potentially crippling leg injuries. The Cadillac Escalade,
Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon Denali full-size sport utility
vehicles have the worst scores for injuries to drivers' legs of any
automobiles on the market that regulators have tested.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeep Grand Cherokee has the worst scores for injuries to
front passengers' legs, according to raw data from recent
government tests.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Volvo S-70 sedan and V-70 wagon have the best
scores on driver's head injury among currently available
automobiles of any type, while the Ford Windstar minivan does best
on chest injuries to drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utilities do better than large cars and almost as well as
minivans on side-impact tests that the government recently began
conducting. Such side-impact crashes, although often deadly, are
much less common in the real world than frontal crashes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4193 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SUV-BUYERS(EXCLUSIVE)     10-01 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-BUYERS(EXCLUSIVE)-ART-3TAKES-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EMBARGO: 6 P.M. EDT) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Mich.)  
 THE UNSUNG COMEBACK OF THE LARGE CAR  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3)  
 (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; DETROIT _ As the 2000 model year arrives, sport utility vehicles
have captured the hearts and garages of millions of Americans,
while sales of large cars and minivans are lagging.
</P>
<P>
   But many in the auto industry say there is an untold story:
large cars and minivans have been greatly improved. They actually
do as well as or better than sport utility vehicles by many of the
criteria American buyers have long considered most important. These
include price, performance, passenger comfort and, perhaps most
surprisingly, safety.
</P>
<P>
   The height and sturdy appearance of sport utility vehicles make
them seem safer than cars to many buyers. But in crashes, people in
the latest large cars and minivans are less likely to die than
people in all but the very largest sport utility vehicles,
according to an insurance industry analysis to be released this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Even the very largest sport utilities have death rates only
slightly lower than those of large cars and minivans, yet are far
more likely to kill occupants of other vehicles in crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The safety comparison goes beyond death rates. Recent federal
crash tests show that large cars like the Ford Crown Victoria and
Chevrolet Impala, and minivans like the Honda Odyssey and Ford
Windstar, provide more protection than large sport utility vehicles
like the Dodge Durango and the Cadillac Escalade.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, sport utility vehicles have received many of the worst
scores in recent tests and are more likely to roll over than cars
or minivans, according to a Federal study last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors that are important to buyers also favor large cars
and minivans over more popular sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Consider price. Auto makers sell large cars and minivans at thin
profit margins and often offer rebates. They tack markups of $5,000
on pickups and of $10,000 to $15,000 on large sport utility
vehicles, often with no rebates.
</P>
<P>
   Consider performance. The typical large car can now accelerate
from zero to 60 miles an hour in 9.2 seconds, almost 2 seconds
faster than a large sport utility vehicle, according to government
figures. And because large cars are lower and lighter, they tend to
be more nimble and to brake more quickly, especially on wet
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Minivans, which are built like large cars but with taller
passenger compartments that produce more wind resistance, roughly
match large sport utility vehicles in acceleration times and handle
better, though not quite as well as cars.
</P>
<P>
   Consider spaciousness. Large cars and minivans offer leg room
and shoulder room similar to that of sport utility vehicles for
passengers in the front two rows of seats, and almost as much
headroom. Minivans also provide a third row of seats, as large
sport utilities do.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans care little these days about their vehicles' fuel
economy or emission of air pollutants, industry surveys show. But
on these criteria, too, large cars do far better than sport utility
vehicles, while minivans tend to be in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Strict government standards for cars have forced auto makers to
design large cars that now get up to 32 miles a gallon on the
highway. That is double the mileage of some of the biggest sport
utility vehicles, which are allowed by law to be considerably less
fuel efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Cars of all sizes also emit less than half the volume of
smog-causing gases for each mile that most large sport utility
vehicles do. (Ford now builds its sport utilities to pollute no
more than cars.)
</P>
<P>
   People who know automobiles usually say that big cars offer a
better combination of driving performance, affordability and
roominess than other large vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would steer most families toward a large sedan because they
provide the best cross-section of capabilities,'' said Csaba Csere,
editor in chief of Car and Driver magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Even auto makers, wealthy from sport utility profits,
acknowledge that big cars are underappreciated. ``Trucks are not as
nimble, they're not as light, and if you don't have the need for
the load-carrying capability or the three rows of seats, the
passenger cars are a great value and a lot of fun to drive,'' said
Ronald Boltz, a senior vice president at DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, large cars have two substantial disadvantages when
compared with sport utility vehicles: they have less cargo space,
and they are not as tall. These days, Americans increasingly like
riding up high, or at least dislike being in short automobiles when
motorists around them are driving taller models.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the many advantages of the latest large cars and minivans
have not been much help to the people who market them because to
many Americans these products are something worse than less safe,
less economical or less nimble: They are out of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, children liked to play with model sports cars
and dreamed of the day when they might drive the real things. But
auto industry market researchers now say that the younger a person
is, the more enthusiastic he or she is about sport utility
vehicles. That could shape the auto market for many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   When DaimlerChrysler held promotional events for its cars and
for its Jeeps recently in a Detroit suburb, visitors to the car
promotion mostly had gray hair or were balding. The Jeep display
across the street, which included an off-road driving course, was
full of families with children.
</P>
<P>
   Milo Perreault, 11, from Shelby Township, Mich., ogled the sport
utilities and spoke wistfully of the long wait until he would be
old enough to drive. ``I'd actually like a Jeep,'' he said. ``Some
of the sports cars, like the Viper, are low to the ground, and in a
Jeep I like the height.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, market researchers did not even ask about
height. Now surveys show that visibility from the driver's seat
ties a vehicle's driving performance and interior comfort as the
most important attributes that buyers seek.
</P>
<P>
   The taller sport utilities do well on this score, especially the
new Ford Excursion. It has just replaced the Chevrolet Suburban as
the world's largest sport utility vehicle, and at 6 feet 8 inches,
it allows tall drivers to look over the roofs of Suburbans.
Excursion drivers must climb two tall stairs and a short one just
to get in to the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mary Cumberland, 76, who drives a big 1997 Chrysler New Yorker
and lives in Southfield, Mich., said she had always driven large
cars. But she was not sure that she wanted another because she was
tired of having other vehicles block her view of the road. ``A lot
of people are considering sport utilities just out of
self-defense,'' she said. ``I'm trying to get my husband to
consider a van, to be up higher.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest cars are low and streamlined, making them very stable
as well as reducing wind resistance and improving fuel efficiency.
But the seats and door openings in large cars are lower than they
were a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion and seating height have contributed to the recent
stagnation in sales of large cars and minivans. Sales of large cars
have tumbled to 4 percent of the overall market, from 10 percent in
the early 1980s and from close to half the market in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Minivan sales, which had been hot and growing rapidly as
recently as the early 1990s, have now leveled off, and actually
lost some of their share of all new vehicles sold, falling to 8
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of sport utility vehicles, of course, have been soaring.
Though their annual growth rate peaked in 1996, the big vehicles
have still been the fastest-growing segment of the auto market
every year since 1994. Sport utility vehicles now account for a
majority of the luxury auto market and almost a fifth of the
overall market, up from less than 2 percent of each in the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Just by looking at sport utilities, some Americans conclude that
they are safer than cars and minivans. Their rugged, even
intimidating, appearance seems to remind buyers of the safety
advantages of size, an advantage that Americans used to forget in
buying small cars, said Adrian Lund, an insurance industry safety
researcher.
</P>
<P>
   But recent research by the government and the insurance industry
shows that, contrary to popular perception, sport utility vehicles
do not keep their occupants any safer than cars or minivans, or
even as safe in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   For example, large cars and minivans are increasingly winning
the government's highest, five-star rating for driver protection in
a frontal crash, but not one sport utility vehicle has won the
highest rating for such protection. And some of the worst safety
scores in crash tests have gone to sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government assigns stars without assessing an
automobile's propensity to roll over. Sport utility vehicles and
pickup trucks fared worst in a federal study last summer that
looked at vehicles' tendency to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   The new insurance industry analysis, which included federal data
on every fatal crash reported in the United States last year, finds
that 106 occupants of large cars like the Impala and smaller
minivans like the Dodge Caravan died in crashes for every million
registered vehicles of those types.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, 131 occupants of large sport utility vehicles
like the Dodge Durango died in crashes for every million registered
automobiles of those types.
</P>
<P>
   For the very largest sport utility vehicles, like the Chevrolet
Suburban and the Lincoln Navigator, the death rate was slightly
lower than for large cars, at 93, while for midsize sport utility
vehicles like the Jeep Grand Cherokee and Chevrolet Blazer it was
much higher, at 151.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller minivans, like the Caravan, ended up being included
in the large car category in the study because they were similar in
wheelbase and construction and behaved similarly in crashes. Bigger
minivans, like the Windstar and Odyssey, wound up in the very large
car category, which also includes Lincoln Town Cars and which had a
death rate of 107.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ricardo Martinez, the administrator of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration, said sport utility vehicles were no
safer for their occupants than other types of automobiles. ``It has
become a popular myth that the SUV is bigger and better, but we're
very concerned that people understand the tradeoffs,'' said
Martinez, a former emergency room physician. ``It's taller, and
that may help it in some kinds of crashes, but it also makes it
more likely to roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while people in sport utility vehicles die at least as
often as people in cars and minivans, they tend to die differently.
With minivans and cars, the fatalities tend to occur in collisions
with other vehicles, especially sport utility vehicles and pickup
trucks. But with sport utilities, deaths come relatively more often
when the vehicle rolls over.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles also tend to provide much less protection
for occupants than cars during collisions with solid objects, as
when a vehicle slides on a slippery road and hits a bridge or tree.
</P>
<P>
   Data from recent government crash tests into solid barriers also
strongly suggest that sport utilities provide poor protection
during collisions with other sport utilities, although regulators
say they have never crashed sport utilities together to check.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles fare better than other types of vehicles
in collisions with cars. The height and weight of a sport utility
vehicle allow it to pass over the strongest parts of a car and
penetrate deep into it, so that the car and its occupants absorb
the brunt of the crash, according to recent studies by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez and other safety experts say it is a mistake to be
concerned only about collisions with cars. Indeed, surveys have
found that most drivers think their own driving skills are far
above average, and do not pay adequate attention to the possibility
that they will make mistakes themselves or encounter poor driving
conditions, like icy roads. Single-vehicle crashes account for
nearly half of all fatal accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Rollovers represent the biggest problem for sport utilities,
causing more than a third of all deaths in those vehicles, compared
with only a tenth of the deaths in cars. Recent federal research
has found very few cases in which vehicles roll over because their
owners swerve violently on a road. Instead, according to federal
research backed by auto makers' own findings, 92 percent of
rollovers occur after a vehicle has been ``tripped'' by striking a
curb, guard rail or another vehicle, or catches the wheels on one
side in the dirt or mud of a road's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers should be concerned about all types of crashes, and not
just the possibility that a bad driver will crash into them,
Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to protecting their own occupants better than most
sport utilities do, large cars and minivans pose less hazard to
other motorists. They are only a third as likely to kill the other
driver in a crash as large sport utilities are, according to a
study to be published in the winter issue of the Journal of Crash
Prevention and Injury Control.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The height, stiffness and weight of sport utilities account for
the difference, according to the study, which was written by W.
Thomas Hollowell, a senior federal researcher, and his former aide,
H. Clay Gabler, now in academia.
</P>
<P>
   William Powers, Ford's vice president for research, said in a
speech on Aug. 5 that in the years ahead, motorists will ``see
increasing diversity in vehicle size, raising further issues in
occupant protection, vehicle-to-vehicle compatibility and
pedestrian protection. There is a lot of work yet to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, before tall automobiles became more common and
made visibility from the driver's seat an issue, Americans shopped
for the roomiest, best-handling vehicles at the best prices. If
that were still true, dealers would have trouble keeping cars and
minivans in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Large cars, minivans and big sport utility vehicles all cost
around $20,000 for carmakers to build, and a little more if they
are luxury models with lots of leather and fancy gadgets like
navigational computers.
</P>
<P>
   But while many large cars and minivans sell for under $26,000,
three-quarters of the nation's sport utility vehicles sell for more
than $26,000. The difference, analysts say, lies in the
manufacturers' fatter profit margins on sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Large cars and minivans offer seats that are just as roomy and
comfortable as sport utility vehicle seats _ more comfortable, if
the bumpy ride of sport utilities is considered. While large cars
these days may look smaller on the outside than the big sedans of
the 1970s, they are just as spacious on the inside. And while the
trunks of large cars may not accommodate tables and chairs, the
cargo areas of minivans do.
</P>
<P>
   Minivans have as much cargo room behind the second row of seats
as all but the largest sport utility vehicles, industry statistics
show. And because the second row of seats in most minivans can be
removed, while the second row in most sport utility vehicles can
only be folded down, minivans are actually the roomiest vehicles
for people with very large possessions to move.
</P>
<P>
   Many television advertisements show cars swooping through tight
curves on mountain roads. Ads for sport utility vehicles seldom
show this, for a good reason: sport utility vehicles are less
maneuverable than cars, or even minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Car and Driver magazine tests vehicles by having them swerve
over one lane to the left and then swerve back into their original
lane, as though circumventing an obstacle. The magazine found last
year that family sedans could accomplish the maneuver safely at
average speeds up to 63.4 miles an hour, and minivans up to 57.9
miles an hour; for luxury sport utility vehicles, the average was
53.9 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Csere said sport utilities' high centers of gravity, high weight
and off-road tires gave them inferior handling. ``SUV's are clearly
worse than cars of any kind, whether small or large,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer weight of sport utility vehicles also makes them
harder to stop than cars or minivans, especially on wet or snowy
roads. Indeed, Thomas Davis, General Motors' group vice president
for light trucks, said that, contrary to popular perception,
four-wheel drive does not help vehicles stop, nor does it help them
maneuver while braking.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the ways they compare favorably with sport
utilities, large cars and minivans suffer from an image problem.
Despite considerable improvements over the last five years,
especially in driving performance, minivans in particular are
unfairly derided, said Ralph Sarotte, DaimlerChrysler's general
manager for minivans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone put the `soccer mom' title on them, and a lot of
people don't want that image,'' he said. ``We could sell twice as
many minivans in this market if it were not for the image thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly that ``image thing'' is what makes sport utilities so
hot, auto executives say.
</P>
<P>
   ``SUVs are about image,'' said Joseph C. Collins Jr., Ford's
brand manager for sport utilities and minivans. ``It's about who
that customer is and who that customer wants to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
