<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-NEW-YEARS-VACANCIE     10-01 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEW-YEARS-VACANCIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1,090(2TAKES)-NY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOMS STILL AVAILABLE AT GROUND ZERO FOR NEW YEAR'S EVE
CELEBRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ADDS another price for tickets in 10th graf, that menu is only for
VIPs in 11th graf , Corrects spelling of ``Plaine'' in 13th graf.) 
(ATTN: Md., Calif., Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite everything you may have heard about
millennium madness, out-of-towners have not booked every overpriced
hotel room in the city for New Year's Eve. They have not snapped up
every $3,000 seat in the Rainbow Room, purchased every $1,000
ticket to every ``gala'' event, hired every limousine _ or even
every baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite all the hype, the puff, the ``reserve now or
you'll be ringing out the 20th century in Scranton'' threats,
bookings for the New Year's holiday have been slow. And there is at
least the possibility that for hoteliers, restaurateurs and
impresarios, the party to end this or any other century may turn
out to be a bit of a bust.
</P>
<P>
   Not a total bomb, of course. Reservations at hotels and
restaurants are still ahead of where they would be in a normal
year, and travel and tourism officials express confidence that
everything will be booked by the big night. A few events, like a
dinner at the American Museum of Natural History, have sold out.
But New Year's Eve has not, so far, been the blowout many expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's concern that it's not as strong as it was anticipated
to be,'' said one longtime hotel manager, who predicts that hotels
will start offering better deals in the weeks before New Year's
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   A new survey by the agency that oversees the city's tourism
efforts, NYC &AMP; Co., finds that three-quarters of the 40 hotels that
responded are not yet fully booked. Cristyne F. Lategano, on her
first day as president of the agency, said that many people are
only now beginning to nail down their plans for New Year's Eve,
adding, ``We expect this to be the greatest party ever thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   While most hotels are reluctant to reveal exactly how much (or
how little) of their space has been spoken for, the Hotel
Association of New York City says that ``most'' of its 158 members
are at least half full. A spot check of Manhattan hotels found
rooms available all over, even near Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   At the New York Hilton on Sixth Avenue at 53rd Street, rooms
start at $550 a night, about double the usual minimum charge. The
Waldorf-Astoria has rooms starting at $695 a night and $1,075
suites big enough for a private party (room service is extra). Even
the Marriott Marquis, which overlooks Times Square and received its
first request for a 1999 New Year's Eve reservation back in 1983,
just had some rooms open up after a group canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Sherpick of Baltimore was pleasantly surprised to find that
she could get a room at the Hilton _ she recently booked three, and
is bringing her husband's family from San Francisco. ``I think
we're a little crazy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations were clearly inflated at the Millennium Hotel on
44th Street. The hotel's management tried _ and failed _ to rent
the whole building to a single party giver. ``It's not inexpensive
to do, and nobody really had the budget for that,'' said Michael
Littler, vice president and general manager of the hotel. It still
has ``several handfuls'' of rooms available for New Year's Eve, at
prices of $695 a night for three nights; for a room with the view
of Times Square, add at least $150 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the hotels alone. Steven Leber, a theatrical producer
who hopes to lure 25,000 people to a party at the Javits Center,
reports that tickets (at $1,000 and $2,500) are still available.
``The scuttlebutt is that we're doing badly,'' he confided, but he
said that is not so though he will not reveal how many tickets have
been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found people are just waiting longer than expected'' to
make their plans, Leber said, adding that many balked at hotels'
high rates and four-day minimum stays. So he has arranged for some
one-night-only rooms at $500. And he plans to step up the
advertising for the event, Celebration 2000, emphasizing all of its
wonders: performances by Sting, Aretha Franklin and Tom Jones, a
disco room, a big band room, and for its VIPs a menu created by
Jean-Georges Vongerichten. ``People are either going to say that I
must be a nut job,'' Leber said, ``or that this is the most fun
thing ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Many restaurants, from the elegant Union Square Cafe to the
boisterous Virgil's Real BBQ on 44th Street, are planning to close
that night. But others are still accepting reservations for
extravagant meals; the River Cafe, for example, has a multicourse
dinner for $2,500 a person.
</P>
<P>
   At Millennium Limousine Service, cars are still available,
though the minimum rental is for 10 hours, and there is ``nothing
for less than $900,'' said Brian Plaine, the owner, who plans to
have 30 cars on the road by year-end. ``Everybody increased the
prices so outrageously, people are waiting for the best deal,''
Plaine said. (He'd like to have a party, himself, he said, ``but
I'll probably be sitting in my office, pulling my hair out.'')
</P>
<P>
   Things have been busy at the Baby Sitters Guild, which provides
sitters for hotels and individual families. People have been
reserving child care since April, said Heidi Davalos, who used the
service for her own children before going to work there. Sitters
are still available, though the price is steep: $250, in advance,
for five hours, and about $30 an hour thereafter. ``It's going to
be a rough holiday,'' Ms. Davalos said. ``If you want people to
work, you have to offer them something mildly attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of New York, Carnival Cruise Lines has hundreds of
cabins still available on a dozen millennial cruises in the
Caribbean and other points south. It turns out that most of the
trips were too long, said Jennifer de la Cruz, a spokeswoman for
Carnival. ``Most people have a limited amount of time.'' (Ms. de la
Cruz is planning to spend her New Year's Eve quietly with friends,
she said, though some of her siblings plan to travel.)
</P>
<P>
   A lack of vacation time and outrage over high prices were two of
the main reasons that 90 percent of Americans plan to stay put at
New Year's, according to a survey by Travel Weekly, a publication
for travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   And when people say they plan to stay at home, they literally
mean at home, according to a survey of more than 10,000 people done
by the Zagat restaurant-rating empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent said they wanted to be at home with friends
and family, which is the way I feel,'' said Tim Zagat, co-publisher
of the restaurant guides and chairman of NYC &AMP; Co., the city's
tourism agency. ``I probably shouldn't say this,'' Zagat said,
``but I want to be as far away from the city as possible and home
with my family.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who do want to go out on New Year's Eve want to be
somewhere extraordinary, like on top of Mount Everest, Zagat said.
</P>
<P>
   And for such people, believe it or not, New York City may not be
exotic enough. Take Margaret Barry, who works for the University of
Notre Dame in South Bend, Ind., but travels every chance she gets
to New York, where she worked for nine years. She considered
returning to the city for the big celebration, she said, ``But I
wanted to do something really different.'' Her New Year's Eve
destination: Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Even if some of the city's 55,000 hotel rooms remain vacant on
New Year's Eve, Times Square is unlikely to be noticeably empty
when the big ball drops. The crowd that traditionally attends tends
to be younger than the group that can afford to plunk down
thousands of dollars on hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And while many New Yorkers say being in Times Square at midnight
has all the allure of riding the Lexington Avenue local _ only
colder _ in the past city dwellers have made up only about 15
percent of the crowd, according to a study done several years ago
by the Times Square Business Improvement District, which sponsors
the ball-drop and attendant hoopla. Most of the revelers come from
the tri-state region, and many are college students whose schools
are closed.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Times Square BID expects more than 1 million
people to attend at least some of the festivities, which begin at
6:30 a.m. on Dec. 31. At that early, chilly hour, ``it's not like
at midnight, but there will be a substantial crowd there,'' said
Peter Kohlmann, the executive producer of the event, who will spend
New Year's Eve in Times Square between 45th and 46th streets,
``watching everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the crowds have become increasingly well-behaved _ and
sober _ in recent years, the very idea of being packed in with a
million revelers may be a turn-off even to those most likely to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Isa Ferguson, a 20-year-old college student living in Brooklyn,
would seem to be a likely candidate, given that she does not have
much money, but does not want to stay home. ``I keep thinking that
when my kids are asking me what did I do, I don't want to say,
`Well, I played Monopoly.'''
</P>
<P>
   So is she going to Times Square? ``Yeah, right,'' she said. ``I
don't think I want to be out,'' she added, confessing to a sneaking
suspicion that the so-called Y2K computer problem may really cause
at least limited problems when midnight rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   Even more sotto voce, some New Yorkers confess to a worry that
terrorists, publicity seekers or plain old nuts might think Times
Square on New Year's Eve is the perfect place to make an explosive
splash, as hundreds of millions of people watch on television.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials are reassuring: ``It will be business
as usual for us, because we are always in aggressive mode,
anyway,'' said Joseph Valiquette, a spokesman for the Federal
Bureau of Investigation. As for what he'll be doing, ``I guess I'll
be home,'' he said, ``I don't have any plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The high expenses that may keep some tourists out of the city
will also keep some New Yorkers home. Christine Kulisek, a
packaging designer, had planned to go to Mexico for the millennium,
but sky-high air fares changed her mind. Now she plans to have a
small black-tie dinner with friends and ``enjoy the Manhattan
festivities.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she plan to stop by Times Square? ``Oh no, I'll watch it on
TV,'' Ms. Kulisek said. ``Everybody there will be from out of town.
I don't think anyone from Manhattan will be anywhere near Times
Square, I really don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
