A4199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-RALL-NYT &LR;      10-01 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: D.C.)  
 DR. DAVID PLATT RALL, CANCER AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SPECIALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. David Platt Rall, a cancer specialist and a leader in
environmental health research, died on Tuesday in Bordeaux, France.
He lived in Washington and was 73.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was injuries suffered in an automobile accident 10
days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   During almost 50 years as a researcher, Rall was principal or
sole author of about 180 scientific papers.
</P>
<P>
   For 19 years, before he retired in 1990, he led the National
Institute of Environmental Health Sciences, a division of the
National Institutes of Health, and was an assistant surgeon general
in the Public Health Service. From 1978 until 1990, he also led the
National Toxicology Program.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Rall was chairman of the Program on Chemical
Safety for the World Health Organization. He also served as foreign
secretary of the Institute of Medicine at the National Academy of
Sciences, was a board member of the Environmental Defense Fund and
a scientific counselor at the National Institute of Occupational
Safety and Health.
</P>
<P>
   He was especially interested in the problems posed by anticancer
drugs, which tend to be toxic in the doses needed to be effective.
That led Rall to predict toxic effects in human patients based on
studies of laboratory animals. He also explored the effects of
chemicals in the environment on the health of people in various
occupations and in the population as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   David Platt Rall was born on Aug. 3, 1926, in Aurora, Ill., and
was reared in nearby Naperville. He received a bachelor's degree at
North Central College in 1950, and a medical degree and a doctorate
in pharmacology at Northwestern University.
</P>
<P>
   He was an intern at Bellevue Hospital in New York City before
joining the National Cancer Institute in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Rall's first wife, Edith Levy Rall, died in 1987. He is survived
by his wife, Gloria Monteiro Rall; two children, Jonathan David, of
Irvine, Calif., and Catharyn Elspeth Ertel of Siegsdorf, Germany;
two grandchildren, and a brother, Dr. Edward, of Kensington, Md. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-01-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991001.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      10-01 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BATTLE OF BROOKLYN  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Oct. 2:
</P>
<P>
   The chaotic nature of the debate over the ``Sensation''
exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum of Art must not obscure the two
big issues involved. They have to do with the ground rules for
government financing of cultural institutions and the political
censorship of constitutionally guaranteed freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable people can disagree about spending tax money to
support the arts, but both Congress, by funding the National
Endowment for the Arts, and the city government, by funding a
variety of museums and programs, have made the political decision
to authorize such expenditures. We support that approach
wholeheartedly, believing support for the arts is essential to both
the intellectual climate and economy of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   We also believe, as a matter of law and constitutional
principle, that once the financial support has been granted, as it
has been for years, the institutions must be free to spend it
according to their own professional standards. Otherwise, citizens
will continually face situations like the current one in which
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has turned a gut reaction into a
destructive, punitive policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has addressed this foundation of principle in
a way that is not totally satisfactory, but that sheds an
interesting light on the current situation. The justices affirmed
the right of Congress to set ``advisory'' standards of decency for
programs receiving grants. But the high court warned against
pulling back or denying money already allocated because of the
content of the works being exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of New Yorkers seem to have a clear understanding of
this principle. To be sure, many citizens of conscience find parts
of the Brooklyn exhibition repugnant, and it is understandable that
many Roman Catholics would find Chris Ofili's image of the Virgin
Mary offensive. Others would agree with our colleague William
Safire that while the museum has a right to show what it likes, the
administrators of the Brooklyn Museum have been clumsy or
needlessly provocative. Yet a Daily News poll shows that the
majority of New Yorkers support the museum over Giuliani by a ratio
of two to one.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers show a broad-based support for New York's role as
the nation's cultural capital. The people understand intuitively
what Giuliani ignores for political gain. A museum is obliged to
challenge the public as well as to placate it, or else the museum
becomes a chamber of attractive ghosts, an institution completely
disconnected from art in our time.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the battle will move to the courts. To support the
mayor's claim that the museum violated its lease, the city's
lawyers have concocted several theories. The city argues that the
museum broke its lease by conspiring with an auction house to
inflate the value of a private art collection at the expense of the
museum's public purpose. The city also argues that the museum
violated its public mission by deciding to charge a fee and to
exclude children under 17. We are confident the court will see the
city's arguments for what they are _ a pretext to justify the
mayor's anger at a museum that dared to defend artistic freedom. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
