r s BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN     10-01 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1,000 GAMES AND COUNTING FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Today's USC-Oregon State game marks the 1,000th
contest in the Trojans' history. Here's a look at some of the
important games that may have been largely forgotten in the first
50 years of this century:
</P>
<P>
   Stanford 16, USC 0; Nov. 4, 1905: This was not the first game in
school history, but it was the Trojans', uh, Methodists', first
against a major college. USC did not play another major college for
nine years after this loss. Football fell out of favor because of
its brutality, and many schools dropped the sport. USC dropped
football after 1910 and began playing rugby.
</P>
<P>
   USC 28, California 10; Oct. 23, 1915: This was the school's
first victory over a major college, although Cal was just beginning
to play football again after nine years of rugby.
</P>
<P>
   USC 14, Penn State 3; Jan. 1, 1923: This was the school's first
bowl game, and the start at the Rose Bowl was 45 minutes late
because Penn State was stuck in traffic. This was USC's first
victory with a national stature.
</P>
<P>
   USC was invited to play in the game because Cal turned down the
invitation several months before the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska 17, Notre Dame 0; Nov. 26, 1925: Why is this game
included? USC had been hoping to find a marquee rival and sent
graduate manager Gwynn Wilson and his wife to Lincoln for this
Thanksgiving Day game.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame coach Knute Rockne was initially against the idea of
a series with USC, but Wilson's wife persuaded Rockne's wife that a
trip to Los Angeles every two years beat out snowy Lincoln, where
the fans were hostile to the Irish. Mrs. Rockne spoke to her
husband, and the rivalry was born.
</P>
<P>
   USC 27, Notre Dame 14; Dec. 1, 1928: This was USC's first
victory over the Irish, and followed two straight one-point losses.
This is the Notre Dame team that defeated Army in the famous ``Win
one for the Gipper'' speech.
</P>
<P>
   USC was led by quarterback Don Williams and running back Russ
Saunders, who was the model for Tommy Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   USC 74, California 0; Nov. 8, 1930: This stands as the worst
defeat in Cal history. USC also defeated Stanford 41-12, marking
the first time it had swept the Bay Area schools.
</P>
<P>
   USC 16, Notre Dame 14; Nov. 21, 1931: Johnny Baker kicked a
33-yard field goal with a minute remaining as the Trojans snapped
the Irish's 26-game winning streak, won their first game in South
Bend and eventually won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   USC 38, Washington 7; Oct. 23, 1944: This was the first night
game for the Trojans in the Coliseum. Washington had travel
restrictions because of World War II, and was allowed to schedule
two games within seven days. Since the game had to be played on a
Monday, it became an evening contest.
</P>
<P>
   The game program said, ``This may well be the one and only
Coliseum night game in Trojan varsity football history.'' The crowd
of 62,865 was the largest of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
