<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-SWEEPSTAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WAITING FOR THE PRIZE MONEY AND GOOD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DUDLEY CLENDINEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the middle of this decade, as mailboxes across the country
filled with junk mail of every kind, all competing for the personal
attention and dollars of the American family, the two biggest
sweepstakes mailers in the nation, Publishers Clearing House and
American Family Publishers, became more aggressive in the language
they used to make people think they were about to win something
big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Eustace Hall,'' began a letter from Dorothy Addeo, the
contest manager at Publishers Clearing House, in Port Washington,
N.Y., to a 63-year-old day laborer in Brandon, Fla., who later
testified about it at a Senate hearing. ``I'm in a bit of hot water
and only you can help me out.'' Her boss had dropped into the
office to ask why Hall had not won a prize yet, Ms. Addeo wrote.
``It's not right when someone as nice as Eustace Hall doesn't
win,'' the boss supposedly said. Hall, who dreamed of sending his
daughter to law school, had bought many magazines from Publishers
Clearing House in hopes of winning a cash prize.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``with a little help from you, I can personally guarantee
that you'll win a prize in our sweepstakes,'' Ms. Addeo wrote _ as
much as $5 million if he replied by a certain deadline. Signed
``Dorothy,'' the letter went out in October 1997 to 900,000 people,
each of whom was told that the boss had dropped in to inquire why
he or she had not won. The conversation with the boss, Publishers
Clearing House has admitted, was a fiction, one of about 100
mailings a year designed to stir up orders for magazines and other
goods. But that letter, along with millions of others sent out by
American Family Publishers over the signatures of the television
personalities Ed McMahon and Dick Clark, to retirees like
Margaretha Cryde, in Hallandale, Fla. (``YOU'VE JUST BEEN
POSITIVELY IDENTIFIED AS OUR $11,000,000 MYSTERY MILLIONAIRE FROM
FL!''), began to have unforeseen effects.
</P>
<P>
   In a Florida nursing home, eight old ladies sat in party hats
all day, waiting in vain for the Clearing House Prize Patrol to
arrive. In Baltimore, a poor young mother pulled her children out
of school, borrowed the plane fare and flew to Tampa, Fla., where
American Family's mail and distribution center is, to claim a prize
she had not won. Scores of others followed by bus and plane. In
Toledo, Ohio, an aggrieved psychologist wrote to Florida's attorney
general, Robert Butterworth, to say that her retired father had
spent almost $90,000 in seven years in response to direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   About 1 billion sweepstakes letters are sent each year. One was
addressed to ``Attorney General,'' in Butterworth's office. One
went to ``God,'' at a church in central Florida. But it is the
poor, the uneducated and particularly the old _ raised in a more
trusting time, and now often failing in eyesight or mind _ who seem
most easily deceived. Their humiliation _ and their families' rage
_ have prompted state suits against the sweepstakes publishers,
congressional hearings and tons of bad publicity for the
sweepstakes companies. The 30 percent of new subscriptions they
normally supply to the nation's magazine publishers are off by a
third.
</P>
<P>
   Because their letters are carefully written to stay inside the
law, sweepstakes companies usually prevail if sued. But now, losing
business and good will, they have become an industry receptive to
reform. American Family Publishers paid $4 million in May to settle
civil charges in four states, and reached agreement with 36 other
states and the District of Columbia on what new mailings can say.
Unimpressed, the Senate voted 93-0 in August to pass the Deceptive
Mail Prevention and Enforcement Act, championed principally by
Susan Collins, R-Maine. In Florida last month, Butterworth filed
suit against Publishers Clearing House for false and deceptive
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would require that sweepstakes letters make it
``clear and conspicuous'' that winning is not automatic, that the
odds of winning are very small, and that buying merchandise does
not improve them. It would also give the Postal Service nationwide
authority to stop deceptive mailings and to impose fines as large
as $2 million. The matter now goes to the Postal Service
subcommittee in the House, which is led by Rep. John McHugh,
R-N.Y., and it should move quickly to a vote, the full committee
and the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the old people hurt by sweepstakes companies
have done a service in complaining. They have given Congress and
attorneys general like Butterworth good reason to crack down on the
monster that direct mail has become. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
