</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC SEEKS PRIME MOTIVATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Searching for a new way to motivate his team this
week, USC coach Paul Hackett sought the advice of Winston
Churchill. That might be all you need to know about how painful
last week's loss to Oregon turned out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett didn't tell the Trojans anything about fighting Oregon
State on the beaches, in the fields or in the hills. Instead, he
chose an easy-to-understand Churchill quotation to post in the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Churchill said, `The only answer for defeat is victory,'''
Hackett said. ``And in football, you can't wait to get back out
there after a loss. There's a lot on the line for this game.
Mostly, it's about getting back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   USC gets its chance to atone for last week's bitter loss by
playing Oregon State today at 3:30 p.m. in the Coliseum. The
Beavers have not beaten USC since 1967 and have not won in Los
Angeles since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not your average Oregon State football team. The
Beavers are undefeated (3-0) and poised to have their first winning
season in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in recent memory, USC will face an Oregon
State team capable of running and passing the football
proficiently. Tailback Ken Simonton leads the nation in rushing
(185.6 yards per game) while quarterback Jonathan Smith averages
277 yards passing. It's important to remember that Smith did not
even play in last year's 40-20 USC victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oregon State is a dangerous team for a couple reasons,''
Hackett said. ``One, they are rested and had a bye. Two, they have
a very potent offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers are formidable, but it stands to reason that the
Trojans need to worry more about cleaning up their own act. USC
committed a school-record 21 penalties against Oregon, and by
week's end Hackett was weary over criticism of the Trojans'
sloppiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of questions about our lack of discipline,'' Hackett
said. ``We've just got guys doing stupid things.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is an acceptable level of mistakes? Hackett said
anything under 10 penalties would be OK. But USC has been under 10
penalties in just four of the 16 games Hackett has coached.
</P>
<P>
   One promise Hackett made was that playing time would be cut
because of the penalties. That means time for freshman cornerbacks
Darrell Rideaux and Kevin Arbet, who will relieve starters Kris
Richard and Antuan Simmons, who each had three penalties last week.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line is also likely to have a minor shakeup, with
guard Faasea Mailo expected to start ahead of Donta Kendrick. The
reason for this change, however, is Kendrick's sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many other options along the line because nearly
every player has been guilty of infractions and few of the reserves
are ready to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can just stop stubbing our toes and putting the offense
in bad situations, we'll be OK,'' offensive line coach Steve
Greatwood said. ``We're our own worst enemy in the running game.
Instead of first-and-10, it's first-and-15, or first-and-20. We've
got to keep ourselves in some second-and-6 situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Another change to improve the blocking has occurred at fullback.
Sophomore Charlie Landrigan, on the scout team three weeks ago,
will make his first start ahead of slumping Brennan Ochs. It's a
sign that anything is being done to eliminate mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett knows that with the Pacific-10 Conference full of
inconsistent teams, it won't take much to get back into the Rose
Bowl race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone can win three in a row and they are right in the same
position as Stanford is today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: A crowd of about 45,000 is expected for today's game....
Hackett said reserve quarterback John Fox would not necessarily see
action in today's game to get him used to the position again. Fox
has not played quarterback in a game since November of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
