<SLUG> BC-WITNESS-FEAR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS COOPERATION IS CRUCIAL IN SOLVING CRIMES, AUTHORITIES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Police call him a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Clay County authorities might never have learned what happened
to 16-year-old James A. Weber had a young witness not volunteered
that a murder had been committed.
</P>
<P>
   He did the right thing, but with much apprehension, police say.
</P>
<P>
   He had good reason to be afraid.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Weber was killed because he
threatened to tell authorities about a planned armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The accused are behind bars, but the young witness may not be
out of harm's way. As a result, authorities will say little except
to praise his bravery.
</P>
<P>
   Police say it is increasingly difficult to get witnesses to come
forward, because many fear retribution.
</P>
<P>
   The fears are not unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Sophia Szymczak was to testify against Michael Farris, 44, in a
burglary trial. On Sept. 3 the 76-year-old Kansas City woman was
strangled in her home. Now Farris faces first-degree murder
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When situations like these happen,'' said Alvin Brooks,
president of the Ad Hoc Group Against Crime, ``it certainly has a
chilling effect on witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Burdened by fear
</P>
<P>
   Fear breeds silence. And that can impede investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to give us information,'' said Clay County
Prosecutor Don Norris, who is handling the Weber case. ``But
there's a very real fear of reprisal, not just from the individual
but also from some of that individual's friends and relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   It is happening in the case of Christy Schroeder, an 18-year-old
Northland woman who was murdered July 10. Authorities said she was
killed by William Brouse, who died in an Aug. 3 shootout with
police in Texas. But many questions remain unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get witnesses to talk so we can follow up on
other aspects of the case, but they're hesitant,'' County Sheriff
Bob Boydston said. ``We're seeing that they don't answer questions
directly, and the only thing we can attribute that to is that they
may still fear friends of Brouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses, he said, might have more to fear now than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's young criminals are more apt to use violence during
the crime and to keep witnesses from going to authorities and
telling what they saw,'' Boydston said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Whitley, spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Kansas City, said safety remained a serious and legitimate concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be some degree of risk,'' he said. ``But if
we ever decide, as a society, that we're going to let fear run that
process, then we have effectively turned over the power to the
criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Building trust
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also must battle distrust of the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found that people don't have a lot of confidence that the
system is going to work,'' Johnson County, Kan., Prosecutor Paul
Morrison said. ``They're thinking, `If it fails and this guy gets
out, he's coming after me.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say a lot of work goes into establishing
relationships and building the confidence of witnesses. Sometimes
police must appeal to the witness' sense of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to tell people, `If you don't help us, this person
will walk,' &UR; '' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Many law enforcement agencies offer temporary-relocation
programs and other protection for witnesses. Boydston said he
routinely informed potential witnesses of such programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Witness Protection Program since 1983 has provided
funding for moving expenses, food, and hotel stays, through the
state Department of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a witness is having a problem with threats and they let us
know, then we can help with relocation expenses or provide
additional security,'' Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said.
</P>
<P>
   County prosecutors can request the funding for witnesses and
victims alike, said Tami Holliday, spokeswoman for the Public
Safety Department. But with a budget of only $10,000, all
relocations are temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly to get them through the trial period and keep them
safe,'' Holliday said.
</P>
<P>
   The program helped six persons last year and two this year,
Holliday said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas the Victims' Assistance Unit in Johnson County has
worked with crime victims since 1978, and more recently, with
witnesses. Counselors from the unit's Courts Awareness Program meet
one-on-one with witnesses to address fears and concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In federal cases the government also provides temporary
relocation. And in the most-extreme situations the FBI's Witness
Protection Program can provide a new identity for persons in
serious and ongoing danger.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymity helps
</P>
<P>
   One way to help solve crimes without witnesses having to
identify themselves is to use anonymous tip lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Kansas City Crime Stoppers TIPS Hotline, sponsored
by the Kansas City Crime Commission, receives about 400 tips each
month, resulting in 50 to 70 arrests, said Sgt. Craig Sarver.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said such tips were instrumental in solving the 1996
murders of two Shawnee, Kan., women. James R. Watson pleaded guilty
to killing April Sima, 16, and Rebecca Carlson, 21, and was
sentenced in February 1998 to life in prison with no chance of
parole for 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to do the right thing,'' said Norris, in Clay
County. ``And that's the greatest asset we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, authorities sometimes must go to extremes to gain witness
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, if a witness is uncooperative or is a flight risk,
police can obtain a court order, under the Material Witness Bond
Law, and hold the person until the scheduled court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   These instances are rare, but Morrison said he had used the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't want to make witnesses a victim,'' he said.
``But we have a job to do, and we're serious about getting it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among authorities is that they cannot fight crime
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact remains that were it not for information from
witnesses, the vast number of cases would never be made,'' said
Whitley, of the U.S. attorney's office. ``The public needs to
remember that law-enforcement agencies and prosecutors alone can't
make a case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have witnesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
