<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-ANTIBRIBERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REASSURING PUBLIC IS IOC GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Utah)  (js) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee decided to let a foreign
anti-bribery treaty govern the actions of its members and cities
bidding for Olympic Games to reassure the public that there would
be no repetition of the recent Salt Lake City Olympic corruption
scandal, a committee spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's significant on a public relations scale,'' said Franklin
Servan-Schreiber, a spokesman for Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC
president. ``But we feel we're building enough firewalls inside the
organization that will be sufficiently deep to make sure the
problems don't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday the Olympic committee asked to be placed under the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development's
two-year-old convention on combating the bribery of foreign public
officials. Thirty-four nations have signed the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaty, any bribe directed at a committee member or
solicited by a member from a city that was bidding for the Olympics
would be prosecuted under anti-corruption legislation in 34
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the OECD was recommended by an independent
commission that investigated the Salt Lake City scandal. Ten
Olympic committee members resigned or were expelled because of the
scandal, and the committee adopted new procedures to limit members'
visits to cities that are bidding for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Duberstein, vice chairman of the investigative commission,
said: ``We welcome this further affirmation that they are committed
to reform. We look forward to their action on all our
recommendations with the hope they will accept them.''
</P>
<P>
   Duberstein said Capitol Hill, which has threatened severe
legislative measures if the Olympic committee is not seriously
reformed, should welcome the committee's agreement to be governed
by the anti-bribery standard ``as an indicator that Samaranch is
committed to a systemic campaign of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Servan-Schreiber said the Olympic committee would decide by
Monday whether Samaranch will testify Oct. 14 before a House
subcommittee investigating charges of vote buying during Atlanta's
successful bid for the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic committee also said it might postpone executive
board meetings in Colorado Springs and Salt Lake City in February,
but denied that a decision would be based on FBI and congressional
investigations into Olympic bids. The committee noted a conflict
with a meeting Feb. 10-13 in Sydney, Australia, the site of next
summer's Olympics. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
