<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-CAMPUS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS WOULD APPROVE A HYPOTHETICAL SPRINT-MCI MERGER, ESREY
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sprint Chairman William T. Esrey on Friday
would not confirm reported merger talks with MCI WorldCom, but _
speaking hypothetically _ he said such a deal could pass muster
with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey addressed reporters after dedicating Sprint's partly
completed $920 million headquarters campus in Overland Park, Kan.,
a suburb of Kansas City. The ceremony was attended by dignitaries
who expressed a mixture of pride in the huge project and
apprehension about Sprint's future ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said he had been fielding questions about possible deals
for a decade. Indeed, reports of the company's impending
acquisition have been standard fare in industry circles since
Sprint was formed by United Telecom and GTE in 1986. As long ago as
1987, The Wall Street Journal reported that Sprint was a prime
takeover target for MCI.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of MCI WorldCom, I think it's pretty clear that
merger could go through,'' Esrey said after the dedication. ``There
may be some Internet assets ... _ the extent of Internet backbone
that Sprint has and WorldCom has together _ that you would probably
have a divestiture there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would not be a big deal in the whole scheme of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey also stressed that if a merger were ever contemplated or
consummated, it would not be a doomsday scenario for about 15,000
Kansas City area employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to pose a hypothetical question, `What if MCI
WorldCom were going to buy Sprint?' I don't think it would make a
heck a lot of a difference around here,'' he said. ``If you look at
a pattern of the way they operate, I don't know anybody (who's)
ever moved to Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom has two headquarters, one in Mississippi and one in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Sprint were going to be acquired by somebody, it's being
acquired because of the capabilities and the talents of the
employees,'' he said. ``Nobody in their right mind would acquire
Sprint and blow up what they're acquiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey acknowledged, however, that recent reports about a
possible merger had been more persistent than those in the past and
were taking a toll on employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If rumors are true, I can't comment on them. And if rumors are
not true, I can't comment on them,'' Esrey said. ``That's the box
I'm in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's caused a lot of water-cooler comment. I've gotten a ton
of e-mail from our employees with questions and anxiety in some
cases.''
`Basic principle'
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said that the company had a ``tremendous commitment'' to
the Kansas City area and its employees and that those factors would
play an important part in any deal the company considered. But
management's primary consideration, he said, was to maximize
returns to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always (had) one basic principle, and that is, we're
in the business of creating value for our shareholders,'' he said.
``That's what management is supposed to do, over time, in the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   A combination of Sprint and MCI WorldCom would form a powerful
force in the global telecommunications industry, with a formidable
presence in local-service and long-distance markets, a substantial
collection of international assets, the premier wireless company in
the country and a potentially dominant share of data and Internet
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Most investment analysts think that combination would be far
more rewarding for shareholders than a deal with an international
partner such as Deutsche Telekom, which has no presence in the
United States. And as long as regional Bell companies, such as
Southwestern Bell, are forbidden from offering long distance, an
MCI WorldCom deal is far more feasible in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey repeated his longstanding position on Sprint's ability to
go it alone in the industry, despite the increasing scale and
deeper pockets of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said the same thing for 10 years,'' he said. ``Our
preference is to go it alone, but if anyone comes up and offers us
a price or creates a situation we think is better, we would act on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Sprint operates in parts of 19 states and would need to
seek approval from state, federal and European regulators, Esrey
estimated that it would take 12 to 18 months to complete any merger
into which the company entered.
--MORE--
</P>
<P>
   the company entered.
Backbone networks
</P>
<P>
   His comments about possible regulatory concerns in an MCI Sprint
deal match those of policy and industry analysts. Most observers
think the biggest hurdle would be potential concentration in the
top-level networks that provide long-haul connections throughout
the Internet, called backbone networks.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom and Sprint are the two largest Internet backbone
providers, together providing more than 43 percent of Internet
service providers with their connection to the Internet, according
to a recent survey by Boardwatch Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   When WorldCom bought MCI last year, Sprint was one of many
parties that complained to regulators that the merger constituted
``a severe threat to the competitiveness'' of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To expedite the merger, MCI agreed to sell its Internet business
to Cable &AMP; Wireless Inc. for $1.75 billion, along with the customer
contracts, employees, assets and services that would allow it to
replace MCI as a competitor in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Cable &AMP; Wireless is now suing MCI, alleging that it failed to
transfer all its customers, customer information and personnel, and
failed to provide all the services and support to operate the
business.
</P>
<P>
   MCI says it has filed a response to the allegations but declined
to provide any details.
</P>
<P>
   Any assets that the merged company would have to sell would be
eminently marketable.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal Constitution reported Friday that BellSouth
had approached investment bankers about the possibility of
purchasing a piece of Sprint, either its Internet network or its
local phone services business in the Carolinas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sprint's Internet backbone might be for sale in the
event of a deal with MCI WorldCom, BellSouth could not buy it until
regulators lifted the ban on Bell companies providing long-distance
voice or data services in their own territory. It was unclear
whether a merged company would be interested in selling any local
telephone assets.
Merger mania
</P>
<P>
   A Sprint MCI merger also might face regulatory resistance based
on the resulting concentration in long-distance markets and in the
ownership of wireless cable spectrum across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and MCI WorldCom collectively control more than 30
percent of the long-distance industry, and by some reports as much
as 37 percent. AT&AMP;T is said to have between 43 percent and 48
percent of long-distance markets.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the government's top telephone regulator sounded a
note of caution when asked about further consolidation in the
long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   William Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, would not specifically address reports of a pending
MCI-Sprint merger. But he did credit competition in long-distance
markets for cutting rates for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in America, consumers are enjoying the lowest
long-distance rates in history,'' Kennard said at a technology
conference. ``We cannot allow any merger to happen in this industry
that turns back the clock on that competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after WorldCom's takeover of MCI, Kennard warned that
the industry might be testing the limits of megamergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this merger is consummated, the industry will again be
poised just a merger away from undue concentration,'' Kennard said
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and MCI also have been acquiring wireless cable assets in
the last year, seeking a way to provide services to local customers
without leasing lines from the regional Bell companies. It was
unclear whether concentration in that market would give regulators
pause.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at Sprint's dedication ceremony Friday were circumspect
about the possibility that the company could be acquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the future holds, I don't know, but I'm counting on this
being a positive development in this state,'' said Kansas Gov. Bill
Graves. ``Until I hear something concrete, I'm operating under the
assumption that we're here to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Today reported this week that MCI WorldCom and Sprint could
announce a deal as soon as Monday. That looks increasingly
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said he planned to return to the office after the
celebration of the campus opening.
</P>
<P>
   And his plans for this weekend?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the weather cooperates, I plan to play golf or take a bike
ride,'' he said. ``I suspect I'll be in Kansas City on Monday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
