<HEADLINE>
SENIOR CIRCUIT PLAYERS AGREE 
MEN'S TENNIS COULD USE HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jimmy Connors can't watch it. Bjorn Borg said
rivalries are needed. Mats Wilander said the game is doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   But on one thing all three former ATP Tour players agree _ men's
tennis isn't in the greatest shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad, but I think I found myself doing other things,''
said Connors, who will play today in the semifinals of the
PricewaterhouseCoopers Champions senior tennis tournament at the
Four Seasons Resort &AMP; Club at Las Colinas. ``I don't watch it, or
talk about it, and it's better that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors has won 133 singles titles over a 20-year career, which
makes his opinion generally well-respected.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he took some shots at the game's current No. 1
player, Andre Agassi, and in July, he ripped the tour in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something needs to be done because tennis had dropped below
lawn bowling in popularity,'' Connors told the ``Detroit Free
Press'' in July. ``In my day, what we did off the court was as
interesting as what we did on it. That was when tennis athletes
were more than just a name.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mel Purcell, who was named the ATP Rookie of the Year in
1980: ``Jimmy gave it his all on the court. And Jimmy didn't have a
lot of talent. I think he sees Agassi with all this talent and
expects him to be No. 1 for the last 200 weeks. I really think he
feels Agassi fooled around with his talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilander, a winner of seven Grand Slam tournament titles, said
youngsters need to start playing the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this senior tour is going to help with the game,''
Wilander said. ``When the ball boys see us having so much fun out
there, they might want to pick up a racket and play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Wilander also said the game itself is fine, more so
overseas than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of play is in good shape,'' Wilander said. ``It's a
little bigger now overseas than it is here. I think people expect
Agassi and \RPete\S Sampras to be in the finals every time out, and
it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Open last month, Sampras took himself out of the
tournament in the first week because of a bad back, and the
stiffest competition Agassi faced on the way to the title came from
Todd Martin. Agassi won the title match against Martin in five
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most of the buzz at the Opencame on the women's side.
The Williams family exchanged barbs with Martina Hingis, the WTA's
No.1 player, and Hingis ended up playing both Williams sisters in
the tournament. She beat Venus in the semifinals before losing to
Serena in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, that was great,'' Purcell said. ``You had all these great
women players in Hingis, and the Williams sisters and Steffi
\RGraf\S and Jennifer Capriati coming back to play; it was great.
The men's game was a real bore.''
</P>
<P>
   Borg, who won 11 Grand Slam tournament titles in his career,
said the current senior tour rivalries with him, Connors and John
McEnroe are needed on the ATP Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoy these rivalries, even now,'' said Borg. ``What tennis
needs are rivalries like what we had in our day. Pete Sampras needs
Agassi and the rivalry that they had four years ago. That is what's
good for tennis.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
