<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGURT-MURDERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police prepare to arrest 4 in yogurt-shop slayings
 &HT;    By Leah Quin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After hearing the news Friday, Dorothy Bradley
pinned a button to her butterfly sweater: In black and white, it
said, ``We Will Not Forget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for this a long time,'' said Bradley, a
data-processing clerk at Lanier High School. She smiled at the
thought that one of Austin's most terrible crimes, the 1991 murder
of four teen-age girls at a frozen-yogurt shop, finally might be
solved. People familiar with the investigation said Thursday that
they are preparing to arrest four suspects, two of whom have
already confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the city, Bradley never knew Amy Ayers, Eliza
Thomas or Jennifer and Sarah Harbison. She started at Lanier two
months before the murders, not enough time to meet Thomas and
Jennifer Harbison, both seniors or Sarah Harbison, a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   But like many in Austin in the early '90s, Bradley was wrenched
by the killings,which prompted a flood of grief and the staunch
slogan, ``We Will Not Forget.'' She wears the pin every year on the
anniversary of the girls' deaths: Dec. 6. On Friday, she wore it as
a badge of hope.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hope that Ayers' mother, Pam, didn't express Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we hear something from police, it's just another
story,'' Ayers said. ``There's been too many ups and downs with
this over the years. You learn to expect the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   For three families, the worst happened in 1991 at the I Can't
Believe It's Yogurt! store in a strip shopping center. Best friends
Eliza Thomas and Jennifer Harbison, both 17, worked there.
Harbison's sister, 15-year-old Sarah and her friend Ayers, 13, were
helping them clean up the store after it closed at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:47 p.m., an Austin police officer on patrol reported a
fire at the store. In the back, firefighters found the girls'
bodies. Each had been shot twice in the back of the head. Three
bodies were burned beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to be taken out of this life with this kind of crime,
it was just horrendous,'' said Wayne Skrhak, assistant principal at
Lanier, where four crape myrtles and four oaks were planted as a
memorial by the school's FFA chapter, to which all four victims
belonged. ``It was pretty solemn around here for a while. Kids
would just start crying, adults were crying. Everybody was watching
the news, reading the paper. Everyone was on alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanier's seniors this year were in fifth grade when the murders
happened, and there was little discussion of the possible arrests
Friday, Skrhak said. However, he said, longtime teachers and
administrators had all heard the news by the time school began
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the year after the murders, dozens of suspects were cleared
and several confessions proved false.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the murders, police arrested a woman suspected
of stealing tombstones, but later said she was not a suspect. Five
weeks later, police arrested a 17-year-old man but later released
him.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1992, Mexican authorities announced the arrest of
Porfirio Villa Saavedra and Alberto Jimenez Cortez and said one had
confessed to the yogurt-shop slayings. Two days later, Villa
Saavedra recanted his confession, saying he had been tortured by
Mexican police. He and Cortez are now in prison on unrelated
charges, but have never been officially charged in the Austin
murders.
</P>
<P>
   When police started a new look at the case in August, they had
more than 2,000 tips, a detective said Wednesday. An early suspect
who suddenly stopped talking drew police attention, leading to the
break. People close to the investigation said four men, two of whom
were juveniles at the time, are suspected.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the girls' parents founded We Will Not Forget SAJE,
named for the first initial of each child. The organization, funded
with a $12 million lawsuit settlement from I Can't Believe It's
Yogurt Ltd., its parent company and the owner of the strip shopping
center, promotes workplace safety for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers said she and Barbara Ayers, mother of the Harbison
sisters, have traveled all over Texas and in other states, talking
about the need for teen workers to remain alert in places where
cash is plentiful and security often lax. Though both have spoken
often in public about the deaths of their daughters, they plan to
hire another speaker soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotions are still on a roller-coaster ride,'' Ayers said.
``I cry when I least expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Pam and Robert Ayers moved to a quarter-horse ranch in
Blanco, where Robert Ayers ranches full time. Pam Ayers works in
the cafeteria of a middle school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were too close to the yogurt shop,'' Pam Ayers said of
their former home in Northwest Austin. ``Too close to the sirens.
It got harder and harder to live there.''
</P>
<P>
   The yogurt shop never reopened after the murders. For a few
years, though the door was bricked over and the windows darkened,
the storefront became a shrine. Friends and strangers left notes,
flowers and burning candles on the window ledge.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, workmen ripped out a counter and started building a
partition, preparing the site for its new occupant, a catalog
company. A few yards from the entrance, an occasional news
photographer filmed the plaque embedded in the ground. Dedicated to
the victims and surrounded by a white picket fence, the plaque was
decorated during the day with a tissue-wrapped yellow rose and a
pot of tiny yellow buds.
</P>
<P>
   But tenants at the strip center said the crimes have never been
far from public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a great while, I'll tell someone the address and
they'll say, 'Is that where those yogurt-shop murders happened?' ``
said one employee. ``People still come to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door, Mary Caffrey said she was offered the space when she
opened Caffrey's sofa store a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to lease it. I didn't want to be where something
like that had happened,'' she said. ``It hasn't been forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
