<HEADLINE>
CULTURE OF YOUTH INVADES EVEN CURRENCY, SOME SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Look closely at your cash. Isn't Andrew
Jackson sexier than he used to be?
</P>
<P>
   Has Ulysses S. Grant been sneaking Grecian Formula and using
just a little anti-wrinkle cream?
</P>
<P>
   And Ben Franklin _ whoa! U.S. currency officials say Franklin's
enlarged image on the recently redesigned $100 bills was based on a
portrait done when he was nearly 80, about the same age as he was
on the old bills. Somewhere along the way he dropped 20 pounds and
regrew some hair.
</P>
<P>
   Next year the federal government's Currency Redesign Project
will unveil $10 and $5 bills with larger faces of Alexander
Hamilton and Abraham Lincoln. Watch out, GQ.
</P>
<P>
   Our forefathers seem to be fitter, less ancient and more
intriguing these days. The changes are not radical, but they are
enough to cause some to wonder. Ernest Lissabet, public affairs
manager for the Seniors Coalition advocacy group in Washington, was
only half-joking when he said, ``These portraits serve as yet more
evidence of the incredible obsession our society has for youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says the engraver, Thomas Hipschen. Some engravings on
the old bills were based on miniatures and reproductions of
paintings, whereas Hipschen's were based on original sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franklin was a vibrant character, and I wanted him to look
vibrant,'' said Hipschen, who works for the Bureau of Engraving and
Printing.
</P>
<P>
   He already has finished Lincoln's new image, which was etched
from a different portrait than the one now on the $5 bill. The
engraver could not disclose any details before the bill's release.
</P>
<P>
   Face it: Nobody today has actually seen these leaders. Their
images were interpreted by painters who embellished, left out
blemishes or added shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Photography had arrived by the time of Lincoln and Grant.
Techniques were so primitive, however, that people had to pose like
mannequins to avoid blurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``An engraver, though he might be copying an image, is still an
artist in that he's making his own interpretations of the
subject,'' said Philip Meggs, a graphic-arts historian at Virginia
Commonwealth University.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that, Meggs said, ``the techniques used in engraving are
cleaner and more precise, the lines are finer. This results in a
crisper image and perhaps one that appears to be younger.''
</P>
<P>
   George Neighbors, a spokesman for the Gray Panthers, an advocacy
group concerned with ageism, does not buy that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think an enlarged portrait and sharper detail would show
more wrinkles, not fewer,'' he said after comparing old and new $20
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Some historians prefer the new engravings, but an article on the
Web site of the Council for Older Adults charged that the buffed-up
portraits reflected ``a classic example of federal mismanagement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In place of the dignified portrait of `Old Hickory' (Jackson),
we now see what appears to be a close-up of Henry Fonda on a bad
wig day,'' wrote columnists Stefan Kanfer and Michael Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was one of the most chronically ill presidents in U.S.
history, a sufferer of kidney disease and gunshot wounds, who
endured severe mood swings. The old image hinted at irritation as
he clutched the lapel of a cloak.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seemed. In the original painting, according to
Hipschen, Jackson's knuckles were not visible below his neck; they
were added by the engraver of the old bill.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Moser, editor of Jackson's papers at the University of
Tennessee, said he likes the thoughtful expression on the new bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks more like a real person,'' Moser said, although ``I
do miss him clutching that cloak.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's images on both the old and the new $100 bills were
based on portraits done in the 1780s by painter Joseph Duplessis.
</P>
<P>
   The old $100, issued in 1929, re-created a 1784 Duplessis
portrait of Franklin _ jowly, thin-haired and beady-eyed. The new
image shades the flab on Franklin's neck, darkens his eyebrows,
thickens his hair and disposes of a heavy fur collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood out more with the darker hair,'' said Hipschen, an
engraver for 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hipschen said he had heard good and bad comments. Some have told
him that the new Franklin resembles Jack Benny with locks, while
the new Jackson looks ``slick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did smooth out a few warts here and there, but I didn't want
(Jackson) to look slick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hipschen's aim, he said, was to make the faces as real, bold and
enigmatic as their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Since launching the Currency Redesign Project in the mid-1990s,
officials have stressed that the larger, off-center portraits and
all other design changes are needed to incorporate
anti-counterfeiting measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not looking for aesthetic values per se,'' task force
director Thomas Ferguson said upon the release of new $50 bills
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Or, perhaps, they paid heed to what Franklin himself once wrote
of great people: ``All would live long, but none would be old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
