<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-OILERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EDMONTON, A GREAT DAY CELEBRATING THE GREAT ONE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Canada's favorite son came home to say
goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   The Edmonton Oilers raised Wayne Gretzky's No. 99 to the rafters
Friday evening, and no one in the National Hockey League will wear
it again. A sellout crowd stood throughout an emotional 45-minute
ceremony that included a video tribute, the raising of No. 99 to
the Skyreach Center rafters and a painting of the Great One.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever's an Oiler always calls Edmonton home,'' Gretzky said
before the season opener between the Rangers and Oilers, which
ended in a 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who played the last three seasons with the Rangers,
truly felt at home here for perhaps the first time since the former
Edmonton owner Peter Pocklington sold Gretzky to Los Angeles after
Gretzky's final Stanley Cup-winning team in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the banner being raised, that's when I got
emotional; that's when I knew it was done,'' said Gretzky, who
began his career here as a 17-year-old and brought four Stanley
Cups to this city.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, the Oilers' president, Glen Sather, had
delivered a moving speech in which he referred to Gretzky's
progression from boy to man to legend in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm very proud to have been associated with all three of
them,'' said Sather, Gretzky's first NHL coach.
</P>
<P>
   Then three of his former teammates, Mark Messier, Jari Kurri and
Dave Semenko, helped Gretzky unveil a commemorative painting,
``Once an Oiler, Always an Oiler.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gretzky delivered his own address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have played one more year,'' he said. ``It
wasn't meant to be. But I guess it's fitting they're parking me
behind that net.''
</P>
<P>
   With that Gretzky walked off the Oilers' ice before being
summoned back for one last curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   The city's anticipation had been mounting for this day since
April 18, when Gretzky played his final game for the Rangers at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, local news stations interrupted programming
with special reports, cutting to Gretzky's private plane on the
tarmac at Edmonton's Municipal Airport. Gretzky entering a
limousine. Gretzky's route to a downtown restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The City Hall ceremony, in which the freeway by the old
Northlands Coliseum was renamed Wayne Gretzky Drive, was broadcast
live across Canada. Gretzky, who played his first 10 seasons for
the Oilers, sat on a dais between Sather and Mayor Bill Smith of
Edmonton. Gretzky's wife, Janet, their three children, his brother
and his parents were seated nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony had a homespun feeling to it. But it soon became
obvious that Gretzky has not lived in Edmonton in more than a
decade _ and that neither of his young sons had ever been here
before Friday. The high temperatures in Thousand Oaks, Calif.,
where the Gretzkys reside, have been around 108 degrees this week.
The temperature here hovered around freezing all afternoon, and
Gretzky's youngest son, Trevor, took refuge beneath a blanket as he
sat on his uncle's lap.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the ceremony, it began to snow. Gretzky, dressed
in a black turtleneck and a black leather coat, was shivering. More
than once, a black overcoat was thrown over his shoulders to help
him fight the chill.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also obvious that Gretzky was having a ball. Nine
schoolchildren had been selected to ask Gretzky a question each
during the ceremony. One second-grader asked the Great One if he
had not been a professional hockey player what would he have chosen
to do for a living?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'd probably clean my highway,'' Gretzky said,
bringing on laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky arrived at Northlands Coliseum shortly before 4 p.m. and
walked straight for the visiting dressing room, where he met with
John Muckler, his coach from both his Edmonton and Rangers years,
and with his former Rangers teammates. Then, it was off to the
Oilers' dressing room, where Gretzky's former roommate, Kevin Lowe,
was preparing for his first game as a head coach. Lowe, who won
five Stanley Cups with Edmonton and one more with the Rangers, is
also credited with scoring the first goal in Oilers history,
although to this day, Gretzky playfully insists that it was he who
actually tipped the goal in. Lowe said he will always remember that
first goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it will be very easy for me to remember my first coaching
game, too,'' Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and the Oilers are likely to remember this day for a
very long time, too. It was the Rangers' president, Neil Smith, who
petitioned the league to allow the Rangers to participate in Friday
night's game. And the Rangers will honor Gretzky with a sweater
retirement ceremony, perhaps Dec. 8, when the Oilers make their
only Garden visit.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gretzky, there is no chance he will ever forget Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the sweater goes up, it will be the official end to my
career,'' Gretzky said. ``The ceremonies in Ottawa and New York'' _
at the end of last season, when it became clear that Gretzky was
retiring _ ``were a celebration. This is going to be very
different. There will be a little bit of sadness. It is over and it
is an end. But I still wish I could play. And I still wish I was
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That was after Sather had engaged in a little wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne's agreed to come back for one more year and play for the
Oilers,'' Sather joked. ``And he said no charge, which fits into
our budget.''
</P>
<P>
   And that _ and the resulting chants of ``One More Year!'' _
brought on the biggest cheers of the day at Edmonton's City Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
