r s BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     10-01 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR LOOKS TO BE IN CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to exhaling sources within the organization, the
Clippers' neighborhood identity crisis will avoid a
public-relations pothole called ``No-Show Time.''
</P>
<P>
   This means a bad situation won't get any worse until later. It
also means that when the show goes on, Maurice Taylor is expected
to be in it.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the pay-me-or-trade-me power forward, has been in touch
with other Clipper employees and plans to join his teammates when
the training camp fire is lit Tuesday at L.A. Southwest College.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds reasonable, but not when we rewind recent history:
</P>
<P>
   See, in our last peek at Donald Sterling's Clips, it was
business as unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the team's best player and considered one of the NBA's
leading post-millennial hotshots, was volunteering to challenge
tradition and re-enlist for six more seasons. His enterprising new
agent, David ``Goliath'' Falk, posted the contract-extension price
tag as a league-maximum 70.9 million simoleons.
</P>
<P>
   But team owner Sterling, who holds a doctorate in sticker shock,
took a pass.
</P>
<P>
   So Falk, threatening to steer Taylor out of L.A. when Mo's
current three-year deal expires June 30, 2000, recommended a
pre-camp trade. When asked last week if Taylor would show up for
the grand opening of training camp, Falk said, ``I hope he's no
longer a Clipper by then.''
</P>
<P>
   But swapping Taylor for even meager value probably would require
Sterling to increase his current payroll, so that option is fading.
</P>
<P>
   Now Taylor, as the Clippers (with fingers crossed) expected,
will report for duty. According to a member of the Clipper staff,
Taylor insists he's ship shape, prepared to improve upon last
season's numbers (16 points, 5 rebounds per game) and prove he
deserves the monster loot.
</P>
<P>
   Falk, by the way, was in Springfield, Mass. for Friday's Hall of
Fame induction of pal John Thompson and could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of nowhere
</P>
<P>
   The team's hunt for a backup center also has been sabotaged by
Sterling's commitment to making a dollar holler.
</P>
<P>
   According to league sources, Elgin Baylor, the Clips' vice
president of basketball operations, was attempting to land Sean
Rooks from the Lakers. But on Planet Sterling, Rooks' reasonably
priced, multi-year deal was considered excessive. Rooks instead was
shipped to Dallas for A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   The latest backup-center candidate, 7-foot Croatian Zan Tabak,
seemed willing to play second fiddle to starter Michael Olowokandi,
but Sterling's frugal judgment wiped out that deal, too. Zabak has
signed with the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to be campers
</P>
<P>
   The non-roster roll call expected at L.A. Southwest includes a
Clipper encore from veteran point guard Scott Brooks (UC Irvine),
who missed last season after injuring his knee in an exhibition
game vs. the Lakers last February.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Jones, who led the nation in scoring for two seasons at
Long Island University, will be in camp after spending last season
with the Chicago Bulls. Other candidates are power forward Anthony
Avent, who used to work for the Orlando Magic, former Georgia
center Terrell Bell, small forward Rodney Elliott (a summer league
alumnus) and 6-11 Antonio Harvey, a former Laker and Clipper. But
with the Trail Blazers dealing six players to Houston for Scottie
Pippen, Harvey may end up in Portland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
