<HEADLINE>
POPPING THE `BUBBLE NIGHTMARE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for a reassuring perspective, it's Merrill
Lynch to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   During a week when the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was dipping
below a ``correction'' level and The Economist featured a ``bubble
nightmare'' cover story, Merrill Lynch's Global Securities Research
&AMP; Economic Group issued a special report titled, ``The U.S. Economy
Is No Bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics may say big investment firms have a vested interest in
playing the cheerleader role even when optimism isn't merited, but
the viewpoints of Merrill Lynch's economists are as valid as those
playing Cassandra. Perhaps even more so.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as though the upbeat analysis was Panglossian. It
acknowledged that there would be ``bumps along the road ahead,''
but said this was no reason to be unduly pessimistic. The economy
is in ``excellent fundamental shape,'' the report said, and the
stock market is not overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   The Economist, on the other hand, sees danger everywhere and
urges Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan to use his influence
to engineer another interest rate boost when Fed monetary
policy-makers convene Tuesday. The main concerns are soaring trade
deficits, and explosive levels of consumer buying and borrowing.
The Economist also challenges the assumption that fundamentals
justify the stock market's historically lofty levels.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, however, quarrels with such arguments and uses
convincing data to buttress its position. Excluding the technology
sector, its analysts note, S&AMP;P 500 companies are selling at 21
times this year's estimated operating earnings per share, which is
``in line with past experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the broader economy, it also takes issue with claims
that consumers are overextended and that America suffers from a
negative savings rate. This point of contention is key, because
personal consumption fuels about two-thirds of all U.S. growth. If
the consumer falters, so does the economy.
</P>
<P>
   While official figures show the savings rate plunging from 5
percent to a point where Americans spend more than their income,
this is due to faulty methodology when treating capital gains, the
report maintains. When the accounting adjusts for this conceptual
flaw, the savings rate is really 8 percent, not negative, ``and has
been stable for the past decade.'' Moreover, even if the stock
market declined substantially, household net worth levels would
still be at historically high levels. Consumption could be expected
to fall, the report says, but the falloff wouldn't be big enough to
be disastrous to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, contrary to conventional wisdom, consumer borrowing
has been weaker than during any prior expansion cycle. Consumer
defaults not only are at a three-year low, but credit card debt is
being paid down at ``the fastest pace on record,'' Merrill Lynch
says.
</P>
<P>
   The key to current growth, according to the report, isn't an
asset bubble, but rather an ``acceleration of an underlying
productivity trend.'' Productivity growth since the mid-1990s, it
says, has been double the pace of the previous 25 years and is
still accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Merrill Lynch's economics team says, ``the doomsayers'
arguments look deeply flawed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
