<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD QUEST BEGINS IN NEW YORK FOR VIRUS RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City and federal health officials started going
door-to-door in northern Queens Friday seeking donors of blood
samples for a study to determine the overall infection rate of the
mosquito-borne West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they would continue to slip information in
mailboxes and underneath doors through the weekend and would
probably not begin visiting homes to actually draw blood from
volunteers until the beginning of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials had expressed concern earlier in the week that
the city had not yet adequately informed residents about the study.
They urged the city to distribute information before sending teams
of health officials into the neighborhoods to interview residents
and take blood samples.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratory tests by the  &UR; f &LR; ederal Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention have confirmed 35 cases of the virus in New York
City, including four deaths. Officials plan to draw blood samples
from 300 volunteers over the next three weeks in the quest to
better understand the scope of the outbreak of West Nile, the first
in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The response from residents throughout the affected area, which
includes parts of the Whitestone, Auburndale, Linden Hill, Murray
Hill and College Point neighborhoods, ranged from apprehension
about strangers wielding needles to eagerness to do their civic
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find how to fight this,'' said Werner Dietrich of
Beechhurst. ``And I don't mind if they take the test in a proper
manner, but not if they come to my house with a needle.''
</P>
<P>
   Dietrich, 61, was even more put off when he learned that
officials would not be taking the names of volunteers and that the
donors would not receive the results of their individual blood
tests. ``Why should I volunteer for a test if I'm not even going to
know how the test came out?'' Dietrich asked.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Cheffo, who lives near Little Neck Bay, said she would
like to know how the West Nile virus found its way to Queens, but
also said she probably would not participate in the study if asked.
``I'm not a fan of the needle, especially on a volunteer basis,''
said Ms. Cheffo, 34. ``And why would you participate and agree to
get poked if you're not going to find out the results?''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Mullin, a spokeswoman for the city's Health Department,
said officials had anticipated that some people would decline to
participate because results of the tests would not be provided. But
she said that the study was being conducted in the same way that
the Centers for Disease Control always carried out such studies.
</P>
<P>
   She added that the people who are to be tested would very likely
be healthy. The health workers hope to identify people who might
have been infected with the virus but who show no symptoms of the
illness or only very mild symptoms. While West Nile virus leaves a
person's blood very soon after infection, antibodies can remain for
months, or even years.
</P>
<P>
   A positive result on a test does not necessarily mean that the
person was ever sick or will become sick, Ms. Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, there is no specific treatment for the virus, and the
only assistance we could give people is supportive therapy,'' she
said. ``So it's not as if we could administer something to make
them feel better even if they were to become sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mullin said that starting next week, teams consisting of a
doctor, a nurse and a public health worker would interview
residents in the designated neighborhoods and ask for voluntary
blood samples. Residents will be able to choose between having
their blood drawn at home or at one of the Health Department vans
that will be stationed in the area. Ms. Mullin said six to eight
teams would visit homes in the evenings during the week and during
daylight hours on weekends.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some residents said they would volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty healthy, so I'm not worried if I have the virus or
not,'' said Enis Mormile, 79, of College Point. ``Sure, I'd be
bothered by the test, but everybody's got to chip in and do their
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter O'Donnell, 61, of Whitestone, was almost blase about the
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not volunteer if it'll help?' &UR; ' &LR;  he asked. ``Besides, the
city takes everything else, why not give a little blood, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city continued spraying parts of Queens and
Manhattan Friday to try to kill mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial spraying will begin Saturday night in Rockland County and
continue until next week. Nassau County had planned to spray
Saturday night, but postponed the spraying until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester County, officials announced Friday that they
planned to expand their spraying into the northern part of the
county next week because of three suspected cases of the virus in
that area. There are at least eight confirmed cases of the virus in
southern Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they also had received reports of 250 dead birds
in northern Westchester. The West Nile virus is generally
transmitted from birds to mosquitoes, which in turn can infect
people.
</P>
<P>
   Communities that will be sprayed next week include Sleepy
Hollow, Ossining, Mount Kisco, Chappaqua, Bedford, Rye Brook, White
Plains and Greenburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
